<HEADER>
A7728 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-07 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich did not know it when he scoured the
list of prospects before the NBA draft last June.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Barkley did not know it when he re-signed with the
Rockets, shunning several teams waving millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And Scottie Pippen surely did not know it when he decided not to
go down with the NBA's version of the Titanic, choosing instead to
head south for the winter to become a Rocket after spending the
first 11 years of his career winning championships in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   No, not even Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley knew that when
the 1999 NBA season shifted into overdrive, as it does every year
when the playoffs begin, they would be the starting backcourt for
the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   But they are.
</P>
<P>
   Two rookies are charged with helping the Rockets return to the
top of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   They get their first playoff test Saturday in Los Angeles when
the Rockets take on the Lakers in a matchup of the Nos. 4 and 5
seeds from the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Dickerson said. ``I'm curious.
The veterans have talked about how different the playoffs are from
the regular season, and I can't wait to experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA lockout aside, Dickerson didn't have to wait long to go
from college star to professional. He was snapped up by the Rockets
with their first pick (14th overall) in the 1998 draft, and then
when the labor agreement was reached he was dropped into the
starting lineup at shooting guard before the regular season began.
</P>
<P>
   It took Mobley, who did not play in the season opener at Los
Angeles, 10 games to find himself thrust into a starting role at
point guard. After a brief interruption, he has made himself at
home with 33 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he had no long-range plans when he plugged
Mobley into the starting lineup Feb. 21, forming the all-rookie
backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think about them being rookies. Honestly, I was
just doing what I thought was best for the team,'' Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   So what might seem like a bold, maybe even questionable move was
a no-brainer to Tomjanovich _ he was trying to win games. The two
have responded, combining for more than 20 points per game, with
Dickerson leading the team in 3-point shooting at 43 percent and
Mobley near the top with 82 percent free-throw shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who has been part of six NBA championship teams, had no
reservations about the rookie starters, though when he was traded
to the Rockets he expected Rodrick Rhodes, a second-year player who
has since been traded, to be a starter.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after his arrival in Houston, Pippen said he saw
something from the rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take long,'' Pippen said. ``During the exhibition
games, I realized that they play with a lot of confidence, a lot of
tenacity, a lot of love for the game, and they work very hard. So I
was impressed then. They're not just average rookies, I don't
think. They have a lot to bring to the table for you.''
</P>
<P>
   They bring it on different plates, or so it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson is the quiet sort, though with guys like Barkley and
Antoine Carr sharing the locker room, a chainsaw could go
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   But that is OK with Dickerson, who shies from the media
spotlight _ literally. After three months of dealing with it, he
finally let on Thursday that shyness is not his problem; the bright
camera lights hurt his sensitive eyes. He has just been too polite
to tell the television cameramen that. It might be too late now.
</P>
<P>
   After pouring in 58 points in the last two regular-season games,
the South Carolina-born 23-year-old, who attended high school in
Seattle and college at Arizona, will draw much attention when the
Rockets roll into Los Angeles this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He just doesn't know it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, who answers to the nickname ``Cat,'' is a cool customer.
Though he went to high school in Maine and played college ball at
Rhode Island, he is more suited to the in-your-face hoops stylings
found in his hometown of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Confident and rarely shaken, Mobley, who posted 18 points in
each of the last two games, is even a bit surprised by his early
success in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really think about anything big. I just came in (to
training camp) trying to get a spot on the team,'' Mobley said.
``Fortunately, I've started. I'm just happy to be here, that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tomjanovich, for one, is happy he is here as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was (about) survival,'' Tomjanovich said of the insertion
of Mobley into the starting lineup. ``I just picked a guy that I
thought could do a job defensively, and he came in and handled the
job. Then I went back and tried to do it with other combinations,
and I felt that with Cuttino in the lineup was the best way to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mobley: ``I appreciate it tremendously that he believes in
me, and I don't want to let him down. That helps me play better.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that opponents remain willing to leave Dickerson
and Mobley wandering unguarded on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be like that for a while,'' Mobley said. ``For
right now, we're the guys they come off of until we prove
ourselves. And hopefully, like it has lately, it will continue to
work to our advantage. That's what we're out there for.''
</P>
<P>
   They have come through often enough that good play is more of an
expectation than a surprise. They even have Hakeem Olajuwon, the
team's leading scorer, saying he is counting on them to continue to
lead the way as long as the shots are there and they maintain their
groove.
</P>
<P>
   Each is confident they can pull it off, even if a few months ago
they didn't know they would have to do it from the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have confidence in myself; I may not have confidence
in my shot all the time, but I always have confidence in myself,''
Dickerson said. ``I worked extremely hard in the summer to be able
to step in and contribute right away. But to have the type season
that I'm having, no, I never thought I could do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some downs during the season, but to have the season
I am having, I thank God every morning when I wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   If opponents don't wake up and recognize Dickerson and Mobley
for the players they are, teams might not have much of a prayer of
stopping the Rockets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
