<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG DAY IN COURT FOR 1 IMMIGRANT AND 5 POLICE OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He looked small and frail in a dark blue suit that
seemed three sizes too large. Abner Louima gazed across the packed
courtroom. He blinked several times, and his dark eyes seemed to
widen at the sight of so many faces focused entirely on him.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took the witness stand to give his account of vicious
abuse by New York City police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Louima told of officers who held him face down in a precinct
house bathroom, rammed a stick into his rectum, then threatened to
kill him and his family if he ever breathed a word of what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor asked Louima what he was doing when a police
officer allegedly removed the stick from Louima's rectum and thrust
it into his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying,'' Louima replied quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the moment when Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad
asked Louima to look around the court and identify the officer who,
prosecutors charge, inserted the stick into Louima's rectum.
</P>
<P>
   Louima stood and methodically searched the courtroom with his
eyes. ``He's right there,'' he said. At the prosecutor's prodding,
Louima pointed a shaking finger at Officer Justin Volpe, who did
not visibly react.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is one of five New York City police officers on trial this
week in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn in the alleged assault of
Louima. They have denied all the charges, and their lawyers have
said Louima is fabricating the assault to win millions of dollars
in a civil suit against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the first day that Louima appeared on the witness
stand. He answered prosecutors' questions about the alleged assault
and questions from defense lawyers about seeming inconsistencies in
his account. He recounted the months of pain as he recovered from
extensive internal damage. He recalled how, before he was wheeled
into surgery, a doctor asked him to drink some fluid, only to feel
it immediately pass through his body.
</P>
<P>
   An immigrant from Haiti, Louima has a voice so heavily accented
that Vinegrad asked him again and again to repeat his answers.
During most of his three and a half hours on the stand, he
maintained his composure, and there were moments of humor. At one
point, Louima described how, on the night of the alleged assault,
which followed his arrest in a street brawl, he danced with several
women at Club Rendez-vous on Flatbush Avenue in Brooklyn while his
wife was at home.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, prosecutors presented Louima to jurors in a
manner clearly intended to undercut some of the major defense
arguments. Defense lawyers contend that Louima was injured through
consensual sex with a man.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad asked Louima about his wife of three years, and about
his two children. Then he asked if his wife was expecting another
child. Yes, Louima replied, later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also raised some blemishes in Louima's background
that defense lawyers are sure to explore as they try to attack
Louima's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Louima admitted to jurors that he failed to report as much as
$10,000 he earned while working as a used-car salesman, and that he
lied when he told reporters that police officers had tauntingly
told him, ``It's Giuliani time,'' a reference to the pro-police
administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers immediately seized on those failings as they
began their questioning of Louima, which will continue next week.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the day was devoted to questions from prosecutors,
who repeatedly drew Louima back to the events of that August night
in 1997, back to what he described as one humiliation after another
at the hands of police officers. At one point, Louima said, they
ridiculed his command of English, telling him to go back to his
country.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he testified, another sort of immigrant experience was
being played out Thursday in the same building, as hundreds of men
and women gathered in another federal courtroom to be sworn in as
U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country embraces you and protects you,'' said Judge
Allyne Ross. ``My hope for all of you and your children is that you
share to the fullest in the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone applauded, oblivious to the man in the baggy blue suit
sitting four floors above.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
