<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOAP-STATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIA ANNOUNCES PLANS FOR SOAP CITY, SOAP OPERA CABLE CHANNEL   
()
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Sony Corp.'s Columbia television studio on
Thursday became the second owner of hit network soap operas to
announce plans for a soap opera cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia Tristar Television Group said it would initiate a
cable channel called Soap City next January, the same month when
ABC, owned by the Walt Disney Co., plans to begin its own soap
opera channel.
</P>
<P>
   Like ABC, Columbia plans to rely on same-day repeats of soap
operas it owns, in this case ``Days of Our Lives,'' the
highest-rated soap opera on NBC. Columbia also has an interest in
several other soaps, most prominently ``The Young and the
Restless'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS retains the rights to broadcast all its soap operas
exclusively, a right that has become a point of dispute in the
increasing friction between several networks and their affiliated
stations.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's decision to start up a soap channel, repeating in prime
time the episodes of soaps like ``General Hospital,'' was strongly
opposed by ABC's affiliated stations. NBC's affiliates vocally
objected when the network decided to use material from news
programs like ``Dateline: NBC'' on its news channel, MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Schwartz, the senior vice president of communications for
CBS, said CBS had ``no intention'' of releasing its exclusive
rights to broadcast ``The Young and the Restless.'' CBS' contract
with Columbia on that show has two years to run. NBC's deal with
Columbia for ``Days of Our Lives'' allowed for the episodes to be
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Two Columbia executives, Jon Feltheimer, the president of
Columbia Tristar Television, and Andy Kaplan, the executive vice
president, both said in interviews Thursday that they would welcome
the idea of adding CBS and NBC as partners in the new soap channel.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan noted that Columbia had experimented for a year with
selling same-day repeats of ``Days of Our Lives'' on a pay-per-view
basis to viewers with the Hughes Electronic's satellite service
DirecTV. ``We were encouraged by the results,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Feltheimer said the channel would also contain other programming
of interest to soap fans, including perhaps repeats of prime-time
serial dramas like ``Party of Five,'' which Columbia owns, and the
soap ``Santa Barbara,'' which was canceled by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan also pointed to the success of a soap Web site
established by Columbia, also called Soap City, and said the new
channel and the Web site would be closely linked. ``We're going to
expand the Web site and pump investment into it,'' Kaplan said.
``It'll be an ongoing convergence, including video streaming of
programming from the cable channel on the Web site.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
