<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-07 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SO now they must do it the long, hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   They have emphasized in the past week they are not the old
Rockets, and yet they enter the playoffs following a familiar path.
</P>
<P>
   The road.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sherpas trekking toward the summit of Mount Everest, they
know their way to the top. They also know getting there can be
difficult. Pack the oxygen tanks and the crampons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in this position,'' Scottie Pippen said with
a shrug. ``I wish I could say that it doesn't matter. But it
does.''
</P>
<P>
   It matters because there is little margin for error along this
route. It matters because a team that has been largely unsuccessful
away from home through this makeshift season now will have to pull
more than its share of victories out of the luggage.
</P>
<P>
   It means everybody must concentrate. It means the part of the
Rockets' game that has often been their weakest will be put to the
test _ their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play smart,'' Pippen said. ``Honestly, there have
been a lot of times this season when we haven't done that. Nights
when the shots weren't falling when we didn't do the other things _
defense and taking care of the ball _ that can still get you wins
in those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Rockets' most significant win away from home
this season came April 12 at Minnesota. It is the only time all
year they won a road game against a team without a losing record.
The Timberwolves finished 25-25, exactly .500.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the mood inside the locker room at Denver's McNichols
Arena was by no means funereal as the Rockets sat watching a tiny
TV screen as the Lakers thumped Portland to wrap up the home-court
advantage in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are worse places to spend the weekend than LA,'' Charles
Barkley said. ``And the truth is that if this team still has the
belief that it can win a championship _ and I'm telling you it does
_ then we're going to have to win on the road eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Having seen this team ride a roller coaster of emotion and
effort all season, the deeper truth is that opening at the Great
Western Forum in front of Jack Nicholson and the Laker Girls might
be just the prescription to cure the Rockets' road woes.
</P>
<P>
   After those two fateful visits by the Dallas Mavericks over the
past two weeks, who is sure about the Rockets' chances of defending
their home court in the first two games anyway?
</P>
<P>
   They have a tendency to drift mentally and let teams settle into
a comfort zone against them. They have a bad habit of getting
sloppy physically, committing turnovers on offense and playing soft
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the ups and the downs we've experienced, this is still
a team with a lot of confidence in what it can do,'' Pippen said.
``It's a team that plays very well when it wants to or needs to. It
seems like we need a challenge, and there's no bigger challenge
than the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The impressive April wins over Portland and the Lakers are proof
the Rockets have the ability.
</P>
<P>
   There is no bigger opportunity than in the first two games in
LA, where the Lakers are just as big a question mark, one huge
dysfunctional family that has, at times, made the Rockets look like
a model for success.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman and his distractions are gone, but the Lakers
still carry so much excess baggage. Can Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe
Bryant find a way to coexist with only one basketball and two
different views of who should shoot it?
</P>
<P>
   Can the Lakers succeed in the playoffs without their best
perimeter defender, Eddie Jones, who was shipped off to Charlotte
with Elden Campbell to bring in yet another shooter? Can first-year
coach Kurt Rambis get any of his players to even look in his
direction, let alone listen, when he draws up plays in a timeout?
</P>
<P>
   If you're the Rockets, you have to view this as more of an
opportunity than a daunting obstacle. What would happen to the
Lakers if the Rockets were to ``steal'' one of the first two games
in LA? Would Shaq squash Kobe like a grape? Would they fracture
from disharmony?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is the home-court advantage does not become
overwhelming until the final game of any series, and in a five-game
set the pressure to defend it at the outset might actually be
greater.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the Rockets' hope, because it's now the only
option at their disposal.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar way. The long, hard way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only six teams in the playoffs with a chance to win
it all,'' Barkley said. ``Two in the East, Indiana and Miami, and
four in the West. You've got Utah, San Antonio, Portland and us. We
belong on that list.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Now all they have to do is prove it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
