<SLUG> BC-KC-BANK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRIEND IN NEED . . . COULD BE A BANK ROBBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAWNA A. HAMEL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Lenore Atagi was just doing a favor for
friends. What a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Atagi, 18, of Independence, had driven two friends to an Army
recruiting center. On the way home, one friend asked to stop at a
bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, he gets in the van and yells, `Roll out! Roll
out!' '' Atagi said.
</P>
<P>
   She said he mentioned something about 15 G's, ``And I thought,
`Oh no, you didn't just rob a bank.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Officials say he did. He and the other man are expected to be
charged today, FBI spokesman Jeff Lanza said.
</P>
<P>
   They said they don't think Atagi was involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman realized something was going on, there was a large
sum of money involved, and she didn't want any part of it,'' said
Gladstone Detective Dave Smith.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning Atagi agreed to take her two friends to the
recruiting center. On the way there they stopped at Hillcrest Bank
to ask for directions.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting the recruiting center, one friend said he wanted
to go back to the bank. So Atagi made the stop.
</P>
<P>
   As she drove away, she heard sirens. When she saw police behind
her, she pulled into a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically turned us in,'' Atagi said.
</P>
<P>
   Police took the three in for questioning, but let Atagi go
later.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said money was found in the van.
</P>
<P>
   Atagi said she realized later that more was at stake than
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe it happened,'' she said. ``Through this
whole thing, it was my life on the line and I didn't even know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not how I expected my day to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
