<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTOR-CONFESSION-SPI     05-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTOR-CONFESSION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES PASTOR CAN'T BE FORCED TO TESTIFY IN MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A state Supreme Court ruling Thursday that a Tacoma,
Wash., pastor cannot be forced to testify about an alleged murder
confession protects the sanctity of the confessional, supporters
said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court unanimously dismissed a Pierce County Superior
Court's contempt charge against the Rev. Rich Hamlin, ruling that
he was protected by a state law that guarantees the confidentiality
of religious confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the ruling significantly broadened legal
protections to any religion, regardless of whether a religion has a
recognized right of confession.
</P>
<P>
   Theologians were buoyed by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (ruling) will be the latest authority on the subject in
the country,'' said Steve McFarland, director of the Virginia-based
Christian Legal Society. ``It will be hopefully a beacon light to
warn other prosecutors away from this unconstitutional sandbar.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin, the ordained minister of the 75-member Evangelical
Reformed Church in South Tacoma, was ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled that the state Supreme Court has ruled and
ruled decisively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the state Court of Appeals sided with Hamlin in a
3-0 vote, ruling the law protects clergy members if they believe
they are hearing a confession out of a religious obligation. The
high court's decision affirms the Appeals Court.
</P>
<P>
   But the Washington Supreme Court ruling does come with a caveat:
The privilege enjoyed by a pastor who hears a confession could be
nullified if there is a third party present _ something that could
affect the case at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The case revolves around the death two years ago of 3-month-old
Devyn Martin. Pierce County prosecutors charged Devyn's father,
Scott Anthony Martin, with second-degree murder, saying he shook
his son to death in a fit of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   To try him, they said they needed to call Hamlin as a witness.
They believe Martin confessed the slaying to Hamlin, who met with
Martin three times after the baby died.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamlin refused to testify, claiming that to do so would
violate the privacy protecting what a penitent tells him in
confidence. Pierce County Superior Court Judge Brian Tollefson
found him in contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has been in custody since he was charged in 1997; his
bail was set at $250,000. His trial was put on hold while the high
court reviewed Hamlin's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce County Prosecutor John Ladenburg said state law before
Thursday's ruling only protected confessions between a penitent and
clergy in a religion with a recognized right of confession, such as
the Roman Catholic or Episcopal churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing they (state justices) did, which is very
significant, is say that it's up to the priest to decide if it's a
confession, as opposed to another statement that is
non-confessional in nature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ladenburg noted, however, that the high court also said that
having a third party present during the confession could negate the
priest-penitent privilege.
</P>
<P>
   In Martin's case, his mother was present as least during part of
his conversations with Hamlin, Ladenburg said. The mother has told
authorities she doesn't remember what she heard Hamlin and her son
discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also believe that yet another person was present
when the pastor spoke with Martin a third time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have evidence that at least two of the three times someone
else was present'' during the conversations, Ladenburg said.
``We'll give whatever evidence we have to the judge and say, `What
do you want to do now?'''
</P>
<P>
   Steven O'Ban, Hamlin's attorney, said a hearing will be held
shortly for a judge to explore that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as what will happen at the evidentiary hearing, I'm not
in a position to guess,'' O'Ban said. ``But I am confident the
judge will not force Pastor Hamlin to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Maddox, a theology professor at Seattle Pacific
University, said the court's ruling affirms an important religious
right that dates to the earliest days of the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``If parishioners did not have the confidence (his confession)
would remain confidential, it would remove an important tool of
spiritual life,'' Maddox said. ``The promise that whatever is
revealed remains private ... goes back very far in the Christian
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Said the Christian Legal Society's McFarland: ``The court has
protected the sanctity of the confessional. You can confide in your
clergy with the assurance what you say will stay between you and
God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troubled people can unburdened their consciousness to clergy
without worrying their pastor will become the government's
snitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      05-07 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Astros had a dreadful spring, and they have subsequently lost
two starters to injuries, after having subtracted no less of a
luminary than Moises Alou from the every-day mix until, at the
earliest, late August.
</P>
<P>
   Also, prodigal son/cleanup hitter Ken Caminiti is only now
completing what would constitute a spring training's worth of
preparation and conditioning, having wasted most of his Florida
laid low by a stubborn sinus infection.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, the Astros should be treading water. Instead,
they're swimming like Mark Spitz. If 17-10 doesn't sound
impressive, consider that, over the course of a season, it
extrapolates to 102-60.
</P>
<P>
   That W-L ratio should ring familiar to you. It, of course, is
the franchise record they compiled last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are doing everything well and can offer up a broad
statistical sampler to prove it. They lead the National League in
hitting, slugging and on-base percentage, with their batting
average a lofty nine points higher than anyone else's. They are
second in stolen bases with 32, and just two teams have committed
fewer errors or converted more double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Astros pitchers have given up one more earned run than Atlanta's
perennial NL leaders; their opponents' on-base percentage is
second-lowest to the Mets. Their 12 saves converted in 13
opportunities ranks first by a comfortable margin, with Billy
Wagner's 10-for-10 as perfect as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   And coming off a 5-1 Florida-New York swing, they're 10-4 away
from the Astrodome, the best traveling record in the major leagues.
No road toads, these guys.
</P>
<P>
   Need a negative? OK, their 7-6 standing in this Dome farewell
celebration could use marked improvement, but three games starting
tonight against Montreal (8-18) and three with middling Pittsburgh
offer a good opportunity to get that apparent aberration righted as
well.
</P>
<P>
   And, true, they are a ``lowly'' fifth in runs scored, meaning
they're leaving a tad too many men on base (7.7 per game).
</P>
<P>
   But let's not quibble here. Grading on the curve, which means
taking into account the fact one-third of the starting lineup is
off line, they're off to a remarkable start, one of the best in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Can it last? First let me say it had better because the Central
Division appears significantly stronger than it has been in the
Astros' past two championship seasons. But, yes, it can, absolutely
_ as long as more players don't stagger off to the infirmary. Depth
remains a potential problem, particularly with the farm system
having been hammered by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But the ever-worrisome health variable notwithstanding, what
favors the odds of such a solid run continuing is there have been
no fluke heroes. The stars carrying the Astros are the ones who are
supposed to be, hence there's no reason to expect them to tail off
precipitously as the months drag on. They are proven commodities,
with well-documented standards of consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a stiff neck, Jeff Bagwell barely could turn his head
in Florida. But he's turning heads now with nine home runs and 26
RBIs. If you multiply those numbers by six (the season is one-sixth
complete), you get 54 and 156, a monster year even in the age of
Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   (Who, by the way, isn't on the leader board in either category.)
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds, in turn, goes after his sixth victory Saturday
night, proving a lucrative contract extension doesn't necessarily
have to turn a man's head. How can Reynolds, in as impressive a
groove as we've seen him, not finally post a breakthrough 20-win
season?
</P>
<P>
   As for Jose Lima, who seeks his fifth W this evening, he's
pitching as well as he did a year ago. And much to everyone's
relief _ mercifully, he hasn't needed much of that lately _ Mike
Hampton has come around nicely after a troubling start, posting a
pair of victories and a 1.20 ERA in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the starters, only 0-4 Chris Holt lags behind, yet Larry
Dierker maintains Holt has had much better stuff than his record
indicates, and who are we to argue with the skipper, he of the
lumbering gait, disarming manner and golden touch?
</P>
<P>
   Every move Dierker makes seems the right one instinctively.
Either managing a ballclub is a lot easier than baseball people
would have us believe, or the former broadcaster his partners in
the booth called ``Sluggo'' has reinvented the proverbial wheel,
having found the secret to keeping a team at once relaxed,
confident and clearly focused on the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker manages for results, not effect. He checks his ego at
the clubhouse door. He neither beats a team up nor beats it down.
He simply lets players play, and when you have as many good ones as
the Astros, the results follow accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in their undermanned state, these Astros are
overachieving. At full force, they could be awesome.
</P>
<P>
   Randy who? Roger who?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
