<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      05-07 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Offer a person incentive, and almost anything is possible. Even a
pitcher coming up with a hit.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once a reliever in the American League, Jose Lima didn't even
own a wooden bat, much less use one, for several seasons. The
feeling of baseball people has long been that pitchers get paid to
pitch, not hit. In Lima's case, it depends on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   With his move to the National League and the Astros before the
1997 season, Lima finally found out what the other side was like. A
relative even bet Lima $5,000 last season, his first as a full-time
starter, that he couldn't get at least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Lima got his first major-league hit May 10, 1998, the first of
11 he collected last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need the money, but I just wanted to prove I could do
it,'' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   For most pitchers, success is measured in victories, innings and
earned run average _ not doubles, home runs and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   But through 27 games, Astros pitchers have become almost as
dependable at the plate as on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds was the first NL starter to win five games. He
also has five runs batted in. Mike Hampton has won his last two
starts, getting two hits in the process. Sean Bergman, who
possesses the best power potential, hit a pair of solo home runs in
consecutive starts to begin the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing nine guys to the plate instead of eight,''
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``As a ballclub, especially in the
National League, if your pitcher can hit, field his position, bunt
guys over and things like that, it's such an added plus to your
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, every time a pitcher gets a hit, something good
happens during that inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' pitching staff ranks a modest eighth in the NL with
a .182 batting average. The pitchers have driven in 11 runs. (The
Florida Marlins' pitching staff leads the NL with a .292 batting
average; the rest of the Marlins' lineup is hitting .249.)
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros, it has been all about timing. Of the 10 hits by
the five starting pitchers, nine have directly figured in scoring
or extended an inning.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Bergman's first homer, a solo shot, tied the Brewers in the
fifth inning April 9. The Astros won 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' two-run double during a three-run seventh against
Arizona on April 27 helped the Astros cruise to an 11-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1 against the Marlins, Lima's two-out blooper to right
field _ his first hit of the season _ kept a second-inning rally
alive; the Astros scored five en route to a 6-4 win.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's two-out triple, his second in 236 career at-bats,
helped the Astros erupt for five runs in the final three innings of
Tuesday's 6-1 win over the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole staff takes pride in hitting,'' said Hampton, who is
tied with Reynolds with a .273 average. ``We know the little things
can help.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said the more pitches the pitchers see in practice, the
greater the chance they will get a hit. On a normal day at the
Astrodome, pitchers are the first to arrive in the batting cage,
spending 20 to 30 minutes taking cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds and Hampton are considered the contact hitters of the
group, the two most likely to come up with a hit or get down a
sacrifice. ``I'm not going to strike out a lot. I'm going to put
the ball in play,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman has wowed some of his teammates with upper-deck blasts
in batting practice. He is 0-for-7 since his last hit, a homer
April 15. If he is going to hit, the pitch must be in just the
right spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it (the ball) hits his bat, he can hit it a long way,''
hitting instructor Tom McCraw said. ``He's hit some no-doubters.''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw says Lima is the most improved hitter on the staff over
the past year. While he may have just one hit in 1999, Lima has
focused on making contact and has struck out only three times in 13
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Striking out an opposing hitter is one thing; being on the
receiving end is another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to strike out. Sometimes you feel bad when you
strike out and you are a pitcher, because you want to show you can
hit,'' said Lima, who began the season 0-for-9. ``Why do you think
the crowd gives such a loud ovation when a pitcher gets a hit?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win 20 games, I can go 0-0-0-0. They don't pay me to
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Griffin owns the highest single-season batting average by a
pitcher in Astros history, when he hit .294 (20-for-68) in 1974.
The club record for career average for a pitcher with at least 200
at-bats is .196 (60-for-306) by Dave Giusti from 1962-68.
</P>
<P>
   The major-league record for highest batting average by a pitcher
in a season is .440 by Washington's Walter Johnson in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Those records seem safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't going to be .300 hitters, but if they can get a
walk or make contact, those contributions can extend an inning or
ignite an inning,'' McCraw said.
</P>
<P>
   And when Astros pitchers aren't driving in runs, they are moving
runners into scoring position. Reynolds already has seven
sacrifices in six games after getting seven in 35 games in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So with the Astros tied with the Mets 1-1 in the seventh inning
of Tuesday's game, did manager Larry Dierker consider pinch-hitting
for Hampton?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' said Dierker, a .180 hitter during his playing
career. ``I know he can do more than most pitchers in the sense
that he can hit and run fast. He can draw walks and steal bases. He
makes plays you wouldn't believe. He's good enough where if you hit
for him, it's only a marginal upgrade. And you lose the guy who's
been shutting the other team down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Chris Holt said, ``No pitcher is faster than him
(Hampton) in either league.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton sent a drive to the center-field wall over a drawn-in
outfield, sparking a three-run inning. He also combined with Scott
Elarton on a three-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect a pitcher to hit the ball 400 feet,'' said
New York center fielder Brian McRae. ``You don't normally see
pitchers hit a ball that far.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything is possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
