<SLUG> BC-KC-FARMLAND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC-BASED FARMLAND, ST. PAUL'S CENEX HARVEST STATES TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The nation's two largest farmer-owned
cooperatives, Farmland Industries of Kansas City and Cenex Harvest
States of St. Paul, Minn., are planning to merge.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal would create an agribusiness behemoth with
about $17 billion in annual sales, nearly double Farmland's 1998
sales and more than four times the size of the next largest
farmers' cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   The combined operation would enter the Fortune 100 and be second
only to Sprint Corp. as the metropolitan area's largest company.
Farmland now ranks 184th on the Fortune 500 list.
</P>
<P>
   Directors for Farmland and Cenex approved pre-merger
preparations in hopes of creating an international cooperative that
would give their owner-members more muscle in the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmer needs two checks. One for his production and one
for his investment in the market from processing and value-added
work,'' said Noel Estenson, chief executive of Cenex Harvest
States.
</P>
<P>
   Estenson and H.D. Cleberg, chief executive of Farmland, would
serve as co-chief executive officers until the businesses had been
blended enough to allow for a more traditional management
structure. The reconstituted board of the combined group then would
determine leadership issues.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions on what the new entity will be called or where the
headquarters will be located are expected to be made by the end of
the year, with final approval for the merger expected by June 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperatives said they expect to retain large presences in
both Kansas City and St. Paul. Farmland said the proposed merger
would not affect plans to build a 1.3-million-square-foot campus
near Kansas City International Airport. The same cost benefits and
efficiencies Farmland expects from that project would be realized
by the new entity, Farmland spokeswoman Sherlyn Manson said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known what effect the merger would have on the number
of employees needed. Farmland has 16,000 employees worldwide and
2,000 employees in Kansas City. Cenex has about 5,600 employees
nationwide, about 700 in St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the merger's benefits will be derived from
transportation efficiencies and expanded purchasing power, not from
employee reductions, officials said. Any employees who do lose
their jobs would be given assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said the companies will use outside professionals to
help make such decisions so they are not influenced by ``emotion or
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason that our concern in this community will be
any different in the future than in the past,'' Cleberg said. ``I
mean that with sincerity. We understand the importance of a
community role. I am most fearful there will be an overreaction
that creates more nervousness than is necessary in the community
and among our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first trip to the altar for Farmland and Cenex.
In late 1988, the cooperatives announced merger plans but called
off the engagement six months later.
</P>
<P>
   Things are different this time, said Cleberg, who became chief
executive of Farmland in 1991. He said the merger was a natural
transition from a growing number of joint ventures over the last 10
years that Farmland has had with Cenex and Harvest States, which
merged last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those ventures range from pet food manufacturing to marketing of
tires and batteries. In March the two announced plans to merge some
aspects of their grain businesses after Cargill Inc. and
Continental Grain, the first- and second-largest U.S. grain
companies, announced plans to merge their grain operations.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said he would not expect big reductions in employees
coming from the Farmland and Cenex merger. The benefits are more in
the areas of transportation and in the sourcing of grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 5,000 rail cars and they have about the same.
The harvest seasons in the upper Midwest and the lower Midwest are
different, so you can see the advantages there,'' Cleberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland's largest concentration of employees is in meat
processing and marketing, a business that Cenex is not in, so there
should be little effect on employees there.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason Farmland has so many more employees than Cenex,
even though their sales are about the same, is because of the
labor-intensive nature of its thriving meat processing, Cleberg
said. Farmland has 10 pork, three beef and one catfish processing
plants.
</P>
<P>
   While staff reductions may not be driving the move, one of the
prime benefits of such a merger would be the economies of scope and
scale, said Mike Cook, professor of agriculture economics at the
University of Missouri-Columbia. Cook specializes in the study of
farm cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``With advances in information and other technologies, for much
less money you can perform the same functions,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Efficiency for the American farmer is essential, Cook said,
because other parts of the world, eastern Australia and South
American for example, now have the infrastructure in place to rival
America.
</P>
<P>
   Estenson said that the competitor for the American farmer is now
in countries such as Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the price of soybeans goes up, Brazil will plant another 10
million acres. This is why we have to be looking at how we can best
help our farmers generate income by adding to their crops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond rating company Standard &AMP; Poor put Farmland's bonds on its
watch list after the announcement. That means the ratings could be
raised, lowered or affirmed after it evaluates the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Lee Egerstrom of Knight Ridder Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
