b x &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-AMCENT-KAN &LR;      05-07 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-AMCENT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 American Century takes role in electronic stock exchange in
Britain  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City's American Century Investments is
joining with four other financial-service firms to buy a majority
share of a company that acts as an electronic stock exchange in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The company being acquired is Tradepoint Financial Networks PLC,
and American Century executives think it could emerge as a model
for the way stocks are bought and sold in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Buying and selling stocks on electronic exchanges is faster and
cheaper than traditional exchanges. Tradepoint can sell about 2,000
British stocks, but the consortium thinks Tradepoint can expand and
its system could be adapted to work for stocks in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the Tradepoint investment as consistent with our
mission to lower trading costs for our investors, to promote
efficient markets and, ultimately, to increase investment returns
for our mutual fund shareholders,'' said Harold Bradley, senior
vice president of American Century.
</P>
<P>
   American Century manages about $85 billion for its 2 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium is being led by Instinet Corp., a subsidiary of
Reuters Group PLC. An Instinet executive, Richard Kilsby, will
become chief executive of Tradepoint.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the consortium are Archipelago, an
electronic communications network partly owned by the investment
banking firm Goldman Sachs and the online investing service ETrade,
and J.P. Morgan and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., both of which
are financial-services firms.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's stake amounts to about $22 million and will
equal 55 percent of Tradepoint's stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
