<HEADLINE>
KANSAS REGULATORS APPROVE MERGER OF WESTERN RESOURCES, KCP&AMP;L 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The proposed merger of Western Resources Inc.
and Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. moved a step closer Thursday when
the utilities settled their differences with the staff of the
Kansas Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement still must be approved by the commission, and by
Missouri and federal regulators. But the compromise is the first
big break in a logjam that has threatened to kill the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for a four-year moratorium on rate increases
and an additional $45 million in rebates to be divided among the
Kansas customers of KCP&AMP;L and Western's KPL and KG&AMP;E electrical
utilities. The allocation among the utilities will be decided
later.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Western and KCP&AMP;L gave up on a plan that would have
allowed their merged utility to keep at least a share of any
profit. Instead, rates would be set in the traditional manner, by
basing them on a percentage above the utility's cost of providing
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a strong signal that in the state of Kansas this
merger is considered doable,'' said Michel' Philipp, a spokeswoman
for Western Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Safer, Kansas Corporation Commission general counsel,
said: ``They give up some pretty big things, and in return they get
some assurances.''
</P>
<P>
   But as details of the settlement emerged, some critics of the
merger said the two utilities got more than assurances. The critics
said they got the best of the deal, including keeping all cost
savings to themselves for the first four years of the merged
company's existence.
</P>
<P>
   The merger has picked up important political support in Kansas,
including that of Gov. Bill Graves, and some think the agreement
was hammered out, in part, because the Kansas Corporation
Commission staff didn't want to be blamed for torpedoing the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question they caved in,'' said Walker Hendrix, the
counsel for the Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board in Topeka, which
represents consumers on utility issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Foreman, a spokeswoman for the commission, said that
there was no political pressure and that the staff thought the
agreement was good policy.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would create a company called Westar Energy, which
would absorb KCP&AMP;L and Western's KG&AMP;E and KPL utilities. It would
have 1 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which is also supported by Topeka officials and
a local of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers,
comes as the commission completes its first week of hearings on the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Those hearings will continue, with the agreement becoming part
of the proceedings. The agreement is expected to smooth the way for
Kansas regulators to approve the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony filed a few weeks ago, the Kansas Corporation
Commission staff recommended that the combined company plow back
$24 million in annual rate relief to KG&AMP;E customers. The agreement
calls for rate rebates in 2001, 2002 and 2003 totaling $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   And the rate relief could be split among Kansas customers of
KPL, KG&AMP;E and KCP&AMP;L. The rebates would amount to only a few dollars
for residential customers, with the final allocation among the
utilities to be determined by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Wichita, which is served by KG&AMP;E, has argued that because its
residential rates are much higher than for KPL and KCP&AMP;L customers,
KG&AMP;E customers should get the rate relief to make them more equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Mayor Bob Knight of Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Rates would not increase in the first four years of the merged
company. But the merged company would be able to keep all cost
savings, which could amount to $300 million or more during the
moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Safer, the general counsel of the Kansas Corporation Commission,
said those savings could end up benefiting consumers because any
rate hearing after the moratorium would account for the lower cost
of service.
</P>
<P>
   But Hendrix of the Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board said the
merged company also would be able to recover other costs that make
further rate reduction more unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   In its previous testimony, the commission's staff said the
merged company could recover $230 million of the acquisition
premium _ the price paid for KCP&AMP;L over its book value _ from
Kansas consumers. The amount that it could recover has been
increased to $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the merged company would be able to recover
carrying charges on about $330 million in new plants that could be
collected after the rate moratorium. Those plants would also become
part of the cost of service in any rate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Western and KCP&AMP;L ``carved a fat hog,'' Hendrix said.
</P>
</TEXT>
