<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST'S LAWYER MAKES A VIGOROUS DENIAL OF SPYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Far from being an atomic spy, Wen Ho Lee is a loyal
American who cooperated in the government's hunt for real spies,
his lawyer has told two newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Mark O. Holscher of Los Angeles, issued a six-page
statement in which he said Lee had never ``given any classified
information to any unauthorized persons.'' Lee was fired from his
job as a scientist at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico amid suspicions that he passed classified nuclear weapons
information to China.
</P>
<P>
   Holscher said his client ``will not be a scapegoat for alleged
security problems at our country's nuclear laboratories,'' and that
he and his wife, Sylvia, had repeatedly cooperated with federal
investigators on the trail of Chinese agents.
</P>
<P>
   Holscher has previously issued denials on his client's behalf,
and it has been reported that Lee may have had earlier contacts
with the FBI. But Thursday's denial and assertion of his client's
patriotism, to be reported in The Washington Post and The Los
Angeles Times on Friday, were by far the most detailed remarks
regarding his client.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer's statement said that Lee took ``substantial steps''
to guarantee the safety of computer programs he had downloaded.
``We are confident that no third party could have or did access his
protected computer files,'' the statement said, according to The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Holscher said Lee cooperated with the FBI on an undercover
mission to Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory near San
Francisco in which a Taiwanese-born Livermore scientist was
investigated for possible espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also said trips Lee made to China in 1986 and 1988
had been approved by officials at the FBI, Los Alamos and the
Energy Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
