<SLUG> BC-SHIP-CARL-VINSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARTY WELCOME FOR SHIP'S CREW DEPLOYED SIX MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREMERTON, Wash. _ Streaked with corrosion and rust but with
sailors in immaculate white uniforms manning the rail, the aircraft
carrier USS Carl Vinson received a hero's welcome Thursday as it
returned home from a six-month deployment to the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier's 47,000-mile journey ended where it began exactly
six months ago as Navy tugs pushed the 95,000-ton warship into its
mooring spot at Puget Sound Naval Shipyard in Bremerton shortly
after 8:30 a.m. More than 5,000 family members and friends jammed
the narrow streets of the naval shipyard, transforming the
industrial facility into a sea of colored balloons and hand-painted
posters.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier reciprocated, serenading the crowd with classical
and pop music broadcast over its flight deck and releasing 5,000
colored balloons as it approached.
</P>
<P>
   The Carl Vinson served nearly half its time in the Persian Gulf
region, taking part in the final day of ``Operation Desert Fox,''
the four-day U.S.-British bombing campaign against Iraq in
mid-December, and conducting repeated air strikes against Iraqi
anti-aircraft units and other sites over the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very challenging and a very exciting time for us,''
said Rear Adm. Al Harms, who as commander of Carrier Group 3 led
the Vinson and eight escort ships to the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks into what had appeared to be a routine cruise to
the western Pacific and Indian Ocean, Harms received urgent orders
to abandon a scheduled visit to Australia and proceed directly to
the Persian Gulf. In fact, the admiral said, the nuclear-powered
carrier and two cruisers went ``ballistic'' for the last 2,000
miles, traveling non-stop at speeds in excess of 30 knots. The
ships sprinted through the Strait of Hormuz on Dec. 18, and
launched warplanes against Iraq the next night, he said. Two escort
ships fired Tomahawk cruise missiles at other Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved the concept of `ready on arrival' by being fully
ready, flexible, mobile and self-sustainable,'' Harms said.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier left Bremerton with 300 vacancies, nearly 10 percent
of the crew roster. However, as the deployment continued,
replacement personnel steadily arrived and by the end of the cruise
the ship and its air wing were at full strength, the admiral said.
</P>
<P>
   He credited new naval communications systems with enabling his
staff to be prepared for complex air strikes on short notice. ``We
were fully integrated'' with the U.S. Central Command headquarters
and were able to receive detailed operational plans, satellite
images and other intelligence data as the Vinson sprinted toward
the combat zone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The capability did not exist during the Persian Gulf War, when
the Navy could not talk directly to the other military services,
and daily targeting orders had to be photocopied and flown to the
carriers from Saudi Arabia, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Harms said he and Capt. David Crocker, the Vinson's commanding
officer, were especially proud of two facts: The carrier lost no
aircraft to hostile fire or accidents despite thousands of flights
conducted during the cruise, and there were no fatalities among the
combined ship and air wing crew of 5,000 personnel. Moreover, the
Carl Vinson was awarded the Battle E award recognizing it as the
outstanding carrier in the U.S Pacific Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent high-technology innovation greatly helped crew
morale during the six-month separation from family members, Vinson
sailors said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Internet and satellite telephone services, crew
members and their families were in nearly continuous contact via
e-mail and direct telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   Electrician's Mate 1st Class William LeVasseur III said he and
his wife, Susan, kept in daily contact throughout the deployment,
which meant much to him because she is pregnant with their second
child. Such a connection was unheard of when he joined the Navy 16
years ago, LeVasseur said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to have to write a letter, and it took two, three
weeks to get there,'' he recalled. ``And it took another two, three
weeks to get an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Aviation Ordnanceman Senior Chief Bill Sinyard, the
communications linking sailors and families kept crew morale
strong. ``This makes the work go by quicker and the days go by
easier,'' said Sinyard, a veteran of nine deployments.
</P>
<P>
   First off the ship upon arrival were about 50 sailors who had
become parents during the six months at sea. They were met by a
delegation of new mothers pushing strollers on the crowded pier.
</P>
</TEXT>
