<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY COUPLES IN L.A. REGISTER PARTNERSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles City Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg and
her partner of 20 years filled out forms Thursday to become one of
the first couples to register as domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg and Sharon Stricker were among dozens of same-sex
couples to seek purple-inked certificates on the first day the Los
Angeles County Registrar-Recorder offered domestic partner
registration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't confer any legal rights,'' Goldberg said. ``But we
do know that in the city of Los Angeles and the county of Los
Angeles, there are many employers who would be more than willing to
do domestic partner benefits if they didn't have to worry about,
Well, what exactly is a domestic partner?''
</P>
<P>
   County Assessor Kenneth Hahn said becoming an official domestic
partner means he and longtime companion Louis Mangual are no longer
``just two guys living down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're loving and committed,'' said Hahn, who was second in
line to register. ``It gives me great pleasure that this celebrates
our 25th anniversary. I'm just extra delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Over slices of ``Just Registered'' cake, the couples and gay and
lesbian activists said their ultimate goal _ civic marriage with
all its binding legal responsibilities _ will take years to get and
will be a tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the homosexual agenda, it's about civil
rights,'' said Andy Ball, public policy manager of the L.A. Gay and
Lesbian Center, a sponsor of the celebration Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, activists count domestic partner registration as an
important first step.
</P>
<P>
   Hahn said he has been pressing for this option for two years.
Goldberg joined in last year and enlisted the help of county
Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky so it would apply countywide.
Supervisors approved it a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page form requires only that the two people give their
name, address, date of birth and a signature. Optional information
can be included such as the length of a relationship, whether the
couple jointly own property or if they share a household.
</P>
<P>
   Registration costs $20 plus $6 for a certified copy. The
registry is also open to heterosexual couples who choose not to
marry, according to county officials.
</P>
<P>
   Some couples said registering was uneventful, but for Rebecca
Luckett, 28, and Lisa Belsanti, 30, who have been a couple for the
past 2{ years, the wait in line was nerve-racking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got butterflies even though we knew we weren't getting
married,'' said Luckett, a college student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems so sterile to come to a government office and fill
out paperwork, but it was exciting to sign it together,'' Belsanti
said. ``At least we know there's something that has a record of our
committed relationships to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas before it was just word of mouth,'' Luckett said
before they went for a ``honeymoon'' breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
