<HEADER>
A7757 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOXIC-SCHOOLS-LADN     05-07 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOXIC-SCHOOLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOXIC PROBLEMS HALT CONSTRUCTION AT TWO L.A. AREA SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ State environmental inspectors halted construction
temporarily at two primary schools in the San Fernando Valley after
finding toxic soil problems at both sites, possibly delaying their
planned September openings.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental problems at Valerio Primary Care Center in Van
Nuys and Monroe Primary Care Center in Panorama City are the latest
in a series of site contamination problems that have plagued the
Los Angeles Unified School District. The most serious stalled
construction of the Belmont Learning Complex downtown and were
supposed to lead to tighter controls.
</P>
<P>
   If the primary centers in the Valley aren't completed on time,
540 children will be forced to double up at three elementary
schools in the area, according to Gordon Wohlers, assistant
superintendent in charge of policy, research and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, in these very overcrowded areas, extra space
doesn't exist,'' Wohlers said after warning board members that the
deadlines must be met to avoid shuffling around the students.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it is still possible Valerio and Monroe could be
ready for occupancy Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Soil samples from the Valerio site revealed that trace levels of
pesticides, probably from gardening in the past, cover the 3.4-acre
lot. In addition, the results of lead testing won't be completed
until Monday, said Erik Nasarenko, a spokesman for the district.
</P>
<P>
   If the tests do not find elevated levels of contaminants,
Nasarenko said, the district will remove the top six inches of soil
next week and test the ground underneath it to determine whether
toxins seeped below the surface level.
</P>
<P>
   Barring any deep contamination, another four- to five-foot layer
of dirt will be excavated and replaced with clean fill.
Construction should proceed at the end of this month, Nasarenko
said.
</P>
<P>
   Delays at the Monroe site arose after a ``miscommunication''
between the project contractor and the district, according to Hamid
Saebfar, chief of Southern California cleanup for the state
Department of Toxic Substances Control.
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD Environmental Health and Safety Branch had performed
the required testing at the site and received approval from the
state, but failed to monitor the contractor's actions. Days after
the soil samples were taken, the contractor added tons of dirt to
the land from an outside source that had not been tested, Saebfar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Additional soil tests at Monroe were completed Thursday
afternoon and revealed that toxin levels at the site are not
dangerous. Construction is scheduled to resume Monday, Nasarenko
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the bungling has held up work for at least a week
and prompted board members to question why the Environmental Health
and Safety Branch failed to follow new rules that ensure all soil
is tested. The new procedures were put into place following the
problems at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Board member David Tokofsky said that with all the new schools
being built, the district should make sure the regulations in place
after Belmont are being followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should get these new rules down,'' Tokofsky said at
Thursday's committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nasarenko said the mix-up at Monroe will cost the district ``a
few thousand dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Several recent leadership changes in the Environmental Health
and Safety Branch had nothing to do with the problem, Nasarenko
insisted. But, in the future, no grading or excavation can occur
without the permission of the branch's deputy director, Yi Hwa Kim,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
