<SLUG> BC-DELIVERY-EXPANSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY DELIVERY SERVICE WITH EXPANSION PLANS ACQUIRES RIVAL
WESTWIND EXPRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Westwind Express, a delivery service based in
Ventura County north of Los Angeles, with seven locations
nationwide, has been purchased by an East Coast rival.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Delivery &AMP; Logistics of Clifton, N.J., bought
Westwind for $5.5 million to expand its operations on the West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to grow dramatically _ from Seattle to San Diego,''
said Drew Kronick, a vice president at Consolidated. ``Westwind has
an exceptional reputation in the marketplace and a history of very
strong profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwind co-founder Steven Keihner said he and his father James
decided to sell. The Keihners had received other buyout offers but
chose Consolidated because the company gave them a better deal and
they liked the management. Consolidated also had an aura of
professionalism and sophistication not often seen in the courier
services industry, Keihner said.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old Consolidated had 1998 sales of $185.7 million,
growing mainly through acquisitions. Westwind, a 15-year-old firm
with $7 million in annual sales and 250 employees, is
Consolidated's 24th purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Westwind will not be laying off any people or closing its
offices in Van Nuys, Palmdale, Ontario, Fresno, Sacramento, Kansas
City and Lexena, Mo., as a result of the purchase. However,
Westwind will be renamed Consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Keihner will become Consolidated's West Coast regional
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can grow with them,'' said the 38-year-old Keihner.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, Consolidated has offices in Los Angeles,
Burlingame, Santa Rosa and Seattle. It employs 3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Consolidated increased 18.75 cents to $3.3125, or 6
percent, on 20,100 shares traded, more than double the 20-day
average volume.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
