<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE THEIR PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Anaheim Angels began the 1999 season with
legitimate concerns about their pitching, but thinking their
offense would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how things turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, though, was laughing in the Angels clubhouse after
Thursday's 4-2 loss to the Detroit Tigers before 12,510 at Tiger
Stadium. The Angels lost two of three to the Tigers and scored only
seven runs in the three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pitched great for three games,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``And believe me, I'm not taking anything away from
the Tigers pitching staff, but when you've got to shut a team out
to win, there's trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to pick the offense up. We come in and score seven
runs in the series. You're not going to win many games that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels wasted a solid performance by starter Chuck Finley
(1-3) _ 71/3 innings, four runs, 10 hits, eight strikeouts, one
walk. But they couldn't do much with Tigers starter Bryce Florie
(1-0) and five Tigers relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers got just enough offense _ three hits and an RBI from
ex-Angel Damion Easley and a two-run homer by former Taft High star
Gabe Kapler (No. 2). The Angels' only runs scored on solo homers by
Todd Greene (No. 5 in the fifth inning) and Garret Anderson (No. 6
in the sixth).
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe every run we scored in this series was via home
run,'' Collins correctly noted. ``That tells you something.''
</P>
<P>
   What it tells Collins is that the Angels are failing to do the
little things to score runs. And with an offense that has in recent
days lost Tim Salmon (sprained left wrist) for three games and
Randy Velarde (stiff back) for one, every little bit counts.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson was a last-minute replacement for Velarde at second
base Thursday, and came up in key situations. In the third inning,
Huson came to the plate with the bases loaded and one out, but
ended the inning by grounding into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, he batted with runners on first and third with two
out and flied out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Huson was batting in Velarde's No. 2 spot in the lineup, and
Velarde is hitting .336. He said he's scheduled to have an MRI test
performed today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt this pain before during the week, but it gradually got
worse,'' he said. ``(Thursday) I tried to hit in the batting cage,
and even when I tried to jog it was real tight. Any time it's a
back, it's something to be concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has plenty of concerns these days as he tries to field a
lineup that must stay in contention until Salmon, Velarde, Jim
Edmonds and Gary DiSarcina get back.
</P>
<P>
   They held their own with Mo Vaughn out of the lineup, but ``when
Mo was out we had several guys swinging the bat better than they
are now,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   It has made things a little frustrating for the starting
pitchers as well. In the three games with Detroit, Ken Hill, Steve
Sparks and Finley each pitched at least seven innings. They
combined for 221/3 innings and allowed six runs, but left town with
only one win among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a starting pitcher, you can't get wrapped up in that,''
said Finley, who hasn't won since his first start of the season
April 9. ``As a starter, you've got to go deep into the game, go
seven or eight innings and take your chances. The offense has their
thing and the pitchers have their thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, though, showed frustration in the eighth inning when he
wanted a new baseball, and fired the old one in to catcher Charlie
O'Brien at about 90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably just a little frustrated _ I usually don't do
stuff like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finley has pitched into the seventh inning or longer in each of
his past three starts but has nothing to show for it. And he says
it's tough to look at the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going to the shrink and he tells you everything's
going to be all right,'' he said. ``But when you leave the office,
you don't feel any better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
