<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-REVIEW-ANA     05-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-REVIEW-ANALYSIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIP TO LOTTERY STATUS LEAVES FRANCHISE AT CROSSROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is like being bounced from a first-class seat to
the worst in coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics these days are in the rear of the airplane, in a seat
that just does not recline.
</P>
<P>
   Uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is undeniable throughout an organization that just
three years ago soared to the NBA Finals. The Sonics were on the
cusp of Western Conference supremacy. But in what seems like a snap
of the finger, they have failed to make the playoffs for the first
time in nine seasons, spiraling from contender to the NBA draft
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is as simple as looking at a situation and
saying `Well, that team failed and they can't get it done
anymore,''' first-year Sonics coach Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   So how did it happen?
</P>
<P>
   As fast as it seems, the Sonics' undoing has been slow. It does
not rest solely on this 25-25, lockout-abbreviated season. In fact,
the team has not advanced past the second round of the playoffs
since the 1996 title run.
</P>
<P>
   Why? There are a number of factors:
</P>
<P>
   CURIOUSLY SHAKEN UP
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the team that pushed the Chicago Bulls to six
games in the 1996 NBA Finals was not given a second chance.
Starting center Ervin Johnson was allowed to sign elsewhere as a
free agent. The Sonics also did not bring back Vincent Askew and
Frank Brickowski, each of whom played key roles that season.
</P>
<P>
   That group of players brought toughness and meshed on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Although the team's core of players remained intact, the Sonics
returned the following season with a noticeably weaker roster.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Wally Walker signed free agent center Jim
McIlvaine, a move that still haunts the Sonics even though he was
traded before this season. McIlvaine's limited production often had
the Sonics playing four-on-five.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Larry Stewart and Craig Ehlo proved just as
futile. The Sonics' lack of toughness and rebounding compelled them
to sign veteran Terry Cummings midway through that 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   FAILURE TO PLACATE KEMP
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the Sonics found themselves reaching for more than
just playoff wins. The McIlvaine signing set off a ripple effect
that ultimately cost the team power forward Shawn Kemp. Kemp
loathed that the Sonics signed McIlvaine to a seven-year, $33
million deal in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics also rewarded All-Star point guard Gary Payton with
an $87 million contract in 1996. The soonest they could sweeten
Kemp's contract was October of 1998. The team said it planned to
reward Kemp, but he was unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kemp eventually forced a trade, the Sonics virtually had
to start over.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp and Payton were supposed to be a new-and-improved John
Stockton and Karl Malone. As it turned out, the Kemp-Sonic divorce
allowed the Utah Jazz to stake claim on the West. Utah, with only
minor tinkering, has played in the last two NBA Finals and is
favored to reach a third.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics got All-Star Vin Baker in a three-team exchange for
Kemp, but they have been busy trying to doctor their chemistry ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   THE GEORGE KARL FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   While no one can dispute his coaching record , it could be
argued that former Sonics coach George Karl did not sustain the
growth of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Karl did not entrust young players to provide significant
contributions. He relied solely on veterans and was unable to
develop rookies, which mortgaged the future of the team. The most
recent example is point guard Eric Snow, traded so Karl could play
veteran Greg Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   This team could have used Snow, who played his first two NBA
seasons with the Sonics. Instead, Snow became a starter with the
Philadelphia 76ers. His strong defense and ballhandling allowed
Allen Iverson to move to the shooting guard _ a switch the Sonics
would welcome for Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Karl was often stubborn. His personality clashed with a number
of players _ Askew, Johnson and Kendall Gill to name a few _ who
Karl ultimately ran out of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the Sonics have begun each season with an average of
six new players.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Westphal replaced Karl as coach. The team also
welcomed eight new players and a new system that included the
development of rookies but minimal defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight it's easy to say that those things had an adverse
affect,'' Walker said. ``But when you're in the situation at the
time, and in those two years (following 1996) we won 118 games, you
think a lot of things are going right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, when you fall short, you look back and say this or that
could have been better or different. For a variety of reasons we
weren't as good as we needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Walker has reached a serious crossroad.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Payton and Detlef Schrempf, he is
responsible for another roster that did not cut it. His intention
was to make the team younger, bigger and more athletic. However,
the Sonics still appeared old, too small and too slow this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the responsibility that we are where we are,'' Walker
told The Associated Press. ``We've just got to take our lumps and
not make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' goals in the offseason are clear-cut. A priority is
to re-sign Baker, who will opt to become a free agent, and add a
tough, defensive-minded center. If the Sonics cannot find an
explosive guard who can create his own shot, they will try to land
a quality point guard and move Payton to the shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   But first they hope to get a solid player from the draft
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Next season will be more of the same. Starting
over without any promises.
</P>
<P>
   Fasten your seatbelt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
