<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7766 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-ROCKET-SPI &LR;      05-07 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ROCKET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING INVESTIGATORS CONFIDENT THEY'LL FIND ROCKET ENGINE'S
MALFUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The second-stage engine on The Boeing Co.'s new Delta
3 rocket fired for only one second of a burn that was supposed to
last nearly three minutes, which left a $230 million Asian
communications satellite stranded in a useless orbit, investigators
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But they are confident the cause of the engine malfunction can
be found and fixed in time to possibly fly Delta 3 before the end
of the year _ this time successfully.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the record for Boeing's important Delta 3 program is
0-2. The first rocket exploded on its maiden flight last August.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators do not know why the engine abruptly shut down
without being commanded to do so after what looked to be a
successful launch Tuesday night from Cape Canaveral, Fla. But they
said the rocket sent back a wealth of good telemetry data to ground
tracking stations that can be analyzed to help find the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigative team now has a good focus with regard to
what we want to do,'' Russell Reck, Boeing's director of
engineering technology for its launch systems, told reporters
Thursday during a teleconference. He is leading the investigative
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are headed in the right direction,'' he added. ``I'm very
optimistic ... we will have some resolution to this problem in a
reasonable length of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the latest problem, Delta 3 was next scheduled to loft an
ICO communications satellite into orbit during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Witzling, Boeing's vice president of Delta 2 and Delta 3
programs, said during the teleconference he believes Delta 3 will
fly again before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to fly successfully,'' he said. ``We are
committed to making Delta 3 work.''
</P>
<P>
   While the investigators focus on the rocket, engineers for
Hughes, which built the Orion 3 satellite for Loral, are trying to
put the spacecraft into a low-Earth parking orbit to give them more
time to study options for possibly salvaging the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Those options include an astronaut rescue mission using the
space shuttle, sending the misplaced satellite around the moon and
back to ease it into the correct orbit, or using the craft's
on-board engine to push it into the proper orbit.
</P>
<P>
   None of those options at this point look particularly promising,
said Hughes spokesman Don O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Even if NASA agreed, a shuttle rescue mission probably could not
be launched in time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't leave it there for four or five years waiting for a
mission from NASA,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes has in the past sent a misplaced satellite around the
moon to slingshot it into the proper Earth orbit after it was left
in a useless orbit by a Russian rocket that failed.
</P>
<P>
   Had the launch gone as planned, after the satellite separated
from Delta 3 its small on-board engine would have been sufficient
to kick it into a circular orbit 22,300 miles above the equator.
</P>
<P>
   To buy some time, Hughes engineers Thursday were in the process
of moving the satellite into a nearly circular orbit of 1,100
kilometers at its low point to 1,300 kilometers at the high point.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite can remain in that orbit for as long as three
years before it re-enters the Earth's atmosphere and burns up. But
after a year or so the electronic systems would be damaged by the
radiation belts that circle the Earth, O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is part of the Boeing-led investigative team, as is
Loral, the Air Force, Lockheed Martin and Pratt &AMP; Whitney, the
maker of the second-stage engine for Delta 3.
</P>
<P>
   The second stage on Delta 3 is similar to the upper stage on an
Air Force Titan 4B rocket that did not work properly last Friday
after its launch from Cape Canaveral. Investigators said the
Titan's upper stage misfired and placed an $800 million military
communications satellite into a useless orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is part of the Delta 3 investigative board
because it makes the Titan.
</P>
<P>
   The RLB10-2 second stage engine on Delta 3 was supposed to fire
twice following separation from the first stage.
</P>
<P>
   The first 10-minute burn was successful and the telemetry data
shows nothing unusual occurred, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   After about 10 minutes, the engine was supposed to fire again,
this time for nearly three minutes. Instead, it suddenly shut down
after only a second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
