<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-THREAT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESCOTT VALLEY TEENS CHARGED IN SCHOOL SHOOTING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT VALLEY, Ariz. _ Two teenagers were charged Thursday in
what police say was a meticulous plan for shooting classmates and
teachers, and 400 parents demanded to know why they weren't warned
about the threats.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified teens, 13- and 14-year-old students at Liberty
Traditional School, were picked up Wednesday and charged Thursday
with misdemeanor counts of disorderly conduct and threatening and
intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities originally had considered charging them with
conspiracy to commit murder and solicitation to commit murder.
</P>
<P>
   Yavapai County Sheriff's spokeswoman Sharron Wachter said the
14-year-old confirmed a plot that the 13-year-old had described to
authorities on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old sketched a diagram, showing how the two planned
to position themselves on rooftops at the kindergarten through
eighth-grade school, what weapons they would use, what walkways
they would target and their escape routes, Wachter said.
</P>
<P>
   The pair also targeted specific students and teachers, she said,
and both teens expressed interest in ``Nazi philosophies.''
</P>
<P>
   No weapons were found and there was no evidence of Internet
usage in either boy's home, she said. No more arrests are expected.
</P>
<P>
   But coming weeks after the massacre at Columbine High in
Littleton, Colo., the arrests sent shock waves through this booming
bedroom community in the rolling hills east of Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies were called Wednesday by two teachers concerned that
Principal Carol Lyons had taken no action on the threats. They told
deputies that the teenagers had been making threatening statements
about shooting teachers and students since January.
</P>
<P>
   But Humboldt Unified School District Superintendent Gary Spikes
disputed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of comments a couple of weeks ago,'' he
told emotional parents in the school gym Thursday night. ``The
statement was made, `If I was to do that, I'd take the teachers out
first.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He said the two teens have been suspended indefinitely and Lyons
has been placed on paid administrative leave.
</P>
<P>
   The parents criticized administrators for not notifying them
Thursday morning, even though the teens were picked up Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers told my kids that they weren't supposed ot talk
about it,'' said Debbie Griffin, a mother of two Liberty students.
``You're playing Russian roulette with the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise St. Clar, who teaches second grade at Liberty, said the
incident had been ``blown totally out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was like any other day here,'' she said. ``I took my
class on a field trip, nobody was worried and we were assured that
everything was safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Wasem's jaw dropped when told of the arrests. She was
preparing to enroll her 5-year-old daughter at Liberty next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goodness, I have another child at Bradshaw Mountain High
School, and they just had two evacuations there because of
threats,'' Wasem said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this traditional school would be the safest
alternative of all. I guess this is happening everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old Liberty school is a public school of about 350
students. It emphasizes traditional teaching methods, and every
parent is expected to take part in school activities.
</P>
<P>
   In a note Thursday afternoon to parents of Liberty students,
school administrators said, ``There are no serious issues of
student safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rita Frye, co-owner of Self Defense Academy, a Prescott
Valley martial-arts school, said all the recent threats of violence
in the local schools had been doing wonders for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've grown quickly, from 40 to 80 students,'' Frye said.
``Parents say they are very concerned about all of these things,
even here in a little town like this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057, or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
