<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7788 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-VOLLEYBALL-LADN     05-07 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-VOLLEYBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYU BEATS PENN STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brigham Young's two first-team All-Americans, who
were feared to be ill with an ``intense intestinal distress'' on
the eve of the NCAA Men's Volleyball Championship, recovered nicely
for the semifinal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ossie Antonetti had 24 kills and 14 digs and Ryan Millar had 20
kills and four blocks for the top-seeded Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars felt right at home with a boisterous fan base
cheering them on as the eliminated Penn State, 10-15, 15-15, 15-11,
15-5, in opening semifinal match in front of at UCLA's Pauley
Pavilion Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up this morning and felt better,'' Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a perfect match, but BYU coach Carl McGown will take
it. This is the Cougars first appearance in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first game, Penn State's serving and receiving was
exceptional well,'' McGown said. ``As the match progressed I don't
think we ever were good in the match, but our receiving got better.
I hope that we can play better than that Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   BYU (29-1) will play the winner of the Long Beach State-Indiana
Purdue Fort Wayne semifinal, played late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The closer the Cougars (29-1) came within winning the match,
their fans starting chanting ``bring on the beach.'' Their only
loss came at the hand of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions opened the match, hitting .353 to take the
lead, but they faltered offensively in the second game. They had 13
attack errors and hit .083, while the Cougars easily tied the
match, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ossie Antonetti, who had eight kills but five errors in the
opener, was errorless in Game 2 with six kills. The Cougars also
put up a ferocious block, with five team blocks compared to one by
the Nittany Lions.
</P>
<P>
   With the momentum on their side, the Cougars went ahead 7-3 and
8-4 in the third game, but their lead didn't last long. PSU
rallied, scoring five unanswered point to take their first lead in
the game on a kill by Tony Mazzullo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cougars regained the lead, 10-9, on a kill by Rich
Lambourne (10 kills, eight digs) and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   BYU ran away from the Nittany Lions in Game 4, opening with a
7-1 advantage, and never relenting. On match point, Millar made a
spectacular save, when he dug the ball with his foot to keep it in
play. The Nittany Lions were out of position and setter Jose
Quiones hit into the net to end the match.
</P>
<P>
   BYU, which leads the country in hitting percentage, hit .344.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed flashes of being able to play with anyone and then
flashes of being a junior high school girls team, not being able to
hit the ball on the court,'' Penn State coach Mark Pavlik.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Miller had 20 kills, and Mazzullo had 15 kills, but also 15
errors. The Nittany Lions hit .204. They finished their season,
22-13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
