<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS     05-07 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS INDOMITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dominik who?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins said all the right things going into
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's opener against the Sabres. They said they
respected Dominik Hasek's ability, his Hart and Vezina trophies,
and his Olympic gold medal. They also talked about ways to beat the
Buffalo goalie. They talked about shooting and shooting and then
shooting some more.
</P>
<P>
   But didn't you wonder, just a little bit? Didn't you fret the
Bruins were going to be just a little intimidated going against the
unorthodox Dominator after his sweep of the Ottawa Senators in
Round 1 and considering the Bruins went 1-4 in the regular season
against Buffalo?
</P>
<P>
   Be honest. You wondered just a little, didn't you?
</P>
<P>
   Well, wonder no more.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins showed there is no respect like self-respect as they
defeated the Sabres, 4-2, in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference
semifinals at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth straight playoff win for Boston, which got
solid netminding from its own Vezina finalist, Byron Dafoe (28
saves).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to stay focused when you come off winning a first
round like that,'' said coach Pat Burns, who had cautioned his team
about being too high coming off the series win over the Hurricanes.
``It's very important that everybody relaxes, even after tonight,
and have our two feet firmly planted on the ground and that the
helmets will fit tomorrow. It's only one step and many steps to go.
They got the message, and I think they handled themselves well.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been pointed out many times that one of the keys to the
Bruins' attack is contribution from the top line, which was only
so-so against Carolina. Center Jason Allison, who had six assists
in six games against the Hurricanes but no goals, was a force
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. He had four shots in the opening 20 minutes and
was buzzing all around the Buffalo zone. He potted his first goal
of the playoffs at 13:59 with Boston on the power play, increasing
his point streak to seven games. Allison took a pass from Darren
Van Impe and skated through the right circle toward Hasek.
Defenseman Richard Smehlik tried to lay the lumber on Allison, but
Allison had built up a head of steam and kept on going. He fired a
shot that went off Hasek's left shoulder and popped over the
netminder and into the cage for a 1-0 lead, providing a giant lift.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Khristich dinged his right shoulder when he checked
Sabres defenseman Rhett Warrener at 18:27 of the first but he shook
it off and not only came back to play but scored his first two
goals of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At 15:21 of the second, Allison skated around the net and
centered a pass for Kyle McLaren. McLaren fanned on the shot and
the puck found its way to Khristich, who was parked at the left
post. He batted it out of the air, giving Boston a 2-0 lead. It
extended Khristich's point streak to four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres battled back at 18:19, tallying a power-play goal
during a four-on-three advantage. Jason Woolley set up defense
partner Alexei Zhitnik for a one-timer from the right circle and it
eluded Dafoe's glove to pull Buffalo to 2-1. It ended Dafoe's
scoreless streak at 134 minutes 49 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins regained their two-goal advantage in the final
seconds of the period when Joe Thornton potted his second goal of
the playoffs. With the Bruins on the power play, Van Impe dished a
pass to Ray Bourque, who fired a shot from the point that went off
Thornton and past Hasek with 13.3 seconds remaining. The goal
increased Thornton's point streak to five games, with two goals and
four assists in that span.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres made it interesting at 9:37 of the third when they
converted a Boston turnover into an unassisted Woolley goal to pull
within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But they could get no closer, and Khristich closed out the
scoring with an empty-netter at 19:48.
</P>
<P>
   At least for a night, Hasek proved mortal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals we scored, there's nothing Dominik could do,'' said
Burns. ``Khristich's (first) goal, I don't care who you are, you're
not going to stop that. Same with Joe Thornton's goal. Who's going
to stop those, whether your name is Dominik Hasek or whatever your
name is? That's nothing to do with him being on top of his game.
He's still on top of his game, we just found a way, that's all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-07 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TOOK NO TIME FOR HASEK TO BECOME SORE SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One game into the series, the Bruins are already tired
of answering questions about the other team's goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he let some goals in this year,'' sniffed coach Pat
Burns. ``His goals-against average was not 0.00.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of silly,'' declared Jason Allison, who had a vital
first goal and a superb assist. ``We won, 4-2, we played great, and
all anyone wants to talk about is that Dominik Hasek got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   We are guilty as charged. Journalists are always searching for
The Hook, and in this Eastern Conference semifinal confrontation
The Hook is The Goalkeeper. And why not? Here is a twice, and,
perhaps, future MVP and Olympic hero for the ages who has just come
off a playoff series where he carried his team to victory. Not for
nothing is he called The Dominator.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday &UR;  &LR; night he was, if not Mr. Ordinary, at least Mr.
Beatable. Well, kinda. He had no chance on goals two and three.
Four was a Dmitri Khristich empty-netter. He wasn't horrible. He
just got beat.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. I'd better not let the coach hear me say that. He didn't
get beat. They got beat. If I'm not careful, Pat Burns will wash my
mouth out with lye.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the only part of their game,'' reminded Burns. ``We
have other things to worry about in these games other than Dominik
Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, sure. That makes sense. But let's not have these
people attempt to tell us that it didn't give them a huge lift when
they got on the scoreboard first against the Buffalo Sabres and
their Dominator, courtesy of an Allison goal that had the phrase
``big-time'' written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they had that many good chances,'' said Hasek.
``I don't want to say they had lucky goals. But they did get the
first goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the first goal. One thing everyone on both sides could
agree on: the first goal in this game was hugely huge and even
humungous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first goal in a game between teams that can play defense
like these two,'' observed the ballyhooed Michael Peca, ``gives you
a big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bearing down on the right side, Allison fought off some
pressure, held his shot, waited for the great man to make a move
and then beat him over the left shoulder at 13:59 of the first
period. You don't score that goal unless you really know what
you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to carry it in like that was a natural goal
scorer's move,'' lauded Steve Heinze, himself an invaluable guy of
late. ``He did what he did, knowing he was going to get whacked and
hacked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought it in,'' explained Allison. ``He goes down a lot. I
saw him go down and I tried to get it over him.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison initiated the action on the second Boston goal as well.
This time he came swooping down the left side, went behind the
cage, and then whipped a pass to Kyle McLaren, who got it to an
uncovered Khristich on Hasek's right. Khristich tapped it in. Hasek
was powerless to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Goal No. 3 was scored by Joe Thornton, who somehow managed to
get a stick on a Ray Bourque blast from the point. How the puck got
by Hasek might forever remain a mystery. But it most certainly
counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Khristich goal there was nothing Dominik could do,''
maintained Burns. ``The Joe Thornton goal? Who's gonna stop that?
It doesn't matter if your name is Dominik Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Burns is knocking Hasek. I don't doubt he has
great respect for the man. But the Boston mentor has got to
convince his team that Hasek is a man, and not a legend. He has to
fill them with confidence. That's part A. Part B is that he's got a
damn good goaltender himself, and he'd like the world to know about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear as much about our guy because his name is Byron
Dafoe and not Dominik Hasek,'' said Burns. ``But Byron is gaining
stature in the National Hockey League. And I said this morning that
there is more pressure in this series on Dominik Hasek than there
is on Byron Dafoe. It's like being a 50-goal scorer. People expect
a certain production from you once you've done it. But he's only
human. He lets goals in. So I'm not surprised we scored a few.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always pressure on the goalie,'' countered Hasek,
``especially in the playoffs. One goal can be the difference in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a whole lot more to this Boston victory than just the
idea that the red light was actually lit three times behind Dominik
Hasek. Ray Bourque was positively ubiquitous, dishing out hit after
hit, breaking up plays, and initiating offense. Thirty-eight? Not
possible. Allison was simply sensational. Dafoe did what he had to
do. And although you won't see Heinze's name on the scoresheet, be
it known he had another strong game which included drawing two
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You noticed, huh?'' he smiled. ``I didn't think you guys
noticed things like that. It was just hard work. You want to help
the team any way you can.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, they all figured they'd know what to expect when they
picked up the paper or flipped on the TV this morning. ``Oh,
sure,'' said Allison. ``All the hype has been about Dominik. He's a
great goalie, but he's human. If some people are going to say that
the story tonight is that we beat him, that's fine. I've been
reading for three days now how one man's going to win the Stanley
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with saying that, as long as you realize
it is very early in the series. The Bruins would do well to listen
to their newly-bearded leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you beat him,'' said Bourque, ``you count your blessings,
and you move on to the next game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 0218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
