<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BO     05-07 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MAY HAVE SUFFERED LOSS IN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bret Saberhagen always knew the road back wouldn't be
easy. Even in victory, the Red Sox starter wasn't surprised to
learn he would endure yet another round of pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   But this time there will be no rush to judgment or treatments
designed to expedite the healing process. No matter what the
doctors say, Saberhagen will have an MRI Friday and then accept a
spot on the disabled list to rehabilitate the muscle strain in his
right shoulder that won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated,'' Saberhagen said after lasting only three
innings in a 3-2 victory at Fenway Park that gave the Sox a split
of a two-game series with the Texas Rangers. ``I do stuff to get
this strong and get to this point. What can you say? The team has
been struggling. I feel like I can help the team, but I can't help
the team when I'm feeling this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Saberhagen's injury, the Sox would have had a lot to
celebrate. On the eve of Mo Vaughn's return, Boston won with sharp
hitting. Jose Offerman went 3 for 5. John Valentin, Damon Buford,
and Trot Nixon had big hits.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 21,412 went home happy after seeing relievers Derek
Lowe, Rheal Cormier, and Tim Wakefield perform beautifully after
replacing Saberhagen at the start of the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that seemed to fade into the background afterward,
when it was obvious that Saberhagen's condition had taken center
stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are expected to make a move Friday to fill Saberhagen's
spot. The details are sketchy, but one thing is certain, according
to Sox general manager Dan Duquette: ``There is no pitching,'' he
said. ``Anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this may have come to fruition had Saberhagen not
injured himself April 24 while facing Cleveland. Thursday &UR;  &LR; night,
after throwing 43 pitches, Saberhagen returned to the mound to warm
up and felt something familiar. The stiffness he had experienced
before returned. It felt like a knot, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no warning,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams when asked
to explain how Saberhagen could reinjure himself without anyone
knowing something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear any statements from anyone that there was any
problem,'' he said. ``I was still in the dugout when I looked out
and saw Bret standing on the mound, looking our way. I knew that
was not good.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good throwing on the side in between starts,'' said
Saberhagen. ``I felt good Friday and Monday. I've been getting up
and down. I don't know if it (the shoulder) is fatigued or just
stiffens up somehow and causes a knot that affects the shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen's replacements, Lowe and Cormier, did their part in
keeping the Texans in tow while the Boston lead grew to 2-0, 2-1,
and 3-1. In the ninth inning, the Sox called upon a rare trump card
when Wakefield relieved Cormier with one out, a runner on second
and Boston clinging to a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield retired the only two batters he faced _ picking up his
first career save _ by getting Lee Stevens to ground to third and
pinch hitter Luis Alicea to fly to right.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield hasn't fared particularly well as a starter this year,
but he did just fine as the Sox' closer in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always told me he would put on the spikes if we needed
him,'' said Williams. ``Nobody even knew he was out there for a
while. But we're trying to win ballgames. Even though he has to
pitch in two days, we'll use every sound arm we can get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
