<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG RELIEF FOR WAKEFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WAKEFIELD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He's often joked about starting 30 games and relieving
30 games, and if you don't think Tim Wakefield can do it, well,
don't be so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Wakefield played the role of Tom Gordon,
pitching two-thirds of an inning to earn his first career save in a
3-2 Red Sox victory over the Texas Rangers at Fenway Park.
Wakefield is still scheduled to start Saturday night against
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a night the Red Sox look back upon as a turning point,
despite Bret Saberhagen having to leave the game after three strong
innings because of shoulder stiffness that will place him in an MRI
machine Friday morning and on the disabled list. The bullpen, which
had been catastrophic of late, seemed to end its slide with strong
performances by Derek Lowe (2 1/3 innings, one run), Rheal Cormier
(3 innings, one run), and finally Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield had informed manager Jimy Williams, as he has in the
past, that he would be available to come out of the bullpen if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   When Saberhagen couldn't start the fourth, Wakefield ran out to
the bullpen to get himself ready if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart's still beating a thousand miles an hour,'' said
Wakefield. ``It's a great feeling to be standing out there at the
end shaking everyone's hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield has been in a slump as a starter, allowing 18 earned
runs and 26 hits in his last 15 innings. He is a knuckleballer and
his streaks start one way and go the other when he's boosted by a
performance. This might have been it.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen coach John Cumberland, who watched Wakefield throw
before the game, also monitored him during the eighth and ninth
innings and came away feeling he had a good knuckleball working.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to be a confidence boost for him,'' said
Cumberland. ``It's a huge lift for Tim and it's a huge lift for the
team. We've been slumping lately, but you can't say enough about
this performance and the job the guys did ahead of him tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield recalls saves in the minors, when he was in the
Pittsburgh Pirates system. He recalls playing one game at second
base and then coming on to pitch the final three innings for the
save.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, the Red Sox held a 3-1 lead heading into the
ninth. Williams elected to stay with Cormier, who was pitching with
great confidence. Cormier induced Rafael Palmeiro to line softly to
Nomar Garciaparra, but Ivan Rodriguez rocketed a single off the
wall before Todd Zeile doubled him in with a shot to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Even with lefthanded batter Lee Stevens coming up, Williams, who
also had righthander Kip Gross warming, called for Wakefield. The
knuckleballer fell behind, 2-0, to Stevens before getting the
benefit of a high strike called by home plate umpire Rick Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens then muscled a knuckler to John Valentin at third, who
threw him out at first. Former Red Sox second baseman Luis Alicea
pinch hit for shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt and flew out to Trot Nixon
in right, preserving the win and ending a stretch of five straight
games in which the Red Sox had blown a save and six out of seven
since Gordon went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a novelty,'' said Williams. ``He's been a reliever
before. Maybe it was a different look. If ever he was going to go
out there in relief, it was going to be today.''
</P>
<P>
   The few scouts who were around the ballpark, who normally like
to clock the speed of the closer's pitches, turned off their radar
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Wakefield had done to change his approach worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game of adjustments and I hadn't been making them
mentally,'' he said. ``Tonight, it worked out. I helped win a game
and I'm happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield could not explain the dynamic of being the pitcher who
closes a game as opposed to one who starts and gets the win. But he
probably was going to go home to think about it and hope it carries
over into his start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might get a chance in middle relief, but I was
surprised I got in there in the ninth,'' said Wakefield. ``My job
was come in and keep the runner on first and get the guys out at
the plate. It worked out tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
