<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON'S GOAL PROVIDES SHOT OF CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The puck was in the net, tucked neatly over Dominik
Hasek's left shoulder and it was, oh, about one one-millionth of a
second later that the obvious thought crossed Byron Dafoe's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Dafoe, ``we got our one.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be more, of course, three to be exact, before the
Bruins exited the Vault with their 4-2 playoff win Thursday &UR;  &LR; night
over the Sabres. But Allison's first goal of the post-season was
the biggest, because it provided that instant booster shot of
confidence that Hasek so seldomly affords the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   For proof of that, if you need it, go to your favorite Internet
provider and plug in the key words ``Hasek'' and ``Nagano.''
Warning: You may get a blank screen, which is precisely what the
rest of the world saw when facing the Dominator in the 1998
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, without a goal in Boston's first-round victory over
Carolina, played his most impressive game since joining the Bruins
just over two years ago. He was strong on the puck, at times
looking like an elongated, somewhat gangly Peter Forsberg, the
heralded Avalanche centerman who is as tough to knock off the puck
as Alan Dershowitz is to knock off the Larry King Show.
</P>
<P>
   With 6:01 to go in the first period, Allison gained the blue
line on right wing and did a power sashe past Buffalo defenseman
Richard Smehlik. In order to keep his pace to the net, Allison had
to suffer a healthy bump from the 6-foot-3-inch defenseman, but
just kept skating, throwing off the whack as if it were just a
pesty gnat along Alligator Alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing, really,'' said Allison. ``As long as I've got the
puck on the outside, he can hit you on the arms, or the leg, that
really doesn't make much of a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the sequence had Hasek dropping down to cover the
ice at the right post and Allison roofing a short wrister to the
top right corner. Come game's end, the Bruins would show 46 minutes
and 1 second of lead time. When Hasek's at his best, he can go
substantial chunks of the season without working in arrears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I elevated my game a little,'' said Allison, who
tallied six assists in the six games vs. Carolina, but couldn't
once dent the net. ``I thought I controlled it sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in complete control again at 15:21 of the second period
when the Bruins boosted the lead to 2-0. He swooshed behind the net
and dished out from behind with a perfect relay to charging,
slightly gambling Kyle McLaren. Dmitri Khristich finished off the
play with a bunt at the left post, but it was Allison's sweet feed
to the opportunistic McLaren that provided all the footwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Jason was going to give it to me even before he
did,'' said McLaren. ``Jason played well. He's one of our better
players. When he's got it going at his pace, and he controls the
game, he's a pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear before this series began that the Bruins would be
in for a long battle if the Allison-Khristich-Sergei Samsonov
combination didn't come alive. Khristich also popped in the
end-of-game empty-netter, which left he and Allison with a combined
3-1_4 for the evening. If Khristich had missed on the long-range
empty-netter, it would have meant a faceoff in the Boston zone with
about 12 seconds to play. Sometimes the right things happen for all
the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Allison finished with a team-high four shots (all in the first
period) and went an impressive 14 for 22 on faceoffs (63 percent).
He showed more jump than in any of his six games against the
'Canes. The Sabres don't attack with Carolina's force and ferocity,
but they have a more sustained, relentless attack, one with a
little less forechecking than Carolina showed but one with a much
smarter, refined system in the neutral zone (read: the dreaded
trap).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more controlled,'' said Anson Carter, the
opening-series standout. ``In the neutral zone, it's like we're
playing against ourselves _ our two games are so much alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe did more than match Hasek save for save. For one night,
the Bruins had the better goalie. That can be debated, if you want
to say the Bruins' shots were unstoppable (essentially Pat Burns's
point in the post-game news conference). But Dafoe faced more shots
and made better stops, by a wide margin. He out-Haseked Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Is that enough for the Bruins to win this series? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   But will this series come down to Dafoe outplaying Hasek? Very
doubtful. Because, just as Hasek is human, so, too, is Dafoe, and
the Sabres put on an impressive show, extremely impressive, for
more than 40 minutes. Dafoe alone won't win the series if the
Sabres can keep coming with that game. They'll get their goals.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us back to Mssrs. Allison, Khristich and Samsonov,
the latter of whom didn't land a single shot and didn't factor at
all in the scoring. It would be unfair to say it's all up to
Allison from here, but for Game 1, it was all up to Allison.
Khristich's goals were gimmes, but he does at least get credit for
being in the right place (not always true against Carolina).
</P>
<P>
   Hasek will get better. The Sabres will keep up their persistent
attack. What they have to do now is come back with the same game
and tie up Allison. Then it will be up to the Bruins to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to beat Buffalo with one guy going,'' Said
Carter, ``or with one line going. They're too good a team for
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
