u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS &LR;      05-07 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE OVERSHADOWED, NOT OUTPERFORMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He's a finalist for the Vezina Trophy. He had two
shutouts in the Bruins' opening playoff series, a 1.46
goals-against average, and a scoreless streak that ran to nearly
135 minutes before it ended Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. But Byron Dafoe is the
Other Goaltender in this series, and he accepts that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all Dominik Hasek, Dominik Hasek, and how are we going
to beat him?'' Dafoe acknowledged after the Bruins had solved Hasek
for three goals to take the quarterfinal opener from Buffalo, 4-2,
at the FleetCenter. ``He's done it for so long. He's been
considered the top guy. He makes these unbelievable saves, and
people expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, nobody expected that from Dafoe. But
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night his 28 saves, a dozen of them in the middle period,
kept the Bruins topside in a grinder of a hockey game that figures
to be followed by four or five or six just like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the whole series is going to be, low-scoring,''
said Dafoe, after he'd backstopped his mates to their fourth
straight victory. ``Every goal is going to be big.''
</P>
<P>
   While his mates were putting a pair of huge goals past The
Dominator, Dafoe was calmly keeping the Sabres off the board the
same way he'd shut down Carolina. And he did his best work when
Buffalo was down a goal and on the power play early in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   After shrugging aside a bid by Joe Juneau, Dafoe kicked out a
55-foot bomb by Geoff Sanderson that had equalizer written all over
it. ``Was it Sanderson?'' Dafoe said. ``I just see the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubber is rubber, he figures, and Dafoe has been stopping enough
of it with high stakes that the Lord Byron Fan Club is grousing _
especially after Thursday &UR;  &LR; night _ that he deserves to have his
name up on the marquee alongside Hasek's. So why isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because his name is Byron Dafoe and not Dominik Hasek,'' said
Bruins coach Pat Burns. ``Byron is gaining steps in the NHL. He's a
kid who's getting his recognition now. Byron has never gotten the
credit. Now, he's getting his due.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres, who didn't crack Dafoe until defenseman Alexei
Zhitnik blasted one off him on the power play (``I was mad at
myself,'' Dafoe said, ``because I knew I was there and I thought I
had it''), knew he'd be far from a simple sieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into the league with Dafoe and he's gotten better and
better and better,'' said Jason Woolley, who scored Buffalo's
second goal through a partial screen with Dafoe down. ``He's got a
little bit of Dominik in him. He's very acrobatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe needed to be down the stretch, when the Sabres had yanked
Hasek and were buzzing the Boston end desperately trying to pop
something in and force overtime. ``They gave us everything they
had,'' Dafoe said. ``They showed us they can come when they want
to.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the siren went off, the Bruins had a critical victory _
but only one. ``We haven't accomplished anything,'' Dafoe shrugged.
``We're supposed to win the home-ice games. If we don't win the
next one, this won't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, history shows that the Sabres, who've won only one of
their previous six playoff series with the Bruins, are usually dead
meat (as in 1-15 lifetime) when they lose the opener. There are
times when one victory is more than one victory.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe is familiar with history and he'll admit to peeking at the
statistics. He knows his current numbers can stand with Hasek's,
and he also knows that Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's story was that the Bruins
beat The Dominator. No problem, muses the Other Goaltender. ``I
don't mind getting second fiddle,'' he said. ``I'll quietly go
through this series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
