<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY PROSECUTORS STRIKE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Here's a little story about political life in one
of this country's most intensely political cities:
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, the great baseball player, once said he could see
the laces on the ball as it came roaring in at 95 mph. For once, I
know how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, even I could see how dopey the Albany Police
Department and the Albany County district attorney's office was
going to look on the Rachel McEneny business. I could see the laces
on this ball.
</P>
<P>
   This one wasn't moving at 95 mph, either. This was a slow,
sloppy pitch. The McEnenys smacked it right out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   This all started when state Assemblyman Jack McEneny, whose lust
to serve as mayor has been an open secret in this town for 20 years
now, made a misjudgment two years ago. Faced with a mayor younger
than he is, a guy who showed no signs of retiring or moving on to
another office, McEneny challenged Mayor Jerry Jennings in a
mayoral primary.
</P>
<P>
   Not a smart move. The last time Albany threw out an incumbent
mayor, Teddy Roosevelt was just finding his way around the state
legislative chambers. And that was a unique situation, totally
unrelated to the circumstances of two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   McEneny knew that. He writes books on local history. He just
couldn't resist giving it a shot, was all.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Jennings rolled over him. Then, in the time-honored
tradition of Albany politics, the mayor set out to assassinate the
guy who'd had the temerity to challenge him. If you're the mayor,
you're more or less obligated to do things like that. Otherwise,
who knows who else might get out of line?
</P>
<P>
   So, the mayor backed County Legislator Gary Domalewicz last year
in a primary challenge against McEneny, who was running to hold on
to his seat in the State Legislature. McEneny won handily.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign manager in both races was his daughter, Rachel, 26.
After last year's win, Rachel McEneny and her boyfriend went to a
bar. She'd had a sip of champagne at headquarters and downed about
a beer and a half at the bar. And, when she left the bar and drove
away, by purest coincidence an Albany cop pulled her over and
charged her with drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did I mention that the police union had backed Jennings the
year before? Well, they had.
</P>
<P>
   McEneny was dragged back to headquarters, in shackles and in a
paddy wagon. They gave her a breathalyzer test. They said that she
blew a 0.11 percent blood-alcohol content, making her legally
drunk. Then, when her parents sprang her, McEneny went to the
hospital and had a blood alcohol test. It read .04, well within the
legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Since the human body sheds alcohol at the rate of .02 per hour,
on average, it was obvious that she would be exonerated of this
charge. In fact, some people thought it obvious that this was a
politically motivated frame-up from the start.
</P>
<P>
   I, of course, would never say anything like that. Hey, I can't
read minds. I can't see into people's hearts. I urge you only to
draw your own conclusions from this fact pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The cops and the DA's office, instead of dropping the charges,
insisted on a trial. On Thursday, Rachel McEneny was acquitted,
after Judge John Egan Jr. threw out that highly questionable
breathalyzer test.
</P>
<P>
   And, incidentally, after her lawyer, Steve Coffey, told the jury
that the cop who'd busted her had lied on the stand about her
condition that night. Why the cops and the DA would insist on such
a public humiliation is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   So now will we see a civil lawsuit against the City of Albany
for false arrest?
</P>
<P>
   Well, look closely. You might see the laces on this one, too.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
