<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKGROUND CHECK: STILL TROUBLESOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this year, I wrote a pair of columns looking at the
issue of software that runs in the background, monitoring a
computer for various events, such as viral activity or a software
installation.
</P>
<P>
   In the first column, I wrote that conflicts between background
programs and other software can cause problems on a PC, and
advocated that people run as ``pure'' a system as possible:
(www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/02/12/compute.html).
</P>
<P>
   In the second, I told how to identify and turn off these
background programs:
(www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/02/19/compute.html).
</P>
<P>
   I used Norton SystemWorks 1.0 as an example of the type of
package that can cause problems. SystemWorks comes with several
components that run in the background, including Norton AntiVirus,
the Norton Utilities System Doctor, CrashGuard and CleanSweep's
Usage Watch. I reported that running all or even just some of these
components slowed my computer down, and in some cases caused
problems with other applications.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Symantec has introduced a new version of SystemWorks
and its central component. The Norton Utilities SystemWorks 2.0
($70) includes Norton Utilities 4.0, CleanSweep 4.5, Norton
AntiVirus 5.0, CrashGuard 4.0 and Norton Web Services, a help
feature. The package also comes with a bonus pack that includes
Norton 2000, which scans your system for Year 2000 issues; a
``basic'' version of WinFax Pro; Zip-It, a Zip-file manager; and
Visual Page, a Web-authoring program.
</P>
<P>
   CrashGuard, Norton AntiVirus and CleanSweep essentially are the
same programs found in SystemWorks 1.0. But they have been tied
together better with a one-click control panel called the
Integrator. From this single window, you can launch any of the
programs' various components.
</P>
<P>
   The LiveUpdate feature, which lets you download patches and new
virus definitions, also has been integrated, so you need click only
one button to get upgrades for each component.
</P>
<P>
   Norton Utilities has had several new components added, as well
as work done under the hood of some others.
</P>
<P>
   Symantec has added the Connection Doctor, a utility that
troubleshoots modem connections, checking everything from Windows'
settings to the health of the modem. It will tell you what's wrong,
but doesn't necessarily tell you how to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to run all the Norton SystemWorks background
modules, you'd have as many as six different icons added to the
Windows system tray _ the recessed area to the right of the
taskbar. One new feature is a kind of ``holder'' for all these
icons. There's only one icon in the tray representing all the
Norton pieces. Hold your cursor over it, and the individual icons
appear for quick access to their features.
</P>
<P>
   There have been significant changes made to two very useful
modules that didn't always behave as they should. The System
Doctor, which monitors your PC's status, and ZipRescue, which lets
you make Windows 95/98 system disks on a Zip drive, have both been
reworked internally.
</P>
<P>
   The System Doctor is much less intrusive in the background, and
it conflicted with only one application _ the game Half-Life, which
requires all the attention of your PC to run. I noticed no slowdown
in my PC's performance as a result of running System Doctor, unlike
the previous version.
</P>
<P>
   The initial version of ZipRescue often didn't work at all. It
was supposed to grab a working copy of Windows from your hard drive
and install it on a Zip disk, giving you enough of an operating
system that you could boot from it in a crisis. It didn't work on a
lot of PCs; this new version is much more reliable. It worked on
all three of the systems I tried _ a Dell Dimension, a
Hewlett-Packard Pavilion and a Compaq Presario.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Norton AntiVirus, CleanSweep and CrashGuard still
presented me with problems. Even on a 500-megahertz Pentium III
system, I could tell when the AntiVirus and CleanSweep programs
were running _ they noticeably slowed performance.
</P>
<P>
   And I still found I had more program crashes when running
CrashGuard than I did when it wasn't present _ particularly in Web
browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I still think the utilities included in this package
are the best Windows 95/98 utilities out there _ so long as you run
most of them manually.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Have a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter
access code 1001.)
</P>
</TEXT>
