<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IF YOU DEFINE YOUR TERMS PRECISELY, YOU CAN'T BE SURE OF CABLE
MODEM SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: Your recently reported on the high-speed Internet
access to be offered by Southwestern Bell and Time Warner
Communications. Speaking of the downsides in both cases, you noted
that cable would slow as more people in the ``neighborhood'' used
it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Warner people said that even the slowest cable would be
far faster than the ADSL phone line. Does ``neighborhood'' refer to
the people on your street or in, say, a subdivision? Or does this
refer to the entire area or town served by a particular cable
station? And when Warner says that slow cable is still far faster
than phone lines, do you know what they mean by ``slow''?
</P>
<P>
   A. The meaning of ``neighborhood'' in this case depends on a
variety of factors, the density of housing being the primary one.
</P>
<P>
   Cable modems work off a node system, where a number of houses
connect to a central point, or node. The cable system is designed
to have a certain number of connections per node.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in a neighborhood where houses are packed closely
together, and a lot of people have cable, you may have multiple
nodes. In large apartment complexes, for example, there typically
are multiple nodes.
</P>
<P>
   But in an area where houses are spaced farther apart, or in
rural areas, there may be fewer nodes.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is saying its cable modems will be capable of an average
speed of around 10 megabits a second and is guaranteeing five
megabits, minimum, even if things bog down. The company promises to
add more nodes in neighborhoods that drop below that.
</P>
<P>
   Five megabits is much faster than a dialup connection at 28.8 to
53 kilobits a second, and also faster than the 1.5 megabits for
residential ADSL from the phone company. On the other hand, in some
communities where cable modems have been widely deployed _ most
notably Fremont, Calif. _ service has been a problem and speeds
have sometimes dropped way below dialup levels.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to bypass the Windows 95 logo screen when I
start my computer. I think I can do this, because I see the screen
twice during bootup, with a glimpse of the DOS prompt in between.
</P>
<P>
   A: To do this, you'll need to use Notepad to edit a file in your
c: folder called MSDOS.SYS. Look for a line that says Logo1 and
change it to change it to Logo0 If you don't see the Logo line, add
it to the end of the file, then save it. You can also use the handy
TweakUI utility to do this, available as part of the PowerToys set
for Windows 95 at 
www.microsoft.com/windows95/downloads/contents/wutoys/w95pwrtoysset/
default.asp.
</P>
<P>
   For Windows 98 users, TweakUI is on the upgrade CD-ROM in the
ToolsReskitPowertoys folder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have figured out how to clear the history information out
of my browser, but it still leaves information in the toolbar area
for America Online 4.0. How do I clear it that out so prying eyes
don't know where I've been?
</P>
<P>
   A: From the My AOL button, go to Preferences, then click on the
Toolbar button. From there, choose Clear History Now.
</P>
<P>
   How you clear the general history in a Web browser depends on
the software. For Internet Explorer, right-click on the IE icon on
the desktop, choose properties. In IE4 and 5, Clear History is on
the General tab.
</P>
<P>
   In Netscape Communicator, click on Edit, then Preferences, and
it's in the initial Navigator configuration screen.
</P>
<P>
   The TweakUI application, mentioned in another Help Line item
above, also has the ability to clear histories from Internet
Explorer. It also can clear other records, including the documents
listed in the Documents area off the Start menu. To get to this
area, use the Paranoid tab.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Have a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter
access code 1001.)
</P>
</TEXT>
