<HEADER>
A8106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FDR-DEPRESSION-HNS &LR;      05-07 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDR-DEPRESSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDR'S QUICK ACTION GUIDED AMERICA THROUGH DARK DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Franklin Roosevelt was impatient to get started.
There was so much to do.
</P>
<P>
   Across America the lights had been dimming into the darkness of
the Great Depression for at least two years before his election in
November 1932. Barely regulated banks inclined to underwriting wild
speculation were failing at an ever-increasing rate everywhere.
Since 1925, unused and unsold stockpiles of manufacturing
inventories and raw materials were choking warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, more and more businesses were laying off more and
more employees. There was no other work to be found, and
unemployment zoomed.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least the end of World War I, those living on farms
were already in a deeply depressed economy, although their chronic
despair had been largely ignored by a Washington establishment
intent on big business and plain old greed. The Great Depression
began on the farm, not on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a widely believed misconception is that the October 1929
stock market crash ``caused'' the Depression. In truth, only about
2 percent of Americans owned any stock in 1929. The vast majority
of Americans had jobs. When they lost those, and banks failed, they
didn't have anything.
</P>
<P>
   By 1933, America was perilously close to chaos _ and more than
ready to be saved. In perhaps the greatest whirlwind of
presidential activity ever, FDR responded.
</P>
<P>
   FDR was inaugurated on March 4, 1933, and a day later he closed
banks for a week's ``holiday,'' to stop the run on them _ the most
immediate crisis at hand. A week later, the Emergency Banking Act
was passed.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days after taking office, in a daring and unprecedented
move, FDR held the first of his ``fireside chats,'' telling
Americans glued to their crystal sets that it was ``safer to keep
your money in a reopened bank than under the mattress,'' in that
distinctive voice of calm, authority and unflagging optimism that
would get the nation through the darkest decade of American life.
</P>
<P>
   When the banks reopened, the money and gold poured back in.
FDR's appeal had worked magic, as he would again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks, FDR and his ``brain trust'' provided
government intervention for agriculture and massive programs aimed
at unemployment relief. Probably the most popular among those
throughout the decade was the CCC _ the Civilian Conservation Corps
_ to this day inspiring fierce loyalty and the fondest memories
from deep conservatives and New Dealers alike.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to employ out-of-work unmarried men from 18 to 25
years of age on forestry, flood control and outdoor beautification
projects. Ultimately the mission expanded to include such tasks as
fighting forest fires, rescuing snowbound livestock and cutting the
Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   The CCC planted 8 billion trees, built 800 state parks, restored
4,000 historic structures _ among them the Gettysburg Civil War
battlefield _ to name but a very few of its accomplishments. By the
time the CCC dissolved in 1942, when America was at war and needed
foot rather than tree soldiers, 3 million had passed through the
camps. More than 250,000 learned to read and write there. Others
earned high school and college degrees _ education was a
requirement of the contract _ while the majority were given trade
skills.
</P>
<P>
   A regular or reserve Army officer ran each camp, although the
discipline was not as rigorous as Army life. Each camp hired
teachers and doctors, offered religious services and entertainment.
Enrollees, as they were called, were fed well and clothed and
earned a respectable $30 a month, $25 of which had to go back to
the folks.
</P>
<P>
   In many instances, that was money desperately needed back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit after my junior year in high school,'' recalled
81-year-old Frank Leonbruno, then of Whitehall, N.Y. ``Things
weren't that good at home. The silk mills closed, the railroads
laid everybody off. I saw the notice in the Whitehall Times, so I
signed up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, it was great,'' he said. ``Reveille was 6
a.m., and we got up quicklike and put in full days, spraying for
gypsy moths, cutting trails or making campsites. Classes weren't
until after dinner and before lights-out, so we slept well. There
were five barracks at (Camp) Bolton, and 40 men to each barrack.
They were always full.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonbruno became the camp cook. He liked it so much he stayed as
custodian nearly six years, even after the camp broke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finished high school there. We had a beautiful library. One
of the supervisors took an interest and helped me get a job with
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonbruno became a New York Department of Environmental
Conservation forest ranger and retired after 42 years as head of
the state's Lake George operation.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lavigna, 86, of Cohoes, N.Y., served in CCC camps in
Michigan, New York and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we didn't do wasn't worth doing,'' Lavigna said.
``Everything. Rescues, built dams, planted trees, took seeds from
cones, even sold cord wood at a dollar a cord, delivered. To this
day, I'm convinced it was one of the best programs that this
country ever had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
