<SLUG> BC-BIRTHMARK-CRUSADER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER BECOMES CRUSADER ABOUT DISFIGURING BIRTHMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Arkansas, Georgia, Massachusetts, New York, South
Carolina)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHAM, N.Y. _ The photos in Linda Rozell Shannon's album
weren't easy to look at.
</P>
<P>
   One image showed Shannon's daughter, her upper lip swollen as if
she'd been punched. Another focused on an infant's deformed cheek,
inflated like a grotesque balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of such disfigurement seemed like unthinkable trauma
or injury, not a fairly common birthmark in children known as a
hemangioma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pediatrician looked at this every week and said, `It's
just a hemangioma, leave it alone,''' said Shannon, a specialist in
birthmarks and executive director of the Hemangioma and Vascular
Birthmarks Foundation in Latham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine just looking at this and saying it's going to
go away?'' Over the past four years, Shannon has become a crusader
for more openness about hemangiomas, developing an international
reputation for her work.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to encourage physicians to treat disfiguring
birthmarks more aggressively, get insurance companies to cover
related surgery rather than call it cosmetic, and to increase
research into the cause and cure of hemangiomas.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, medical textbooks have taught doctors to let nature
take its course with these red-purple lesions.
</P>
<P>
   Caused by an abnormal distribution of blood vessels under the
skin, hemangiomas are the most common benign tumor in infants,
affecting one in 100 babies with varying severity.
</P>
<P>
   Although many hemangiomas disappear entirely on their own
without any medical intervention, others can take years to go away,
leaving behind disfiguring scars and psychosocial problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's those worst cases that concern Shannon, an author of the
only general book on the topic, ``Birthmarks: a Guide to
Hemangiomas and Vascular Malformations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have trouble in school, they have trouble
adjusting,'' said Shannon, who works part-time as a research
analyst for the New York Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon, 43, had never heard of hemangiomas until shortly after
her daughter Christine's birth in February 1994. She didn't think
twice about the tiny red mark that appeared on her baby's bottom
lip, until it began to grow.
</P>
<P>
   By the time her daughter was 18 months old, the tumor was as big
as a golf ball. The family's pediatrician continued to offer only
the vague prognosis that it would eventually go away.
</P>
<P>
   After consulting with specialists in Boston and New York, she
was told her daughter was too old for steroid treatment and too
young for the multiple surgeries needed.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon eventually found Dr. Milton Waner, a plastic surgeon in
Little Rock, Ark. During a three-hour outpatient procedure, he used
a laser to remove her daughter's lesion before reconstructing the
girl's lip.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Christine Shannon, 5, shows few signs of her ordeal. She
is outgoing and has only a tiny scar from her surgery. ``Every
child has a right to look normal and every parent has the right to
a normal looking child or to at least have options,'' Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage more aggressive treatment of hemangiomas, Shannon
has helped set up multidisciplinary clinics of dermatologists,
surgeons and pathologists to evaluate and treat children in Atlanta
and Boston; Albany and Buffalo, N.Y.; Arkansas; and, most recently,
in London.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Shannon will travel to South Carolina to work with
doctors there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really on a crusade to offer proper therapy to these
patients,'' said Dr. Martin Mihm, an internationally known
specialist on skin cancer and vascular tumors who has worked with
Shannon to establish some clinics, including one in Tokyo slated to
open next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical community is very slow to change. The dictum is
that the great majority of these lesions will go away,'' he said.
``The reality is that only 25 percent go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm, director of the newly founded Rare Tumor Institute of the
World Health Organization, credits Shannon for increasing awareness
about vascular birthmarks and treatment options, including
steroids, lasers and surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really an inspiring example of what a lay person can
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers don't know what causes hemangiomas, though they tend
to be more common in premature infants. But unlike other
birthmarks, they don't appear until after the baby is born and
then, most often, on the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is catching them early,'' said Dr. Edwin Williams,
chief of facial plastic and reconstructive surgery at Albany
Medical Center Hospital and principal surgeon for the Albany
clinic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
