<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINMODEM IS A LOSERMODEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I can't use Linux on the Web because I have a
Winmodem, which only works with Windows. Unlike other modem cards
I've seen, this one connects to other cards via small cables. Do
you know if a standard, non-Winmodem card were to replace the
existing one, would it work?
</P>
<P>
   _Linux Wannabe
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WANNABE: Just take the sucker out and see what happens. You
can always put it back later if removing it hammers your system.
I'm guessing you tossed the instruction book like most people, so
this is about the only way to do it unless you can find some
documentation on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   No telling what those wires are for. I've seen some goofy modems
in my time, like the ones that were part sound card. They hooked up
to other stuff. I've seen ones that were built into the motherboard
or relegated to a proprietary slot that grabbed the communications
port you really needed for something else.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since you have a Winmodem, the real solution is to
take a big wooden mallet and pound it into its component molecules.
These cheesy things use your microprocessor instead of on-board
chips like regular modems do. The software that drives them only
runs under Windows, so if you want to play with DOS or Linux,
you're out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out you absolutely need to keep that piece of junk
in your PC to make other stuff work right, there's no law against
having two modems, assuming you have a free slot. Just make sure
you set the new modem's communications port and interrupt to
something different from the Winmodem's. Yes, that means you have
to keep the instruction book this time.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're serious about playing with Linux, avoid Plug and
Play, a Windows abomination that automatically assigns ports and
interrupts. You'll have to set a few jumpers on the modem, but
you'll save yourself a ton of migraines later.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I don't think Bill Gates has a great deal to
fear until the Linux documenters learn to use English instead of
Linux-speak. They are so enamored of their jargon that they make it
next to impossible, even for an experienced user like myself, to
understand what they're saying.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forms Complete Sentences
</P>
<P>
   DEAR FORMS: On the other hand, they probably didn't understand a
single word you wrote. You know how it is: Linux-speak is like the
secret handshake of the geek fraternity. I suppose it makes them
feel special.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember how bad DOS documentation used to be, though. I'm
sure as soon as Linux goes mainstream, all the people running Linux
companies will realize the value of users actually being able to
understand the documentation, and they'll be clamoring for me to
write it for a seven-figure salary. Then I guess all the geeks will
have to make up a new language.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I find your comment ``You know who I'm talking
about: the four-eyed geek in Information Systems who gives
`socially dysfunctional' a whole new spin'' to be absolutly
repulsive! As an IT proffesional I am outraged that you would use
such a discription in a new artical.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a Snit
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SNIT: Gee, I thought a big-time IT ``proffesional'' would
at least know how to use his spell-checker.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
