A8153 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-GUNS-TEX     05-07 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BUSH'S STAND ON EMOTIONAL GUN ISSUE HAS LEFT BOTH SIDES
UNHAPPY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ First the gun control advocates criticized him
for not going far enough. Now many gun rights enthusiasts are
pounding Gov. George W. Bush for going too far in the debate over
instant background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   A national gun rights organization has put out a ``multistate
alert'' on Bush, calling his stand on instant background checks a
``scheme to take away yet more of the rights of law-abiding
owners.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail alert from the hard-line Gun Owners Association of
America sparked hundreds of phone calls to Bush's state offices and
presidential campaign headquarters in Austin, Bush officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Littleton, Colo., school shooting, the gun control
debate has become a focus of the 2000 presidential race, which Bush
is leading.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's comments about guns have left few happy on either
side of the emotional debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people who I think tend to be one-issue voters are
indicating a great deal of concern over quotes they have read from
some of the (presidential) candidates,'' said Rep. Suzanna Hupp,
R-Lampasas, a gun rights supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Bush was one of them, Hupp said he was.
</P>
<P>
   The other, she said, was Elizabeth Dole, who expressed support
in a recent New Hampshire speech for retaining the ban on assault
weapons and mandatory trigger locks on guns, among other
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Bush supports federal legislation _ though not
state efforts _ to require background checks on people buying
weapons at gun shows, according to Bush and his aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the federal law ought to change to give gun show
operators the ability to conduct instant background checks at gun
shows,'' Bush told reporters this week. ``If instant background are
good enough for gun dealers and storefronts they ought to be good
enough for gun shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he favors a federal approach because the law now says
only federal firearms dealers who have established storefronts must
conduct checks. That law needs to be changed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dave Beckwith said the governor wants to require
that all sales by gun show vendors be subject to background checks
by making the National Instant Check System available to the gun
show organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who is a vendor, that is, who has bought a table, or
is setting himself up in business there,'' would be subject to a
background check under Bush's proposal, Beckwith added.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would screen out criminals, you'd screen out minors and
you'd screen out mental patients and others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the gun control issue began after reporters
asked Bush to explain his gun control stands in the wake of the
Colorado shooting.
</P>
<P>
   When he expressed support for instant background checks, gun
control advocates criticized him because a state bill that would
require those checks had died in a legislative committee the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said that Bush does not support that now-dead
legislation, and that that's what the campaign has been telling
upset gun enthusiasts who call.
</P>
<P>
   ``He opposed that bill and it died. The Gun Owners of America
know that Governor Bush opposes the legislation and he assured them
it won't pass,'' Beckwith said.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Butts, a lobbyist for Texans Against Gun Violence, said she
was disappointed that Bush did not get behind efforts to pass the
controls on the state level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his heart is in the right place, but I'm very
frustrated that he has not helped us pass a strong gun show law,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Bush gotten behind the state legislation, it's still not
clear whether the bill would have passed.
</P>
<P>
   Texas hosts nearly 500 gun shows a year _ twice more than any
other state _ and well-publicized efforts to revive the bill in the
pro-gun Legislature have gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
