<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF PORTFOLIO FITS INVESTORS' COMFORT LEVEL, STICK WITH IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 09, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are both 44 and I am concerned about the
allotment of our portfolio. I work part time and have a 401(k) plan
through my employer. I contribute $120 a month, which is 5 percent
of my salary, and my employer contributes 3 percent. This goes in
equal amounts to SSGA Growth and Income fund, where I now have
$6,300, and SSGA Small Cap fund, where the balance is $6,000. We
have these mutual fund IRA accounts: $11,800 in Fidelity Puritan,
$20,700 in Fidelity Contrafund, $$10,500 in Fidelity Convertible
Securities, and $35.000 in Fidelity Asset Manager. My husband works
for the local government, and can expect a pension representing 80
percent of his average salary for the last three years he works.
What do you estimate our present holdings will be worth at age 60?
Would you suggest any changes?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the math is the easy part: If you simply left the
401(k) and IRA portfolios alone and they produced average annual
returns of 10 percent for 16 years, your retirement savings would
grow to $418,142. If you continued your contributions of $120 a
month and your employer added a further $72 each month, the account
would grow to $504,745. And if you maintain your contributions as a
percentage of salary, the contributions and likely accumulation
would rise every time during the next 16 years that you get a
raise.
</P>
<P>
   Would I recommend changes? Maybe. It seems to me that three of
your holdings, including the largest, are pretty conservative for a
person 16 years away from retirement. Fidelity Asset Manager and
Puritan both maintain 35 to 40 percent of their portfolios on the
fixed-income side of the ledger, and while Fidelity Convertible
Securities has produced solid results, by its nature it is unlikely
to outperform traditional stock funds over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   But before you rush out to make changes, there's also the
question of whether you are comfortable with this fairly
conservative portfolio and would be uncomfortable with a higher
risk profile. No portfolio can be right for all investors, and if
what you now hold reflects your appetite for risk, by all means
stick with it. And I've found over the years that when a portfolio
has been built along fairly conservative lines, it's because the
owner knows his or her own risk tolerence better than I ever can.
</P>
<P>
   That said, if it were my portfolio and I were 44, I'd reduce the
Asset Manager position sharply, putting about $10,000 in Fidelity
Select Health Care and another $10,000 in Fidelity Spartan Market
Index, a fund which tracks the results of the Standard and Poor's
500 index. I probably would stick with Convertible Securities for
the short term, based on my distrust of the current market, but
when the market seemed neutral to me, I would transfer that money
to either Contrafund or Market Index.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while dividing your contributions evenly between the
SSGA Growth and Income and Small-Cap funds is fine at this point,
you'll want to watch those accounts over the years, since you
should want the small-cap holding to eventually represent some 10
to 15 percent of the total portfolio (including the IRAs) wheras
the Growth and Income account can be combined with your other
large-cap positions (Contrafund and the stock sides of the Puritan
and Asset Manager portfolios) to comprise your core position, which
might run as high as 60 percent of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Now that Vanguard's Health Care fund is closed to new
investors, could you recommend another in the sector? Both Fidelity
Select Health Care and Putnam's Health Sciences charge loads. Would
you invest in these funds anyway? These are the only three health
care sector funds I can find.
</P>
<P>
   P.H., South Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. My instinct would be to pay the small load _ 3 percent _ and
go into Fidelity Select Health Care. But if you insist on finding a
no-load fund in the sector, consider Invesco Health Sciences, which
also wins the highest grades from Morningstar Mutual Funds and
charges only a 12b-1 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the sector which are followed by Morningstar and worth
considering are AIM Global Health Care, Eaton Vance Worldwide
Health, Franklin Global Health Care, MSDW Health Sciences, Warburg
Pincus Health Sciences, and H&AMP;O Healthcare Investors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a previous column you said proceeds of a home sale could
be used to establish up to $2,000 in IRA accounts each year.
Doesn't an IRA account have to be funded with earned income?
</P>
<P>
   R.T., Haverhill, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The rule establishes that the individual opening an IRA
account must have earned income representing at least the amount
that is put into the IRA _ but the money need not come directly
from the earned income. In fact, a number of parents have written
to me proposing to fund their working children's IRAs as a form of
a gift _ and it's perfectly all right, so long as the children's
earnings exceed the amount that goes into the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Please help my children, ages 13 and 15, invest what they
call their _ life savings. Each has about $2,500. I would like to
see the money invested in a fund which would be profitable for them
and would prove interesting to them, so they could learn how to
invest and save. I will assume that the money will be used for
their education in the near future, or for a car for work. What
fund would be best?
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Ortonville, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   A. Alas, I think all they can learn at this stage is that the
first rule of investing, which is to match the duration of the
investment with the time frame in which the money is likely to be
used. It sounds to me from what you say that the older child is
likely to tap into this money in about two years, and the younger
in four. Either way, that's short-term money, and so your
investment should match.
</P>
<P>
   At the most venturesome, I'd look at a fund such as the
Fidelity's or Vanguard's Short-Term Bond funds, which are pretty
far from the kind of things which generate a lot of excitement. But
they will give the kids an idea of how mutual fund investments
work, and the chances are strong that over the next two to four
years they will generate a slightly better total return than if you
left the money in the bank, bought CDs, or put it in a mutual fund
company's money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
