<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEATING, COOLING AN ENCLOSED PORCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 9, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I enclosed my 10- by 12-foot porch, with virtually 100
percent windows on three sides, and am wondering how I can best
heat and air-condition it. Would those windows make it difficult to
heat and cool? It faces west.
</P>
<P>
   R.S., Brockton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The fact that it faces west means that at least one side (the
south side) gets sun for at least half a day, and the west side
gets sun (albeit a setting sun) for part of the day. That should be
good in winter, but tough in summer, making a/c more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The small size of the room will make it all possible. If you
cannot extend the cool from the house, I suggest a window a/c would
work.
</P>
<P>
   As for heat, you could buy a power-vented gas stove, the type
that doesn't need a chimney and shows the dancing flames. It looks
good, and turns on with the flip of a switch. The smallest such
stove will heat the room in minutes. Such a stove costs about
$1,000. Another option is to buy a power-vented pellet stove. You
could also adapt the stove to burn propane gas, but the bottled gas
is very expensive. Energy companies sell both, plus accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I clean my wide pine floor boards that have been
stained and oiled? The sander said he can't sand them any more
because some are tongued and grooved.
</P>
<P>
   SALLY KITTROSS, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The reason tongued-and-grooved boards cannot be sanded is
because there is only 1/4 inch of sandable wood surfaces, as
opposed to a full inch or 3/4 inch of sandable surface of
square-edged boards. That 1/4 inch probably cannot be sanded more
than three tmes, and you must have reached the limit.
</P>
<P>
   And, alas, an oiled finish cannot be cleaned except by dry
mopping or vacuuming.
</P>
<P>
   But hope springs eternal, and you can try this: Hand sand to
remove the dirt, which has been ground into the wood. If that
works, you will probably restain the entire floor; then apply two
coats of an oil-based polyurethane varnish over the oiled finish;
the longer the oil has been on and in the wood, the better the
varnishing will work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Two years ago I bought Sears exterior latex paint, and
recently painted ceilings with it. It smelled skunkish, and the
stench is still there. How can I remove or cover that odor?
</P>
<P>
   GENE SAVAGE, Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That is one of the reasons that exterior paint should not be
used indoors, but you already know that. Other reasons for the
taboo is that exterior paint is heavy, and would be more likely to
pull itself off a ceiling than regular ceiling paint; exterior
paints may exude more fumes than interior paints; and exterior
paints take longer to cure than interior paints.
</P>
<P>
   Try covering the odor by applying a latex enamel undercoater or
BIN, a shellac-based white primer. Then you can apply a white latex
ceiling paint (it's by definition interior).
</P>
<P>
   The only reason there is a taboo against interior paints
outdoors is that they simply do not stand up outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have three layers of wallpaper to remove from a room. I
used a paper tiger to score it so the steamer will soften the
paste, but I find that the steamer produces too much water, and it
is difficult to take the paper off when it is sprayed by hot water.
Is there an additive I can put in the water to make it easier?
</P>
<P>
   JOE NORMANDY, Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are many additives to make the stripper water wetter,
keeping it on the paper longer so it can do its work. They might
help, but I have found that getting the water almost boiling, then
applying it with a roller is most effective and uses very little
water.
</P>
<P>
   A steamer will provide heat with a minimum of water; your
steamer might not be creating enough steam. And, to prevent excess
water from hitting the floor and/or baseboards, tape a light
plastic tarp on the wall just above the baseboard and cascading
over the floor.
</P>
<P>
   I never used a tarp, because I was going to sand and finish the
floors anyway. It was amazing how much paper that I took off and
pasted right on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a small dilemma; I can't find filters for my oil-fired
hot air furnace. They are an odd size, 18 by 20 inches. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   HOWARD KATZ, Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. That is a dilemma, and I don't think 18 by 20 inches is an
odd size, unless someone cut a larger filter to fit your furnace.
Some permanent filters (the kind you can wash when they get dirty)
can be cut with scissors. The other type, with a cardboard border,
cannot be trimmed practically.
</P>
<P>
   So, check your filter; if it does not have a border, it is a
permanent one and can be washed _ and trimmed. Also, check your oil
dealer; he should know, or carry them. Or, call the manufacturer to
find out what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   If your filters have the cardboard border, you can clean them a
little by whacking them against a hard surface, just to remove some
of the dust and dirt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
