<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-07 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP THE HEAT ON MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What may be the beginning of the end of the NATO's Balkan air
war brings the Russians back under the West's tent, totally
isolates the Serb menace, Mr. Milosevic, and sets out on the
diplomatic table a solution that is acceptable, if not ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Slobodan would be Slobo-gone after a stray piece of
NATO ordnance found him during a night raid; that would be justice
in action. But the Group of Eight agreement announced Thursday
achieves the NATO objectives and fences off the Serb threat,
quarantining the rabid Serb chief in his own lair.
</P>
<P>
   Till he knuckles under and pulls his military machine out of
Kosovo, NATO should hammer him day and night. The blowing up of
petroleum supplies, after the reduction of power plants and the
knockdown of bridges and rail connections, imposes a frightening
price on his resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, his marauders forced more than half the Kosovars out of
their territory, and no, NATO was unable to really get at the Serb
ground forces and artillery that did most of the damage. In that
sense, Milosevic has achieved more of his infernal objectives than
NATO's hurried rush to prevent more massacres.
</P>
<P>
   But the character of modern Balkan politics is irretrievably
altered. Milosevic is a war criminal in search of indictment. Like
Chile's Pinochet, he'll be at risk of arrest, imprisonment and
trial if he ever leaves Serb territory. He and many of his thugs
will be identified, labeled, and their pictures will be on post
office walls all over Europe. Nowhere to run, nowhere to hide,
these men have no future in the civilized world.
</P>
<P>
   To an extent unimagined by Bill Clinton's many enemies at home,
the White House has managed one of the astonishing balancing acts
of modern warfare. With US forces in the lead, mounting 15,000 air
sorties, 5,000 of them combat strikes, with all sorts of missiles
and bombs and guns filling the often-murky skies over Serb
territory, enough damage was wrought to bring the Serb assault to
the brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   All of this took place, at least up till Thursday afternoon,
without any NATO combat casualties. Two planes were downed, three
soldiers captured, but both pilots were rescued, and the three
soldiers were sprung. True, there were the two regrettable deaths
in a training mission of the Apache helicopter crew.
</P>
<P>
   But to manage such a complex and vast military operation, with
fighting forces of 16 nations in place, without any more losses
than these, and the political coalition still intact, is
remarkable. A week ago the West was rattled by Kremlin bluster,
talk of World War III, and a Slav alliance rallying behind
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The White House cajoled the Yeltsin government back under the
tent. Russia needs its IMF and World Bank infusions, the Serbs have
made hardly a dent in the resolve of Western governments to see the
bombing campaign through, and the much-trumpeted second-guessing
and misgivings about how the war was waged seem less impressive
now. Alas, we may have to put up with the Milosevic regime. He'll
join the nose-thumbers in Iraq, Libya, and Cuba, dictators rattling
diminished cages, cowing their own people.
</P>
<P>
   But one can hope that the NATO chiefs keep up the pressure,
unrolling the B-52s and all they can carry, till Milosevic is truly
back in his cage. That may only be a matter of days. It's hard to
envisage Milosevic staying defiant with the Russians on record as
favoring the G-8 deal.
</P>
<P>
   What will the peacekeepers _ I prefer the term
``peace-enforcers'' _ find when they roll into Kosovo? Blood-soaked
soil. Hastily-buried bodies. Raped womenfolk. Traumatized children.
Wasted crops. Slain livestock. Burned houses. Destroyed
infrastructure. Broken families. Desperate needs for housing, a
reliable food supply, medical, and psychiatric care.
</P>
<P>
   We already have the testimony of tens of thousands of victims as
to the ferocity and extent of Serbian war crimes. Milosevic's
forces swept through the southeast corner of Europe like the Nazis,
Goths and Vandals before them.
</P>
<P>
   What's different now from the days when Western diplomats
deliberated endlessly with Slobodan the Slaughterer over his
depradations in Bosnia is that there are no more illusions about
the Serb chief. He's not to be trusted; he must be trussed up.
</P>
<P>
   There are lessons we learned closer to home. Where was the
``Never Again!'' chorus when the refugees by the hundreds of
thousands were driven from Kosovo at bayonet-point? What did we
hear most, in the Land of the Free and the Home of the Brave? Don't
fight, don't bomb, don't join 18 other NATO allies, cried many.
It's too dangerous, mysterious, uncertain and treacherous. You know
those Balkan peoples, they're always at each other's throats, let
them kill each other, it's not our fight. That sentiment slopped
over the Congress too, and quenched the fighting spirit of our
Quisling Quongress .
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will slaughter Milosevic in the PR war to come. The
president pointed to a woman refugee wearing an Olympic T-shirt.
``I could imagine that any of you could be my neighbors in
America,'' cooed the president whose bedside manner infuriates his
Republican enemies.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman from Pristina told Clinton: ``You understood us
and you understood our pain. And even if we die, the dying would be
easier because we know that somebody knows what we're going
through.'' Clinton told the refugees to forego becoming embittered.
``I ask you not to give them that victory,'' the president said.
``Don't let yourself be broken by this.'' Vintage Clinton. Bill
pulls it off yet again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
