<HEADLINE>
JONATHA BROOKE'S INDEPENDENCE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine you're a major label recording artist on a national tour
to support a new album. The single is just beginning to move on the
radio. You're selling out theaters. A month into the tour your
record company calls to inform you that your option is coming up.
They ask you to take a giant cut in budget for your next project.
You _ who are more concerned with promoting your current record and
are frankly inclined to defer this final judgment of your worth _
ask for a six-month extension on the option. You wait for word.
They never call back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deadline for the option came and went. There was no phone
call. No nothing,'' says Boston-bred singer-songwriter Jonatha
Brooke, who was unceremoniously dropped by her label, MCA, in March
of last year. So Brooke did what any levelheaded, recently rejected
girl would do: She threw a dinner party and invited all her friends
who'd been dumped. ``Wendy and Lisa were there. Me'Shell
Ndegeocello, all my friends who had been dropped from labels,''
recalls Brooke, on the phone from a hotel in Albany, N.Y. ``It was
like, `I've been dropped three times.' And someone would say,
`That's nothing. I've been dropped four times.' It became a
celebration. We figured we all must be so good,'' she says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to suggest that Brooke didn't take an emotional
nosedive as well. ``It was an incredible blow, to be in the middle
of a national tour and suddenly be label-less again. And I couldn't
believe it had happened to this record in particular. I was so in
love with `10(CT) Wings,' '' she says of her 1997 album for MCA.
``It broke my heart.'' But Brooke persevered, went back out on the
road using her own means, and the tour wound up being supplying her
with the reassurance she needed to pick herself up by her
bootstraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beautiful thing about the situation was that I realized
nothing had really changed. I was selling out concerts. I was
intact. My career was intact. MCA had nothing to do with that.''
Last summer Brooke created her own label, Bad Dog Records, and
released ``Jonatha Brooke Live,'' a collection of 10 tracks
recorded during the 1998 spring tour _ about half of them in Boston
at a WXRV-FM (92.5) concert at City Hall Plaza and at the
Somerville Theatre. It includes material from Brooke's early days
in the Boston-based duo the Story (with Jennifer Kimball) as well
as songs from her two solo albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started listening back to those shows last summer, the
live thing had this energy. It was an intenseness and sparseness,
with everything centering around the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer supported by the corporate machinery, Brooke released
the album through her Internet Web site (www.jonathabrooke.com), an
experience she says was initially daunting for a self-described
``computer spastic,'' but ultimately fruitful. ``We've sold 3,500
records over the Internet. It was a great way to get it out there,
to get things started and see what the vibe was, and then come out
with a commercial release.'' Koch International, an independent
company that also distributes indie-queen Ani DiFranco's records,
has put ``Jonatha Brooke Live'' in retail stores nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke moved from Boston to a hillside cottage in the Brentwood
section of Los Angeles several years ago. ``I'd been here a long,
long time,'' says Brooke, the daughter of a journalist father and
poet mother who grew up in Weston and the Back Bay. She says Boston
was a great place to cut her acoustic chops, but that ``I wasn't
really being supported or challenged. Although that was probably in
my own mind. I had all these musician friends in LA. And it seemed
like it would be a good place to be heard, you know, to be in close
proximity to my record label. That worked out really well, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke has learned, however, that neither location nor label has
much to do with the creative aspect of making music, ``which is
hell either way. You'd think that after 10 years it would be no
problem. But it's a strange masochistic process for me, this
incredible wrangling with the muse.'' Indeed, Brooke's songs _
finely cut, exquisitely wrought folk-pop gems that are as precise
in melody and tone as they are elliptical in their poetic
excavation of relationships _ sound as if they've been wrenched
from deep inside, painstakingly sculpted and sanded, and finally
polished to a glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few are gifts,'' Brooke concedes. ``They plop in your lap.
But mostly it's this game of hide-and-seek. It's like a very
superstitious ritual. I have notebooks full of ideas. Bits and
pieces that I'm working on. And you have to chain yourself to the
table to find out which page fits with which melody. Plus I'm such
a brutal, brutal critic of my own work, it's amazing that anything
gets through.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke's music is complex, spare but remarkably sophisticated,
and just plain better than much of the singer-songwriter fare
that's out there. Asked if she feels she hasn't received her due
respect or success, especially in light of the current wave of
chart-topping female artists, Brooke is circumspect. ``I think it's
more that people haven't had a chance to hear me, that all these
opportunities just haven't worked out. We were just starting to
chart when MCA dropped me. I don't know . . . maybe it's good to
build a career this slowly and steadily.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the false starts and dashed hopes, Brooke has a sure
sense of herself and her music. As to whether she'll try to jump
back in the game, Brooke says she's of two minds. ``I do appreciate
what the major label can do for you, if you're the lucky girl who
wins the lottery and gets a person who sticks behind you. I haven't
had that luxury. And it would probably take a lot to convince me to
go back. But I will go ahead and record the next studio project. I
don't have $200,000. But I'm liking the sparse, visceral sound,''
Brooke says. ``And I wouldn't necessarily have known that if things
hadn't happened this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
