<HEADLINE>
BURNSIDE UPDATES HIS MISSISSIPPI BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The blues never sounded like this before. Take three hip-hop
DJs, including Beck's mix-master genius, Tom Rothrock, and have
them rework the music of Mississippi hill-country bluesman R. L.
Burnside. The results are revelatory on Burnside's latest disc,
``Come On In,'' a techno-blues breakthrough that is one of the
best-selling blues records in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I was going to like it, but man, it came back
good,'' says Burnside, a 71-year-old golden ager whose deep
brawling voice and cutting slide guitar have been modernized but
not bastardized by the remixers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never done nothing like that, you know? But the people
like it and it's selling good, and that's the main thing,'' says
Burnside. These will be stripped-down, juke-joint affairs _ don't
expect any sampled hip-hop beats _ but ``we might decide to jam''
on some of the songs from ``Come On In,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Burnside, who was rediscovered in 1992 in the documentary film
``Deep Blues'' and later recorded with the Jon Spencer Blues
Explosion, has also made history by being the only blues act
distributed by the punk-oriented Epitaph Records. Usual Epitaph
clients include the Offspring and Rancid, so you get the picture.
Burnside's home label remains Fat Possum Records _ a label beloved
by blues connoisseurs _ but Epitaph is thrilled with its
partnership with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``R. L.'s album has definitely hit a nerve with a different
crowd,'' Epitaph spokeswoman Kathie Koehler says. ``It has sold
50,000 copies _ and many have been bought by young people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing a lot of young faces at our concerts now,'' adds
Burnside, whose touring group features his grandson, Cedric, on
drums. ``Young people are just now beginning to realize that all
the music started from the blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnside is one of the last living masters. He learned from
guitar great Fred McDowell (a neighbor) and Muddy Waters, who
married his first cousin, Anna Mae. ``I heard Muddy's music in the
'40s when I went up to Chicago to live with my father for a
while,'' says Burnside. ``I'd go to his house about every other
night to listen to him play. I loved his music.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the ``Deep Blues'' movie, Burnside has toured eight months
annually, at a time when other bluesmen his age are winding down.
``If the Lord will bless me, I'll do it for a few more years,''
says Burnside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting Staind: It's been an uphill climb, but the Springfield,
Mass.-based Staind has joined Godsmack as Bay State metal-rockers
with a national profile. The band toiled for years just trying to
break into the Boston market through such clubs as the Rat, Mama
Kin, and Middle East, but a chance meeting with Limp Bizkit singer
Fred Durst has propelled the band to a larger spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It started when Staind handed a tape to Durst at a Limp Bizkit
show in Hartford two years ago, then they saw Bizkit again at a St.
John's Gym show in Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 2:30 in the morning after that show and my phone
rang,'' says Staind guitarist Mike Mushok. ``I heard our tape
blaring in the background as Fred said, `I love this. I'm going to
get you signed.' '' Durst kept his word and co-produced the new
``Dysfunction,'' a high-octane, atomic bomb of an album that has
come out on Elektra Records. Durst also got the band signed with
the Firm, a management agency that represents Bizkit and Korn.
</P>
<P>
   Staind has lyrics that make Pearl Jam seem like well-adjusted
Boy Scouts. Singer-lyricist Aaron Lewis sings: ``I hate myself and
I hate my face and I hate my world.'' Maybe he'll be hating it a
little less now that the record is selling, but regardless, he
sounds genuine and is a remarkably powerful singer. ``When I first
heard him, he was in my cellar with just an acoustic guitar, but he
woke my parents up,'' says Mushok.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Sunday's Worcester show, Staind is expected to open for
Limp Bizkit this summer. Look for that tour to hit Lowell's Tsongas
Arena in July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and Pieces: Dave Matthews has stadium shows in only four
markets this summer. He's at Foxboro Stadium May 29-30, plus two
nights at Giants Stadium in New Jersey, three at Veterans Stadium
in Philadelphia, and one at Mile High Stadium in Denver. Otherwise,
it's sheds and arenas. . . . Guster's new CD is produced by Steve
Lillywhite of U2 fame and will be out Aug. 3. . . . Aerosmith plays
the Hollywood Bowl Friday night. The band's return to the Tweeter
Center, though, now appears unlikely. Aerosmith's last show of the
tour will be Woodstock '99. They'll also be feted this summer with
the opening of an Aerosmith ride at Disneyland. Details to come. .
. . Sad news: Boston-based Joe Pope, who published the Beatles
fanzine Strawberry Fields Forever, died April 22. Nazareth drummer
Darrell Sweet died of a heart attack before a show in New Albany,
Ind., April 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
