<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GREAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRESENTATION WORTHY OF EVERYONE'S `EXPECTATIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GREAT EXPECTATIONS 
Directed by: Julian Jarrold 
Starring: Ioan Gruffudd, Justine Waddell, Bernard Hill, Ian
McDiarmid, Charlotte Rampling, Clive Russell 
On: PBS, Ch. 2, Sunday and Monday nights at 9 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not too surprising that moviemakers continue to mine the
novels of Charles Dickens. For one thing, Dickens's best work is
profoundly cinematic, as it reaches from the shadowy, grimy London
lowlife to the lonely landscapes of rural England. Just the
topography of his vivid characters' faces would be enough to seduce
a filmmaker. And Dickens invites contemporary interpretation with
his moral passion for elaborate plots that cross over
socio-economic boundaries. So many contemporary writers, after all,
aim for smaller, more culturally specific stories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's one quality in Dickens' fiction, however, that doesn't
travel easily to the 20th century: sentimentality. And that is the
one quality that the appealing new PBS adaptation of ``Great
Expectations'' wisely avoids. Presented on Sunday and Monday nights
at 9 as part of ``Masterpiece Theatre,'' this BBC-WGBH production
is a cool, picturesque, suspenseful, and slightly ambiguous movie
that hardly recalls director David Lean's 1946 black-and-white
version, the most famous film of the novel. It has a look and feel
of its own, with a realism that well suits Dickens' famous tale of
a poor boy who is made into a gentleman with the help of a
mysterious benefactor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, the cinematography in this ``Great
Expectations'' is dynamic and gritty, with sustained close ups of
the maggots and rats crawling over Miss Havisham's rotting wedding
table, and glimpses of blood trickling along the streets of
London's marketplace. As the adult Estella waits for Pip on a gray
street, her red dress is a small explosion of color, and lawyer
Jaggers' office is a lofty morgue out of ``The Cook, the Thief, His
Wife, and Her Lover.'' The camera moves right up to the faces --
the mouth of the piggish Pumblechook as he eats, the hateful eyes
of Pip's cruel sister -- as often as it distantly pans the marshes
of the North Country where Pip grows up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, more subtly, director Julian Jarrold distinguishes his
movie by keeping the reigns in on his characters, emotionally and
morally. They are unromanticized and low-key performances that only
rarely spill over into the maudlin and righteous. As Pip, Ioan
Gruffudd (pronounced YO-an GRIF-ith) is unshakeably deadpan, an
approach that works slowly but surely. By the end of the movie,
once his character has grown from an arrogant youth into a true
gentleman, Gruffudd's wide-eyed face acquires a hidden, but
definite, air of nobility. His expressive final scenes with the
dying Magwitch, the man he accepts as his father, work beautifully
because of Gruffudd's previous restraint. Justine Waddell deepens
her dollike Estella with similarly slight shifts, changing almost
invisibly from the heartless pawn of Miss Havisham to the needy
rejected wife of the nefarious Bentley Drummle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Miss Havisham, Charlotte Rampling is remarkably effective.
She avoids appearing demented and over the top, emphasizing instead
the wounded side of the jilted woman who plays ruthlessly with Pip
and Estella. Her power over the two children has as much to do with
her insidious, hypnotic personality as it does with her money.
Jarrold avoids lapsing into cartoonishness throughout, not even
letting the good characters -- Biddy, for instance, or Joe --
appear too unbelievably good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour movie, shown in two parts, might have benefited
from another hour or two. Some of the pacing is off, as the plot
starts its inevitable, Dickensian slide toward denouement before
our curiosity has been sufficiently aroused. Also, some of the
smaller characters -- Jaggers, for instance -- could stand closer
scrutiny. Surely, in 1999, there is more than a small interest in
lawyers who are detached from the consequences of their work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
