<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-RELIEF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE GROUP ORGANIZES UNIQUE AID FOR REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many other concerned citizens, Douglas P. Williams has been
haunted by the images of refugees streaming out of Kosovo, limping
across the border with empty hands and empty eyes. From his home in
Boston, Williams felt there must be something he could do to help,
so shortly after he began hearing reports of atrocities in the
Balkans, he contacted more than a dozen aid organizations working
in the area and offered to volunteer. He was turned down by all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were looking for medical help,'' said Williams, 27, a
marketing professional who is between jobs. ``Or they only relied
on experienced volunteers. It was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he came upon a group on the Internet called the Balkan
Sunflowers, and he found his calling. He's now working as the US
coordinator for the grass-roots organization and receives 70
e-mails a day from kindred spirits nationwide. He will join other
Sunflower volunteers in Albania or Macedonia early next month to
work in the refugee camps. The group, organized exclusively on the
Web, has already amassed volunteers working in 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to supplement the essentials provided by traditional
humanitarian groups. The Red Cross, for instance, distributes food
for the body; the Balkan Sunflowers offers sustenance for the soul,
organizing schools and play groups, arts projects and sports
events, self-help groups and cottage industries.
</P>
<P>
   The unique effort was launched by Wam Kat, a Dutch sociologist
who has spent seven years promoting nonviolent conflict resolution
in Eastern Europe. In 1992, he traveled to Zagreb, a city divided
by the war between the Croats and the Serbs. UN peacekeeping forces
had occupied Zagreb, and the streets were littered with sandbags
used to shore up antiartillery shelters all over the city. Kat
planted sunflower seeds in the sandbags, and when the plants
blossomed, the flowers became a symbol of hope and the metaphor for
Kat's humanitarian work.
</P>
<P>
   Kat, 43, spearheaded SunCokret (Croatian for sunflower), a
grass-roots organization made up of 5,000 international volunteers
who helped rebuild the Croatian town of Pakrac, among other
projects. Members of the group came from all over the globe, from
South Africa to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way of empowering people to say, `OK, there is a way
we can help even if we are not trained in special situations,' ''
Kat said from Germany, just before he set off for Albania to set up
the Sunflower office there. ``This is about the emotions of normal
people who are saying, `This is not human. We should start acting.'
You could say that professionals have to do this job, but I think
it should just be humans doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanja Nikolic is one of those humans. Born in a small town in
Croatia, she was a student in Zagreb when SunCokret sprouted. ``I
am not a statement-writing or demonstrations against war or
peace-marching sort of activist,'' she said. ``I love concrete,
grass-roots, practical and creative types of work.'' Since working
with the Sunflower efforts, she is now a full-time activist at the
Center for Peace Studies in Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   Though its 1992 creation was two years before the invention of
the Web, news of Sunflower's work spread worldwide when Kat
published his Zagreb diary on electronic bulletin boards. The group
caught the attention of Vice President Al Gore, who applauded it in
a 1994 speech about global communication. ``After reading Kat's
Croatian diary, people around the world began to send money for
relief efforts,'' Gore said. ``The result: 25 houses have been
built in a town destroyed by war. Governments didn't do this.
People did. But such events are the hope of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those who took action is Sinisa Slijepcevic, who was a
21-year old math major at the University of Zagreb in 1992. He
spent six months working with children in Sadudrija, a refugee camp
in Croatia near the Italian border. ``Most of my friends went to
fight, but I was lucky enough not to have to go,'' said
Slijepcevic, now a doctoral student at the Cambridge University.
``But I couldn't just stay home and not do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The group also recruited former Croatian soldiers to its cause.
``I would run into them and say, `You are perfect for running a
children's garden,' '' Kat recalled. ``They would say, `You are a
fool. I am a soldier.' But they actually learned to do it, and some
of them stayed working with children and became very good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Balkan Sunflowers will attempt to plant such gardens in
refugee camps in Albania and Macedonia, working to improve quality
of life for the refugees once their essential needs have been met
by the traditional aid operations. The group emphasizes that its
work is not about rescue efforts; it is about relieving the
monotony of life in the refugee camps and establishing a sense of
normalcy under abnormal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do this kind of work if you want to change the world
or solve other people's problems,'' said Kees Driessen, a Dutch
psychology student who volunteered in 1992 and will travel to the
camps later this year. ``It's about simple things such as
organizing a Christmas party . . . or learning to make something,
painting for the first time in your life, acting in some small
play. It's not feeding my soul but feeding their brains with
something other than misery and dread.''
</P>
<P>
   Driessen, like other volunteers, was untrained but motivated
when he joined the group. Volunteers receive about a week's worth
of training before they go into the field for stays of three weeks.
Kat and his colleagues are planning the training sessions now, in
addition to setting up field offices in Skopje and Tirana and
connecting with such established groups as the International Rescue
Committee and the office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees,
which supported their work during the Croatian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Kat is treading carefully as he does the groundwork for the
volunteers. ``We are not naive,'' he said. ``We're not saying,
`Just get on an airplane and come.' There is enough chaos going on,
and we have to try to find a way to help rather than create more
chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams and the US volunteers make their sojourn next
month, they will live in the same conditions as the refugees.
Brought together by sophisticated technology, they will work
together in primitive conditions. ``The camps are hell,'' recalled
Slijepcevic, who plans to volunteer again once he submits his
doctoral thesis in June.
</P>
<P>
   But for the members of this unusual cyber group, the experience
has changed their lives. ``It brought war, the effects of war,
closer to home, but it also brought it down to earth,'' said
Driessen. ``It all comes down to this: War is simple, peace is
difficult. And as soon as the fighting stops, the struggle for
peace begins.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Web address for the group is www.balkansunflowers.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
