<HEADLINE>
REMAKING INGALLS, WITHOUT THE AD PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following a restructuring, Ingalls and the president of its
advertising division have parted ways, Ingalls chief executive Bink
Garrison said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second departure of one of the ad agency's three
principal owners in a little more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said the departures were coincidental and unrelated.
``This is not an owners-in-collision situation,'' said Garrison,
who added that the purpose of the restructuring was to position the
agency for robust growth in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Following last week's sale of Mullen to a unit of a New York
communications giant, Boston-based Ingalls has emerged as the
largest independently owned ad agency in New England and the
region's fourth-largest agency as measured by billings.
</P>
<P>
   But Ingalls, whose big clients include T.J. Maxx, Radisson
Hotels, and Citizens Bank, endured a lackluster 1998 while New
England's three largest agencies, now all controlled by outsiders,
enjoyed growth of 20 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison, who is also the majority owner of Ingalls, says he has
no plans to sell Ingalls and follow the lead of Hill Holliday
Connors Cosmopulos, Arnold Communications, and Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ingalls just won the account for the Cambridge
SoundWorks retail chain, it has gone through a string of
second-place finishes in recent ad agency pitches.
</P>
<P>
   According to Garrison, that had nothing to do with the departure
of Steve Connelly as president of Ingalls Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly's departure may be partly a sign of the times as money
made from creating TV and print ads account for a smaller and
smaller percentage of an agencies' total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the action _ and profits _ now come from direct
marketing, interactive marketing, and public relations. Ingalls had
been organized into six divisions. Besides the advertising unit
under Connelly, there were, among others, an interactive marketing
unit and a PR shop.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to differentiate itself from other ad agencies and to
help clients better build brands, those units have been integrated
into a single entity under a ``brand team'' of 10 people reporting
to Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   But one side effect of that restructuring may have been that
Connelly's bailiwick, traditional advertising, lost some of its
preeminence over PR and other disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered Steve a spot on the team, but he chose not to take
it,'' Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bink felt we needed one leader going forward and he was
determined to be that leader,'' said Connelly. ``I'm deciding what
to do with my life right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly owns a piece of Ingalls, but both he and Garrison
declined to say how the ownership issue would be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to offer a variety of services, many agencies are now
made up of several divisions _ one for advertising, another for PR,
each accountable for its own profit-and-loss statement. That means
there's no incentive for the ad department to propose a
direct-marketing solution because revenues then might be credited
to a different agency unit. By integrating all divisions into a
single entity, Garrison hopes to transform Ingalls into a single
brand team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes a lot of sense for them,'' said Adweek New England
editor Judy Warner of the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly is the second top official to leave Ingalls recently.
About a month ago, executive vice president Tom Block resigned to
take a job with an Internet company in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The new job was too good to resist, and in no way should his
departure be interpreted as bailing out of Ingalls, Block said.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said Thursday he does not expect more departures; the
restructuring will result in no layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In this market at least, it seems that big and small shops can
thrive, but the middle can be a tough place.
</P>
<P>
   One reason other local agencies agreed to be bought by outside
companies: They could be part of a larger network that lets them
offer their clients a wider range of services and benefit from
economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   But Garrison sees an opportunity in winning the business of
firms with annual advertising budgets of $7 million to $18 million.
They're too big for a boutique ad agency to handle but too small
for a behemoth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Ingalls had billings of $141 million; revenues fell 9
percent to $17 million after four years of growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ingalls has been around for more than 75 years,'' says Skip
Pile of Pile and Co., a Boston firm that helps companies find ad
agencies. ``And Bink Garrison is resourceful and creative. There's
no doubt they'll survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
