<HEADLINE>
LARRY VS. LARRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Larry King, known almost as well for his serial marriages as
his &UR;  &LR; softball interview style on CNN, is Splitsville again: this
time from his longtime Boston agent, Bob Woolf Associates.
</P>
<P>
   National Enquirer, start your engines!
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine where this could go? King, the 65-year-old,
gravel-voiced broadcaster, has been with Woolf longer than any of
his seven wives. Over the last two decades Woolf has negotiated the
contracts, arranged the speaking engagements, coordinated the
weddings (and the divorces), bought all those gifts for all those
women, some of whom ended up as wives, some of whom didn't. Talk
about knowing where the bodies are buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think King has thought through what he is going to
have to go through in this case,'' Boston attorney Harry L. Manion
III, who has sued the King of Gab on behalf of the Woolf agency,
warns not so subtly.
</P>
<P>
   Now that this long marriage is quite definitely done, there's
the matter of the financial settlement. And Woolf, run by Larry
Moulter, the man who helped buy the down-and-out agency in 1996
after founder Bob Woolf's death, says King owes it roughly $1.3
million as its share of King's latest CNN contract.
</P>
<P>
   A King spokesman didn't return my calls.
</P>
<P>
   The basic facts in a nutshell:
</P>
<P>
   Bob Woolf, a pioneer in the business, had been King's agent
since 1978, when King was making $50,000 a year as a Miami DJ. As
King's star rose, so did his paycheck. In 1993, just before he
died, Woolf negotiated a $14 million CNN contract for King, running
into this year. Woolf's cut: 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, with Woolf dead, King got the agency to cut its share
to 7.5 percent. According to the Woolf suit, the agency agreed to
reduce its fee in exchange for a promise that it would receive 5
percent on any future contracts ``or any modifications, extensions
or renewals thereof irregardless (sic) or whether (Woolf
Associates) negotiaties the contract, modifications, extensions or
renewals.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year International Creative Management, the giant Hollywood
talent agency, negotiated a new five-year, $25 million CNN contract
for King. Woolf maintains it is entitled to 5 percent of that deal.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Moulter says King wanted to change his deal
with Woolf to a flat-fee arrangement, and the agency tried to
accommodate him. King later wanted a contract that would only pay
Woolf a commission on any new deals it brought him. Moulter called
King's latest proposal, made just last week, ``worse than an
insult.''
</P>
<P>
   Moulter and his people sound a little like the good wife who
raised the kids and worked part-time to get hubby through med
school only to be dumped when the big dough started rolling in.
Woolf, and its lawyer Manion, could be just about as willing to
even the score, too.
</P>
<P>
   What did Woolf do for King?
</P>
<P>
   There was the time Woolf overnighted a diamond ring to a hotel
room so King could get engaged on the spot. (This was, ultimately,
one union that didn't happen.) There were years of shopping for
expensive gifts for the wives, the ex-wives, and the girlfriends,
not to mention cars for the children of the wives and girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Woolf helped King manage his 1985 bankruptcy. And it is still
steamed about the one-man Broadway-bound show it helped King
develop, right up through the preview in Louisville, only to have
King walk away after a single performance.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time, just two days before he was to get married
in 1997 to his current wife, 39-year-old Shawn Southwick, that
Woolf arranged a Medivac flight from Los Angeles to New York for
heart surgery. Woolf recommended _ and King rejected _ that he sign
a prenuptial agreement; think Mrs. King number seven might still
harbor a little resentment?
</P>
<P>
   This could be fun in discovery, unless you're Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   Says Moulter: ``Our agency believes the relationship is a
two-way street. We can only help a client if a client wants to be
helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Call me a homer, but I'll take my chances in a foxhole with
Moulter. He may not be half as entertaining, but 20 years later,
he's still on marriage number one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can reach me sbailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
