<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST LICKS FOR THE BIG `LOLLIPOP'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an outdoor art flap percolating in Boston, where the new
owners of 100 Summer St. are not-so-graciously giving the heave-ho
to Gloucester, Mass. artist Rob Amory's 26-foot-tall kinetic
sculpture, ``Helion.'' More informally known as the ``Lollipop''
sculpture, the gaudy orange assemblage has been a landmark for
almost 25 years. The site's new owners, Chicago-based Equity Office
Properties Trust, plan to ``reposition'' (read: raise rents) the
building, and they want ``Helion'' out of there.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, no one wants the thing. The Children's Museum
doesn't want it. The University of Massachusetts won't take it for
their harborside sculpture garden. ``It's an unfortunate kind of
deflated pop art,'' UMass art historian Paul Tucker told the Wall
Street Journal. Amory is waging a publicity counterattack through
his lawyer against what he perceives as negative coverage of the
sculpture's plight in the Journal and by WHDH-Ch. 7, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   I am in receipt of two testimonials, drafted by friends of
Amory's, hailing the timeless nature of ``Helion'' 's contribution
to the Boston landscape. New York-based artist Karen Lukas bemoans
Boston's shortsightedness in ditching the sculpture: ``The
philosophy of New Urbanism and its emphasis on humanism and
diversity relating to architecture and urban development has arisen
in response to this lack of perspective and represents a corrective
effort to restore a sense of continuum and familiarity within our
environments.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey _ she's an artist, not a writer . . .
</P>
<P>
   I like Amory, and I gently suggested that a quarter-century was
a pretty good run for a project that he got paid for. How many
books, I asked, stay in print for 25 years? (Answer: virtually
none.) But he was not to be assuaged. ``This piece has spoken to a
lot of people,'' he says. ``I think it still has life to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Banned in Brookline?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly a year ago that liberal dweebs ran Boston Beer
Co. founder Jim Koch out of his Little League sponsorship (Globe,
May 6, 1998). Koch, who had been invited to become a sponsor, was
hooted out of the league where his own son played baseball when the
PC patrol took offense at a Boston Lager poster in left field _ a
poster that read: ``Our beer is carefully aged before drinking. You
should be, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So one can only imagine the reaction of the Volvo-NPRniks when
they discover that 11-teaspoons-of-sugar-per-serving Pepsi is
invading Boston's Little League. Pop quiz: Which is the greater
health problem in America? Sugar-fueled obesity or alcoholism?
(Answer: obesity.) But I digress . . .
</P>
<P>
   Here are the facts. Pepsi has just launched its ``Takin' It to
the Field'' promotion in the Greater Boston area. Little League
coaches who participate agree to display a 3-foot-tall cooler
designed like a Pepsi can on the sidelines during the game. They
also get 144 free Pepsis, a free score pad, and some coupons for
Pizza Hut comestibles and Major League Baseball kitsch. Pepsi has
assigned ``spotters'' to roam the ballfields and hand out more
rubbish to the teams that have the coolers displayed front and
center.
</P>
<P>
   About a thousand teams have signed up for the free caffeine and
sugar water, says Pepsi spokesman Dave DeCecco. ``Most people love
it because they'd take the kids out for a soft drink after the game
anyway, and now they don't have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   I've discussed the promotion with coaches in Watertown, Newton,
and Roslindale. Some have refused the offer and some have signed
on. (One friend attributes a recent late-inning comeback victory to
a much-needed Pepsi jolt.) One coach who turned down the Pepsi
offer admits that his decision triggered a near revolt in the
dugout. ``The kids think I'm nuts,'' he admits. ``They'd love to
have a soft drink after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi in Little League? I'm told the really interesting story is
how Coca-Cola has insinuated itself into the middle schools. A
future column perhaps . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots haiku
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's good about the team
</P>
<P>
   Bob. But we still think
</P>
<P>
   You're a double-dealing jerk
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
