<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-TALBOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BAD MEMORIES OF '97 FADE, TALBOTS LOOKS TO REGAIN MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a fashion misstep two years ago, can Talbots Inc. regain
the momentum it enjoyed in the early 1990s?
</P>
<P>
   President and chief executive Arnold B. Zetcher thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right on target now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Hingham, Mass. retailer's 50th anniversary, Talbots
had a midlife crisis, or what Queen Elizabeth might call an ``annus
horribilis'' _ a horrible year.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, Talbots boomed as its stores and catalogs
sold classic clothing, shoes, and accessories to affluent women 35
and older.
</P>
<P>
   But overreacting perhaps to casual Fridays and a move toward
less formal careerwear, Talbots attempted in 1997 to woo younger
women with some shorter skirts and flashier styling.
</P>
<P>
   What ensued was disaster, as what was meant to be incremental
shift turned into a radical fashion faux pas in execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``1997 was horrible,'' concedes Zetcher, who adds, ``I don't
ever want to go through another 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Young women weren't at all impressed by the 1997 fashions, and
the chain's loyal middle-aged customers reacted with shock and
dismay. The result? Profits dropped lower than an ankle-length
skirt's hem line _ from $63.6 million to $5.84 million.
</P>
<P>
   Talbots has since repaired much of its self-inflicted damage,
rebounding to a profit of $36.7 million last year as it won back
many of its core customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``1998 was a comeback, a very good year,'' Zetcher says.
</P>
<P>
   So far in 1999, the comeback seems to be continuing apace.
Talbots said Thursday first-quarter earnings should be above Wall
Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Talbots' experience is an extreme example of what can happen
when a retailer implements a new strategy too suddenly. Having come
full circle, Talbots has been able to return to its roots and win
back customers.
</P>
<P>
   But for Talbots a question remains: Can the chain regain the
momentum it enjoyed in the mid '90s?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big question,'' says PaineWebber analyst Richard E.
Jaffe, who's in the wait-and-see mode.
</P>
<P>
   Besides lengthening skirts and returning to classic styles,
Talbots has taken a number of steps to avoid another 1997. It's
replaced its merchant team twice. And new checks and balances are
in place to prevent another fashion mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also introduced a larger-sized clothing line,
and an ad campaign created by Arnold Communications of Boston
promotes the image of a customer who wants to be well dresed but is
too smart to be gulled by Paris fashion trends.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1997 plan was to expand the customer base and sell to
women under 35 and over 35, part of the comeback strategy is to
persuade women who are already customers to spend a bigger share of
their wardrobe dollars at Talbots.
</P>
<P>
   A second part of the strategy is to attract middle-aged women
who don't include Talbots on the list of clothing stores they shop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Talbots is trying to listen more closely to its
customers who can get passionate about its clothing and who were
appalled by the chain's fashion shift in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   `` `You jilted me! I've got no place to shop,' '' Zetcher says
of the feedback he got in customer focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Talbots, some trends now break its way.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing sales are strong for many retailers, and pastels are
nearly as hot this spring as capri pants and Irish linen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastels help Talbots,'' says Hambrecht &AMP; Quist analyst Harry
A. Ikenson, adding, ``We're having one of the strongest spring
seasons for apparel for the entire decade.''
</P>
<P>
   After major consolidation among department-store chains, many
consumers find department store merchandise ``homogenized and
stale,'' analyst Jaffe says; looking for excitement, more are
shopping at specialty chains such as the Limited and Ann Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Talbots may be another beneficiary of this shift. Sales at
Talbots have been ``above plan'' since last fall, Ikenson says.
</P>
<P>
   For its most recent fiscal year, Talbots had sales of $1.142
billion, up from $1.054 billion. Roughly 15 percent of sales come
from the 53 million catalogs it mailed out last year, but catalogs
also play a key role in attracting traffic to the chain's 651
stores, which include Misses, Petites, and Kids stores.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of store customers receive a Talbots catalog,
says Michele Mandell, Talbots senior vice president of stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come into the stores with dog-eared copies'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In helping to put together the fateful spring collection of
1997, Zetcher was like someone trying to figure out a jigsaw
puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   With a lead time of more than a year, Zetcher could look at one
or two pieces of the puzzle at a time, but he says he never saw the
full picture until he walked into a Talbots store in Memphis in
early spring 1997. What in planning was meant to be a nuanced
change was, in reality, a dramatic departure from what Talbots was
known for.
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, what Zetcher saw in Memphis nearly floored
him, a vista of low hemlines and trendiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't seen the whole assortment together before,'' Zetcher
says. ``I stopped and said, `Wait a second. Where am I? Show me
what's classic.' And they couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customer expects us to upgrade our fashion with regularity
but not go to extremes,'' Zetcher says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he says, ``We went too far.''
</P>
<P>
   In looking back at 1997, the chain's great strength may have
also turned out to be its great weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike department stores, which stock their apparel sections
with a wide variety of designer labels, nearly everything sold by
Talbots is made exclusively for the chain through contracts with
clothing factories around the world.
</P>
<P>
   When popular, this so-called private-label clothing provides a
retailer with a high profit margin. With designer clothing, in
contrast, store profits are shared with the designer.
</P>
<P>
   For a retailer, the downside of private label is that the
operative cliche can be ``having all your eggs in one basket.''
</P>
<P>
   A department store can spread its bets. If one designer label
fares poorly, merchandise can quickly be replaced, an option
unavailable to a retailer reliant on private label.
</P>
<P>
   ``A private-label company is less nimble,'' Zetcher says.
``There's risk with private label.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, a retailer will use a catalog to test a new
clothing line. That's what L.L. Bean Inc. may be doing with
Freeport Studio, a line of women's career-wear that's a far cry
from the outdoor clothing stocked at Bean's store in Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   If Bean is cautiously experimenting in 1999, Talbots seemed to
take a headlong leap in 1997, stocking too much of what turned out
to be unwanted inventory. To clear out this merchandise, Talbots
had to mark down prices, which hurt profits.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Talbots could have so miscalculated, Zetcher noted the
chain was coming off several years of record performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up taking some things for granted that maybe you
shouldn't have,'' he says, adding that perhaps he had delegated too
much authority for the 1997 collection.
</P>
<P>
   Preventive measures, including lower inventory levels, have
since been put in place, and recent revenues, with customers again
paying full price, are cause for optimism, Zetcher stresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the fashion business,'' he says. ``You have to take
chances . . .. We'll continue to make changes. We'll continue to
make mistakes. But I don't think we'll have another 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbots stock, trading near its 52-week high, closed Thursday
down 9/16 at 31 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
