<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI HOPEFULS TURN TO AMERICANS TO SHAPE CANDIDACIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With Pizza Hut and McDonald's ubiquitous across the
Israeli landscape, it should come as no surprise that this country
has imported another franchise: American-style politics.
</P>
<P>
   The result, familiar to Americans but a rude awakening for
Israelis, has been a diet of political fast food that puts sound
bites over substance, shock over complexity, and winning over
governing.
</P>
<P>
   As Israel heads into the final stretch of a too-close-to-call
campaign for prime minister, the messages of the leading candidates
are being shaped by two of America's most influential Washington
insiders. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud Party
has again hired the reclusive conservative political strategist
Arthur Finkelstein, while challenger Ehud Barak's Labor Party has
brought in liberal pitbull James Carville.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel is not America, especially when it comes to the
issues voters face. In the May 17 election, the issues are: the
fate of the peace process and the redrawing of Israeli-Palestinian
borders, the battle for the soul of Israel as a secular democracy
or a religious state, the deep cultural divides among Israel's
ethnic groups, and a flagging economy that threatens its future.
Overriding these themes is an even more primal concern of security
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   With such daunting challenges before them, many voters,
political analysts, and even insiders in the campaigns are alarmed
that Israel's electoral debate _ always vitriolic but rarely
lacking substance _ has been reduced to an American brand of slick
TV marketing, attack ads, focus groups, and relentless polling.
</P>
<P>
   In the run up to the May 17 election, Finkelstein, who used
skills honed in Washington to bring Likud to victory in 1996, flew
in last weekend from his horse farm in Ipswich, Mass. and is
running Likud's ``war room'' at an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's choice, Carville, whose ferocity couched in a Cajun
drawl helped bring President Clinton to the White House in 1992, is
the leader of an American trio of advisers trying to clinch the
election for Labor. For now, he is still advising from Washington,
but has been visiting Israel on and off for months to focus Labor's
message and unleash his trademark tirades on talkshows.
</P>
<P>
   A third important candidate, Yitzhak Mordechai of the new Center
Party, has not retained any American consultants, his staff says,
primarily because they cannot afford them. Despite early excitement
about his prospects, polls show Mordechai slipping dramatically,
while the race between Netanyahu and Barak remains neck and neck.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-paced, no-holds-barred political style imported by
Finkelstein and Carville, critics argue, has encouraged candidates
to obscure their views on seminal issues in favor of a battle over
personalities, trivializing Israeli politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israeli politics has always been tough, but never trivial. The
fact that it is less focused on the issues may be nothing new for
Americans, but it is utterly foreign to us,'' said Leslie Susser,
who covers politics for The Jerusalem Report, an English-language
magazine that targets Israeli and American Jews. ``And it couldn't
have come at a worse moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The images in the parties' television campaign ads are the
battleground in this election, which almost certainly will have to
be settled in the June 1 run-off.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, beginning to trail Barak by as much as 8 percent in
polls taken over the last two days, has stepped up his television
ad campaign of fear, a classically Finkelstein approach. One
searing image is of a burning bus in the aftermath of a suicide
bombing in 1996 by the Islamic resistance movement Hamas, while a
narrator, speaking over the sirens and screams, asks voters,
``Remember this?'' His use of these images is credited with winning
Netanyahu the 1996 election, by less than one percent, over
then-Labor Party leader Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   This year Netanyahu's party has also focused on the emotionally
charged issue of Jerusalem, whose final status is yet to be debated
under the terms of the 1993 Oslo peace accord. Israel sees the city
as its indivisible and eternal capital, but the Palestinian
leadership sees East Jerusalem, which Israel occupied after the
1967 Six Day War, as the capital of a future state. In one ad,
Netanyahu shows Jews praying at the Western Wall in Jerusalem's Old
City. In reality there are no flags at the wall, but the ad shows
Israeli flags, until the sky darkens and the camera pans up to show
them replaced by Palestinian flags.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's Barak faces the challenge of convincing voters that he,
too, will be tough on terrorism, but that Netanyahu is ``stuck,''
as Barak often puts it, and unable to move a deadlocked peace
process forward. After close scrutiny of focus groups and polls by
Carville and two other American advisers, Bob Shrum and Stanley
Greenberg, Barak seems to have constructed a policy on the peace
process that is nearly indistinguishable from Netanyahu's. He, too,
insists that the future of Jerusalem is ``non-negotiable'' and
fosters an image of toughness by trumpeting his career as a
distinguished army general.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is also using attacks ads. One features ominous shots of
Netanyahu winking to a far-right Cabinet minister who was indicted
on fraud charges. In another, haunting music creeps in over a
scowling Netanyahu, followed by a graphic of rising unemployment as
a narrator asks, ``A hundred thousand people lost their jobs, why
should he keep his?''
</P>
<P>
   Television ads, restricted to only three weeks before the
election, are broadcast nightly in two, half-hour blocks. Most are
a minute or less, and time is allocated based on each party's
representation in the Knesset, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
   This is a unique, almost quaint, Israeli political tradition,
and many analysts saw it as a solid format for debate. Since the
mid-1970S, Israelis gathered around the television to watch focused
explanations of each party's positions. The next day, the parties
would respond to each other or perhaps deepen their message. Visual
techniques were crude, mostly talking heads and a clear focus on
the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   Although American political advisers have come and gone in
elections here since at least 1981, when Prime Minister Menachem
Begin hired David Garth, their presence was previously low key and
they operated within this Israeli style of campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in 1996, when Israel shifted to direct
elections for prime minister. Before that, voters had chosen a
political party, which nominated its leader and clumsily
constructed political platforms. In 1996, Netanyahu hired
Finklestein and almost overnight changed Israeli political
discourse by focusing on key issues and personalizing the debate.
He was the first to shorten the ads to 20-second visual blasts with
a slogan of only several words, such as ``Peace with security.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, ads for both parties are a rush of images.
Sentences are short and declarative. The message is simple. For
Netanyahu, it's security. For Barak, it's the economy. The
graphics, the quick cuts, the music, the mood are as American as
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Yaron Ezrahi, a professor of political science at Hebrew
University of Jerusalem, said, ``It is utterly unprecedented that
the most salient issue of this campaign is the campaign itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is discussing the Americanization of our politics,
and mourning the fact that it comes just as we face monumental and
historic decisions about peace and war and borders,'' he added.
``We are a society whose identity is still in a formative phase and
we end up being brought to the ballot box by Americans whose
expertise is in how to divert the attention from the performance of
the leaders they represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those directly involved are wary. David Bar-Illan, a
spokesman for Netanyahu who used to write a scathing weekly column
on foreign media coverage of Israel for the Jerusalem Post, is
among them. Even though Netanyahu is credited with starting the
trend, Bar-Illan believes that this time, it works against
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency of the American system is to concentrate on
personalities, which does not work to his adavantage,'' explained
Bar-Illan. ``The concentration on policies would be more to his
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bar-Illan and others are also quick to assign some of the blame
for the downward spiral of political debate to the Israeli media.
Ehud Ya'ari, Israel's top TV political commentator who has also
been a correspondent in Washington, admits the media hold some
resonsibility for getting caught in Finkelstein and Carville's spin
cycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that Finkelestein and Carville do not understand
the nuances of Israeli politics,'' he said. ``We should be more
vigilant in not allowing them to set the agenda. There is too much
at stake here to let that happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
