<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LOUDON-BOS &LR;      05-07 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOUDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY A PRIORITY AT NHIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The auto racing world, rocked once again by tragedy, returns to
Loudon, N.H., and the New Hampshire International Speedway this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   NHIS opens its 10th season with a NASCAR Busch Grand National
race and Busch North race Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, three fans watching an Indy Racing League event at
Lowe's Motor Speedway _ formerly Charlotte (N.C.) Motor Speedway _
were killed when a tire and debris from a crash flew off the track,
over a protecting fence, and into the crowd. It was the second such
incident at a major racetrack in less than a year. Last July, three
fans were killed as a result of a similar crash and flying debris
at Michigan Speedway in a CART Indy car race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing is obviously a dangerous sport, but it shouldn't be
dangerous for folks sitting in the grandstands, that's for sure,''
said Gary Bahre, president of NHIS. ``You should be able to cross
the street downtown and be able to live to tell about it. Freak
things happen every day. But that doesn't make it any more
acceptable. It's a shame, it really is a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The cars involved in the accidents at Charlotte and Michigan
were open-wheeled Indy race cars.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Busch Grand National and Busch North cars at NHIS
this weekend race at slower speeds, have fenders, and the wheels
are less likely to fly off in a crash. The Indy cars are designed
to break apart upon impact. Breaking apart absorbs the impact from
the crash and helps protect the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Reports out of Charlotte, which is a mile and a half long track
with longer straightaways than NHIS, had the cars going about 210
miles per hour on the straights. Last year, the IRL ran the last of
three races at New Hampshire, and CART had run there several years
before that. The Indy cars went about 185 m.p.h. down the
straightaways at the track, Bahre said.
</P>
<P>
   Bahre and his father, Bob, ended their affiliation with the IRL
last year because they were losing money and had been unable to
increase attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR cars this weekend should hit speeds of about 140
m.p.h., Bahre said.
</P>
<P>
   As with Charlotte and other tracks, the racing surface at NHIS
is surrounded by a high catch fence and cement walls. The fence,
Bahre said, is reinforced by a cabling system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge concrete barriers every 300 feet and if a car
gets into the fence, it would spring back,'' Bahre said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been two fatalities at the track. One man was killed
in a go-cart crash and another had a heart attack while racing a
motorcycle, Bahre said. No spectators have been injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety of our guests and folks who work here is
paramount,'' Bahre said. ``We're real comfortable with what we
have, but that's not to say accidents can't happen. They can happen
to anybody at any time. But we are comfortable with the precautions
we've taken here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup drivers Terry Labonte, Geoff Bodine, Kenny Wallace,
Kevin Lepage, and Johnny Benson are taking advantage of the break
in their schedules to compete in the Busch Grand National race . .
. The Busch Series, the main event, goes off at 12:30, with the
North race to follow . . . Dale Earnhardt Jr. leads the Busch
Series points standings and Matt Kenseth is second. Elton Sawyer,
Jason Keller, and Mike McLaughlin round out the top five . . . Brad
Leighton of Center Harbor, N.H., sits atop the North series point
standings with Tom Carey of Orange, Mass., close behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
