<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FLAWED BOOK AT ALBRIGHT'S UNPRECEDENTED RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT 
A Twentieth-Century Odyssey 
By Michael Dobbs 
Henry Holt, 466 pp., illustrated, $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madeleine Albright tensed up in her first interview with Michael
Dobbs, knowing from subordinates that the Washington Post reporter
would be dropping this bombshell: Did Albright, the devout Roman
Catholic emigrant from Czechoslovakia, know that her family was
Jewish and that her parents concealed their past to survive the
Nazis and prevail in the postwar Czechoslovak government? Did she
know that many of her relatives were killed in the Holocaust?
</P>
<P>
   In digging up background on Albright's Old World roots,
interviewing relatives, visiting gravesites, death camps and old
apartments, Dobbs researched a story that won journalistic awards
and makes up a highly compelling first third of his biography,
``Madeleine Albright: A Twentieth-Century Odyssey,'' which was
excerpted in the New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   But in questioning an uncomfortable Albright about her lost
history, of which she had generally professed ignorance, the
veteran foreign correspondent alienated his best source,
complicating his task as he moved beyond newspaper articles to his
book.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to find a more timely subject to chronicle or a
better time to publish this work. Washington is on battle-footing
in what Dobbs's paper has dubbed ``Albright's War.'' And in seeking
to comprehend the deepening US involvement in the Balkans, it is
useful to understand the Czechoslovak emigrant who rose to become
the US secretary of state. And Dobbs, who has spent years reporting
from Moscow and Belgrade, is comfortable in reporting on her
European roots and the crises that convulsed the region.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs delivers lyrical, compelling prose, with references to
Franz Kafka, cameos by George Kennan, detailed descriptions of the
Nazi killing machine and F. Scott Fitzgerald quotes in evoking the
Long Island high life of Albright's future relatives by marriage,
Harry Guggenheim and Alicia Patterson. Albright's years at
Wellesley College and as a young wife and mother, a woman too
preoccupied to catch the Sixties rebellion, would contrast with her
later activist career. Dobbs describes her as the prototype of the
``new woman'' heralded by Betty Friedan's ``The Feminine
Mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs carefully traces Albright's ascent, as the wife of
newspaper heir Joseph Medill Patterson Albright, as board chief of
a prestigious private school in the shadows of the National
Cathedral, as Democratic fund-raiser, campaign worker,
congressional aide, National Security Council assistant, university
lecturer, foreign policy expert and US ambassador to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs traces her steadfast loyalty to a series of mentors and
employers _ Edmund Muskie, Zbigniew Brzezinski, Geraldine Ferraro,
Michael Dukakis and an early favorite at her informal and
policy-oriented Georgetown political salon, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many sides of Madeleine Albright that it is
difficult to sum them up in a sentence,'' Dobbs writes. ``She can
be both charming and ruthless. She can be extraordinarily kind and
generous but also abrupt, even vindictive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Madeleine Albright'' is a vital guide to understanding the
forces that she fought on her rise _ and the intensity of the
scapegoating and backstabbing of Albright that began in the first
days of this increasingly complicated US-led offensive on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Albright irritated some Pentagon officials earlier
this decade when she argued, correctly, that limited US force could
ensure peace and stop the killing in Bosnia. Her rivalry with
Balkans troubleshooter Richard Holbrooke is well known. Her rapid,
unorthodox and caste-crashing climb to power _ she is the first
female secretary of state _ has irked Washington's social,
political, and academic Brahmins.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, without significant cooperation from Albright or
some of her close associates, Dobbs raises many potent questions
that linger long after his attempts to answer them. A conclusion
such as this by Dobbs _ ``she can be understood only in the context
of where she came from and the struggle to get to where she is'' _
only deepens curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Did she, like her father, fashion her faith for survival and
success, converting from Catholicism to Episcopalianism for a
marriage that made her a millionaire, denying her Jewish background
until presented with Dobbs's reportage from Eastern Europe? Or had
her parents successfully obscured her past and Albright never
seriously questioned it?
</P>
<P>
   A broader question, particularly timely in the waning years of
the ethically challenged Clinton administration, also remains: Is
her drive for assimilation, acceptance and success so strong that
it could alter her principles?
</P>
<P>
   It is this point where Dobbs's biography suffers from Albright's
cold shoulder _ and from its publication in the thick of her
career. In a way, Dobbs was cursed with blessings. The very
immediacy that makes this work such a compelling magazine excerpt
and trendy page-turner consigns it to second-rough-draft-of-history
status, its material waiting to be turned over and re-examined
years later by a scholar seeking to realize the promise of a more
comprehensive biography.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
