<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-EMPTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'MIRROR' REFLECTS A DULL IMAGE OF HITLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE EMPTY MIRROR 
Directed by: Barry J. Hershey 
Screenplay by: Hershey, R. Buckingham 
Starring: Norman Rodway, Camilla Soeberg, Peter Miochel Goetz, Doug
McKeon, Glenn Shadix, Joel Gray 
Running time: 129 minutes 
Rating: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So how did Hitler pass the time in his bunker at the end? It
well may have been that he spent his last hours in bombastic rant.
There is, after all, ample filmed evidence to support the
contention that his natural form of address was the harangue, even
when he was talking to himself, which he mostly does here. But
watching talented British actor Norman Rodway impersonating Hitler
in ``The Empty Mirror'' fills us with no terror or pity or,
unfortunately, much of anything except sympathy for an actor
laboring against great odds. He is largely getting nowhere,
dramatically speaking, even when we get past our initial
impression, after seeing that little streetsweeper mustache on a
face that obviously isn't really Hitler's, that we're about to see
John Cleese do a Monty Python Hitler bit.
</P>
<P>
   As he gazes raptly upon filmed footage of himself, the film's
Hitler keeps raving on about what a master of illusion he is. But
his then-novel skill at image manipulation is now high school
textbook stuff, and does not strike with the force of revelation.
The truth is that we're never convinced for a minute that we're
watching the real Hitler in this labored little psychodrama that
also is unable to bring off its conceit of having pointed questions
posed by the spectre of Sigmund Freud. Joel Gray's Goebbels _ a
more silken version of the serpent-like emcee he payed in
``Cabaret'' _ is wasted, too. And so is the poor actor who's
supposed to be playing the SS trooper, obedient to the end at his
typewriter, following orders, taking dictation from Hitler, however
incoherent it gets as Hitler's mind doesn't so much wander as stall
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Empty Mirror'' is no mirror, but it is empty. It plays
like a stage piece, artificial and claustrophobic, that hasn't been
translated into a film. Even if it were, it would still face
formidable and ultimately overwhelming competition from the real
footage the film uses _ newsreels, Eva Braun's home movies that
remind us of the banality of evil, and Leni Riefenstahl's
still-frightening documentary, ``The Triumph of the Will,'' from
whose massed symmetries Hitler still gets off, arch control freak
that he was. At every turn, the real footage withers the would-be
dramatization, making it seem rudimentary and contrived, even when
it goes for the jugular by switching from vague master race
gassiness to vicious anti-semitic fits. But why bother to fantasize
what might have gone on in Hitler's head if you aren't going to
tell us anything we didn't already know? There's just nothing scary
or cathartic, much less revealing, in ``The Empty Mirror.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
