<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S SQUEEZE PLAY IS PURE SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing missing from Major League Baseball is a tin cup
and monkey. League officials might as well remove the mask of being
America's national pastime and tell the world they are shamelessly
trying to keep up with the Joneses.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Joneses are the other professional sports,
each flush with new staggering television deals. The most
astounding is the $600 million deal between ESPN and the NHL, one
of the lowest-rated sports on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The deal averages about $120 million per year for the next five
years. ESPN pays Major League Baseball about $40 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who wants a new deal?
</P>
<P>
   Yup, those needy brats at Major League Baseball. They claimed to
be upset about the three games that ESPN wanted to air on ESPN2.
They whined about ``being forgotten'' by ESPN. But the real deal is
that they wanted ESPN to fork over $350 million for a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, last season's home run chase was great for the sport.
It doesn't mean baseball has the ratings muscle to command a
gigantic increase in rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, baseball has earned a 1.3-rating average on
ESPN. That's pathetic for the so-called national paastime. As ESPN
vice president Dick Glover said, the NFL is the gold standard for
television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, baseball was decimated by the players' strike.
The game's popularity was low and it took Sammy Sosa and Mark
McGwire to put a little strut back in the sport. All of that good
will was erased when Major League baseball tried to terminate its
deal with ESPN, its partner of the last decade. The contract was
scheduled to end in 2002, and, as a result, ESPN has filed suit for
breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   As ESPN explains the story, Major League Baseball was upset over
switching three games to ESPN2 to air NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   They have a point. ESPN has 76.2 million subscribers; ESPN2 has
64.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to ESPN, Major League Baseball agreed to allow ESPN to
pre-empt as many as 10 games for ``events of significant viewer
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ESPN has bumped baseball games to show auto racing,
NHL playoffs, golf, World Cup soccer, the College World Series, and
NFL games. Until now, baseball approved of each of those events.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Major League Baseball is miffed that ESPN decided to
bump games to earn higher ratings with the NFL. The feud came to a
head April 21 when ESPN received a letter from Major League
baseball's chief operating officer Paul Beeston terminating their
contract at the end of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball needs to understand some new economic realities. For
one thing, it signed an agreement through 2002. It signed that
extension in 1997 when the sport's popularity was at an all-time
low. That's not ESPN's problem. Nor does ESPN have to worry about
Major League Baseball's agreement with Fox and NBC, both of which
expire in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better for baseball if all of its television
contracts expired at the same time in order to negoitiate a better
deal. But they don't.
</P>
<P>
   And to try to make up any old reason to end its contract with
ESPN is preposterous, especially considering that baseball games in
September are the lowest rated of the regular season. Last year,
September games received a 1.7 rating on ESPN; the three NFL games
earned a 7.3 average.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about the nine hours of programming.
</P>
<P>
   It's about baseball standing up for its right to squeeze a few
more nickels out of a network.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder baseball doesn't have anything to say when the
Fox-owned Dodgers sign Kevin Brown for $90 million or the
Disney-owned Anaheim Angels spend $80 million for Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   They are trying to get some of that television money as well.
Its the American way, trying to get something for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spanish rights
</P>
<P>
   The NBA and Radio Unica signed a deal to allow the Spanish radio
network to air live coverage of this year's and next's NBA Finals
and the 2000 All-Star Game. . . NBC's Isiah Thomas and Bill Walton
join MSNBCSports.com's NBA playoff coverage team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MUMMY-HNS     05-07 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MUMMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITHER THE DECENT MONSTER FLICK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horror films used to be terrifying. Monsters used to be
mysteries. And movies used to be more than an excuse for insensate
violence and gruesome special effects, 90 percent of which are
aimed straight at the gag reflex.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a nostalgic rant, but the folks who made ``The
Mummy'' are asking for it. Any remake of a 1932 horror classic
starring Boris Karloff as a 3,700-year-old dead guy demands
comparison with the original _ and with the later Christopher Lee
version, released in 1959 by that venerable cheese factory, Hammer
Films. The Hammer version is the nastier of the two, but both are
gripping tales with moody settings and slowly mounting suspense.
And they're both _ ready for this? _ scary.
</P>
<P>
   The new one isn't. Written and directed by Stephen Sommers
(``Deep Rising''), ``The Mummy'' is less a horror film than a
frenzied hybrid of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and the ``Alien''
sequels, a bloated gross-o-rama that mistakes jokiness for humor,
action for excitement and violence for bona fide chills.
</P>
<P>
   It's a prime example of what happens when the urge to show off
(look, Ma, new computer gimmicks!) overwhelms the urge to tell a
story. Filmmakers don't care about spooking us any longer; they
want to make us retch.
</P>
<P>
   The elements are familiar: 3,289 years ago, a high priest named
Imhotep (Arnold Vosloo) canoodled with the Pharaoh's mistress.
Unfortunately, Pharaoh discovered them in flagrante delicto they
stabbed him to death, after which the mistress was executed, after
which Imhotep tried to revive her with a blasphemous prayer from
The Book of the Dead (no relation to Tibet).
</P>
<P>
   Pharaoh's guards stopped him, cut out his tongue, wrapped him in
linen and entombed him alive in a secret compartment alongside his
mummified lover. There he remained, bearing a curse for anyone who
dared open the vault.
</P>
<P>
   Skip ahead a few years, to 1923. The French Foreign Legion is
battling an army of fierce Egyptians sworn to protect Hamunaptra,
the elaborate underground ``city of the dead'' where Imhotep nurses
his curse. One of the legionnaires is a smart-aleck American named
O'Connell (Brendan Fraser, trying hard), who gets a whiff of evil
when the sand around him rises into the shape of a mummy's face.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connell escapes, and before long he's chaperoning a
feisty, klutzy English librarian (Rachel Weisz) and her no-goodnik
brother (John Hannah) back to Imhotep's resting place in hopes of
finding a royal stash. Along the way they bump into a bunch of
treasure-seeking Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, the Americans wake up the mummy. And oops, the roused
mummy embarks on a maiming-and-killing spree of astonishing range
and computer-generated ingenuity, plucking organs from the unlucky
explorers and sucking the juice out of them like milkshakes through
a straw. In a bold stroke, he also inflicts upon humanity the
plagues of Egypt. Imhotep: demon mummy from hell.
</P>
<P>
   Bits of this are entertaining. The first 20 minutes (the
ancient-Egypt flashbacks and legionnaire battle scenes) are
magnificently conceived and staged, and the mummy itself is an
amazing feat of animation. But Sommers doesn't know when to end it:
He piles on the visual showstoppers until the entire thing is a
nonstop parade of disfigurements, dismemberments, exposed entrails,
gouged eyes, rotting faces and skin-burrowing beetles reminiscent
of ``The Matrix.'' Keep in mind, this is a film in which the
mum-man's one kissing scene is cut short when his face starts to
decompose.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trouble is modern Hollywood's tendency to inflate
everything, from budgets to body counts to the producers'
blimp-size egos. The running time is inflated from 72 minutes to
two hours plus. The tomb is inflated into a subterranean metropolis
with chasmal, jewel-filled crypts. Suspense is inflated into
flat-out shock, ignoring Hitchcock's old dictum that waiting for a
bomb to go off is vastly more interesting than watching it explode.
</P>
<P>
   And the mummy? He's inflated, too _ from a walking Band-Aid into
a flesh-eating, viscera-spewing, sandstorm-blowing, semi-decayed
corpse who growls like a T-Rex and slings swarms of locusts onto
the streets of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think is out there?'' asks Weisz. ``In a word:
evil,'' says Fraser, doing John Wayne one second, Clint Eastwood
the next.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser is well cast for this sort of thing; he has a natural
goofiness that offsets the movie's abundant gore. Sommers' jocular
script is alternately punchy and trite, including a few profoundly
racist cracks about an Egyptian guide's body odor. It's all a big
joke, you see _ a far cry from the deadly earnest monster films of
yore, when manly men with British accents saved well-coiffed
damsels from lumbering ghouls.
</P>
<P>
   The men are still manly, the damsels still coiffed, but no one
takes the ghouls too seriously these days. Terror in the splatter
era is by definition comic: Even the most gruesome (and genuinely
frightening) examples, like ``Evil Dead 2'' or ``Scream,'' mix
irony in with the blood.
</P>
<P>
   That's what ``The Mummy'' aims for, and that's where it fails.
By emphasizing waggish, nonstop violence over a cool, slow scare,
Sommers and company have made a film as eager to please as it is
fatiguing. Is it revolting? Yes. Is it fun? Now and then. But is it
horror? Not even close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
