<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE WINS THIS `ELECTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ELECTION 
Directed by: Alexander Payne 
Screenplay by: Payne, Jim Taylor (novel: Tom Perrotta) 
Starring: Matthew Broderick, Reese Witherspoon, Chris Klein, Phil
Reeves, Mark Harelik, Delaney Driscoll, Molly Hagan, Colleen Camp,
Jessica Campbell, Frankie Ingrassia 
Running time: 103 minutes 
Rated: R (strong sexuality, sex-related dialogue and language, and
a scene of drug use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Election'' is an invigoratingly mordant comedy that proves
that Alexander Payne's rambunctious debut, ``Citizen Ruth,'' was no
fluke. That film pivoted on Laura Dern's far from model citizen and
her fight to avoid being turned into an abortion pawn. This one is
driven by Reese Witherspoon's high school overachiever wh is too
much of a perfect citizen for her well-intended civics teacher's
comfort. You've got to laugh at Witherspoon's tightly wound Little
Miss Perfect, rising at dawn to do her hair and encase herself in a
preppy look before baking cupcakes to pass out at school as
vote-getters in her campaign for student council president.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Flick is the name of this Stepford Candidate. It's a name
that goes with her hard, snappy manner and the don't-mess-with-me
look behind her frighteningly synthetic cheeriness. The message,
written in icing on top of those cupcakes, is Pick Flick. The
unwritten message is: Look out if you don't. Matthew Broderick's
teacher, afraid of her relentlessness, thinks maybe it would be
better for everybody if she were stopped. So he talks a popular
jock with a disarmingly modest manner into running against her.
That turns the life of the jock's sister upside down when her
bisexual girlfriend dumps her and begins chasing her brother
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Campbell's angry and jilted outsider, alienated to begin
with, jumps into the race as a third party candidate, promising to
abolish the student council altogether if elected. Drawing upon Tom
Perrotta's novel inspired by the three-way 1992 presidential
election and a high school principal's attempt to nullify the
election of a pregnant prom queen, Payne boldly weaves a morality
tale peopled by spineless administrators, sexually wayward teachers
and merciless students. As he did in ``Citizen Ruth,'' he convinces
us that there's something rotten in Omaha, his hometown, and, by
extension, everywhere. By the time he's finished, there's smoke
coming off the screen as well as laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Following the dictum that no good deed goes unpunished,
Broderick's earnest teacher finds himself paying dearly for daring
to cross Witherspoon's steely Tracy. But part of his undoing is his
involvement with the wife of a colleague fired for having sex with
a student. To Payne's credit, the characters in ``Election'' aren't
wholly virtuous or villainous. Broderick's teacher is as much a
victim of boredom and marital dissatisfaction as he is of Tracy.
And there's something touchingly vulnerable in Tracy's enslavement
by her own ambition. Without hitting the point too hard,
Witherspoon makes clear that there's something pitiable about
Tracy's compensation for her own feelings of inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that doesn't mean she can't do considerable damage. But
then nobody is very nobly motivated in the seamy little microcosm
on view here. These days, it doesn't take much to float a black
comedy view of high school, and ``Election'' accomplishes this with
Swiftian brilliance. In fact, the film's most sympathetic
characters aren't Witherspoon's rigid little success machine or
Broderick's nice guy about to self-destruct on a midlife crisis.
They're Chris Klein's charmingly affable jock and Campbell, as his
understandably angry and bracingly honest sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election' is the scalding morality fable it is because it
never falls into the trap of dividing the world between caricatures
of good and bad. It proceeds from an essentially pessimistic view
of human nature. Its performances achieve the impact they do
because Broderick makes contact with a good man's tragic flaw and
Witherspoon tempers her fury with a sense that she works as hard as
she does partly to avoid confronting her own inner emptiness.
``Election'' is a natural running mate to the decade's other
exceptional high school movie, ``Rushmore.'' It's as original, and
has sharper teeth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
