<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-STARWARS-BOS &LR;      05-07 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STARWARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SOARS ON NEW SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Lucas and Steven Spielberg can sing all of John
Williams's main themes from the ``Star Wars'' trilogy. In that
respect, they are scarcely unique _ probably most Americans under
the age of 50 can duplicate the feat. The original ``Star Wars'' LP
outsold every other soundtrack album in history _ and every
orchestral recording ever made _ and it's likely to leave last
year's ``Titanic'' behind in a cloud of Pod-racer exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just in advance of the eagerly-awaited release of ``Episode
I _ The Phantom Menace,'' &UR;  &LR; Sony has delivered Williams's new CD to
the stores. It's a stirring and far-reaching score, one of the most
ambitious that Williams has ever crafted. In it one can hear the 20
years of additional experience in composing, recording, and
conducting his music and that of others that Williams brought to
this task. Some of the thematic material is familiar _ he could
hardly avoid the ``Star Wars'' main title _ but there is a lot of
entirely new music, and some of it transcends generic categories.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is billowing flight music sweeping across galaxies;
jagged fight music; whirring infernal-machine chase music; striding
marches of nobly resolute character and marches of heavy and
sinister tread; there's a whimsical novelty bit, ``Augie's Great
Municipal Band,'' with children's chorus and police whistles, that
reminds us of Williams's deft cabaret parody in the original ``Star
Wars.'' The harp is repeatedly used to add a touch of mystery and
wonder. But there are also many new colors in this score, which
features a prominent role for the chorus for the first time (London
Voices joining the London Symphony Orchestra, which has performed
throughout the series), and an equally prominent part for
synthesizer, which contributes some chilling otherworldly touches
and a few slices of the light sabre too.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking passage may be the second track, ``Duel of the
Fates,'' for chorus and orchestra, which comes back in the end
credits _ a battle between the forces of good and evil turned into
a violently rhythmical pagan ritual; Stravinsky lurks in the
background. The text Williams found in an old Celtic poem
translated into English by Robert Graves in ``The White Goddess'';
Williams had it translated into a number of ancient languages, and
chose Sanskrit because he loved the vowels. Another key passage is
``Anakin's Theme,'' depicting the child-hero of the film _ the
figure who will grow up during the next two films and cross over to
the Dark Side and become Darth Vader. A melody of innocence spins
out over a gently flowing accompaniment; the whole thing is so
attractive we almost don't notice how unstable it is harmonically,
and how underneath and within it the familiar theme of Darth Vader
is threatening to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner wrote the librettos for his ``Ring'' cycle backwards,
adding the ``back story'' that would make sense of ``Siegfried''
and ``Die Gotterdammerung'' But Wagner had the advantage of writing
the music in order, and of knowing he was composing a vast,
unprecedented cycle of works. Williams has had to work backwards,
so among other things, his score is a triumph of professional and
imaginative craftsmanship. It is also remarkably fluid; Williams
knows how to change musical character within a few beats, and how
to develop themes and interweave them to achieve an emotional
complexity that matches the way Lucas's primal images recur
throughout the films, assembling and reassembling in the memory,
and accruing a different resonance every time.
</P>
<P>
   The principal new novelty character, Jar-Jar Binks, is likely to
prove as controversial as the Ewoks in ``The Return of the Jedi''
did. Jar-Jar is there for the kids, and the ``Star Wars'' junkies
are going to grow impatient with him. Williams may help win people
over with his music, the way he made the audience fall in love with
Princess Leia even though Carrie Fisher didn't make it easy. For
Jar-Jar, Williams has fashioned a charming lopsided theme,
captivatingly orchestrated, that sounds like an extra ``Enigma''
variation from Elgar. The English composer, Williams's favorite,
also influences the noble music for the death and funeral of the
Jedi knight Qui-Gon (Liam Neeson).
</P>
<P>
   Williams's music is unabashedly and affectionately derivative of
music the composer loves _ Prokofiev as well as Elgar _ and
including the film music of ``golden age'' composers like Erich
Wolfgang Korngold and Miklos Rozsa, to which he pays conscious
homage. In this, the music parallels the films, which are an
anthology of themes from ancient and Wagnerian epics, comic books,
serials, and old movies. After all, the opening scroll firmly
places the action in the distant past, not in the future (``A long
time ago, in a galaxy far, far away''). Out of his sources, George
Lucas created a personal synthesis that is original, and Williams's
music is original too. Listening, in advance of actually seeing the
movie, one can nevertheless clearly hear the story that is
unfolding, and the emotional resonances that it unleashes.
</P>
<P>
   In the album, Lucas writes a brief tribute to Williams. ``John
had to draw upon the signature themes while creating a new, if
somehow familiar, musical galaxy. And he had to visit new emotional
territory in Episode 1. His music had to help tell the story of a
pacifist Queen who confronts the need to fight for the survival of
her people, a mother who must give up her son that he might achieve
his true potential, and noble Jedi faced with the rise of an
unimaginable. Once again, John has exceeded my expecations and
produced a lavish, rich, moving and thrilling score. Every fan of
`Star Wars' _ and of great music is in his debt.'' What lingers in
the memory after hearing the music to ``The Phantom Menace'' is not
bombast and outsize heroics but the richness of emotional texture _
this is a score that only John Williams could have written, and
that John Williams probably couldn't have written 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's presentation leaves a lot to be desired. The CD does not
present the complete score, which means that fans will have to buy
another album at some future point (just as they did with the
earlier films in the series). The annotation is skimpy _ no text or
translation for the choral episodes _ and it is printed in sepia
type on a yellow-orange background that is almost impossible to
read. The sticker on the box promises that the leaflet will unfold
into a poster, and so it does, if your idea of a poster is about
the size of a Sunday bulletin in church, 19 by 14 inches. This may
be the only thing about ``Star Wars'' that isn't outsize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
