<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WINSLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WINSLOW BOY' A SOBERING LOOK AT THE HIGH COST OF JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WINSLOW BOY 
Directed and written by: David Mamet, based on Terence Rattigan's
play) 
Starring: Nigel Hawthorne, Jeremy Northam, Rebecca Pidgeon, Gemma
Jones, Guy Edwards, Matthew Pidgeon, Colin Stinton, Aden Gilette,
Sarah Flind, Neil North 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name of David Mamet would not be the first to spring to mind
as the one to update ``The Winslow Boy,'' Terence Rattigan's
portrait of British justice celebrating its own oaken decency. But
it works beautifully on several levels. In some ways, Mamet's new
film even exceeds the fine 1950 film of Rattigan's 1946 play. Nor
is it the leap it might at first seem for Mamet. His reputation as
a writer rests on the words he puts in the mouths of American
lowlifes. But his writing has always been exquisitely precise and
chiseled, and it's easy to see how the equally lapidary writing of
Rattigan would appeal to him. The important point in all this is
that they are soulmates linked by a passion for crafting spoken
lines, however different they may be in other respects.
</P>
<P>
   The calibration of passions in Mamet's take on ``The Winslow
Boy'' is as keenly gauged as anything in any of the recent Jane
Austen films. And there are passions. Foremost, the simple but
profound passion for right. It's not difficult to see, beneath the
play's Edwardian carapace, how subversive Rattigan's play was. It
zeroed in on a cause celebre of the time, the expulsion of a naval
cadet accused of stealing a five-shilling postal note, and the
one-sidedness of it because under the law the boy's parents had no
way of clearing their son, whom they believed innocent. Because,
legally speaking, the naval academy and by extension the king could
do no wrong, the Winslows' recourse is limited. There is a
loophole, but the odds are against them slipping through it.
</P>
<P>
   Which of course makes the struggle more dramatic and noble.
Nigel Hawthorne as the elder Winslow, respectable and financially
comfortable enough to enjoy societal perks as a retired bank
manager, although not really wealthy, is the film's center of
gravity. Although an initially forbidding patriarch, he softens in
his moments with his young son, whom he believes enough to gamble
everything on clearing his name, even to the point of exhausting
his family's security and his own health. He's stern, but loving
and humane, a believable incarnation of moral passion. It's an
underplayed performance of silken delicacy and inner ruggedness,
the kind for which awards were invented.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. In addition to knowing how to alter the original
(mostly, he pares), Mamet in his sixth film continues to grow and
deepen as a director of actors. He impressively orchestrates the
largely unspoken but increasingly eloquent duet between Rebecca
Pidgeon as the Winslow boy's suffragette sister and Jeremy Northam
as the taciturn but brilliant lawyer the family engages to defend
and exonerate him. Mamet encourages them to express what lies
between the lines, and they do so satisfyingly, merging the high
passions they attach to their respective callings with their more
reserved personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, Mamet gives us a world bathed in a grave clarity and
somber light, analogue to its moral climate. There's nothing
nostalgic or celebratory about it. Clearly, it's a world rumbling
with change and it requires strength to negotiate. The film
craftily puts the focus on the economic, social, emnotional, and
physical drain the case puts on the family. If the elder Winslow is
visibly aged and walking on canes as the case drags on, wondering
if he hasn't been more motivated by destructive pride than by a
search for justice, Pidgeon's wan, pale visage convincingly
reflects the erosion of her hitherto undentable resolve. That we
see the cost of fighting for justice is what's so touching here. In
a world where nothing comes easily, justice certainly doesn't. In
the film's muted style lies its own integrity and its own success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
