<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-PHANTOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHANTOM' SETS NET ABUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Force is out, and the reviews are, well, lukewarm to
glowing.
</P>
<P>
   In case you live in a non-Jedi universe, the reviews in question
concern ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' the
long-awaited prequel to George Lucas's wildly popular trilogy. Ever
since the film was screened Tuesday night for industry types at
``private'' sneak previews in eight cities the Internet has been
abuzz with advance word. Thursday afternoon it was nearly
impossible to gain access to many of the popular movie gossip
sites, which were overloaded with hits. Some of the headlines on
reviews posted at www.ain't-it-cool-news.com, the site run by cyber
renegade Harry Knowles, ranged from hesitant pans like ``Er'' and
``D'oh'' to enthusiastic raves like ``WOW'' and ``Yeah, baby!''
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders are usually reserved about such advance
screenings, but the general consensus on line was that the film
doesn't disappoint when it comes to the wow factor. The special
effects were ``mind-boggling,'' according to Wired News. Ditto for
the costumes and cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   But insiders differed on their view of the characters and the
story. The anonymous Wired report claimed, without a touch of
irony, ``The story is the weakest aspect of the film.'' Daily
Variety reported that the New York audience ``was ready to embrace
the film but never did.'' The Hollywood Reporter praised the film
as kid-friendly, but other reviewers complained that it was aimed
too heavily at children instead of adults.
</P>
<P>
   In short, every ``Er'' was countered by a ``Wow.'' Without
giving away any secrets, here are some of the key points.
</P>
<P>
   --Acting: Some folks had less than positive things to say about
Jake Lloyd, the boy who plays 10-year-old Anakin Skywalker (a.k.a.
Darth Vader). But a reviewer who calls himself Sithslayer who saw
the film in Detroit and wrote about it on ain't-it-cool-news begged
to differ: ``He was fantastic,'' he cooed. Most folks agreed that
the malicious Darth Maul was sufficiently evil, but some wanted to
see more of him while others thought he was too scary for younger
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   --Jar Jar Binks, the computer-generated cuddly character, was
described as adorable for the kiddies but annoying (and cloying)
for grown-ups. ``What's up with the Jamaican accent?'' one reviewer
wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   --The special effects, most sneak-preview attendees agreed, are
as good as they get, especially when they're generated by the
legendary Industrial Light and Magic.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which way the thumb points, the film is still expected
to rake in about $400 million in domestic ticket sales after it
opens officially on May 19. What do you expect from a film that has
fans camping out on street corners to buy tickets and lining up at
toy stores to buy trinkets at midnight?
</P>
<P>
   The on-line fan sites have been gearing up for the opening for
more than a year, posting the tiniest tidbits of information about
the upcoming release. But for the most part, the fans didn't manage
to sneak into the advance screening, which is creating contention
among some diehard enthusiasts. ``The problem is that these reviews
are not coming from fans, they're coming from industry types,''
says Steve Head, a Weymouth real estate professional and a
contributor to TheForce.net fan site. ``Positive reviews would have
filtered out if the fans had been let in.'' All in good time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
