A8242 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOAT-MILK-SOAP-HNS &LR;      05-07 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOAT-MILK-SOAP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMER TURNS EXCESS GOAT MILK INTO NATURAL SOAPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By H.E. MacDONALD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You probably won't come across this goat-milk
soap in a chain supermarket or drugstore. But according to one goat
farmer who makes it, the product is drawing interest _ and
customers _ from all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to get away from commercial products,'' said
Dottie Cross, owner of Capri-Dot's Nubians, a dairy goat farm in
Rensselaer County, N.Y.. ``I think it's a growing trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross has found a new and potentially profitable niche in skin
care. She began making Capri-Suds goat milk soap about a year ago,
hoping to find a good use for her herd's excess milk. Since then,
she has attracted a customer base that includes a 4-H club, a Long
Island health food store, a church in Rochester, N.Y., and an Ohio
candle shop. She also makes goat milk shampoo bars.
</P>
<P>
   Goat milk soap isn't such an unusual idea _ milk baths go back
to the days of the ancient Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   Cross came up with her original recipe through trial and error,
research on the Internet and contacting other soap makers. Each bar
contains about an ounce of milk along with olive oil, palm oil,
coconut oil and other natural ingredients, including glycerin, a
good-for-your-skin byproduct often removed from commercial soap.
The mixture is poured into a mold and frozen. After about 24 hours,
the soap bars _ embossed with a figure of a Nubian goat _ are
removed, dried and ready to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The soap comes in over 20 different fragrances, including
vanilla musk, cucumber, milk 'n honey, orange blossom, spicy lime,
peaches 'n cream, apple blossom and one scent with a racy name _
naked ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Cross named the product Capri-Suds to establish a link between
the soap and her herd. Also, capri goat.
</P>
<P>
   So far, sales have varied widely. Cross says she makes about 60
bars each week and doesn't plan to build up too large an inventory.
At this point, she sometimes goes a few weeks between sales, then
might receive an order for 32 bars at once. At $2.50 to $3 per bar,
Capri-Suds bars are competitive with the $4 bar of goat milk soap
sold at specialty shops.
</P>
<P>
   Cross currently markets her soaps on the Internet at
www.enaturalmall.com, an on-line natural products shop, and
www.simplerway.com, a craft fair site. She plans to create a Web
site of her own to promote the farm as well as Capri-Suds. She also
may develop goat milk soap for animals that will include citronella
to repel fleas.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Capri-Suds portion of Cross' business is small
compared to the breeding and selling of dairy goats, which keeps
her busy and close to home. However, she hopes to do more business
with Capri-Suds by selling wholesale to stores and reaching out to
customers herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream is to have a mail-order business from the house,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
