<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHERS-$ADV09-COX     05-07 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERS-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN LESS LIKELY TO BE MOTHERS THAN IN THE PAST
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American women are less likely to be mothers than a
generation ago, according to the U.S. Census Bureau, and those who
are mothers have fewer children and go back to work sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, two out of five women of child-bearing age won't be
celebrating Mother's Day. According to the latest Census Bureau
statistics, 42 percent of women aged 15 to 44 were childless in
1995. That's up from 35 percent in 1976, the first year such
figures were available.
</P>
<P>
   Women who do become mothers have fewer children, the census data
shows. In 1995, the average mother had 1.2 children, down from 2.0
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``This data might possibly indicate that women have better
access to contraception and are making different life choices than
in 1976,'' said Diane Bell, director of the George Washington
University Women's Studies program.
</P>
<P>
   Today's mother is more likely to work outside the home during
the first year of their child's life than a generation ago. More
than 55 percent of women who had a child in 1994 went to work
within a year, up from 31 percent in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women can't afford not to return to work,'' said Karen
Johnson, vice president of membership for the National Organization
of Women. ``We are seeing that more and more families have to
become two-income families.''
</P>
<P>
   The census data also showed that older women were more likely to
work sooner than younger women. Among women having a first child,
77 percent of those 30 to 44 went back to work in the following
year, compared to 72 percent of women 25 to 29, 63 percent of women
20 to 24, and 43 percent of women 15 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau report for 1995 recorded 60.2 million women
between 15 and 44 years of age. Of these women, there were 35
million mothers and nearly 3.7 million births within the year.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia had the most childless women, with 55.4
percent, followed by Massachusetts with 51 percent. The states with
the lowest percentages of women without children were Arkansas,
with 34.8 percent, and Wyoming, with 35.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of unwed mothers has also risen. In 1995, of the
22.8 million women who had never been married, 21 percent had given
birth to at least one child. Just five years earlier, 18 percent of
the 20.7 million mothers had never been married.
</P>
<P>
   While the majority of mothers in 1995 were adults, 800,000 teens
aged 15 to 19 were mothers, up from 450,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families are changing, and the only question is whether it
will be for the better or for worse.'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
