   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Wen Ho Lee, the scientist accused of
passing nuclear secrets to China, issues a statement through his
lawyer defending himself. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ROMANIA (Bucharest) _ Pope John Paul II arrives on the
first visit by Pope to an Eastern Orthodox Country in 1,000 years.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-ELECT (Edinburgh) _ In voting for the first Scottish
Parliament in 300 years, Labor finishes first with 39 percent, the
Nationalists second with 29 percent. Labor is expected to form a
coalition with the Liberal Democrats. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TV (Hong Kong) _ In a move that may reflect China's
jitters during a year of politically charged milestones, the
Chinese government has begun to clamp down on illegal reception of
foreign television channels. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FUNDRAISING (Austin, Texas) _ President Clinton speaks
at two fund-raisers in Texas, expecting to raise a total of
$800,000 for the DNC from a lunch in Houston and dinner in Austin.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-STEELE (Alexandria, Va.) _ The jury continues to
deliberate in the trial of Julie Hiatt Steele, accused of perjury
in testimony about the Kathleen E. Willey case. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   CNN-TAILWIND-SUIT (Undated) _ In the continuing dispute over
CNN's much-criticized Tailwind report, one of its producers, April
Oliver, files suit against the company and names a source. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   JENNY-JONES-SUIT (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Jenny Jones, a TV talk show
host, was found to be negligent in the death of a guest on the
show. The jury in a civil suit awarded $25 million to the family of
the dead man, Scott Amedure, who was slain by another guest,
Jonathan Schmitz, after Amedure revealed his homosexual attraction
to Schmitz. (Summary from wires) By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-HESS (New York) _ Leon Hess, who took over his family's
bankrupt fuel-oil business during the Depression and built it into
one of the world's largest petroleum companies, but was perhaps
best known as the steadfast owner of the long-floundering New York
Jets football team, died Friday in New York. He was 85. By Gerald
Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy resumed its torrid pace of
job creation last month after an interruption in March, generating
234,000 jobs without putting pressure on companies to raise
employees' wages. The jobless rate crept up to 4.3 percent in April
from 4.2 percent in March. While the gain in new jobs was somewhat
larger than forecasts, hourly wages rose less than expected, easing
concern that interest rates are headed higher. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
