<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ARCTIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDEM FILM IS THE `DIE HARD' OF LOVE STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julio Medem's ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle'' has the potent
detailed beauty of an autumn gale in which the leaves do a slo-mo
blow-by and the raindrops seem to need parachutes to descend. It's
sopping wet with involving comeliness and its action divinely
telegraphed.
</P>
<P>
   But it's easier to get inside one of those little wintry snow
domes than to access Medem's star-crossed love saga.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Lovers'' has a similarly hypnotic arrangement in which
everything has been situated just so. Medem constructs a world with
the surgical meticulousness it takes to build a ship in a bottle _
and the effect is just as how'd-he-do-that mysterious, and just as
synthesized. Not in the way a film-by-committee would be but in
that grand experimental way most writer-directors ruin in the
execution. Medem earns the unique distinction of having made one of
the greatest love stories never felt.
</P>
<P>
   Photographed by Kalo F. Berri with exceeding vibrancy,
``Lovers'' is the ballad of two people meant to be together. But
you know this only because the refrain is ``we were meant to be
together.'' Otto and Ana, the film's lifelong paramours played in
three stages of life by six different actors, live in a state of
irony that Medem concocts to bring them together then drive apart,
with the constant ebb and flow of complication, coincidence or
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The moment young Otto (Peru Medem) sees young Ana (Sara
Valiente), he knows they were meant to be together, and when he's
unsure, she isn't. The film see-saws between each other's memory _
told in chapters _ of the evolution of their mutual intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   Medem would have you believe the two were born in love. Through
a gracefully imagined series of happy accidents and bizarre
tragedies, Otto's father (Nancho Novo) remarries Ana's mother (Maru
Valdivielso), and brother and sister discover the joys of each
other's sex, in secret as a gaggle of jokes only we're let in on.
</P>
<P>
   Medem, in fact, makes us privy to everything we need to know
about Otto and Ana without allowing them to do more than dangle
from the strings attached to his agile screenwriting like a
marionette rendition of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' or an Isabelle
Allende version that goes easy on the history and politics. Medem
fancies himself a magic-realist, and he is. He's also an emotional
illusionist who makes you think you're experiencing something when
you're not.
</P>
<P>
   His script is too rich to start giving it away. But it has the
hocus-pocus velocity of a roller coaster cum tunnel of love, ending
where it began, suffocatingly self-contained like Otto and Ana's
palindromic names. And the story seems told on levers and pulleys
as though it were a Rube Goldberg love story, in which Alberto
Iglesias' soaring, inflamed score and each of the fantastic
performances _ particularly Valiente and Najwa Nimri, who plays Ana
as a drifting love-sick adult, looking alternately like Winona
Ryder and Natalie Wood _ are so beautifully windswept but airtight
that no one seems to breath organic air. This may be the ``Die
Hard'' of love stories: so much adrenalized pulchritude your heart
barely feels a thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
