A8250 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAZY-WAR-HNS &LR;      05-07 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAZY-WAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO UNDERSTAND THE KOSOVO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAYNE WOLFE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Please, somebody, explain this Kosovo thing to
me.
</P>
<P>
   I've watched the news, clicked on background stories on the
Internet, and I still don't get it. I know it's more than a
``Gulliver's Travels'' tale _ a war over cracking soft-boiled eggs
at the pointed end or the fat end. And yet, as I watch the six
o'clock news, the people involved look pretty much the same to me.
And I wonder: How do the bad guys even know who to shoot?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that I can't even get the name of the country
straight. It's not Yugoslavia, but it used to be Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is not a state, but it looks like one on the map with its
solid yellow border. The region. The Balkans. The Albanians. The
ethnic Albanians. The conflict. The war? Could it happen here? What
if a private army bankrolled by the Haas family (forgive me,
darling, civic-minded Haases), decided to run all the folks who
quit wearing Levi's button-fly 501's out of San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   What if soldiers wearing rasping, hard jeans marched half the
people of San Francisco across the Golden Gate Bridge in their
Diesels, VC and Arizona jeans to camps dotting the Marin Headlands?
</P>
<P>
   It's cold up there overlooking the bridge, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Cold and wet. There is no shelter, no water, no sanitation.
You'd have to go to the bathroom in front of thousands of
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   If it happened here, Apache helicopters and guided missiles
couldn't be used because the concentrated cellular phone use would
jam all frequencies. And whom would everyone be calling? Their own
voice mail, of course. To check for messages because we're all so
damned important. The traffic would eventually crash the system,
forcing folks to actually walk around and look for loved ones. And
we'd all need our own personal covey of friends and family nearby,
because tomorrow _ off to Norway!
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic. I've heard Norway is lovely in the spring. The
goats, the Gruyere, the 100-proof glug. And it's one of those
countries you never get to. France. Italy. Greece. They get all the
vacation action. But in this special circumstance, you've won a
lottery ticket for Norway and that's OK. The women are pretty,
right? Socialized medicine, right? They probably have really,
really nice refugee camps. Scandinavian furniture, I bet.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that smelt is their main source of protein. Think of
the calcium. And you'll get used to only three hours of sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   So, that's the ticket. Look on the bright side. You didn't want
to finish that Y2K project at work anyway. And truth be told, even
if you had rent control, you were pretty sick of that dingy little
apartment, weren't you? And who really needs pets, anyway? Let the
Levi's people turn San Francisco into a pure, jack-booted,
lock-stepped 501 city. Who cares if they sponsor sporting events at
the Oakland Coliseum? People who wear Lee jeans deserve to be fed
to the lions and televised live on Fox TV.
</P>
<P>
   So, relax. it's just a conflict. When you get to Norway, they'll
let you eat your soft-boiled eggs from whichever end you choose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
