A8258 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALIENATED-YOUTH-HNS &LR;      05-07 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALIENATED-YOUTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOLS ARE HOTBEDS OF EXCLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM SHAW  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ How many alienated youth are out there? I
suspect that many are quietly simmering in the shadows of the
gruesome headlines from Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were alienated young men. But what
was their problem? Alienation is a social disease, not something
you ``catch'' like the flu. Alienation is something people do to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   For often rather shallow reasons, people selectively ignore
other people. They reject. They exclude. They alienate.
</P>
<P>
   Being denied or excluded from parental love is undoubtedly the
most destructive form of alienation. But as Hollingshead and later
James Coleman wrote in their celebrated studies of American youth,
adolescents in this culture wage an active campaign of exclusion
and status one-upmanship within their peer society.
</P>
<P>
   Bullying by one's peers, if it occurs regularly throughout one's
middle and high school years, can take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the bullying is a value system that establishes who
warrants exclusion and why.
</P>
<P>
   The murderous outcasts in Littleton targeted school ``jocks,''
who other students said had been targeting them for months, maybe
years. Having come of age in an American high school, I remember
the envy and isolation that accompanied my being less competitively
athletic than I thought I should have been.
</P>
<P>
   I got good grades, yet to really attract the good graces of
students and teachers, I felt I would have had to be first-string
on the football team, or at least visibly involved in some
competitive sport. (That I was on the tennis team didn't seem to
count.) Being in school was an alienating experience on a daily
basis, even though I cannot remember anyone ever overtly hassling
me. Since I had internalized the value system, I hassled myself.
</P>
<P>
   Jocks seemed to enjoy more of everything: more information,
privileges, attention from teachers, career advice, interpersonal
intimacy in the school. I didn't feel resentful so much as
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   A value system that promotes ranking results in the labeling of
``cool'' and ``uncool'' students. These values are more pervasive
than any single instance of bullying on school grounds. We don't
think of schools as places where kids come to believe that there is
something fundamentally ``uncool'' or deficient about them, but
schools often are.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't have to be the case, and in many school systems
overseas _ in Asia for example _ schools are places where students
are intentionally shielded from the status differences that pervade
society beyond school walls.
</P>
<P>
   School officials in Japan and China require school uniforms as
one means to equalize the disparate backgrounds of students.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways as well, students are actively prevented from
reveling in their differences, either as groups or as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot reinvent American schools, but we can learn from other
societies that recognize the insidious results of allowing the
social distinctions which pervade society to blossom in school
where adolescent identities are nascent and fragile. We should keep
such distinctions and hierarchies at bay.
</P>
<P>
   While grades may be a necessary evil, it is the more invisible
forms of exclusion and status ranking that are, precisely because
of their invisibility, much more dangerous and difficult to
regulate.
</P>
<P>
   To have to be reminded every day that one is at the bottom of
one or more of these informal hierarchies can easily become too
much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Shaw is the academic dean at Verde Valley School in Sedona,
Ariz.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
