<SLUG> BC-SECOND-AMENDMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE GUNPOWDER TO THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE SCOTT  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALNUT CREEK, Calif. _ It's time to repeal the Second Amendment.
As beautiful and majestic a blueprint as is the Bill of Rights in
the U.S. Constitution, 'tis not infallible, no more than the
oft-contradictory Bible or any other work of man.
</P>
<P>
   Even our great nation was based on a lie, built on the backs of
slaves. It took us another 75 years to end that institution, and
yet another 102 years to guarantee Americans of African ancestry
the right to vote without being beaten or lynched.
</P>
<P>
   We repealed the 18th Amendment, the prohibition on alcoholic
beverages, in 1933. All the ``noble experiment'' did was empower
and entrench organized crime in America.
</P>
<P>
   Are we so smitten by top 10 lists and the divinity of numbers,
that by virtue of being the Second Amendment, the ``right'' to bear
arms becomes sacrosanct? Even the noblest and brightest of
slave-owning land barons could not foretell a distant future of
armor-piercing 12 rounds-a-second at Guns-R-Us.
</P>
<P>
   So, if it took us 133 years (144 since the Declaration of
Independence) to give women the vote, 177 years to safeguard all
citizens' right to vote, perhaps 212 years is high time to deliver
us all from the ever-present threat of impromptu insta-death.
</P>
<P>
   Those suffering a compulsion to bang away at targets with deadly
ammunition could still do so at gun clubs _ as they do in the
United Kingdom, a grown-up country, where the lethal toys are
returned to locked storage at the club after playtime.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Charlton Heston, the president of the National Rifle
Association, might one-up his Moses role by not parting but
cleaning up the Red Sea and all the world's oceans, a timely adult
campaign. Why play great men, visionary leaders, when you might
become one, using your acting gift to encourage the populous to
sacrifice for the greater good?
</P>
<P>
   We did this, gave up our guns, once before. They were called
scrap metal drives during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom is an adult concept. Children are meant to graduate
beyond self, to comprehend the ``us'' of adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA is a small-minded, albeit focused (aimed) organization
hinged solely on an ancient amendment of an agrarian, tentative,
experimental society whose members might at any moment have had to
drop their plows and hoist single-shot muzzleloaders.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's insistence on legalized assault weapons underscores
its members' shallow, immature self-interest. Concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Cop-killing bullets. What's next _ bazookas, personal cannons?
</P>
<P>
   At what precise diameter does bullet become projectile? If
exploding bullets are validated, what size personal bomb might the
18th-century Second Amendment allow?
</P>
<P>
   OK. If you really are the National Rifle Association and stand
proudly for the Second Amendment of 1787, you may register, license
and keep your 6-foot-long, single-shot, flintlock muzzleloaders
with the explosive chemistry and metallurgy available during the
1780s. Nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   See how many banks are knocked over with one of these; how many
children and police officers are slaughtered; how many innocent
bystanders, shoppers and postal workers mowed down.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, gun nerd: Freedom. To keep and bear 1787 squirrel guns
not one whit better than those available when the Second Amendment
was written by slave-owning, female-vote-denying, indigenous
peoples-killing, land-grabbing patriarchs. Your hefty taxes,
license and registration fees will fund national trauma centers for
the rest of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-$ADV09-COX     05-07 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEGAL EXPERTS SAY SETTLEMENT A LIKELY END TO COCA-COLA BIAS SUIT
 &HT;    700&AMP;add. With COKE-EEOC. For release Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The advice may be hard to swallow, but some crisis
managers and marketing specialists suggest Coca-Cola should settle
an employment discrimination lawsuit filed against the company.
</P>
<P>
   One former and three current employees sued April 22 in federal
court in Atlanta, charging the company discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions, evaluations and terminations.
They also sought class-action status, which would raise the stakes
considerably for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most important thing is that a company take a look
at what we call its trust bank, or how likeable it is,'' said Eric
Dezenhall, a crisis manager and a founder of Nichols-Dezenhall
Communications Group in Washington. ``A company like Coca-Cola is
an extremely likeable company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The general rule of thumb (for companies) with a high trust
bank is to keep it out of the news and settle it promptly,''
Dezenhall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand not wanting to settle,'' said Pam Scholder
Ellen, an associate professor of management at Georgia State
University who specializes in marketing and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The down side of going through with the lawsuit is that the
connection between Coca-Cola and racism gets played over and
over,'' she added. ``In the long run, it may not be worth the
negative publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the easiest way is to settle,'' offered Asterios (CQ)
G. Kefalas, a management professor at the University of Georgia and
a Coca-Cola shareholder. The benefit of doing so, he said, is that
it gets ``all the bad publicity off your back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, argued Martin R. Stoller, a professor of
organizational behavior at Northwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why capitulate the moral high ground unless there is clear and
compelling evidence you don't deserve it?'' asked Stoller, who has
helped defend companies in employment-related litigation. ``A
vigorous defense of your innocence is my advice.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, it is ``rare'' for a company to mount a
proactive defense like the one put on by Johnson &AMP; Johnson during
the Tylenol poisoning scare of 1982. Instead, he said, ``The
company will leap on its own sword without being pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of good crisis management is to fight on the
territory between what you did and how deliberately you are alleged
to have done it,'' Stoller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Settlement is the safest course of action from a legal
standpoint,'' advised Ian I. Mitroff, a professor of business
policy at the University of Southern California and founder of the
school's Center for Crisis Management.
</P>
<P>
   If a company defends itself, it needs to be ``squeaky clean, or
you're going to make the crisis worse,'' he said. ``If (the
allegations are) not true, and you have the hard facts, I would
come out blasting.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the four plaintiffs and what they allege:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gregory Allen Clark, a security officer at Coca-Cola. The suit
charges ``he has been denied promotions on the basis of race, and
has been repeatedly denied the opportunity to even apply for
promotions, because of the common practice of filling supervisory
jobs without posting the positions.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Motisola Malikha Abdallah, an administrative assistant at the
company. The suit alleges she ``has experienced discrimination in
performance evaluations and in the terms and conditions of her
employment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Ingram, an information systems analyst at Coca-Cola. The
suit alleges she ``has been consistently paid below her grade level
and thousands of dollars less than comparable Caucasian
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kimberly Gray Orton, a former employee of Coca-Cola. The suit
charges she ``was significantly underpaid compared with comparable
Caucasian employees, was compensated at the low end of her pay
grade range, and supervised Caucasian employees who were paid more
than she was.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit also alleges a company-wide pattern of discrimination,
a charge Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester denied in a memo to
employees.
</P>
<P>
   He also issued a statement saying the lawsuit is without merit.
``Discrimination at the Coca-Cola Co. is not tolerated,'' Ivester
said. ``If discrimination is alleged, we investigate it. If we find
it, we act to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Companies that find themselves under attack have to deal with
two courts, Mitroff said. One is the actual legal system, and the
other is public opinion. ``Even if you are not guilty, in the court
of public opinion, the burden of proof is on you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What a company has to do, he said, is ask: ``What's going to do
the least damage?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, calculating the long-range impact of publicity goes
into formulating strategy, according to attorneys. And that
apparently is not lost on Cyrus Mehri, whose Washington-based law
firm filed the suit against Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a public dimension to (the suit), that's something
the company may have to deal with,'' Mehri said in a recent
interview. ``They are the most prominent company in Atlanta.
There's an African-American community there, and the
African-American community has a right to know what is going on in
this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, said Northwestern University's Stoller, the publicity
is not necessarily going to affect business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unlikely, in my mind, that a customer of Coca-Cola is
going to make a change based on some as-yet-unproven allegation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which has not filed a legal response to the suit,
says it would be premature to comment on the issues, including on a
debate whether it would be more advantageous to fight or settle.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, attorneys say, most employment discrimination suits
are not resolved by trial, particularly class action ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If class action gets certified, generally they work out some
means of trying to settle,'' said Max G. Brittain Jr., a Chicago
attorney who specializes in employment law.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
