<BODY>
 BEYOND ROLLERDOME: DANCING ON SKATES BRINGS PEOPLE TOGETHER  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By ROSS FINLEY  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A short, balding man in a beige shirt and black
trousers skates with a troupe of twenty-somethings, all of them
swaying to a dance beat in synchronized steps. A young woman in
spandex shorts glides around the dreadlocked DJ, hop-stepping, then
twisting around to skate backwards, and twisting around again.
</P>
<P>
   The sun is shining in Central Park, and the regular dance
skating crowd _ all smoothness and cool energy _ is out doing its
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an oasis in a concrete jungle,'' said Aristides Ruiz, a
regular who keeps his inline skates moving while taking a breather.
``To me, this is one of the best social scenes in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene is the ``Dead Road'' between 66th and 72nd streets in
the park, where dance skaters show up each weekend sporting jogbras
and tight shorts or tie-dyed shirts or preppy pants. And as they
skate, they groove to the musical gamut: techno, hip-hop, funk and
salsa. Motion and music are mixed in a polyglot of cultures. Young
and old, dark and light-skinned _ all mingle to the beat-and-glide
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Looking good takes a lot of practice, though. ``It's tough _ I
always feel like I'm embarrassing myself,'' said Charlie Koven, 22,
on his second time in the dance-skate zone.
</P>
<P>
   While Koven attempted to boogie off by himself to the throbbing,
techno beat, others skated partners or bobbed and whirled in
synchronized groups. The eye-catching tableau, as usual, attracted
more than 100 appreciative onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is great is that all kinds of people are here,'' said
Delphine Bedson, a visitor from Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   She and her friend ogled Jose Arzola, 48, a Puerto Rico native
who has been roller skating here for 22 years. Arzola says he also
appreciates how skating seems to attract people of all ages and
ethnicities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody leaves their baggage outside the park,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only place I've noticed where black and white, Jew
and Muslim, gay and straight, all kinds of backgrounds, you know,
just get together,'' said Steve Kay, a professional dance skating
instructor. ``Wheels and the music are a common denominator to
which these people can bond.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Williams, president of the Central Park Dance Skaters
Association, said the dance skating scene appeals not only to
teen-agers but to doctors, accountants, Wall Street brokers _ even
a few police officers. But the best thing about it is, Williams
said, ``It allows people with no cash to boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   The association was formed after a tumultuous period in the
early 1990s when rowdy DJs battled with police and park officials
over how loud they could play their music.
</P>
<P>
   Lezly Ziering, one of the founders of the skating association,
met his wife, Robbin, on skates in the park. They were married in
1997 at the Roxy rollerskating rink _ on skates, of course. ``The
whole park was there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kay also said that skating in Central Park changed his life. A
onetime Manhattan lawyer, Kay was practicing his moves one weekend
when an advertising crew spotted him and asked him to do a
commercial for Guess clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, Kay had become a full-time inline dance skating
teacher, and professional performer who has skated on Broadway and
in a soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did this for pure enjoyment, not thinking that this would be
any kind of career move,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   Another skater who has turned his expertise into a career is
Roger Green, who is well-known in Central Park for his odd choice
in skates. He wears an inline skate on one foot and a traditional
roller skate on the other. He toured with Michael Jackson in 1987
and once opened a show for Stevie Wonder. Green said skating has
become a kind of religion for him. ``It's not just about skating
for me. It's another level now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ross Finley is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
