<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-SCHVITZING &LR;      05-07 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SCHVITZING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHVITZING AT THE BATH HOUSE: A TRADITION CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By KEVIN ROTHSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The burly old Russian strapped himself with a bundle
of oak leaves and grunted in the eucalyptus-scented heat. Lesser
men can't take the pain for more than a few minutes, but this
Russian, who has more hair on his body than this head, motioned for
another ladle of the leaf-infused water to be thrown on the sauna
rocks. In seconds, brutally hot air covered him.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Bania, a Russian-style bath house in Brooklyn, where
$15 buys all the heat and steam you can stand. The oak-leaf
whipping costs extra, unless you do it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is one of the best gifts you can give to your
body,'' said Dimitri Lamdon, a native of the former Soviet republic
of Moldova, as he watched Russian music videos in the bath house
lounge. A few yards away, the burly Russian continued to bake,
silent save for a snort or two and an occasional heavy sigh.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian bath, or bania, is a centuries-old tradition
designed to warm the bones and relax the body. It cleans the pores
and, some say, sweats toxins out of the body. The tradition is
alive and well in New York City, thanks in part to a new wave of
immigrants from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Around the turn of the century, large numbers of Russians and
East Europeans immigrated to New York and brought the bania
tradition with them. The newcomers, many of them Jewish, called it
schvitzing, Yiddish for sweating.
</P>
<P>
   Besides offering a place to talk and argue, the baths served a
practical purpose. As in the old country, many couldn't afford an
apartment with a bath.
</P>
<P>
   The bath house in Brooklyn began, co-owner Craig Brasky said,
when Russian native Alona Kruglak approached him with the idea of
opening a bath for the newest wave of immigrants, who had come to
New York during the early 1990s. Brasky, who previously ran a
school bus company, agreed. The two opened Bania in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Russians are not the only people who like to schvitz. Alexia
Brue, 26, a Vermont native, visits a bath house on Manhattan's
Lower East Side about once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Brue, a marketing manager who lives in Manhattan, even tried a
platzka treatment, paying a professional to beat her body with the
leaf broom. Brue doesn't like the traditional drubbing of oak or
birch leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like you're a human being in a car wash,'' Brue said.
``It's definitely not as pleasant as getting a massage.''
</P>
<P>
   A Russian bath sometimes starts with a dip in a heated pool. The
idea is to warm the body in preparation for what's to come.
</P>
<P>
   The two saunas and one steam room in Bania have three tiers of
benches. Each puts the bather in a different heat zone. The higher
the seat, the hotter the temperature. The so-called Russian Room in
one of the saunas heats to a sizzling 200 degrees. The wood-lined
sauna rooms each seat about 30 people. But, the heat can be more
intense than newcomers are used to. Water on the body dries so fast
it can give a chilling sensation, much the way rubbing alcohol
cools the skin as it evaporates. After the chill, the sweating
starts. Men and women share the facility in Brooklyn and wear
bathing suits. Brue prefers to visit the sauna on the Lower East
Side on ``women-only'' days.
</P>
<P>
   A platzka treatment, as the oak- or birch-leaf scrubbing is
known, is considered a way to further open the pores. At Bania, a
10-minute scrubbing costs $20. Customers can also select a broom
from a barrel of soapy water and give themselves or a friend a
platzka.
</P>
<P>
   After a good bit of schvitzing, a dip in the 58-degree cold pool
brings relief. The quick move from hot to cold makes the skin
tingle and brings the blood to the surface, sometimes producing a
sunburned look.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, patrons can relax at one of the poolside tables with
a glass of juice or vodka. If all the sweating has induced hunger,
Bania's restaurant offers a full Russian menu.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bernstein was a bath house aficionado when he moved to
Manhattan from Michigan in 1977. He's been going to the baths ever
since, frequenting an East Village bath house until about two years
ago, when he switched to Bania.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein used to schvitz daily, if only for 15 minutes. He
remembers seeing John Belushi, the former ``Saturday Night Live''
comedian infamous for his hard living, at the East Village bath,
sweating out the weekend's excesses. Now Bernstein goes about once
a week.
</P>
<P>
   The long hours in the heat have given him a deep appreciation
for the bath's relaxing qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the deepest sense of the word, tension is an impurity,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein figures that a good schvitz also exposes him to
ancient air trapped inside the sauna rocks, which is released as
they crack in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a primal level, you're reconnecting with something that was
there millions and billions of years ago,'' he said. ``All you have
to do is sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Kevin Rothstein is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
