<HEADER>
A8321 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  GAYSSTRUGGLEFORPLACEINOR     05-07 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 GAYS STRUGGLE FOR PLACE IN ORTHODOX COMMUNITY  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By SARAH DOUGHERTY  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michelle, a 30-year-old office worker, has been
disowned by her parents. When she saw them a year ago, at her
grandparents' anniversary, it was the first time she had seen her
parents in seven years, even though they live in the same city. She
is forbidden from speaking to her youngest sibling, now 12. Her
older sister is one of her only connections to her family.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle is a lesbian. She is also a Hasidic Jew. Hasidism is
one of the most traditional branches of Orthodox Judaism _ and in
the eyes of Michelle's family and community, there is no room for
being both Hasidic and homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle, who asked that her full name not be used, has had few
people to turn to. She tried joining a more liberal synagogue, but
did not feel at home. And she felt rabbis were not properly
educated to deal with her problems.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has found some solace with a support group for Orthodox
women who are lesbian, bisexual or transgender. About 20 women
ranging from 19 to 50 years old meet monthly, and with the help of
a facilitator discuss family difficulties, coming out, and finding
a partner who shares their traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Such groups have been around for over a decade, in some cases,
in cities from Los Angeles to London to Tel Aviv, helping their
members _ both men and women _ reduce their sense of isolation and
reconcile their religious beliefs with their sexual orientation.
But now the message of such groups is beginning to find its way
into public dialogue. Some members of the Orthodox community have
come out in recent years, and struggles of Orthodox gays and
lesbians will be highlighted in the film ``Trembling Before G-d,''
by filmmaker Sandi DuBowski, due to be released next year.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemmas faced by those struggling with their sexual
orientation are compounded by the fact that the Orthodox life can
be all encompassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The religion really circumscribes your whole day from the time
you open your eyes in the morning to when you go to sleep,'' said
Shlomo Ashkinazy, facilitator for a men's group in New York City.
``There are prayer services, rituals to observe, certain foods you
can eat and dress you can wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Greenberg, an Orthodox rabbi who recently came out,
agrees. ``The Orthodox life is both oppressive, if you don't fit
well, and very sweet for those for whom its rhythms are natural,''
Greenberg said. ``The calendar, relationships, and expectations are
set out in advance and there's a dependability and meaningfulness
of life that is never questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, Greenberg was a rabbi at a synagogue, but would
not have been able to remain there if he had revealed his
homosexuality. He is now an educator and community developer at the
National Jewish Center for Learning and Leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family's reaction has been, 'It's hard, but we love you,'''
Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg has given interviews to newspapers in the United
States and Israel and strongly believes that change will happen
only when sufficient numbers of people come out to family and
rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they see that these people are their children, their
friends, their students and nephews and nieces leading decent
lives, things may change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions differ on whether Orthodox Judaism will ever be
completely accepting of homosexuality. Although there is a range of
communities within Orthodoxy itself, with some being more
traditional than others, other movements, like Reform and
Reconstructionist Judaism, are much more accepting.
</P>
<P>
   The Reconstructionist movement, for example, voted in 1984 to
accept openly gay and lesbian students to its seminary and to
ordain them. It urges rabbis and congregations to be as inclusive
as possible, but leaves decisions on performing same-sex marriage
ceremonies up to individual rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Richard Hirsch, executive director of the
Reconstructionist Rabbinical Association in Philadelphia, believes
that there will be liberalization in the Orthodox movement in the
future. ``There are lots of prohibitions Orthodoxy has gotten
around in the past,'' he said. He cited the prohibition on burying
suicide victims in Jewish cemeteries with a Jewish ceremony as an
example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the prohibition on male homosexual acts may have been
based on the assumption that homosexuality was a choice,'' Hirsch
said. ``That is a receding assumption.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Orthodox rabbis do not believe that fundamental change
will occur _ in particular for the prohibition on male
homosexuality, which appears in the Torah. (The rule against
lesbianism appears in rabbinical writings.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Torah is God's revealed word to man,'' said Rabbi Steven
Dworken, executive vice president of the Rabbinical Council of
America, which represents about 11,000 mainstream Orthodox rabbis.
``So any new scientific knowledge about the nature of sexuality
will not change the prohibition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we demonize the act and not the person,'' Dworken said.
``I don't know of any congregations that are not open to admitting
homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many gays and lesbians don't feel comfortable going to
their rabbis for support. Myriam K., the facilitator for the
support group that Michelle attends, said, ``The reaction of rabbis
varies. Often their public position and private responses varies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashkinazy agreed. ``Rabbis will often say, this is between us,''
he said. ``Not many want to go on the record'' _ which effectively
forces gays and lesbians to stay in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   But most Orthodox homosexuals look for approval closer to home.
``We always talk about the family issue in the group,'' Myriam
said. ``It's the issue that brings the most distress to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle is still trying to replace the family and community she
has lost. She focuses a lot of energy on developing a talent she
was never able to pursue in her family's home _ singing. It was
considered immodest for women to sing in front of men. She now
sings with two choral societies in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although Michelle claims that the pain of being cut off does not
hurt as much now, the look in her huge blue eyes seem to suggest
otherwise. ``Jews of all people should know what it's like to be
oppressed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Sarah Dougherty is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
