<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CANADIAN-STUDENTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN UNDER-EXPOSURE HITS U.S. COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By CHRIS NUTTALL-SMITH  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minot State University, a tiny school in the northwestern North
Dakota farm belt, has always looked north to fill its classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the school relied on students from Saskatchewan and
Manitoba to increase its enrollment. Canadians often made up 15
percent of the student body and gave a significant lift to the
school's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   But now the university of 3,150 is facing a population crisis.
Already facing a gradual decline in enrollment of American
students, Minot this past fall found only 281 Canadians, just 9
percent of its student body, enrolled at the school _ down from
602, or more than 15 percent, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That drop in students, and the decline in revenue they bring to
the school, has forced Minot to cut faculty positions and some
courses, said Nancy Hall, Minot's registrar and dean of
institutional planning. For example, the school has essentially
shuttered its political science department, declining to replace
its sole instructor after he left the school, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the bottom line is we brought in fewer tuition
dollars, so we had to reduce the budget,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit is the same one that has thinned Canadian enrollment
at colleges across the country: the Canadian dollar. At an average
of 65 cents to the U.S. dollar, the currency this year has been at
its weakest ever. As its value has fallen, paying U.S. tuition fees
and living expenses has grown more expensive for Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty and administrators around the country complain that the
decline in Canadian enrollment hits more than the bottom line. They
say it also affects the level of diversity in classes, and it
strips away some of the students many U.S. educators consider among
their best.
</P>
<P>
   Many schools are being forced to adapt. Some offer incentives,
such as lowered tuition rates to Canadians; others have stepped up
financial aid and recruiting. But for many colleges, locked into
tuition levels set by state boards, and unable to increase
scholarships, the options are few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless that exchange rate turns around,'' Hall said, ``we
could send four more recruiters up to Canada, and I don't think
we'd get more students.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's presence in U.S. colleges is still strong. Only five
other countries, all in Asia, send more students to the United
States. Canada sent 22,051 students across the border to study this
fall, according to the Institute of International Education, a
non-profit research and advocacy organization for international
education exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that number is 4 percent lower than in the fall of 1997. And
the dip could be steeper than the figures show, said Peggy
Blumenthal, the institute's vice president of student services. The
institute records only the total number of Canadians enrolled in
education programs, not the number of new students. The drop in new
enrollments, she said, is likely higher than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the colleges noted by the institute for their sizable
Canadian populations now report falling numbers. The University of
North Dakota in Grand Forks has 100 fewer Canadians than it had
four years ago, bringing its current total to just over 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not as good a deal as we used to be,'' said Barry
Stinson, the university's director of international programs.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers at Calvin College, a Christian school in Grand
Rapids, Mich., mirror those at North Dakota: In 1992, the college's
292 Canadians formed 8 percent of the student body. Today, there
are just 212 Canadians, constituting over 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This despite Calvin's long history of admitting Canadians, its
strong French department and its political science and history
courses tailored for Canadians. Tuition and board there total
nearly $18,000 per year, or nearly $28,000 Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   An education at the most expensive Canadian university,
including tuition and living expenses, costs Canadians about
$12,000 in Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Like many colleges, Calvin has also put in place some hefty
carrots to keep Canadians coming.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it has beefed up Canadian exchange grants _ worth
$2,000 a student _ to lessen the effect of the currency exchange,
and officials there say the grants will likely increase in value
next year. Calvin also supports more than two-thirds of its
Canadian students with financial aid; the average amount is $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne State University, near Detroit, has always relied on
Canadian students who come to the school, just a few minutes south
of Windsor, Ontario. Last June, the university lowered tuition fees
for Ontario residents to the same rate Michigan residents pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Windsor is so close that we should be providing
the same opportunity to them,'' said Tom Sees, Wayne State's
associate vice president of student affairs. More than 500
Canadians enrolled there this fall, up nearly 150 from the
preceding year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many colleges and universities do not depend so
strongly on Canadian enrollments as Minot State, and many more,
such as Wayne State, have managed to hold onto and even increase
their Canadian population in spite of the feeble Canadian dollar.
And some schools, such as hard-to-find chiropractic programs and
the Ivy League, are in such demand that affordability won't stop
students from coming.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Minot, the school's directors are in the midst of
considering whether to continue recruiting Canadians, or whether
their recruiting dollars would be better rewarded in the United
States. They say they might focus more on nearby states, such as
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, if that exchange rate turns around,'' said Nancy
Hall, the registrar, ``we would change our recruiting plan in a
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Chris Nuttall-Smith is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
