A8324 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-FLOWER-BUSINESS &LR;      05-07 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-FLOWER-BUSINESS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSES ARE RED, VIOLETS ARE BLUE _ AND THE MARKET, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By MANUELA BADAWY  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jason Edmonds, a flower seller, begins his day at
3:30 each morning. Mother's Day is coming on May 9, and he wants to
be ready.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, 29, works in a small room where the aroma of roses,
carnations and chrysanthemums guides buyers to one of the several
cut-flower wholesalers in midtown Manhattan, a group whose members
face cutthroat market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds tells his Mexican employees how to handle the flowers
newly arrived from Europe and South America. The five hours leading
up to 8:30 a.m. are crucial, as floral designers and retailers will
have come and gone by then, their purchase orders _ if any _
filled.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, wholesalers on the block of 28th Street
between Fifth and Seventh Avenues, where Edmonds operates, not only
compete with ``delis,'' or small groceries, but also with growers,
retailers, and other flower-related businesses. Time, location and
transportation are also factors that determine economic success or
failure.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers are being bypassed by chain supermarkets and small
Korean groceries, which buy as a group, directly from growers. The
market is ``decreasing in Manhattan because there's a non-literal
Korean mafia,'' said Edmonds, sales director of the New Concept
floral shop, referring to what he says is price-fixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all agreed to have the same prices,'' Edmonds said. ``If
you look at the volume that they sell, that was all business that
we were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture and the Society of American
Florists say they have not heard of such a claim. But ``we don't
monitor the industry that closely,'' said Doyle Johnson, an
agricultural economist at the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   The competition in New York City is fierce, Edmonds said,
because ``there are fewer delis in other cities.'' In New York, he
said, ``you can find two delis in one block open 24 hours a day.
How can you compete with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Koukladas, a Greek retail florist who owns Flowers by Valli
on the Upper West Side said he faced the same competition from
delis, even though ``here we have a refrigerator while they have
them out in the heat. Now even newspaper stands sell flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets are also competing with wholesalers buying the
stock in bulk directly from importers. ``Supermarkets are buying
bouquets straight from Miami,'' Edmonds said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is the biggest entry point for flowers from Latin America,
receiving 95 percent of all the flowers brought from Colombia and
Ecuador, according to the Colombian Flower Council. Colombia is the
biggest cut-flower exporter, providing 64 percent of all the
flowers bought in the United States, and receiving $500 million a
year in revenue, the Colombian Flower Council said.
</P>
<P>
   With the development of telecommunications, such as the
Internet, large supermarket chains and retailers are finding it
easier, faster and sometimes cheaper to buy cut flowers directly
from growers. That eliminates the middle man, which ``is called
'Disintermediation,' '' said Philip Nowers, managing director of
the Colombian Flower Council in Miami. With Web sites and
advertising, growers ``feel they need fewer people'' to sell their
flowers to consumers. Nowers said wholesalers also avoid importers,
approaching the growers directly.
</P>
<P>
   But for other wholesalers near the New Concept shop, the biggest
problem affecting sales is the lack of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stores are very small,'' said Rob Hountenbos, one of the
three owners of another wholesaler, Dutch Flower Line, also on 28th
Street. Retailers, customers and designers cannot easily come into
Manhattan to buy and carry away flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working in early-century buildings,'' Hountenbos said,
referring to the early 1900s. ``If you create a building where
people can go in and choose their flowers _ and with parking _ we
could grow far more.'' There is one parking lot between Fifth and
Seventh Avenues with a capacity for 45 cars, but there are about 40
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation also affects the market. Once Edmonds had to
deliver a flower shipment for a reception for President Bill
Clinton at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, but the flowers never arrived
from Holland because inspectors found bacteria in them. ``See,
Clinton has been affected by the flower business too,'' Edmonds
said.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerated trucks carrying flowers at 34 degrees Fahrenheit,
to keep them from blooming prematurely, arrive in Manhattan at
sunrise. Edmonds says he buys about 400 boxes of flowers a week,
which is about 80,000 to 100,000 bunches. But, as many as 100 boxes
might be thrown away if the trade hits a low ``like right now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This year has not been good for anyone who sells flowers because
of the timing of some holidays. The most important days for the
cut-flower market are Valentine's Day and Mother's Day. But if
Valentine's Day ``falls on a Sunday it is a tragedy,'' Edmonds
said. ``It's good for restaurants, bad for the flower industry.''
People prefer to dine on the weekends; if the holidays fall during
the week, then the fastest and easiest thing is to buy a bouquet of
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's Day fell on a Sunday this year, and the New Concept
shop received its shipments of flowers late. Anticipating good
sales, they imported 150,000 ``stems'' of flowers from Ecuador and
Colombia. But the flowers did not begin selling until the end of
the week because ``Ecuadorean pilots went on strike, so everything
came late,'' Edmonds said.
</P>
<P>
   Mother's Day always falls on a Sunday, but Edmonds plans to buy
``probably a million stems'' for the occasion. ``It's now or
never,'' he said, to make up for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be crazy,'' Edmonds said comparing the week with
that of Valentine's. ``Not everybody has a girlfriend but everybody
has a mother.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Manuela Badawy is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
