<HEADLINE>
TV REVIEW: PBS OFFERS NOT-SO-GREAT `EXPECTATIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The learned producers of the latest ``Great Expectations'' know
what was wrong with Charles Dickens and what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens was a sentimental slob. That's the problem. So ice his
story and then surgically excise the sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to a ``Masterpiece Theatre'' rendering of ``Great
Expectations'' that's hard as a diamond and likable as a rabid
squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Coolly intelligent and yet off-putting, the BBC production _
it's at least the fifth film version of the Dickens tale _ stars
Ioan Gruffudd as Pip, Justine Waddell (``Tess of the
D'Urbervilles'') as Estella and Charlotte Rampling as a
bleached-out Miss Havisham.
</P>
<P>
   Rampling is pale-eyed and dreary in the role. When a ``Great
Expectations'' won't give any juice to the dotty Miss Havisham, who
lives among the maggoty ruins of her unconsummated wedding feast,
you've got one frigid TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Gruffudd is the ticket. He came to ``Great Expectations''
straight from his star-making title role in ``Horatio Hornblower''
(televised on A&AMP;E cable last month), and the Welsh actor has every
reason for expectations.
</P>
<P>
   He's more loose-jointed as Pip than he was as Hornblower, and
here his innocence mixes with a nastily haughty streak. But
whatever the role's veneer, Gruffudd is a naturally appealing
actor. If only movie audiences can look at his name and learn to
say ``(set ital)Yo(end ital)-an (set ital)Griff(end ital)-ith,''
without thinking ``Elmer Fudd.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Marchant's script takes some liberties with Dickens' story,
especially in sealing up the conclusion. But in the main, a long
work has been smartly compressed into three hours _ 90 minutes each
night.
</P>
<P>
   Pip (played as a child by Gabriel Thomson) is a north country
orphan raised by his shrewish sister (Laila Morse), whose kindly
husband, Joe (Clive Russell), a blacksmith, takes Pip on as an
apprentice.
</P>
<P>
   Two events alter Pip's destiny. First is a brutish encounter in
a marsh with an escaped prisoner, Magwitch (Bernard Hill), whom Pip
helps. The second is a summons from the wealthy Miss Havisham to
become the playmate of her ward, Estella (Gemma Gregory plays the
young Estella).
</P>
<P>
   Years later, when a mysterious benefactor brings Pip to London
with the promise of a handsome property and a gentleman's station,
Pip assumes that Havisham is grooming him for marriage to Estella.
</P>
<P>
   But Dickens has surprises, which Marchant's script grudgingly
concedes, and Pip needs to learn that one's humanity isn't divvied
out on a class basis. Indeed, as one of Pip's tutors observes, ``No
varnish can hide the grain of the wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruffudd's Pip ingests his lesson and finds his Dickensian
reward without much violation, but the production around him is
chillingly austere.
</P>
<P>
   At first, ``Great Expectations'' plays almost like a hard-edged
psychological thriller. In the starkly photographed north country,
Pip is beaten down and abused by his sister, and terrorized by
Magwitch.
</P>
<P>
   Then it seems intent on proving the comment of the solicitor,
Jaggers (Ian McDiarmid), that ``there are two sorts in life, Pip _
beaters and cringers.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, when we see Pip screw up his tormented face and shout,
``Estella!'' you might sense a hint of Tennessee Williams. Either
that, or director Julian Jarrold was enjoying a bizarre little
joke.
</P>
<P>
   What the production never gets around to willingly is the full
Dickens. Yes, there's the blistering bleakness of the new
industrial age in England but scarcely any of Dickens'
counterbalancing poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose apparently is to modernize ``Great Expectations'';
the recent Americanized film with Gwyneth Paltrow was similarly
intended. It's a compliment to Dickens, in a way, implying that his
characters and their predicaments are timeless.
</P>
<P>
   But one reason Dickens is adored is that he is rooted in 19th
century England. In fact, he defined the time and place as much as
Queen Victoria. And in that setting, Dickens could point his
reportorial finger at greed and grime, then finally surrender to
love, charity and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Great Expectations'' seems to smell weakness in Dickens'
optimistic bow to humanity. It would be better with Charles in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
