<SLUG> BC-FORD-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAINTIFFS DROP CHARGE IN FORD FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISO _ Lawyers suing the Ford Motor Co. for allegedly
covering up a defective ignition part they say could cause
dangerous stalling in millions of cars dropped one count of fraud
from their case.
</P>
<P>
   But they proceeded with two other claims accusing Ford of
deceptive business practices and false advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The move was announced Thursday as lawyers on each side of the
case prepared for opening statements May 11 before Alameda Superior
Court Judge Michael E. Ballachey, in the largest-ever class-action
lawsuit to go to trial against an automaker.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that Ford withheld information from federal
regulators and the public about alleged defects in its Thick Film
Ignition module, which was mounted on the distributors of 22
million vehicles nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought on behalf of 3 million Californians who
own or owned 1983 to 1995 Ford vehicles. It seeks more than $3
billion in fines, and an order that Ford give back money to
consumers who had to pay for module problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has acknowledged the module was flawed, but denies it posed
a safety risk. The company said it fixed some cars under warranty,
others under a service campaign and improved the module in newer
models.
</P>
<P>
   In pretrial sparring, Ford on Thursday issued a press release
saying the lawyers for the plaintiffs ``have dropped charges of
fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fazio, one of the lawyers bringing the case, called the
public relations release ``blatantly misleading.'' He said the one
count was dropped for ``strategic reasons,'' but added that ``each
and every claim in this case is based on fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford also claimed the plaintiffs had admitted they ``cannot
prove a single accident or injury'' due to the module.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio called the statement ridiculous, adding, ``We know that
Ford had a (module) failure rate that was unacceptably high. We'll
stand or fall on the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The case pits the nation's second largest automaker against an
unusual team: the San Francisco law firm of Hancock, Rothert &AMP;
Bunshoft, which is best known for insurance coverage work; and
Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety, a
Washington, D.C., nonprofit organization started in the 1970s by
Ralph Nader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
