<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KILLER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV REVIEW: DEFTLY TOLD CRIME TALE IN NBC'S `UNICORN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Noah's Ark'' was such a smash-mouth Nielsen hit _ hey, 63
million sets of eyeballs, at one time or another _ that from now
on, we'll have to look clinically at sweeps-month spectaculars and
say, ``Well, it was good, but it was no `Noah's Ark.' ''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' is very good indeed.
And, thank goodness, it isn't ``Noah's Ark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' is a rare network triumph
for unvarnished storytelling. Confident it has the goods without
stooping to trickery, it's the deftest crime grabber in many a
sweeps month.
</P>
<P>
   Based on fact, the two-parter stars Kevin Anderson (``Nothing
Sacred''), Tom Skerritt and Naomi Watts and airs Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves the 1977 murder of Holly Maddux, a Bryn Mawr
graduate whose remains were found in a trunk at her former
boyfriend's apartment. He was Ira Einhorn, a well-known political
activist and New Age guru in Philadelphia. Also, a professed
pacifist with influential friends.
</P>
<P>
   Those are all the details you get from me, though the case is
well-known and continuing. It was in the headlines only three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatically, the key fact about ``The Hunt for the Unicorn
Killer'' is that it's produced by Dan Wigutow, whose credits
include the 1984 NBC blockbuster ``Fatal Vision.'' ``Fatal Vision''
was a thinking man's thriller, at least by TV standards. It
captured a chilling murder case by means of studiously paced
suspense, solid characterization and meticulous plotting, rather
than souped-up gimmickry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' is cut from the same fabric.
Once again, the viewer's shiver comes from the unfolding evidence
that a talented, respected man committed a horrific act in a
murderous rage.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's first installment unhurriedly details the unholy
relationship between Maddux (Watts) and the scruffily charismatic
Einhorn (Anderson). She's the moth to his flame, subordinating her
own personality and ambitions to his.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Ira cheats on her, humiliates her in front of their
friends and forces her to have an abortion she doesn't want.
</P>
<P>
   Holly's family, in far-off Texas, endures all this with grudging
forbearance. Her father (Skerritt) can barely conceal his own
worries.
</P>
<P>
   Holly vanishes at the close of the first installment. Obviously
she's dead, and we know who did it, but the case drags on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The case drags, not the production. The miniseries never flags
until the last few scenes on Monday, and by then any viewer can
toddle off to bed satisfied with two nights of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who fought to save ABC's ``Nothing Sacred'' last year
will be shocked to see Anderson _ sweet Father Ray, the
ever-compassionate Catholic priest _ as a heavy.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy he is; he's practically uranium, a man whose wits and
progressive social agenda conceal a seething, violent rage. He's a
man with an ego so huge that he'd sooner kill Holly than let her
leave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women don't leave me,'' he says dismissively to a private
detective hired by Holly's father. ``I leave them.''
</P>
<P>
   True, in a way. He leaves them in locked trunks off his bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   There's no guesswork in the miniseries, except for if, when and
how Ira will be brought to justice. That's enough.
</P>
<P>
   I do have quibbles. Three hours would have been a better length
than the more conventional four. There are too many shots of young
women oozing with doe-eyed admiration as they hear Ira lecture. I'm
not sure why Holly's mother, Elizabeth, is practically invisible.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the networks has approached perfect since ``Lonesome
Dove.'' These days, I'll settle for pretty damn good. With its
intelligence, restraint and sure-handed pacing, this one will do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
