   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, pictures and
graphics on the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Ledeall: Following the accord
between Russia and NATO on a plan to end the fighting in Kosovo and
the rest of Yugoslavia, a report on where things stand and what
happens next. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis: From the
Russians' point of view, it is NATO that is now on board with them,
thanks to shrewd Russian diplomacy. Viktor Chernomyrdin, the
special envoy, is to return to Belgrade to meet Slobodan Milosevic,
the Yugoslav president. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Velike Dobranje) _ In a Kosovo village that is
all Albanian, no one has left or been told to leave, but everyone
is terrified. They wonder if the worst of the storm has passed, or
are they merely in the quiet eye with more to come. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Belgrade) _ At least 11 civilians are dead and 30
wounded as NATO missiles are reported to have hit a hospital
complex and a market in the town of Nis. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ An interview with the Serb who
heads the interim executive council that runs Kosovo. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on developments,
diplomatic and otherwise, in Brussels, Belgrade and at the United
Nations; and the arrival at Fort Dix, N.J., of more Kosovo
refugees.
</P>
