   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-HESS (New York) _ Leon Hess, who took over his family's
bankrupt fuel-oil business during the Depression and built it into
one of the world's largest petroleum companies, but was perhaps
best known as the steadfast owner of the long-floundering New York
Jets football team, died Friday in New York. He was 85. By Gerald
Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy resumed its torrid pace of
job creation last month after an interruption in March, generating
234,000 jobs without putting pressure on companies to raise
employees' wages. The jobless rate crept up to 4.3 percent in April
from 4.2 percent in March. While the gain in new jobs was somewhat
larger than forecasts, hourly wages rose less than expected, easing
concern that interest rates are headed higher. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ECON (Frankfurt) _ German unemployment rose by 10,000 in
April, halting a three-month decline and reflecting a slowdown in
economic growth. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GOLD (London) _ Gold prices tumble after Britain says it
will sell more than half its $6.5 billion gold reserves and invest
the proceeds in foreign bonds. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LITTON-ACQUIRE (Los Angeles) _ Looking at Litton Industries,
which late Thursday made $1.8 billion offers to buy both Newport
News Shipbuilding and Avondale Industries. Amid a wave of recent
consolidation in the defense industry, Litton had been largely
sitting on the sidelines until yesterday. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:35, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 12 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was up 4 points, while the Nasdaq
composite was up 20 points. Stocks in Europe were modestly lower,
but Asian stocks fell sharply: Hong Kong 4.2 percent, the Nikkei in
Tokyo 2.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS-INVEST (London) _ Ever since Martin Taylor quit as
chief executive in a dispute over investment-banking strategy six
months ago, Barclays, Britain's No. 2 bank, has been trying
desperately to avoid the impression that it is drifting while other
European financial institutions forge ahead with energetic
restructuring. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   INSTINET-TRADEPOINT (Undated) _ The Instinet Corp. has formed a
consortium of major financial services firms to buy a majority
stake in Tradepoint Financial Networks PLC, an electronic stock
exchange based in London, for $22.5 million. By Diana Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-FLOWERS (Guaymaral, Colombia) _ Colombian flower
growers are angry at Dole Food over its purchase of farmland. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND-U.S. (Bangkok) _ Looking at the angry reaction in
Thailand over U.S. opposition to the candidacy of Supachai
Panitchpakdi, Thailand's deputy prime minister and commerce
minister, to head the World Trade Organization. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
