<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8368 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     05-07 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FONDA: WAS THAT `GREAT' OR `GRATING'?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara Walters, shame on you.
</P>
<P>
   To include Jane Fonda among the cast of notables in the April 30
special ``A Celebration: 100 Years of Great Women'' is an insult to
every American man and woman who ever donned a U.S. military
uniform, and an affront to the survivors of every Vietnam War
veteran whose name is etched in the black granite wall in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   All 58,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   And shame on you, ABC. Doesn't the ``great'' Ms. Walters have
editors who should have said: ``Hey, Barb, let's think about this a
minute. We know you have canned footage of an interview with Fonda,
but maybe you should dig a little deeper in the archives and come
up with someone who actually deserves the accolade.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly which definition of ``great'' did Walters and the
high-paid suits at ABC use when deciding to include Hanoi Jane
among the honorees in last week's 90-minute special? My dictionary
doesn't include committing treason as a qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   What sad, sad irony that PBS, at least in this part of the
country, was airing a segment of its moving series ``Battlefield:
Vietnam'' during an overlapping time slot. This exceptionally
well-done documentary, running every Friday night in the Fort
Worth-Dallas market until June 3, catalogues the military realities
of that ``conflict'' without including social slant or political
bias.
</P>
<P>
   ABC chose to celebrate the career of a woman who personifies all
the political ugliness of that chapter in American history _ and
just as this nation sits mired in another war-that's-not-a-war,
with pundits right and left drawing analogies to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Have the myopic egos at ABC totally forgotten history? Are they
so used to the revisionism seen through the animated eyes of parent
company Disney that they were oblivious to the fact that Fonda was,
and to many Americans still is, a traitor to her country?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming to a theater near you, Disney presents `Jane Err,' the
delightfully touching story of a misunderstood American lass who
travels halfway across the world in search of peace and finds true
love chanting the poetry of Ho Chi Minh.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone under 30 out in TV land might be excused from not knowing
much about Fonda beyond her marriage to media titan/ballclub owner
Ted Turner and her ``earn the burn'' exercise videos. But for
crying out loud, Walters and ABC surely remember.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was Walters who landed the 1988 ``20/20''
interview with the pseudo-repentant actress when she apologized to
veterans for her ``thoughtless and careless'' judgment in going to
North Vietnam to be used as a propaganda pawn for the communists.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtless and careless judgment? This woman went invited to
the enemy's side of a war zone to broadcast anti-American
propaganda over Radio Hanoi. She peered into the sights of an NVA
anti-aircraft artillery launcher and wistfully pined that she
wished she could target one of those blue-eyed U.S. imperialists
dropping bombs on the Viet Cong.
</P>
<P>
   That's a whole lot of thoughtless and careless.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda had the same right as every other American to protest what
was happening in Southeast Asia in 1972, but she crossed the line
from exercising freedom of speech to treason when she aided and
comforted the enemy during wartime. Photographs of Fonda sitting
around a firebase with communist troops singing camp songs are as
nauseating today as they were almost 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As for that ``apology'' 16 years after the fact, it had more to
do with quieting the daily protesters mobbing the set of the movie
she was shooting in New England than it did with any epiphany to
seek forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the ``great'' part come in? Her Best Actress Oscar in
1971 for playing a hooker in ``Klute'' (apparently good experience
for prostituting herself for the communists)? That she's in darn
good shape for a woman her age? That she married ``up''? Or was it
that recent crack in front of the United Nations about northern
Georgia being a Third World country when it comes to how its
children are treated?
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Ball and Golda Meir are lucky not to be around to see
their names linked with such an outrage. Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Oprah Winfrey probably didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Fonda will be ``celebrated,'' all right _ as a traitor who
to this day has escaped punishment. Let's not forget that little
piece of reality as Disney tries to make her a female icon for the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1536EDT &QL; 
