<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8369 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     05-07 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL GUMBEL'S RETURN TO MORNING KEEP HIM AWAKE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bryant Gumbel is said to be heading back to morning television
as joyfully as a kid let loose in toyland, but I've heard more
convincing stories emanating from jail cells. Of late, CBS has been
paying its prize defection from NBC so much for so little that it
was a certainty he'd either help revamp the dead-and-buried morning
show or start mopping floors and emptying trash bins.
</P>
<P>
   The question now isn't whether Gumbel will successfully
resuscitate the lifeless, third-place-out-of-only-three program
that will undoubtedly drop its name of ``This Morning,'' but
whether he'll be bored stiff trying.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel, who starts Nov. 1, has never struck me as a morning
person, and this observation has nothing to do with him having to
rise at 3 a.m. and slip on a tie. It's about having to work in a
setting that didn't, and won't now, use his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel's perceived stuffy, snooty demeanor is twofold, one part
being that for a large chunk of his 15-year reign as co-host at
``Today,'' he figured life had to be far more challenging than what
was before him. I'll address the other later.
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to those who make their living in the
infotainment biz, the job calls for someone willing to endure
fluffy celebrity chats, ``People-''type human-interest stories and
those dreadful cooking segments.
</P>
<P>
   There's the occasional early morning wrap-up of breaking
stories, such as the recent Colorado shootings, but it's like
watching a pitcher take the plate with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Gumbel report on forged golf clubs on the acerbic HBO
magazine series ``Real Sports With Bryant Gumbel'' the other night,
I was reminded of his deft, no-frills interviewing skills, as well
as his poise and exquisite preparation. It also reminded me that
Gumbel, long known as a perfectionist, has never felt comfortable
being in the ``comforting'' business, which is what those breakfast
shows are all about.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the Ken-and-Barbie context of on-air talent, he is
more apt to come across as rather intimidating, and certainly not
warm and fuzzy, either to the subjects paraded before him or to the
viewers watching. He certainly never seemed all that interested in
the hordes of sign-wavers freezing their petunias off on 49th
Street and Rockefeller Plaza, even though I truly believe that it
was that darn window that put ``Today'' over the ratings top.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose Gumbel believes that, too, because he reportedly
signed on after being promised a move to a studio with a ``window
to the world,'' as NBC calls it, at Trump International Plaza in
the heart of New York City's foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Window or no, Gumbel might still feel a sense of slumming. Just
watch Gumbel's expression when he's facing some celeb promoting
whatever and he's trying his best to look intrigued. You figure he
must be compromising every bit of his journalistic integrity.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the thought of Gumbel returning to a.m. fluff TV is
unnerving, if only to wonder if he's going there with his heart
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, his choices were limited. CBS lured him from NBC in
January 1997 by tossing a newsmagazine with his name in the title
and millions on his doorstep. ``Public Eye With Bryant Gumbel,'' a
high-minded hour refusing to stoop to the gutter level of
manipulative fear TV supplied by the likes of ``Dateline,'' won a
pair of Peabody Awards, an Overseas Press Club Award, and an
American Women in Radio and Television Award, but few repeat
viewers. CBS axed it at midseason last year.
</P>
<P>
   You have to respect a man who vowed to take the high road
despite the price. Now conjuring up morning ratings magic looms as
yet another hurdle. Not that he hasn't cleared others before.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel was a print journalist before turning to television in
1972, and he's had to battle viewer and industry misperceptions
ever since. One was that a print sports reporter couldn't do
television, another that a TV sports journalist couldn't switch to
news, yet another that an African-American shouldn't have the
audacity to reek of confidence (read: ego and conceit).
</P>
<P>
   That's the second theory for Gumbel's perceived cockiness. Blame
my cultural bias if you wish. But black men who wear their
intellect on the outside are, more so than their white
counterparts, viewed as blowhards full of themselves. We can start
with Paul Robeson and work our way up.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons won't matter when ratings come out and the CBS sales
team wants to boost the price of a 30-second commercial, and can't.
When just as many viewers detest you as love you, there's a reason
for concern.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that Gumbel has placed himself into the position
of savior, shoving aside current hosts Mark McEwen and Jane Robelot
(the plan is for them to stay until November), but he'll have to do
it against former co-host Katie Couric and golfing buddy Matt
Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing the ratings hill will be tough. There are 6.1 million
viewers who watch ``Today,'' 2 million more than ABC's ``Good
Morning America'' and 3 million more than the program CBS will
literally start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Next up will be the selection of a co-host, which I think will
be a difficult task, seeing that conventional wisdom would lean
toward perky cuteness over substance, something that would only
irritate its star.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain, though, is that despite any disinclinations from
CBS' new a.m. star, this is a win-win for us early morning viewers.
The moment Gumbel arrives, the wake-up television wars will be
watchable again.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
