<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     05-07 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNICORN' IS SINGULARLY AND SADLY TRUE TO LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those still disgusted when seeing O.J. Simpson putt-putting
around golf courses, attending movie premieres and, well,
breathing, what's your take on Ira Einhorn? The mummified body of
Tyler native Holly Maddux was found stuffed into a trunk tucked in
the corner of Einhorn's back porch, reeking from 18 months of
decomposition. She'd been beaten by one or two heavy objects; her
skull was caved in.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Einhorn and charged him with murder. That was 20
years ago. Where is Einhorn now? Last report had him in rural
France, where he's been living quite well, and quite free.
</P>
<P>
   The two-night, four-hour ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' (8
p.m. CDT, NBC) arrives Sunday and Monday, telling the absorbing
story of a sad affair that doesn't seem to have an end.
</P>
<P>
   This well-crafted NBC movie dramatizes the events that led to
Einhorn's dash out of the country and the initial legal and illegal
maneuvers that allowed him to escape capture. How he met Holly. How
he seduced, manipulated and systematically abused her. How she
became so drastically dependent on him that she sought therapy to
break the bond. How Einhorn became a legendary figure in
Philadelphia's political, social and intellectual circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' is based on a book by Steven
Levy, who had full cooperation from the Maddux family. It's upfront
about Einhorn's guilt. If anything, it's the movie's shedding of
Einhorn's layers that makes it fascinating to watch, particularly
as he dupes nearly everyone and constantly slithers just out of the
reach of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn was initially freed on bail when influential friends and
associates, believing his claims of government conspiracy, provided
him a top-notch attorney and convinced the presiding judge that he
wouldn't flee. But with a case building against him, he did.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a Philadelphia jury convicted the fugitive Einhorn of
first-degree murder. But even after his arrest in France, the
French government has refused to extradite him, claiming that being
sentenced to life in prison, without being able to defend oneself,
is a violation of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn, now 58, could very well elude U.S. prosecutors
altogether, particularly if ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' is
on target with its portrayal of the hippie guru as a kind of
seductive superman.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Anderson, last seen as the liberal priest on ``Nothing
Sacred,'' portrays Einhorn as a blend of hippie, intellectual,
creepy psychopath, con man and babe magnet. He's disarmingly
charming. Refusing to cut his shoulder-length hair and long,
scraggly beard even as the '60s ended, Einhorn was eccentric enough
to get noticed, smart enough to gain the respect of intellectuals,
politicians and rich business types, and sexually confident enough
to lure women into his bed almost at will.
</P>
<P>
   He adopted the Unicorn nickname in his writings for an
underground newspaper, even though by the 1970s he'd shifted
allegiance from peace and love to ``the powers of the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Persuasion remained his forte, seduction his calling card. He
met Holly, played here by Naomi Watts, at a Philadelphia restaurant
in October 1972. A smart woman with high ideals and many dreams,
she was attending Bryn Mawr, from which Einhorn had graduated with
an English degree. Two weeks later, they were living together.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn was the textbook abuser, one who chipped away at Holly's
self-esteem, deepening her dependence. Most everyone else loved
Einhorn. During his first prosecution, many respected
Philadelphians, from clergymen to a future U.S. senator, rallied to
his defense, admitting Einhorn's eccentricities but hardly deeming
him capable of murder.
</P>
<P>
   One scene shows him being summoned to end a war demonstration
that was about to turn violent. Einhorn walked in, took the
bullhorn, and asked the demonstrators to chill. They all sat down,
and started to sing before disbanding.
</P>
<P>
   Holly watched this and was filled with admiration. But Holly's
love _ or better yet, obsession _ with Einhorn merely showed the
hold he had on people in general, women in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson succeeds in portraying the character's insidious
nature, saddling him with the same creepy charisma that gave serial
killers such as Ted Bundy a trustworthy persona. Holly's sister,
Buffy Hall, who lives in Everman, calls it ``a hypnotic kind of
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, even after he became psychologically abusive,
Holly wouldn't leave him for good. According to ``Unicorn Killer,''
Holly was picking up her things from the couple's shared apartment
when Einhorn decided that if he couldn't have her, no one would.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by William A. Graham (''Sleeping With the Devil'') and
written by Bruce Graham (''Anastasia''), ``Unicorn Killer'' has a
re-created scene showing Einhorn picking up an object and striking
Holly with unmitigated force.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``Unicorn Killer'' avoids the usual TV-movie tricks
of juggling the chronology of various events and changing names of
minor characters. Rather, it stays close to published accounts,
Hall says. When we talked by phone, she'd held off watching the
second part of the miniseries, having watched the first two hours
late at night so her children wouldn't see it.
</P>
<P>
   She does, however, call the characterization of her father,
(played by Tom Skerritt), who later killed himself with a shotgun
blast to the head, a composite; he was never quite the tireless
crusader the movie makes him out to be.
</P>
<P>
   But other than that, Hall calls what she'd seen ``unpleasantly
accurate,'' particularly Anderson's portrayal of Einhorn: ``I can
assure you that I'll never like watching him (Anderson) in anything
ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
