<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-WASH-2TAKE     05-07 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-WASH-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT A CARWASH CONVENTION, SOFT SOAP MEETS THE HARD SELL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., N.Y., Colo., Utah, Nev.)   (af)  
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ A hypnotic fugue has fallen over the crowd
watching the Mac Neil RW-102s. The powerful water sprayers gyrate
frantically inside a stainless-steel cuff. Nearby, attached to an
overhead arch like you might see at a carwash, the nozzles stop and
turn, flip and churn, like choreographed stage lights at a Broadway
musical. People wobble their heads unconsciously as they watch the
water cannons dance.
</P>
<P>
   No running water has been supplied to the floor of the 1999
International Carwash Association's convention at the Opryland
Hotel here, but there is plenty of soft soap.
</P>
<P>
   Tearing his gaze from the Mac Neil device, Andy Malecha, a
representative of the Broadway Equipment Co. in Minneapolis, said:
``These things don't work any better than some guy with a hose. But
let's face it, car washing is subtle. We have to use a little
showmanship so people feel like they are getting their money's
worth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Subtle'' was definitely not on the list of adjectives
describing the convention floor here late last month, crowded with
more than 300 exhibitors hawking everything from hand-cranked coin
sorters to barn-size bus-washing robots.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a chronic shortage of labor in the $3 billion-a-year
carwash business, the industry relies heavily on automation. Dozens
of automatic carwash devices _ those familiar, antenna-eating
machines with the spinningbrushes _ are deployed on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Some are simple, bare-metal machines moving with the clumsy
kinetics of the elves in Saks's Christmas window displays, their
felt curtain ``mitters'' sloshing to and fro. Others look like
escaped set pieces from ``Starlight Express'': huge chrome and
glass naves with blinking neon signs and scrolling LED readouts
above the bill changers that take customers' money.
</P>
<P>
   Some machines are specialized, glumly slaving away at their
appointed tasks: dressing tires, for instance. Others roam from
bumper to bumper, their thick drum brushes whirling like Champions
on Ice.
</P>
<P>
   Econocraft Worldwide Manufacturing Inc. of the Bronx has brought
its ``Pizazz'' floor model, a 100-foot-long, $135,000 apparatus
whose mirrored chrome and candy-colored lights seem inspired by
somebody's favorite pachinko game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to spice it up, make it glitzy and glamorous,''
said Tim Hiller, the company's well-dressed representative. ``The
customer deserves it. He's paying $12 to $14 for a carwash. He
wants to see more than a little soap and water.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not charge less and offer a simpler machine? He acts as if
he has seen a gazelle run down the aisle. ``Why would we want to do
that?'' he asked. ``A wise old man told me never to leave any money
on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   A good carwash machine offers evidence of things unseen. Many of
the contraptions use flashing neon signs to indicate, for instance,
when the liquid called ``rust inhibitor'' _ its specific
ingredients are carefully guarded _ is applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, who would know what it was?'' asked Steve Chase of
Aurora, Colo., an inventor whose tri-color washing and waxing
agents are staples at many automated washes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Turtle Wax booth, Chase watches as a Saab 9-3 is
enveloped in rainbow ribbons of goopy spray. The stuff melts
together like the walls in a particularly lurid passage by William
Burroughs. In a touch of synesthesia, the area around the booth is
suffused with an intense berry fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice,'' he said, ``and it will keep customers in the
carwash longer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea. Carwashes are expensive operations _ a
top-of-the-line machine can cost $165,000; the average investment
per bay in a conveyor carwash is about $1 million. Also, the
industry's effluent is federally regulated, requiring either a
separate sewer system for new carwashes, or water reclamation
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To increase revenue, the industry has made an art form of
``extra services,'' code for any frill that adds to the cost of a
visit. These can range from the reasonable (Armor-All tire
treatment makes the rubber look nice and shiny) to the ridiculous
(a lemon-scented sealer wax that would be worthwhile only if
passengers rode outside your car).
</P>
<P>
   In truth, consumers could probably skip the premium-priced car
vacuum, its festively colored ``fragrance enhancers'' bubbling up
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of money is what falls under the rubric of
``profit centers.'' These can include everything from quick oil
changes and gasoline sales to car detailing and gift shops. Dozens
of vendors at the convention represent these peripheral retail
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more convenience we can give to the customer, the better
he likes it,'' said Guy W. Goddard, of Park City, Utah, the
president of the International Carwash Association. ``What we are
looking at is a transition from `carwash' to `car care.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, next year's convention in Las Vegas will be grandly
called the Car Care World Expo 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Goddard, who with his cowboy boots and long hair looks right at
home in Opryland, says the business will inevitably reach into
other services that busy people crave: dry cleaning, gourmet food
and coffee, insurance services, shoe repair, even massage
therapists _ ``duly licensed and registered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As promising as the future looks _ the industry is growing 7
percent annually _ the business does have its problems: the rift
between ``friction'' and ``touch-free'' washes, for instance.
Friction washes put brushes or pads on cars. These can be worrisome
because the new clear-coat compounds applied over new cars' paint
can be easily marred by brushes, leaving telltale whorls.
</P>
<P>
   Touch-free carwashes use high-pressure sprays, but they are less
effective. To be competitive, some touch-free operators use
pre-soak solutions of hydrofluoric acid, a highly toxic material,
to loosen clay, brake dust and asphaltic hydrocarbons, otherwise
known as road tar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the industry to take the moral high ground,'' Goddard
said. ``We hope our membership avoids the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   As in all things, the moral high ground is slippery. Goddard
said the industry's single greatest problem was that more than half
of all drivers still washed their own cars. These driveway washers
_ perhaps a million of them on a summer weekend day, by some
estimates _ send their waste water into the gutter, where it makes
its way into lakes and rivers. ``They can do with their waste water
what we can't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the association's opposition to driveway washing _ which is
both green and self-serving _ means that it opposes charity washes
for churches and schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been developing a voucher system that charities can
sell, rather than wash cars in parking lots,'' Goddard said.
</P>
<P>
   Such controversies notwithstanding, the entrepreneurs of the
carwash industry seem an untroubled and gregarious lot. As they
trundled away from Nashville, they seemed to want nothing more than
to love the next big, noisy, soap-spitting machine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
