u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING5/7-HNS &LR;      05-07 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING5/7-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANT'S SCHEDULE LEAVES EPILEPTIC WORKER OUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Undated) Robert Stevenson is an epileptic and is perfectly capable
of working, but he was fired from his job last year after working
27 years at the Simpson Pasadena Paper Co. in the Houston suburb of
Pasadena
</P>
<P>
   Like many industrial employers, Simpson went to a 12-hour
rotating shift several years ago, which required employees to work
some days and some nights. But Stevenson said the new schedule
triggered more seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Many epileptics need to take a regime of medicine every day at
the same time and get an adequate amount of sleep, especially when
they get older like Stevenson, who's 46. It's important to keep an
epileptic's blood levels even, so drug levels don't become toxic.
</P>
<P>
   So Stevenson went to his employers, seeking what he considered a
fairly simple accommodation: working the same straight eight-hour
shift five days a week without a lot of stress. It didn't matter if
it were a straight night shift or straight days.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevenson said the company fired him after saying it
couldn't give him what he wanted, even though there were several
hundred people working at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Simpson sold its plant to Belgravia Investments,
which changed the company's name to the Pasadena Paper Co.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pawlicki, spokesman for Stevenson's former employer, the
Simpson Paper Co. in Sacramento, Calif., said the company won't
comment on personnel matters.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Blum, a neurologist in Pasadena who has been treating
Stevenson, said he talked to Simpson officials several times about
getting Stevenson back to work, but they wouldn't budge. Other
doctors sent similar pleas to Simpson officials.
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, Stevenson's doctor is none too pleased with
his patient's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Stevenson got completely screwed by the Simpson Paper
Co.,'' Blum said.
</P>
<P>
   Lex Frieden, co-director of the Americans with Disabilities Act
Technical Assistance Center at The Institute for Rehabilitation and
Research in Houston, said he isn't surprised to hear about
Stevenson's case. He has encountered many employers who don't want
to be flexible about work schedules _ even though it doesn't cost
them anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like having to build an elevator for three floors,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frieden said he has seen many companies spend more money
fighting a request for an accommodation than providing one.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, H. Joan Ehrlich, district director of the U.S. Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission in Houston, said complaints about
failure to accommodate a disability are the most frequent type of
charges her office receives as enforcer of the Americans with
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson said he has a charge pending before the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never encountered an employer who was less resistant to
suggestions,'' Blum said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company seemed to go out of its way to put
Stevenson in a stressful situation that could easily trigger more
seizures, Blum said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after he lost his 18-year-old son in a train
accident, Stevenson was assigned by Simpson officials to work in
the company's train yard, looking for trash in the rail cars
carrying wood chips. Stevenson said it was excruciating to walk up
and down the tracks _ he'd often go around the corner and cry _ and
said that the emotion he felt brought on several seizures.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you define stress, putting an employee to work on
the rail cars after he lost his son to a train accident fits the
definition, Blum said. It's a matter of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as he waits for his EEOC complaint to work its way
through the system, Stevenson carries a pillbox in his shirt pocket
that beeps when it's time for his next dose of medicine. He loves
to recall headier times when his nickname at the quality control
lab was ``Eagle Eye Beater Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   His disability has run out, he is ineligible for unemployment
checks and he no longer has health insurance. He is too healthy for
Social Security, so he is getting by on his savings. His medicine
costs him $375 a month, but luckily he got enough for five months
before his insurance was cut off.
</P>
<P>
   He can't drive and often walks five miles to his doctor's office
and another five miles back to save the $14 cab fare.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, who lives in Pasadena, has applied for jobs as a
Postal Service worker and as a custodian for the city of Pasadena.
But so far the high school graduate hasn't received any offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's driving me crazy,'' said Stevenson, his voice cracking.
He's an able-bodied man who just wants a chance to work.
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone (713) 220-2000 and dial in code
1002. Send e-mail to lm.sixel(a)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
