<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-STOCK-OPTIONS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEE STOCK PLANS PAY OFF IN PERFORMANCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Ark.)   (af)  
 By DYLAN LOEB McCLAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Setting up an employee stock ownership plan improves companies'
financial performance, and not just staff morale, according to a
new study of the plans by Hewitt Associates, a consulting firm
based in Lincolnshire, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined the performance of all 382 publicly traded
companies that adopted such plans, known as ESOPs, from 1971
through 1995. The average company in the study improved the annual
return on its stock by 6.9 percentage points and the return on
assets by 2.7 percentage points after establishing its plan.
</P>
<P>
   An ESOP acquires or is granted significant holdings of company
stock on employees' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggested one possible reason why starting an ESOP
might improve performance: Employees are typically told more than
they were before about how the company is doing, better equipping
them to make decisions that help the company they now partly own.
</P>
<P>
   Eight out of 10 companies said they share information with
workers for this reason, and two-thirds of the total said they saw
direct benefits.
</P>
<P>
   At Baldor Electric, a motor manufacturer in Fort Smith, Ark., a
plan that grew in 1996 to cover almost all employees has made
workers feel closer to the goals and future of the company,
according to Lloyd Davis, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big issues in the workplace is not `how much money
I make,''' Davis said. ``It's an issue of security, of belonging.''
He said that the benefits for morale show up in Baldor's frequent
high standing in ``best companies to work for'' surveys and that
operating margins have been improving gradually since the plan was
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Rosen, director of the National Center for Employee
Ownership, said the findings of the Hewitt study echoed those of
smaller, earlier studies. The average company in the Hewitt study
had 17,000 employees and annual sales of $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best-known ESOPs have been started to help rescue
faltering companies, with employees trading wage and work-rule
concessions for equity stakes. But Rosen said such cases were the
exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESOPs are almost never a substitute for compensation,'' he
said, noting that wages at companies with the plans are typically 5
percent to 12 percent higher than industry averages.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Rosen said publicly traded companies were turning
away from ESOPs in favor of granting stock options, because of more
favorable accounting treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-WOMEN-BIAS-$ADV09     05-07 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WOMEN-BIAS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT DOING WHAT THE ROMANS DO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.Y., Conn., Ore., Calif., Canada)   (af)  
 By CAROL STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Kay Ainsley of Detroit traveled to Saudi Arabia several
years ago to sell the rights to open Domino's Pizza shops there,
she felt the full force of being a woman in a man's land.
</P>
<P>
   Her business visa was rejected twice, she said, before the
intervention of the Saudi businessman with whom she planned to
negotiate. Then she arrived at a low-rise office building in Jidda
to find that employees near the meeting room had been cleared away
because of her presence.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a business suit, she was asked to cover herself with
an abaya, or traditional long black robe, for lunch at the
businessman's home. In scouting the competition, Ms. Ainsley, then
Domino's director of international development, found that a local
sandwich shop didn't allow women to enter, so she had to peer into
a window and have male colleagues fetch take-out.
</P>
<P>
   In a global economy, United States business people are learning
how to grin and bear many overseas cultural challenges. And women
often face added obstacles, especially where business is still
almost entirely conducted by men.
</P>
<P>
   Recent research suggests that only about one of every 8 or 10
managers assigned abroad by American corporations are women. But as
more companies and more female executives see other women
succeeding overseas, and recognize that such jobs can speed
advancement, more women are likely to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses in the U.S. have wrestled with their desire,
honestly, to assign women who are otherwise qualified to work
overseas,'' said Bill Carmell of Winston &AMP; Strawn in New York, a
labor lawyer for management. ``Part of the problem, though, for
them has been the acceptance of that in some countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Orlov, a work-force consultant in New York specializing
in sexual harassment, said some employers were quietly allowing
potential cultural clashes to influence their choices for foreign
jobs. ``We all know it's illegal to allow your customer preference
for gender or race to determine who will be assigned to that
business,'' she said of United States companies. ``However, people
still consider, `Can we send a person into an environment where the
customer might not be responsive?'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Saudi Arabia is still regarded as among the toughest
places for an American woman to conduct business, Ms. Ainsley, now
a senior consultant with Michael H. Seid &AMP; Associates of West
Hartford, Conn., said she would go back. But even she would advise
clients otherwise. All things being equal, she said, ``I'd probably
assign a project to a male _ it would be easier for them to get
business done.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge is to be sensitive to a culture, but not
mimic it, said Nancy Adler, a professor of international management
at McGill University in Montreal. ```When in Rome do as the Romans'
do is not particularly good advice, and it's horrible advice for
women in many cultures,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When abroad, American businesswomen can circumvent some local
customs by making it clear they are different from local women. A
Japanese-American in Japan, for example, should clarify up front
that she was born, say, in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Women often must strive to be taken seriously. Sue Roll of
Gaston, Ore., a human resources manager at the Intel Corp., was
ignored for 45 minutes while meeting with an employee training
agency in Shanghai. Only after her male peers repeatedly turned to
her and said, ``Sue, you're in charge,'' was her authority
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Women coach female colleagues to signal their importance by
displaying knowledge and having top executives send introductory
letters, make calls and accompany them to meet clients. For small
companies, a United States consulate or industry group can open
doors. Women are also sometimes advised to travel business class
and stay in good hotels as symbols of their status.
</P>
<P>
   As for building relationships, ``the biggest mistake made by
women is assuming they have to act identically to males,'' Ms.
Adler said. Referring to foreign habits of heavy after-hours
drinking, she said, ``We have a quiet joke that it's possible to be
highly successful as a woman in Asia without losing your liver.''
</P>
<P>
   Covering Asia from Hong Kong until recently as a
customer-service executive for Lucent Technologies, Edith Parham
Melton was included in dinners in Japan. But then male colleagues,
Japanese and American, would drop her off at her hotel and go
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Developing rapport through other social opportunities, like
lunches or dinners, can work better than protesting such exclusion.
``It didn't impede the business relationship, but it took longer,''
Ms. Melton said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, women have also found that even a casual comment can
be misinterpreted. At a dinner in Japan, a male client told Jane
Echols, who has a public relations firm in San Francisco, that her
children must miss her when she travels. When she replied that her
husband stayed home with them, ``he was dumbfounded,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His image of me became someone who could overpower men,'' Ms.
Echols said. ``It distracted him.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are often basic strategies for coping with, while
still respecting, foreign customs. In Pakistan, for example, it is
possible to evade the taboo against meeting with a man behind
closed doors by keeping the door open or meeting as a group.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Ainsley completed her Saudi deal, she kept silent
when she was banned from the contract signing at a palace in
Riyadh, where her boss, a man, signed instead. ``I wasn't there to
revolutionize their culture,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1605EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8401 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     05-07 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
  (rm)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, May 8, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis: From the
Russians' point of view, it is NATO that is now on board with them,
thanks to shrewd Russian diplomacy. Viktor Chernomyrdin, the
special envoy, is to return to Belgrade to meet Slobodan Milosevic,
the Yugoslav president. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ An interview with the Serb who
heads the interim executive council that runs Kosovo. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ROMANIA (Bucharest) _ Pope John Paul II arrives on the
first visit by Pope to an Eastern Orthodox Country in 1,000 years.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JENNY-JONES-SUIT (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Jenny Jones, a TV talk show
host, was found to be negligent in the death of a guest on the
show. The jury in a civil suit awarded $25 million to the family of
the dead man, Scott Amedure, who was slain by another guest,
Jonathan Schmitz, after Amedure revealed his homosexual attraction
to Schmitz. (Summary from wires) By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-HESS (New York) _ Leon Hess, who took over his family's
bankrupt fuel-oil business during the Depression and built it into
one of the world's largest petroleum companies, but was perhaps
best known as the steadfast owner of the long-floundering New York
Jets football team, died Friday in New York. He was 85. By Gerald
Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news filed)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy resumed its torrid pace of
job creation last month after an interruption in March, generating
234,000 jobs without putting pressure on companies to raise
employees' wages. The jobless rate crept up to 4.3 percent in April
from 4.2 percent in March. While the gain in new jobs was somewhat
larger than forecasts, hourly wages rose less than expected, easing
concern that interest rates are headed higher. By Sylvia Nasar.
