<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SCHREIBER     05-07 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SCHREIBER-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPRESARIO OF BRAND NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)  
 (af)  
 By ALEX FOEGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Schreiber may resemble an advertising executive in some
ways, but his casually rumpled look is clearly not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 70 degrees outside,'' said Keith Ritter, a senior vice
president at CBS Sports, welcoming Schreiber, 44, the founder and
president of the John Schreiber Group, into his mid-Manhattan
office one recent afternoon. ``What's with the corduroys?''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter was kidding, of course. After all, he had hired Schreiber
_ whose round glasses and erudite manner suggest a literature
professor _ precisely because he turns convention on its head.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter oversees CBS's sponsorship of NASCAR, a stock-car racing
licenser, and the day's task was to put the finishing touches on
NASCAR Rocks, a music tour featuring the Allman Brothers that
Schreiber had designed to expand both stock-car racing's growing
audience and CBS's involvement with the sport.
</P>
<P>
   In an advertising-saturated society, corporations increasingly
come to people like Schreiber to develop such campaigns. A leader
in the relatively young field of entertainment marketing, he works
with clients like American Express, Philip Morris and the Hard Rock
Cafe to bring a new dimension to their brands. His Manhattan firm,
which he runs with two partners and 30 employees, projects 1999
billings of $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber is the brain behind the Toyota Comedy Festival, the
premier gathering of its kind in the nation. (This year's event is
June 3-12 at sites around the city; the main event is Ray Romano at
Carnegie Hall.) The seven-year-old festival stands out because of
Laugh Well, a program Schreiber added in 1995 to send comics into
local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Toyota-sponsored benefit starring the comedian
Steven Wright at Morristown Hospital in New Jersey raised $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between what we do and what I call
slap-on sponsorships,'' Schreiber said. ``I like to do things where
one and one equals three, where everybody wins.''
</P>
<P>
   His clients champion him for keeping his eye on the ball.
``Other people got focused on the idea that we were doing NASCAR
Rocks simply as a concert series,'' Ritter said. ``John immediately
understood that we wanted a really cool entertainment experience,
but that it also had to serve a broader marketing goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber's feel for quality entertainment, unusual in his
bottom-line-oriented industry, is rooted in his background. The
Queens-born son of a jazz-loving father in the construction
business and a mother who did volunteer work, he began arranging
music events in the early 1970s as a student at Haverford in
suburban Philadelphia, ``a little Quaker college where nobody goes
into show business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Marian McPartland, the British jazz pianist, offered to
introduce him to George Wein, impresario of the Newport and Kool
jazz festivals, he jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, shortly after graduating, Schreiber was hired by Wein's
Festival Productions and was introduced to Dizzy Gillespie, Charles
Mingus and Ella Fitzgerald. ``The first month I was there, I was at
the jazz festival in Nice, running the stage with all these music
heroes of mine,'' he said. ``I thought to myself, `I have died and
gone to heaven.'''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his early career, his home life now seems oddly
quiet. He lists reading, jogging and music as his main pastimes; he
met his wife, Debra Simon, head of marketing for the Alliance for
Downtown New York, when she worked for him as a producer. Married
four years, they live in Manhattan with their 2-year-old son, Ben.
``What we do for fun,'' he said, ``is hang out with the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1980s, he produced some 20 jazz festivals for
Wein, crediting his former boss with teaching him that
``corporations have the ability, by virtue of their objectives and
their pockets, to make valuable things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When American Express asked him in the mid-1980s to come up with
a strategy that would build brand loyalty among premium-card
holders, he came up with Gold Card Events and Platinum Card by
Invitation, programs offering prime seats to entertainment events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very careful about what Gold Card seating was,'' he
recalled in an interview at his firm's cramped offices near Times
Square. ``We would sometimes go to the performances, see where the
members were and ask them if they were happy with their seats.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, during the stand-up comedy craze, he had an idea to
hold a comedy festival in New York but knew that he would need
backers. The region's Toyota dealers are particularly pleased with
the idea, especially Laugh Well, the local charitable connection.
</P>
<P>
   After Schreiber started his own company in 1995, he kept a hand
in the comedy festival, of which he is co-producer, with Wein and
Alan King. Since then, he has juggled projects varying from ``Hard
Rock Live,'' the televised concert series he produces for Hard Rock
Cafe and VH-1, to National Public Radio's 25th anniversary
celebration at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   One client might open him to controversy _ Philip Morris, with
which he produces Club Benson &AMP; Hedges, a rhythm-and-blues series
in clubs around the country.Tobacco companies, shut out of most
advertising channels, need new ones.
</P>
<P>
   But Patrick Reynolds, of the Foundation for a Smoke-Free
America, said, ``Such events lend an aura of respectability and
caring about the community when in fact they are aggressively
marketing their deadly products.''
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber is unapologetic. ``That's a first-class program,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He sees beauty in the variety of his work. ``Half of what I do
is stuff I'm passionately interested in as a guy, the other half is
as a guy who thinks of himself as a smart marketer,'' he said.
``We're like glass blowers _ everything is different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
