A8408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-CHILDREN08-COX     05-07 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CHILDREN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACCIDENTS AND HOMICIDES KILLING HEALTHY YOUNG AMERICANS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A century of improvements in sanitation, public
health and medicine has produced a generation of healthy American
children whose worst dangers are guns, cars and drugs, a private
health policy group said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As America enters the 21st century, the nation is
unsuccessfully confronting the most difficult hazards to the health
of its children,'' the Public Health Policy Advisory Board said
following a yearlong study.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, founded recently by former Health and Human
Services Secretary Louis Sullivan, said the public must begin
discussing ``difficult issues'' that cannot be solved with
medicines and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the turn of the (20th) century, spectacular successes in
the prevention and treatment of injury and disease have
dramatically demonstrated the value of focused public health
interventions,'' the board's report on ``Health and the American
Child'' stated. It said mortality rates for children have dropped
over 90 percent since 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet today's children face new hazards of a changed era.
Despite the enormous consequences for our nation and its economy,
we lack a comprehensive national framework to help set goals and
target resources to enhance children's safety and physical and
mental health.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of disease like smallpox, measles and diarrhea,
Americans under 20 are most likely to die of accidents, homicides
and suicides, the board said. Accidents accounted for 42 percent of
all deaths in this age group in 1995, the report stated, and nearly
two-thirds of these deaths involved motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides and suicides accounted for 14 percent and 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, homicide and suicide pose some of the biggest
risks to children in this nation,'' said Maria J. New, chairman of
Department of Pediatrics of Cornell University Medical Center and a
member of the new organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to recognize that the sad events in Littleton,
Colorado, are indicative of larger trends in teenage violence,''
she said. ``While children once faced the greatest threats from
diseases like polio and smallpox, threats to children's health now
relate more to social, cultural and behavioral changes in
society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's children face new hazards of a changed era,'' said
Sullivan, now president of Morehouse Medical School in Atlanta.
``This report serves as a wake-up call to parents, schools,
religious and community groups and policy-makers. Our nation needs
to recognize what is really putting our children at risk and
respond with a comprehensive strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Public Health Policy Advisory Board describes itself as a
nonpartisan public health organization established to advance
``sound, science-based policy-making in public health.'' Its
funding comes from ``unrestricted grants'' from industry,
government and other nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
