<HEADER>
A8413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-PESSIMISM-HNS &LR;      05-07 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-PESSIMISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEYS SHOW AMERICANS IN A FUNK OVER SCHOOL SHOOTINGS, KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Voters are expressing a new sense of pessimism over
America's future in the wake of the high school massacre in
Littleton, Colo., and the conflict over Kosovo, a Democratic
pollster said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The pollster, Celinda Lake, told reporters that her
Washington-based consulting firm interviewed 100 voters in
so-called focus groups of 10 each in Seattle, Denver, Oklahoma
City, Los Angeles and Baltimore over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of every 10 participants described their view of the
nation's present and future in negative terms, using such words as
anxious, depressed, disappointed and confused, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, only half the participants or fewer used such
words, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's noticeable is a profound shift in the mood of the
public,'' Lake said. ``In every focus group, there's never more
than one person who has something positive to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift, if it holds up, will have profound implications for
candidates in the 2000 race, she said, predicting that Vice
President Al Gore, the Democratic frontrunner, cannot expect the
high-flying economy to propel him to victory, as it did in 1996 for
President Clinton and him.
</P>
<P>
   The feelings of depression have ``ended any hope of (Gore's)
being able to run on `four more years,''' Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   To have any chance, Gore must ``define a separate and
contemporary agenda that's responsive to the problems,'' she
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   But she added that the public's negative feelings have ``upped
the leadership ante for (Texas Gov. George W.) Bush,'' the
Republican frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's living on borrowed time,'' she said. ``He cannot sit in
Texas on the general assumption that a governor ... knows how to
run the country. He's going to have to demonstrate it. That's going
to be tougher. When he engages (voters), he's got nowhere to go but
down''
</P>
<P>
   Lake said the public's pessimism stems from the April 20
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., which left
15 dead, and the air war in Yugoslavia, which started March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The concern over Kosovo has less to do with international
relations, human rights and U.S. leadership than with the military
effort's cost, she said. Focus group participants were worried that
it will eat up the budget surplus, leaving little money for Social
Security or other domestic concerns, Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would just like to be going into the 21st century in
better shape,'' she said, noting that 72 percent of the focus group
participants said the country is heading in the wrong direction
culturally and morally.
</P>
<P>
   Polls and focus groups often are simply snapshots of the public
mood that may quickly change. Analysts often cite Governor Bush's
father, former President George Bush, whose poll numbers were high
in 1991 after the Persian Gulf War but who lost the election in
1992 to then Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Lake insisted the trend that surfaced in her latest round of
focus groups may be longer lasting. She said congressional
Democrats scored political points by seizing the gun issue and
introducing proposals Thursday to put safety locks on hand guns and
regulate gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that even in traditionally pro-gun areas of the South
and the Rocky Mountain states, a gender gap is surfacing with women
increasingly supporting controls while men oppose them, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
