<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-OLIVER08-COX     05-07 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-OLIVER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRED CNN PRODUCER SUES NETWORK AND CONFIDENTIAL SOURCE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ April Oliver, the former TV producer who was fired
by CNN after the news network retracted her controversial
documentary on Operation Tailwind last year, fired back at her
detractors Friday with a pair of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver filed a claim against her former employer, charging that
she had been wrongfully dismissed, and filed a defamation
countersuit against retired U.S. Army General John Singlaub. The
countersuit identified Singlaub, who led covert forces during the
Vietnam War, as ``a confidential source for the Tailwind report.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal actions came after a preliminary hearing in Singlaub's
own defamation lawsuit against CNN and Oliver stemming from the
June 7, 1998, report. The story claimed that covert U.S. forces had
used a deadly nerve gas and targeted American defectors in a secret
1970 raid on a jungle camp in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver has stood behind the report despite CNN's retraction and
widespread criticism that it was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said Singlaub's lawsuit effectively ended her agreement
not to publicly identify him as a source who provided information
for the story, which launched the joint CNN-Time magazine Sunday
night show ``NewsStand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Singlaub shattered our confidentiality contract,'' she said.
``First, he told the public he wasn't a source. Then, at a Pentagon
press conference in July, he told the world he was a source, but
had always denied the story. Then he filed suit against me. These
actions nullify our agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   In the countersuit filed in District of Columbia Superior Court,
Oliver said she had interviewed Singlaub six times in connection
with the Tailwind report and took detailed notes at each meeting.
Afterward, the document said, Singlaub joined in attacks on the
report and filed a suit ``alleging that Oliver has defamed him by
reporting the very information that he, on condition of
confidentiality, had confirmed to her.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own legal filings, Singlaub denies confirming that nerve
gas was used in Operation Tailwind or that the mission was aimed at
finding and killing U.S. defectors in Laos. Indeed, he said he was
not involved at all and was defamed by the CNN report, which
implied he commanded the unconventional forces that carried out the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   While Oliver and CNN were united in defense against Singlaub's
charges of defamation Friday, the 36-year-old producer charged
after the hearing that her bosses had ``hung me out to dry'' when
the military community challenged the report. Oliver and
co-producer Jack Smith were fired shortly after the report was
shown, and the on-air correspondent, Peter Arnett, parted ways with
the cable news network several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In her suit against the network, Oliver said she was made a
scapegoat. CNN did not ``terminate the employment'' of
``supervisory executives, editors and managers who reviewed the
Tailwind report and were responsible for the decision to air the
piece, including CNN executives Tom Johnson, Rick Kaplan, David
Kohler, John Lane, Frank Sesno, Pam Hill and Jim Connor,'' the
document said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said she not only lost her $60,000-a-year job, but that
derogatory remarks made by some of her former bosses ``have hurt my
career very badly.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit against CNN ``is an opportunity to get the facts of the
case out there,'' she said in an interview. ``There has been a lot
of misinformation, and really character assassination. It is
important for people who know who made the decisions on this
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the lawsuit, a CNN spokesperson said, ``We do not
comment on matters of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Friday, attorneys agreed on a schedule that would
extend the case well into next year. And Singlaub is only one of
several Vietnam veterans who have filed suits against CNN, its
parent company Time-Warner Inc., Oliver, Arnett and others involved
in the report about Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
