</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNUALS THAT MAKE LAZY GARDENERS LOOK GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 9)  
(mk) 
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through sheer laziness, I had a beautiful retaining-wall garden
last year.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm confident that I will again this year because of the
glories of long-blooming, self-seeding annuals.
</P>
<P>
   These are plants that don't want to quit. They flower all summer
and often into fall. Then they return the next year, with no effort
on my part, like perennials repeating their superb performance all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   Until I had that gray stone retaining wall built to level some
ground in front of my house for a garden, annuals were not a
significant part of my horticultural life. I felt that they
required too much time and expense because they had to be bought
and planted every year.
</P>
<P>
   It was only because the foot-high wall was in the front that I
decided to use a large display of annuals. They would provide
instant color above the wall's curved, 24-foot length, giving me
time to decide what perennials to use.
</P>
<P>
   I looked for plants that would stand no more than a foot tall,
so that they wouldn't overwhelm the wall. With potted annuals in
full bloom at garden centers by mid-May, it was easy to search for
the colors I wanted _ light blues, soft yellows, creamy whites and
blush pinks.
</P>
<P>
   To have easy-care flowers, I chose dwarf ageratums and
marigolds. The marigolds had lemon yellow flowers, a pleasant
surprise because I had long assumed that they came only in garish
colors.
</P>
<P>
   Serendipity joined my search when I came across flats of Crystal
White zinnia. Though I had never seen these small-flowered zinnias,
a Kansas City friend had told me of their long flowering period and
resistance to mildew.
</P>
<P>
   These traits, plus the plant's tolerance for heat and drought,
earned it a place as a 1997 All-America Selections winner, a
distinction given to outstanding plants field-tested across the
country. The zinnia's height, 8 to 10 inches, was perfect for my
border, and so was its color. Despite the name Crystal White, it is
more creamy than brilliant white.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, serendipity popped up again, this time in a
nearby garden where I saw the silver-green foliage of California
poppies (Eschscholzia californica) emerging. I commented that the
typical orange and gold of the flowers were too vivid for me.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, a transplanted Englishwoman and fanatical gardener,
replied that she had got a seed packet of mixed colors and had
pulled out all but those that were a creamy white. These had seeded
true to their color over the years. Before my drooling became
excessive, she offered to ``weed out'' a handful for me.
</P>
<P>
   To add a dash of pink and a foliage contrast, I transplanted
several Mexican daisies (Erigeron karvinskianus). A perennial in
the Southern states, this plant behaves like a self-seeding annual
in my borders in central New Jersey. It has wiry foliage sprays,
somewhat like those of Moonbeam coreopsis, and profuse, tiny
daisylike flowers, which open white and turn to pink before neatly
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Though I frequently admired the color combinations and foliage
variation topping my wall, my laissez-faire approach to gardening
meant that I never pinched off seed heads, or deadheaded, so as to
encourage the annuals to keep producing flowers. As a result, the
ageratums and marigolds pretty much shut down production by
mid-September. The zinnias, California poppies and Mexican daisies
needed no special treatment and bloomed until knocked out by hard
frosts.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, from May through early November, I had a pastel flower
display in my sunny front garden. Neither pests nor diseases
attacked the plants. I watered, at most, weekly during dry spells
and never fertilized.
</P>
<P>
   And because I didn't deadhead, mulch or even clean the border in
the fall, I had an ample supply of seedlings when I cleared the
border in early May last year. The sight was a happy surprise, with
seedlings for all but the Crystal White zinnias.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it would be easy to buy more at a garden center, but
none were available. It seems that not enough were bought the
previous year. Thus, despite being honored by a premier national
organization as ``bred for gardeners who want to enjoy flowering
plants all season without labor intensive care,'' Crystal White is
not profitable for wholesale growers in my area.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for me, a group of seedlings emerged in late May. I
transplanted them to the ground abutting the top of the wall and
the base. Though they did not flower until July, they created a
smashing display into the first week of last year's warm December.
</P>
<P>
   My neighbors enjoy my colorful border as much as I do. One of
them commented, ``Your garden always looks so beautiful, yet I
never see you working in it.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the kind of praise you like, these lovely self-seeding
annuals will help you earn it.
</P>
<P>
   While ageratum and marigold plants and seeds are widely
available, the others are not. Should you obtain seed, sow
immediately, because it can take up to three months for blossoms to
appear.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal White is available from Park Seed, 1 Parkton Ave.,
Greenwood, S.C. 29647; (800) 845-3369; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   A creamy white California poppy is offered by Gardenmakers, P.O.
Box 65, Rowley, Mass. 01969; (978) 948-8481; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican daisy is available from Thompson &AMP; Morgan, P.O. Box
1308, Jackson, N.J. 08527-0308; (800) 274-7333; free catalog.
</P>
</TEXT>
