<SLUG> BC-MOTHERS-WHO-THINK-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERS WHO THINK .... ABOUT SEX AND MEN AND NOT MUCH ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Excuse me, but did anyone notice how beautiful the
men are in there?'' Camille Peri asked a group of writers standing
in front of the W Hotel in midtown Manhattan last Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Moses, an earthy-looking woman with the long flowing hair
of a teen-ager, said, ``They don't make them like that in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peri and Ms. Moses are the editors of ``Mothers Who Think,''
a collection of essays (Villard Books, 1999) that first appeared in
the Web-based magazine Salon, which comes out of San Francisco. The
``Mothers Who Think'' feature has developed an avid following for
its insightful coverage of provocative subjects, from abortion to
raising a son without a father. But when the literary mothers
gathered to celebrate the book's publication, the conversation was
about men, sex and Bill Nye, the the science guy.
</P>
<P>
   When the party moved from the W Hotel to dinner for 10 at the
Gotham Bar and Grill, like mothers, they passed around pictures of
their children. Like high schoolers, they passed around their books
to be autographed. When the main course came, the talk was all
about Nye, host of a PBS children's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only man around in the middle of the day, and you
can't help but make him the object of your affection,'' Ms. Moses
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you find him sexy?'' said Elizabeth Rapoport, the
executive editor of Times Books-Random House, who contributed the
essay ``How Many Working Fathers Does It Take to Screw In a Light
Bulb?'' She said, ``His Adam's apple is bigger than his thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moses said: ``He's the nerd you turned down in high school
when you shouldn't have. He could have fixed your bicycle. You
watch him because he's  &UR; the &LR;  man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no zoft,'' countered Ms. Rapoport, who prefers Brendan
Fraser, who played Tarzan. ``Just when you think you have no sexual
feelings at all, there he is, in his loincloth.''
</P>
<P>
   They did touch on serious subjects, like the friction between
nannies and mothers, and whether pregnant women should drink. But
the subject always gravitated back to sex and having babies. As the
evening progressed, the talk grew more graphic. By dessert, they
all talked at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are all the sex stories in the book fantasy?'' Rahna Reiko
Rizzuto asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peri, who claims the sexiest thing her husband could do is
clean the house, said, ``I've always wanted to do a story called
`Housekeeping Is Foreplay.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Anne Phillips, the novelist, added, ``Sleep is very
sexual.''
</P>
<P>
   Lori Leibovich, an associate editor at Talk magazine, asked,
``Did you read about the foreplay pill?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moses said: `` It burns fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their frustrations, the mothers agreed they had no
regrets. Over espresso, Ms. Rapoport said: ``My husband and I
marvel that we had a life before the kids. What did we use to do?
We'd go to Zabar's and buy an interesting cheese. Then we'd go home
and eat it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
