<SLUG> BC-COSMETIC-SURGEONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL BOARD REVIEWS PROBLEM WITH COSMETIC SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A special committee of the Medical Board of
California, which has been exploring problems in the field of
cosmetic surgery, has launched a study on how hospital privileges
are issued to doctors.
</P>
<P>
   With more and more medical procedures performed in outpatient
clinics instead of hospitals, consumers increasingly rely on a gold
standard _ hospital privileges _ to help ensure the competency of
their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But privileges _ a doctor's ability to perform certain
procedures at a hospital _ sometimes are granted on a seemingly
arbitrary basis with no uniform measure of skill or training,
numerous physicians says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we know what hospital privileges mean,'' said
Dr. Robert del Junco, a consultant to the Committee on
Plastic-Cosmetic Surgery. ``Some institutions grant you
unrestricted privileges to do whatever you want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be guided by our primary responsibility, which is
the welfare and best interests of the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is regarded as a medical hot button, particularly
among dermatologists who are sometimes denied privileges or simply
don't apply for them ``because a lot of what they do doesn't
require privileges,'' said Janie Cordray, a program support manager
with the Medical Board.
</P>
<P>
   California hospitals currently have no ``uniform or standard,
consistent, objective minimum criteria,'' Cordray said in a report
to the committee. For individual hospitals, guidelines to assess
the qualifications of a surgeon can be ``somewhat vague,
subjective, and open to interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by dozens of deaths over the last two years of patients
who underwent liposuction, a slate of legislation has been
introduced since January designed to provide stronger consumer
protection. The pending bills range from tightening advertising
restrictions to requiring malpractice insurance for outpatient
surgery. About 60 percent of all surgery now takes place in
outpatient settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of this new legislation points to hospital privileges but
the question is what does it mean to have privileges?'' del Junco
said. ``If tomorrow they implemented a law saying you have to have
privileges, some institutions will grant them based on whatever
criteria they want.''
</P>
<P>
   During a cosmetic surgery board meeting on Thursday, the members
wrestled with a bill introduced by state Sen. Jackie Speier,
D-Hillsborough, to limit the amount of fat that can be suctioned
during liposuction.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, in the wake of lethal outcomes triggered by so-called
``large volume'' liposuction, the committee instituted a
moratorium, restricting surgical aspirate to 5,000 cubic
centimeters. Speier's bill would turn that moratorium into law.
</P>
<P>
   But some committee members voiced concern, saying doctors might
not have the latitude they need to make medical judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem putting a specific number into statute,''
said Dr. Thomas Joas, an anesthesiologist who heads the committee.
``I would hope this isn't a knee-jerk reaction to unfortunate
lethal complications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBAY-ONLINE-$ADV09-NY     05-07 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-ONLINE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING AMOK ON EBAY WHILE SITTING STILL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Fla.)   (af)  
 By FRANK DE CARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among my friends, Ebay is hotter than Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   On-line bidding on everything from lady-head planters to Batman
bubble bath bottles has become a daily ritual for us at home, at
work, even at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   One pal, who doesn't own a personal computer but does have the
East Village's largest collection of poodle bric-a-brac, bids on
ceramic pooches and velvet dog paintings while sweating on the
treadmill. His health club has a Web TV setup in its cardiovascular
workout area.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wallet are thinner than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Internet shopping for canine kitsch has not entirely replaced
his flea market habit, or mine. But the convenience of virtual
browsing on Ebay _ the online auction service that is a national
swap meet for 6.5 million users _ has become a shared obsession for
our little clique.
</P>
<P>
   Why traipse to 26th Street at the crack of 9 every Sunday
morning when you can hunt for junk in your pajamas any night of the
week and still sleep in?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the pickings are better in cyberspace than in the
flower district.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, I have successfully bid on four
superhero drinking glasses from Pizza Hut from 1976, a footed tiki
bowl from a defunct Polynesian restaurant in Las Vegas, a vase
shaped like Barbie, a set of 90 ``Munsters'' trading cards, six
Archie comics jelly glasses with Sabrina's head embossed on the
bottom, a glossy of Gypsy Rose Lee on ``The Mike Douglas Show'' and
a copy of Phyllis Diller's last book (which at $11.50, including
shipping, seemed like a real steal).
</P>
<P>
   It would have taken years to find such a diverse haul in person.
</P>
<P>
   Every time an Ebay-brokered shipment arrives in a recycled
Kool-Aid carton or one of post office issue, I open it with the
enthusiasm of a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   My domestic accomplice, a clutter-hating proponent of financial
responsibility, says: ``Save the box. We're going to have to live
in it someday.''
</P>
<P>
   But I can't stop, even if I may soon need a warehouse. No
pastime gives me greater pleasure than giving a good home to a
Supergirl glass that was sitting in someone's basement in
Kissimmee, Fla. for the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Ebay is not limited to the ephemera my friends and I
treasure. You can bid on vintage clothes, art, even real estate.
But Ebay's true flavor comes from offerings more kitschy than
vintage Chanel _ a rare pickle jar that sold for $44,000 in March
is more quintessentially Ebay than a cashmere sweater that went for
$220.
</P>
<P>
   The online auction house may not specialize in ``junque,'' but
it does sell a lot of it. Recent statistics estimate that Ebay
users exchanged more than $500 million of merchandise last year and
that fully one in 20 packages sent between private individuals via
the post office is a purchase made on Ebay. That's a lot of
tchotchkes changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Even those of us whose idea of heaven is spending 10 hours
trudging through 1,600 booths at an Atlantic City collectibles show
are sometimes surprised by the things people collect.
</P>
<P>
   USA Weekend, a Sunday magazine insert to many newspapers,
reported recently that Glenn Wright, a building contractor from
Bothell, Wash., will make seven figures on Ebay this year selling a
stash of antique fruit crate labels that he and a partner amassed.
They called him the ``fruit label millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a 13-year-old boy from Haddonfield, N.J., spent like
one. He bid away $3.2 million of his parents' money on such objects
as a $1.2 million medical center in Jacksonville, Fla.; a van Gogh
sketch, a 1971 Corvette convertible and a $400,000 bedroom suite
that belonged to Canada's first Prime Minister, Sir John A.
Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
   There were no poodle plates on his list, but my friends could
relate. We've all overspent in a heated moment, bidding more than
we should in the final minutes of an auction for lilac Fiestaware
or a mint, box-fresh Hall China gold-dot casserole. Unlike our
spending sprees, however, the New Jersey boy's bids were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not rolling in bucks,'' his mother told The Newark
Star-Ledger last month. ``I don't know if he decided it was a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's exactly what Ebay is. Navigating through the
now-familiar Web site is like poking through the stalls of any flea
market in search of that one item that will complete a collection
or start a new one. My new Holy Grail is a set of ``Hollywood
Squares'' collectors plates from the 1970s. A friend has one, but I
want them all.
</P>
<P>
   I check in every day to see if someone is selling Rose Marie.
</P>
<P>
   As auctions progress, it's exciting to see how much people are
willing to spend for such articles _ not to mention how they'll
splurge on the type of toys their mothers gave away when they left
for college in 1974 _ and to note which postings go ignored.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting, too, to see which brand-new items become
instant collectibles. Beanbags shaped like characters from the '60s
Christmas special ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer,'' for instance,
which were sold at CVS stores last December to nostalgic baby
boomers for about $5 each, are already commanding much higher
prices. There is comfort in knowing that someone else is willing to
pay 20 bucks for a stuffed Abominable Snowman.
</P>
<P>
   At a cocktail party I attended two weeks ago, a young
computer-savvy man told me that in the last month he'd earned
enough money selling on Ebay to buy a DVD player. His take was
hundreds, not the millions of the fruit-label guy, but it was a
start.
</P>
<P>
   He sold the T-shirts, snow globes and photographs that press
agents had sent him over the years to promote new movies or
television shows, things that had filled his cubicle at work and
would most likely have ended up in the trash should he ever change
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will buy anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having just spent $10 on a copy of the Totie Fields
mashed-potato-diet book, who was I to argue?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
