<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUMMY-PRECURSORS-TEX     05-07 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUMMY-PRECURSORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MUMMY WRAP-UP: TOMB RAIDERS OF OLD FACED A FRIGHTFULLY CORNY
FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's fun to imagine what Karl Freund would think watching
Universal Pictures' remake of his 1932 directorial debut, ``The
Mummy.'' Walking mummified skeletons, flesh-eating scarab beetles
and computer-animated sandstorms in the shape of a gaping-mouthed
face would probably have sent Freund into cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But for special effects-savvy audiences, the new ``Mummy'' is
really just a sandy hors d'oeuvre before George Lucas serves up his
effects-laden main course, ``The Phantom Menace'' Star Wars prequel
on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't afford much time for Universal's big-budget monster
movie to capture an audience, but thanks to a number of visually
stunning coming- attraction trailers, ``The Mummy'' is almost
critic-proof.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser leads a band of treasure-seeking explorers to the
fabled Egyptian City of the Dead, Hamunaptra, the burial place of
the Pharaohs and all their riches. It's also the final resting
place of Imhotep, an ancient evil high priest who was cursed to be
undead forever and is just waiting for someone to let him out.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a startling number of computer-generated images from _
coincidentally enough _ Lucas' Industrial Light &AMP; Magic, you almost
feel like you're watching DreamWorks' animated ``The Prince of
Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   But this $60 million ``Mummy'' still embraces the melodramatic,
over-acted, shoestring-budgeted origins of the original mummy
movies. Here's a peek inside the tomb of some of our favorite
mummified memories:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' (1932) Though Freund's debut picture was hardly
the first appearance of a movie mummy (they actually date as far
back as 1901's ``The Haunted Curiosity Shop''), his vision of
Egypt's ancient dead became the icon to which future versions were
compared. Boris Karloff is the regenerated 3,700-year-old priest
Imhotep who eventually sheds his bandages and becomes the
menacingly pale Ardeth Bey. Zita Johann is the stalkee, believed to
be the reincarnation of Bey's former lover.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy's Hand'' (1940) Not really a sequel to Freund's
film, even though it uses almost 10 minutes of the picture as
flashback footage. This time, the vengeful undead priest is called
Kharis (Tom Tyler). (He also stalks the next three sequels.) The
new ``Mummy'' also borrows from this story of an ancient
brotherhood protecting the tomb of Princess Ananka from scavengers.
George Zucco is the high priest, with Dick Foran and Wallace Ford
doing a kind of Abbott and Costello routine as leaders of the
expedition and Peggy Moran as the mummy's love interest.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy's Tomb'' (1942) Kharis (Lon Chaney Jr., who plays
him in both subsequent sequels) and a new high priest schlep all
the way to the States to exact revenge on the aging Foran and Ford
(and their families). Elyse Knox is the mummy's gal, and there are
many cowering ninnies unable to escape the slow-moving, shambling
creature. You'd think that with one arm bandaged to its chest and
one leg dragging, this thing would be pretty easy to outmaneuver.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy's Ghost'' (1944) Kharis really starts to wear out
his welcome in this one. John Carradine joins the cast as the
mummy's mentor, out to find the reincarnation of Princess Ananka,
played by Ramsay Ames. The two eventually end up lost in the swamp,
and not a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy's Curse'' (1944) The end of the Kharis series (for
Universal at least) has both mummies unearthed from the swamp by
construction crews. There's so much flashback footage from previous
``Mummy'' movies, this hardly even counts as a new effort. But it's
fun to note that this Ananka, Virginia Christine, went on to play
Mrs. Olsen in the Folgers coffee commercials.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbott and Costello Meet the Mummy'' (1955) As with most of
the Bud and Lou monster comedies, this spelled the end for
Universal's mummy outings. The monsters tended to lose their shock
value after being played up for punch lines, especially when they
looked as crummy as Eddie Parker as ``Klaris.'' Not surprisingly,
the last of the meet-the-monsters movies and the next-to-the-last
movie for the comedy duo.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' (1959) England's Hammer Studios revived the mummy
legend with this remake, starring Christopher Lee as the cursed
Kharis. Peter Cushing desecrates the tomb of Princess Ananka
invoking the mummy's wrath. Yvonne Furneaux is believed to be the
princess's reincarnation. Several of the more stylish elements of
this version also wound up in the new movie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Curse of the Mummy's Tomb'' (1964) The mummy is Ra-Antef
(Dickie Owen) this time, an attraction brought to Victorian England
only to go on an obligatory killing spree. Jeanne Roland is carried
through the sewers until the monster is stopped by the
reincarnation of its brother. This by-the-numbers follow-up was not
a sequel to the Lee version.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy's Shroud'' (1967) Edie Powell is Prem, the undead
reincarnation of an Egyptian slave in the lousiest of the unrelated
Hammer mummy outings. Peter Cushing narrates.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood From the Mummy's Tomb'' (1972) Valerie Leon is possessed
by the soul of Queen Tara after she and fellow archaeologists
desecrate the queen's tomb. Murders ensue. Pretty good effort based
on Bram Stoker's ``Jewel of the Seven Stars'' and remade in 1980 as
``The Awakening,'' with Charleton Heston and Jill Townsend as his
possessed daughter.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if you can't find these bandaged bad boys at your
local video store, the Sci-Fi cable channel will air a whole crypt
full of mummy movies at 2 p.m. every day next week, including: the
'59 ``Mummy'' on Monday, the '32 version on Thursday, ``Tomb'' on
Wednesday, ``Ghost'' on Thursday and ``Curse'' on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call him at (817) 390-7691. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
