<HEADER>
A8449 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EEOC-$ADV09-COX     05-07 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EEOC-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EEOC PASSED ON COMPLAINT THAT LED TO SUIT AGAINST COCA-COLA
 &HT;    With COKE. For release Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission
investigated a discrimination complaint by Gregory Allen Clark
against Coca-Cola, and found that the available information did not
support the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was the original plaintiff in a racial discrimination suit
filed against Coca-Cola in December and amended April 22. The
amended suit includes three other plaintiffs and asks for class
action status. In the suit, Clark charges he was denied promotions
on the basis of race.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC is an independent agency that enforces federal laws
forbidding employment discrimination. Its decision on the Clark
complaint came in what's known as a ``dismissal and notice of
rights'' letter, which has a checklist of possible reasons the file
is being closed.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Voyles, a Marietta, Ga., lawyer representing the
plaintiffs, confirmed this reason was cited: ``Based upon its
investigation, the EEOC is unable to conclude that the information
obtained establishes violations of the statutes. This does not
certify that the respondent is in compliance with the statutes. No
finding is made as to any other issues that might be construed as
having been raised by this charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the details of the EEOC complaint nor the extent of the
investigation is public information.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC finding ``has no application to the merits of the case
we subsequently filed,'' Voyles said Friday. ``Basically, it's a
non-determination letter. Neither have they found discrimination,
nor have they not found discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola declined comment on the EEOC finding.
</P>
<P>
   Clark did not have an attorney when he filed his EEOC complaint,
Voyles said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the EEOC finding is uncertain, but less than what
it might have been if a lawyer had represented Clark at the time,
said New York attorney Arnold H. Pedowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals without attorneys can get ``short shrift'' on such
complaints, said Pedowitz, who specializes in employment law. That
happens, he said, because ``most people are not good lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
