<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEISHA-FASHION-$ADV09     05-07 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEISHA-FASHION-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEISHA GLAM: DARING TO CONCEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ``Silk,'' Alessandro Baricco's cult novel of
erotic enthrallment, a French silk trader travels to remotest Japan
in 1861, where he meets a ravishing young courtesan. Her face is
turned away, her body enfolded in layers of brocade. He catches
only a glimpse of her hand peeking from her sleeve, but it is
enough to spark an obsession that haunts him for years.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit embodied by Baricco's temptress in his 1997 fable
(Random House, 1998), first published in Italy _ a spirit of
elusiveness, seduction, restraint _ has lately infused the world of
style, flourishing in high fashion, music videos, movie costumes,
even soap design. A flurry of obi-wrapped waistlines, bell sleeves,
thong sandals and trailing kimonos _ the hallmarks of Geisha Glam _
lends a provocative edge to the newest collections of Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana and Jean Paul Gaultier. They also furnish Madonna, still
pop's ranking culture chameleon, with her latest incarnation. They
turn up in the costumes for the new ``Star Wars'' installment
zooming into theaters next week.
</P>
<P>
   An infatuation with the stylized, circumscribed Japan of tea
houses, parasols and painted fans represents a pendulum swing away
from the slick esthetic and overt sexuality of just a minute ago,
as popularized by designers like Donatella Versace and Tom Ford of
Gucci. Geisha chic may express a yearning for a post-Monica return
to mystery and sexual reticence. It is Sayuri, the heroine of the
best-selling ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' by Arthur Golden (Alfred A.
Knopf, 1997), not Monica Lewinsky, who is fashion's latest muse;
the kimono, not the thong, is the year's most erotic garment.
</P>
<P>
   Schooled to keep her opinions as cloaked as her erogenous zones,
Sayuri symbolizes ``our thirst for mystery and hiddenness,'' said
Irene Wilson, the vice president of trend forecasting and consumer
behavior for Spiegel, the catalog company. The geisha's masklike
white makeup and concealing robes represent ``the beauty of the
unknown and unknowable,'' said Ms. Wilson, who created Elements, a
Spiegel Asian-influenced home and apparel catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Tricia Biggar, the movie costume designer who outfitted Natalie
Portman as the monarch Amidala in ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' wrapped her in extravagant robes that owe a debt
to Japanese noblewomen's traditional garments. Ms. Portman's
stiffly formal get-ups and Noh-like whiteface function as a screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In them you maintain a distance and a certain courtesy,'' Ms.
Biggar said. ``In a way, white makeup is like sunglasses. It allows
you to hide, perhaps to say one thing and mean another.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Fisher, an anthropologist at Rutgers University who has
studied courtship behavior, views the fascination with the geisha
as a sign that ``we are finally beginning to appreciate the nature
of female sensuality, which is essentially hidden.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The geisha culture is all about creating a context for that
sensuality through flirting, touching, kissing, satin sheets and
scented flowers,'' she said. The obi-tied kimono functions
metaphorically as the cover for a vibrant sexuality that is best
kept under wraps, Ms. Fisher maintained.
</P>
<P>
   In a book coming out this month, ``The First Sex: The Natural
Talents of Women and How They Are Changing the World'' (Random
House), she examines the increasing number of women pouring into
the job market worldwide and argues that it's just smart to
cultivate geisha-like reticence, ``Women have nothing to gain by
airing their secrets or slinking into the office in a turquoise
pants suit,'' Ms. Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   That wisdom _ if not the exact fashion references _ is shared by
John Galliano, whose past collections have shimmered with allusions
to the high-bred Japanese courtesan. More recently, the glamour
that resides in the geisha's mystery and illusion has appealed to
Gaultier in Paris and to Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana in
Milan. These three, who were once fashion's foremost exponents of
sexual availability _ purveyors of cone bras and corsets worn as
evening wear _ have been among the strongest champions of Geisha
Glam.
</P>
<P>
   In his spring collection now in stores, Gaultier offers
kaleidoscopically patterned robes cinched obi-style at the waist
and cut to reveal the nape and upper back _ the No. 1 erogenous
zone in traditional Japan, but a new one in the West. The models in
Gaultier's Paris runway show last fall minced down the catwalk on
okobo, the geisha's high, thonged sandals, trailing sleeves so
capacious you could stuff a week's laundry inside.
</P>
<P>
   Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, too, resurrected the obi, a hit of their
previous collection, updating it for spring 1999 as a
torso-encasing surgical bandage. Their friend and muse, Madonna,
was swift to pounce on the geisha theme, adopting the designers'
hip-to-breastbone binding as her latest style insignia. The
ethereal girl wore her a red vinyl waist-cincher stretched tight
over a scarlet kimono at the Grammy Awards in February, and she
shows that costume in her new ``Nothing Really Matters'' video. Her
performance, she has said, is inspired by another character in
``Memoirs of a Geisha'' _ Hatsumomo, a schemer whose enigmatic
smiles conceal a buried sensuality.
</P>
<P>
   The same smoldering eroticism glows in the opaque visage of the
model of the moment, Devon Aoki, the face of Chanel. Karl
Lagerfeld, Chanel's designer, cast Ms. Aoki, whose background is
Japanese, German and British, to star in advertisements he
photographed himself. ``She has the modern geisha attitude,'' he
said when asked about his inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld seems increasingly captivated by the kind of delicacy
that until now seemed as dated as the peignoir. So does the
designer Vera Wang, whose Madison Avenue window this month features
three wispy outfits patterned with gray-brown misty peaks she found
in a traditional Japanese landscape painting. Ms. Wang so admired
this look, which she discovered in a painting at her doctor's
office, that she had it copied by Ratti, a premier Italian textile
house.
</P>
<P>
   There is a classical Japanese sensibility in the designs of
Akira Isogawa, sold at Barneys New York. Isogawa, a Japanese-born
Australian, makes regular trips to Kyoto in search of vintage
kimonos that inspire his beaded dresses and obis, the latter a
recent sellout at Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   Demure as they are, these looks can be provocative, said Julie
Gilhart, the vice president of fashion merchandising at Barneys.
``They are fluid and structured at the same time,'' she pointed
out, much like the geisha's architected coif. ``You imagine that
once you take out those sticks holding it in place, all that hair
comes cascading down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   To many, Geisha Glam may seem to have arrived only minutes ago.
But in some quarters it has reached the bandwagon stage. Lafco, a
soap maker based in TriBeCa, has introduced a line of $15 soaps it
calls Kimono, and wraps them in paper with old-fashioned Japanese
designs and ties them with satin cords. The company's news release,
boasting of ``sensitivity to society's shifting trends'' cites as
influences Madonna's new look, ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' feng shui
in home decor and the new ``Star Wars'' costumes. The company is
``doing the Asian thing,'' Jon Bresler, one of the founders, says
in the publicity package.
</P>
<P>
   Some might interpret the geisha's pale face and constricting
costumes as signaling a return to a decorous femininity that went
out with Pat Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you wear a kimono you're suddenly forced into a ladylike
posture in the old-fashioned sense of that word,'' said Ms. Wilson
of Spiegel. ``You have to sit up, to stand very straight and take
very small steps. There's no way that you can slouch or sink into
an overstuffed sofa. It just doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The geisha as style icon may also suggest that preening,
manipulative behavior by women in the war of the sexes, once
scorned by feminists, is becoming respectable again. ``The geisha
has taught us that a woman can use her wiles _ that's the ultimate
power she has,'' said Irma Zandl, president of the Zandl Group, a
trend and consulting company in New York. ``When we talk about a
geisha, we're talking about a tease.''
</P>
<P>
   But Liza Crihfield Dalby, an American anthropologist who lived
in Kyoto as a geisha in the 1970s and wrote a book, ``Geisha,''
which was reissued by the University of California Press last year
in response to what a press spokeswoman called ``geisha mania,''
said that sometimes a dress is just a dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy to take the metaphor of clothing constriction as
symbolizing social constriction,'' said Ms. Dalby, also the author
of ``Kimono'' (Yale University Press, 1994), a look at Japanese
society and culture through clothing. ``I don't buy that. It's a
fashion game, something new and different for this season.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West, ``we've totally mythologized the geisha,'' she
continued. ``She's someone who can satisfy all your desires. She's
very mysterious under all that white makeup. And also, because
she's foreign and, if you don't speak Japanese, sort of mute, she's
an ideal screen for projecting fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   What more has fashion ever asked?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
