<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROOKS-BROTHERS-ART-$     05-07 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKS-BROTHERS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SQUARE AT THE NEW BROOKS BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 9) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By BENJAMIN CHEEVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The waiters wore white Brooks Brothers shirts, opened
at the throat and with the sleeves rolled up to show off massive
biceps. There were strobe lights; the music was loud. Set
tastefully around the store were squares of plastic turf with rep
ties rearing out of them like toothless serpents. ``This is Brooks
Brothers for the millennium,'' said Joseph Gromek, the store's
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cumming, Matthew Broderick and Marisa Tomei had invited me
(or at least signed the invitation) to celebrate the opening of a
new, hip branch of the retailer that sold suits to Abraham Lincoln,
at 666 Fifth Ave., on Monday night. The line to get in went up
Fifth Avenue to 53d Street, and then out almost to the Avenue of
the Americas. Inside, there were smoke machines, people who hadn't
shaved. A drag performer called Lady Bunny introduced the club
singer Ultra Nate.
</P>
<P>
   I had meant to fit in. I wore my pink button-down Brooks shirt.
I didn't have a Brooks tie, so I wore one with Labrador retrievers
on it. My chinos were Brooks (W32 L30), no pleats, and cinched at
the waist with a sharkskin belt, which I had purchased when a
cruise ship I was on docked at Cozumel. You see the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I was introduced to Broderick. He was there for Naked Angels,
the downtown theater group with Hollywood connections, whose stars
were lending their names to the occasion. (Brooks made a
contribution in return for their presence and support.) He said he
was pleased to meet me. I said I was pleased to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I've been helpful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I said, ``very helpful,'' and then he left.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what he could have done. I never did fit in at
Brooks. For years, I wasn't square enough. During the late 1950s
and early '60s, when the Madison Avenue store was a high temple of
respectability and taste, my father used to drag me there. I lugged
three Brooks suits off to Loomis, a boarding school for boys in
Connecticut, and wore them to chapel and to mixers. I don't know
what God thought, but the Chaffee girls from our sister school were
easily able to keep their passions in check. Who knew what was
going on inside that sack of flannel? You might have emptied a
revolver, hit the suit six times and left me unscathed. I couldn't
imagine clothes that fit less well.
</P>
<P>
   Then I joined the wrestling team and developed an 18-inch neck.
When my father brought me in to buy shirts that year, it turned out
that the only ones they had with necks that large were large all
over. They were so large that modesty did not require the purchase
of any other article of clothing. A shirt that fastened at the
throat trailed its arms and tails on the floor. Did they have any
shirts that might better approximate the shape of my body? They did
not, we were told. This was the Brooks shirt. We could buy it, or
not. ``All right,'' my father said. ``We'll have six in white and
as many in blue.''
</P>
<P>
   I was simply the wrong shape. I slouched and mumbled, ate with
my mouth open. I wasn't a Brooks man. Not yet, but perhaps one day
I would be. At least the clothes didn't reject me like a plastic
heart. My father had had a friend who bought a pair of shoes at the
Brooks on Madison and by the time he had walked to Grand Central
Terminal the shoes were filled with blood. This story was told and
retold gleefully, not as a criticism of Brooks, but as an attack on
the man who foolishly thought he could stuff his fat, nouveau feet
into the shoes of privilege and command.
</P>
<P>
   Jarlath Mellett is the design director for the new line of
Brooks clothes, which are appearing on the sides of buses all over
town _ elegant slate sweaters worn without shirts by members of a
family, if everyone in a family were handsome, thin and the same
age.
</P>
<P>
   Mellett is a cheerful, stylish man, who wore a suit jacket and
shirt buttoned at the throat with no necktie. I mean, you could see
his collar button. Brooks could be ``hip and fun and still 100
percent true to its roots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 24,000-square-foot store is on two levels, sleek and airy.
The dark wood and glass cases of the original store on Madison
Avenue and 44th Street have been replaced with open displays.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Gromek if he didn't think he had an image problem,
he didn't see it. ``Brooks is a phenomenal brand,'' he told me. The
pear-wood display cases came from Utah, he said, from the same
company that supplied wood for the Mormon Tabernacle.
</P>
<P>
   Then his friend Tom Florio, the publisher of GQ magazine,
appeared, and the two embraced. ``Two weeks and the boat's in the
water,'' Gromek told him.
</P>
<P>
   After this, I saw a striking young man in a dark suit, a black
shirt, black vest, black tie and black cowboy hat. I saw another in
leather pants and a red top. Nobody else seemed to be wearing a
shirt anything like mine. I felt like a hen in a fox house.
</P>
<P>
   The first floor of the store is connected to the second floor by
two side-by-side staircases, and at about 9:30 p.m., men with those
earplugs we know from the Secret Service closed off both
staircases. Then, the models came down one staircase, walked across
an improvised runway and went up the other.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the men were unshaven and had rumpled hair. The women
didn't seem to be wearing brassieres. When they hit the cameras,
they'd smile, briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks had been stodgy and conservative when I was trying to get
in. Now, the organization seems to have whizzed around behind me,
and I'm the square and stodgy one. These models looked even less
respectable than I am. And that's going somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   At the Loomis School for boys, breakfast was the least formal
meal, but we were still required to wear a necktie and jacket. Many
of those jackets were from Brooks. Looking at the striking and
strikingly appareled young men and women coming down the stairs, I
couldn't help reflecting that not one of them would have been
admitted to breakfast at the Loomis School for boys.
</P>
<P>
   A charter member of the bridge-and-tunnel crowd, I left the
party at 10. I saw Marisa Tomei, but missed some of the other Naked
Angels, like Fisher Stevens and Rob Morrow. I did stay long enough
to see somebody smoke a cigarette. And I heard a woman say, ``Hi,
my name is Tiffany.''
</P>
<P>
   The next Brooks advertising campaign is being shot by the
high-fashion photographer Peter Lindbergh, who usually works for
clients like Italian Vogue and Bottega Veneta. He was in town the
other day, shooting fall clothes on a variety of New York
characters who represent the new Brooks man. They include Cliff
Williams, a hip downtown restaurateur; Vikram Chatwal, a hip
midtown hotelier, and Richard Johnson, the Page Six columnist for
The New York Post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
