<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8467 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-COX     05-07 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lions and tigers and Mickey
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You say Target just got in the cutest little girl's clothing
promoting the latest Disney movie? I'm there. The Little Mermaid is
skating on ice at the Erwin Center? Ka-ching, I've got seats.
</P>
<P>
   Let the adventurers have Mount Everest and the Grand Canyon. Our
family vacation every other year is to Disney World in Central
Florida. Our friends ask, ``Why?'' I reply, ``Three reasons:
Alexandra, Victoria and Isabella, ages 7, 5 and 2.'' Truth be told,
I love Disney World every bit as much as they do. I tear up every
time I watch them on the It's a Small World ride. I don't mind
riding Snow White's Scary Adventures five times in a row. I pose
with Mickey, again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   And every time we return, there's something's new in this
30,500-acre entertainment and recreation resort. Haven't been there
lately? Let's catch up. There's been a flurry of growth since 1998
with at least a dozen new shows and attractions added; Disney is
expert at reinventing its theme parks to keep us coming back for
more. That's why it continues to be the nation's most popular
tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest new Disney World attraction is the new 500-acre
theme park, Animal Kingdom. We'll go there first.
</P>
<P>
   An African safari
</P>
<P>
   Boarding Kilimanjaro Safari's 32-passenger open all-terrain
truck, my kids' eyes were wide and their arms tight around me. We'd
told them they'd see real wild animals. They weren't prepared for a
family of baboons sunning on rocks just a few yards away, or a herd
of elephants splashing at a watering hole, or black rhinos in pools
and giraffes or zebras and antelope foraging for food. Disney has
spared no detail in re-creating the savannah and bush country of
Africa to simulate a real safari experience. Landscapers scoured
the world to bring in millions of plants, shrubs and trees. With
1.5 million cubic yards of soil, they built a rolling savannah.
</P>
<P>
   My middle child, Victoria, was quick to notice that the lions
weren't chasing the zebras. ``They ate them in 'The Lion King,' ''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   I had to come up with something clever. ``Oh, honey, they have
these secret whatchamacallits in the ground that won't allow the
lions to leave their area. That way, the zebras can say 'na, na,
na, na, na, na.' '' In reality, there are hidden moats to keep
animals from escaping.
</P>
<P>
   A couple from Flagstaff, Ariz., Dave and Amanda Collier, enjoyed
the bumpy 20-minute ride so much that they hurried off to get back
in line to ride again. ``There were so many animals. We tried to
look at everything but missed the black rhino,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Kingdom opened last spring, and already waits for
attractions are just as long as at the other Disney theme parks.
While this theme park has fewer attraction than MGM Studios, to see
it all will take you a full day. The park is divided into several
sections: Africa, Asia, Safari Village, Camp Minnie-Mickey,
Dinoland and The Oasis.
</P>
<P>
   Don't pass up the Pangani Forest Exploration Trail at Africa,
where you're treated to a close-up look at a dozen lowland
gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   Dinoland U.S.A.'s main attraction is the Countdown to Extinction
thrill ride, where guests board vehicles that take them back 65
million years on a journey to save the last dinosaur from
extinction before the crash of an asteroid. Camp Minnie-Mickey
features the stage shows ``Festival of the Lion King'' and
``Pocahontas and Her Forest Friends.'' At Safari Village, see the
incredible 145-foot man-made ``Tree of Life'' that has plaster
carvings of more than 300 animals. At the base of the tree's
gnarled trunk, you can enjoy the 3-D film ``It's Tough to be a
Bug.'' Little kids may get frightened when they feel like bugs are
zooming right at them, sneezing wet stuff in their faces or
crawling under their bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tree has got to be the most interesting sculpture I've
ever seen,'' said Rick Savane of Grand Rapids, Mich., who's taken
his three children to Disney World twice in the past two years.
``We've got to go get our picture taken with the tree in the
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia, featuring the Kali River Rapids, a white-water raft
adventure and the Animal Kingdom's newest adventure, is dedicated
to the rainforests and wild animals of southern Asia. You're
launched on 12-person rafts into the Chakranadi River for a very
wet ride through the jungle habitat. The Maharajah Jungle Trek is a
walking journey where you see tigers and other animals native to
that region.
</P>
<P>
   Other new attractions abound throughout Disney World's three
other theme parks _ Epcot, Disney-MGM Studios and the Magic Kingdom
_ in what officials are calling the busiest growth period in the
resort's 27-year history.
</P>
<P>
   More is on the way. ``With the same level of energy and
enthusiasm that we'll celebrate the new millennium, Walt Disney
World Resort will actively pursue breakthrough ideas well into the
next century,'' said Duncan Wardle, Disney's director of public and
media relations.
</P>
<P>
   Added to the lineup:
</P>
<P>
   -- As if the Magic Kingdom's 40 adventures weren't enough, Buzz
Lightyear's Space Station Spin engages guests in an interactive
space fantasy in Tomorrowland. You join forces with Buzz Lightyear
to defend the Earth's supply of batteries from the Evil Emperor
Zurg. It replaced Take Flight, an aviation history attraction.
Coming to Fantasyland this summer, the little ones will enjoy ``The
Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh,'' a ride into the Hundred Acre
Wood to see Winnie, Pig, Eeyore, Tigger and Roo. It's replacing Mr.
Toad's Wild Ride.
</P>
<P>
   -- Remember ``The Enchanted Tiki Room'' in Adventureland in the
Magic Kingdom? It's under new management, the new landlords being
Iago from Disney's animated film ``Aladdin'' and Zazu from ``The
Lion King.'' The original cast of birds is still there, but new
songs make the show more upbeat and jazzy.
</P>
<P>
   -- On Test Track, the longest (one mile) and fastest (65 miles
per hour) ride ever at Disney, riders in test vehicles see how GM
vehicles are tested before they hit the market. You'll climb hills,
hang on during hairpin turns, bounce down bumpy roads and then whiz
on straight-aways. The Epcot ride isn't scary, just long and fast.
Also at Epcot is Innoventions, where more than 100,000 square feet
are devoted to tomorrow's breakthrough technology today _ a look at
the latest in computers and communications. You can take a virtual
tour of a Roman basilica and see it as it looked in the 14th
century.
</P>
<P>
   -- Disney-MGM Studios is more than a working film, TV, radio and
animation studio. The most talked about attraction is up in the sky
in a brilliant display of lights, lasers and colorful pyrotechnic
explosions at a new 6,500-seat amphitheater. The 25-minute
``Fantasmic'' nightly show features 50 performers, Disney
characters and dancing waters synchronized to melodies of Disney
classics. And, if your kids can't get enough of the dorky Doug from
ABC Saturday morning cartoon fame, take them to see ``Disney's Doug
Live.'' The musical stage show is performed several times a day and
invites members of the audience to participate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Winter Wonderland, a 36-hole miniature golf course next to
Blizzard Beach water park, opens this month. The story goes that
one Christmas Eve, Santa spotted snow while flying over Florida and
decided it'd be a good vacation spot for the elves. He called it
Winter Wonderland but noticed it lacked a golf course, which
motivated the elves to build a sand course and a snow course.
Guests are treated to wild antics while playing the greens.
</P>
<P>
   -- Downtown Disney's West Side is home to a state-of-the-art
1,671-seat theater built for Cirque du Soleil , the world-renowned
theater company from Quebec. The current production, ``La Nouba,''
is presented twice nightly except Monday and Tuesday. Reservations
can be made by calling (407) 939-7600.
</P>
<P>
   -- In October, Epcot will kick off a 15-month celebration of the
new millennium featuring new entertainment and exhibits of
cutting-edge technologies. ``The unique festivities will highlight
mankind's triumphs, challenges and opportunities,'' said Wardle.
Epcot will also introduce a new nighttime spectacle filled with
lasers, fireworks and special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
