<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISASTER-COMMANDER-$A May9) &LR;    05-07 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-COMMANDER-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SEEKS TOP COMMANDER TO RUN DISASTER RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 9)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon is seeking the appointment of a
military commander for the United States who would help civilian
agencies take charge of the government's response to domestic
disasters, sending troops, equipment and medical gear into a crisis
zone.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for a top emergency military commander stems from White
House fears that terrorists may strike U.S. cities, subways,
buildings and other population centers with chemical and biological
weapons sometime in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is awaiting final approval by Defense Secretary
William Cohen and President Clinton. Deputy Defense Secretary John
Hamre said that Cohen will formally review the plan in June, with
Clinton scheduled to act by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military now has no pre-defined role for handling
domestic emergencies. National Guard units, which are available to
help when disaster strikes, are under the control of the nation's
governors.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will be ready for its expanded role in domestic
disaster relief by October, according to Air Force Gen. Joseph
Ralston, vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. The disaster
commander's unit is to be called the Joint Task Force for Civil
Support.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the Pentagon's proposal are still being worked
out, but, according to Ralston, the officer who directs the Joint
Task Force would report to the military's Commander-in-Chief for
the Atlantic Command based in Norfolk, Va., who in turn reports to
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Task Force would not have a standing collection of
armed forces immediately under it. Instead, in time of crisis, it
would draw Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force personnel as
needed from the Atlantic Command. The military leader also would
have powers to dispatch uniformed medical and emergency personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency would continue to have
responsibility for coordinating disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the specialized help the Pentagon could supply include
troops trained in chemical and biological weapons clean-up and
cargo planes to airlift medical equipment to a crisis zone,
according to Ralston.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are specialized Marine Corps troops _ the
Chemical-Biological Incident Response Force _ which has ``an expert
and robust decontamination capability,'' Ralston said. The Pentagon
also is training 10 specialized teams of National Guardsmen to
combat chemical and biological weapons attacks and assist local
authorities in determining the scope of a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for an expanded military role stems from
administration concern about the potential for a terrorist strike
with chemical weapons such as sarin or biological weapons such as
anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in January said a terrorist attack on American
soil using these types of weapons was ``highly likely'' in the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Cohen said ``one of the greatest threats that
we're going to face in the future would be chemical and biological
attacks, and likely to take place nearly simultaneously in multiple
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamre, explaining the Pentagon plan, said, ``Losing 200
Americans at Oklahoma City was a true tragedy. But if a terrorist
incident involves a chemical or a biological weapon, we're now
talking about consequences far larger. And we must begin to get
ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, who is pressing the military to take on the
expanded disaster relief role, said, ``I don't mean to be an
alarmist, but we have got to address this problem as if it could
happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon proposal has generated concern from critics who
charge that having U.S. troops policing U.S. citizens, even in time
of crisis, would threaten privacy rights and civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   The Posse Comitatus Act, passed after the Civil War, forbids
federal troops from arresting civilians or doing routine police
work or intelligence gathering within U.S. borders.
</P>
<P>
   In order to address these concerns, the Pentagon insists that
civilians would have control of any active duty troops sent to a
crisis zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the civil agencies, `We recognize your authority,
we are going to operate under your direction,''' Hamre said.
``We'll be absolutely under your oversight and control and
supervision and direction.'''
</P>
<P>
   That assurance doesn't impress the American Civil Liberties
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country has had a tradition of separation between law
enforcement, which operates in the U.S., and the military, which
operates abroad,'' said Gregory Nojeim, legislative counsel on
national security for the ACLU, based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldiers are trained to fight wars, not to enforce laws with
proper respect for civil liberties,'' he added. ``Mixing the
military with law enforcement is a recipe for disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposal stops short of creating what some Pentagon
officials had initially sought _ a new commander-in-chief, or CINC,
slot for civil defense, a four-star admiral or general who would
have a standing military force at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamre still believes that there eventually may be a CINC
position created. ``Our view is that having a CINC is a possibility
in the future if this mechanism isn't sufficient. At this stage, I
think we feel this mechanism will be sufficient,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
