<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE08-COX     05-07 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER BUMPY CAMPAIGN START, GORE ADJUSTS HIS MESSAGE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the headquarters of Al Gore's presidential
campaign, veterans pass on this advice to panicky new recruits: the
front-running candidates will go through 12 lifetimes between now
and the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, Gore has only 11 lifetimes left.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's claim to the Democratic nomination was once
seen as inevitable. But with a series of small gaffes like claiming
to have invented the Internet, and by doggedly sticking to a few
narrow, poll-tested themes, he has let challenger Bill Bradley back
into the race, many believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be,'' Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar laughed
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar could afford to laugh. The vice president's bumpy road
to the nomination has smoothed a bit, suggesting an end to Gore's
first ``season in hell,'' as such rough patches are known in
political circles.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, Gore's only opponent, enjoyed a ``boomlet'' of media
attention after an unexpectedly strong first quarter of fund
raising that brought him $4.3 million. The former New Jersey
senator also charmed many of the people he met in campaign stops,
sparking comparisons to Gore's caution and rigid style. Bradley
also presented himself as the candidate of big ideas, although he
has yet to articulate those ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's lead in the polls is back up. One recent poll in New
Hampshire, the nation's first primary state, shows him leading
Bradley by 45 points. And after months of following the Clinton
1996 re-election model of small initiatives to keep a happy
electorate engaged, Gore too is reaching for boldness and bigness.
</P>
<P>
   The American people didn't want ``the vision thing,'' as former
President Bush used to call it, in the 1996 contest between
President Clinton and Bob Dole. The strong economy and peace abroad
had voters generally satisfied with the course of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict in Kosovo and the massacre of high school
students in Littleton, Colo., have left the electorate unsettled,
said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake, who does not work for the
Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not going to elect their president in the 21st
century because of the size of airplane seats,'' she said.
``They're going to elect someone who has a major vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the first of the year, Gore has had the starring role in
announcing a number of limited administration initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   He announced new regulations aimed at clearing the haze in
national parks, new regulations requiring larger print for
nonprescription medicine and a proposal for a telephone line for
drivers to get up-to-the-minute road conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, he unveiled the administration's efforts to
standardize car seats for children and an initiative to give
airline travelers more opportunities to complain about service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to be half-hearted about (issues) only reinforces the
notion that Gore is half-hearted,'' said Carl Pope, president of
the Sierra Club. ``(Voters) don't have the sense that this is a
stand-up guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the high school massacre, Gore has talked
about ``the lessons of Littleton'' and launched what aides describe
as a national ``call to action'' on an agenda that melds gun
control, curbs on media violence, better access to mental health,
values education, character formation and making communities ``more
liveable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Gore's harshest critics have noticed the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gore, a straight arrow in his private life, emphasizes
the role of right and wrong, good and evil, in Littleton, no one
snickers,'' Fred Barnes, executive editor of The Weekly Standard,
wrote in the conservative opinion magazine this week. ``Gore is
being dragged down in polls because of his association with an
immoral president. On Littleton, he's on the side of good,
Christianity and morality.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate political question, though, is whether Gore can
beat Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front-runner for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gore trailed Bush by only a point, 48 percent to 47
percent, in a CNN/Gallup/USA Today poll. The latest poll shows Gore
far behind, 59 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the party majority that supports the vice president
seems to be as panic-free as his campaign veterans. There's no sign
that the prominent Democrats who decided not to challenge Gore for
the nomination are reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   But unless Gore can turn his poll deficit against Bush into an
equally comfortable advantage, he may face another ``season in
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The party elites want to see that gap closed,'' said Lake.
``They don't want to go through the election with white knuckles.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
