<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-KOSOVO-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER SAYS HOUSE VOTES HAVE PUSHED CLINTON TOWARD PEACE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 9)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If a peace agreement is reached over Kosovo, Rep.
Tom Campbell, R-Calif., will claim a small part of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says the peace drive intensified after he forced
Congress to take stands that amounted to a refusal to expand the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite President Clinton's repeated statements that he had no
plans to send ground forces to stop Yugoslavia's killing and
uprooting of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Campbell says he thinks
the administration was in fact planning to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The maverick congressman insists that the plan started to change
after he forced the House _ against the wishes of his own
Republican leaders _ to vote April 28 to either declare war or pull
out the U.S. troops who are taking part in the NATO air campaign
over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of ballots, House members voted against declaring
war, against pulling U.S. troops out of the region _ and against a
resolution authorizing the air campaign, which had begun March 24.
</P>
<P>
   While the votes were inconsistent and confusing, they at least
signaled that the lawmakers did not want to expand the war. Then
last Tuesday, the Senate voted to kill a resolution that would have
allowed Clinton ``to use all necessary force,'' including land
troops, in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it did a lot of good,'' Campbell said of the
congressional votes on Kosovo policy. He also credits the Rev.
Jesse Jackson and the Russians with adding to the pressure to end
the conflict quickly over the rebellious Kosovo province in Serbia,
the dominant republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   To secure the votes against the wishes of the Republican
leaders, Campbell invoked a provision of the 1973 War Powers Act
that allows any lawmaker to demand such votes.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman, who teaches law at Stanford University,
insisted that the Constitution gives Congress the sole power to
declare war even though it also makes the president
commander-in-chief. Campbell interprets those provisions to mean
that if Congress declares war, it is then up to the president to
conduct that war.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Campbell admitted that most lawmakers
didn't want to take a position on the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot easier politically'' not to take a position, he
said. Lawmakers can say that if the war succeeded, they backed the
president, but if it didn't, they can say they saw defeat coming,
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is a man who thinks things through,'' House Majority
Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, said before the House votes. ``He is
very bright, and he is a man of what seems oftentimes to be
unbending resolve once he sets himself on a course.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-term congressman from San Jose is used to bucking the
leadership. In 1997 he was one of nine Republicans who refused to
vote to retain Newt Gingrich as House speaker after Gingrich
admitted breaking House ethics rules. Campbell, who holds a
doctorate in economics from the University of Chicago and a law
degree from Harvard, is a fiscal conservative but is pro-choice and
has voted in favor of gun control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He clerked for former Supreme Court Justice Byron White in the
late 1970s and worked for the Federal Trade Commission from 1981 to
1983 before becoming a Stanford law professor in 1983. He was
elected to Congress in 1988 and served two terms before running
unsuccessfully for the Senate in 1992. He returned to Congress in
1995 after former Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says he opposed the Vietnam War and the U.S.-led North
Atlantic Treaty Organization involvement in Kosovo because he views
them both as civil wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fault the president's intentions a bit,'' he says.
``But the Albanians are worse off after we started bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he insists he did not force the House vote on Kosovo policy
because of his own opposition to it. ``I really am coming at it
from the Constitution,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He and 16 other lawmakers also filed suit in a U.S. District
Court here on April 30 asking a judge to order Clinton to withdraw
troops or seek a declaration of war from Congress.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Presidents have argued that their role as commander-in-chief
allows them to send troops into battle without consulting Congress.
The 1973 War Powers Act was adopted in the waning days of the
Vietnam War as an effort to give lawmakers a greater say in
military conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The law says that unless U.S. troops are under attack, a
president must obtain congressional approval before deploying
troops. In an emergency, the president has 48 hours to consult with
Congress on the military deployment and must remove troops within
60 days if Congress does not declare war.
</P>
<P>
   But the law has not stopped presidents from sending U.S. troops
into conflicts including Ronald Reagan's invasion of Grenada in
1983, George Bush's deployment of troops to Panama in 1995 and
Clinton's interventions in Somalia in 1993 and Bosnia in 1995. Bush
did seek and receive permission from Congress to conduct the
Persian Gulf War in 1991, although the vote came after the troops
were already in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
