<SLUG> BC-RED-LIGHT-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY TEXAS MOTORISTS SEE RED, BUT RUN THE LIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (for release Sunday, May 9, 1999) 
 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In Dallas, unmarked cars are the chief weapon against
lawlessness. In suburban Arlington and Plano, undercover cops keep
an eye on high-crime venues. In suburban Richardson, special lights
mounted on poles signal police that offenses have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big problem,'' said Richardson Deputy Police Chief
Larry Zacharias, ``and we take it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Running red lights has become such a problem that for most of
the past year, police agencies in 27 cities and towns in the
Dallas-Fort Worth area have had special programs and units _
something like rolling SWAT teams and sting operations _ on the
streets to combat it.
</P>
<P>
   Scoffing at traffic lights is not just a North Texas phenomenon.
Across the country, police departments are considering a number of
extreme measures _ including installing cameras at key
intersections _ to control a problem which, according to U.S.
Department of Transportation estimates, causes 260,000 collisions
and 750 deaths each year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Greater Dallas Injury Prevention Center,
red-light running is the most common cause of injury accidents and,
Zacharias said, they are the most serious because ``you are
broadsiding another vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dangers, motorists increasingly are ignoring them.
In Dallas, according to police statistics, the number of accidents
caused by running red lights increased 22 percent from 1992 to 1996
and in 1997, that violation contributed to 2,000 accidents. At some
Richardson intersections, red-light violations have increased 50
percent in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   So prevalent is the practice, police said, that during rush hour
at some busy intersections the lights are run nearly every time
they change.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Richardson Police Department proposed a
coordinated crackdown throughout the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
Representatives of 27 police agencies, including some campus
police, signed on and adopted the slogan ``Red Still Means Stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, it is a motoring fundamental that many motorists seem
to have forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started in June,'' Zacharias said of the intensified
enforcement, ``and we wrote 7,000 tickets in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me,'' said Arlington Lt. Travis Moore, ``that
driving behavior has changed as much as it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlington's approach was to establish a squad of plainclothes
traffic cops who pose as surveyors at high-traffic intersections.
When a car runs a light, the ``surveyors'' write down the tag
number and radio it to a motorcycle officer a block down the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moore had no tally of the tickets that have resulted
from the program, he said it has appeared to lower the accident
rates at some intersections. It is not uncommon, he said, for
officers to issue 50 or 60 citations in a two-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, we're not even going after the ones who are close,'' he
said. ``We only stop the ones who are at least a car length out
when the light turns red.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people have complained about the use of undercover
cops, he said, but he thinks it is the only way to change driving
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will behave if they see a police car,'' he said, ``but
then they go back to their old ways when it is gone. We hope that
this will make them think about what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Nguyen, a 20-year-old college student, was one of those
who cried ``foul'' when he was caught by undercover officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, man, that's not right,'' he complained to the Arlington
Morning News. ``If you want to stop it (light running), have
somebody in a marked car stationed out there. If I saw a cop out
there, I wouldn't run a red light.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude, Moore said, is what the police department is
trying to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have to put an officer at every intersection,''
he said. ``That's why we put lights there.''
</P>
<P>
   Police in Plano are using a similar tactic, with officers in
plainclothes milling around intersections and posing as
construction workers or commuters waiting for a bus.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year the department has issued 3,092 tickets for red
light violations, double the number issued in the previous 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``People complain,'' said police spokesman Carl Duke. ``They
say, `Why are you out writing tickets? You should be arresting
criminals.' I have to explain that we should be writing tickets. We
have a traffic unit and that's their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas police have taken a broader approach by targeting other
symptoms of road rage or aggressive driving _ speeding, tailgating
and erratic lane changing _ as well as blowing through red lights.
</P>
<P>
   Called STARR (Strategic Targeting Against Road Rage), the
enforcement is carried out with the help of six blue Ford Crown
Victorias that cruise the major thoroughfares. The cars are
unmarked and equipped with red and blue strobe lights mounted on
the inside. The officers driving them, however, wear uniforms and
are prohibited from chasing violators.
</P>
<P>
   The cars were put into service last November and in the first
four months, officers operating them issued 11,164 citations _ an
increase of 8,800 over the number issued during the same period a
year earlier. There also were 540 fewer accidents on Dallas
streets, compared with the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of magic formulas,'' said police spokesman
John Leggio. ``You just get out there and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some police departments are experimenting with technological, if
not magical, formulas to supplement the unmarked cars and, perhaps,
replace the undercover officers.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington, Richardson and Plano and a few other cities have
installed white lights on traffic signal poles. When the light
changes to red, the white bulb, which can be observed by an officer
from any direction, flashes on, signaling to the officer that any
car subsequently crossing the intersection has run a red light.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras may be next. Richardson has tested a camera-monitoring
system at one intersection and the Dallas City Council's
Legislative Affairs Committee recently voiced support for
legislation that would permit photographing red-light runners and
issuing tickets to them by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Unmarked cars. Undercover cops. Electronic gadgets.
Surreptitious photography. Extreme measures, perhaps, but,
Richardson's Zacharias said, the public seems to support the effort
to curb dangerous drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had one complaint about our program,'' he said,
``except from those who have been caught.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
