r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MTV-RELEVANCE-840(2Ta     05-07 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-RELEVANCE-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WANT MY MTV ... LIKE IT USED TO BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, MTV held its ``I Wanna Be a VJ Too'' contest, the
winner of which earned a yearlong spot as an MTV VJ.
</P>
<P>
   This was a big deal, drawing 6,000 entrants in tryouts in Los
Angeles, New York and Chicago. The contestants were winnowed down,
like beauty-pageant entrants, to five finalists, who were tested on
their music knowledge, poise and stamina. Then viewers chose the
winner, Thalia D. DaCosta of Sunrise, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   DaCosta is 21, which means she would have been 3 or 4 when MTV
went on the air in August 1981. Back when MTV mattered _ or at
least mattered more.
</P>
<P>
   That the news media would even report the contest shows that
SOMEONE believes MTV matters, at least a little. But in the nearly
20 years since it reinvented music programming, leading to spinoffs
and competitors of varying size and clout, it has mattered less and
less.
</P>
<P>
   And that irrelevance is based on the same complaint MTV has been
drawing for nearly a decade _ that the music-video channel doesn't
play enough videos. A weekday of watching bore this out: From 8
a.m. to 2:30 p.m., only 12 videos aired. When videos returned at
2:30 with the countdown show ``Total Request Live,'' they were
abridged _ the better to make room for fan e-mails and
pronouncements (''Joey McIntire is so cute, I want him so bad
...''). Full-length videos didn't return till ``MTV Jams
Countdown'' _ that's right, another countdown show, this one
hip-hop based _ at 4:30.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of videos wouldn't be such a big deal, if it weren't
for three things: 1) Most of MTV's original programming is mediocre
at best; 2) other music-TV networks either have better original
programming or play more videos; and 3) the vast majority of music
videos that MTV does air are pretty dull, and consist largely of
the Top 40 fare that diminishes the channel's cutting-edge
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   So why would people still want their MTV? Consider the recent
``I Was an MTV VJ Too,'' a brief documentary about MTV's late-'80s
VJs that had a nostalgia factor yanked from the subconscious (who
even remembers Kevin Seal?). This was the most interesting nonmusic
show seen on MTV in recent weeks; nothing like seeing Daisy Fuentes
in her pre-MTV days, as a big-haired weatherwoman on a
Spanish-language TV station in New York. It was also a rare
instance in which MTV beat another music network at its own game.
</P>
<P>
   That network is VH1, MTV's boomer-friendly sister channel, the
second-most popular video network with an estimated 62.4 million
``subscribers'' (MTV has an estimated 68 million, but
``subscribers'' don't equal ``viewers''). VH1 went on the air in
1985, playing distressingly middle-of-the-road adult-contemporary
videos before going through a series of phases: ``adult
alternative'' (pre-fame Shawn Colvin), MTV's greatest hits (an
early-'90s love affair with video's early-'80s heyday), and, in its
latest and best incarnation, the pop-culture channel.
</P>
<P>
   Like MTV, VH1 has steered away from just playing videos. Nobody
complains, though, because VH1's original programming is almost
unfailingly entertaining: ``Pop-Up Video,'' a
much-imitated-never-matched mix of factoids and snarky commentary,
led the revolution, which now includes a seemingly endless supply
of ``Where Are They Now'' and ``Before They Were Rock Stars''
programs. These are watchable at worst, addictive at best. MTV's
efforts to imitate them, such as ``BIOrhythm,'' have yet to catch
on, perhaps because in the quick-turnover world of late-'90s pop
music, nobody's around long enough to HAVE a biography. How much of
a life story could the Backstreet Boys have compared to, say,
Fleetwood Mac?
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   The day of MTV-watching _ the one that included a dozen videos
between 8 a.m. and 2:30 p.m. _ included original programming like
this: ``Station Zero,'' a hip-hop cartoon that's a poorly animated,
poorly written hybrid of ``Fat Albert'' and ``Beavis and
Butt-head.'' An hour (two episodes) of ``FANatic,'' in which
obsessed fans get to meet and interview the stars they idolize. A
half-hour Drew Barrymore special. And THREE hours (six episodes) of
``Road Rules,'' just in case you needed to catch up with the antics
of a bunch of squabbling, self-absorbed twentysomethings crammed
into an RV traveling through Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   This, from a network that says it's renewing its commitment to
music programming. There is music programming on MTV, generally
from 1 to 5 a.m., as well as on the Sunday-night show ``120
Minutes,'' the network's last connection with anything resembling
cutting-edge.
</P>
<P>
   You can't totally blame MTV for its long-lasting identity crisis
because, frankly, most music videos today are pretty bland. Last
year brought only one potential classic _ Garbage's bizarro clip
for ``Push It.'' The '90s as a whole have given us few knockouts
(the Beastie Boys' ``Sabotage,'' Soundgarden's ``Black Hole Sun,''
Beck's ``Loser''). And even the best current videos _
``Girlfriend/Boyfriend'' by BLACKstreet and Janet Jackson, ``Why
Don't You Get a Job?'' by the Offspring, ``Freak on a Leash'' by
Korn _ can't hold a candle to earlier '90s entries, much less such
'80s classics as Peter Gabriel's ``Sledgehammer.''
</P>
<P>
   Which could be why networks that air more videos haven't caught
on. MuchMusic, a Canadian music channel, aired for about a year on
Arlington's TCI Digital Cable before vanishing at the beginning of
this month; Matt Fleury, a Denver-based TCI spokesman, says
MuchMusic was taken out of digital-cable packaging. Too bad;
MuchMusic looked like early MTV with its mix of videos and
concerts, and it actually played artists ``you might not have heard
of.'' MTV's spinoff, M2, does plays music videos 24-7, but it's
only available on satellite, and an hour of watching its heavily
mixed bag (much of which can be seen on MTV or VH1) can help you
understand why MTV drifted from all-video programming.
</P>
<P>
   On the country side of the clicker, upstart Great American
Country is mounting an assault against 16-year-old Country Music
Television. GAC, which went on the air nationwide in September
1996, boasts that it plays 400 more videos a week than its
competitors, along with fewer commercials. CMT airs more videos
than most music channels, but also takes the VH1/MTV route of
airing nonvideo programming.
</P>
<P>
   Although country videos are often more slow-paced and soft-focus
than their pop counterparts, clips by Montgomery Gentry and Shane
Minor revealed a strong MTV influence, with rapid cutting and, in
Minor's case, dancing girls.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the way in which MTV still matters most _ as an
influence. Without it, the existence of the other video networks
(or heavy video programming on such channels as Black Entertainment
Network and the Nashville Network) would be unlikely. During its 18
years, MTV has filtered into advertising, radio-station programming
and movies (such as last fall's busy ``Belly,'' directed by video
auteur Hype Williams).
</P>
<P>
   But MTV has become stagnant, despite the occasional timely news
report (the recent teen-violence documentary ``Warning Signs''
received some strong reviews in the wake of the Littleton, Colo.,
high school massacre) or guilty pleasure along the lines of
``Beavis and Butt-head'' and the late-night call-in advice show
``Loveline.''
</P>
<P>
   As the channel reaches adulthood, it's having a harder time
being groundbreaking. The incessant airing of its ``Real World''
and ``Road Rules'' series betrays a dearth of original-programming
ideas. If you can find the videos, though, the network can give you
a crash course in surface pop culture. Want to know why people are
yakking about Eminem and Ricky Martin? Tune in to ``Total Request
Live'' for an hour a week, and don't surf away during the
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But it shouldn't take that much effort; you shouldn't have to
check a TV book to find out when the pioneer video-music channel is
playing videos. If you want anything of any depth, you're going to
have to make an extra effort and do some research. But if you just
want a quick cross section of what's out there, MTV may be for you.
It might be a good idea, however, to watch much of it with the
picture off.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot writes on pop culture for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
