<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-0508-C     05-07 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBANIA TO TAKE UP TO 1 MILLION MORE REFUGEES, BUT WANTS THEM
RELOCATED
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The Albanian government pledged Friday to take
in fully one million Kosovar refugees, more than double the number
it has sheltered so far, as neighboring Macedonia readied to begin
transferring tens of thousands of refugees who fled there.
</P>
<P>
   The first 6,000 ethnic Albanians from Yugoslavia are expected to
leave Macedonia on Sunday, according to Dennis McNamara, the
special envoy of the United Nations refugee agency. They will be
followed by others into southeastern Albania around the city of
Korce.
</P>
<P>
   McNamara, who visited here briefly Friday on a tour of the
region, also stressed that Kosovars in this crowded border area
must get ready to evacuate immediately.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say they would be forced to leave now, but made it
clear that failure to clear this militarily volatile area will lead
to the closure of tent camps sheltering more than 30,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't close the tents on top of the refugees, but we will
use every method we can to persuade them to move,'' he said. ``We
are going to tell them that at a certain point, these camps will
not be there. The services they currently enjoy will not be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Under increasing pressure from the Albanian government to move
the Kosovars south, the United National High Commissioner for
Refugees said for the first time this week that it may be forced to
simply shut down the camps.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of cross-border attacks from Serb-controlled
Yugoslavia is a main reason both the government and the UN want the
refugees here to relocate. Besides the possibility of a tent camp
being hit, authorities fear the shelling of a road or bridge could
cut off access to this area and leave more than 100,000 refugees --
plus local residents -- without access to food or other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   About 70,000 refugees are staying in private homes or camping on
their own in this region.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government also fears social and political
problems, as well as the potential of disease and deprivation as
summer approaches and the heavily taxed water supply diminishes by
two-thirds of the present capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to take in as many as one million refugees came as
neighboring Macedonia demanded that other nations help lift the
burden of about 200,000 ethnic Albanians who fled there from
Yugoslavia. Macedonia is a fragile mix of ethnic groups, and
leaders have said they fear the heavy addition of Albanians will
dislodge the tenuous balance.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Macedonian authorities continued to choke off the
refugee flow at the Kosovo border, forcing hundreds of Kosovars
fleeing Serb troops to find more treacherous mountain routes across
a harsh frontier dotted with land mines, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of increasing refugee flow, the regular border
points were nearly deserted. Only people with Macedonian passports
or travel papers were allowed across at Blace, 12 miles northwest
of the capital of Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   The few people who managed to cross said there were 300 to 400
people on the other side of the border in the town of Djeneral
Jankovic. The refugees there were reportedly huddled outside in a
persistent drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cash-poor Albania already has accepted more than
400,000 refugees, so has agreed to more than double the numbers. In
the last several days the volume of refugees crossing the border
here has diminished, but relief officials believe new waves could
come at any time if the Serb authorities in charge in Kosovo allow
more to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, the Kosovo Liberation Army held a news
conference in which KLA leaders said conditions in some parts of
Kosovo are becoming critical. Spokesman Gani Syla said some areas
are almost totally without food, and called for a humanitarian
corridor through which relief supplies could be sent to civilians
remaining there.
</P>
<P>
   The guerilla separatist group, which has been fighting for
Kosovo's independence from Yugoslavia, also said its doctors claim
Serb forces have used chemical weapons and nerve gas, which
resulted in the deaths of two young boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia is making Kosovo and its people live as though in
prehistoric times,'' Syla said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
