<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8540 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUPLE-SLAIN-$ADV9-HN     05-07 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLE-SLAIN-$ADV9-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO SENSE' TO SLEDGEHAMMER SLAYING OF SMALL-TOWN MINISTER, WIFE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (for release Sunday, May 9, 1999) 
 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Texas _ Grieving members of the Weimar United Church of
Christ, fighting back tears, stooped under a hot sun and planted
rows of bright flowers in the church courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if those who loved and cared for the Rev. Norman
``Skip'' Sirnic and his wife, Karen, hoped the simple beauty of
flowers would overpower the dark and confusing horror of their
unsolved murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense, but violence never does,'' said Mark
Sirnic, a 44-year-old minister from Colorado and Skip Sirnic's
younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   The murders of Sirnic, 46, and his wife Karen, 47, have brought
fear, confusion and sadness to this hamlet of 2,052 residents
nestled in the rolling hills 90 miles west of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Sirnics were bludgeoned to death with a sledgehammer
as they lay in bed last weekend, violent crime was almost unknown
in this picture postcard community established by German and Czech
settlers in the 1870s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty crime-free little town, until this thing
happened,'' said longtime mayor Bennie Kosler, owner of Bennie's
Cafe on Mechanic Street. ``It just leaves the whole town in
shock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it is someone local,'' the mayor added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a week of extensive investigation by police in Weimar,
with help from Texas Rangers and the county sheriff, no arrests
have been made nor any suspects identified, Police Chief Bill
Livingston acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't have anything new,'' he said. The Sirnics'
1998 red Mazda pickup, with Texas license 2DK-J47, had not been
found as of late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said an intruder broke into the rear of the couple's
home, a parsonage behind the United Church of Christ, and attacked
the couple with a sledgehammer. The mayor said that whoever broke
in used a glass cutter, and found a sledgehammer in a cabinet or
storeroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Weimar Mercury reported that the murder weapon was found
leaning against a wall in the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   And while police first noticed only a few possessions missing _
a VCR, video games and their truck _ Livingston said a check with
family members has now lengthened the list and added to its value.
Family members say some jewelry was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have discovered other things missing,'' the chief said,
declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The couple was last seen on Friday, April 30, and their pickup
was missing from the carport early Saturday morning and has not
been located. Church officials, alarmed when Sirnic and his wife,
the church secretary, did not appear at services last Sunday, May
2, went to the parsonage and found them in bed and beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   One resident, who asked not to be named, theorized that a
stranger hitching a ride on a freight train would have passed
within yards of the parsonage since it is next to the rail line. It
would have been easy to hop off a freight train and walk up to the
home, the resident said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a 35-hour head start and could have been out of the
country before anybody knew what happened,'' the resident said.
</P>
<P>
   With few clues, friends and family are left to wonder who killed
the popular couple, and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to figure any kind of motive and you know, we
don't know of anyone who had a sour relationship with them. He was
one of the good guys, a golden boy,'' said Mark Sirnic, the
minister's brother. ``At this church, ministers do not make a lot
of money. They did not have many material possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless it was someone who had no clue as to what was in the
house and was just randomly hitting some house.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew the Sirnics describe them as an energetic,
compassionate, well-educated and intelligent couple who had
dedicated themselves to bettering the communities of Weimar and
neighboring New Bielau. In addition to his duties at the 375-member
Weimar United Church _ established in November 1988 _ Sirnic was
also pastor at the Trinity Evangelical Lutheran Church in New
Bielau, a small community eight miles south of Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   Sirnic, born in Pennsylvania, moved to Texas in 1964, graduating
as valedictorian of his class at Friona High School in 1970. He
graduated with honors from Trinity University in San Antonio, and
studied for the ministry at Vanderbilt Divinity School. He was
ordained in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and church members in Weimar and New Bielau describe
Skip Sirnic as a down-to-earth man who did not preach to his
congregation, but rather engaged them in conversations about God.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very humble man, and just funny as all get out. He
had a wonderful sense of humor,'' said Helen Boysen, a member of
the Lutheran congregation in New Bielau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost as if he talked with us about God and the Bible
and the way the Bible instructs us to live. He brought the Bible
alive for us, truly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since Sirnic and his wife came to Weimar and New
Bielau, both churches flourished and gained members.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Sirnic, a native of Bryan, Texas, earned degrees in
biochemistry from Texas A&AMP;M University, and was still conducting
research at A&AMP;M, the family said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, she became church secretary, sang in the choir, was
president of the Weimar Literary Guild and a member of the town's
garden club. She also oversaw a church youth program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I can tell you other than it's such a shame
the community lost these two kids and the work they could do,''
said Anna Belle Mohr, the mother of the slain minister. ``They both
loved the community _ he loved both communities he served.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, more than 1,200 people attended a memorial service
for the Sirnics at the Weimar United Church, and plans are under
way to erect a memorial garden to the slain couple in the city
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable that this has happened,'' said Boysen, who
moved with her husband to New Bielau from San Antonio two years
ago. ``It's such an innocent community.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
