<SLUG> BC-HEARST-ARGYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST-ARGYLE TELEVISION REPORTS RESULTS FOR FIRST QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc. on Friday announced
operating results for the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On a GAAP-reported basis, revenues for the three months grew
nearly 30 percent, to $113.4 million; broadcast cash flow (station
operating income, plus depreciation and amortization, plus
amortization of program rights, minus program payments) grew 33.5
percent, to $45.0 million.
</P>
<P>
   After-tax cash flow (income before extraordinary item, plus
depreciation and amortization), a key financial measurement for
broadcast companies, grew nearly 30 percent to $19.1 million, or
$0.33 per share. Income applicable to common stockholders was $2.5
million, or $0.04 per share.
</P>
<P>
   In order to provide ``same-station'' comparable results, the
company also presented pro forma results including all its current
stations as though the company had owned all the stations on Jan. 1
of each year.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle completed its acquisition of the Sacramento,
Calif., properties of Kelly Broadcasting last Jan. 5, and of the
Pulitzer Broadcasting stations on March 18.
</P>
<P>
   On a pro forma basis for the quarter, revenues grew 2.3 percent,
to $161.5 million; broadcast cash flow rose 3.1 percent to $63.6
million; and after-tax cash flow grew 1.4 percent, to $29.7 million
or $0.33 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Loss per common share on a pro forma basis narrowed to $(0.01),
from $(0.03) in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really hit the ground running after completing the
Pulitzer Broadcasting acquisition in March,'' said Bob Marbut,
Hearst-Argyle Television chairman and co-chief executive officer.
``Significantly, we had our seventh consecutive quarter of cash
flow margin improvement and after-tax cash flow growth on both a
GAAP and pro forma basis.''
</P>
<P>
   John G. Conomikes, Hearst-Argyle Television president and
co-chief executive officer, said the second quarter looks like ``it
could be below last year's very strong second quarter.'' He cited
some softness in national advertising categories, continued ratings
pressure at ABC and very difficult ratings comparisons for NBC,
which had the Seinfeld finale in last year's second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding this slow start to the first half, preliminary
indications for the third quarter are for solid growth,'' Conomikes
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
