<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 9, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA-REVIEW (Undated) _ A bold, if impractical,
question is just now beginning to be formulated: Is it finally time
for outside powers to crush Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
to make the effort necessary to cure a national psychosis inside
Serbia that has been destabilizing a corner of Europe for a decade?
Put another way, has the time come for NATO to do in Serbia what
the Allies did in Germany and Japan after World II? By Blaine
Harden. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SHOOTING-REVIEW (Washington) _ If there is anything left to
be said about the tragedy in Littleton, Colo., it may be this: the
cold, hard reality of the school massacre is that it was the
statistical equivalent of the proverbial needle in a haystack. And,
precisely because such events are so rare, and because it is
impossible to eliminate risk from life, there may be no larger
lessons to draw, and no way to prevent another one. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   NEWSMEDIA-DEATHS-REVIEW (Atlanta) _ The news media's philosophy
appears to be that while people may be created equal, they do not
necessarily die that way. On the swiftly calculated sliding scale
of death, disasters are assigned a news value based not on how many
lives were lost, but on how and where they happened to die. A
recent Arkansas boating accident that killed 13 people received far
less coverage than events that claimed a comparable number of
lives, such as an Amtrak crash or Colorado school shooting. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-POLITICS-REVIEW (San Francisco) _ It's a bad time to be
on death row. Politicians win points _ and votes _ by wearing the
tough-on-crime banner. In this environment, granting clemency has
become an act of courage that requires an outlay of political
capital few governors are willing to spend. In the current
political climate, clemency is nearly impossible. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-DOSTOYEVSKY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Among the problems to be
addressed or evaded in the coming report by the National Gambling
Impact Study Commission is the problem gambler. Some of the most
vivid accounts of gambling addiction in world literature come from
Fyodor Mikhailovich Dostoyevsky, who for miserable years was an
unregenerate roulette punter in the casinos of Germany. By Walter
Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-CRUELTY-REVIEW (Undated) _ For cats, dogs and other
animals, life in the movies is beginning to appear less than
glamorous. At this historical juncture of political correctness and
feeling the pain of others, pretending to hurt animals has become
an intentional laugh-getter in movies, TV and advertising. By
Douglas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The U.S.
military-literary-industrial complex is gathering might with the
surprising success of new books that portray modern warriors as
complex heroes who confront enemies and their own mistakes with a
mixture of courage and fear. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SCOUT-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Baseball scouting reports:
soft hands, bat-breaking kinks and other intimations of
immortality. Excerpts from scouting reports filed on players while
they were unknown amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EUROPE-JOBLESS (Undated) _ Europe's cradle-to-grave safety
net means not only that being out of work has become a viable way
of making a living, but that there is no longer much stigma
attached to joblessness. That goes a long way in explaining the
contrast between America's current jobs boom and the contrasting
jobs bust in Europe. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-DIVISIONS-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ Such depictions of Israeli
society as an aggregate of groups, not individuals, reflect the
hardening of social divisions here in recent years. More than ever,
Israelis view each other as members of ideological, religious or
ethnic sub-units, rather than as one society with shared values. By
Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-REVIEW (Podgorica) _ Montenegro is unusually
hospitable to foreign journalists because the tiny republic is in
big trouble. Its new, Western-leaning government has all but pulled
out of the Yugoslav federation with Serbia. The Montenegrin
government is bending over backwards for foreign journalists
because it cannot allow the state-controlled Serbian media to
present the only images of what is actually happening. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
