<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   An inch of snow coated the lowlands near Seattle on Friday, as a
deep layer of unseasonably chilly air over Alaska was discharged
southward into the Pacific Northwest. As the potent May sun heats
the lower atmosphere Saturday, vigorous currents of air will ascend
into the cold air, causing clouds and isolated afternoon
thunderstorms to form.
</P>
<P>
   Spotty afternoon thundershowers will also erupt over the
northern Rockies, along the leading edge of the advancing cold air.
Meanwhile, generally sunny and warm conditions will cover the
southern Rockies and Southwest with afternoon readings reaching 100
degrees near the California-Arizona border.
</P>
<P>
   Residual moisture behind departing low pressure will cause
clouds and spotty showers to linger across the central and western
Great Lakes Saturday. Daytime readings beneath the thick cloud
cover will be about 10 degrees cooler than average.
</P>
<P>
   A compact jet stream disturbance will cross the interior
Northeast, sparking a thin zone of showers and thunderstorms over
Pennsylvania and New York. The fast-moving system will cause any
precipitation that occurs to be brief, though small hail and gusty
winds will accompany a few of the storms.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy and cool weather will persist near the Northeast seaboard
with spotty light rain and drizzle. Brighter conditions will return
to the region Sunday. The Southeast will be partly to mostly sunny
with lower humidity than in recent days. Thunderstorms will speckle
parts of Florida Saturday as a weak front interacts with sultry
air.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Double Record
</P>
<P>
   A weather event as rare as a triple play in baseball occurred in
Orlando, Fla., on Thursday. The mercury rose to a record 94
degrees, tying the previous maximum set in 1984. A thunderstorm
then deposited 1.21 inches of rain at the airport, marking the
wettest May 6 ever in the city. Typically, the hottest places are
also the driest. However, in a maritime climate such as on the
Florida peninsula, extreme temperatures also produce active sea
breezes. The meeting of the Atlantic and Gulf breezes near Orlando
resulted in potent thunderstorms, one of which rained itself out at
the airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-FLOWERS-NYT &LR;      05-07 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-FLOWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWER INDUSTRY IN COLOMBIA GROWS INTO A BIG BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Wash.) (rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUAYMARAL, Colombia _ The Acuarela flower farm here grows
nothing but roses of every hue, and Thursday morning workers were
rushing to fill the last Mother's Day orders from American clients.
</P>
<P>
   They snipped, chilled and bundled thousands of delicate buds
just starting to bloom, then quickly trucked them to the Bogota
airport for a three-hour flight to Miami and next-day delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when places like this were simple rustic
operations, but we have been transformed into an industry, and an
ever more competitive one at that,'' said Maria Eugenia Ramirez,
general manager of this 33-acre farm north of the Colombian
capital. ``Before a big holiday like this one or St. Valentine's
Day, we process more than 35,000 roses a day, a scale that would
have been unthinkable when our industry was born.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country plagued by narcotics trafficking and guerrilla war,
the flower export business is a rare success story. Exploiting
advances in transportation and refrigeration and its proximity to
the world's largest consumer market, Colombia has surpassed
California as the principal supplier of roses, carnations,
chrysanthemums and other popular blooms to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 30 years ago a flower export industry did not exist here.
Today, two-thirds of all the fresh-cut flowers sold in the United
States are grown in Colombia, making this South American country
the biggest flower exporter beside the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Colombian flower producers earned $555 million from
exports, 80 percent of which went to the United States or Canada.
Exports have grown by more than 50 percent since 1992, helping to
make Miami International Airport the world's second-busiest cargo
destination, with an average of 30,000 boxes of Colombian flowers
arriving there daily.
</P>
<P>
   But now that success appears to be ushering in consolidation.
Colombia's achievements have not only encouraged Ecuador, Israel,
India, Kenya and Zimbabwe to expand flower-export operations, but
have caught the attention of multinational companies that want a
foothold here.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest sign of a new era is the arrival of Dole Food here.
In recent months, the American food giant has bought four of
Colombia's largest and most successful flower growers, which
account for about 25 percent of production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrival of a multinational with such a vast experience
with perishable products has meant a fundamental change for our
industry,'' said Felipe Ramirez, president of the board of the
Flower Exporter's Association of Colombia. ``We know this means an
increase in competition, that smaller producers are going to have
to seek alliances, but we think this is a healthy development that
will awaken demand and make us more innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dole has remained a passive owner. But Jose Maria de la
Torre, founder of Florex SA, a company Dole purchased last fall,
said that ``it is just a question of time before they take the
other leap'' and begin to merge their acquisitions here and utilize
their growing, refrigeration and distribution expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not know flower technology, but it's not Greek to
them, and some of what they know from other areas can probably be
applied to our industry,'' de la Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The distribution end of the business, in which Colombian
producers also play an important role, is undergoing a similar
transformation. More than a half-dozen large flower importers in
the United States in which Colombian growers held interests have
been sold to USA Floral Products, a company with $1 billion in
annual sales formed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Poiret, USA Floral's chief executive officer, called its
role in relation to Dole ``more complementary than competitive.''
He did not rule out the possibility of buying farms here, but made
it clear that his focus now was on what he called ``the front end
of the train rather than the source.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombian growers have a product that is of exceptional
quality when it is cut from the stem,'' Poiret said in a telephone
interview from USA Floral's Washington headquarters. The challenge,
he said, is to minimize the time it takes to get fresh flowers to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That is important to producers here because more flowers are
available and yet, according to industry studies, only a quarter of
American families bought flowers last year, spending an average of
$25 a person. In Europe, 60 percent of families bought flowers,
spending an average of $41 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Producers here have also spent years fighting a complaint filed
by growers in California accusing the Colombians of dumping, or
selling flowers at below cost to increase their market share. The
Colombians have denied the accusation, but a tentative settlement
was negotiated earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The accord calls for Colombian flower growers to pay at least
$7.5 million over the next 30 months into a fund that will create
advertisements urging Americans to buy more flowers. ``It's an
opportunity to spend money on something that will benefit all of us
who are growers instead of fighting each other and spending our
money on lawyers,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
