<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-UNICORN-REVIEW-NYT     05-07 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UNICORN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUNT FOR THE UNICORN KILLER': UNSUCCESSFUL RETELLING OF TRAGIC
TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer'' distills real events into a
grim inversion of ``Beauty and the Beast.'' This time, even
unconditional love cannot transform the beast's dark soul. Just as
sadly, the filmmakers' unconditional effort cannot overcome the
limitations imposed by both the source material and the
inflexibility of the network movie form.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the gap between the two parts of this NBC
mini-series is far more than 24 hours. The drama begins Sunday
night by offering memorably drawn characters. But the most
compelling among them, the tragic beauty, must die just before the
11 o'clock news. And viewers who return for Monday night's
conclusion are in for a letdown as the story drifts on for the
requisite two more hours.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it must be quickly added that the film displays some
first-rate work: by the director, William A. Graham; the writer,
Bruce Graham (they're not related), and a cast that includes Tom
Skerritt and Naomi Watts. They all keep a complicated and often
bleak story moving forward, engaging both the mind and the heart.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of that story are well known. Holly Maddux (played by
Ms. Watts), a bright, rebellious Bryn Mawr College graduate from
Tyler, Texas, vanished in 1977. The disappearance solidified her
conservative family's deep distrust of Ira Einhorn (Kevin
Anderson), the counterculture activist with whom Holly had lived in
Philadelphia for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Holly had told her sister Meg (Kellie Overbey) that she was
planning to leave Einhorn. But his carefully tended reputation as a
guru of nonviolence helped shield him from suspicion until 1979,
when an investigator hired by Holly's father, Fred Maddux (
Skerritt), persuaded the Philadelphia authorities to search
Einhorn's apartment. The police found Holly's body there, locked in
a trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with murder, Einhorn maintained his innocence, blaming a
nutty-sounding government conspiracy aimed at discrediting him.
Awaiting trial, he was freed on bail and fled the country. In 1993
he was convicted in absentia and sentenced to life. He remains in
France and continues to fight extradition.
</P>
<P>
   The script compresses and rearranges some of the details but
stays within sight of the facts as laid out in the book ``The
Unicorn's Secret,'' by Steven Levy, a writer and editor at
Newsweek. Einhorn, whose name means one horn in German, sometimes
referred to himself as the Unicorn. The television people
needlessly inflated the book's title; only a small part of the film
depicts the hunt for Einhorn after he went on the lam.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's Holly and Ira are painted as polar opposites. She
glows with life (and an unlikely shade of platinum-blond hair). Her
eyes sparkle with intelligence, but they cannot see through this
dark, hairy boor. As he seduces her, he boasts that being so famous
aids his work. ``What  &UR; is  &LR; your work?'' she asks. ``Enlightening
the planet,'' he announces.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptually, this Ira is a problem. Although you are told that
he is widely respected by rich industrialists, top universities and
even senior police officials as well as some leftover hippies, all
you ever  &UR; see &LR;  is a self-important jerk. The film, made with the
blessing of the Maddux family and the man who prosecuted the murder
case, is quite emphatic on this point. Anderson, appearing in
``Death of a Salesman'' on Broadway, is not permitted to find any
hints of goodness in his beast. That may make for accurate
reporting and for a kind of justice by television, but it stifles
the drama.
</P>
<P>
   The other cast members are given more room to maneuver, and they
use it to good advantage. Ms. Watts is a sympathetic Holly.
Skerritt, in another variation on the craggy, loving father, totes
his pain believably.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the supporting players hit just the right notes of
humanity, among them Ms. Overbey, whose character grows up in the
story's margins; Ruben Santiago-Hudson as a police detective, and
Martin Donovan as the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Their work is hardly in vain. But having chosen to lavish such
obvious effort on a tale that still sadly has no end and having to
let that tale unfold in precisely timed network morsels, the
storytellers are ultimately defeated.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE HUNT FOR THE UNICORN KILLER
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday and Monday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 4 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Directed by William A. Graham; written by Bruce Graham, based on
the book ``The Unicorn's Secret'' by Steven Levy; Scott White,
producer; Ralf Bode, director of photography; Drake Silliman,
editor. A Dan Wigutow Production in association with Regency
Television for NBC. Dan Wigutow, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Kevin Anderson (Ira Einhorn), Tom Skerritt (Fred Maddux),
Naomi Watts (Holly Maddux), Brian Kerwin (Saul Lapidus), Martin
Donovan (Richard DiBenedetto), Kellie Overbey (Meg Maddux), Kristin
Booth (Buffy Maddux), Wanda Cannon (Liz Maddux), Angela Vint (Mary
Maddux), Kirby Morrow (John Maddux), Susan Coyne (Sandra Rothman),
Albert Schultz (Lucas Rothman) and Ruben Santiago-Hudson (Jake
Newhouse). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
