u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     05-07 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORITES IN SECTORS THAT ARE NOW IN FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No party lasts a lifetime, but since early November investors in
technology shares of a variety of stripes have been in full boogie
mode.
</P>
<P>
   From a 52-week low on Nov. 6 until April 9, its most recent
peak, Morgan Stanley's High-Tech 35 Index gained more than 64
percent; many Internet stocks performed far better. The index has
since cooled a bit, as money has moved into more staid _ and
cheaper _ cyclicals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, through Friday, the index remained 47 percent above its
November low. And Morgan Stanley's on-line brokerage unit is still
running television ads of adolescents with their own helicopters
and tow-truck operators who own islands. Or is it countries? The
ads don't seem to be aimed at those who buy stocks for the dividend
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Charles A. Morris, who has managed the $5.8 billion T. Rowe
Price Science and Technology fund since 1991, took some time last
week to talk about the sector and the possibility of a tech wreck. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)People have been talking about a major correction in
technology for some time. Is what we are seeing now the start of
that, or is it the beginning of something else?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think the rotation we are seeing indicates an end to
the technology cycle, because technology reinvents itself every
decade.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, it was automation of the back office and
deployment of mainframe and minicomputers. In the 1990s, it has
been personal computers and cellular. Now, the industry is
reinventing itself to Internet-work computing. Since these things
tend to run in 10-year waves, arguably this particular cycle is
just beginning. The real question is what happens over the very
near term, because we have come a little too far, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Technology funds are about 100 percent off the lows established
last fall. Over the last 12 to 15 years it hasn't gotten much
better than that without a correction of around 15 percent. That
thins out the herd and sets the stage for the next leg up.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tech stocks tend to do better in the fall and
winter months than they do between April Fool's Day and Halloween.
And Y2K is another complicating factor, because it may lead to a
slowdown in spending in summer and early fall. Lastly, you have to
look at some of the froth in the market, most specifically in the
Internet sector.
</P>
<P>
   So all of that has to give you pause over the next three to six
months. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What about Internet stocks? Aren't they likely be
the hardest hit in the sector?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You are already seeing signs that the Internet market is
starting to tire. Amazon.com made a series of announcements
recently that three months ago would have sent its stock up 30
percent. This time, the stock fell.
</P>
<P>
   You have seen some initial public offerings that have been
mediocre performers. Indeed, Comps.com, which was priced on
Tuesday, finished below the offering price when it traded on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If you can get a meaningful correction of 30 percent to 50
percent across the Internet space, the market capitalization of
these stocks will start to represent economic reality and encourage
institutional ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years, the median return for the Internet
group is going to be negative. But a small minority of those stocks
will put up terrific valuations that make today's valuations look
low. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What is a realistic way to value Internet companies
that have no earnings?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Wall Street has everyone fixated on a ratio of price to
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't like that, and for the last six weeks we have been
using what we think is a more practical valuation method, which
starts with the multiple of revenues relative to a company's market
capitalization. Once you get that number, then divide it by the
target net margin a company aspires to in the future. This method
allows you to compare stocks within the Internet stocks as well as
to more traditional companies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)How much of an individual's portfolio should be
invested in this sector?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. People should have anywhere from 5 percent to 15 percent of
their financial assets in this class. The more money they have to
lose, the greater the percentage can be. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Have you been raising cash in anticipation of a
blowoff?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Typically, between 3 percent and 7 percent of our fund's
assets are in cash. Right now we are on the high side. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Which stocks do you like?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We run a fairly balanced portfolio by sector. Five sectors
comprise 80 percent of the fund's assets: software, communications
equipment and services, hardware, semiconductors and information
services.
</P>
<P>
   Our three largest positions are PSInet, a business Internet
service provider, America Online and Softbank, which I think of as
a closed-end mutual fund for Internet holdings. Our favorite holds
include MCI Worldcom, Airtouch Communications, Xilinx, Adobe
Systems, Ascend and Cisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
