</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has been in the department's legal gun sights for
years. At an antitrust trial due to resume later this month,
government lawyers have argued that the software giant has sought
to extend its huge market power over personal computers to the
Internet and other emerging domains, like the ones that AT&AMP;T wants
to carve out. For its part, AT&AMP;T says it will also offer other
operating systems in its set-top machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we're headed is toward a new oligopoly,'' said Mark
Cooper, research director for Consumers Union, a Washington
advocacy group that strongly opposes the AT&AMP;T deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we'll be left with something like a Ma Bell East
and a Ma Bell West and a Ma Bell Cable. The sad part is that the
Clinton administration, by approving the early concentration of the
Baby Bells, has no intellectual leverage left to stop it,'' he
added
</P>
<P>
   The Baby Bells, which need to match AT&AMP;T's torrid pace in
rolling out video services and other high-speed technology, may
seek regulatory relief or court rulings to right what they regard
