<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR SAYS REGULATORS TO PROBE WEST COAST GAS PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Calling it the strongest response yet to her
quest for lower gas prices on the West Coast, Sen. Barbara Boxer
said the Federal Trade Commission has assured her it is
investigating the recent surge in the cost of gasoline in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission is thoroughly investigating pricing activities
in those markets to determine whether recent increases were in
whole or in part the result of anticompetitive conduct,'' said FTC
Chairman Robert Pitofsky in a letter to the California Democrat
dated May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said he could not comment on the details of the
investigation, but he confirmed that staff members were examining
the impact that two proposed mergers _ Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp.,
and BP/Amoco PLC with Atlantic Richfield Co. _ could have on
competition in the industry, particularly in California where gas
demand and prices are high.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky is being helped by attorneys general in 21 states,
including California's Bill Lockyer.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency is ``mindful of ARCO's importance in
California,'' Pitofsky wrote, ``and expect that our investigation
will pay particular attention to the potential impact of the
transaction on retail gasoline prices and other aspects of
competition in California and other western states.''
</P>
<P>
   While the response may seem guarded, Boxer said it ended the
``deafening silence'' she has received from the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This letter has given me tremendous assurance,'' she said. ``I
look at it, frankly, as a breakthrough. Up to this point, we were
not able to get anything back from the FTC other than some vague
oral statements.''
</P>
<P>
   California drivers are paying as much as $2 a gallon for premium
gasoline in some spots.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer asked the FTC a year ago for investigation into why gas
prices in California, particularly in the San Francisco and San
Diego areas, were so much higher than in the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In March, when prices skyrocketed as much as 50 percent in the
San Francisco area, Boxer asked the FTC to require gas companies
seeking merger approval to reserve a portion of their fuel to sell
to independent marketers and refineries at fair market prices.
</P>
<P>
   The independents are not affiliated with major oil companies, so
they are free to buy from any source. They often buy excess gas
from the big companies at a discount and pass the savings on to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In Pitofsky's letter, he noted that sources of supply to
independent gas stations have been an antitrust concern for many
years. He pointed out a 1981 Court of Appeals decision in which the
court upheld a ruling blocking the merger of Marathon Oil Co. with
Mobil, based partly on the potential for less gas being available
to the independent sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer took that citation as a positive sign: ``I was glad that
he seems to feel, without directly saying so, that aspect _ giving
a sure supply to the independents _ is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Anita Mangeles, spokeswoman for the Western States Petroleum
Association, wasn't fazed by the FTC's response. ``This is nothing
new. Senator Boxer requested this investigation about a year ago,
and it's still ongoing,'' said Mangeles, whose group represents the
major Western oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Mangeles said she expected the investigation, both into prices
as well as the mergers, to reveal no evidence of wrongdoing. She
said the FTC investigators ``look at big mergers no matter what the
industry is.''
</P>
<P>
   The gas industry has maintained that recent refinery accidents
in California, combined with an increase in crude oil prices, are
to blame for the rising prices. Prices also typically increase in
spring to take advantage of holiday travelers. Finally, the state's
high taxes and requirements for cleaner burning gas add to the
price tag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
