<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-PREACHING08-COX     05-07 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-PREACHING08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traditional black preaching draws forth two-way communication
between pew and pulpit
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Adorned in a flowing robe, the Rev. James Davis rises
from his seat in the pulpit of the historic Big Bethel African
Methodist Episcopal Church. There's a tension in the air. Members,
filing one by one from their seats, had taken turns at the altar
rail for individual prayer, while a soloist crooned a song in
tribute to the faith in God that she learned from her grandmother:
</P>
<P>
   ``He walks with me, and he talks with me, and he tells me I am
his own. And the joy we share as we tarry there, none other has
ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   As the song ends, Davis positions himself behind the carved
mahogany lectern on the pulpit. Emotions are still running high, as
shouts of joy and grateful ``hallelujahs!'' echo across the
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   In the front pew, Monica Johnson is moved close to tears by the
soloist's song. ``It was like everybody in here who had that kind
of connection with their grandmother, we were just drawn in,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis bows his head and begins to pray. ``As this word is
delivered, so fill it with power that it might go forth and fall on
fertile ground. . . .'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the people of God said in agreement . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . Amen!'' worshippers respond.
</P>
<P>
   Davis then instructs the congregation to turn in their Bibles
with him ``for these next few moments'' to the 11th chapter of
John. ``When you get it, let me know,'' he instructs, listening as
the voices chime in, one by one: ``Got it!''
</P>
<P>
   The sound of turning Bible pages flutters across the church like
the rustling wings of a flock of birds preparing for flight.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the pastor's sermon will last more than a ``few
moments.'' And though Davis has taken the ecclesiastical spotlight
at this point in the service, his sermon will be no monologue.
</P>
<P>
   In the unique cultural tradition of black worship, preaching is
a group exercise led by the minister, who serves as a sort of
homiletic host, setting a Bible-based buffet of teaching and
inspiration, while inviting the congregation to partake without
inhibition. A mix of spirituality, image-rich rhetoric and verbal
calisthenics, traditional black preaching is a performance art form
deeply rooted in Christian Gospel and African religious tradition.
Unlike the sermon-as-lecture approach, crowd participation is an
integral part of preaching in the black church.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about it is you don't have to be an usher, in the
choir or on the ministerial staff'' to participate in the service,
explains Chris Parker, who has been a member of Bethel since 1996.
``It's an inclusive worship experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not for everyone. Some feel the boisterous
call-and-response experience that characterizes the traditional
black church service is less than dignified, and others simply
prefer a more sedate style of worship.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 years ago, writer-activist James Weldon Johnson
worried that a lack of appreciation for traditional culture would
spell the death of black preaching. Johnson created a literary
tribute to the folk sermons that were the staple of the preachers
of his day. He wrote ``God's Trombones: Seven Negro Sermons in
Verse'' (Viking Penguin, $8.95, 64 pages) in the style of the
poetic prose and spirit-filled oratory of traditional black
preaching. ``The old-time Negro preacher is rapidly passing,''
Johnson wrote in the preface of the book, published in 1927. ``I
have here tried sincerely to fix something of him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's warnings were evidently premature, judging by the
number of black churches embracing the tradition today. In Atlanta,
congregations showcasing such traditional preaching include Antioch
Baptist Church North, Ben Hill United Methodist Church, Ray of Hope
Christian Church, and others spanning the denominational spectrum
from Methodist to Baptist, Pentecostal to nondenominational.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much has changed since Johnson first penned his
pessimistic prediction. Two members of a troupe that recently
presented dramatic readings of Johnson's sermons at Emory
University were women. ``Negroes'' no more, many modern-day
ministers hold credentials never dreamed of by Johnson. A
fifth-generation preacher, Bethel's Davis, 44, is a good example.
</P>
<P>
   The first in his familial line of preachers to attend college,
in 1985 Davis earned a doctorate of ministry at Atlanta's
Interdenominational Theological Center, which graduates 80 to 90
students each year, including one of every 10 black students
enrolled in a master of divinity program at accredited Association
of Theological Schools. In 1997, 5,800 African-Americans were
enrolled in U.S. and Canadian seminaries, according to data
collected by the association.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Davis also demonstrates, the art of traditional black
preaching remains very much alive. ``There has been no significant
change in two centuries in the best of black preaching,'' says ITC
homiletics professor Henry Mitchell in his book ``Black Preaching:
The Recovery of a Powerful Art'' (Abingdon Press, $16, 143 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Black preaching translates the message of the Gospel to address
the peculiar needs of an isolated people, says Mitchell. This is
the enduring legacy of so-called ``old-time religion,'' which is
both the heart of Johnson's writings and the soul of traditional
black preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's crucial about black preaching . . . is that there's
nothing new under the sun,'' says Teresa Fry Brown, assistant
professor of homiletics at Emory's Candler School of Theology, who
was part of the performing group at Emory. ``The God spoken about
then is the same God we know now.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Bethel, established 151 years ago, is the oldest black
congregation in Atlanta and is home to a well-educated, socially
and politically prominent membership. Members clearly revel in the
religious traditions of their parents, grandparents and bygone
generations.
</P>
<P>
   The style and substance of Davis' preaching echo a past that is
still very much a part of the community identity. ``He allows me to
come home, so to speak,'' says parishioner Carl Powell, who was
reared in rural Mississippi. ``He's got relevant stuff that speaks
to where I am now as an educated professional,'' with sermons that
``relate to where we were, where we are, and where we're going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're always on edge because you're waiting on your
opportunity to respond,'' adds Parker. His sermon ``will stimulate
something in your spirit that will make you respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' delivery of a sermon on a recent Sunday, ``Valuing the
Devalued,'' is based on the biblical account of Lazarus' death. In
the gospel according to Davis, Jesus' friends, Martha and Mary, are
``making a mean table when Jesus came over.'' A smiling parishioner
waves his hand, ``Go 'head!''
</P>
<P>
   The message, as always, begins with the Bible. After reading the
Scripture aloud, Davis relates the biblical account of Lazarus'
resurrection and updates the narrative. ``The folk weren't worried
about Lazarus when he was alive. When Lazarus died, that's when
Lazarus sho 'nuff took on his thing. You see, Jesus had dealt with
the resurrection of folk before, but there was always a speculation
as to whether or not they were really dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that sistah that Jesus got to, she had died, and
everybody was around there talking about her being dead. But then
somebody, somebody _ who may have been a member of Bethel back then
_ somebody got into the midst of the conversation and said, `Now,
she wasn't really dead. I mean, she was just comatose. She was in a
deep coma, and she wasn't really dead.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And, as the congregation responds with laughter, Davis chides,
``Y'all need to stop talking about miracles (as if) it wasn't
really a miracle, `It was just that she had gone into a coma'!''
</P>
<P>
   Through the course of the sermon, Davis' voice is at times raspy
and booming, at times tender and soft, at times playfully
stuttering. He uses repetition for emphasis, often repeating a
phrase, constructing a rhetorical refrain that punctuates a rhythm
that builds to a boisterous climax.
</P>
<P>
   Starting slowly, Davis intones, ``This, this is what he did: He,
he, he, he was the key, Lazarus was _ with his dead self _ that
dead Lazarus.'' His voice rises and gains volume and pitch as he
states, ``And you know what made him the right witness? Not only
was he dead, but he was stinky!''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, again, ``He had been dead so long until the Word says,
`He stinketh.' And, if that wasn't bad enough, he was not only
dead, stinking, but he was buried! He was dead, stinky and buried _
and believe it or not _ thank God for some dead, stinky folk right
now. Yea, yea, yea!''
</P>
<P>
   And with a full-throated shout, Davis exclaims: ``The only
reason the church is in business today is because of dead, stinky
folk _ and I'm one of 'em! If it weren't for dead, stinky folk, the
church wouldn't have a reason to exist. Huh?!! But thank God that
God knows how to bring value out of dead, stinky folk!''
</P>
<P>
   After Lazarus is brought back to life, the way Davis describes
it, you can almost picture him just outside on the corner of Auburn
and Butler. A rhythmic exchange between the preacher and listeners
ends the sermon. Davis takes a few steps about the pulpit depicting
Lazarus ``walking around there throwing high-fives and talking
about how good Jesus was . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah!'' someone yells from the pews.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . bragging about the fact that `I was dead, but I ain't
dead now!' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who saw (Lazarus) walking and pimping up and down
the street talking about, `I'm a baaaadddd so-and-so' . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah!''
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . everybody saw him talking about the fact that `my friend
did this for me, my friend Jesus!' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you discredit a dead, stinky, buried man walking
around? They could not discredit this dead, stinky, buried man
walking around!''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions hit a fevered pitch and many Bethelites are standing,
clapping and yelling, ``Yea! Preach!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting, he really puts himself in it,'' Monica Johnson
says after the service. ``He's just so real!''
</P>
<P>
   Davis acknowledges this is by design. ``We have so many
different kind of folk among us,'' he says. ``From way back, we had
people who couldn't read. Black preachers had to make sure all
their folk were communicated to. The objective always is to find
something relative and the easiest way to relativity is allegory.
Jesus did it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, that relativity is evidence of the Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's led from the (Holy) Spirit, he's going to bring things
from the Word that you can identify with,'' says the Rev. Bessie
Robinson, a member of the Bethel ministerial staff. Davis ``is a
Holy Spirit-led preacher. The Holy Spirit is the one who's
ministering through him, and when the Spirit speaks, it comes forth
with power, and it touches people's hearts . . . and that's when I
get to hollering.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, effective black preaching ``connects with the inner
being and emotion,'' says Davis. ``The church, the sermon and the
shout was a therapy that we black folk could afford,'' he explains.
``All of that plays together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
