<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OMILAMISQ&AMP;A09-COX     05-07 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OMILAMISQ&AMP;A09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actors play supporting roles in their `mission' to family, each
other
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even now, they rarely miss a chance to call each other baby.
They have a knack of smoothly finishing each others' sentences
without interruption. Their body language _ hands patting knees,
stroking shoulders _ resembles that of newlyweds rather than a
husband and wife in their late 40s, married for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Meet actors Afemo and Elisabeth Omilami, soulmates of the
Atlanta stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell about those movies you've got coming up, baby,'' says
Elisabeth in the deep, soft coo she uses when her husband is next
to her. ``That's a fine body of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Omilamis (the name means ``water heals me'' in Yoruba)
rarely get to share a stage. They shuttle from their Atlanta home
to film and TV centers (New York and Wilmington, N.C.,
particularly) to support their children, Awodele, 19, and Juanita,
13. So it's a treat for audiences _ ``paradise for us,'' says Afemo
_ to have these larger-than-life thespians under the same, Alliance
Theatre roof in overlapping plays.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth, the daughter and longtime political helpmate of Hosea
Williams, is giving the performance of her career as Quilly
McGrath, the crafty, wisecracking, deceptively strong sister in
``The Old Settler,'' a romantic drama on the Alliance mainstage.
Afemo, a key player in establishing Alliance artistic director
Kenny Leon's national reputation in the late '80s and early '90s
(``Miss Evers' Boys,'' ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone''), returns as
a staunch, God-fearing single father in ``Crumbs From the Table of
Joy,'' opening Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Recently they spoke in the Woodruff Arts Center galleria.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How did you meet?
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: We met in Ted Shine's ``Contributions'' at People's
Survival Theater, (an Atlanta) group I led in the '70s. Afemo was
supposed to be the son and I was supposed to be the grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Q:That's a loaded situation.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: Very loaded. But I sure didn't feel like a
grandmother around him (laughs).
</P>
<P>
   Afemo: I wasn't really all that interested romantically at that
time, I think she was more interested in me.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: Oh, listen to that now! (Laughs.) I don't believe he
said that.
</P>
<P>
   Afemo: I wasn't ready. . . . I was a bohemian.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: Yes, walking up and down the streets with no shoes
on, singing at the top of his voice. But I knew I had him when
there was a blizzard. The snow was over his ankles and here he came
trudging through the snow to see me in my apartment. I said,
``Hmmmm.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:What happens when you don't see eye-to-eye?
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: I have to defer to him. He's very loving and usually
gives me whatever I want, but it's important that as an
African-American male he be the head of the family and that my son
sees a strong male figure in the home. But he's wise enough to know
that I'm usually right.
</P>
<P>
   Afemo: I'm not one of these controlling husbands. Sometimes she
goes out for a job and I watch the family. We lived in New York for
years, but when our daughter came along, Elisabeth went to see her
mom (in Atlanta) and said, ``I'm not coming back.'' I held on
another six months but finally saw that Atlanta was best for our
family.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: Yes, you came back first of '87, baby, same year I
went on the Forsyth (County) march (led by her father, Hosea
Williams). I was the first black woman held in the Forsyth County
jail. My cell was right next to the KKK people, shouting horrible
things to me all night. I never stopped chasing my father, trying
to have a normal father-daughter relationship. The movement often
came between us, so I'd rather be in jail than away from him. Time
is short and family is No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You often mention spiritual life and artistic life in same
breath.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: They're one in the same.
</P>
<P>
   Afemo: They go hand in hand. Theater is not a frivolous thing,
it can be as valuable as church. It took a while for me to give up
that ``stardom'' nonsense, for the Lord to burn all that away. I
see now that he gave me this talent so that I could give it back.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What have been your rewarding roles?
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: He saw ``Old Settler'' in New York and said, ``Baby,
I found . . . the play . . . for you.'' Bluespeak Woman in
``Spunk'' at Jomandi was fun because I got to sing and be funny and
sexy. I love to represent the sensuality and vivacity of the older
African-American woman.
</P>
<P>
   Q:There's so much affection in your Quilly. Is it a tribute to
someone?
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: I was thinking about Pearl Bailey. My mother (Juanita
Williams), too, she's like 5 feet tall but so full of spunk. My
aunt Sarah Wilson, librarian at (Clark Atlanta University) has that
certain way of firing things off.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Afemo, what about your role in the upcoming ``Crumbs''?
</P>
<P>
   Afemo: It's a fine family story about how society has to
appreciate the little blessings again, the crumbs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: It's the little things that kept us alive. Our faith
kept our sanity. It's been a journey of frightening times and just
holding on to each other, encouraging each other. One would be down
and the other would say, ``Come on now, baby, something will come
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Afemo: This business will beat you down if you don't have a firm
foothold, a meaning, a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth: That's what we've got.
</P>
<P>
   THE OMILAMI FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Background: Afemo, raised in Petersburg, Va., received a full
scholarship to study acting at New York University. Elisabeth,
raised Elisabeth Williams (daughter of Hosea and Juanita Williams)
in Atlanta, has a degree from Hampton College and is producer of
``Feed the Hungry,'' free dinners served in Atlanta neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her roles: Stars in ``The Old Settler'' on Alliance mainstage
through May 16. Past roles on TV series ``I'll Fly Away''; TV film
``Selma, Lord, Selma,'' based on the civil rights march she took
part in as a girl.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His roles: Returns to Alliance in Studio's ``Crumbs From the
Table of Joy,'' opening Wednesday. Co-stars with Nicolas Cage in
Martin Scorsese's film ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' due this fall.
Appears as father of the boy version of Sidney Poitier's character
in ``The Simple Life of Noah Dearborn,'' 9 tonight on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: For ``The Old Settler'' and ``Crumbs,'' call the
Alliance at 404-733-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
