<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8608 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOLETO-ANDERSON09-CO     05-07 1929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-ANDERSON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laurie Anderson's latest: Multimedia opera
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday May, 9.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Still looking slightly spooked after all these years,
with the trademark spiky hair she cuts herself, performance artist
Laurie Anderson seems hermetically sealed in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   With the androgynous sensibility of Andy Warhol, the
anesthesia-soaked voice of William S. Burroughs and the eternal
presence of a Mapplethorpe photograph, she remains, at 51, the
queen of the experimental downtown scene she helped define more
than 20 years ago. She is one of the few artists who've stuck
around long enough to become an oxymoron _ having, as The New York
Times recently put it, evolved into the ``mainstream avant-garde.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, at her Canal Street studio overlooking the Hudson
River, Anderson is wired for sound. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking coffee, breaking the filters off Marlboros before
lighting them up, she closes a window to drown out the noise of a
jackhammer, then decides later she wants to tape the intriguing
sound. We're here to discuss ``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick,''
the multimedia opera based on the Herman Melville novel. She's
bringing the piece June 3-4 to Spoleto Festival USA in Charleston,
S.C., but before this hour is over, she'll talk about everything
from her father's recent death to the time she taught poetry to
prisoners at Rikers Island.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in red loafers, gray socks, black pants, an orange tank
top and a meshy, chartreuse sweater, she shucks off her stern
demeanor when asked about the time in 1978 that she worked as a
migrant farmer with a family near Covington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was a cotton picker,'' she says in a country twang,
smacking her lips and sounding as if she's about to spit chewing
tobacco from her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   She had almost forgotten about her Rikers Island days, she says,
until she happened upon a set of purple notes from an old
mimeograph machine. ``It was a list of things like, `Always
remember your client is mentally ill.' And I thought, `I'm going to
put that on my desk right now, because that's a useful thing to
remember.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is the voice of a woman with a deadpan sense of humor and a
dark sensibility, a person who works with equal success as a visual
artist, filmmaker, poet, spoken-word performer, singer, musician,
stand-up comic and electronics wizard.
</P>
<P>
   Her influence has been profound.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really has changed the history of art in very big ways,''
says Roselee Goldberg, a New York University art professor and
curator who is writing a book on Anderson. ``I've taken the
opportunity to say loud and clear that she's indeed one of our most
important American artists at the end of the 20th century. She's
way up there, along with Warhol and (Robert) Rauschenberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Larry Larson, Anderson's company manager for the past two
years: ``I don't know of any other artist who is involved on an
international level with so many different disciplines. We work
with record companies. We work with international presenters. And
at the same time, we meet with the heads of the great museums of
the world. ''
</P>
<P>
   Professionally outgoing by necessity, Anderson is intensely
private. She never brings up the rock singer Lou Reed, for example,
even though he's been her boyfriend for six years. A
black-and-white photo of Reed hangs in the book-filled studio,
which is full of electronic instruments, a telescope pointed toward
the river and a scale model of the ``Moby Dick'' stage.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who grew up in the small town of Glen Ellyn, Ill., in
the 1950s, has always embraced nonconformity and rallied for
individual rights. In 1987 she made a video titled ``Alive From Off
Center.'' In 1980, she performed at the anti-inaugural ball for
Ronald Reagan. The program notes to her 1989 album, ``Strange
Angels,'' contain a poignant letter to her friend Robert
Mapplethorpe, the controversial photographer who died of AIDS that
year. His images of Anderson grace the cover.
</P>
<P>
   After getting degrees in art history and sculpture, and putting
in her years of community service, Anderson launched her career in
1974 with a mixed-media performance art exhibition titled
``As:If.'' She played her trademark violin, which she has studied
since age 5 _ with her feet encased in blocks of ice.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, her eight-hour version of ``United States'' was covered
by Newsweek and Time magazines. ``Big Science,'' the first of her
seven albums, sold 800,000 copies, and ``Strange Angels,'' with its
lush arrangements and conventional verse-chorus structure, signaled
that she had crossed over into the popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   She has given numerous concerts in Atlanta. In 1989, her
much-hyped Spoleto world premiere, ``Empty Places,'' so enraged
festival founder Gian Carlo Menotti that he banned her from the
sister event in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson says she is looking forward to returning to
Charleston with ``Moby Dick.'' She says she enjoys Spoleto
audiences because ``they are up for something different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People kind of go, `OK, this is an extremely bizarre thing,
and this is a classic.' They aren't afraid to mix 'em up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moby Dick'' is Anderson's most ambitious work to date and the
culmination of a 25-year obsession with the 1851 novel. It employs
three other actors, countless computers and a new gizmo called the
Talking Stick, which allows performers to manipulate computer
sounds and the sophisticated computer software that controls them.
</P>
<P>
   Something unknowable
</P>
<P>
   As a visual artist, Anderson has had a retrospective at the
Guggenheim Museum in SoHo, and an exhibition is planned for the
Whitney Museum of American Art. In the arcane world of ``Moby
Dick,'' Anderson seems to have found a perfect partner for her free
associational, image-driven narratives and her own bleak worldview.
When a visitor notices a picture of the Dalai Lamai in her
book-filled studio, he asks if she's Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a seeker,'' she says, turning on the mordant sense of
humor and evading the answer. ``I'm not in anything, although
that's part of my attraction to `Moby Dick,' that I am trying to
find something unknowable. I mean Melville's very funny, but he's
very dark, too. His conclusions, if there are any, are incredibly
bleak. That is, if there is something that created the world, it's
completely mechanical and it's heartless and it will eat you
alive!''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says she's read the book five times. It's been a
recurring theme in her work since the 1974 film ``Dear Reader.'' On
the 1989 song ``My Eyes'' she crooned:
</P>
<P>
   ``And down in the ocean where nobody goes
</P>
<P>
   ``Some fish are fast, some are slow
</P>
<P>
   ``Some swim round the world, some hide below
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ocean, so deep, so old.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's two-hour production, says Spoleto director general
Nigel Redden, uses the book as a springboard. ``It will be a
combination of images in a variety of different media,'' he says,
``slides, video and laser, overlaid one on top of another. It's not
going to be a retelling of the Melville novel.''
</P>
<P>
   In exploring the world of Captain Ahab, Anderson echoes the
first line of her first album: ``Good evening, this is your
captain.'' She's always had a thing for airplanes; now she's on a
journey through water and the brain. Asked about the connection,
she says it's all about ``getting out of the box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm having trouble getting out of the book, because the
book is a kind of box for me. So I've given up on telling the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has always used technology to illumine the
banalities of modern life (answering machines, plastic surgery) and
to meditate on questions of spirituality, is asked for her thoughts
on angels and the afterlife. ``I think we are the closest to angels
there is _ that's what I think, and I think when you die, you turn
into rain, and then you disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   According to her friends and colleagues, Anderson is as kind as
she is smart. ``First of all, she's just white-hot brilliant,''
says Larson. ``And she is also the kindest major artist I've ever
met, much less worked with. Laurie is up there with, say, Merce
Cunningham and Philip Glass as being a good human being as well as
being a great artist.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's a fragile core hidden underneath the
guarded surface. Anderson recently had to interrupt a vacation to
rush to the side of her 88-year-old father, who was dying of
cancer. She said a Buddhist friend coached her on how to ease his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I wasn't too irritating. But I did try to help him a
little bit, just by synchronized breathing and trying to make a
situation that wasn't too panicky, to try to encourage him to bring
his energy from the heart up to the top of his head so he could
come out that way. I do believe that is important, that you catch
the part of yourself that is the deepest and let that go, not just
die from your gut but have your heart pass through your head and
then out.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Anderson decides she wants to tape the articulated
sound of the jackhammer outside. She jumps up and goes down into
the bowels of her recording studio for a gigantic tape recorder,
which she clearly has no idea how to operate.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment, she leads her visitor to the elevator. When he
mentions that he might call again with questions about ``Moby
Dick,'' Anderson _ who has been acting a little anxious about not
having an end for the piece _ responds, without skipping a beat,
``And I'll call you if I have any questions about the structure,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Laurie Anderson file
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: She's 51. Three sisters and four brothers. Boyfriend
is rock singer Lou Reed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education and awards: Bachelor of Arts in art history from
Barnard College (1969). Master of Fine Arts in sculpture from
Columbia University (1972). She has received honorary doctorates
from the Art Institute of Chicago, the San Francisco Art Institute
and the Philadelphia College of the Arts. Guggenheim Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Critical response to ``Moby Dick'': After the April 29 world
premiere in Dallas, The Dallas Morning News wrote: ``(The basic
story line from the novel) doesn't begin to explain the
mind-blowing brain candy, visual and aural, that Ms. Anderson
served. . . . Thanks to the nonstop, highly stimulating projection
of backdrops and lights, the show had a dreamy, filmlike, nearly
transcendent quality. When it was over, it was as if the audience
had been on a ship _ for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Discography: ``The Ugly One With the Jewels'' (1995); ``Bright
Red'' (1994); ``Strange Angels'' (1989); score to her film ``Home
of the Brave'' (1986); ``United States Live,'' five-record set
documenting the performance (1985); ``Mister Heartbreak'' (1984);
``Big Science'' (1982). Has collaborated on film scores with Wim
Wenders, Spalding Gray and Jonathan Demme.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The book: Roselee Goldberg's ``Laurie Anderson'' is scheduled
for publication by Abrams in the spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To hear selections by Laurie Anderson, dial 511, enter 8600
and Soundline number 427. Each call costs 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   SPOLETO FESTIVAL USA
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs and Stories
</P>
<P>
   From Moby Dick''
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Laurie Anderson. 8 p.m. June 3-4. $10-$45. Gaillard
Municipal Auditorium, 77 Calhoun St., Charleston, S.C. Spoleto runs
May 28-June 13. Tickets: 843-723-0402; brochures: 843-722-2764.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
