<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOLUNTEERS-BREASTCANC     05-07 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLUNTEERS-BREASTCANCER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breast cancer patients give hope, support to each other
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After being diagnosed with breast cancer, Vicki
Castleberry was told she had only six years to live. ``I was
devastated,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years later, Castleberry, 67, is very much alive. And
she attributes her recovery to finding the right support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew very little about breast cancer, and found out about a
support group through my church,'' says the Tucker (Ga.) resident,
a former interior decorator. ``At that time there were only one or
two cancer support groups in Atlanta, and they were general _ for
all types of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Castleberry saw a need for a group focused on breast cancer, one
of the most prevalent of all cancers in women. In 1983 she created
such a group, meeting with three other women in her home. Today the
volunteer-run organization, Bosom Buddies of Georgia, includes 35
support groups in 17 Georgia counties and Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   For founder-president Castleberry, the organization has become a
full-time, unpaid job. ``I know I was given a second chance at
life,'' she says. ``This is my way of paying back. I'm here to make
life a little easier for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors now recognize the healing power of support groups. A
recent Stanford University study found that women with terminal
breast cancer who had regularly attended support groups lived 18
months longer than patients not attending such groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``By attending support groups, we give hope to one another,''
says Barbara Quinn, 63, a DeKalb County (Ga.) resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not gloom-and-doom meetings. There's a lot of
laughter,'' says the retired insurance adjuster, who stays busy
these days dancing with the Kennesaw Mountain Kloggers, despite
undergoing a double mastectomy in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   'A bright and shining star'
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing emotional support and encouragement, members
of Bosom Buddies share practical information about diet, vitamins,
meditation
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest volunteer needs of the support organization
is for group leaders, or facilitators, who must be breast cancer
survivors who have completed their treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't need to have had breast cancer to volunteer with
Bosom Buddies. The organization needs help at its Chamblee office,
at health fairs, and with the speakers' bureau. Volunteers are also
needed to accompany patients to treatments and doctor's
appointments, to visit patients in hospitals, even to provide
bereavement support to family members.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a ``Stitching Buddies'' program in which volunteers
sew pressure pillows for mastectomy patients and turbans for women
with hair loss caused by chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Guffin of Suwanee (Ga.) was diagnosed with breast cancer
12 years ago. ``It was very, very frightening,'' she says. ``You
don't know if you will live or die, and no one can tell you.'' She
had six rounds of chemotherapy, 35 rounds of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Getting involved with Bosom Buddies was like seeing ``a bright
and shining star when you are in a deep, dark pit,'' says Guffin.
``You see survivors that look so attractive and good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a real estate agent, Guffin, 58, worked for 28 years doing
psychiatric social work and drug counseling in Atlanta's inner
city. ``Addicts used to tell me I couldn't help them because I
didn't know what I was talking about. No one in Bosom Buddies can
tell me that,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Guffin's message to breast cancer patients and survivors is
straightforward: ``There is quality life after cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   To volunteer or learn more about the organization, call
770-455-7637.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
