<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITADEL-COX     05-07 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITADEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: TODAY is SATURDAY in lede.
 &HT;    First woman cadet to graduate from Citadel
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ All alone, Nancy Mace strides across the
grassy parade ground. Eyes straight ahead, her slender arms
swinging in gentle cadence, the 21-year-old woman in gray will
march into history today as the first woman to graduate from The
Citadel in its 153-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Mace will complete the arduous journey started by Shannon
Faulkner. A federal judge ordered Faulkner admitted to the corps of
cadets in August 1995, but she dropped out within days, saying she
felt isolated and exhausted by her 2 1/2-year legal fight to become
the school's first female cadet.
</P>
<P>
   Mace's isolation at noontime Thursday was fleeting, and that
illustrates the progress by the state-supported military college in
assimilating women. Their numbers are growing _ 41 among 1,800
cadets this year _ and there could be 100 next school year.
</P>
<P>
   Mace crossed the parade grounds from her barracks to Mark Clark
Hall, where members of the state-supported military college's Board
of Visitors congratulated the cadet captain with a 3.67 GPA in
business administration.
</P>
<P>
   That same board of prominent alumni had fought Faulkner's
assault on single-gender education. Now in embracing women, they're
making it possible for female cadets to tap into the influential
network of alumni who've provided jobs and contacts to male cadets
for generations. In court, Faulkner's lawyers argued that by
denying women admission, the school was depriving them of such
contacts. Mace is going to work in Charlotte as an analyst for
Andersen Consulting, a job she said she found during a job fair,
not from a Citadel alumnus. But she said, ``The alumni network is
out there alive and well. There are a large number of individuals
who are ready to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Masculine history pervades The Citadel, from a plaque honoring
the ``Citadel men'' who died during War II to gold-framed portraits
of the school's war heroes dating back to the Civil War. But among
steps intended to make the school inclusive of women, the
Association of Citadel Men changed its name to the Association of
Citadel Alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni support has been particularly crucial for 21-year-old
Petra Lovetinska. The Czech national enrolled in the Citadel in
August 1996 with Mace and with two other women who quit after they
alleged cadets had hazed and sexually harassed them. The college
settled with Kim Messer; it still faces a federal lawsuit by Jeanie
Mentavlos.
</P>
<P>
   Citadel alumni in Washington, where Lovetinska's father worked
for the Czech Embassy, are helping pay her tuition. During her
grueling freshman year, Lovetinska said she received letters from
an alumnus who encouraged her to stick it out.
</P>
<P>
   Now alumni are helping Lovetinska, in the United States on a
student visa, to secure a work permit so she can remain in this
country when she graduates a year from now. This fall, she will be
the executive officer of one of the corps' four battalions, as well
as commander of the cadre of upperclassmen who train the freshman
athletes. Mace, from Goose Creek, S.C., arrived at The Citadel with
community college credits, allowing her history-making early
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had hand-picked a woman to be the first to graduate
from The Citadel, they couldn't have done better than Nancy,'' said
Charleston talk radio host Dan Moon.
</P>
<P>
   When Faulkner enrolled 3 1/2 years ago, callers to Moon's show
hurled ugly remarks at the 20-year-old from Powdersville, S.C. Moon
called Faulkner, who was overweight and poorly conditioned, a
``toadfish,'' a remark he said he now regrets but defends as
reflective of public sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was caught up three years ago in the sentiment of a lot of
people who asked, `Why can't they just leave the place alone?'''
Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Citadel's Board of Visitors abandoned its legal fight in
June 1996, after the U.S. Supreme Court declared that Virginia
Military Institute's single-gender policy was unconstitutional. On
May 15, two women _ Melissa Graham of Burleson, Texas, and
Chih-Yuan Ho of China _ are scheduled to graduate from the
Lexington, Va., state-supported college.
</P>
<P>
   Women haven't yet achieved universal acceptance among cadets and
alumni at either VMI or The Citadel, the South's two most prominent
military colleges. A few Citadel alumni are so disgusted by the
admittance of women that they've written off the school. Others are
still upset at orders to end hazing issued by Citadel President
John Grinalds and retired Army Brig. Gen. Emory Mace, Mace's father
who became commandant of cadets in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell Week'' _ knobs' grueling introduction to a lowly, at
times miserable, freshman year _ has been eliminated. The
administration now stresses leadership development among cadets.
When Mace crosses the stage today to receive her diploma, she's not
certain some cadets won't hiss at her, as some did during last
fall's senior ring ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be so thankful to get my diploma from The Citadel,''
Mace said, ``I could care less about anything else, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution in Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
