<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES08-COX     05-07 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEMPORARY HAVEN LIKELY TO BE PERMANENT FOR KOSOVARS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the arriving Kosovo refugees are like previous
waves of ``temporary'' migrants, most will never go home again,
immigration experts say.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton promises to make Kosovo safe for ethnic
Albanians, most of the 20,000 headed for the United States will
probably put down roots here instead, said Mark Krikorian of the
Center for Immigration Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer you stay, the less likely you are to go home. ...
It's just common sense,'' he said, citing refugees from Central
America, Cuba and Poland. They were also supposed to return home
after turmoil ended, but most did not, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If tomorrow the situation changes in Kosovo, a significant
percentage are going to stay (in the United States), and the more
time passes, the bigger the proportion will be,'' Krikorian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not necessarily a bad thing. It's just a fact,'' he
said, adding that U.S. officials should be more realistic in
setting refugee policies.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at agencies that help resettle refugees make similar
observations. At the Immigration and Refugee Services of America,
spokeswoman Melissa Wyers said that ``every'' refugee she meets
wants to go home at first, ``but in some cases that never becomes
possible.'' After a few years, she said, the families abandon plans
to return, especially if they have children.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be a symbolic event for the newcomers, the first
baby was born just hours after his Kosovar parents landed in the
United States, and his father said he would call his son, a U.S.
citizen, ``America.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Clinton administration has portrayed the Kosovars'
stay as temporary. When Vice President Al Gore announced last month
that the United States would take in the refugees, he said they
would stay ``until they are able to return home safely.''
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton last Wednesday greeted the
first planeload of Kosovars at Fort Dix, N.J., by telling them,
``We will not let (Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic)
succeed in keeping you out of your homes.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Kosovars have been given the status of permanent
immigrants, which entitles them to stay here indefinitely. As
refugees, they will be allowed to receive government benefits,
including welfare and Medicaid, and be permitted to hold jobs.
After a year, they can apply for a ``green card'' as a permanent
resident, and after five years, they would be eligible for
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Using federal funds, private agencies find homes and apartments
for the families and provide the first month's rent. The State
Department has announced that the cost of resettling the Kosovars
is $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Krikorian said he had strong doubts that once the refugees are
settled in cities such as Des Moines, Iowa, Dallas, New York and
Atlanta, many will want to return to a war-ravaged homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is that we take that kind of thing into
account when we make refugee policy, so that we don't fool
ourselves,'' said Krikorian, who frequently criticizes U.S.
immigration policy as too lax.
</P>
<P>
   The 20,000 Kosovars, who will be added to the 78,000 annual
limit for new refugees, will not have a huge impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Krikorian said that they represent a new stream of
immigrants that will increase over years as they bring more family
members into the United States. ``You start the flow, and it keeps
flowing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
