NYT-05-07-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FINANCES-4TAKES-     05-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FINANCES-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S BUSINESS DEALINGS SHOW SOME SUCCESS INHERITED, SOME
ACHIEVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: An abridged version of this article is also being filed.)  
(rm) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When George W. Bush first ran for governor of
Texas five years ago, he had no record in politics, only a famous
name and a business career that he described as a success ``by any
objective measure.''
</P>
<P>
   In one significant way, that boast may be truer today than it
was in 1994. As Bush seeks to spring from the governorship to the
presidency, he does so with the financial security provided by his
2,359 percent gain from last year's sale of the Texas Rangers,
which transformed his $606,000 investment in the baseball team into
a $14.9 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is not the only objective measure of a
business career. And closer inspection of Bush's two decades in the
private sector in Texas, which began in the oil patch in Midland
and ended in the owner's box in Arlington, suggests that his record
was mixed. While some ventures made healthy profits, others
struggled for survival. Some of his dealings raised ethical
questions that have provided fodder for political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush emerging as an early front-runner for the Republican
nomination in 2000, his business dealings also illuminate an
essential question of his biography: whether his success is
primarily inherited or achieved. It is a question that has dogged
Bush, as a son of former President George Bush, throughout his
business career, as throughout his political life.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensible answer, it seems, is that Bush deserves credit
for much of his success, but that he also has benefited at critical
points from his family's prominence and the financial support of
family friends and business and political acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Bush, 52, acknowledged that his name has
generated opportunities not available to everybody, both in
business and in politics. But he asserted that he has never relied
on his name or heritage to ensure his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the integrity of my dad and mom, I've inherited a
great name that has sometimes opened doors and sometimes slammed
them shut,'' he said. ``But the business world is a world of
results and performance, and having a famous last name didn't
strike oil or conceive and build the Ballpark at Arlington, or help
the team's win-loss record. And my name hasn't made any decisions
for me as governor.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Bush clearly has received significant help along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving an MBA from Harvard Business School, for
instance, he started a small oil company in Midland with the
$17,000 remaining in an educational trust fund established by his
parents. Some of the most powerful businessmen in America then took
a chance on the untested oilman by investing hundreds of thousands
of dollars in his first drilling funds. Many were recruited by his
uncle, Jonathan Bush, a New York City stockbroker and the brother
of the former president. When the company stagnated because of
declining market conditions and a serious miscalculation by George
W. Bush, it survived by merging twice with larger firms.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush's role in the 1989 purchase of the Rangers and the
attention he gained by managing the franchise that launched his
career as governor. His partners praise him for working
aggressively to secure the purchase and for making improvements,
including the construction of a graceful new stadium, that tripled
the value of the team by the time they sold it last June.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the Rangers, Bush's fortunes were aided by his
status as a first son and by the help of others. The late Eddie
Chiles, who sold the team to Bush's group, was a longtime friend
and political supporter of President Bush who picked George W. Bush
from among other suitors at least partly because of his deep
affection for the president, said Richard E. Greene, the former
mayor of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush rounded up half the money used to buy the team,
the deal came together only when Peter Ueberroth, then the baseball
commissioner, personally persuaded Richard E. Rainwater, a
prominent Fort Worth investor, to take a major interest and join
forces with Bush. Bush had previously failed to recruit Rainwater.
One source close to those negotiations said that Ueberroth had
insisted that Rainwater team up with Bush ``out of respect for his
father,'' the president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there was a time when he was sensitive to his
reputation as a child of privilege. ``When people say silver spoon
and all that business, it may have bothered me when I was a
teen-ager,'' he said. But he said the passage of time and the
compilation of his own record, both in business and in politics,
had thickened his skin. ``Look, I've had some successes and I've
had some failures,'' he said. ``I'm very comfortable now with who I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE OILMAN: MORE MERGERS THAN GUSHERS
</P>
<P>
   Bush, eldest son of George and Barbara Bush, graduated from Yale
in 1968. He then enlisted in the Texas Air National Guard at the
height of the Vietnam War, worked in Houston for an agricultural
conglomerate run by a former employee of his father's and helped
manage an unsuccessful U.S. Senate campaign in Alabama before
enrolling in business school. Graduating in 1975, he returned to
the West Texas oil town of Midland, where he had spent part of his
youth, and began learning the oil business by running courthouse
title searches on mineral rights.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his business school classmates, Bush had
developed no real plan for his life. But his father had made his
fortune in the oilfields, and the industry was enjoying one of its
cycles of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my instincts are toward entrepreneurship,'' Bush said,
``and I really wasn't interested in trying out the corporate
culture at that point in my life. I was single, I didn't have many
needs, and I felt that the barriers to entry were pretty darn low
in the oil business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, oil made Bush a millionaire, and he used his profits
to build an even larger fortune in baseball. But his success in oil
had far more to do with mergers than with gushers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Bush formed Arbusto Energy Inc., ``ar-BOO-stow'' being
Spanish for ``bush.'' Using the unspent balance in his educational
trust fund _ ``my sole inheritance, except for a great name and a
lot of love'' _ he opened a small office and began to solicit
investors for annual drilling funds that typically bought modest
interests in wells operated by other firms.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's early years, Bush's father was either running
for president, filling Ronald Reagan's ticket or serving as vice
president, and state securities filings show that the original
investors included wealthy and prominent friends of the Bush
family, corporate chieftains, Republican leaders, Bush family
members and clients of Jonathan Bush. The list of investors was
remarkable for a young company owned by a man of 32 with scant
experience and virtually no track record.
</P>
<P>
   It included the likes of Lew Lehrman, the drugstore magnate who
narrowly lost the 1982 governor's race in New York, and George L.
Ball, then president of E.F. Hutton &AMP; Co. Ball said he was
recruited by Scott Pierce, a colleague at Hutton who is the brother
of Barbara Bush. William H. Draper, a venture capitalist from
California who was appointed president of the Export-Import Bank of
the United States by President Reagan, invested in several funds,
as did John D. Macomber, the chief executive officer of Celanese
Corp. who was later named to the same Export-Import post by
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   One investor recruited by Jonathan Bush, who noted that Bush was
compensated for his work, was Russell S. Reynolds Jr., a leading
corporate headhunter from Greenwich, Conn., who has known the Bush
family for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan called me up one day,'' Reynolds said, ``and said he
had a nephew named George who was an absolute star and had been to
Andover and Yale and Harvard Business School and was getting into
the oil business and would I be interested in being an investor.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds invested $23,250 in 1980, according to the securities
filings. ``The bottom line is it didn't work out very well with
Arbusto,'' he said. ``In fact, George Bush called it `I busted.' I
think we ended up getting 20 cents on the dollar. That's a real
crapshoot, that business. But the guy's absolutely terrific. He's
straight as an arrow. He's a world-class player.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Reynolds, all of the approximately 20 business associates
interviewed for this article described Bush as astute, hardworking,
affable, gritty and honest in their dealings with him.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the first three years, Bush managed to increase the
amount invested in his oil funds, from $565,000 in 1979 to $1.7
million in 1981. But eager to grow faster, he switched strategies
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   First he shored up his company's cash flow by selling 10 percent
of its stock to a New York investor, Philip A. Uzielli, for the
highly speculative price of $1 million. Uzielli, who declined to be
interviewed, was a Princeton classmate and longtime friend of James
Baker, who was serving at the time as chief of staff in the
Reagan-Bush White House. George W. Bush said he met Uzielli through
another Arbusto investor, George L. Ohrstrom, and only later
learned of Uzielli's relationship with Baker. Baker and Ohrstrom
did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Next, with his company regularly mocked as ``Ar-bust-o'' and his
father serving as vice president, Bush changed the firm's name to
Bush Exploration. Then, in the biggest miscalculation of his
business career, he decided to sell public shares in his 1982
oil-drilling fund rather than rely solely on private investments.
The offering failed dismally, with Bush securing only $1.14 million
of the $6 million he had sought to raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really realized that I had made somewhat of a strategic
error,'' he said. ``The business took a little bit of a downturn,
and the luster was off the drilling funds. I was a small guy trying
to enter the market. And it just didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the company had average luck in its drilling
ventures, but never made a major discovery. ``We went about it the
right way,'' said K. Michael Conaway, the company's treasurer,
``made very cautious decisions. But we just didn't find enough oil
and gas in the ground to be rousingly successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who drove a beat-up Buick and wore sport shirts to work,
recalls his firm as being ``a good, solid little company'' that had
a positive cash flow and provided a steady return for his limited
partners. He said he believes that some at least recouped their
investments, and some, like Ball, verified that they had made
modest profits.
</P>
<P>
   But a company prospectus suggests that many partners, like
Reynolds, must have lost money. It shows that limited partners
contributed $4.67 million to various Bush funds through 1984 but
received distributions of only $1.55 million. Through federal tax
laws aimed at encouraging energy production, they also received
$3.9 million in tax write-offs. Bush, meanwhile, drew a $75,000
salary and owned 80 percent of Arbusto, which contributed $102,000
to the various drilling funds and took distributions of $362,000.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE DRY WELL: OIL PRICES FALL; ENTER AN EMIRATE
</P>
<P>
   Burned by his 1982 experience but still anxious to grow, Bush
merged Bush Exploration in 1984 with Spectrum 7 Energy Corp., a
drilling firm based in Cincinnati with an office in Midland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good fit because we were both small and it gave us
bigger size,'' said William O. DeWitt Jr., one of Spectrum's
principals, who also was the son of the former owner of the
Cincinnati Reds. ``We saw it as an opportunity to grow and to get
George, too, who we thought was a dynamic leader and who we thought
would be very good for our business.'' After a stock swap, Bush
became chairman, chief executive officer and a director, with
ownership of about 15 percent of the company, according to a
Spectrum prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in 1986, world oil prices collapsed, plummeting
from $26 a barrel in January to below $10 in April. Faced with the
prospect of laying off Spectrum's 15 employees and liquidating its
reserves while waiting for prices to recover, Bush and his partners
decided to merge with Harken Energy Corp., a significantly larger
conglomerate based near Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Spectrum, Harken was not willing to give Bush a daily
management position. But it made him a director, and he received
212,152 shares of Harken stock, worth $530,380, according to
Securities and Exchange Commission filings. By the end of 1989,
Bush had accumulated 345,426 shares, or 1.1 percent of the
company's common stock, often with the help of low-interest loans
and stock options offered to directors.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the merger, Bush moved to Washington to help run
his father's 1988 presidential campaign. But Harken hired him as a
consultant, giving him contracts for between $42,000 and $120,000
in each of the next five years, according to a shareholder's
document.
</P>
<P>
   Several current and former Harken executives declined to comment
on Bush's role at the company. But they have in the past. In 1994,
for instance, E. Stuart Watson, a Harken director, described Bush
as an important asset during dark days for the oil business. ``We
didn't have a fair price for oil, we just had George,'' Watson was
quoted as saying in The Dallas Morning News. ``And George was very
useful to Harken. He could have been more so if he had had funds,
but as far as contacts were concerned, he was terrific. It seemed
like George, he knew everybody in the U.S. who was worth knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is why questions were raised when Harken, which
had little experience with overseas or offshore production,
announced in early 1990 that it had won a potentially lucrative
contract to drill offshore for the island emirate of Bahrain in the
Persian Gulf. Many in the industry assumed that the Bahrainis had
handed the concession to Harken to curry favor with the Bush White
House.
</P>
<P>
   But by all accounts, the younger Bush played no role in pursuing
or negotiating the deal, and he warned board members vigorously
that the company was not ready for a project of that magnitude.
``He was the most skeptical of the bunch,'' said Monte N. Swetnam,
who was then the president of Harken's exploration division.
</P>
<P>
   The man who actually brought Harken and the Bahrainis together
was Michael Ameen, a former Mobil executive in the Middle East with
longstanding relations with the Bahrainis. Ameen said that the
Bahraini minister of development and industry at the time, Yousuf
A. Shirawi, had asked him to find a small American firm to drill in
Bahrain because the Bahrainis did not think a major oil company
would devote adequate time or resources to such a risky project.
Ameen said he then heard about Harken from an investment banker in
Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Shirawi said in an interview that the Bahrainis learned of
Bush's involvement with Harken only after the deal had been
negotiated. ``Maybe he was on the board but I was not aware,''
Shirawi said. Swetnam remembers it differently. ``There was never a
question,'' he said. ``They were clearly aware he was the
president's son.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Harken drilled two very expensive dry holes, with
financing provided by the billionaire Bass family of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   THE QUESTIONS: STOCK IS SOLD, AND PRICE DROPS
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Bush decided to sell stock to pay off a $500,000 bank
loan he had used to buy his share of the Texas Rangers in 1989. On
June 22, he sold his original 212,140 shares of Harken stock for $4
a share, or $848,560.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days later, the company finished the second quarter with a
spectacular loss of $23.2 million, more than eight times the loss
it showed for the second quarter of 1989. In early August, Iraq
invaded Kuwait, and within two weeks Harken's stock fell to $3 a
share on fears that the conflict would threaten the deal with
Bahrain. Then on Aug. 20, when the second-quarter loss was publicly
reported, the price fell to $2.37 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Bush realized quickly that the stock's slide would raise
concerns that he had sold with insider knowledge of the
yet-to-be-reported loss. Although an outside director, he sat on an
audit committee that regularly reviewed the company's financial
practices. The suspicions were compounded when the Securities and
Exchange Commission discovered it did not have a form from Bush
that insiders must file when they sell stock, although Bush
previously filed a different form that had disclosed his intent to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintained that he had filed the missing disclosure form.
But the commission investigated the transaction anyway. Bush's
lawyer defended him by arguing that he had not known about the
impending loss when he sold his stock and that he had thought he
was selling into the anticipated good news that the Basses were
underwriting the Bahrain project. His ethical intent, the lawyer,
Robert W. Jordan, said, was demonstrated by his decision to seek
the clearance of a Harken lawyer before making the sale.
Furthermore, Jordan said, Bush did not seek a buyer for his stock
but was solicited by a Los Angeles broker. The broker, Ralph D.
Smith, now retired from Sutro and Co., confirmed that account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I was the son of a president,'' Bush said. ``I was
very sensitive to the scrutiny. I felt like liquidating the stock
for personal reasons, but I was also fully aware that any deal I
did was going to be fully scrutinized.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission investigators apparently were convinced by Bush's
explanation, particularly his consultation with counsel, said
officials familiar with the investigation. In 1993, as Bush
prepared to run for governor, the agency sent a letter at the
request of his lawyer advising that ``the investigation has been
terminated as to the conduct of Bush, and that, at this time, no
enforcement action is contemplated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponent in the campaign, the incumbent, Gov. Ann
Richards, suggested that the investigation had been a political
whitewash overseen by commission officials appointed by Bush's
father. But commission officials have denied any political
pressure, and noted that commission leaders with direct ties to the
Bushes had been screened out of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE BASEBALL OWNER: A DREAM DEAL NETS THE TEXAS RANGERS
</P>
<P>
   In the years when Bush and DeWitt, his Spectrum 7 business
partner, flew around the country in search of investors, they spent
a lot of time attending baseball games and dreaming about owning a
team. As the Bush presidential campaign wound down in 1988, DeWitt
heard that Eddie Chiles, the crusty and conservative owner of the
Texas Rangers, was looking for a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the election, Bush returned to Texas to try to put
together a deal with Chiles, who had known the Bush family for
decades. ``I walked into his house,'' Bush recalled, ``and said, `I
would like to buy the team. I'm serious about it. I'll put together
a group of people to buy it. I want you to give me serious
consideration.' And therein began the courtship.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles was ailing, both physically and financially, and was
anxious to find a buyer. Knowing that Bush had limited resources of
his own, he questioned whether Bush could come up with the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a long line of people at his doorstep wanting to buy
the team, many of whom had the capacity to just write a check,''
said Greene, the former Arlington mayor. ``But his very words to me
were that because of his great admiration for the president and the
initiative shown by the president's son he was going to deal first
with George.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly collected financial commitments from a Yale
classmate, the classmate's business partner, one of his father's
campaign aides and the husband of a Bush cousin. DeWitt, meanwhile,
put together a group of Cincinnati investors.
</P>
<P>
   But Ueberroth, the baseball commissioner, wanted to ensure that
the Rangers remained in the Dallas-Fort Worth market, and he
expressed concern that Bush's small investment would be the only
Texas money in the deal. Ueberroth and Bobby Brown, the American
League president, then visited Rainwater, the Fort Worth investor
who had already rejected Bush's advances, and persuaded him to bid
for the team.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about that meeting, Bush went back to Rainwater,
with encouragement from Ueberroth, and the two men joined forces,
with each agreeing to raise half of the purchase price. The deal
called for Bush and Edward W. Rose III, a Dallas investor who is
close to Rainwater, to share responsibilities as managing general
partners. When Bush asked Rainwater what had changed his mind, Bush
said Rainwater told him, ``The commissioner's a better salesman
than you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bush described his role in buying the Rangers as
pivotal. ``I wasn't going to let this deal fail,'' he said. ``I
wanted to put together the group. I was tenacious.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his partners agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``George, I would say, was the catalyst in bringing this thing
together and making it happen,'' said Roland W. Betts, the Yale
classmate who became the team's single largest investor.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth is less generous. ``George W. Bush deserves great
credit for the development of the franchise,'' he said in an
interview. ``However, the bringing together of the buying group was
the result of Richard Rainwater, Rusty Rose, Dr. Bobby Brown and
the commissioner.'' Both Rainwater and Rose declined to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   PLAY BALL! WINNING ON FIELD AND OFF, FOR NOW
</P>
<P>
   On April 21, 1989, the Bush-Rose group bought 86 percent of the
Rangers for about $75 million, a price that placed the full value
of the team at $86 million. Bush's initial investment was $500,000,
which he borrowed with his stock holdings as collateral from United
Bank of Midland, where he had served previously as a director. He
later invested more money in the partnership, eventually bringing
his total stake to $606,302, or 1.8 percent of the team.
</P>
<P>
   To reward Bush for his role in structuring the Rangers deal and
managing the franchise, the partners agreed to grant him an
additional 10 percent share of the team once they recouped their
investments along with 2 percent interest. They also voted him a
salary of $200,000 for his full-time work as a managing general
partner.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying the Rangers' success during Bush's tenure,
both on the field and in the stands. After posting losing records
in six of the seven years before the sale, the Rangers were winners
in seven of the 10 years that they were owned by the Bush group.
They won division titles in 1996 and 1998. Attendance soared from
an average of 18,218 a game in the five years before the sale to an
average of 31,228 in the 10 years after.
</P>
<P>
   Bush played a role in approving the dismissal and subsequent
hiring of one general manager and two field managers, and he
approved major trades, including one lamentable move that sent a
promising minor-league outfielder to the Chicago White Sox. His
name was Sammy Sosa. Bush also became one of the team's most
visible and popular ambassadors, giving speeches, chatting up
reporters, negotiating television contracts, representing the team
at league meetings and signing autographs for hundreds of fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a well-known name and that created interest in the
franchise,'' said Tom Schieffer, the Rangers president. ``It gave
us a little celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest improvement for the Rangers was the construction of
the Ballpark at Arlington, a 47,000-seat stadium with old-fashioned
elegance and plenty of revenue-producing sky boxes. Bush helped
conceive the design of the stadium, and supported the notion of
financing its construction through a half-cent increase in
Arlington's sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   With other cities in the Dallas-Fort Worth area eager to steal
the team, Arlington officials quickly signed on to the tax increase
and then joined with the Rangers in selling the measure to voters.
Bush helped plot strategy for the referendum campaign but kept a
relatively low profile. With Bush's father in the White House, the
Rangers did not want the politics of the new stadium to become
partisan. Bush critics speculate that the aspiring politician also
did not want to be closely associated with a tax increase. Early in
1991, the tax referendum passed by a margin of nearly 2-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   Under the city's agreement with the Rangers, Arlington would use
its sales tax to generate $135 million while the team would foot
the rest of the bill, ultimately about $60 million. Those proceeds
not only built the stadium, which opened in 1994, but also paid for
an office building, an amphitheater, a museum, a park, a youth
field and substantial acreage surrounding the ballpark that is
slated for commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   The team pays the city's sports authority about $5 million
annually for rent and maintenance. It eventually will have the
option of buying the $195 million complex for less than its
original cost, with the Rangers' annual rent and maintenance
payments acting as credits toward the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the stadium arrangement call it the most egregious
form of corporate welfare and argue that the tax increase stands in
contrast to Bush's anti-tax politics. He responds that Arlington
voters made their own decision. ``I could see the case if this were
cramming down a tax and people had no choice in the matter,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium, and the adjacent landholdings, vastly increased
the value of the franchise. Last June, Thomas O. Hicks, a Dallas
entrepreneur, paid $250 million for it, the second largest amount
ever paid for a professional baseball team. Bush's share came to
$14.9 million, and he may receive up to $2 million more after a
final accounting, on his small initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had withdrawn from the daily management of the Rangers
franchise after being elected governor in 1994. But many of his
business associates have become valuable political friends as well.
Rainwater, for instance, gave $100,000 to Bush's 1994 campaign, and
Hicks and his wife have contributed $70,000 since 1995, according
to campaign finance records.
</P>
<P>
   On April 15, Bush reported that he and his wife, Laura, paid
$3.8 million in federal income taxes for 1998 on estimated taxable
income of $18.4 million. Their annual income had averaged $416,703
in the previous seven years. ``I never dreamed I'd write a check
that big,'' Bush said of his tax bill at the time. ``Of course, I
never dreamed I'd make that much money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
