<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, attention weekend editors:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans an in-depth look at George W. Bush and
his finances for its Saturday front page. We commend it to your
attention for possible weekend use:
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FINANCES (Austin, Texas) _ When George W. Bush first ran
for governor of Texas five years ago, he had no record in politics,
only a famous name and a business career that he described as a
success. That boast may be truer today than it was in 1994. As Bush
seeks to spring from the governorship to the presidency, he does so
with the financial security provided by his 2,359 percent gain from
last year's sale of the Texas Rangers, which transformed his
$606,000 investment in the baseball team into a $14.9 million
payday. But closer inspection of Bush's two decades in the private
sector in Texas, which began in the oil patch in Midland and ended
in the owner's box in Arlington, suggests that his record was
decidedly mixed. His business dealings also illuminate an essential
question of his biography: whether his success is primarily
inherited or achieved. It is a question that has dogged Bush, as a
son of former President George Bush, throughout his business
career, as throughout his political life. By Kevin Sack. (4500
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, we are also preparing an abridged version approximately
half the length of the original.
</P>
