<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGER THAN FICTION, DUMBER THAN DIRT
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, May 10)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing you can say about a life of crime: It's a profession
open to anyone, no matter how low your test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, judging by the following honest-to-goodness police
stories, culled from the Web site www.dumbcrooks.com, it appears
that your average toaster oven has more live cells bumping around
upstairs than some of today's criminals:
</P>
<P>
   THE JOB: In California, a pair of would-be crooks pulled into a
bank's drive-up lane, put their stick-up note in the pneumatic
tube, pressed the button to send it in, then patiently waited in
their car for the loot to arrive. Police arrived a few minutes
later and arrested the two men.
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSON: Pneumatic tubes are a poor way to deliver stick-up
notes because you've got to drive to the bank and there's always
the chance that the person in front of you will undertake some
complex and time-consuming financial transaction, like asking for a
personal check to be cashed or taking out a second mortgage on his
or her house. Better to send in your stick-up note by mail. Just be
sure to enclose a self-addressed, stamped envelope and your
driver's license or some other form of personal ID so the bank does
not send the money to the wrong person.
</P>
<P>
   THE JOB: A 350-pound man tried to rob a Long Island jewelry
store. While ordering everyone in the store to ``hit the floor,''
the would-be robber lost his balance and fell to the floor himself.
Unfortunately for him, he was unable to get up. Some police
officers were kind enough to help him to his feet a few minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSON: Physical fitness is very important in today's
fast-paced world of jewelry-store stickups because you never know
when you're going to fall to the floor and not be able to get up.
However, as a general rule, it is not necessary to personally
demonstrate the command ``hit the floor,'' just as it is not
usually necessary to demonstrate the command ``stick 'em up!'' or
``put all your cash and valuables into this bag!'' Also, at no time
should you shoot yourself to demonstrate that your gun is loaded.
</P>
<P>
   THE JOB: A Houston man stood in front of a store, pointed to a
wanted poster in the window, and said proudly to everyone walking
by, ``That's me!''
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSON: It can be a heady experience to see one's picture
posted in a public place. Still, unless the photo on your wanted
poster is extremely flattering, it's probably best not to mention
it to strangers, especially if they happen to be wearing a badge.
</P>
<P>
   THE JOB: A San Francisco bank robber robbed one teller and then
strolled over to the new-accounts desk and tried to open a savings
account. The first teller quietly called police as the second
teller helped the crook complete his application.
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSON: This is really one stupid crook. Everybody knows
you're wasting your time putting your money in a savings account
these days. He would have been much better off putting his money in
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   THE JOB: A masked gas station bandit aimed his index finger at
the attendant and demanded money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be kidding,'' said the attendant. The bandit
moved in closer, at which time the attendant grabbed the deadly
finger and gave it a good twist. The robber screamed and ran out
the door.
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSON: In a situation like this, the robber probably would
have done well to fire his finger in the air a couple of times to
show the clerk he meant business. Since most finger guns are
noiseless, the robber will have to provide his own sound effects
such as POW!, KERBLAM!, or the tried-and-true BANG! And never,
never stand close enough to your victim that he can grab your
finger-gun, as this jams the mechanism and makes it impossible to
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
