<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTOR-DIES08-COX     05-07 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-DIES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctor's generosity will live on, despite her death
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The greatest tragedy in Dr. Peggy Rummel's death
Friday is that more people didn't know what she did with her life.
</P>
<P>
   One of only four physicians in Colquitt, Rummel, 43, attracted
national attention after she was diagnosed last January with
terminal liver cancer and began searching the country for another
doctor to continue her work in the tiny southwestern Georgia town.
</P>
<P>
   But for years, Rummel had quietly built a reputation in Colquitt
for doing far more than her job as a family physician required,
caring for foster children and nursing home patients and treating
anyone who needed care, even if they couldn't pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been that way, always so giving,'' Rummel's
husband, Larry, said Friday. ``You don't know how lucky a person
I've been to know her. I've known that a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of South Carolina, Peggy Rummel came to Colquitt 16
years ago to start a medical practice in a place where few doctors
wanted to be. Miller County has only about 6,200 residents and just
one hospital, an aging facility with 38 beds. Soon after arriving,
though, she began working to improve the community and the lives of
its residents _ particularly the children, said James Ard, who met
Rummel when he ran the state Department of Human Resources office
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a medical neglect case would come about and somebody
would claim they didn't have the money to take the children to the
doctor, there was no problem,'' Ard said. ``Dr. Rummel would say,
`Send them to me,' and she'd take care of them and provide medical
care at no charge or little charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could not have made a whole lot of money,'' he said,
``because if there was a need by a child, she would close her
office and go take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rummel also began taking in foster children, even those with
behavioral or medical problems who were hard to place.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Rummel opened her home to 10 foster children,
and she filled the stockings of 150 others with toys every
Christmas and gave them baskets of goodies every Easter. She
provided playground equipment for the local social services office.
She took Christmas gifts to every nursing home resident in the
county and paid to furnish the birthing room at Miller County
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   When a lack of business threatened the hospital's future, she
encouraged other doctors to send more patients there, and the doors
remained open. For five years, she chaired the county's Board of
Health, developing plans to provide care to the area's poorest
residents _ work that continued even after she was diagnosed with
cancer and given no more than eight weeks to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when you would expect someone to be more concerned
about themselves,'' said Ann Addison, who runs the Miller County
Health Department, ``she just continued to turn her attention
toward her community.''
</P>
<P>
   Rummel especially wanted to make sure another doctor took over
her practice, treating the poor and delivering the 40 or so babies
born every month at Miller County Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after learning she had cancer, Rummel posted a letter on
the Internet, pleading for a doctor to come to Colquitt. The
unusual appeal generated national and international publicity and
brought hundreds of responses from well-wishers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But for weeks, as Rummel's time grew shorter, she could find no
physician to continue her practice. Friends said Friday that the
effort sustained her as she lived two months longer than doctors
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what was keeping her here,'' said the Rev. Eric
Sizemore, a Methodist minister. ``I really believe these last few
days, she literally lived by willpower.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, just last week, Dr. Ikefan-Shango Simon, 34, a native
of the U.S. Virgin Islands who recently completed his residency at
a Columbus hospital, agreed to take over. He drove to Colquitt to
meet Rummel last week, the day she was admitted to the hospital for
the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was at such peace,'' Simon said Friday from the Columbus
hospital, where his wife, Wendy, was about to give birth to their
first child. ``When you give, you do well in life. I think you
could die with that peace. That's a lesson we all need to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Rummel, who leaves behind her husband, a son, Larry Rummel Jr.,
her father and two sisters, taught many lessons in Colquitt, her
friends said, not the least of which was to honor the quiet
achievements of ordinary people while they're still alive. That
theme will resonate during a memorial service at 10 a.m. Monday at
the Colquitt United Methodist Church. The family has requested that
Rummel be honored with contributions to the Miller County Hospital
or the American Cancer Society, rather than with donations of
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She deserved the recognition,'' said Ard, the state
social-services official. ``It's just a shame we didn't do it
during her lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
