</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADGRAD08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA dropout back in town to get his degree _ at age 89
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Throughout his life, Hubert Tucker often planned how
he would return to the University of Georgia and finish his
undergraduate degree, a goal he had abandoned in 1934 to care for
his ailing mother.
</P>
<P>
   But he never made it. A successful career in education, marriage
and a son, service in the U.S. Army during World War II and running
a family business all intervened, preventing him from re-entering
the Terry College of Business as a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been on my mind all the years,'' said Tucker, 89, who
operates a gift shop on the square in Lawrenceville a few days a
week. ``It didn't hold me up not to have a college degree, but I
did think of it often. I was just too busy to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   As things turned out, he didn't have to _ the university
determined this spring that he had earned enough college credits
while in the Army to complete his B.S.C., a bachelor's of science
in commerce, based on standards in place when he was a student.
This morning, Tucker will be among the 5,000 or so students
receiving undergraduate degrees from UGA _ only his is dated June
5, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker received his diploma a few weeks ago at an awards
ceremony for business school alumni, but plans to participate in
today's festivities. When he held the diploma in his hands, ``we
both cried, we were so thrilled,'' said Annette Tucker, who married
Hubert in 1941. Their son, Hubert Tucker Jr., a dentist in
Lawrenceville, had contacted UGA about the 1940s credits, which his
father earned while studying psychology so he could counsel wounded
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `We're not giving this to you, you earned it,'''
said Hubert Tucker. ``It was a joy to me to get it. I appreciate it
so much. Now I'll be an alumni.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without a degree, Tucker is no stranger to Athens. His wife
and he have been season ticket holders for Georgia Bulldog football
games since 1942, when the university began keeping records of
seating assignments. Both Tucker and his son have served as
president of the Gwinnett County Bulldog Club.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating as valedictorian from Royston High in 1927,
Tucker attended Oglethorpe College until 1929, when the stock
market crash sent him back home to work. With a loan from family
friend D.W. Brooks, later the president of Goldkist, Tucker
enrolled at UGA in 1932, taking an overload of classes until he
left to care for his mother in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   He became a junior high principal in Hart County, then worked
for the Crane Plumbing Supply Co. in Atlanta before joining the
National Youth Administration in Habersham County, running a trade
school in Clarkesville.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II army duty, Tucker and his family settled in
Lawrenceville, where his father-in-law was a physician who had
started Williams Drug Store. The Tuckers bought the store and ran
it for years, with Mrs. Tucker _ one of the state's first female
pharmacists _ as druggist and Mr. Tucker as manager.
</P>
<P>
   They sold the business in 1965, and Tucker returned to his
education roots, running a Manpower Development Training program
and setting up a training center in Gainesville. He oversaw the
vocational center and then worked with an educational program for
youth offenders, retiring from the state Department of Education in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Tucker clan _ including Hubert Jr., his wife, Carol,
and most likely their two daughters _ will gather on campus for
graduation. Tucker said he already has tried on the cap and gown
his son had gotten for him, ``and it felt fine. I'm just pleased to
be able to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
