<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-FAMILY-2NDTAK     05-07 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-FAMILY-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
OKLAHOMA CITY: looking bad.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oklahomans are accustomed to bad weather, but there was
something different about this storm; its size, the warnings _ the
Howards couldn't ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   They briefly discussed leaving, but opted to stick it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a radio, flashlights, shoes, pillows, blankets and all
of us a jacket, and we got in the closet,'' Tommy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we just waited and waited and waited.''
</P>
<P>
   When the tornado finally hit, Tommy saw debris from his
shattering house flying overhead. He used his body to cover Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Karen held Jimmy as tightly as she could.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all caved in on me and Jimmy,'' she said. ``Actually, I
think I had my eyes closed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and I saw my wife's car go over,'' Tommy said.
``Something hit me in the ear and head. I have no idea what hit my
arm. Bailey was screaming. Karen was screaming. Jimmy was
screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, ``They're all right, they're alive.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he could stand, Tommy dug his way free.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken and battered, the Howards found rides to the Whitterns'
home about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Tommy and Karen pulled their kids to freedom,
they were survivors, not victims, and they started looking ahead
and taking care of details that would rebuild their futures.
</P>
<P>
   Both contacted their employers and got some time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work for a good company,'' said Tommy, who is employed by a
wholesale office supply firm. ``They said, `Your paycheck will be
there every week.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Karen, too, is guaranteed her job as the family gets over the
aftershock of the tornado.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's insurance company provided some cash to tide them
over. Three days after the tornado, they were still getting busy
signals from all the government numbers where loans and other help
for survivors was being offered.
</P>
<P>
   Once the rubble is bulldozed from their plot, the Howards will
know what condition the foundation is in and the chances of
rebuilding on the same site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to move from our neighborhood,'' Tommy said.
``Bailey is one of the top students in her school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really liked it there,'' Karen said. ``We loved all our
neighbors. The kids were just wonderful together.''
</P>
<P>
   As they sat close together on the Whitterns' couch, their
children playing nearby, the Howards said they would never consider
relocating. Oklahoma City is their home.
</P>
<P>
   Physically exhausted, they still laughed and talked, never once
expressing doubt in the future.
</P>
<P>
   After all, said Tommy, ``those two little rugrats made it
through.'' He shook his head in amazement and stared at Bailey and
Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out ``The Wizard of Oz'' is Jimmy's favorite movie.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy wrapped his arms around Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to nickname her Dorothy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
