<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY'S PLIGHT: `HOLD ME, MOMMY, HOLD ME' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (with art) 
 
By PATTI MUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Two-year-old Jimmy Howard is just learning to
talk, but he already knows how to say ``tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the killer storm destroyed his home Monday, he's been
asking his parents when the twister is coming back. Safe and sound
in the spacious and comfortable living room at his grandparents'
undamaged home here, he still doesn't like it when his parents,
Karen and Tommy Howard, leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   The spunky, blond toddler, feeling the effects of an earache and
an interrupted routine, stretched up his little arms and begged,
``Hold me, mommy, hold me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not gonna hit us again, Bubba,'' Tommy assured him.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting cross-legged on the floor nearby, carefully coloring a
picture of a lizard, Jimmy's 6-year-old sister, Bailey, wondered if
they still planned to travel to a family wedding in Tennessee soon.
But all her pretty dresses are gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Howards are among thousands of Oklahomans who escaped
Monday's monster storms with their lives saved, but forever
changed.
</P>
<P>
   For the Howard family, daily life, routine, the things you can
set your watch by, stopped at 7:18 p.m. May 3.
</P>
<P>
   It was an agonizing 36 hours before Tommy Howard was allowed to
return to the home where his family had lived and nearly died. The
Howards passed the hours in the undamaged nearby home of Jim and
Janette Whittern, Karen's parents, watching news reports to tell
them when it was safe to go back. They answered phone calls from
worried family members and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Finally they heard that the gas lines and electrical wires were
shut off, and the area opened to residents.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy and his father-in-law were the first ones in Wednesday
morning. The comfortable middle-class subdivision was barely
recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   The Howard house on 127th Place was a mangled heap.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning brought sunny skies, and several of the
Howards' relatives and friends showed up, along with Karen, to put
in a 10-hour shift at the post-storm salvage operation.
</P>
<P>
   All their major appliances were gone; vehicles totaled; not a
stick of furniture to be found. Piece by piece, hour by hour, the
family picked through piles of debris, discovering small treasures
that made them happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's my kids,'' Karen shouted with joy as her sister-in-law
held up a photo of Bailey and Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   Karen flipped through the pages of her grandmother's Bible,
thrilled to have saved that piece of family history.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband keeps asking why don't I cry,'' Karen said. ``I
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the family's important papers were safe at Karen's
office, where she works for the state of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy found his fishing poles and some of his tools.
</P>
<P>
   Karen's wedding ring, placed temporarily on a kitchen shelf,
never appeared.
</P>
<P>
   But some of her treasured Beanie Babies were fine.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Jimmy's pacifiers were scattered around the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always carries a spare,'' his father joked.
</P>
<P>
   They filled Jim and Janette Whittern's garage with their
first-day's discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more than happy with what we found,'' Tommy said. ``We
wanted all those pictures, and I wanted my wife to get her Beanie
Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   As they prepared to put Bailey and Jimmy to bed for the night,
there was one item they still missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy, honey, I didn't find your blanket,'' Karen said as the
child hugged her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Tommy, his best friend, Steve Bryant, and Jim
Whittern were first on the scene again. A cool north breeze blew,
and the sky, cobalt blue, promised another day of fine scavenging.
After the Wednesday crowds, the neighborhood was sparsely populated
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy found the hat he was wearing when the tornado struck and
vowed to return it to the friend who gave it to him. The men were
optimistic but more selective in what they decided to save.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the salvage job had more of a purpose as the Howards
started thinking about rebuilding. The neighborhood wouldn't look
like this forever, they knew.
</P>
<P>
   They hoped the pattern would be debris removal _ then
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, May 3, was Karen Howard's 33rd birthday. After work that
evening, she went to a nearby gym to work out and then drove to the
family's new home in Eastlake Estates in southwest Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Remodeled and with all new appliances, the Howards' home of 10
months was exactly what they'd dreamed of during their eight-year
marriage. Both born and reared in the area, they were within a few
miles of an extended family of in-laws, sisters, brothers and
lifetime friends. Their children were happy in the new neighborhood
and made fast friends with other kids their age.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy fired up the grill to cook his wife a special dinner. Then
he turned on the TV news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Karen to feed the kids, I'm gonna put the chicken on
hold,'' he recalled. ``By then, it was really looking bad.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
