<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-B     05-07 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAU GESTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 09, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than a decade of people talking about it,
``convergence'' is finally becoming a reality, though widespread
broadband service is still years in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The cable television, telephone, computer, software, and
Internet industries are beginning to come together to provide a
single wire _ ``a fat digital pipe'' _ that will be capable of
delivering a torrent of video, voice, and data to homes and
offices. The many new business combinations last week were just the
beginning of the latest round.
</P>
<P>
   How will the communications infrastructure be assembled from
among competing technologies of copper telephone wire, coaxial and
fiber-optic cable, wireless, and satellites? Who will write the
protocols that govern their interconnection? It isn't clear, though
AT&AMP;T Corp.'s decision to buy the nation's largest cable TV company
gives a strong signal of the direction that change will take.
</P>
<P>
   What seems reassuringly certain, however, is that the regulators
at the antitrust division of the Department of Justice, who set in
motion these far-reaching events with a trio of key decisions made
over the course of a quarter century, will retain the power to
shape events in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1969 that government antitrust attorneys brought suit
against IBM Corp. on the last day of the administration of Lyndon
Johnson. Even before they filed, they gained important relief when
IBM defensively unbundled the software it had been selling with its
mainframes, thereby permitting an independent software industry to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1981, with the government still doggedly
pressing its case (and suffering biting criticism,) that IBM made
its crucial error. It granted an exclusive license to supply
operating systems for its new personal computers to Microsoft Corp.
_ and the little start-up quickly learned how to dominate the
market for personal computer software.
</P>
<P>
   The very next year, Ronald Reagan's antitrust division folded
its suit against IBM _ but forced the breakup of AT&AMP;T. Within a few
years it had become clear that the effect of separating the Bell
System's long distance business from its regional phone monopolies
had been to stimulate a blizzard of innovation in satellite
technology and fiber-optic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement became the basis for the deregulation of other
utilities, including electric power and natural gas. And of course
the restructuring of the communications industry was still picking
up speed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1997, the antitrust division again filed suit, this time
against Microsoft, charging it with attempting to use monopoly
power to squeeze Netscape out of the market for Internet browsers.
The trial is still going on; a great deal of evidence has been
adduced.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible Microsoft will be found innocent. It doesn't seem
likely. Whatever happens, it is already clear that the next epoch
will be ``post-PC,'' and that Microsoft will have to find new
strategies if it is to remain dominant.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all this commotion, Microsoft last month threw a
party, or rather a one-day meeting, on ``Competition and Innovation
in the Personal Computer Industry.'' (Twenty other leading computer
companies footed smaller parts of the bill.) Once postponed, the
conference was held in late April at a fancy hotel near a golf club
in Carlsbad, California.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was guessing why.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding was Richard Schmalensee, 55, dean of the Sloan School
of Management at the Massachusetts institute of Technology, former
member of the President's Council of Economic Advisers, former
consultant on privatization to the Russian government _ and chief
economic witness for Microsoft. Attending was much of the cream of
the community of economists who study the new electronic networks.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting new work were some of the strongest of a new
generation of microeconomists: Joseph Farrell and Michael Katz of
the University of California at Berkeley on ``Integration and
Innovation in Systems Markets''; Jean Tirole, Jacques Cremer, and
Patrick Rey of the Institut d'Economie Idustrielle in Toulouse on
``Connectivity in the Commercial Internet''; Hal Varian of the
University of California at Berkeley on ``Buying, Sharing and
Renting Information Goods.'' Listening were a galaxy of stars,
including a couple of antitrust division chief economists.
</P>
<P>
   What were they doing there?
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence Microsoft ever gave serious thought to
starting an economics department to inform its strategic behavior.
Unlike AT&AMP;T _ which during the years it was under threat, hired
top-notch researchers, sponsored conferences, even founded a
refereed scholarly journal _ Bill Gates and his fellow Microsoft
managers have relied on their instincts to tell them what was fair
and what was legal.
</P>
<P>
   Only when they landed in court did they hire Schmalensee and a
battery of other economists at National Economic Research
Associates, a subsidiary of Marsh and McClennin, the insurance
company. Nothing at the Carlsbad meeting suggested that Microsoft
was thinking of starting an economics department now.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they were expecting to learn something about the state
of the art? It didn't seem likely. The only senior Microsoft
executive in evidence at the meeting was Rick Rashid, vice
president of the company's computer science research lab, who gave
a luncheon talk about how Microsoft hoped to change the workplace
of the future.
</P>
<P>
   What, then? The most persuasive interpretation that many
participants could put on it was that the meeting was a sop to
Schmalensee, a way of repairing whatever damage he might have done
to his reputation in the profession in the course of his expert
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   By staging a a showcase for some of the best recent work in
network economics, Schmalensee certainly demonstrated his mastery
of the subject, even if his client hadn't yet assimilated all the
subtleties. If this were the explanation, it would have be an
expensive way to say ``thank you'' to a loyal retainer _ the rooms
were somewhat larger than the usual economics conference, the food
better _ but no big deal by Microsoft standards. A beautiful
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   (Especially at a time when the company is otherwise engaged in
what the Washington Post last week described as ``an all-out
crusade to win friends in Washington that draws on every page of
the traditional political influence playbook.'')
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Carlsbad presenters brought some tough-minded
stuff. Especially interesting were the French, who made a useful
distinction between Internet Service Providers (ISPs) and Internet
Backbone Providers (IBPs) who provide high-bandwith transmission,
routing and interconnection to the ISPs. Antitrust authorities fear
that backbone operators would have incentives to degrade the
quality of their connections to the rest of the network, and the
French provided plenty of reasons to fear that proprietary
standards (of the sort that Microsoft is developing for the cable
TV market) pose a significant threat to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Only one paper that transparently defended Microsoft was
included in the proceedings _ ``Causes and Consequences of Market
Leadership in Software Applications,'' by Stanley Liebowitz of the
University of Texas at Dallas and Stephen Margolis of North
Carolina State University. And only one obvious candidate for
inclusion was not there: a powerful new argument about bundling as
a barrier to entry by Barry Nalebuff of Yale's School of
Management.
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about Microsoft's party, therefore, was the
strong rhetorical point that it quietly made. Economists now
understand the new electronic network industries relatively well.
The analytic toolbox that government economists bring to their task
as architects of competition remains way ahead of business
executives' intuitions _ in even the highest-tech marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
