<P>
   PUBLIC-PESSIMISM (Washington) _ The Littleton, Colo., massacre
and the war in Kosovo have voters feeling depressed and pessimistic
about the nation's future, says Democratic pollster Celinda Lake.
She adds that this mood, if it continues, means Vice President Al
Gore cannot run on a message of ``four more years.'' By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Houston) _ President Clinton is in Texas for
fund-raising events in Houston and Austin, then plans to head to
Oklahoma to visit areas ravaged by tornadoes. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   RELIEF-BUS (Laredo, Texas) _ Seven tons of wheelchairs and other
supplies from a charity in Fresno, Calif., sit in a school bus in
the Rio Grande Valley instead of helping poor people in the
highlands of Mexico's Chiapas region because the Mexican government
won't allow the shipment to enter the country. By DANE SCHILLER.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-BOY (Bridge Creek, Okla.) _ When the winds stopped,
Jordan Wiese's mother was gone. ``I should have held on tighter,''
the 6-year-old later told his grandmother. The mother perished in
the fury of an Oklahoma tornado on Monday. By PATTY REINERT.
(Already filed; photo available on the NYT photo service.)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-SEARCH (Oklahoma City) _ Amid the rubble of Tornado
Alley, rescue workers with dogs continue the grim task of looking
for bodies. So far, the death toll is 41 from Monday's horrific
storms. By KEVIN MORAN.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-VOLUNTEERS (Oklahoma City) _ The effort to deal with
people who no longer have homes and clean up Oklahoma City in the
aftermath of a stormy day has been taken on by an army of
volunteers. By PATTI REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   GONZALES-HOMECOMING (Dallas) _ Army Spec. Steven M. Gonzales,
the Huntsville GI who was released by Yugoslavia last weekend,
arrived back in Texas. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ (Houston) _ Compaq Computer Corp., the world's largest
personal computer maker, is expected to cut the number of
distributors that sell its products to about four from as many as
40 to curb costs and manage inventory, analysts said. By TRICIA
HARRIS.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Robert Stevenson is an epileptic and
is perfectly capable of working, but was fired last year after
working 27 years at a paper company. When the paper company went to
a 12-hour rotating shift, which required employees to work some
days and some nights, Stevenson said the new schedule triggered
more seizures. He is now fighting to get his job back. By L.M.
SIXEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-ARGYLE (New York) _ Hearst-Argyle Television Inc.
announces that revenues for the first quarter grew 30 percent, to
$113.4 million, with earnings of 4 cents per share. Hearst-Argyle
owns and/or manages 26 network-affiliated television stations, and
owns and/or manages seven radio stations. The company's TV stations
reach about 17.5 percent of U.S. households, making it one of the
two largest non-network owned television station groups in the
United States. By The Hearst News Service. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS (Houston) _ Coming off an impressive 5-1 East
Coast road trip, the Houston Astros try to keep it going as they
open a nine-game homestand against Montreal. Jose Lima will be
trying for his fifth victory of the season against the struggling
Expos. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The NBA players have said all along this
season that one of the few benefits of the lockout and shortened
season will be a more inspired, fresher team once the playoffs
start. How will the Houston Rockets, with their three
thirty-something superstars, hold up? By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DISASTER-COMMANDER (Washington) _ The Pentagon this summer will
urge the appointment of a military commander for the United States
who in times of disaster would dispatch troops as needed. The plan
is a response to fears that terrorists may strike U.S. cities with
chemical and biological weapons in the next few years. But some
critics warn that the plan would violate civil liberties. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL-KOSOVO (Washington) _ If a peace agreement is reached
in Kosovo, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., will be claiming a small
part of the credit. Campbell says that the peace drive intensified
after he forced Congress to take stands that amounted to a refusal
to expand the war. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-FAMILY (Oklahoma City) _ A look at one family's struggle
to cope with the aftermath of the tornado. By PATTI MUCK. (Filed
Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   COUPLE-SLAIN (Weimar, Texas) _ The brutal slaying of minister
Norman Sirnic and his wife, Karen, has left the town of Weimar in
the midst of a sad, dark mystery. At first it looked as if their
deaths were the act of someone who knew and targeted them. The
police found no sign of anything significant missing. But the
investigation has since revealed that valuable jewelry was missing.
By JAMES PINKERTON. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   RED-LIGHT (Dallas) _ In Dallas, unmarked cars are the chief
weapon against lawlessness. In Arlington and Plano, undercover cops
keep an eye on high-crime venues. In Richardson, special lights
mounted on poles signal to the police that offenses _ namely
red-light runners _ have occurred. Running red lights has become
such a problem that for most of the past year, police agencies have
had special programs and units on the streets to combat it. By JIM
HENDERSON. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   OLD-WEST (Pflugerville, Texas) _ A huge collection of Old West
memorabilia once owned by Wyatt Earp, Doc Holliday, Annie Oakley
and others goes on the auction block. One man compiled the vast
collection over 55 years. By JAMIE STOCKWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The terrible massacre at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., has reinforced many of
our biases instead of opening our minds and changing opinions. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
