<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-LIACOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL J. LIACOS, FORMER CHIEF OF SUPREME JUDICIAL COURT, AT 69 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Paul J. Liacos, former chief justice of the
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court whose opinions on abortion,
the death penalty, and jury selection helped the state retain its
reputation as a bastion of liberalism, died Thursday in
Massachusetts General Hospital. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Liacos was appointed chief justice by then-Governor
Michael S. Dukakis in 1989 and held the post for seven years. He
had been an associate justice of the SJC for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, the court ruled that the state constitution
prohibits the death penalty, provided greater protection for a
women's right to an abortion, and gave defendants greater
protection against search and seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Liacos wrote more than 800 opinions during his 20 years on
the bench. In a Globe story on July 21, 1996, he said he was
proudest of the opinion that prohibited the exclusion of a
prospective juror based on gender, race, or ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1979 opinion on the case that led to the ruling,
Commonwealth v. Soares, he wrote that state law forbids the ``use
of peremptory challenges to exclude prospective jurors solely by
virtue of their membership in or affiliation with particular
defined groupings in the community. ''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office the 13th floor of the Suffolk Courthouse
beneath an oil portrait of Lemuel Shaw, the 19th-century chief
justice who ruled that any slave who arrived in Massachusetts would
be set free, Judge Liacos described the death penalty as ``torture
in the guise of civilized business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What dignity can remain for the government that countenances
its use?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, US Supreme Court Justice Stephen G. Breyer described
Judge Liacos as ``a good friend, a brilliant lawyer and teacher, a
humane judge, and a great chief justice who contributed enormously
to our nation's judicial system. We shall all miss him very much
indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   A second-generation attorney, Judge Liacos was born in Peabody,
where his father worked his way through law school in a leather
factory. Judge Liacos graduated from Boston University and its law
school and earned a master's degree in law at Harvard University. A
veteran of the Air Force, he practiced law in Peabody with his
father and sister as a member of the firm Liacos &AMP; Liacos before
being appointed to the SJC.
</P>
<P>
   He was the author of the ``Handbook of Massachusetts Evidence,''
the definitive volume on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, state Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly described Judge
Liacos as a ``lawyer's judge'' who ``brought practical experience
to his decision-making on the bench'' and understood the
``real-life implications of the cases before him.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Liacos, who was sometimes referred to as ``King Paul'' in
the hallways of the courthouse by some who saw him as abrasive and
arrogant, said he was proud to have forced the court out of its
``ivory tower'' by holding oral arguments in courthouses around the
state and by asking justices to sit on commissions studying racial
bias, substance abuse, and other social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've turned the system around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 Judge Liacos was named to the state Ethics Commission,
which provides legal advice and information to public officials and
public employees and administers the financial disclosure process
for state and county officials.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the current chief justice of the SJC, Herbert P.
Wilkins, said, ``Paul Liacos was a dedicated scholar, a tireless
defender of constitutional rights, and a committed advocate for the
improvement of the administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Maureen (McKean); three sons, James, Mark,
and Gregory; a daughter, Diana; a sister, Katherine Liacos Izzo, a
former Superior Court justice; and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
