<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JOURNAL-0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    REPORTER'S JOURNAL: WORLD'S MEDIA JOCKEYS FOR THE RIGHT TO
REPORT FROM A ``SEA OF MUD''
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This story is UNBUDGETED 
 &HT;    NOTE: Cox Newspapers correspondent Joe Albright is representing
the world's newspapers in a U.S. Army pool set up to cover possible
Apache helicopter attacks. In his first report, he takes a
behind-the-scenes look at the jockeying by media organizations to
get close to the action.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAWK BASE, Albania Six days after our pool was ``activated'' by
the U.S. Army for long-term coverage of its Apache helicopter
strike force, we were finally ``embedded'' late Friday in an Army
tent city perched on a sea of mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embedded pool'' is what the new Army calls it when they allow
a few journalists to live with fighting units and cover what's
happening for the hordes of other journalists stuck outside the
gate. There are six of us ``embeds'' _ two representing the world's
TV stations, one for wire services, one for newspapers and one for
still photographers.
</P>
<P>
   After being ``activated'' last Saturday, we waited four days,
some of us beating back the pangs of anticipation at the bar of the
main hacks' hotel in Tirana, an overpriced hostel called the
Rogner.
</P>
<P>
   When first activated, the pool consisted of CNN, BBC-TV,
National Public Radio, Cox Newspapers, Reuters wire service and AP
photo. But every day since then, the lineup has shifted as the
world's big media scrape to staff what will probably turn out to be
the world's most expensive war to cover. First CNN dropped out,
then BBC-TV, after they and other TV networks around the world
agreed to share video feeds from a slimmed-down TV crew of two
persons, one each supplied by Reuters TV and Associated Press TV.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, the panjandrums of network television were
skirmishing in Washington about the very concept of an
</P>
<P>
   ``embedded pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ABC's Nightline program got permission several weeks
ago to be ``embedded'' with Task Force Hawk here at Rinas to
provide so-called ``unilateral'' (exclusive) coverage, protests
from NBC, CBS, CNN, and Fox television have ricocheted around the
Pentagon back in Washington. How can you call it a ``pool,'' CNN
demanded, when there is also a ``unilateral'' crew like Nightline
living with the Army and grabbing off the best visuals?
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, we embeds-in-waiting got a decisive e-mail
from Lt. Col. Garrie Dornan, the spokesman of Task Force Hawk. We
were to report to be embedded at 10 a.m. on Friday at what has come
to be called the ``humanitarian gate'' of Rinas Air Field near
Tirana. (''Humanitarian'' because it is where the trucks come when
they are hauling in food to be transported to ethnic Albanian
refugees by humanitarian helicopters.)
</P>
<P>
   But then on Friday at the crack of dawn, we got another e-mail
from Task Force Hawk. At the suggestion of the Pentagon, our
``embedment'' had been postponed by 24 hours. And all the
journalists in Tirana were suddenly invited to attend a meeting
with Dornan at 11 a.m. at the humanitarian gate.
</P>
<P>
   All sorts of wild thoughts scampered through our sleep-deprived
brains. Had peace broken out in Kosovo? Had someone decided that
the Apaches were no longer needed?
</P>
<P>
   We showed up at 11 a.m. along with a crowd of television
producers loaded for bear. They included NBC, CNN, AP-TV, Fox,
Reuters-TV, ABC, two networks of German TV and AP-TV. Plus most of
us six embed-wannabees.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan was clearly in a conciliatory mood. As we all sat around
on the grass, he told us, ``I am not out here to hurt anybody. I'm
not out here to give exclusive rights to anybody.'' This brought
some rapid-fire ripostes from our television colleagues, still
smarting from Nightline's dramatic exclusive footage of the crash
of an Apache.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan stressed that the main reason for embedding media for a
lengthy period was that when actual combat may be in the offing,
there is a legitimate need for ``operational security.'' He said
that if journalists come in and out of Hawk Base like a ``revolving
door,'' the commanders cannot be certain that they can preserve
operational security.
</P>
<P>
   As Dornan put it, ``in planning news coverage of the military,
some have fallen into the mindset since the Gulf War that all
military operations are for peacekeeping purposes. But Task Force
Hawk is not a peacekeeping operation.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nightline first asked for special access to ``do a piece''
at Rinas a few weeks ago, Dornan said, Task Force Hawk officials
were cool to the idea because there weren't enough public relations
officers to host the crew. But the Nightline team, headed by
correspondent Forrest Sawyer, had support up the chain of command
and was admitted to the Apache base to do some daily stories and a
one-hour documentary to air later.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, there should have been a pool arrangement
sooner,'' Dornan said. But the pool would have been embedded with
the Army sooner if the networks had more quickly come to an
agreement about which of them would supply a crew to staff the pool
assignment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by a string of network producers to make Nightline share
its future news coverage inside Hawk Base, Dornan said this would
be decided at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   All this, plus some detours into the logistics of ``standup
positions'' and ``microwave'' relays for direct TV feeds to
satellites, took nearly two hours.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, there was suddenly a consensus among the
networks that the best thing for the moment was to ``embed'' the
``activated'' pool as rapidly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   By an alphabetical quirk, Cox happened to draw the ``newspaper
print'' slot on this embedded pool that will get direct access to
the Army's Apache force for the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   If an Apache attack should be ordered during that time, we'll
produce the raw materials for the next day's news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Our ``pool reports'' _ video, still photos and written accounts
_ won't be worth anything if we cannot somehow transmit them very
soon after the Army says we can send them.
</P>
<P>
   This is easier said than done. When I was a ``pool reporter''
with an artillery unit in the Gulf War, my editors got none of the
pool reports I gave to the Army during the four-day ground war. In
the Gulf War, we would type out our reports and hand them to
</P>
<P>
   Army couriers, who tended to get lost in the desert on the way
back to the filing centers.
</P>
<P>
   This time, to my amazement, the Army is allowing us to bring in
our own satellite telephones so we can file instantaneously after
news is released.
</P>
<P>
   Progress! But my immediate task is to find some place above the
mud to set up my satphone.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
