<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN TOUCH ALL OVER BRUINS' SUCCESS THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was the all-time classic Youth vs. Experience NHL
trade. On March 1, 1997, the Boston Bruins shipped three players
with a combined age of 96 to the Washington Capitals in exchange
for three players with a combined age of 65.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps received Adam Oates, Rick Tocchet, and Bill Ranford.
The Bruins received Jim Carey, Jason Allison, and Anson Carter.
</P>
<P>
   So which is it? Does Harry Sinden get a standing O next time you
see him, or do you just send him a brief note of apology? And
please don't lie to me. I know you didn't like that deal at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trade was made as much to get rid of some people as to
get some people,'' says Sinden. ``That sometimes happens. But what
was our best choice? Youth.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're in need of an update, Oates remains with Washington,
and one can presume he has a nice big TV on which to watch the
remainder of the playoffs. Tocchet is with Phoenix, presumably with
his own high-quality TV. Ranford is in Detroit, but pretty much in
name only.
</P>
<P>
   Carey, whose baffling descent from Vezina Trophy winner at age
21 to forgotten journeyman backup netminder before his 25th
birthday is downright scary, has landed in Detroit, where he will
at least have a nice view of a likely Stanley Cup march.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just can't play in the league anymore,'' Sinden says.
``I'll take the blame for that one, but I don't understand what has
happened to him. It's like Mo Vaughn hitting three home runs in an
entire season.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two? Live, and in living color, they are doing exactly
what Harry hoped and prayed they could do when he pulled the
trigger on what we referred to in these pages as a ``blockbuster''
deal. That is to say, they are helping a Boston Bruins team that is
sailing merrily along in the Stanley Cup playoffs win hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns was not in the Bruins' employ when that deal was made
with 22 games remaining in the 1996-97 regular season (there would,
alas, be no postseason for the Bruins that year). But he is its
primary beneficiary. Allison and Carter, both now 23, are key
players on his team.
</P>
<P>
   Their imprint was all over the Carolina series. In Game 1 of the
current confrontation with Buffalo, Allison played a magnificent
game, with one very nice goal and one very nice assist the most
tangible demonstrations of his ability. It was the kind of game
everyone hopes will become the norm for this talented center in the
years to come. What, you wonder, was going on in Washington? The
man came here working on a 46-game goal-scoring drought, and it's
not as if people didn't think he had talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's faster than people think and he's stronger than people
think,'' says Burns. ``He has the ability to be a top player in
this league.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had liked Allison since his junior hockey days, but
he arrived here with a reputation, and it wasn't good. ``I had
heard it all,'' Burns says. ``Lazy. Wouldn't work hard. I'll be
quite honest. When I first came here, I didn't have a hard time
believing all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   They kind of came as a package deal. Allison and Carter had been
teammates on a Canadian World Junior Championships team, then spent
time together in the Capitals organization. They readily identify
themselves as very good friends. ``That's why it was exciting for
us to come to Boston together,'' says Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Things weren't particularly rosy for them in Washington, so each
man welcomed the trade. Then there was the matter of coping with
the skepticism that abounded in their new home port.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people knew what to expect,'' Carter says.
``With me, it was, `Who's this Carter guy? If he's so good, why did
he spend time in the minors? This year? What are we getting?' With
Jason, it was, `Oh, he's an underachiever.' We were a bit shocked.
We came to a last-place team, and people were dogging us right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2-inch, 210-pound Allison made a very firm impression
with 33-50_83 numbers last year, a performance that led him into a
major salary battle with the front office. He had no training camp,
and don't get the coach started on that subject. He did not have
the regular season expected of him (23-53_76). The 53 assists were
fine, but the demanding mentor saw a significant flaw in his game,
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's stubborn,'' says Burns. ``He sometimes stays on the puck
too long. He could have had 10 or 12 more goals, easy, but he'll
keep going and then wind up in what we call the `dead' zone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burns has had no complaints with Allison's playoff
performance thus far, and never mind the fact that he was goalless
against Carolina. ``He had six assists, didn't he?'' Burns says.
``There are other contributions someone can make to help a hockey
club, and he did those things. Jason plays every power play, and
he's at the tail end of every penalty kill. He logs a lot of ice
time.''
</P>
<P>
   His new mates would have a hard time reconciling the
underachieving Allison the Caps knew. ``We can see the ability he
has,'' acknowledges Rob DiMaio. ``He can be that go-to guy. He has
the perfect game to shine in the playoffs. When he's on his game,
he can lift you. He can carry you on his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, whose champion two years ago was head pro scout Gerry
Cheevers, was another contract balker. He didn't even join the club
until 12 games into the season, and didn't score a goal until he
bagged two against Tampa Bay in Game 18. In the middle of the
season he missed 15 more games with an ankle injury, leaving him
with modest final totals of 24-16_40. So perhaps it's a good thing
_ assuming he'd like to remain in the coach's good graces _ that he
began to step it up late during the Bruins' late-season charge into
the playoffs (8-3_11 in his final nine games). He had a nice series
against the Hurricanes, the highlight being the double-overtime
game-winner in the pivotal Game 5. Of late, he has been highly
visible on just about every shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really only his second year in the NHL,'' Burns points
out. ``He is much stronger than people think. Guys will run into
him, and you can see them thinking, `Uh-oh, what did I just hit?'
He's always attentive. Some guys fall asleep on you every once in a
while, but he never does.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the deal was supposed to have been Carey, but that's
another story. That would ultimately bring us to the Byron Dafoe
deal, but we don't want Harry's head to get any bigger today. Let's
settle for saying that he can smile from sunrise to bedtime on the
basis of what he pulled off on March 1, 1997. That was a day he did
some four-star GMing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
