<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAUMA-STUDIES-2TAKES     05-07 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAUMA-STUDIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A SLOW START, UNIVERSITIES BEGIN TO RECOGNIZE THE FIELD OF
TRAUMA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Fla., S.D., Ill., Conn., Mass., Calif.)   By PATRICIA COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Soeren Buus Jensen got ready to give a seminar on treating
the shaken Kosovars arriving at Fort Dix, N.J., he recalled the
chaos of the Bosnian refugee camps where he had worked four years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen, the chairman of psychiatry at Copenhagen University
Hospital in Denmark and the World Health Organization's former
coordinator for mental health during the war, was frustrated by how
difficult it was to help terrorized survivors cope with their
trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to New York to learn how it was done here,'' he said,
``but that turned upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no program in the city. So he and Jack Saul, a
clinical assistant professor in psychiatry, decided to create one.
Last year, they inaugurated the International Trauma Studies
program at New York University. Designed for professionals already
working in the field, Saul says it is one of the first in the
United States to combine academic research on trauma with mental
health programs developed under wartime conditions.
</P>
<P>
   From the punishing cycle of violence in the Balkans to the
string of teenage killing sprees at high schools, trauma has become
nearly as commonplace as the weather on the evening news. Whether
in the form of wartime compensation, charges of childhood sexual
abuse, or insurance claims, it has rippled through boardrooms and
bedrooms, emergency rooms and courtrooms across the United States.
Nearly everywhere, it seems, except the university classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Although many skeptics question whether the effects of trauma
are genuine, a number of specialists in the field say that American
universities have been slow to contribute to the recent flood of
advances in the study and treatment of trauma. Traditionally the
domain of psychology, trauma has more recently grabbed the
attention of nurses, social workers, neurobiologists, public health
workers, medical researchers and more. Yet universities, they say,
have often failed to knit together these various disciplines and
take the lead in creating comprehensive study and research
programs.
</P>
<P>
   That may be changing. The experience of clinicians who work with
sexually abused children, disaster survivors, refugees and the like
has begun to force colleges to rethink their approach. At the same
time, advances in neurobiology are showing that trauma can affect
the body much more than previously thought. Brain imaging
techniques and medical research have found that trauma leaves its
scars on the very structure of the brain and central nervous
system, that it can alter the immune system, cripple learning, and
shorten lifespan. The result could transform the way trauma is
taught, understood and treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academe is being overtaken by what is happening in the real
world,'' says Charles Figley, Director of the awkwardly named
Traumatology Institute at Florida State University. ``Now there is
a critical mass of scholarly and professional work in trauma
studies, and a critical mass of students who demand this. That's
exactly how new fields start.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Florida State is reviewing a proposal to become the
first school in the country to offer a graduate degree in trauma
studies. Said Figley, ``It's almost like the university is finally
coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Other colleges are experimenting as well. The University of
South Dakota now offers a degree in disaster psychology. The
program, approved four months ago by the state board of regents, is
aimed at psychology students who want to specialize in researching
and responding to catastrophes like hurricanes and earthquakes. The
University of Illinois at Chicago has just established a fellowship
in Refugee Mental Health for psychiatry residents. Both UIC and
Yale University have sponsored monthly trauma studies workshops in
recent years for professionals, scholars and survivors to talk
about the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This field is exploding; it's taken off,'' said Judith Herman,
a clinical professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Trauma is not a new idea. Writers as far back as Homer wrote of
it, societies as old as Carthage lived through it. But the
recognition of trauma as a specific disorder appropriate for
scientific scrutiny is barely 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Herman explains in her classic book ``Trauma and
Recovery,'' the understanding of trauma has been shaped as much by
social attitudes and politics as by medical research. Without a
political movement to support the scientific investigation, trauma
research has sunk out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century French neurologist Jean-Martin Charcot was the
first to study hysteria, rescuing it from the domain of demons and
witches, and claiming it for science. Sigmund Freud, Joseph Breuer
and Pierre Janet, who attended Charcot's famous
Barnum-and-Bailyesque lectures, built on the idea that hysteria was
the result of traumatic experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The subject disappeared until the First World War resuscitated
it. Traumatic reactions were considered a sign of deep character
flaws. Shell-shocked soldiers were often described as ``moral
invalids'' and threatened with court martials. The British
psychiatrist Lewis Yealland tried to shame and punish traumatized
soldiers back to health. He applied electric shocks to the vocal
cords of those who had lost their ability to speak. As the anti-war
movement in Britain grew, so did a more compassionate approach
based on psychoanalytic principles.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly Vietnam veterans who joined the antiwar movement
argued their comrades who were haunted by nightmares and
flashbacks, rage and panic were not weak-willed cowards, but
suffered from the severe aftershocks of combat. Bessel van der
Kolk, who now runs the country's largest trauma clinic in
Brookline, Mass., remembers treating veterans after the war: Even
in 1978, ``there was not a single book in the Boston Veterans
Administration library on war neurosis.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only a political alliance between Vietnam veterans and
feminists (who brought the trauma of rape victims and battered
wives into the open) that eventually forced the scientific
establishment to take notice. In 1980 ``post-traumatic stress
disorder'' was included in the official manual of mental disorders
put out by the American Psychiatric Association.
(MORE)
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trauma is not simply a more extreme version of everyday stress.
People can't just snap out it. Exposure to terrifying events can
overwhelm and break down the body's natural system of self-defense.
Traumatic memories continually bulldoze their way into the present.
Research shows these may be stored in a different part of the brain
than regular memories, says van der Kolk, who is also a psychiatry
professor at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Trauma leaves its mark on the brain in other ways as well, he
adds. Researchers examining Vietnam veterans who suffered from
severe PTSD found that the hippocampus _ the part of the brain
involved in memory _ had significantly shrunk in size. Another
study found that women with histories of chronic sexual abuse had a
higher than average number of immunological disorders. Most
recently, a large-scale study in California found that people who
were exposed to traumatic events as children were much more likely
to develop lung disease, obesity, diabetes, heart disease, cancer
and drug and alcohol addictions. Yet even now, van der Kolk says,
``major institutions, notably Harvard, have resisted looking at how
reality shapes biology.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Trauma's sprawling character is precisely what has made it so
difficult for universities to swallow. ``It doesn't fit into
existing structure,'' said Figley, a Vietnam veteran whose anti-war
activities got him interested in the field, ``that's why
universities have been slow to move into this. ''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   With the field less than 20 years old, many questions about
trauma remain unanswered: How does it affect the ability to learn?
How does it cripple a child's development? Does trauma trigger
other mental disorders? Physical diseases? Is psychoanalysis an
outdated approach for dealing with mass trauma?
</P>
<P>
   Both university professors and clinicians believe no single
discipline has the answers. ``Psychoanalysis was never intended to
be all things,'' explained Stevan Weine, an associate professor of
psychiatry at the University of Illinois, who has worked with
Bosnian refugees. ``One thing it certainly was never to be was a
public health effort to address the social suffering of genocide
survivors. The mental health work with survivors... was influenced
far less by psychoanalysis and more by the social psychiatry and
the community mental health movement.''
</P>
<P>
   At this early stage, it's not surprising that intellectual
breakthroughs, particularly in regard to treatment, are more likely
to come from the field than the classroom. For instance, clinicians
working with severely abused children here developed techniques to
curb traumatic memories.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   But while Saul think it will take years before such experience
is woven into the academic mainstream, he believes ``creating a
multidisciplinary program, enables the kind of work that is being
done in the field to be done in the university setting.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herman says there has been a lot of intellectual
cross-fertilization between clinicians and university researchers.
But she add, ``Sometimes academics don't understand how deeply
dependent they are to the grass roots activists and how indebted
the whole field is to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
