<SLUG> BC-MEEHAN-TO-RUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. MEEHAN TO BREAK PLEDGE, SEEK FIFTH TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representative Martin T. Meehan, the Massachusetts
Democrat, has decided to break his pledge against seeking a fifth
House term, telling constituents in a letter mailed Friday that it
would be unfair to ``arbitrarily limit my own service.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after Meehan for years had criticized
politicians who were unwilling to limit their time in office,
saying at one point that such people were ``bad for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   While Meehan's announcement has long been expected, he said in
an interview that he spent months weighing the political impact of
breaking the vow. He said he knows some people will interpret his
decision as confirmation that politicians say one thing and do
another.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Meehan said he decided he has gained too
much influence and seniority in the House to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made sense at the time,'' Meehan said of his pledge. ``It
was a mistake, there is no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, 42, said he was told dropping out of the race would hurt
the congressional district. ``People have said to me, `If you are
not doing your job, we'll throw you out,' '' Meehan said. ``It is
the people's choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan had a different view in 1992, when he promised to step
aside after four two-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for the country to have members of Congress who are
absolutely desperate to get reelected,'' Meehan said at the time.
``I don't want to spend 20 years in Washington. I want to do my job
and do it well, and then get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Meehan has continued to say he favored term
limits. In 1995, he said on the House floor: ``I have always been
skeptical of the legislators who claim they are for term limits but
have been in office for 15 or 20 years. The best test of any
politician's credibility on term limits is whether they are willing
to put their career where their mouths are and limit their own
service.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1998, it was reported by the organization US Term
Limits that Meehan had reaffirmed his term-limit pledge, and he
told a group called Project Vote Smart that he supported term
limits.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's letter, whose distribution was paid for with
campaign funds, Meehan said: ``When I ran for public office for the
first time in 1992, our economy was failing, unemployment was
rising, and Congress was mired in scandal. In response to
overwhelming sentiment, I developed a campaign that focused on job
creation, deficit reduction, and congressional reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan continued: ``To arbitrarily limit my own service puts the
people I represent at a disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were critical of his explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't trust Marty Meehan to keep his word on a simple
term-limit pledge, why should voters believe anything else that
comes out of his mouth?'' said John Brockelman, executive director
of the Massachusetts Republican Party. ``His reaffirmation of his
term-limits pledge every election was a sham to keep himself in
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Brockelman said Republicans would be ``aggressively recruiting a
candidate to run against Marty Meehan. I would imagine this would
have a big impact on potential candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But former representative Chester Atkins, whom Meehan easily
defeated in 1992, said he doesn't bear a grudge against the
congressman for violating the term-limit pledge. Atkins said the
pledge had ``no measurable impact'' on the race. ``I was
flat-lining for a long time,'' Atkins said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that he is running again,'' Atkins said. ``He
has been an extraordinarily effective for the district, the state
and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, who received 71 percent of the vote last year, so far
faces no announced opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
