<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-VOLUNTEERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS EAGER TO HELP NEIGHBORS CLEAN UP TORNADO DAMAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST CITY, Okla. _ Stationed around the world with the U.S.
Navy, Elizabeth Day has weathered a volcano eruption in Italy, a
typhoon on Guam, and an Icelandic storm that swept her and her son,
Roderick, under a semi-truck as they tried to reach shelter.
</P>
<P>
   So when deadly tornadoes roared through the Oklahoma City area
Monday night and passed them by, Day, who is moving to Arkansas,
took the week off from packing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the single mother put 10-year-old Roderick and
23-month-old Joshua in the car and made three trips to area
shelters to drop off clothing and toys.
</P>
<P>
   When Roderick saw that the television stations were collecting
donations, the Days spent Wednesday and Thursday volunteering to
sort and box and lift and carry.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, as residents began the tedious work of removing
the debris, the Days boarded a school bus at the Midwest City
Service Center and joined hundreds of volunteers in picking up
trash along Southeast 15th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working right now on dreaming up something for Mother's
Day. Maybe take some roses over to the shelters so the boys can
help other kids cheer up their moms,'' said Day, 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have helped us, so we need to help them,'' she said.
``And this is time that I can spend with my boys and teach them
something positive. When something like this happens, I want them
to know, you drop everything and go help your neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Christy Wampler, a city worker who helped organize the cleanup
crews, said people started showing up by 8 a.m. Friday, hours
before the buses were scheduled to shuttle volunteers to the
cleanup sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent three busloads over there before the 10 a.m. start,''
she said as she handed out gloves and respirators to volunteers.
``People are really anxious to pitch in.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinker Air Force Base sent more than 100 uniformed servicemen
and women to pull large debris from residential neighborhoods in
the city, while civilians concentrated on clearing parking lots of
businesses and churches. They moved wood scraps, twisted metal,
paper and whatever else they found toward the curbs where truck
crews could easily pick it up, and salvaged any personal items they
came across. City workers and relief agencies will try to get
photographs, checks and other belongings back to their owners.
</P>
<P>
   For many residents, the cleanup was an opportunity to meet with
their neighbors, to tell their stories of surviving the killer
storms and to count their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Guild, a nurse and former Houston resident, said she was
used to hurricanes, but this was her first tornado. ``I hid in a
bathroom with three dogs, a cat, a hedgehog and a friend,'' she
said, laughing. But then, tears. ``I feel so guilty,'' she said,
``because everybody around us was hit and we were fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for pictures of my kids,'' said a visibly upset
Karen Upton, a prekindergarten teacher at nearby Traub Elementary
School, which was closed all week. ``I have 36 in my class, and so
far, I've only accounted for 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Royce Davis, a retired military man who served with the Air
Force in Vietnam, also broke down as he and his wife, Dorothy,
carried tree limbs toward the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a daughter who's a teacher and a son who's a paramedic.
He was in Moore working triage Monday night,'' he said, tears
welling and voice breaking. ``The Lord was really gracious to me
and to my family. Midwest City has also been very good to us, and
we're going to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the volunteers recalled helping out during the cleanup
around the Murrah Federal Building after the 1995 bombing. Because
that tragedy was confined to a smaller area, and because it
involved a secured crime scene, it was more difficult for average
residents to offer their services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to get in,'' recalled Steve Anderson, a retired
offshore oil rig worker. ``I had to get a permit every day to get
in, but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, anyone who wants to help is welcome, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even little Joshua Day, who donned adult-size work gloves and
carried sticks and paper, one piece at a time, to his mom, who
helped him put the debris in a trashbag attached to the back of his
stroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Elizabeth Day told her youngest son. ``Every
little bit helps.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
