<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8733 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX     05-07 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS/STARS OWNER HICKS IN DIRE NEED OF MORE COACHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year or so ago, having interviewed Tom Hicks on a couple of
occasions and having watched him being interviewed by a score of
other reporters at various times, I commented to someone who should
know that the Rangers/Stars owner was very good with the media.
</P>
<P>
   They liked him, it seemed. Privately, several members of the
local press corps said he appeared to be a no-nonsense guy, a
straight shooter who returned calls about as often as you can
expect from a guzillionaire. The sort who wouldn't flat-out lie to
you, even if he would occasionally dodge giving a complete answer.
</P>
<P>
   This compliment came from a group not inclined to say nice
things about rich guys in suits, and that includes those of the
sporting kingdom such as Mr. J. Jones and Mr. R. Perot Jr.
</P>
<P>
   That ``someone who should know'' replied something to the effect
of, ``Well, he hasn't always been that way.'' The implication, I
guess, being that Hicks had been coached, and coached well, to say
the right things at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is not always an easy thing to do when you're trying
to convince voters to part with $100 million or so for a new arena
so that you can make yourself a few hundred million more.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he pulled it off. He not only got his vote, he could do
almost nothing wrong in the eyes of the media, short of striking
out on Roger Clemens. And even then they could blame it on Doug
Melvin, or Yankee imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the honeymoon is always sweet, ain't it? It's the next
50 years or whatever that are the test.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is getting his first real media test now that he has
presided over the departure of Rangers president Tom Schieffer.
Usually, it's the dismissal of managers and coaches, or, in some
cases, general managers that gets the media worked up. But a club
president?
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer, however, was well-respected by the area media, in
part because of his love for the game and his support of tradition.
He struck a chord with many when he voiced his concerns for
baseball's have-nots, even as the Rangers' payroll eclipsed that of
several South American nations.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Schieffer's popularity that cast Hicks in a new,
and not altogether flattering light, though. It also was a matter
of style.
</P>
<P>
   Some media portrayals pictured Hicks as a bit of a bully, a
budding George Steinbrenner, for his role in Schieffer's leaving.
It's a funny thing: Texans love entrepreneurial people who do
things big and do them successfully _ oil barons, cattlemen and the
like _ but they don't appreciate it when they get to riding too
tall. Then they like to chop them down.
</P>
<P>
   From reading the accounts of l'affaire Schieffer and listening
to the television and radio post-mortems, it appears Hicks has been
targeted for a bit of chopping himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks also may be paying a price for being a businessman first
and a sportsman second. Every club owner in this century has made
economics his primary focus, of course. Nowadays, it's just a lot
more obvious and a lot less acceptable to those in the media who
don't have $250 million of their own cash invested in
sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Hicks, there are ways to remedy some of this new
image problem, slight changes in style that could trigger a second
honeymoon. The kind a media coach might suggest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hicks should never use the term, ``vertical
integration'' unless, that is, he's talking about having black,
white and Hispanic players up and down the lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he should refrain from using the word ``synergy'' except
when discussing Cinergy Field in Cincinnati, where the Reds play.
Even at that, it might be preferable to drop in a reference or two
to ``old Crosley Field.'' Traditionalists will lap it up.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas are more complicated. Should, for instance, Hicks be
seen attending a Rangers game when the Stars have a playoff match
the same night? Hockey fans, no doubt, weren't thrilled to see the
shirt-and-tie clad boss at The Ballpark watching ``The Rocket'' get
hammered while the Stars were gutting out a triple-OT win over
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think you can fault Hicks for wanting to see Clemens get
lit up. No one likes to be spurned. For those who don't appreciate
revenge, however, it might be wise to play up Hicks' other side,
the one he showed earlier this season when he broke up that row in
the stands at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's throwing around your muscle Texas style. That's the
kind of owner the media and fans can both appreciate.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
