<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT &LR;      05-07 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB BOOM LIFTING UNDERCLASS OUT OF POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's jobs boom has turned into a powerful tide that is
lifting many of the nation's most vulnerable citizens out of
poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the national economy added, on a net basis, nearly a
quarter of a million new jobs despite continued losses in
manufacturing and farming, the Labor Department reported Friday.
Last month's unemployment rate was 4.3 percent _ statistically
indistinguishable from its 30-year low of 4.2 percent in March.
(All numbers are adjusted to take account of expected seasonal ups
and downs.)
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate has now been at or below 4.5 percent for
slightly more than a year and at or below 5 percent for a full two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who were a bit rattled on Thursday by a warning from
the Federal Reserve's chairman, Alan Greenspan, that the tight
labor market still posed an inflation threat, generally took the
strong April job growth in stride. That was mostly because the
report showed no signs that wages were accelerating. But after an
initial gain in the bond market, prices fell, and the yield on the
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose to 5.81 percent. Stocks
gained, with the Dow industrial average up 84.77, to 11,031.59.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking feature of Friday's report was how broadly the
benefits of economic growth are being spread. Joblessness among
workers who have long suffered the highest unemployment rates
continued to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment among African-Americans, already at historic lows,
dropped to 7.7 percent. Teen-age unemployment declined to 14.1
percent. But joblessness among Hispanic workers _ a diverse group
that spans affluent third-generation Americans as well as
impoverished new immigrants _ bumped up from the record low set in
March. Still, at 6.9 percent, the Hispanic rate remains lower than
at almost any time in the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing large gains by the most disadvantaged groups,''
said Rebecca Blank, a member of the White House's Council of
Economic Advisers and an expert on poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nearly half of Americans live in cities and towns where
the unemployment rate has dropped below 4 percent, according to a
new study published by the National Bureau of Economic Research. In
these ``high pressure'' local economies, the employment and incomes
of the most disadvantaged _ the young, those who have only a high
school degree or less, and minorities _ have jumped, said Richard
Freeman at Harvard, one of the study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   Growth that is shared by most Americans has not been the norm
since the economic Golden Age that followed World War II from the
late 1940s to the early 1970s. Back then, rapid economic growth had
a powerful effect on the fortunes of America's poorest citizens,
prompting Arthur Okun, President Johnson's chief economic adviser,
to declare in 1973 that a rising tide lifts all boats. But that
changed almost as soon as he said it, when the Arab oil shock and
the collapse of the Bretton Woods system of stable currency
exchange rates ushered in an era of high inflation, widening
inequality and stagnant wages.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the long, strong boom of the 1980s, when 20 million new
jobs were created, poverty barely fell, and many of America's
working poor, particularly less-educated men, wound up becoming
poorer.
</P>
<P>
   But today there are a host of signs that the gains from economic
growth are once again being spread around. ``The '90s are starting
to look a lot like the '60s,'' said Lawrence Katz, a labor
economist at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers, basketball stars and computer whizzes _
those at the very top of the pay scale _ are still doing great,
just as they did in the '80s. What has changed is that they are no
longer alone. ``Inequality hasn't necessarily diminished, but we
seem to be in a world where the bottom and top are rising
together,'' Dr. Blank said. ``That's a very different world.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the '90s different from the '80s? Two things, the
experts say. First, the current expansion, which began with the
unemployment rate slightly above 7 percent, compared with a
double-digit jobless rate in the early 1980s, has lasted longer and
has pushed the unemployment rate even lower than at the end of the
1980s expansion. Second, for the last three years or so, wages for
workers at the bottom of the pay scale have been rising rapidly. In
the 1980s, declining pay at the lower rungs of the wage scale
offset the positive effects of robust job growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not just getting more job opportunities, but rising
wages,'' Dr. Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Economic Policy Institute in Washington, a
worker whose pay put him one-fifth the way up the wage-distribution
ladder earned $7.11 an hour in 1986 but only $6.66 in 1996. By this
spring, that figure had climbed to $7.17 an hour. (All the figures
are in 1998 dollars and take inflation into account.)
</P>
<P>
   Those gains have helped fuel a spree of consumer spending and
borrowing in the last year or so. But in March, Americans reined in
a bit, with consumer credit expanding by just $1.6 billion, well
below the $8.7 jump in February. Credit card debt actually shrank,
but borrowing to buy cars rose $3.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, not everything is rosy on the job front. The
nation's factories shed another 29,000 jobs last month, bringing
the total number of manufacturing jobs lost since the beginning of
the global financial crisis to 400,000. But increasingly
well-paying service jobs more than made up that loss. Last month,
service industries created 261,000 additional jobs. In the last
year, they have added 2.8 million jobs while the number of
construction jobs has grown by 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going back to the days when the economy was creating
jobs that called for easily acquired, modest skills,'' said Kevin
Murphy, a labor economist at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the old relationship between economic growth and a
reduction in poverty seems to have been restored _ at least for
now. According to Professor Katz's study, between 1983 and 1990,
poverty fell by just 1.7 percentage points, less than half what
would have been predicted based on the pattern that existed in the
1960s and 1970s. By contrast, between 1993 and 1997 (the last year
for which poverty figures are available) the percentage of
households in poverty has declined by 2.6 percentage points, more
than in the entire 1980s and right in line with the old pattern.
(The study's numbers include income from the earned-income tax
credit.)
</P>
<P>
   Low unemployment is good for newcomers to the labor force like
women and teen-agers and those at the bottom of the pay scale. When
the labor market tightens, people who are out of work or are
jumping in for the first time get jobs. Part- time workers get
full-time jobs. And those in dead-end jobs find better ones and
have a chance to acquire more experience and skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
