<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCHINA08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate report: Lax satellite security allowed China access to
missile technology
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Chinese government obtained sensitive
technology from American satellite launches that improved their
country's ballistic missile fleet, according to Senate
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In a 45-page document released late Thursday, the Senate
Intelligence Committee alleges that lax monitoring of satellite
exports has enhanced Beijing's ability to develop highly
sophisticated missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that U.S. missile technology was indeed
transferred to China,'' Sen. Richard Shelby (R-Ala.), chairman of
the panel, said Friday. ``The administration and certain U.S.
aerospace companies joined in a conspiracy of carelessness and
recklessness that allowed unlicensed, unauthorized transfers of
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended increasing the monitoring and security
surrounding commercial satellite launches. Long term, the panel
recommends examining whether American commercial satellites should
be allowed to be launched from China.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they agreed with much of the report's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share the committee's concern that unauthorized assistance
and transfers of technology relevant to space launch vehicles and
ballistic missiles may have occurred during certain space launch
failure analyses,'' said Gary Samore, a senior official at the
National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Senate investigators examined whether China
attempted to influence the 1996 elections with donations funneled
through former Democratic fund-raiser Johnny Chung.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators found that Chung accepted $300,000 from Liu
Chao-ying, daughter of one of China's highest ranking military
generals, to help President Clinton win re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI could trace only about $20,000 to the Democratic
National Committee. ``Most of the remaining funds went for his
personal use, including mortgage payments,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is intelligence information indicating PRC officials
provided funds to U.S. political campaigns,'' the report states.
But the information is ``inconclusive as to whether the
contributions were part of the overall China plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that they recognized that the White House had
no knowledge of any contributions originating outside the United
States,'' said Jim Kennedy, special counsel to the president on
campaign finance issues.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not mention recent news accounts of alleged
Chinese espionage at the Los Alamos laboratory and other
laboratories where nuclear weapons are designed.
</P>
<P>
   That allegation surfaced after the committee had completed its
investigation. It will be addressed in a classified report by a
House committee headed by Rep. Christopher Cox (R-Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the committee focused on two failed commercial
satellite launches during which investigators believe sensitive
technological information was given to the Chinese. Both cases are
under investigation by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved a satellite launched by Loral Space and
Communications in February 1996. After the satellite exploded Loral
allegedly shared information with the Chinese that has improved
their missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   The second case involved information that Hughes Electronics
Corp. allegedly shared with the Chinese involving a satellite
launch in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the report found that U.S. government officials
were not called to the scene to ensure that sensitive technology
was protected from the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite industry is quick to defend their launches and
deny that technology was given to the Chinese on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that no security information was released to the
Chinese,'' said Richard Dore, director of communications for
Hughes. ``We were never in the position of passing on anything that
would harm the nation's security.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis Allen, spokesperson for the 51-member Aerospace Industry
Association, is concerned that the congressional investigation is
undermining the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Congress has taken the satellite license approval
process away from the business-friendly Commerce Department and
returned it back to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   All that does, Allen said, is make it easier for foreign
competitors to take customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we don't lose our satellite industry to
foreign companies,'' said Allen, who estimates that the industry
may have lost as much as $1 billion as a result of Congress
switching the licensing back to State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
