u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARV-PILGRIM-RESIGN-B     05-07 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARV-PILGRIM-RESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CFO OF LARGEST BAY STATE HMO QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The chief financial officer of financially troubled
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care resigned Friday, just one day after the
chief executive of New England's largest health maintenance
organization stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Brophy's departure from the region's largest HMO was
announced in an internal memo written by Alan Morse, chairman of
the Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   The memo did not state a reason for Brophy's resignation.
Harvard Pilgrim spokesman Alan Raymond declined to elaborate,
saying, ``There's nothing to add.''
</P>
<P>
   Brophy, reached at his home, refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   His depature did not come as a surprise because of the CFO's
close ties to Allan Greenberg, who abruptly quit Thursday as CEO.
The dual resignations came a week after Harvard Pilgrim announced
it lost $94 million from operations, its largest annual losses
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom has been closely aligned with Allan for a long time, so
it's not entirely surprising,'' said Stephen Weiner, a health care
attorney for Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky &AMP; Popeo in Boston.
``But it does reinforce concerns about the stability of the
leadership and whether the management is going to be able to handle
the constant internal and external pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation swirled Friday about the future direction of Harvard
Pilgrim, which covers 1.3 million patients throughout New England.
With Brophy's exit, the HMO currently has no CEO and no CFO, and is
continuing to search for a chief operating officer, a newly created
position.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond insisted that Harvard Pilgrim ``has a strong leadership
team in place. The strategy we're following is one that we believe
will produce the kind of results we're looking for. There is no
reason for anyone to be concerned about the leadership of the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Morse, in his memo, said Brophy's duties will be assumed by
members of a transition team named on Thursday after Greenberg's
resignation. Those on the team include Morse; Dr. Gilbert Shapiro,
a board member; William Frado, general counsel; Esther Emard,
senior vice president for operations; Larry Gibson, senior vice
president for human resources and information technology; and Dr.
Joseph Dorsey, medical director. Raymond said the team will meet
for the first time on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the team's biggest tasks involves integrating its
fragmented computer systems, which were partly to blame for the
nonprofit company's larger-than-expected 1998 losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't manage what you can't measure,'' said Susan
Connolly, a principal at William M. Mercer Inc., a consulting firm
in Boston. ``Data is key to managing costs. This has been Harvard
Pilgrim's Achilles' heel.''
</P>
<P>
   Another task is to quickly find a permanent management team. A
number of names surfaced Friday among health care circles as
possible candidates, including Charles Baker, chief executive of
the Harvard Vanguard physician group that was once part of Harvard
Pilgrim. Baker would not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to find leadership,'' said Stephen Caulfield,
chairman of the Chickering Group, an insurance company. ``The board
has the responsibility to preserve their franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim controls roughly 38 percent of the managed care
market in Massachusetts, according to the state Division of
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg received $656,770 in salary, benefits, and other
compensation in 1997, according to the latest public filings.
Brophy, the fourth-highest paid executive in the company that year,
received $373,315 in compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
