<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8740 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FINANCES-ABRIDGE     05-07 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FINANCES-ABRIDGED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S BUSINESS DEALINGS SHOW SOME SUCCESS INHERITED, SOME
ACHIEVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: this is a shortened version of the original
BUSH-FINANCES, which was about 4,500 words and moved earlier) 
(ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 (bl)  
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When George W. Bush first ran for governor of
Texas five years ago, he had no record in politics, only a famous
name and a business career that he described as a success ``by any
objective measure.''
</P>
<P>
   In one significant way, that boast may be truer today than it
was in 1994. As Bush seeks to spring from the governorship to the
presidency, he does so with the financial security provided by his
2,359 percent gain from last year's sale of the Texas Rangers,
which transformed his $606,000 investment in the baseball team into
a $14.9 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is not the only objective measure of a
business career. And closer inspection of Bush's two decades in the
private sector in Texas, which began in the oil patch in Midland
and ended in the owner's box in Arlington, suggests that his record
was mixed. While some ventures made healthy profits, others
struggled for survival. Some of his dealings raised ethical
questions that have provided fodder for political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   His business dealings also illuminate an essential question of
his biography: whether his success is primarily inherited or
achieved. It is a question that has dogged Bush, as a son of former
President George Bush, throughout his business and political
careers.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensible answer, it seems, is that Bush deserves credit
for much of his success, but that he also has benefited at critical
points from his family's prominence and the financial support of
family friends and business and political acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bush, 52, acknowledged that his name has
generated opportunities not available to everybody, both in
business and in politics. But he asserted that he has never relied
on his name or heritage to ensure his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the integrity of my dad and mom, I've inherited a
great name that has sometimes opened doors and sometimes slammed
them shut,'' he said. ``But the business world is a world of
results and performance, and having a famous last name didn't
strike oil or conceive and build the Ballpark at Arlington, or help
the team's win-loss record. And my name hasn't made any decisions
for me as governor.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Bush clearly has received significant help along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving an MBA from Harvard Business School, for
instance, he started a small oil company in Midland with the
$17,000 remaining in an educational trust fund established by his
parents. Some of the most powerful businessmen in America then took
a chance on the untested oilman by investing hundreds of thousands
of dollars in his first drilling funds. Many were recruited by his
uncle, Jonathan Bush, a New York City stockbroker and brother of
the former president. When the company stagnated because of
declining market conditions and a miscalculation by George W. Bush,
it survived by merging twice with larger firms.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush's role in the 1989 purchase of the Texas Rangers and
the attention he gained by managing the franchise that launched his
career as governor. His partners praise him for working
aggressively to secure the purchase and for making improvements,
including the construction of a graceful new stadium, that tripled
the value of the team by the time they sold it last June.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the Rangers, Bush's fortunes were aided by his
status as a first son and by the help of others. Eddie Chiles, who
sold the team to Bush's group, was a longtime friend and political
supporter of President Bush who picked George W. Bush from among
other suitors at least partly because of his deep affection for the
president, said former Arlington Mayor Richard Greene.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush rounded up half the money used to buy the team,
the deal came together only when Peter Ueberroth, then the baseball
commissioner, personally persuaded Richard Rainwater, a prominent
Fort Worth investor, to take a major interest and join forces with
Bush. Bush had previously failed to recruit Rainwater. One source
close to those negotiations said Ueberroth had insisted that
Rainwater team up with Bush ``out of respect for his father,'' the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush graduated from Yale in 1968 and from business school in
1975. He then returned to Midland and began learning the oil
business.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his business school classmates, Bush had
developed no real plan for his life. But his father had made his
fortune in oil, and the industry was enjoying one of its cycles of
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my instincts are toward entrepreneurship,'' Bush said,
``and I really wasn't interested in trying out the corporate
culture at that point in my life. I was single, I didn't have many
needs, and I felt that the barriers to entry were pretty darn low
in the oil business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, oil made Bush a millionaire, and he used his profits
to build an even larger fortune in baseball. But his oil success
had far more to do with mergers than with gushers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Bush formed Arbusto Energy Inc., ``ar-BOO-stow'' being
Spanish for ``bush.'' He began soliciting investors for annual
drilling funds that typically bought modest interests in wells
operated by other firms.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's early years, Bush's father was either running
for president or vice president or serving as vice president, and
state securities filings show that the original investors included
wealthy and prominent friends of the Bush family, corporate
chieftains, Republican leaders, Bush family members and clients of
Jonathan Bush. The list of investors was remarkable for a young
company owned by a man of 32 with scant experience and virtually no
track record.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All of the approximately 20 business associates interviewed for
this article described Bush as astute, hardworking, affable, gritty
and honest in their dealings with him.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the first three years, Bush managed to increase the
amount invested in his oil funds, from $565,000 in 1979 to $1.7
million in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   With his company regularly mocked as ``Ar-bust-o'' and his
father serving as vice president, Bush changed the firm's name to
Bush Exploration. Then, in a major miscalculation, he decided to
sell public shares in his 1982 oil-drilling fund rather than rely
solely on private investments. The offering failed, with Bush
securing only $1.14 million of the $6 million he had sought to
raise.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the company had average luck in its drilling
ventures, but never made a major discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recalls his firm as being ``a good, solid little company''
that had a positive cash flow and provided a steady return for his
limited partners. He said he believes that some at least recouped
their investments, and some verified that they had made modest
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Burned by his 1982 experience but still anxious for growth, Bush
in 1984 merged Bush Exploration with Spectrum 7 Energy Corp., a
drilling firm based in Cincinnati with an office in Midland. Bush
became chairman, chief executive and a director, with ownership of
about 15 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in 1986, world oil prices collapsed. Faced with
the prospect of laying off Spectrum's 15 employees and liquidating
its reserves, Bush and his partners decided to merge with Harken
Energy Corp., a larger conglomerate based near Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Spectrum, Harken did not give Bush a daily management
position. But it made him a director, and he received 212,152
shares of Harken stock, worth $530,380, according to SEC filings.
</P>
<P>
   On June 22, 1990, Bush sold his original 212,140 shares of
Harken stock for $4 a share, or $848,560. Eight days later, the
company finished the second quarter with a loss of $23.2 million,
more than eight times the loss it showed for the second quarter of
1989. In early August, Iraq invaded Kuwait, and within two weeks
Harken's stock fell to $3 a share. By Aug. 20, it was at $2.37 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Bush realized that the stock's slide would raise concerns that
he had sold with insider knowledge of the yet-to-be-reported loss.
Although an outside director, he sat on an audit committee that
regularly reviewed the company's financial practices. The
suspicions were compounded when the SEC discovered it did not have
a form from Bush that insiders must file when they sell stock,
although Bush previously filed a different form that had disclosed
his intent to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintained that he had filed the missing disclosure form.
But the SEC investigated the transaction anyway. Bush's lawyer
defended him by arguing that he had not known about the impending
loss when he sold his stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the son of a president,'' Bush said. ``I was very
sensitive to the scrutiny. I felt like liquidating the stock for
personal reasons but I was also fully aware that any deal I did was
going to be fully scrutinized.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC investigators apparently were convinced by Bush's
explanation, said officials familiar with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponent in the 1994 gubernatorial campaign, incumbent
Gov. Ann Richards, suggested that the investigation had been a
political whitewash overseen by SEC officials appointed by Bush's
father. But SEC officials have denied any political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In the years when Bush and William O. DeWitt Jr., a Spectrum 7
business partner, flew around the country in search of investors,
they spent much time attending baseball games and dreaming about
owning a team. In 1988, DeWitt heard that Eddie Chiles, the crusty
and conservative owner of the Texas Rangers, was looking for a
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush returned to Texas to try to put together a deal with
Chiles, who had known the Bush family for decades. Bush quickly
collected financial commitments from a Yale classmate, the
classmate's business partner, one of his father's campaign aides
and the husband of a Bush cousin. DeWitt, meanwhile, put together a
group of Cincinnati investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush described his role in buying the Rangers as pivotal. ``I
wasn't going to let this deal fail,'' he said. ``I wanted to put
together the group. I was tenacious.'' Many of his partners agree.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth is less generous. ``George W. Bush deserves great
credit for the development of the franchise,'' he said. ``However,
the bringing together of the buying group was the result of Richard
Rainwater, Rusty Rose, Dr. Bobby Brown and the commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 21, 1989, the Bush group bought 86 percent of the
Rangers for about $75 million, a price that placed the full value
of the team at $86 million. Bush's initial investment was $500,000,
which he borrowed from United Bank of Midland. He later invested
more money in the partnership, eventually bringing his total stake
to $606,302, or 1.8 percent of the team.
</P>
<P>
   To reward Bush for his role in structuring the Rangers deal and
managing the franchise, the partners agreed to grant him an
additional 10 percent share of the team once they recouped their
investments along with 2 percent interest. They also voted him a
salary of $200,000 for his full-time work as a managing general
partner.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were a success during Bush's tenure, both on the
field and in the stands. After posting losing records in six of the
seven years before the sale, the Rangers were winners in seven of
the 10 years that they were owned by the Bush group. They won
division titles in 1996 and 1998. Attendance soared dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took an active role in the team's management. He also
became one of its most popular ambassadors, giving speeches,
chatting up reporters, negotiating television contracts,
representing the team at league meetings and signing autographs.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest improvement for the Rangers was the construction of
the Ballpark at Arlington, a 47,000-seat stadium with old-fashioned
elegance and plenty of revenue-producing sky boxes. Bush helped
conceive the design of the stadium, and supported the notion of
financing its construction through a half-cent increase in
Arlington's sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   With other cities in the Dallas-Fort Worth area eager to steal
the team, Arlington officials quickly signed on to the tax increase
and then joined with the Rangers in selling the measure to voters.
Bush helped plot strategy for the referendum campaign but kept a
low profile. With Bush's father in the White House, the Rangers did
not want the politics of the new stadium to become partisan. Bush
critics speculate that the aspiring politician also did not want to
be closely associated with a tax increase. Early in 1991, the tax
referendum passed by a margin of nearly 2-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the stadium arrangement call it the most egregious
form of corporate welfare and argue that the tax increase stands in
contrast to Bush's anti-tax politics. He responds that Arlington
voters made their own decision. On April 15, 1999, Bush reported
that he and his wife, Laura, paid $3.8 million in federal income
taxes for 1998 on estimated taxable income of $18.4 million. Their
annual income had averaged $416,703 in the previous seven years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
