<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKWARS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida `War of the Theme Parks' escalates
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ He's only a mouse, but they're bringing in the
Super Heroes to battle him, along with Jurassic Park's dinosaurs
and even that tongue-twisting Cat-in-the-Hat.
</P>
<P>
   Kids from Sao Paulo to St. Paul are surely celebrating as
Universal Studios Escape this month unveils its second major theme
park, Islands of Adventure, a $1 billion array of high tech roller
coasters and movie rides.
</P>
<P>
   The much-ballyhooed debut marks a new phase in Orlando's
ever-escalating War of the Theme Parks, in which entertainment
giants spend billions in a fight for the almighty tourist dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando now boasts a mind-boggling seven major theme parks, not
to mention the dozens of smaller water parks, dinner theaters,
video shoot-em-ups, animal attractions and other venues.
</P>
<P>
   But the landscape is dominated by the Big Three _ Universal,
SeaWorld, and the granddaddy of all family vacation destinations,
Walt Disney World. Disney still towers over all others, with four
major theme parks, 26 resort hotels, three water parks and two
entertainment/shopping districts on its sprawling, city-sized
property.
</P>
<P>
   But Universal appears determined to catch up, and even SeaWorld
is joining the expansion game, recently announcing plans for its
first-ever high-speed roller coaster and a new
swim-with-the-dolphins venue.
</P>
<P>
   It's all enough to keep starry-eyed youngsters dragging their
parents back to Orlando year after year until they reach adulthood,
when suddenly they'll find themselves on the pulling end of little
hands headed for excitement.
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what theme park planners count on.
</P>
<P>
   60 million tourists
</P>
<P>
   The only cloud marring the postcard-perfect vacation landscape
is the nagging question: Just how many theme parks is too many
theme parks? When does a market even as seemingly infinite as
Orlando's reach saturation?
</P>
<P>
   No time soon, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see some cannibalization with attendance flat or
dropping at some parks for the next year or two, but I don't think
there's any doubt the tourism demand will catch up with the
supply,'' said Tim O'Brien, who tracks the theme park industry for
``Amusement Business,'' a trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Price, an industry consultant who helps theme parks
answer just that question, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a study several years ago in that market and didn't find
saturation at that point,'' he said. ``What they've done is create
the world's top tourism destination. Years ago the people who went
there for the parks might visit one or two in a week's vacation.
Now they're visiting four or five.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, worry that Central Florida's heavy dependence on
tourism is creating an unsteady economic base, built on thousands
of low-paying theme park and tourism service jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in a bit of a trap,'' said Richard Foglesong, a
Rollins College politics professor who is writing a book about
Disney's impact on the area. ``We've created an infrastructure that
is drawing more tourism here, but tourism is primarily low-wage
jobs. It's a shaky foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bandwagon shows no sign of slowing down. Last year,
Orlando's 80-plus attractions tallied a staggering 60 million in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists seem to love the place, although ask when they're
sitting in the shade and not waiting in some long line with
screaming kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place like Florida,'' said Malcolm Dalgleish, 49,
of Newcastle, England, who recently took his third Orlando
vacation. ``If they open another one, we'll just have to come back
again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that we've got the best product this market
has to offer,'' said Tom Williams, Universal's president. ``I think
the market continues to grow and I'm confident that we'll get our
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park and Bullwinkle
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Universal drew nearly 9 million visitors, a number
its executives hope to surpass quickly with the addition of Islands
of Adventure. The park will feature several separate venues,
including a Jurassic Park island based on the Steven Spielberg
movie, a Super Hero island featuring Spiderman and other Marvel
Comics characters, a Dr. Seuss landing and Toon Lagoon, populated
by beloved cartoon favorites like Rocky, Bullwinkle, Popeye and
Dudley DooRight.
</P>
<P>
   But Universal's plans don't stop there. Taking a page from
Disney's book, executives want to keep the visitors _ and their
money _ on the property for their entire vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's first on-property hotel, Portofino Bay, opens this
September, to be followed by four others in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Already open is CityWalk, a shopping/entertainment district that
competes with Downtown Disney and Pleasure Island. Add to that
Wet'n Wild, a nearby water park that Universal purchased last year,
which answers Disney's Typhoon Lagoon and Blizzard Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Even more expansion could come down the road. Last year,
Universal bought 1,900 acres near its current location.
</P>
<P>
   For all its growth, though, Universal still lags Disney in sheer
size. Its 840 acres under current development and plans for 20,000
employees pales compared to Disney's 25,000-acre complex employing
some 50,000 full-time and seasonal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has never strayed from its original plan to build an
entertainment complex that would be ever-changing and expanding.
Last year it opened its fourth theme park, Animal Kingdom, which
competes directly with SeaWorld and Busch Gardens in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Disney continues upgrading existing attractions,
while adding new ones, such as Cirque du Soleil; a new track where
people pretend to be Detroit car testers; a Buzz Lightyear
video-game ride; a new roller coaster and several new live shows.
The company is also adding its second cruise ship, based in nearby
Port Canaveral. If Universal is a growing challenger, Disney seems
determined to hold onto its franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish them the best,'' said Disney spokesman Craig Dezern.
``But we're focused on what has been a year of explosive growth. We
keep focused on giving our guests something new and exciting each
time they visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller parks scrambling
</P>
<P>
   If anybody is getting left behind in the rush, it would have to
be the smaller parks.
</P>
<P>
   At Gatorland, a 50-year-old attraction just south of Orlando,
the challenge has meant expanding constantly, adding new shows and
renovating existing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But simply keeping up seems to be getting harder all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bleak, but the little guys are concerned,'' said Tim
Williams, Gatorland's spokesman. ``Some of us are really
scrambling. At some point you do reach saturation, and it's
probably the little guys who will be hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Central Florida economist David Scott cites
another worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is that we haven't had a recession since 1990-1991,''
said Scott, who also believes hoteliers may be over-building,
citing dropping occupancy rates the past two years. ``The business
decision-makers are gambling, but I don't think many of them
realize what an unusual time we're in. This is the 99th month of
this economic expansion, and the longest one on record is 106
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is no economic downturn, some believe the Orlando
juggernaut will eventually reach a point of saturation.
</P>
<P>
   Industry consultant Price says it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far you can push it, I don't think anybody knows,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
