<SLUG> BC-GONZALES-HOMECOMING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT'S GOOD TO STEP BACK INTO TEXAS,' SAYS FORMER POW 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ ``Wow. Hey everybody. It's good to step back into
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the first words of Army Spc. Steven Gonzales when he
arrived here Friday on a flight from Germany three days after being
released from prison in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Huntsville, Texas, cavalry scout, dressed in a
blue and white sweat suit, declined to discuss details of his
capture on the Macedonia border or the month he spent as a prisoner
of the Serbs. He told a throng of reporters and a handful of
relatives who met him at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport,
``I'm looking forward to a little bit of rest. It's great to be
free, but it's a little bit stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson negotiated the release of Gonzales and
two other American soldiers last weekend. After three days of
medical examinations and military debriefings, all returned to the
United States Friday. Gonzales' parents, Gilbert and Rosie
Gonzales, and his aunt, Rosie Barrow, accompanied him on the flight
from Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   During the 32 days he was a prisoner, Gonzales said, ``Isolation
was a big factor'' and he filled the time ``with a lot of prayer, a
lot of thoughts of family and all the happy memories I could think
of.''
</P>
<P>
   He described spending his 22nd birthday as a prisoner of war as
``depressing,'' but, in retrospect, he added, ``I spent my birthday
in a place few people have had an opportunity to spend their
birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   From Dallas, Gonzales and his family left for an undisclosed
location for a few days of rest before returning to Huntsville,
where he will be honored with a parade and activities at Sam
Houston State University on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   As Gonzalez and his parents were en route, the Pentagon released
the first substantive details of the capture of the three soldiers.
Gonzales, Staff Sgts. Christopher Stone, 25, of Michigan, and
Andrew Ramirez, 24, of California were on a training mission March
31 near the Macedonia-Yugoslavia border when their Humvee was
surrounded by Serb soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pulled from their Humvee and they were kicked,
punched and hit with rifle butts and treated extremely roughly,''
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said, according to The Associated
Press. ``There were also periods of harsh treatment during
interrogation in the days following their capture.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon did not reveal details of the harsh prison treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Army has concluded ``beyond a shadow of a doubt''
that the three soldiers were on the Macedonia side of the border,
not on the Yugoslav side as the government of Slobodan Milosevic
claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the three were armed with a .50-caliber machine gun,
one M-16 rifle and two side arms but did not fire them because they
were outnumbered by Serb soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the machine gun) was not ready to go because typically
when you drive around you don't have the thing ready to fire,'' he
said. The soldier manning the machine gun ``followed the normal
rule of getting out of the line of fire so he wouldn't be shot,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to evade their captors, Bacon said, they ran the Humvee
into a ditch or some obstacle, ``which made it difficult for them
to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
