<HEADER>
A8758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-CIVIC08-COX     05-07 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-CIVIC08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Civic Si worthy successor of CRX
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Car shoppers today who start out thinking of the
venerable Honda Civic as a bastion of practical and reliable _ but
unexciting _ transportation are going to find dealerships
delightedly offering them a quick reality check. It's the new Civic
Si, a truly worthy successor of the recently departed CRX and the
Si models of the early and mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Its looks are, well, ordinary. No flashy graphics. No rakish
color schemes. No eye-grabbing, boy-racer rear spoiler. About all
that stands out is the relatively small lettering ``VTEC'' below
the beltline and just in front of the rear wheel wells.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that Honda, catering to the enthusiasts _ the
younger ones in particular _ dropped its potent little 1.6-liter
four-cylinder engine with variable valve timing and lift electronic
control (VTEC) into the 2,600-pound Civic Si. That makes it a
little monster with 160 horsepower and 111 pounds-feet of torque
coming from an engine that redlines at 8,000 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   AutoWeek calls it ``the pocket rocket of our time.'' The West
Coast, where car crazies proliferate, calls it the current next big
thing. Honda gleefully reports that young women and men are so
devoted to pepping up and personalizing their Civic Si coupes that
Oscar Jackson of Jackson Racing tags it ``the '57 Chevy of the
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   A reality check here is that Frank Bohanan, tech director of the
Specialty Equipment Market Association, says Hondas are ``the most
popular cars'' among buyers looking for relatively inexpensive cars
to customize.
</P>
<P>
   Civics start at $10,650 for a CX hatchback and run through a
variety of coupe and sedan models with manual and automatic
transmissions before getting to the Si coupe. It lists for $17,445,
and there isn't much missing in the way of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bypass the dealer-installed floor mats, and buyers can drive
away in a Civic Si like the ``electron blue'' test car for $17,860
(plus tag, taxes, etc.). It came with air conditioning, a strong
stereo with CD player and six speakers, the expected power
equipment and, yes, drink holders. Neat features included a locking
fold-down rear seat, smallish but solid front seats, a supple
shifter and the tachometer that conservatively redlines at 8,000
rpm.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Civic Si's best feature, of course _ the
smooth-revving VTEC engine. It does prefer premium fuel, but the
EPA figures (26 and 31 mpg) are respectable, and its performance is
rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   The ride, it should be noted, is enthusiast-oriented, meaning
the Civic Si resists body lean and roll and feels surprisingly
stable for a car of its size. Anti-lock brakes, unfortunately,
aren't standard, although they should be on a car that targets
enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Driven responsibly, though, the Civic Si is a rewarding ride,
one that mates non-overwhelming performance with good standard
features and plenty of potential for personalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Honda Civic Si front-drive coupe
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $17,860 (includes delivery, base price:
$17,445)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, side-impact beams
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 1.6-liter four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (160
horsepower), five-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: none
</P>
<P>
   Standard features include: air conditioning, six-speaker stereo
with CD player, power windows and locks, power moonroof, keyless
entry system
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 26 mpg premium unleaded city, 31 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
