u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-UN-BOS &LR;      05-07 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-UN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN MOVES TO SEIZE INITIATIVE IN YUGSLAVIA PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ After being relegated to near-irrelevance in a
series of conflicts from Iraq to the Balkans, the United Nations
moved to reclaim center stage Friday, answering for now critics who
have said it was fading into diplomatic insignificance.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan appointed two prominent European
envoys, former Swedish Prime Minister Carl Bildt and Slovakian
Foreign Miniser Eduard Kukan, to step up the organization's
diplomatic activities in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also ordered a small advance team team to leave for
Belgrade Sunday to pave the way for a 15-member team that hopes to
head for Kosovo a week later to assess humanitarian needs in the
ravaged province. Annan also said he has been mulling a personal
visit to Belgrade to meet with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations is indispensable,'' Annan said. ``And
whether we like it or not, on certain global issues, this is the
only organization. And sooner or later we have to turn to it. I
hope in the future we will do it sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   The world body got a boost last week from a proposal for ending
the Kosovo conflict that Russia and the major Western powers agreed
to Thursday. The deal was a diplomatic advance for Moscow and
Belgrade, which have been pressing for a larger UN role. It also
provides the US and its NATO allies with the prospect of UN
sanction for any ultimate political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   While it remains unlikely that the US would agree to putting
NATO troops in the region under UN command, there is now agreement
in Washington and Moscow that any peacekeeping role will require
approval of the UN Security Council. And the world body is expected
to play a role in overseeing the creation of a transitional
government in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This statement brings the United Nations into a greater
post-conflict role than it played in Bosnia,'' said Ivo Daalder,
the former top Balkans expert at the National Security Council.
``And it reestablishes the importance of UN legitimacy, if not in
going to war, at least in how you build a peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, some observers and diplomats have decried what
they saw as the growing irrelevance of the United Nations. Its role
in international peacekeeping had been scaled back following
troubled operations from Somalia to Angola, where the United
Nations withdrew after a $1 million-a-day peacekeeping failed to
stop a decades-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
   On March 24, the US and its NATO allies bypassed the UN Security
Council as they launched the greatest offensive military operation
since the birth of the alliance 50 years ago. Faced with a certain
Russian veto in the Security Council, American and European
diplomats argued that they were justified in acting by the need to
halt a looming humanitarian calamity.
</P>
<P>
   But six weeks of a punishing NATO air campaign have failed to
prevent the expulsion of ethnic Albanians by Serbian forces or to
pressure Milosevic to accept NATO troops in Kosovo to guarantee the
Albanians' right to return and to a degree of self-government. NATO
has stepped up its air campaign in recent days, but the Clinton
Administration has also increased its contacts with Russia to find
a diplomatic solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Thursday by Russia and the Group of Seven
industrial powers, the United States acceded to Russia's demand
that a key role in a postwar settlement for the UN Security
Council, where Moscow enjoys veto power. The United States also
agreed to omit the mention of NATO from the statement, although US
officials insisted that NATO would play a central role in any
international force.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has been pressing for the UN chief to take a more active
role in mediating the conflict. On Monday, Moscow's chief peace
envoy, former Prime Minsiter Viktor Chernomyrdin, asked Annan to
travel on a peace mission to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who pledged to work closely with the Russians, said
Friday that he won't rule out a visit to the Serb capital when the
time is right.
</P>
<P>
   Vladislav Jovanovic, Yugoslavia's ambassador to the United
Nations, said in an interview that his government first invited
Annan on Oct. 1. Jovanivic said Annan has been ``evasive'' about
his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade prefers a peacekeeping role for the United Nations,
which is likely to field a less heavily armed force than NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Jovanovic said the UN humanitarian mission has not yet been
granted access to Kosovo by Yugoslav authorities, and any UN effort
would have to address the needs of Serb victims of the NATO bombing
campaign as well the situation of displaced ethnic Albanians still
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The UN's reputation ``was very seriously damaged by the act of
NATO,'' said Jovanovic. ``Only the speedy recovery of its role can
save the UN from repeating the fate of the League of Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan acknowledged that his diplomatic intervention carried
risks for the organization, whose reputation has been badly
tarnished by diplomatic setbacks from Angola to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are high for the governments involved,'' Annan
said. ``The stakes are high for the United Nations, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
