<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8762 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTT-FUNDRAISING-ART-     05-07 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTT-FUNDRAISING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES ANTE UP FOR CENTER HONORING TRENT LOTT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An academic center being built at the University of
Mississippi and named for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott is
being endowed with million-dollar donations from companies with
huge stakes in pending congressional legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In less than six months of fund raising, university officials
say they have collected pledges for more than half of the $8
million they hope to raise for the Trent Lott Leadership Institute,
which is scheduled to open next year. Among the donors are MCI
Worldcom Inc. and Lockheed Martin Corp., each of which has pledged
$1 million. The companies are on opposite sides of a legislative
battle over Lockheed's planned acquisition of a giant satellite
company.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, at a Kennedy Center gala honoring Lott, still more
money for the center will be raised. One of the principal
fund-raisers for the event is Haley Barbour, another prominent
Mississippi Republican, who is also one of the most powerful
lobbyists in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Given Lott's importance in Mississippi and Washington, it isn't
surprising that the university has had so little trouble finding
backers for its new leadership institute.
</P>
<P>
   But observant students of government may well divine an
additional lesson: that money follows politicians to a surprising
number of places, and that individuals and corporations have ways
above and beyond direct campaign contributions _ and the legally
mandated limits on those donations _ to make politicians feel
loved.
</P>
<P>
   While this type of fund raising for academic centers honoring
powerful politicians is not new, the Lott institute has drawn
unusually heavy corporate support _ all of it wholly
tax-deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, these types of academic centers seem to be
multiplying; at least five additional current senators have such
institutions named after them, a manner of tribute once reserved
for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Several political analysts said this trend raises the troubling
specter that monied individuals and companies are plying new
avenues to purchase influence. Unlike campaign donations,
contributions to these centers do not have to be publicly disclosed
to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having temples built to yourself while you're still in power
is a very dangerous proposition,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president
of Democracy 21, a public policy group. ``It's very pleasant for
the honoree, and very dangerous for citizens who are looking for a
fair political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for MCI and Lockheed said that the companies' gifts
were intended solely to promote education and noted that all of the
money goes to the University of Mississippi, not to Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, in a prepared statement, said, ``The only thing
benefactors will be `buying' with their gifts are the desks, books
and other materials to help students in this new Ole Miss
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Although university officials said that they would publicize the
names of all of their donors in the program for the gala, they said
they did not want to disclose contributors yet without their
consent. But they did identify the sources of their three largest
gifts so far.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to MCI and Lockheed, J.L. Holloway, who runs a
company in Mississippi that manufactures equipment for offshore oil
drilling, also gave $1 million. Although that company, Friede
Goldman International, could also be affected by federal
legislation, it does not have an armada of lobbyists comparable to
those employed by MCI and Lockheed.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said his donation was a personal recognition of Lott's
achievements. ``I think Senator Lott is one of those very unusual
and special leaders that only come by once in a lifetime,''
Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the publication Roll Call reported that the tobacco
company Brown and Williamson had given $50,000 to the institute,
but several calls to the company Friday were not returned. A
spokesman for AT&AMP;T said that it had made a contribution, too, but
would not disclose the amount.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Mississippi, like any large university, has
its own interests in federal policy. But like other schools with
programs or centers named for politicians, it benefits most
immediately by a politician's _ and especially Lott's _ ability to
attract money.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said that the Lott institute will offer a
special curriculum in leadership and be housed in a renovated
dormitory on the university's main campus in Oxford, Miss. The
officials stressed that Lott had not been directly involved in the
fund raising and that both the center and its name were their idea.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Khayat, the university's chancellor, said that Lott has
self-effacingly tried to play down the honor. ``He would not allow
the gala to be scheduled unless it honored all of Mississippi
leadership,'' Khayat said. ``He didn't want it to be about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising event, for which there are 2,200 tickets at
$1,500 apiece, is indeed titled ``A Celebration of Mississippi
Leadership,'' and it will use film clips to pay tribute to famous
writers from Mississippi, like William Faulkner and Eudora Welty,
and famous entertainers from Mississippi, like the opera singer
Leontyne Price and the jazz singer B.B. King.
</P>
<P>
   But it will culminate in an appearance onstage by Lott and a
performance of the musical quartet to which he belongs, the Singing
Senators. University officials said they expected to sell all of
the available seats.
</P>
<P>
   Gala sponsors MCI and Lockheed could be greatly affected by
legislation pending in the Senate that sets the terms for the
privatization of Intelsat and Inmarsat, two international satellite
systems to which Comsat Corp. has exclusive access for the United
States. Lockheed is in the process of acquiring Comsat.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies like MCI and AT&AMP;T would like the
legislation to allow them to renegotiate long-term contracts with
Comsat and give them their own access to Intelsat and Inmarsat.
Lockheed opposes such amendments to the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed by the Senate Commerce committee on Wednesday did
not give MCI and other telecommunications companies what they
wanted, but they continue to lobby Lott and other senators for more
favorable provisions, which could save them tens of millions of
dollars annually and reduce Lockheed's earnings by an even larger
amount.
</P>
<P>
   James Fetig, a spokesman for Lockheed, which has its
headquarters in Bethesda, Md., said that the corporation's $1
million gift, to be paid over five years, was in line with the sums
it gives other educational institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent Lott's leadership position or any other legislation
pending before the Congress is not related to this decision,''
Fetig said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Walter, a spokesman for MCI, which has its headquarters in
Jackson, Miss., said that the company was simply continuing its
longtime support of its home state's schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While corporations themselves cannot give campaign contributions
to a politician and the political action committees affiliated with
corporations are limited to donations of $5,000 per election, there
is no limit to the charitable contributions made to an institution
or foundation associated with a politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has increasingly become standard operating procedure in
the world of politics,'' said Brian Moir, a telecommunications
lawyer. ``If you can't contribute directly, you contribute to
activities that members of Congress hold dear.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lott's, the names of other sitting senators who
have been engraved on school buildings, programs or libraries,
include Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.; Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.; Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., and Conrad Burns, R-Mont. Former Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, an astronaut, also has an academic center at Ohio State
University named after him.
</P>
<P>
   Burns' namesake, christened by Montana State University in 1997,
is the Burns Telecommunications Center, which promotes the
education of students who live off campus and commute via telephone
lines, modems and computers. According to an official at the
center, several telecommunications firms contributed to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee's
communications subcommittee.
</P>
</TEXT>
