u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-LAWSUIT08-COX     05-07 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke argues it can communicate with all employees
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. said Friday it has the right to
communicate with all employees about a racial discrimination
lawsuit, rejecting allegations by plaintiffs that it violated a
federal court rule when it sent e-mails to salaried black
employees.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the plaintiffs' attempt to get a court order to
prevent the company from communicating with potential members of a
class-action suit promotes discrimination, the company said in its
first legal response in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relief plaintiffs seek would impose an unconstitutional
prior restraint on Coca-Cola's right to free speech, require
Coca-Cola to segregate and discriminate against its own employees _
the very employees plaintiffs seek to represent _ and punish
Coca-Cola for having African-American employees in positions of
significant authority,'' the company told the judge in its written
response.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, one former and three current Coca-Cola employees
filed suit in U.S. District Court in Atlanta, alleging the company
systematically discriminated against African-Americans in pay,
promotions, performance evaluations and terminations. The
plaintiffs are seeking class-action status for their suit so they
can represent 1,500 salaried black employees of Coca-Cola in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, the plaintiffs said company Chairman and Chief
Executive M. Douglas Ivester violated a court rule by sending two
e-mails about the lawsuit to all 10,000 U.S. employees, including
African-Americans. The plaintiffs' attorneys contend that Ivester
had no right to communicate with potential members of a
class-action suit without prior court approval, which he did not
seek.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the plaintiffs' attorneys want the court to stop
Ivester or any other company official from communicating about the
suit with the salaried black employees who might become plaintiffs
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola argued Friday that case law requires evidence the
company abused employees' rights before the court can limit its
communication with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absent specific findings of abuse, Coca-Cola is entitled to
communicate openly and honestly with its employees, including
prospective class members, in order to conduct its business and
defend itself against this lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Story will hold a hearing next
Thursday on this issue. The plaintiffs' attorneys had no comment
Friday on Coca-Cola's response to their motion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
