<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-ROMANIA-1STLDWRI     05-07 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ROMANIA-1STLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN PAUL II MAKES HISTORIC VISIT TO ROMANIA 
</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHRU-NYT  
 (Eds: Subs 1st and 5th graph to correct) (rm) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania _ Fulfilling a dream long denied, John Paul
II arrived in Romania Friday for the first visit of a pope to a
predominantly Orthodox country.
</P>
<P>
   Reveling in the symbolism, the pope drove up to the Orthodox
Cathedral in his glass-encased white jeep with Patriarch Teoctist
of the Romanian Orthodox Church at his side, both of them in white
vestments and smiling broadly. It was the first time that a
non-Catholic religious leader has ridden shoulder to shoulder with
the pope inside the pope mobile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I kissed the ground with great emotion, grateful most of all
to God who in his benevolence allowed me to see this desire
realized,'' the pope said at the airport, where the patriarch
greeted him with a kiss. The two leaders later prayed side by side
at the Orthodox Cathedral, amid icons, incense and the chanting of
an Orthodox choir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For this pope, who 20 years ago first expressed his hopes of
mending the breach between the Catholic and Orthodox churches
before the end of the second millennium, the trip has a haunting
resonance. On the eve of the year 2000, the aging pope's three-day
visit is a historic step that nevertheless falls short of his early
aim of full reconciliation between East and West. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His delight was evident, but his carefully curtailed schedule in
Bucharest also underscored the deep divisions that have kept
Catholic and Orthodox Christians apart since the schism of 1054. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pope himself referred to the most recent tensions between
the Orthodox Church and Romania's Greek-Catholic church, which
follows Eastern rites but is loyal to Rome. Both suffered under
communism, but Catholics, seen as less compliant by the regime,
were persecuted mercilessly, and their church property was given
over to the Orthodox church. Now, the churches are locked in a
bitter battle over the return of confiscated property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that my visit will help heal the wounds inflicted on
the relationship between our churches during the past 50 years,''
the pope said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those troubles, moreover, have been inflamed by the bombing
campaign next door, where Orthodox Serbs are at war with NATO. In
the eyes of at least some Orthodox leaders, the West is not just
attacking the political regime in Belgrade, it is also undermining
a rival Christian church. In his visit, John Paul II is seeking to
allay deep-seated mistrust among Orthodox Christians at a time when
their faith in their fellow Christians is daily tested by the war
in Yugoslavia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Teoctist on Friday suggested a joint effort to end
that conflict, telling the pope, ``you fight against the spirit of
secularization and you work for the reconciliation of peoples, and
that is why we hope the presence of your holiness will be a good
occasion to bring a common testimony to the drama of Yugoslavia _ a
territory placed in the middle of Christian Europe _ by asking
together for an immediate halt to the war.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch praised the visit's importance, but he also
pointed out its limits. ``We hope this visit will deepen and
reinforce our efforts of dialogue,'' the patriarch told reporters.
``This moment represents one effort among others. This is easier
than the theological effort,'' he added dryly, ``because
theologians always complicate things.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He referred to the pope's presence as an ``essentially
ecumenical visit.'' The Vatican, however, described it as a
pastoral visit, in which the pope could also minister to his
Catholic flock. The Orthodox church has sought to minimize that
aspect, insisting that the pope remain in Bucharest and not travel
to Transylvania, where most Romanian Catholics live, and where
tensions are particularly high. (In one incident last year, the two
sides came to blows inside a contested cathedral, overturning the
altar.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox church is made up of 15 autonomous denominations
with 300 million members, most of whom are in Eastern Europe. More
than 80 percent of Romania's population of 23 million is Orthodox. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main issue separating Orthodox Christians and Catholics is
the authority of the pope. Orthodoxy rejects the Catholic belief in
his primacy and his infallibility on matters of faith and morals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Romania's was the only Orthodox Church to extend the pope an
invitation, and it did so under considerable pressure from
President Emil Constantinescu. To the Romanian government, which
wants to join NATO to help its painful transition to democracy
after the overthrow of the communist dictator, Nicolae Ceausescu, a
papal visit is an important symbol of membership in the West.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8767 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-ROMANIA-2NDTAKE-     05-07 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ROMANIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUCHAREST, Romania: the West. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the Orthodox church's conditions for the pope's visit was
that the Catholic church drop all civil suits to reclaim lost
property and allow a church commission to settle the dispute. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that the pope's visit inspired concessions on
the Orthodox side as well. Last last month, Metropolitan Nicolae
Corneanu of Timisoara gave an interview to an Italian Catholic
magazine and apologized for his own collaboration with the
Communist regime, and for not helping his persecuted Catholic
colleagues. Metropolitan Nicolae is one of the few Orthodox bishops
in Romania who has willingly returned Greek-Catholic churches in
his diocese. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch, who was accused of collaboration with the
Communist government, resigned after the Ceausescu regime was
overthrown in 1989 and entered a monastery. Three months later,
church leaders pressed him to return. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The property dispute is veined with centuries-old grievances,
which include Orthodox fears that the Greek-Catholic church is
seeking new converts and, because of its links to Rome, is a
better-financed, more powerful rival. Such suspicions are widely
shared throughout the Orthodox world, despite a pledge made by the
pope in 1991 that the Catholic Church would not seek to convert
Orthodox Christians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the pope repeated his desire to visit Moscow.
But Patriarch Aleksei II has declined to meet with him, citing
unresolved disputes with Rome.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the manifestations of the divide between the churches
of the East and West has been the Eastern-rite Catholics,'' said
the Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky, ecumenical officer of the Russian
Orthodox Church in America. ``Many Orthodox see these churches as a
kind of Trojan horse, a deceptive way for Rome to extend its reach
into the East. Those feelings are very powerful among many Orthodox
believers.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who on Saturday plans to celebrate a Catholic mass and
visit a cemetery where Greek-Catholics who were persecuted by the
Communists are buried, also met privately with Catholic bishops in
Bucharest today. He told them that it would be ``just'' to return
some church property, but also warned that it would be difficult
for the Greek-Catholic church to regain everything it lost in
1948. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pope's efforts to reconcile Catholics and Orthodox
Christians is part of an edgy process of rapprochement which began
in 1965, when the two churches annulled their mutual
excommunication edicts, in force since 1054. Vatican Council II
made ecumenical dialogue between East and West even more of a
priority. But those changes in Rome's thinking are not always as
apparent to religious leaders in Romania as they are to their
Western counterparts. ``The new attitudes that came out of Vatican
II all happened when Romanians were trapped behind the Iron
Curtain,'' the Rev. Robert Roberson, author of ``The Eastern
Christian Churches,'' explained. ``There is still a lot of
catching-up to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the pope set out to charm his Orthodox hosts. Before
delivering a speech in Romanian, the pope beamed at his audience
and, speaking in French, recalled his first words to Italian
believers after he was elected pope. ``This is what I said: `If I
make any mistakes, you'll correct me,' '' he said. ``I would like
to repeat the same words here, all the more so as I am even less
prepared to speak Romanian.'' The Orthodox bishops responded with
laughter and applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
