u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WELCOME-BOS &LR;      05-07 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WELCOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR WELCOME WEARS THIN IN ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ The police, waving guns, burst into a downtown
hotel while the Kosovar Albanians were eating lunch, telling the
Kosovars they had five minutes to collect their things and file
onto buses.
</P>
<P>
   For the refugees, who were welcomed six weeks earlier by their
Albanian cousins, eviction at gunpoint seemed all too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were worse than the Serbs,'' said Selim Ferizaj, 22, one
of about 300 refugees evicted from the state-run Hotel Arbana this
month. ``We didn't know Albanian police were like that. We thought
they loved us.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after the first refugees began the mountainous
trek from Kosovo to safety here, the welcome mat graciously laid
out by local Albanians is wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians at first said they would eagerly take in their ``blood
brothers'' _ the Kosovar Albanians _ and share their meager food
supplies with them. But with cash running short and the number of
refugees growing exponentially, locals say they cannot continue to
support the Kosovars. Some are even gouging the refugees with high
prices for food and continued lodging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they didn't expect the invasion,'' said refugee Dritan
Cena, 27, who was bused to a squalid camp after being thrown out of
another downtown hotel. ``Maybe they were ready for 10,000 or
20,000, but not a half-million people.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees began filing into Albania last year, escaping the
fighting between the Kosovo Liberation Army and the Yugoslav
military. But since the Serbs' program of forced expulsion went
into overdrive after the NATO bombing began in March, more than
400,000 people have flooded Albania _ tired, homeless, and often
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Aid organizations estimate that the number of refugees entering
Europe's poorest nation may reach 1 million _ resulting in a 30
percent increase in Albania's population of 3.2 million. Many
Kosovars are coming from neighboring Macedonia, which has balked at
taking more Kosovars, and from Montenegro, a politically unstable
republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar refugees are extremely visible in Tirana, drying their
clothes on bushes and sleeping in public parks. Refugee centers
take up almost every empty public building in Tirana, and parks and
parking lots have turned into filthy tent cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovars complain that the Albanians are trying to gouge them on
housing and transportation. In a nation where the average monthly
wage is $106, landlords are demanding $250 a month and more for
tiny apartments. Sinbad Sadiku, 30, is paying for two such
apartments to house his extended family, and said he had to fork
over $240 to a driver to take his family, among them his diabetic
mother who nearly died while fleeing Kosovo, from the border town
of Kukes to Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't believe us, that the Serbs took all our money''
when they forced the Kosovars to march to Albania, Sadiku said.
</P>
<P>
   Old resentments and jealousies are also fueling the tension
between the locals and the refugees. The Kosovar Albanians have
long been wealthier, better educated, and better traveled than the
Albanians, who for a half-century lived under the most repressive
regime in the communist bloc, that of dictator Enver Hoxha.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rule of longtime Yugoslav leader Josip Broz Tito,
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo enjoyed a more open society and
political autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Albanians are beginning to resent helping out their
``rich'' brothers, Sadiku said. ``We are one blood, but they only
look to take money from us,'' Ferizaj said.
</P>
<P>
   Local Albanians say the Albanian and Western governments are not
doing enough to help the host families.
</P>
<P>
   In Fier, about 100 miles south of Tirana, 12 Kosovar families
who had been staying with host families have moved back into the
overcrowded refugee collection center because the families could
not carry the burden any longer, said Vahide Majad, director of the
Kino Teatri refugee center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government said they would give 100 leke (about 75 cents)
per person per day, but they haven't even done that,'' Majad said.
``So we are taking them here and then to the camps. What else can
we do?''
</P>
<P>
   Zyrafete Axhanela has just a week more with a host family in
Fier before she will be asked to leave. ``I don't know where I will
go _ maybe to the street,'' Axhanela said, holding back tears as
she sat among her dirty, threadbare belongings in a Fier park.
</P>
<P>
   Aristidh Theka, manager of the Arbana, said the $20-a-night
hotel had to evict the refugee families because ``we would have
been bankrupt'' if they had stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't happy about it, but what could we do?'' he said.
``The Albanians are in a very bad situation, made worse because
they took in refugees. In my opinion, someone must care for the
Albanian families'' who are taking in refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Theka denied that the police forced refugees to leave _ an
account disputed by a half-dozen refugees who said the group of
several hundred was rounded up and sent to the Mullet camp, about 6
miles from Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick, so I was sitting down'' at the hotel, said Shahe
Kukaj, 38. ``The police said, `What are you doing here? Get on the
bus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `At the beginning, you treated us well, but at
the end, you force us to leave, like the Serbs,' '' said Kukaj, who
is staying at the Mullet camp.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian officials say the cash-strapped government cannot
reimburse families who have taken refugees into their homes. ``We
don't yet have a solution for the host families,'' said Arben
Malaj, a legislator. He said host families tend to be Albania's
poorest households, often made up of two retired people.
</P>
<P>
   Some families, however, are struggling to support refugee guests
and say they will not throw them out on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an expression _ space is space, water is water, and
bread is bread _ they belong to everyone,'' said Petrit Knuti, an
engineer who has taken a Kosovar family of five into his home. ``We
will never ask them to leave. The poorest the person, the bigger
the heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
