<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media Metrix stock price soars on first trading day
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Media Metrix, currently the provider of the Internet's
best measurement of eyeballs on Web sites, more than doubled its
stock price on its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which merged with Atlanta-based Web measurement
firm Relevant Knowledge last year, opened for trading Friday at
$33, the first price at which most investors were able to buy the
stock _ and gained an additional $12.56 1/4 to close at $45.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix surveys computer users to determine how many people
are visiting individual Web sites at home and in the workplace, the
measurement on which advertising rates for those sites are set.
</P>
<P>
   The company's clients include almost every major Internet
company, including America Online, Yahoo!, CNN, Amazon.com and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a direct correlation between the growth in
revenue of this company and the growth in advertising revenue on
the Internet,'' said Paul Bard, an analyst with Renaissance Capital
Corp. in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix faces potential competition from
Nielsen-NetRatings, which launched its own Web measurement business
in March. Nielsen-NetRatings offers subscribers detailed
advertising data but has drawn fire from critics for failing to
offer a measurement of use at the workplace, where Web activity is
the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix, itself, raised $51 million from the offering of 3
million shares at $17 per share. The original pricing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission was $12 to $14. In its SEC
filing, Media Metrix said it planned to use the money for new
product development, international expansion and general corporate
purposes, including working capital.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
