<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TV-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA MOVES TO STOP RECEPTION OF FOREIGN TELEVISION CHANNELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a move that may reflect China's jitters during a
year of politically charged milestones, the Chinese government has
begun to clamp down on the illegal reception of foreign television
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government issued a warning in an official
newspaper that cable operators were barred from carrying foreign
satellite programs. And on Thursday, state television showed the
police confiscating satellite dishes, receivers and decoders from a
Chinese satellite television company in Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives said China's crackdown appeared to be the
latest in a periodic enforcement of laws that restrict
satellite-delivered television services to hotels and residential
complexes for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the government has rarely enforced the laws. That
has allowed hundreds of cable operators to pick up and retransmit
channels like ESPN and the Phoenix Chinese Channel to millions of
viewers. In China's prosperous regions, rooftop satellite dishes
are a common sight.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen Square
massacre less than a month away, some industry experts believe the
government wants to curtail foreign channels that might carry news
reports about the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sensitive time,'' said Eric Li, a director at
Claydon Gescher Associates, a consulting firm in Beijing that
advises clients on the Chinese communications market. ``With so
many big events going on, it would be natural for the government to
take a look at what's coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Tiananmen anniversary, in October China will
mark the 50th anniversary of the establishment of the People's
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The government's action could pose a threat to several major
Western media companies with ambitions in China, including Walt
Disney Co. and Viacom. ESPN, which is owned by Disney, and MTV,
owned by Viacom, are both distributed in China through satellite
signals that are retransmitted by cable.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most vulnerable is News Corp., which owns part of
Phoenix Satellite Television, a Mandarin-language entertainment
channel that is aimed exclusively at the mainland Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix reaches an estimated 45 million households in China,
most through cable operators who pick up its satellite signal from
Hong Kong and retransmit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether this is a temporary thing or something
more permanent that could affect our business,'' said Jannie Poon,
a spokeswoman for Phoenix, which is also partly owned by two
Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Poon said executives at Phoenix were consulting with
industry regulators in Beijing. But she noted that decisions
governing foreign television programming were often made by
higher-level officials, and it was not clear why the authorities
had chosen to take a hard line now.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the speculation about Tiananmen Square, industry
executives said Beijing may also be nervous about the spread of
satellites in Fujian, a coastal province that faces Taiwan. These
satellites enable thousands of homes in Fujian to receive
television broadcasts from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown would be a setback for Rupert Murdoch, the
chairman of News Corp. Murdoch has lobbied for years to establish a
foothold in China. Last December, he met with China's president,
Jiang Zemin, seeming to cement his return to favor after a speech
in 1993 in which he said that satellites posed ``an unambiguous
threat to totalitarian regimes everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some industry analysts said that given the murkiness of
their status in China, Phoenix and other foreign satellite
television services ought to be prepared for sporadic challenges to
their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build your business model on a law not really being
implemented, you are running a lot of risks,'' Li said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The timing of China's crackdown on satellite television would
seem odd, given that the government is in the latter stages of
negotiating to enter the World Trade Organization. But legal
experts noted that the openness of the Chinese television market
was not an issue in the broader WTO talks.
</P>
<P>
   And some said that China's action should not be interpreted as a
wholesale closing of its communications market. The government,
they said, could tighten its grip temporarily out of a perceived
short-term political interest while still maintaining a long-term
policy of gradually opening its market.
</P>
<P>
   Kaushik Shridharani, a media analyst at Salomon Smith Barney
here, said foreign television broadcasters had made considerable
headway in China in the last few years. One of Hong Kong's most
popular channels, TVB, is widely and illegally distributed in
neighboring Guangdong province by Chinese cable operators who
receive and retransmit its signal over their networks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, TVB is close to a deal in which the cable operators will
continue to carry the channel, but will pay the company for the
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, China moves two steps forward and one step
back,'' said Jeanette Chan, a partner who specializes in
communications law at Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison in
Hong Kong. ``Just because they're doing a crackdown doesn't mean
they're not also trying to liberalize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
