<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE IN DARKNESS AFTER HEAVY NATO BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a day of increasing optimism that Yugoslav
officials were warming to an international peace plan, NATO planes
pounded Belgrade with bombs Friday night, setting the Chinese
Embassy ablaze and sending the city into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials had been edging closer to discussing a peace
agreement earlier in the day, prompting a flurry of hopeful
diplomatic activity around the world. Yugoslav television described
the path toward peace as ``a very lengthy and complex process,
which will probably end successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin had also shown signs
of cautious optimism, announcing plans to visit Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to discuss the peace proposal, agreed to by
Russian and Western leaders Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the attack on the Chinese Embassy threatened to jeopardize
the earlier progress. China, as a permanent member of the UN
Security Council, has the power to veto any peace agreement brought
to the table. Chinese leaders are opposed to the NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they did not believe anyone was killed in the
attack. Around the same time, blasts were also reported at three
major power stations in the Serbian capital. Heavy anti-aircraft
fire _ some of the heaviest seen thus far in the air campaign _
also lit up the sky, according to television reports.
</P>
<P>
   The attack followed another controversial NATO strike the night
before, in which NATO admitted it had probably accidentally rained
cluster bombs on civilians. Officials said it was ``highly
probable'' it had dropped a series of devastating bombs near a
hospital and a market 120 miles southeast of Belgrade early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists who were escorted to the scene by Serb officials
reported seeing splintered buildings and dismembered human bodies
where the bombs apparently hit. Serb officials said the attack left
15 civilians dead. At least 1,500 Yugoslavians have been killed and
another 5,000 wounded since the conflict began March 24, Yugoslav
officials said earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is performing daytime attacks. That is a western
democracy, this is a residential area,'' Jovan Zlatic, head of the
county of Nis, said, joining the chorus of Serb objections to the
NATO missiles, which have strayed from their military targets
repeatedly in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we ask the whole world and every man on the planet: `How
can this genocidal aggression be possible only one day after the
G-8 meeting decided to solve the conflict by peaceful means?' ''
asked Serbian Deputy Premier Milovan Bojic. ``This is not an
accidental mistake by the NATO air force. This is an intentional
act to destroy a nation, an act of genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   The renewed vigor of the air campaign reflected the US political
message of the day: That any diplomatic weakening on the part of
Milosevic will be met only with further bombing until he agrees to
total peace.
</P>
<P>
   American officials rejected pleas from both Serb and Russian
officials for the bombing to stop. General Hugh Shelton, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, vowed to continue the campaign
``until such time as Milosevic has agreed to the terms established
by NATO.'' President Clinton issued a call for similar resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for the United States and our allies
neither to add nor subtract from the basic conditions that we have
said all along are essential to make this work,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Friday:
</P>
<P>
   _ For the second time, a NATO missile struck Bulgaria, roughly
12 miles west of Sofia. An earlier missile strayed into Bulgaria on
April 28.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Congress, Representative Benjamin A. Gilman, Republican of
New York, announced plans to hold hearings next Thursday in the
House International Relations Committee. Gilman cautioned Congress
to ``be mindful that it is diplomacy that will ultimately shape the
future of Kosovo and Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Over earlier objections of Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, UN Secretary General Kofi Annan announced the appointment
of two new special envoys to the Balkans: former Swedish Prime
Minister Carl Bildt and Slovakian Foreign Minister Eduard Kukan.
Bildt had publicly criticized the NATO airstrikes, saying they were
insufficient to win the war and indicative of NATO's lack of
commitment to sending in ground troops. Annan said both men were
``very experienced and very good negotiators.''
</P>
<P>
   _ As many as 176 US Air Force and Marine Corps planes _
including 36 more F-15 fighter jets, 18 more A-10 attack planes and
80 more tanker planes _ were on their way to the Balkans to join
the war effort, Pentagon officials said. A day earlier, the House
approved $13 billion for spending on the conflict and military
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The distance between war and peace remained difficult to gauge,
particularly as several sticking points repeatedly emerged. Among
the most serious: whether NATO, or US troops, would be a part of
any international peacekeeping force to take control of Kosovo
after the fighting stops.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials have said NATO would be at the core of any
such force, and yet Milosevic has rejected that idea. The force is
defined in the plan only as an ``effective international civil and
security'' presence. Presidential National Security Adviser Sandy
Berger Friday described it as a ``robust presence that would not
only be able to defend itself but maintain civil order,'' leaving
its definition completely unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement over peacekeeping forces was among the
controversies that caused the Rambouillet peace talks to fail,
prompting NATO to begin airstrikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
