<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR WINS MOST SEATS IN NEW LEGISLATURES IN SCOTLAND AND WALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ Prime Minister Tony Blair has succeeded in
holding off threats from nationalist parties in Scotland and Wales,
with his Labor Party winning the most seats in the new legislatures
there, election results showed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Labor failed to win outright control of the Scottish Parliament
or the Welsh National Assembly, but Blair said he still felt the
results represented an endorsement of his reform of British
politics. He has made the parceling out, or devolution, of
authority to the regions of Britain a principal objective of his
two-year-old government.
</P>
<P>
   ``In relation to Scotland and Wales, I think the most important
elements are that we have made devolution work, and in Scotland
it's absolutely clear that the vast majority of people voted for
parties that are opposed to the nationalist agenda of
independence,'' the prime minister said in London as tabulations in
Thursday's election concluded. ``People have rejected the notion of
separatism.''
</P>
<P>
   He said devolution represented no threat to the future security
of a united Britain. ``I believe and I hope that out of these
elections the union of the United Kingdom will have been
strengthened rather than weakened,'' he told reporters at 10
Downing St.
</P>
<P>
   The election also filled more than 12,000 local council seats
across Britain, voting that is viewed as a midterm barometer
reading of the party in power.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservatives showed stirrings of recovery from the their
overwhelming setbacks in the general election in 1997 and the last
midterm election, in 1995. Their modest gains of 1,300 town hall
seats were seen as sufficient to save their beleaguered head,
William Hague, from an immediate leadership challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties traditionally recover ground in midterm
elections, and the Labor Party was particularly susceptible to
losses now because of the runaway numbers they had scored in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Tory gains gave no encouragement to the party's hopes of
winning Britain back in the next election. Labor's overall vote
total was higher than the Conservatives', a rare occurrence in
Britain of a party in power beating the opposition in a midterm
election. Hague sought to put a gloss on that setback, saying,
``After everything we have been told about how the Labor Party
walks on electoral water, we have come within 3 percentage points
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   By falling 9 seats short of a majority in the 129-seat Scottish
Parliament, Labor will be obliged to enlist the centrist Liberal
Democrats in a coalition, a form of governing not seen in Britain
since World War II. In Wales, Labor won 28 of the 60 seats and will
quite likely adopt the same tactic there.
</P>
<P>
   For Scotland it is the first legislature since union with
England in 1707, and for Wales it is the first ever. Mindful of
this historic dimension to the balloting, politicians urged people
to show up at the polls in high numbers. The BBC prefaced its
periodic reports with the heraldic introduction ``History in the
Making,'' and the front page of The Scotsman read, ``This is the
day we have dreamed of ... today we vote.''
</P>
<P>
   But fewer than 60 percent of eligible Scottish voters cast
ballots, some 13 percentage points less than at the general
election two years ago, and politicians bemoaned the low turnout.
Some people blamed the wet and windy weather, some faulted the
undemonstrative nature of Scots and others pointed to negative
campaigning in the hard-fought contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the political class failed to get across to the voters
how important this was,'' said John Curtice, professor of politics
at the University of Strathclyde.
</P>
<P>
   In Wales the turnout was 38 percent, and in England, where the
voting was just for council seats, 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The two new regional legislatures will gain authority and
budgets to pursue matters like transportation, health, education
and housing. The British Parliament in London keeps the broader
portfolios of foreign, defense, economic and fiscal policy. The
Scottish Parliament has lawmaking and taxing powers, while the
Welsh National Assembly does not.
</P>
<P>
   In both new legislatures, the principal opposition parties are
the nationalists, leaving the Conservatives in unaccustomed third
place. The Welsh nationalist group, Plaid Cymru (pronounced plyde
KUM-ry), is not a pro-independence party, but the Scottish
Nationalist Party is.
</P>
<P>
   Led by their politically canny head, Alex Salmond, the Scottish
Nationalists stunned Labor in the early months of the campaign by
climbing 15 points into the lead in opinion polls. But as the race
drew to a close, they lost followers and finished Friday with less
than 30 percent of the vote and under 40 seats in the legislature,
two goals they had set for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the slightest bit downhearted,'' Salmond said, noting
that his party had polled 7 points higher than in the last
election.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that many voters, approaching the brink of the idea
of secession from Britain, stepped back. ``There was a lot of talk
about independence, and that scared people off a bit,'' said
Professor James Kellas of the University of Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were the first time that mainline Britain had
experienced proportional representation voting; it was used in the
elections to the new Northern Ireland Assembly last year.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is intended to produce a result that better
reflects the total vote won by each party than does the traditional
system used in Britain, in which each seat goes to the top
vote-getter in a legislative district.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Labor government's idea to use proportional
representation, even though it tends to benefit smaller parties
more than larger ones and can end up producing the kind of
coalition arrangements more common to Continental countries. Blair
said Friday that ``it was always going to be the case that by
taking a different electoral system, it was highly unlikely any
party would have an overall majority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
