<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-INFLUENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHADAFY SEEN AS PEACEMAKER IN MANY AFRICAN NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As Washington warily prepares to end an 18-year
boycott of Libya, Colonel Moammar Khadafy has been anything but
isolated on his own continent, where he has armed, financed and
trained many of Africa's emerging leaders, from Liberia to Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Since the UN suspended sanctions on Libya last month,
processions of African heads of state have traveled to the
colonel's desert tent to pay their respects. And the former sponsor
of international terrorism is now being welcomed as a peacemaker by
prominent African leaders, including one-time comrade-in-arms
Nelson Mandela, who owe their own political survival to the Arab
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Kabila, the president of the Democratic Republic of
Congo, turned to the Libyan colonel in the 1980s for help in his
rebellion against Mobutu Sese Seko, the corrupt dictator who ruled
the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Taylor, who now leads Liberia after being educated and
doing jail time in Massachusetts, received military training and
weapons from Tripoli during his rise to power.
</P>
<P>
   And Uganda's President Yoweri Museveni, a favorite in
Washington, recently thanked Khadafy for supplying him with 900
rifles when he was a struggling rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   But as Libya embarks on a series of high-level diplomatic
initiatives to mediate African conflicts in the Congo, Sierra
Leone, and in the Horn of Africa, US policymakers are wondering
whether the Libyan leader will continue his role as spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   And they fret that the fiercely anti-American Khadafy will use
his new breathing-room to undermine American policies in the region
and to train and arm a new generation of African insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   While US officials concede that Khadafy has moderated his
behavior in recent years, they still suspect he continues to
secretly develop chemical weapons. And they suspect he continues to
fund armed groups, including those in Sierra Leone and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Acting through his long-time allies, Taylor in Liberia and
Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso, Khadafy channels money and arms to
Sierra Leonean rebels seeking the overthrow of the country's first
elected president, according to US and African officials.
</P>
<P>
   He financed the deployment of several hundred Chadian soldiers
in Congo to fight alongside Kabila's forces. He funneled arms
through Gambia into Guinea Bissau, whose government was overthrown
by rebels Friday. And he has provided funding for Eritrea's war
against Ethiopia, prompting a formal protest from the Ethiopian
government, according to diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a situation that the Libyans can screw up, they
will do it,'' said Joseph Sala, a political analyst who served in
the State Department's Africa bureau until 1998. ``Nobody sees a
clear pattern to it, but there has been a consistent effort in the
past to destabilize West Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, Khadafy handed rifles to Museveni's successful rebel
army, but earlier he had provided military support to the brutal
government of Idi Amin, who was deposed in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Libya continues to hedge its bets, supplying modest
financial and military support to insurgencies in countries with
which it has warm relations.
</P>
<P>
   Chad and Niger, for instance, have provided critical support for
Libya in its quest to have UN economic sanctions lifted. But US
officials charge that Khadafy continues to arm rebel Toubous and
Tuaregs in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly much of our media portrays Khadafy as a bungling idiot,
but he is one of the masters of realpolitik,'' one US official
said. ``He'll support a rebel force to keep his own allies in
check.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Khadafy's continued support for African insurgencies,
the Clinton administration remains committed to sitting down at the
table with Libyan officials at UN-sponsored talks for the first
time in 18 years. The meeting later this month will consider
whether to permanently lift sanctions following Tripoli's surrender
of two suspects for trial in connection with the 1988 bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, meanwhile, has agreed to ease US sanctions on Libya,
Sudan and Iran, granting US companies the right to sell food and
medicines to those countries. The softening of the American
position on Libya marked a major shift in its policy since it broke
diplomatic relations with Libya in the early 1980s, charging that
Tripoli was a chief sponsor of international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   While Khadafy has sought to build bridges with his African
counterparts, his relations with the Arab world have become
considerably more chilly. Angered that Arab leaders failed to join
Africans in violating a UN air embargo, Khadafy has made it clear
he will spend his oil wealth on his own continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these African leaders defied the embargo and came to
visit him when he was sick,'' said Clovis Maksoud, a former UN
ambassador for the Arab League. ``The Arabs did not go.''
</P>
<P>
   US and European officials say that Khadafy still owes hundreds
of millions to European and Russian creditors, whose accounts were
frozen after sanctions were imposed. They say his current
popularity is likely to fade when the economic realities set in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
