<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ TO SLASH THE NUMBER OF ITS PC DISTRIBUTORS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Compaq Computer Corp. will announce next week a
distribution alliance plan that is expected to slash the number of
PC distributors who sell its products to four from about 40.
</P>
<P>
   The PC maker is expected to make the cuts to lower costs, manage
inventory and better track consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   The distributors who survive the downsizing will receive more
volume to make up for the loss at other outlets, but they may have
to give Compaq better terms.
</P>
<P>
   The likely survivors will be Ingram Micro, Tech Data Corp.,
Merisel and CompuCom Systems, Ashok Kumar, an analyst at U.S.
Bancorp Piper Jaffray, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram Micro and Tech Data make Compaq's Prosignia products for
small and medium-sized businesses and build some other products at
Houston-based Compaq's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Merisel also works with Compaq to build some computers on site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq's job of managing distribution will become a lot
simpler,'' said Kurt King, an analyst at NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Although the PC maker would not give details of the plan, the
surprise measure was greeted with enthusiasm from analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' Kumar said. ``They needed to
make some tough decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   This would be the first major move Chairman and acting Chief
Executive Officer Ben Rosen has made since Eckhard Pfeiffer was
forced to resign as CEO and Earl Mason, Compaq's chief financial
officer, quit to become the president of a company in a
non-technology industry last month.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been under rising pressure from analysts and
shareholders for some time now. Sales have slowed and earnings have
slipped. The stock price has lost more than half its value since
reaching a record high of 49 1/4 in January.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq rose 1/4 to 24 7/8 in heavy trading Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The distributors who don't make the cut may end up competing
with Compaq as the company moves further away from traditional
storefront selling to offering its products on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't satisfy all the people all of the time,'' Kumar
said. ``They have to do what's best for Compaq and its
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also is likely to reduce the amount of price protection
it gives to distributors, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   When a computer is sold through a distributor, the manufacturer
often guarantees that if prices fall before the machine is sold, it
will make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But that makes it difficult for Compaq to compete with Dell
Computer Corp., which carries only days of inventory and don't have
to offer any price protection.
</P>
<P>
   Computer prices can fall as much as 1 percent a week while
sitting on warehouse shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer-related companies already have made similar moves
in consolidating distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer cut the number of distributors to two from five,
and Seagate Technology reduced its distributors to five from 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-07 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOVAK QUIETLY DECIDES `IT'S TIME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was always quiet and would never do anything to call
attention to himself. So it is not surprising that just a few weeks
short of his 80th birthday, the marvelous Mike Holovak walked away
from a football career that covered 68 years and has been matched
by few.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for me,'' Holovak said Friday from his Florida
retirement home. ``I've been so lucky. All of my life I have worked
at something I loved to do. But coaching was the most fun. That's
what I loved best.''
</P>
<P>
   Holovak, son of a Polish immigrant who immigrated to the coal
mines of Pennsylvania, was one of Boston College's first great
football players. He was All-American running back in the early
1940s and a first-round draft choice of the powerful Chicago Bears.
After serving in World War II, he returned to play in Chicago. He
then coached BC for nine years, was coach and general manager of
the Patriots for 10 years, had a tour as assistant and interim head
coach of the Jets, went back to the Patriots as a scout, then went
to Houston for 19 years as GM and player personnel director.
</P>
<P>
   Holovak is one of three men whose tremendous contributions to
the Boston area have not been properly recognized. The others are
Milt Schmidt of the Bruins and Johnny Pesky of the Red Sox. Schmidt
and Pesky have been in the area for 60 years, playing, coaching,
and doing countless good works for all kinds of charities. They are
truly part of the fabric of this city.
</P>
<P>
   Holovak, though he started in Pennsylvania and ended in
Tennessee (where the Oilers moved), will always be a Bostonian.
Billy Sullivan founded the Patriots, but the guy who saved them was
Holovak. It was his personality, and the love his players had for
him, that kept the team afloat in its first decade of existence.
The team won consistently with the lowest payroll in the league and
the worst practice conditions imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my players on those teams,'' said Holovak. ``I will
always think of them as `my boys.' They were such good guys, and so
many of them did so well when they were finished playing. I still
feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Holovak's life story reads like a history of pro football. He
played for the legendary George Halas, who founded the National
Football League. ``I liked him a lot. He was a regular guy. I was
the number one draft choice and he gave me a thousand dollars,''
Holovak said with a laugh. ``Not bad for those days. We had fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Hall of Famers like Sid Luckman, George McAfee,
and Bulldog Turner. Now there was a player.'' Turner was the Dick
Butkus of his day. ``The night before a game Halas would have a
meeting and give the team a test to make sure they were paying
attention. Bulldog would always sit beside me, because Halas would
ask us to identify the numbers of the key players on the other
team, and Bulldog knew I would give him the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Holovak's biggest disappointment came as the general
manager of the Oilers. As a scout, he brought quarterback Warren
Moon out of Canada to Houston with the intent of building a strong
contending team around him. ``I went to Canada the final year
Warren was up there and watched every game he played in person. I
told Houston we had to get him.'' Holovak helped build a powerhouse
with the Oilers, a team that went to the playoffs eight straight
years, but never got to the Super Bowl. ``It was frustrating,''
Holovak said. ``There were a couple of years in there I knew our
talent was as good as any team in the league, and a lot of other
people felt that way. But we just couldn't get it done. A couple of
years a guy named Elway beat us, and then another year in Buffalo,
we blew the biggest lead ever to the Bills and lost. That was
devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Holovak, like Schmidt and Pesky, gave up part of his life to
fight in World War II but has no regrets. ``After I got out of
Boston College in 1943, I went to PT (boat) school in Melville,
R.I., and then to the South Pacific. On Christmas Day, on the
island of New Guinea, I came down with malaria. I didn't know what
hit me. I went into the hospital and was unconscious for a week. I
woke up on New Year's Day. I didn't know anything that happened
that whole week. So when I look back, there is very little I would
have changed in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holovak was deeply saddened by Friday's death of the wonderful
Leon Hess, as were most of us who had the privilege of knowing the
owner of the New York Jets. ``He was just a fabulous man, one of
the best,'' said Holovak. ``He never interfered. He was one of the
most thoughtful men I have ever met. I remember each year at
Christmas, no matter what the team's record was, he would have a
party for every member of the organization and their children. And
he would have a gift for every person who came. He would have to be
considered one of the best owners ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess was one of the wealthiest men in the United States, but he
had a common touch. There was never any pretense to Hess, the
consumate gentleman in dress and manner. Two stories show what he
was like. When defensive tackle Dennis Byrd suffered a serious neck
injury and looked as though he could be paralyzed for life, Hess,
even though he was closing in on 80 at the time, visited Byrd every
single day he was in the hospital. And just this past January, when
Hess was not strong enough to make the trip to see his team play in
the AFC Championship Game in Denver, which it lost, he was waiting
for the team when it arrived back in New York at 1:30 in the
morning. As the team got off its plane, Hess shook the hand of
everyone on it, and personally thanked them for their contribution
to the season. All the while a friend had to hold him by the arm to
help him stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved this guy,'' said Jets coach Bill Parcells. ``He was as
fine a man as anyone I've ever met. It was a privilege to be able
to know him, and I'm very fortunate that I had the chance to coach
for him and to get to know him. His loss will be a tremendous one
to the New York Jets.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots owner Bob Kraft on Hess: ``When I first came in to the
league, he was great to me, giving me all the benefits of his
experience in the game. He was a real elder statesman in the
National Football League. It's hard to replace men like him.''
(Obituary, page B7.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let me see if I understand this. The Dream Team of doctors that
was called in to try to help Reggie Lewis when he first collapsed
was no good, so Donna Harris-Lewis pulled him out of New England
Baptist Hospital. Then the next set of doctors at Brigham and
Women's Hospital were no good, so she is suing them. What should be
remembered is the Dream Team was made up of the top cardiologists
from most all of the top hospitals around the city, not just New
England Baptist. Dr. Arnold Scheller, who testified on behalf of
Lewis (and the Celtics) this week, is an orthopedic doctor, not a
cardiologist. One item in Scheller's testimony I found particularly
interesting was that he said he told Lewis he was going to test him
for cocaine the next day, and at midnight that night, Donna moved
him to Brigham and Woman's . . . When Heisman Trophy winner Ricky
Williams showed up at the NFL's scouting combine in Indianapolis in
February, he weighed in at 240. When he worked out in San Diego in
early April for teams interesed in him, he weighed 224. Seventeen
days later, when he arrived in New Orleans after being drafted by
the Saints, he was back up to 240, gaining almost a pound a day
after the workout . . . The best-kept secret around here is BC
slugger Sean McGowan, the best collegiate power hitter ever in New
England. ``Sean is as good as anyone I have seen in college ball,''
said coach Peter Hughes. ``What he has done this season is
phenomenal.'' McGowan, a 6-foot-6-inch, 240-pounder with just 8
percent body fat, has 23 home runs in 41 games this year and leads
the nation in home runs per game. In the last three years at BC, he
has hit 51 home runs in 102 games. ``He has never been drafted,''
said Hughes, ``but he will go high this year. A year ago, scouts
questioned whether he could hit with a wooden bat, so he played in
a league where they used wooden bats last summer and he hit 14 home
runs and batted .430. We played against Arizona State this year,
and he had three home runs against them. In my mind, Sean is the
best power hitter in college ball.'' Who holds the Big East record
for home runs in a single season? Mo Vaughn with 28 when he played
for Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
