<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUDDLEHOUSE08-COX     05-07 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUDDLEHOUSE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huddle House tries to serve up new image
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Huddle House is tired of playing the poor cousin to
other restaurant chains.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur-based company, which has spent the past 35 years
catering to blue-collar palates, is trying to expand its customer
base with a new look, expanded menu and slick television and prints
ads.
</P>
<P>
   The diner-style chain of 335 restaurants is hoping more
professionals and families will sit along side factory workers and
bricklayers to eat its made-to-order burgers, eggs and salads.
</P>
<P>
   It's greasy-spoon, mom-and-pop image is fast fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to take Huddle House to a whole new level,''
said President and Chief Executive Officer Philip M. Greifeld.
``It's a dynamic world out there. We have to adapt, adjust and
listen to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Greifeld, who joined the company as chief financial officer in
1995, considers the chain known for its ``any meal, any time'' deal
and 24-7 hours of operations, ``a gem.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the next year, he expects same store sales, a major
indicator of a retail or restaurant company's financial health, to
grow at a respectable 2.5 percent clip.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to grow, says Greifeld, who assumed the top post in
October, the company will have to look outside its traditional
southeastern stronghold. Currently, the chain has restaurants in a
dozen states, but soon Huddle House plans to open units in new
markets including Ohio, Kentucky, Virginia and West Virginia.
Still, it will be dwarfed by another Georgia company, its main
competitor, Waffle House, which has more than 1,000 units
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to focus on being good at what we do,'' said Greifeld.
``We have to look at every aspect of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of news that franchisees like Elden Carmichael
want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Carmichael, whose Brunswick company now owns 15
units, considered getting out of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was kind of stagnant,'' said Carmichael, president
of EH Inc. ``We weren't seeing much bounce out of corporate. But
they're doing a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael said he is already starting to see a change in his
customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have blue collar customers, but we're starting to see a
wider spectrum of customers,'' he said. ``We're doing pretty nice
in terms of where we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurial streak
</P>
<P>
   Franchisees credit Greifeld, who has a degree in business
economics, with the company's new direction.
</P>
<P>
   Greifeld, who has a strong entrepreneurial streak, decided to
skip corporate America and strike out his own. He and several
partners formed a retail home furnishings business, financed
primarily with venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the business hit rocky times and closed. But, by
then, Greifeld's skills had come to the attention of the venture
capitalists, Quad C, who had just bought a small restaurant company
in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed, they convinced him to take the chief financial
officer job. It wasn't a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a kick out of building things,'' said Greifeld. ``I like
to plant acorns and watch them grow into oak trees.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case his acorn was Huddle House.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the company wasn't doing well. Huddle House was named
one of the top 50 growth companies by Restaurant Business magazine
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And the family-owned business was profitable, but clearly needed
some retooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What impressed me most was their market position,'' he said.
``And this was an underserved segment of the industry. It could
only go up. This was a golden opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Greifeld has a laid-back style, preferring employees to call him
by his first name.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone says 'sir' I start looking for my dad,'' said
Greifeld, who lives in Conyers with his wife and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He continually refers to the staff as a ``team'' and strongly
encourages workers to voice their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job here is to cultivate the team and get them excited,''
he said. ``At the end of the day, I don't want everyone looking to
me for all of the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Head-to-head competition
</P>
<P>
   Greifeld plans to go head to head with his competition, mainly
``brand X with the W''.
</P>
<P>
   He also is feeling increased pressure from other restaurant
companies including chains such as Applebee's, Shoney's and Cracker
Barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say Greifeld's plans are ambitious, but not
impossible
</P>
<P>
   ``Their reputation is probably of having medium quality food at
a reasonable price, but certainly not someplace that I would want
to dine with my family,'' said Leenie Rubin, president of Marketing
Spectrum, an Atlanta-based restaurant consulting business. ``It's
going to be very hard for them to keep their core business and
expand. Their key competitor is Waffle House, which has done an
exceptional job. Waffle House has stayed with who they are. They
haven't changed on their promise and deliver exactly what they say
they are going to _ a decent meal at a reasonable price in a
reasonable environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin doesn't write off Huddle House's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is because of lifestyle changes,'' she said.
``People are now out and about on a more irregular basis and like
the convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining the core base
</P>
<P>
   Greifeld's strategy is to ``polish the apple'' by changing the
company's image and diversify its clientele. He is adamant,
however, about keeping its core base.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that will achieved through marketing. The company is in
talks with at least one sports celebrity about becoming a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   It recently began a promotion with Pepsi Cola and Dodge to award
customers prizeds including trips to Disney World and new Dodge
van.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to open a new prototype of the restaurant soon, which
will use brighter colors and be more open. There are also plans to
expand the menu offerings and to have new uniforms for workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes are not just cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also on an aggressive growth binge opening new
co-branded units with convenience stores, fuel centers and travel
plazas.
</P>
<P>
   Greifeld plans to open 35 new stores by the end of the next
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really going to start to take notice,'' he said.
``I'm not afraid to make the hard decisions to improve this
brand.''
</P>
<P>
   The former entrepreneur, who assumed the top spot last October,
had made it clear to franchisees that it will take a team effort to
reach the company's goals. Some have been told they must either
shape up or risk being booted out of the chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know that you can't go wrong with a Huddle
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
