u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENNY-JONES-SUIT-600&AMP;     05-07 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNY-JONES-SUIT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JENNY JONES SHOW' FOUND NEGLIGENT IN SHOOTING DEATH OF GUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ In a case that has focused attention on
confrontational talk shows, a jury here on Friday ordered ``The
Jenny Jones Show'' to pay $25 million to the family of a gay man
who was shot to death after revealing that he was sexually
attracted to another man on the show.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in this northern suburb of Detroit found that Warner
Brothers, which owns, produces and distributes the show, was
negligent in the death of Scott Amedure, who died at the age of 32
in March 1995. Amedure was shot to death in the doorway of his home
three days after he revealed on the television show that he was
attracted to another guest, Jonathan Schmitz, and described his
sexual fantasies about Schmitz.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitz, who has been diagnosed as manic-depressive, was
convicted in 1996 of second-degree murder in the killing. The
conviction was overturned last November on a dispute over whether a
juror should have been dismissed, and a second criminal trial has
been set for August.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been closely watched by interest groups on all
sides, and Friday's decision immediately drew sharp reactions. Even
before the verdict was rendered, the case had an effect on daytime
talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the killing, shows like Jenny Jones', along with
others featuring Rikki Lake, Montel Williams and Jerry Springer,
were among the most profitable on television, earning as much as
$50 million to $60 million a year in profits. Often they relied on
ambushing some guests with people they were not expecting to see,
and discussing subjects they had not been told were going to be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the killing, the shows have fallen off sharply in
popularity and advertisers have begun to shy away from them. Except
for Springer's show, which still relies heavily on confrontational
topics that lead to fistfights virtually every day, the subject
matter has been toned down.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Fieger, the lead attorney for the Amedure family, said
he hoped Friday's civil verdict would change the way such talk
shows treat their guests. ``This industry has got to clean itself
up because these people care nothing about the people they use and
abuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner Brothers' lawyers vowed to appeal the verdict to the
Michigan Court of Appeals, a process that could take two years.
Even if the verdict stands, the amount of the award could be
changed by an appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   The company's lawyers contended that the decision would force
all media to worry about liability if the subjects of their
interviews later behaved in destructive ways. ``This will have a
profoundly chilling effect not only on talk shows but on all
media,'' said Warner Brothers' senior attorney, Zazi Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, a prominent First Amendment lawyer, said the
verdict was unwarranted. ``Whether we have a Jenny Jones show or a
Jerry Springer show is a matter of public taste,'' he said. ``I
think that the public is entitled to watch these shows if it wishes
and that these shows are protected'' by the Constitution's First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But William Bennett, who was education secretary in the Reagan
administration and has been a strong critic of Hollywood in recent
years, said the verdict was part of a welcome trend. ``It's a good
thing for the public to look the entertainment companies in the eye
and say, `We've had it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The talk show episode featuring Schmitz and Amedure was never
broadcast, although local television stations here have repeatedly
aired the segment in which Amedure proclaimed his affections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schmitz smiled during the show, and Warner Brothers' lawyers
said during the trial that he and Amedure had entered into a brief
relationship after the show. But the Amedure family's lawyers
denied this; Schmitz, who has said he is heterosexual, did not
testify during the civil trial because of his forthcoming criminal
retrial.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights advocates also assailed Friday's decision,
criticizing the Amedure family and its lawyers for having said that
Schmitz had been publicly embarrassed by Amedure's advances.
Jeffrey Montgomery, the executive director of the Triangle
Foundation, a gay advocacy group in Michigan, said that by blaming
the talk show rather than Schmitz, the plaintiffs in the case had
fed homophobia and created a legal blueprint for Schmitz eventually
to win acquittal on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Friday, Fieger, the Amedures' attorney,
said that talk shows should screen their guests and provide
psychiatric care after taping, as some have started to do, in order
to avoid negligence cases.
</P>
<P>
   The five women and four men on the jury voted 8-1 to find Warner
Brothers negligent; Michigan law does not require unanimity in
civil verdicts. The jury awarded Amedure's family $5 million for
his pain and suffering when he was shot, $20 million for his loss
and $6,500 for his funeral expenses. But Warner Brothers does not
have to pay anything until its appeals are exhausted. Time Warner
Inc. owns most of Warner Brothers through a limited partnership.
</P>
<P>
   If the company loses in the Michigan Court of Appeals, it could
appeal to the Michigan Supreme Court, and from there to the U.S.
Supreme Court. Each level of appeal could delay a final decision by
two or more years.
</P>
<P>
   A local NBC station covered Friday's verdict live, breaking into
``The Jenny Jones Show,'' where Friday's topic was ``teens obsessed
with their looks.'' After the show resumed, Ms. Jones was shown
moderating arguments between her audience and guests, with one
guest telling viewers that an audience member ``looks like a
45-year-old hooker.'' Discussions ensued about the woman's
hairstyle and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut, the director of the Washington-based Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press, said that Friday's decision
was another sign of rising public hostility toward the media,
particularly after the shootings in Littleton, Colo. ``I'm
reasonably sure,'' he said, ``that the public would be on the side
of the plaintiff in this case because they feel the media don't
care enough about the consequences of their actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
