<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHUNG TO DESCRIBE SOURCE OF CHINESE FUNDS TO HOUSE COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Calif.) (rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A fund-raiser who pleaded guilty to tax violations
has told government investigators that a Chinese general in charge
of Beijing's intelligence service was behind $300,000 in payments
that were used in part as contributions to the Democratic National
Committee, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser, Johnny Chung, is expected to describe his
dealings with Gen. Ji Shengde and other Chinese intelligence
officials when he appears under subpoena on Tuesday before the
House government Reform and Oversight Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chung, who has cooperated with the authorities investigating
campaign finance issues, is the first Asian-American fund-raiser to
testify publicly about his activities with elite Chinese business
and political figures who live in China and have remained beyond
the reach of congressional and Justice Department investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Brian Sun, Chung's lawyer, said Chung was never a
witting participant in a suspected Chinese intelligence scheme
intended to influence American elections, as Republicans in
Congress have asserted. Instead, Chung wanted to further business
contacts for his Asian contacts, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not about campaign finance,'' Sun said. ``It was about
entrepreneurs in China who wear both government and business hats
who were seeking access and relationships and business
opportunities. Johnny provided them with services. They could not
come here without visas that Johnny would help them get. He paid
their expenses and took them around.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung also made contributions to the Democratic Party totaling
$360,000 and sought access to senior government officials, visiting
the White House on more than 50 occasions and often taking along a
group of Chinese business officials.
</P>
<P>
   But for all Chung's activities, the most explosive subject Chung
is expected to address in his testimony is the source of the
payment he received from the People's Liberation Army through Liu
Chaoying, a lieutenant colonel and aerospace executive whose father
was a top military commander and member of the Communist Party's
ruling leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, government officials have said that Ms. Liu was
an intermediary for the funds, which were provided to her by Ji,
the intelligence chief, whose involvement was first reported by The
Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much of the $300,000 was turned over to the
Democrats. Campaign finance records show that Chung donated about
$35,000 of the money to the Democratic National Committee while
Chung kept the rest in his bank account in California.
</P>
<P>
   It is also uncertain whether Ji supplied the money from his own
funds or whether he too was merely an intermediary for someone
else. The general did ask Ms. Liu for a receipt for the money, one
official said, an unusual request for an intelligence operation,
suggesting that the general had to account for the money to a
higher authority.
</P>
<P>
   Chung is also expected to testify about conversations with Ms.
Liu that mentioned Mark E. Middleton, a former aide to Clinton and
lawyer from Arkansas, who left the White House in 1995 to set up an
international consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Chung said she told him that Chinese officials entered into a
$500,000 business arrangement with Middleton. But Robert D. Luskin,
Middleton's lawyer, said Middleton had never worked for Chinese
clients, but had received a payment of about $500,000 from an
Indonesian company for work unrelated to China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
