<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARCLAYS-INVEST-ART-2     05-07 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-INVEST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED _ AND NEEDED _ AT BARCLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The shares of Barclays PLC surged 39 percent in two
months after Michael O'Neill, a top executive at Bank of America,
was appointed chief executive in February.
</P>
<P>
   The market apparently expected O'Neill, an American who helped
oversee the merger of Bank of America and Nationsbank in the United
States, to shake Barclays, the profitable but troubled British
behemoth, out of its lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when O'Neill resigned last month for health reasons, the
shares of Barclays moved up 2.5 percent to yet another high. With
no other management knight riding to the rescue, the market
apparently expected a rival British bank to make a bid for
Barclays.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the market's message was clear: This is a great
bank, but it needs a lot of outside help.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Martin Taylor, the last full-time chief executive,
quit in a dispute over investment-banking strategy six months ago,
Barclays has been trying desperately to avoid the impression that
it is drifting while other European financial institutions forge
ahead with energetic restructuring. In an interview, Sir Peter
Middleton, the bank's 65-year-old chairman and acting chief
executive, made it clear that he, for one, believes the bank has
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I set out to do when Martin Taylor left was to make
sure that the bank didn't stall either in its day-to-day operations
or strategically,'' said Sir Peter, a former British Treasury boss.
``So the business short-term is moving ahead and will continue to
move ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I am sure about with big organizations _ it
doesn't matter what it is _ is that if they are not being moved
forward, they move backwards. And I think we've managed that. We
have moved it forward. The business is doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chief executive, he said, is being sought from the same,
closely guarded short-list that produced O'Neill, with both bank
insiders and outsiders under consideration. No names of outside
candidates have been made public, in part to avoid tipping off the
current employers of those being head-hunted. Within the bank, two
insiders, Chris Lendrum, head of corporate banking, and John
Varley, head of retail financial services, are viewed as
front-runners if no outsider is chosen. Big institutional
investors, however, reportedly oppose the appointment of an
insider, who they fear would be too susceptible to Sir Peter's
influence and might upset a management hierarchy that has barely
taken root after years of upheavals.
</P>
<P>
   If precedent is any guide, Barclays _ Britain's No. 2 bank and
the sixth-biggest in Europe _ will be willing to pay top dollar to
lure its top choice. O'Neill won a first-year salary-and-bonus
package of $2.8 million and an agreement by the bank to match his
purchase of $8.25 million in Barclays stock if he stayed for three
years, a compensation package regarded as very generous by British
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever takes the job will have his hands full, though.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out investment-bank strategy will be priority No. 1.
Like other big British banks, Barclays has already stumbled in its
attempts to muscle into the sector, which is dominated by the big
American securities firms. In late 1997, Barclays sold off the
European equity-and-merger businesses of its BZW investment unit to
Credit Suisse First Boston for about $170 million, a considerable
discount to book value.
</P>
<P>
   Then last year, Barclays Capital, the successor to BZW, lost 265
million pounds ($431.9 million at current exchange rates) in the
Russian financial meltdown. It subsequently closed down three
proprietary trading businesses seen as high-risk, reduced its
exposure in emerging markets, hedge funds and corporate bonds and
reined in its investment capital.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays' executives insist that the paring-down has left core
investment businesses intact, but analysts have their doubts.
``Investment banking more than any other is becoming global and the
idea of having a niche operation the size of Barclays Capital
strikes me as unlikely,'' said an analyst at a big American
investment bank, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Another big question mark hanging over Barclays is its plan of
action for Continental Europe, where a flurry of banking mergers
has reinforced a sense of upheaval since last January's arrival of
the European single currency, the euro. In that domain, Sir Peter
seemed almost deliberately vague. While he said Barclays has
``designs on Europe'' and is seeking to expand its presence there,
he suggested that Continental Europe is playing catch-up to British
banking, rather than leading the way into a new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consolidation that's taking place in Europe is of a sort
we have already done here,'' he said. ``What's taking place in
Europe is consolidation within countries, not between them.'' He
didn't rule out future acquisitions by Barclays, but said none were
``on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue in Europe is when trans-border business is going
to be easier than it is now,'' he said. ``If things there would fit
our European ambitions at a reasonable price and we could get a
reasonable return, we are interested.'' The question is whether
Barclays can afford to be so laid-back when European banking is
seething with euro-driven consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than abroad, Barclays faces challenges at home, where
established banks confront a basic problem of maintaining expensive
retail branches while newcomers cherry-pick their most lucrative
businesses. For the past decade, Britain's building societies, or
savings-and-loans institutions, have been turning themselves into
banks by providing not just mortgages, an area where Barclays is
weak, but also over-the-counter retail services, where it is
traditionally strong.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, upstarts as far afield as supermarkets and
Richard Branson's Virgin Group have been offering financial
services. Some are even offering telephone banking. ``Everyone from
Tesco (a supermarket chain) to Virgin to building societies is
getting into the banking business,'' said one Barclays executive.
``There's been a complacency among bankers that says: People don't
change their banks. But what's happening is that they may keep
their checking accounts with you and be buying products somewhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
