<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-watch-PA     05-07 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, May 7 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday failed to pass a measure that would have
authorized President Clinton to use ``all necessary force,''
including ground troops, to resolve the conflict in Kosovo. Voting
78-22, the Senate tabled, or set aside, the proposal that was
offered by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. Supporters of the proposal
said Clinton needs to implement a tougher strategy in Kosovo
because the air strikes are not working. Opponents of the proposal
said it was premature and too broad. A ``yes'' vote favors setting
aside the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: BANKRUPTCY
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 313-108, a bill intended to
make it more difficult for debtors to file Chapter 7 bankruptcy,
which basically wipes out all debts. Under this bill, more people
would be forced to file Chapter 13 bankruptcy, which allows people
to keep their assets, but requires them to pay off as many debts as
possible within a certain time frame. Supporters said action needs
to be taken to stop the rising number of personal bankruptcies.
Opponents said the measure unfairly implements a ``means test,''
which determines what kind of bankruptcy debtors must file for
based on their income. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: OFFSETS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 101-322, an amendment to the
Kosovo emergency spending bill that would have required Congress to
pay for the $13.1 billion bill by cutting funds from other
government programs. Supporters said the government should not raid
the projected Social Security surplus to pay for the measure.
Opponents said offsetting the costs would defeat the purpose of an
emergency spending bill, which does not have to abide by spending
caps, according to budget rules. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: LESS FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 164-260, an amendment to the
Kosovo emergency spending bill that would have pared down the cost
from $13.1 billion to $11.7 billion. Supporters said the original
bill was too loaded down with non-emergency spending measures.
Opponents said the military needs the full $13.1 billion to carry
out the mission in Kosovo. A ``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: GROUND
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 117-301, an amendment to the
Kosovo emergency spending bill that would have prevented President
Clinton from using the $13.1 billion for ground troops unless he
first sought congressional authorization. Supporters said Clinton
needs to involve Congress when making decisions regarding the
troops in Kosovo. Opponents said the amendment was inappropriate
and could cause a presidential veto. A ``yes'' vote favors the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: FUNDING
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 311-105, a $13.1 billion
emergency spending bill that will fund the conflict in Kosovo
through September. The final amount more than doubles President
Clinton's initial funding request of $6.05 billion. Supporters said
Congress should send the troops in the Balkans whatever resources
they need to safely carry out their mission, even if members do not
agree with Clinton's handling of the conflict. Opponents said the
bill is too loaded down with non-emergency spending requests, such
as military construction projects and pay raises, and will further
sap the Social Security fund. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5
</P>
