<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARCLAYS-INVEST-ART-2     05-07 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-INVEST-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: somewhere else. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``At the heart of all this is a real sea change in the way we
deliver services to our customers,'' the executive said. ``Banks
have to become more like consumer companies, and orient themselves
to the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem that the next CEO will have to tackle is costs.
Even as competition intensifies, costs keep going up, surging 5
percent last year as the bank coped with an internal
reorganization, the introduction of the euro and the upgrading of
its computers to avoid glitches associated with the year 2000 bug.
Barclays says it will hold the line on costs this year, but
analysts are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The most momentous decision confronting O'Neill's successor will
be whether to follow the lead of other big American and European
banks and seek out a merger partner. In recent years, there has
been frequent talk of potential mergers with suitors like
Lloyds-TSB, Britain's largest bank; Standard Chartered, and the
Royal Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays appears in no hurry to act. The thrust of its recent
moves has been to set its own house in order, maximize the value of
its brand and broaden the range of its consumer products. ``The
organization is not vulnerable in any classic sense,'' said Simon
Samuels, a banking analyst with Salomon Smith Barney here.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays insists that, far from losing its way, it is very much
on track. Despite its losses in Russia last year, profits surged 12
percent to 1.9 billion pounds ($3.1 billion). And the news is good
on many other fronts:
</P>
<P>
   _ The bank's Barclaycard credit-card division, long under siege
by American intruders, has launched an aggressive campaign to claw
back market share by lowering the interest rates it charges and
cutting costs by reducing its staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barclays Global Investment is flourishing as the world's
biggest money manager, with 370 billion pounds ($603.03 billion)
under management. It handles $407 billion in investors' money in
the United States, making it the No. 2 fund manager there after the
giant Fidelity Investments, with $765 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barclays executives insist that Barclays Capital has swung
back into the black, thanks largely to the revival of world stock
and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The retail financial-services branch, the core of Barclays'
business, is luring customers with new products like Internet
banking. It is also working on redesigning its branches and is
exploring ways to offer its customers a wider range of products,
such as the ``B2'' savings account for younger depositors,
introduced last year.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that simply isn't enough in today's cutthroat banking
environment. ``From the strategy view-point, one feels that
Barclays is at a cross-roads,'' said Samuel Theodore, managing
director for European banking at Moody's Investors Services here.
What Barclays must do, he said, is become ``a more nimble
provider'' of retail financial services tailored to the needs of
customers. What that could mean, executives say, is a quest for
acquisitions giving Barclays a bigger presence in mortgages and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Peter says the search for a new chief executive could take
another six weeks. But he insists that Barclays isn't looking for a
savior, for the simple reason that it isn't in need of salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crises are only crises if you think they are,'' he said.
Compared with some of the predicaments that beset the British
Treasury in his years there as permanent secretary, he added,
Barclays' recent tribulations ``don't even get onto the Richter
scale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
