<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT GIVES SENATE COMMITTEE SOME DOCUMENTS ON
HOLBROOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Foreign Relations Committee is trying to
determine whether it has sufficient evidence from the Justice
Department to go forward with confirmation hearings for Richard
Holbrooke as the top American diplomat at the United Nations,
congressional officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., has refused to
schedule a hearing on the long-stalled nomination until he has
received a variety of documents from the Justice Department about
its ethics investigation of Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the department provided at least some of the
documents to Helms. ``We are hopeful that this will resolve the
issue,'' a spokesman for the department, Myron Marlin, said. He did
not describe the documents.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Helms had no comment on whether the documents
were sufficient to satisfy the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The requested documents included witnesses' statements in the
inquiry of Holbrooke's contacts with State Department officials
after he resigned from the department in 1996 and joined an
investment banking concern in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic congressional official who insisted on anonymity
said that the Justice Department and White House were holding some
of the documents, but that Senate investigators were extremely
likely to gain access to all the papers by the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department investigation ended in February, when
Holbrooke agreed to pay the department $5,000 to settle civil
charges that he had violated lobbying laws in his contacts with the
U.S. Embassy in South Korea in 1996. He denied wrongdoing and said
he had agreed to the settlement to avoid delays in his nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
