<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-07 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: THE ELECTORATE'S OVERLOOKED CORNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to political activity by religious believers, the
nation's evangelical Protestants often seem to get most of the
attention from the news media and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   That would be because evangelicals, particularly the many
conservatives among them, have clearly emerged as a political force
over the last 20 years, aided in part by media-wise organizations
like the Moral Majority and, more recently, the Christian
Coalition. As a result, they have made an impact on the Republican
Party, often pressing causes like efforts to restrict abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But this circumstance should not obscure a larger picture about
religion and politics or, says one expert, keep reporters and
scholars from paying close attention to other Protestants _ the
mainline variety, like Methodists and Presbyterians _ who could
play an important role in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   That suggestion came, in a telephone interview, from John C.
Green, director of the Ray C. Bliss Institute of Applied Politics
at the University of Akron, who delivered a paper last week
analyzing various political data related to religious groups. (The
data were drawn from the University of Michigan's National
Elections Studies and a poll on ``values'' by The Washington Post
and the Kaiser Family Foundation.)
</P>
<P>
   Green's paper, presented at the Center for the Study of Religion
and Public Life at Trinity College in Hartford, Conn., described
the outlooks and complex voting patterns that prevailed among
Protestants, Roman Catholics, Jews and unaffiliated ``seculars'' in
the 1994, 1996 and 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   He had enough data to divide each of the three largest groups
(evangelicals, mainline Protestants and Catholics) into two general
categories: the ``traditionalists,'' meaning people who maintain a
high level of religious observance and accord the Bible a high
authority, and the ``nontraditionalists,'' a varied group including
theological liberals, moderates and people who say they are not
highly observant.
</P>
<P>
   Green found that Republican candidates had done much better than
Democrats with the religious traditionalists as a whole, while
Democrats had drawn most of their support from nontraditionalists,
seculars, Jews, Hispanic Catholics and African-American
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical Protestants accounted for nearly one-third of
Republican voters during 1994-98, Green said. During that period,
Democrats' largest voting blocs were seculars, nontraditionalist
Catholics and black Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   As for mainline Protestants as a whole, Green found that they
accounted for 16 percent of the electorate _ somewhat less than the
evangelicals, who accounted for about a fifth _ with 11 percent
fitting in the nontraditionalist category and 5 percent in the
traditionalist.
</P>
<P>
   A slight majority of mainline Protestants identify themselves as
Republicans, the historic affiliation of these voters. But the
nontraditionalists have lately been ticket-splitters, a majority
backing President Clinton in 1996 but voting for Republicans for
Congress in each of the elections from 1994 through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Clinton appealed to these people with his talk of a
``new covenant,'' of shared responsibility for society between
government and citizens. As president, he renewed his appeal in
1996 by pushing government interest in school uniforms and higher
academic standards, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks seem to have become comfortable with a large
public sector,'' he said. ``But they don't want it to get bigger,
and they want it to be efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are they important? Mainline Protestants are especially
numerous in the Upper Midwest, a broad area rich in Electoral
College votes running, Green said, ``from western Pennsylvania
through Iowa, and you could probably include Nebraska and Kansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Were certain social issues to play a major role in the next
election, a candidate might find it hard to appeal to those
Protestants and other religious voters, too. For example, most
mainline Protestants oppose school vouchers, while most
evangelicals and Catholics support them, the data show.
</P>
<P>
   Green's report also points to common ground: a majority of
voters in all religious groups say they favor protecting
homosexuals from job discrimination, although most also say they do
not support gay marriage. And a majority in all groups say they
believe that government should reduce poverty, one of several
responses that lead Green to say he sees no evidence of ``culture
war'' among Americans over economic issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYRIA-MARRIAGE-NYT &LR;      05-07 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-MARRIAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SYRIA, 2 WHO DECIDED TO HAVE THE KNOT TIED FOR THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Mohammed wanted a wife who was ``obedient and
beautiful.'' Olaa wanted a husband who was ``tall, kind, rich and
cultivated.'' Armed with those instructions, their mothers went to
work in search of a match.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed's stepmother visited 150 homes; Olaa poured coffee day
after day as her mother received such callers. It took two years
for their trajectories to cross, and that first visit was followed
by a second, this time with Mohammed in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stepmother did a good job,'' said Mohammed, who married
Olaa four months later, at the age of 33, and counts himself lucky
that he is among the Syrians who owe their unions to the
bride-seeking ritual.
</P>
<P>
   About half of all Syrian marriages are arranged, even some for
people like Mohammed, a university graduate who has traveled in
Europe and speaks four languages.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is certainly the Arab world's most secular state, tolerant
of its large Christian population and bordering on libertine in
some ways, particularly at the Damascus nightclubs that feature
risque shows. But when it comes to men and women, people like
Mohammed and Olaa say, traditions run deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I walk into the kitchen, that's shame for me,'' Mohammed
said, ``because that is not a man's place. If I let my wife go
outside alone, that's shame for me. I know this is wrong, not
right. But it's our tradition; it's in my blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not tradition,'' said Olaa, who was married at 17 and
now, at 23, is the mother of two boys. ``It's jealousy.''
</P>
<P>
   A long talk with Mohammed, a thoughtful tour guide, and Olaa, a
housewife who said she felt trapped, opened a rare window on Syrian
society. Tensions between the old and the modern were exposed in
the bride-seeking ritual _ performed in Damascus with a fealty that
died out years ago in many other Arab capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed in their cramped Damascus apartment, the two spoke
frankly for several hours over Arabic coffee and Marlboro
cigarettes, seated beneath a bookshelf that included works by Camus
and Voltaire. But they would speak about their marriage only on
condition that they not be photographed and that their full names
not be used. They said they first wanted to protect their families'
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, even though they would not discuss politics, they
did not want to invite scrutiny from Syrian authorities, who tend
to frown on citizens' talking to foreign journalists without
government permission.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mohammed nor Olaa said they had any qualms about the
ritual that brought them together; their families, they said, had
their best interests at heart. The marriage may have been arranged,
they said, but it had not been imposed. Both the prospective bride
and the groom have the opportunity to turn down any match.
</P>
<P>
   But tradition is clearly a point of friction in other ways,
particularly when Olaa tries to persuade Mohammed to allow her to
return to school or to take a job, and hears him repeat what her
father told her when she was a teen-ager: ``Your university is your
home; your university is your children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to take our tradition softly,'' Mohammed said,
admitting to feeling torn. ``I want my wife to be able to live her
life and to go outside the home, but something inside me tells me,
`No!'''
</P>
<P>
   Olaa was just 15, and in her second year of high school in 1991,
she said, when her father, a dentist, and her mother first asked
whether she was willing to begin considering suitors. An only
daughter, she had been sheltered, always wore a head scarf and was
not allowed even to walk to and from school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Olaa immediately said yes, and the process began,
following rules and customs understood by everyone in Damascus. At
single-sex gatherings, Olaa would be appraised by the mothers of
marriageable sons, who would later telephone to invite themselves
over for a coffee-and-cakes meeting with the young woman and her
mother. A blow-by-blow description would then be carried home to
the absent suitor.
</P>
<P>
   As Mohammed pointed out, the mother of the prospective bride
might ask questions about his ``keys'' _ to an apartment, a car or
a villa outside of town. If the man was interested in meeting the
young woman in person, the mother would propose a second visit,
this time including her son.
</P>
<P>
   But Olaa and her family did not approve of any of the early
candidates, so the requests were always deflected, according to
form, with the news that she had decided to ``continue her
studies.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mohammed was ready to find a wife, also in 1991, he
was already 31, old by Syrian standards, but not unusually so for a
man these days, because the economy has made it difficult to become
financially established. He had a girlfriend in college, a
Christian, but knew that his parents believed a marriage should be
arranged _ and to a fellow Muslim. And so after graduating from
Damascus University in 1985 and completing his mandatory military
service, he worked ``day and night'' to save the money necessary to
make himself an attractive candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He asked for a wife with blond hair and blue eyes, a rare
combination in Syria. But his stepmother (his mother died young)
took her mission to heart, calling on as many as two families a
week, and arranging at least 60 times for him to join her on a
second visit.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, Mohammed said, he would glimpse his prospective
bride for the first time as she entered the room, to serve coffee;
there would be time for only a few words of shy conversation. In
two years of looking, Mohammed decided seven times that he would be
happy with the match, only to be refused.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such obstacle when it came to Olaa. She remembers
peering from an upstairs window to see whether Mohammed was indeed
tall and whether he arrived for the second visit in a taxi, a car
or a bus. (He drove a black Volkswagen Golf.) When their eyes met,
both Mohammed and Olaa say, they felt the same happy surge.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit, as their families huddled separately to compare
notes, each announced that it would be satisfied with the match. A
few anxious moments remained. When Mohammed's stepmother requested
the customary third meeting, to discuss the dowry, she was
temporarily rebuffed, as is usual in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   This allowed for Olaa's father to question Mohammed's neighbors.
Did he go to the mosque? Did he drink? Was he a good man? The
answers were satisfactory, so a third meeting took place, but not
without a final bit of brinkmanship. Acting on his instructions,
Mohammed's stepmother told Olaa's father that her son could afford
no more than $4,000 of the requested $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain of the outcome, Mohammed arrived at Olaa's house as
the third meeting was finally taking place. Her father greeted him
as a son. As a welcoming gesture, the father even pulled off his
daughter's scarf, so that her husband-to-be could glimpse her hair
(not blond, but no matter) _ a move so brazen that Olaa cried out
with shame.
</P>
<P>
   The couple were married soon afterward, and the consummation of
the marriage was announced jointly the next morning by their
mothers. Their ululations, a final taste of tradition, were to
celebrate that the bride had indeed been a virgin, as proven by the
discovery of a bloodstained sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mohammed and Olaa became husband and wife, tradition has
sometimes been their foe. Mohammed says his father's advice that a
wife should be made to fear her husband has sometimes led him
astray. He has tried to be easier, allowing his wife to get a
driver's license and even to attend all-women computer classes.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that she should be allowed to work with men, or
even attend classes with them, is one that he still cannot brook.
``You know what it says in the Koran,'' Mohammed said, as Olaa
rolled her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a man and woman are together, the third one is the
devil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
