<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RETURN08-COX     05-07 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RETURN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewish visitors to Tirana return with tales of need
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PLAM BEACH, Fla. _ When war doesn't intrude, the area
outside the Albanian capital city of Tirana is a summer swimming
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is an instant city of 5,000, a camp of mostly ethnic
Albanians forced out of neighboring Kosovo. A city of tents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lift the flap on a tent _ hardly bigger than a pup tent _ and
10 people are living inside,'' said Mark Levy of West Palm Beach.
Mostly they are women, children and old men. ``They don't know
where their men are _ killed or forced to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Levy and Norman Goldblum of Palm Beach, vice presidents of the
Jewish Federation of Palm Beach County, returned Friday from a
five-day trip to Israel and Eastern Europe that took them on a
whirlwind 22-hour visit to the refugee camp and to Budapest,
Hungary, where Jews have fled from the bombing in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Goldblum, Levy and 28 others from American Jewish groups flew on
a relief mission from Israel to Albania with 20 tons of food,
medicine, blankets and bigger, waterproof tents.
</P>
<P>
   The local pair brought soap, shampoo, other toilet articles and
toys to add to the effort. Their mission is to tell what they saw
and encourage the Jewish community to donate to relief efforts.
American Jews have donated $2.25 million for Kosovo relief,
according to the United Jewish Communities, formerly the United
Jewish Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Agency for Israel manages half of the camp and has
relocated 400 mostly Muslim ethnic Albanian refugees. ``A lot want
to be close to the border so they can return quickly to find their
families,'' said Goldblum, 75.
</P>
<P>
   More important than the one bucket of water a day each refugee
gets is the bulletin board outside the camp entrance that lists the
name of everyone in camp. The refugees check often for the names of
missing relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem is that when they do go home, they have no
homes to go to. Something has to be done now before the cold
weather sets in,'' said Levy, 44.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also visited a Jewish-owned hotel in Budapest that
has become the refugee center for Yugoslavian Jews who have fled
from Belgrade. The plane took 32 of them back to Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every story was overwhelming. Every story heart-rending,''
Goldblum said. ``The need is so massive that whatever you do, it's
not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy said the Israeli and Jewish relief effort is entirely
humanitarian and has no political implications. ``This is the same
thing that happened 50 years ago,'' Levy said. ``We've got to get
over there and help people.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
