<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JONES-VERDICT2-BOS     05-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JONES-VERDICT2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES VERDICT SEEN A WARNING FOR TALK SHOWS, JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects spelling of Klieman in penultimate graf; a and e
coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Michigan jury found ``The Jenny Jones Show'' negligent in the
murder of a guest on the program, in a ruling decried by First
Amendment advocates and seen as an ominous warning about public
anger not only at trash TV, but at the increasingly murky mix of
entertainment and journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The $25 million verdict stemmed from a Jenny Jones episode in
which one guest, Scott Amedure, revealed himself as the secret
admirer of another guest, Jonathan Schmitz. Three days after the
March 1995 taping, an apparently humiliated Schmitz shot and killed
Amedure. He is currently awaiting retrial after a 1996 murder
conviction was thrown out on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's ill-fated, secret admirer show seemed ``unusual and
extreme, even by talk television standards,'' said television
historian Alex McNeil. And it was hard to find anyone with a kind
word for the brand of video voyeurism that the jury penalized with
its verdict Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers believe that decision is more than simply a
repudiation of junk programming. They interpret it as part of a
public backlash against a range of media outlets that produce
everything from outrageous TV talk shows to serious investigative
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a jury found ABC liable for $5.5 million in damages
after it used undercover reporters to unearth allegedly unsanitary
conditions at the Food Lion supermarket chain. Last year, The
Cincinnati Enquirer's use of purloined voice mails in an expose of
Chiquita Brands company spawned a major criminal investigation of
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction (to the Jones verdict) is first that it's another
sign that the public is angry at the `media at large,' &UR;  &LR; '' said Tom
Rosenstiel, director of the Center for Excellence in Journalism.
``And it's a warning signal to journalists that that the public in
some manner...wants to hold us accountable for consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether Jenny Jones is a journalist or not...any journalist
should recognize that there's a message here for them,'' he added.
``Increasingly, there is a blending of the media. What's the
difference between Oprah's book review and The New York Times book
review?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Paratone, president of Telepictures Productions, which
produces ``Jenny Jones,'' announced his intention to appeal, noting
that the ``public and every single media outlet should fear the
chilling effect of this verdict.'' Some analysts seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney and civil liberties proponent Harvery Silverglate
harbors few illusions about the value of the Jones show, noting
that the ``the history of incursions into the First Amendment is
(that) they pick on the medium that doesn't have respectable public
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he compared the verdict to ``the other cases that
have arisen where courts have attacked the techniques by which news
has been gathered. ... There is a continuum that goes from what we
would agree is hard news to entertainment. We're talking about one
phenomenon. You can not, as a legal matter, distinguish between
Jenny Jones and The Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Friday's news, McNeil wondered whether as
``the next step, you'll see in a TV crime show a particular type of
crime committed. Then someone goes out and replicates that style of
crime'' and a case is brought to prove the ``causation link between
the television depiction and the action the defendant took.''
</P>
<P>
   Court TV anchor Rikki Klieman pointed to the performance of
plaintiffs' attorney Geoffrey Fieger _ who gained fame as Jack
Kevorkian's lawyer _ in convincing the jurors. But she also
contended that the tricky First Amendment issue and ``proximate
cause'' theory (that the show was responsible for the subsequent
murder) ought to keep the matter in the courts for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think they have viable issues on appeal,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's $25-million repudiation of the Jones show comes at a
time when some analysts think the hardcore talk TV wave _ pioneered
by people like Morton Downey Jr. and Geraldo Rivera and now
championed by Jerry Springer _ may have crested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Springer took it to its illogical extreme,'' said
cultural critic Steven Stark, who points to success of such kinder
gentler talk show hosts as Oprah Winfrey and Rosie O`Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones verdict ``probably will be seen as a turning point,''
that helped cool public ardor for trash television, added McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such predictions are at least partly refuted by Klieman's
explanation of why the Jones case was one of Court TV's
highest-rated trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have sex, you have murder, you have possible
homosexuality. Then you've got Feiger. This would have made a
great-made-for-TV movie.'' And a darn good Jenny Jones show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
