<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-ECON-NYT &LR;      05-07 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBLESSNESS RATE UNEXPECTEDLY EDGES UP IN GERMANY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In a worrisome sign that Europe's biggest
economy is still sputtering, the German government reported an
unexpectedly big monthly jump Friday in the German joblessness.
</P>
<P>
   After declining slowly for more than a year, the seasonally
adjusted unemployment rate here edged up to 10.7 percent in April
from 10.6 percent in March, according to a report from the central
bank, the Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
   Although the change was fairly small, it surprised many
economists who had been expecting either no change or a
continuation of recent improvement. It also pointed to renewed
pressure on Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who has come under
widespread criticism from industrialists for what they call his
listless economic program.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which accounts for about one-quarter of western
Europe's economic output, now has one of the slowest rates of
economic growth in the region. The government itself recently
scaled back its revisions for growth this year from more than 2
percent to 1.5 percent. That puts it on a par with Italy and
significantly behind most other neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The German Federal Labor Office reported Friday that the
unadjusted rate of unemployment declined from 11.1 percent in April
to 10.7 percent in March. But government officials acknowledged
that most of that increase was due to the normal increase in hiring
that takes place in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The economic picture is unusually muddled. Government officials
and many economists believe that a mild recovery may have begun,
fueled by lower borrowing costs from the European Central Bank and
the relatively weak value of the euro, Europe's new single
currency, which is stimulating European exports.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Friday's numbers reinforced the sense that European
unemployment will remain stubbornly high. German industrial
executives are hoping for a lift from a number of signs that Asia
and Latin America are recovering from their financial crises, which
had deeply depressed exports of machinery, chemicals and other
products ever since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But even if German growth does accelerate, nobody expects
anything more than a mild improvement for the rest of this year.
Some experts worry that joblessness will remain high because
Schroeder's center-left government has stiffened Germany's already
rigid work rules and pushed through tax increases on business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSTINET-TRADEPOINT-N     05-07 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTINET-TRADEPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING GROWING COMPETITION, INSTINET SCRAMBLES FOR POSITION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)   By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the competition intensifying for America's stock-trading
business, Instinet, a unit of the Reuters Group PLC and the
nation's largest private electronic stock-trading network,
announced a series of strategic moves last week aimed, not only at
its competitors but also at its potential allies.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Instinet announced that it had organized a
consortium to buy a 54.4 percent stake in Tradepoint Financial
Networks PLC, a tiny British electronic stock market that recently
got permission from the Securities and Exchange Commission to
accept orders directly from American money-managers.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium includes American Century, the Kansas City mutual
fund giant; Archipelago, an electronic communications network, or
ECN, whose co-owners include Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and E-Trade
Group; and two global investment banks, J.P. Morgan and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Tradepoint has highly regarded technology _ its chief appeal to
the consortium _ but until now it has lacked the trading volume
necessary to earn a profit. It handles only about 1 percent of
London's trading and has consistently lost money. The consortium's
$22-million investment provides a nice life jacket, but the real
reward for Tradepoint is the promise of trading business from
consortium members, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the deal make Tradepoint a stronger competitor in
the European market, it also signals a provocative shift in
Instinet's role in the American market.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Instinet has been discussing some sort of electronic
alliance with both the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq, as those
traditional markets try to compete with the growing ECN community.
The Big Board wants a share of the trading in Nasdaq's hot Internet
stocks, and Nasdaq is trying to retrieve business it has lost to
the ECN's.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Douglas M. Atkin, the chief executive of Instinet,
said he was now far less interested in an individual partnership
with one of the giant exchanges, unless it was aimed at forming a
single domestic electronic trading network that mirrors Tradepoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that is what our markets need,'' said Atkin. ``Even
if one exchange wanted to do a deal with Instinet as a single
partner, we don't really think that's the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkin conceded that his vision of a unified electronic market
ran counter to the current proliferation of competing electronic
services. ``But I think the tide is shifting,'' he added. ``We
would much prefer the natural parties _ Nasdaq or the NYSE _ to be
putting this together,'' he said. ``But Tradepoint guarantees that
there is a very significant third option if the other parties don't
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Instinet also opened a new front on Wednesday in its battle with
its smaller competitors by announcing that it was talking to a
handful of online and traditional brokers about the possibility of
opening its electronic trading system to individual investors. It
is the dominant non-exchange trading service for institutional
investors, but this step would put it in more direct competition
with the ECN's, like The Island ECN, that have cultivated brokers
serving the retail customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JONES-VERDICT2-BOS     05-07 0831
