<HEADER>
A8829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ITALY-NYT &LR;      05-07 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ITALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS ROUTS SERENA WILLIAMS TO AVENGE EARLIER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Martina Hingis and Serena Williams walked on court as
equals Friday in the quarterfinals of the Italian Open, but when
they walked off little more than an hour later, it was clear that
Hingis was No. 1 and Williams still has a little way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had wanted a measure of revenge after losing to Williams
in Key Biscayne, Fla., and she got it by the surprisingly
convincing score of 6-2, 6-2. But then, the score will be a
surprise only to those who did not watch this mismatch of a
rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't win; I gave it to her,'' Williams said. ``I hit so
many errors. It was absolutely absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' analysis was far superior to her performance, and now
it will be up to her sister, Venus, to try to give the Williams
family its first victory over Hingis on clay. Venus Williams earned
a date with Hingis in Saturday's semifinals by defeating Dominique
Van Roost, 7-6 (7-1), 6-2, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating the whole family all the time, it's not easy,'' Hingis
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the task was certainly easier than expected.
What has come so naturally to Serena Williams in the past three
months, when she has regularly dominated opponents with her
attacking baseline play, looked agonizingly difficult this
afternoon. Instead of crisp winners and overwhelming first serves
and well-timed forays to the net, there was the sort of overhitting
and impatient play that occasionally got Williams into trouble
during her first two years on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis won 16 of the first 17 points to jump out to a 4-0 lead,
and the only point Williams won during that slightly surreal
stretch came on a Hingis double fault. The match was never that
lopsided again, but Williams' fundamental failings would change
little: inconsistency from the backcourt and a very poor
first-service percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a really weird day,'' the 10th-ranked Williams
said. ``I thought I was playing well here. I was pretty much on a
roll. It's kind of weird to walk into a match and not be able to do
the things you've done for so long. I can't really explain that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, visibly and audibly delighted after her victory, had an
explanation of her own: ``On clay, you can't just kill the ball,
because it's going to come back over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   On clay, a parabola is often a wiser path to choose for your
balls than a relatively straight line, and despite the occasional
effort to rediscover her lost rhythm by taking pace off the ball
and adding topspin, Williams frequently ignored that slow-court
principle. The result was not pretty: 40 unforced errors to Hingis'
10, which was also testimony to the Swiss star's sound tactics. She
aimed most of her shots in the direction of Serena's backhand and,
in the precious few extended rallies, picked her spots and changed
pace astutely.
</P>
<P>
   Those tactics were perhaps refined after an impromptu and
unprecedented practice session with Williams earlier in the week.
Usually, Serena and Venus Williams are each other's practice
partners, but Venus Williams was still in Hamburg, Germany, playing
and winning a tournament, and Serena Williams chose to train with
Hingis, the sisters' principal rival.
</P>
<P>
   For Hingis, Friday's overwhelming victory _ which gave her a 3-1
career edge over Serena Williams _ sprang from the same source as
Venus Williams' overwhelming, 6-2, 6-2, victory over Anna
Kournikova the night before. ``Mentally, we were stronger, me and
Venus,'' Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams has not yet proved strong enough to defeat Hingis
in a Grand Slam event or on clay. Last year, she lost to Hingis
here in the final and then lost to her again on clay in the
quarterfinals of the French Open. They have not played since, and
though Venus Williams has now won 17 of her last 18 matches, Hingis
looks fit and fresh after a four-week layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``She won Wimbledon, the U.S. Open and got to the finals of the
French; I've never done these things,'' Williams said. ``She must
be doing something right. I guess she's comfortable on clay. She
grew up on it, so maybe that's an advantage to her.''
</P>
<P>
   The other semifinal at the Foro Italico on Saturday will be an
all-French affair between Mary Pierce and Amelie Mauresmo. Pierce,
actually an American playing under the French flag, advanced by
defeating another French player, Sandrine Testud, 6-4, 7-5.
Mauresmo had an easier time with Sylvia Plischke of Austria,
winning by 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Plischke, a Czech-born polyglot who moved to Innsbruck with her
family when she was 6, upset two small players with big reputations
this week: Amanda Coetzer and the reigning French Open champion,
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario. But neither Coetzer nor Sanchez Vicario
can come close to applying the same pressure as Mauresmo when she
is in form, and the strapping, aggressive 19-year-old who came to
prominence in a hurry earlier this year by reaching the final of
the Australian Open believes that she is again approaching her peak
after a lackluster early spring on American hardcourts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, mentally and tennistically, it's all coming
together like in Australia,'' she said in her improving but still
imperfect English.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
