<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Saturday, May
8, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-FORCE (Seattle) _ Seattle Police internal affairs
investigators didn't fully investigate complaints of excessive use
of force made by a man who says he was beaten at the West Precinct,
and failed to even interview a now-former officer who said his
colleagues did in fact use excessive force. Officer Paul Vang, who
was later fired from the force, says three officers beat the
prisoner after he took a swing at a cop. The prisoner, who is known
to be ``no Boy Scout,'' is now in jail on an unrelated charge.
</P>
<P>
   By Vanessa Ho. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA-SEWAGE (Victoria, B.C.) _ Despite protests from the
United States and a lawsuit filed by a labor union and
environmental group, Victoria-area officials continue to dump of
millions of gallons of untreated sewage into the Strait of Juan de
Fuca between Canada and the United States, saying the environmental
impact is ``minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-STUDENTS (Seattle) _ Emotions ran high and Sequoia
Junior High School students said they'd never in their life forget
Friday's speech by Holocaust survivor Bronka Serebrin, who was
interned at Auschwitz and Mannhausen. During her talk she implored
them to be nice to each other and speculated the Columbine horror
was caused by two boys who had been teased and treated badly for
years. The kids rushed up after the speech to hug her. A G.I. who
helped liberate Mannhausen camp also talked to the 350 students as
part of their ongoing Holocaust symposium.
</P>
<P>
   By Judi Hunt. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CABIN-HELP (EDMONDS, Wash.) _ A historic log cabin in downtown
Edmonds is deteriorating and needs repairs fast. Children are
dropping coins into ``Save Our Cabin'' donation boxes. The
historical society has prepared a cabin slide show. The city
government is sending in log cabin experts. So what does all this
have to do with ``Here Come the Brides,'' a minor cult-classic TV
show from decades past? Not much, but enough that the show's fans
from around the country want to save the cabin too.
</P>
<P>
   By Rebekah Denn. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MOMS (Seattle) _ Material Mom. She wants silks and sapphires,
truffles and trifles, the two-piece outfit with the three-digit
price tag in the full-page advertisement for ``that special day.''
Material Mom wants it all. But where is this woman? Not,
apparently, on the streets of Seattle. Cruising downtown this week,
we asked moms what they wanted for The Big Day.
</P>
<P>
   By M.L. Lyke. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (New York) _ Seattle Mariners play the Yankees in
New York. It's the first game in major league history with two
Japanese starting pitchers By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the
``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Notes column leading with former
