<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8841 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-800(2TAK     05-07 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAILS BOSNIA OPERATION AS MODEL FOR PEACE KEEPING IN
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday described the
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia, which includes U.S. soldiers
working under the direction of NATO with U.N. approval, as a model
for the force that is envisioned to return and protect ethnic
Albanian refugees to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the arrangement in Bosnia was a good example
for Kosovo because it involved Russian and Ukrainian participation
even though NATO was involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in Bosnia was functional,'' Clinton said at the
White House before leaving for Texas, where he attended
fund-raisers and then planned to travel to Oklahoma on Saturday to
see the destruction from this week's tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials declined to be specific on how closely
the Bosnia model could be copied in Kosovo, which unlike Bosnia,
remains part of Yugoslavia. But Clinton and NATO officials asserted
Friday that NATO would indeed have a role in the peacekeeping
force, despite the absence of such language in the Group of Eight
communique agreed upon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Russians decided to agree to the communique's call
for an international force in Kosovo, they remain opposed to the
involvement of NATO, in part because, the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, opposes such a force.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has insisted that, among other things, a NATO force
would infringe upon the sovereignty of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Work on an international force for Kosovo will start in Moscow
when deputy secretary Strobe Talbott visits there Tuesday,
accompanied by officials from the Pentagon and the National
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade also has insisted that the United Nations be part of
any force. The secretary general of the United Nations, Kofi Annan,
met Friday at the State Department with the secretary of state,
Madeleine Albright, to discuss a U.N. Security Council resolution
that would mandate a military force in Kosovo. They also discussed
what role the United Nations would play in a civil administration
governing a post-conflict Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade Friday was likely
to complicate the hopes of winning a Security Council resolution
mandating a security force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have said that they hoped that
if Russia agreed to a resolution, the Chinese would follow. It was
unusual, they said, for the Chinese to object on their own to a
Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese, nervous about the precedent set by NATO's
bombing of a sovereign country, have been extremely critical of the
operation in its early weeks. The bombing of their embassy is
almost certain to revive Beijing's opposition to the NATO
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Another complicating factor was the closeness of the Belgrade
regime to the Chinese government. In particular, Milosevic's wife,
Mira Markovic, who leads a major political party and is considered
by many to be the second most powerful figure in Yugoslavia, is
considered a great admirer of the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who is poised to take a greater role in the search for a
solution in Kosovo, announced on Friday the appointment of two
special envoys, Carl Bildt, a former Swedish Prime Minister and
Eduard Kukan, the foreign minister of Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan had no plans to visit Belgrade, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting in Germany on Thursday, the Group of Seven
richest nations and Russia laid the ground work for a Security
Council resolution that would endorse ``effective international
civil and security presences.''
</P>
<P>
   Western countries agreed to drop the word NATO from their
communique in order to get Russian agreement for a force with NATO
at its core in Kosovo. At the meeting in Germany, the Russian
foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said that the security force could
not include NATO forces without Milosevic's permission.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott intends to insist in his meetings in Moscow that NATO
troops would be part of the force, administration officials said.
Beyond that, Talbott would discuss the kind of detailed command
arrangements that would permit Russia to participate.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, the 1,500 Russian troops are under the command of a
Russian deputy to Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme commander of NATO.
A similiar arrangement was feasible in Kosovo, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed, State Department officials said, that Russian
soldiers would be deployed in areas of Kosovo where Serbs rather
than ethnic Albanians are dominant.
</P>
<P>
   A critical juncture in the unfolding diplomatic process toward a
settlement in Kosovo would come after the Russian envoy, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, returned to Belgrade to talk to Milosevic about the
security force.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is expected to go to Belgrade in the coming days,
officials in Moscow said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stepped up diplomatic activity in the last few days,
almost of all it has been on one side and has not yet involved
Milosevic. The Yugoslav leader has said he would accept a lightly
armed U.N.-led mission and not the well-armed military force NATO
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Officials warned again Friday that the appearance of all the
negotiating between Russia and the West could give Milosevic the
impression that he could win more concessions by waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have said it would be difficult for them to
agree to a Security Council Chapter 7 resolution that allows for
the approval of a military action without the consent of the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the Russians have not closed the door on a
Chapter 7 resolution and have suggested that they are waiting to
see what flexibility there is in Milosevic's attitude to the
security force.
</P>
<P>
   On another aspect of U.N. involvement in Kosovo once the bombing
stops, the State Department said Friday that Annan talked to
Albright about the shape and responsibilities of a civil
administration and police force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's spokesman, Jamie Rubin, said that the future of
Kosovo had to be thought about so that the plans could be ready for
when ``President Milosevic reverses course and we need to implement
the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaborating on the kind of force that would go into Kosovo,
Rubin stressed that there would be no U.N. involvement in the
actual military operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in the United States or any of the NATO countries
envisages the United Nations Secretariat and the blue-helmet
peacekeeping unit to play any role in the peacekeeping force,''
Rubin said. ``This would be a situation where the United Nations
Security Council, acting on behalf of the world, would authorize
member states to put together a force.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin added: ``It has to be a NATO core force, which for us
means the NATO forces must be under the command of a NATO
commander, meaning through the authority of the Supreme Allied
Commander in Europe _ period, full stop.''
</P>
<P>
   While the administration was focusing on dealing with the
Russians, there was opposition to the settlement, as outlined in
Germany, from an unexpected quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army announced in the Albanian capital,
Tirana, that the proposed settlement was ``unacceptable'' because
it did not foresee the independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Bilal Sherifi, a spokesman for the guerrillas, said they opposed
a solution that preserved Kosovo as a part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sherifi's comments were in line with a general stiffening of the
guerrilla's demands since the expulsion from Kosovo of more than
700,000 ethnic Albanians by Milosevic in the last six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Like all other declarations by the Western allies on Kosovo, the
agreement in Germany called for the disarmament of the guerrillas
once an international security force entered the province. But in
the last several days, officials representing the guerrillas have
said they will not put down their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has made no official comment on the agreement between
the Western allies and Russia on the need for an international
security force. The government run newspaper, Politika, printed the
set of principles in full on the front page Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
