<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLD-WEST-HNS &LR;      05-07 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-WEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS OF WYATT EARP, DOC HOLLIDAY AMONG ITEMS AT OLD WEST AUCTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PFLUGERVILLE, Texas _ David J. Hall insists he does not collect
artifacts. Rather, he collects history.
</P>
<P>
   For 60 years, Hall, a renowned author and historian of the
American West, has collected weapons, photographs, documents and
other such items pertaining to the Old West. But the 72-year-old
self-proclaimed cowboy from Wood River, Ill., recently announced
his retirement, and the immediate dispersal, at auction, of his
vast collection.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day auction, which began Friday in this small
community, is part of the 24th Annual Firearm, Art, Western and
Indian Relic Auction. Five hundred items will be auctioned each
day.
</P>
<P>
   As the auctioneer's expeditious tongue completes a bid, Hall
smiles, more to himself than to others. A Colt Lightning pistol is
sold to a man from Arizona for $900.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can say it's all going toward my little retirement
fund,'' Hall says.
</P>
<P>
   But just because Hall has decided to part with his Western
frontier collection _ which includes Annie Oakley's lucky Indian
head penny glued onto a blue and purple ribbon that used to be
attached to her wardrobe trunk, and Doc Holliday's O.K. Corral,
10-gauge, double barreled shotgun _ does not mean his days of
collecting are over.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Hall has a military collection to build. And a law
enforcement collection. And a Navy collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I can stop now,'' he said. ``I'm going to keep
doing what I've been doing: collecting old things.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the estimated 150 bidders Friday afternoon was former
Texas House Speaker Gib Lewis. Lewis said he frequents most area
auctions and enjoys collecting Western artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just bought some spurs and I'm sure I'll buy more things,''
he said. ``But I'll regret it later, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more famous, and unusual, of the 1,500 items being
auctioned this weekend include Wyatt Earp's 10-gauge shotgun from
1878, photos of Pancho Villa and his wife, Annie Oakley's engraved
silver pistol, horrific photos from the massacre of Sioux at
Wounded Knee and a framed old cardboard warning poster from the
1800s that states: ``Spitting on Sidewalk Prohibited. Penalty $10
to $200.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated to bring $1,700 is a photograph of the sole survivor
of Gen. George Armstrong Custer's command from the battle against
the Sioux at Little Bighorn, a horse called Comanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a hundred stories behind all these items,'' said Tom
Burks, a consultant for Tom Keilman &AMP; Son Auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Also being auctioned is a large photograph collection compiled
by the late Gen. F.W. Sackett. The collection of more than 100
photographs from the 1880s includes Indian Chiefs Sitting Bull,
Geronimo and Red Cloud, Buffalo Bill and actress Lillie Langtry.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his life, Hall has collected, studied and wrote
about the artifacts of the frontier era. His collection of guns,
badges, documents, photographs and Old West memorabilia has been
exhibited in museums throughout the nation, including the
Smithsonian Institution. The Smithsonian also sponsored a
nationwide two-year tour of Hall's U.S. Marshals Exhibit, enabling
Hall to become an honorary deputy U.S. marshal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to do anything dangerous and risky and I get to
be part of the U.S. Marshals,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has worn out six or seven new cars traveling from
state to state purchasing artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'd do if I couldn't keep collecting
stuff,'' the World War II veteran said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall sat in the back corner of the Lions Hall and watched the
commotion over his collection unfold.
</P>
<P>
   With adrenaline as their primary source of energy, hands bobbed
up and down at their chance to claim a piece of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going at twelve, do I hear twelve fifty? Do I hear twelve
fifty? Sold at twelve fifty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sold. Hall sighs deeply, his face flushed with excitement. Sold.
A Colt Lightning owned by former U.S. Marshal Chris Madsen for
$12,500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
