<SLUG> BC-HAMVENTION08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamvention brings thousands to Ohio
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dick Miller, general chairman for this year's
Hamvention, wants the event to be a success _ but not too much of a
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting 25,000 to 28,000 people, and if we get about
25,000 I'll be tickled pink,'' Miller said. ``When you get 28,000
and above it really starts getting crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamvention, which is in its 48th year, is the annual gathering
of amateur radio enthusiasts from all over the world. Participants
will gather at the Dayton Hara Complex Friday through May 16 to
check out the latest in radio and other electronic equipment and to
meet people with whom they've communicated by radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We refer to it as `eyeball contact,''' Miller said. ``Last
year a guy from Australia recognized my call letters from my
license plates and introduced himself. That sort of thing is an
important part of Hamvention.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said about 1,500 vendors will set up sales displays of
hard-to-find parts and equipment in the flea-market area in Hara's
back parking lot. Another 250 manufacturers and vendors maintain
booths inside the arena's buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Hamvention also features forums and seminars in Hara's meeting
rooms. ``We take up every square foot of available public space
there,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   For participants who don't want to spend all their time in
Dayton twiddling knobs and raising antennae, Hamvention offers a
series of alternative activities next Saturday. Miller said those
activities, organized with the help of the Dayton/Montgomery County
Convention and Visitors Bureau, include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cooking classes: Starting at 8:45 a.m. at Sinclair Community
College, a local chef will share recipes and food preparation tips.
Participants will prepare a lunch. The fee is $20, and admission to
this and all other alternative activities is open to people holding
Hamvention tickets only.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shop Around: A bus tour of local boutiques and specialty shops
starts at 9 a.m. and runs until midafternoon. Admission is $5.
</P>
<P>
   _ How Does Your Garden Grow? A gardening class held at
Meadowdale High School from 10 to 11:15 a.m. Saturday. The fee is
$3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dine Around: A bus will pick up guests at Hara on at 10:45
a.m. Saturday and take them to the Bravo Italian Kitchen, L'Auberge
and El Meson Restaurant. Admission is $17 per person.
</P>
<P>
   _ City Tour: A bus tour leaves Hara at 1 p.m. and returns at 4
p.m. after showing the sights of the city. Admission is $7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make It, Take It: A craft class in which participants will
keep the craft items they produce will be held at Meadowdale High
School from 1:30 to 2:30 p.m. The fee is $5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Let's Get Beautiful: The event, which carries a $5 fee,
features tips and demonstrations on nails, lip colors, fragrances
and color matching. It will be held at Meadowdale High School from
3 to 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Banquet and Concert: A banquet will be held at the Nutter
Center at 7 p.m. Saturday, and a concert featuring Joe Walsh,
formerly of the Eagles, will be held later in the evening.
Admission to the banquet and show is $40 a person. Admission to the
concert only is $20, and tickets are available at the Hara and
Nutter box offices as well as through Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
