A8854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-07 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LEON HESS DESERVED MORE THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the New York Jets were about to go to Denver for last
season's American Football Conference championship game, Leon Hess
was asked if he would make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I have a little problem.''
</P>
<P>
   His little problem was a blood disease that required periodic
transfusions. But when the Jets, after losing in that opportunity
to go to the Super Bowl, returned and filed out of their chartered
airliner at La Guardia Airport around 2 o'clock the next morning,
Leon Hess was at the gate to greet all the coaches and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that night's freezing cold,'' Jets president Steve Gutman
recalled, ``Leon came out to shake hands with everybody and thank
them for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 13-5 record, it was the Jets' best season in their more
than two decades with Leon Hess as the principal owner. And his
last season. He died early Friday at Lenox Hill Hospital in
Manhattan, at age 85, of what he had called his little problem.
Typical.
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman of Amerada Hess Corp., he was worth $720
million, according to Forbes magazine last October, but he never
flashed his money clip or his ego. One year, when the Jets'
public-relations staff couldn't find a photo of him, he chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' he said, ``You won't be able to put my picture in the
media guide.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his wealth, Hess lived quietly, privately. After a
National Football League meeting one year, he discovered that he
was to ride to the airport in a white Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not me,'' he said. ``I'm not riding in a white Rolls-Royce.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a dark sedan was all Leon Hess needed. No glitz, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   After a Jets game, win or lose, he would stop by the lockers of
a few older players to talk, then he would sit in the coach's
office for maybe half an hour, mostly listening or consoling, then
quietly depart through the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Any time an injured Jets player had to stay overnight at Lenox
Hill, Hess always visited. When Dennis Byrd was partly paralyzed in
1992, Hess visited the defensive end nightly for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hess was cherished by the Jets' coaches, players and office
employees, but as the team struggled through so many disappointing
seasons, their frustrated fans mistook his introverted manner for
indifference. Many hoped he would sell the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets haven't been worth the aggravation,'' he once
acknowledged, ``but I'd be damned if I'd quit. I'll never sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jets made the playoffs in the 1969, 1981, 1982,
1985, 1986 and 1991 seasons, they never returned to the Super Bowl
that the 1968 team had won when Hess was a part owner. As the
principal owner, Hess had approved the hiring of Walt Michaels, Joe
Walton, Bruce Coslet and Pete Carroll as coaches. Then, he hired
Rich Kotite himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of those coaches were in over their head; I probably
kept them two or three years longer than I should have,'' he said
late last season. ``I had the idea the team could be run by
committee, but it's like a business. You need a strong man.''
</P>
<P>
   When that strong man, Bill Parcells, was available in 1997 after
having resigned as the New England Patriots' coach, Hess pursued
him, only to discover that he had to negotiate compensation with
Patriots owner Robert Kraft and NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   As an oil baron, Hess once sat with Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi's negotiator, who put a revolver on the table. Another time
he went to see the Shah of Iran in a car with soldiers' guns
sticking out its windows. Each time, he got the oil contract he
wanted. So the negotiations with Kraft weren't about to intimidate
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraft put his offer down on one side of a piece of paper, we
put down our offer on the other side,'' Hess later recalled. ``Then
I suggested that we give our offers to the commissioner and accept
his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue decreed that the Jets give the Patriots four early
draft choices over the next three years. Hess acknowledged that
Kraft ``got more out of us than we wanted to give, but he got less
than he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, Hess got Parcells, who last season guided the
Jets to their first divisional title since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the division,'' Hess said then, ``is one of the
greatest thrills of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Jets' owner, it was one of Leon Hess' few thrills. He
deserved many, many more.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
