<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8856 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-FLYING-VOTERS-     05-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-FLYING-VOTERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF U.S.-BASED ISRAELIS TO FLY HOME TO VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a trans-Atlantic expansion of one of America's
oldest political practices _ getting out the vote _ supporters of
the two major candidates for prime minister of Israel are arranging
for thousands of Israelis living in the United States to fly home
at cut-rate fares for the coming national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Like cars dispatched by big-city precinct captains to taxi
voters to the polls, chartered jets are scheduled to begin flying
out of New York and a few other North American cities next weekend,
timed to arrive in Tel Aviv as the polls open on May 17. The jumbo
747s are to be met by buses which, organizers say, will take the
arriving passengers, most of whom hold dual Israeli and American
citizenships, directly from the 12-hour flight to the polling
stations in the Israeli communities they call home.
</P>
<P>
   The get-out-the-vote campaign marks a dramatic expansion of a
much more modest effort that was organized in 1996, mostly by
religious Jews in Brooklyn who flew to Israel to vote for Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his Likud Party. By contrast, this
time there are two New York-based groups that, with the backing of
wealthy American benefactors who have taken an interest in the
election, are offering round-trip fares ranging from $180 to $449,
much less than the standard coach class round-trip fare of about
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   They estimate that between them, they will ferry as many as
15,000 Israelis back home for the vote and a possible runoff in
June _ a number that could prove to be a major factor if the
election turns out to be anywhere near as close as the last one, in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of legal reasons, the two organizations, Chai
L'Yisrael and Kesher, are presenting themselves as nonpartisan,
interested only in insuring that Israelis living in America have an
opportunity to participate in the election. In fact, though, each
organization has a clear allegiance to one of the two major
candidates _ Chai L'Yisrael has ties to Netanyahu, while Kesher is
seen as favoring Ehad Barak of the Labor Party _ and has sought to
market the discounted seats to Israelis who they presume will share
their sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   The flights, which have been advertised in Israeli newspapers
distributed in the United States, on a Web site and in Hebrew- and
English-language fliers posted in Jewish neighborhoods in Brooklyn
and Queens, are the latest evidence of American influence on
Israeli politics. This campaign for prime minister has already been
distinguished by the reliance of both Netanyahu and Barak on
American political consultants to help run their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to fly voters to the polls also suggests the depth of
the ties that Jews who have moved to United States maintain with
the country they call their homeland, as well as the intensity that
Israelis _ no matter where they live _ bring to their politics.
Turnout in Israeli elections is typically more than 80 percent of
the voting-age population, and a number of Israelis living in
America said this week that they thought nothing about flying 12
hours to cast a vote in what could be a very close election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very important election,'' said Tami
Giniger, a 22-year-old New York University student who is booked on
a Kesher flight and is planning is planning to vote for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But the flights have caused clear concern in Israel. Although
Israel bans foreign contributions to its political campaigns, the
subsidized flights allow wealthy Americans, who as a rule have not
identified themselves publicly, to affect the outcome of the
Israeli election in a much more direct way than just contributing
money to a candidate. And the image of thousands of Israelis who
live in America jetting in, voting and then leaving a week or so
later, after a short vacation, has drawn the attention of the
Israeli press and clearly rankled some Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who don't live here, who don't bear the
consequence of their vote,'' said Alon Pinkas, a political
consultant who is advising Barak.
</P>
<P>
   On a practical level, many Labor leaders are concerned that the
influx will encourage voter fraud that may play to the advantage of
Netanyahu. At polling places, Israelis are required to display
identity cards that include their photographs. But Barak's
supporters say that many of the returning Americans are Hasidim
who, with their beards and black hats, can be difficult to
distinguish from one another.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the possibility, these supporters say, that those
voters will fly in with a stack of their friends' identity cards
and employ another old American political practice: voting early
and often, and most likely _ given their conservatism _ for
Netanyahu and the Likud slate of candidates for the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that has stuck in the side of the left for a
long time,'' said Steve Rabinowitz, a Washington political
consultant who is advising Barak. ``These are the guys who have
historically been believed to be flooding back to Israel for the
election _ and if not them, at least their identity card.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to verify claims by the two New York groups that
they will fly 15,000 Israelis back home for the May 17 election and
the June 2 runoff that will take place if neither Netanyahu nor
Barak wins more than 50 percent, as now appears likely in a crowded
field.
</P>
<P>
   But even accounting for exaggeration _ another political
practice that crosses international boundaries _ it is now fairly
certain that the Israeli electorate this year will include a
sizable number of dual citizens who live and work in the United
States but are able to vote in Israel because of Israeli
immigration laws intended to encourage Jews dispersed across the
world to establish residency there.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And considering that Netanyahu defeated Shimon Peres in 1996 by
only 29,457 votes out of about 3 million cast, the
American-generated turnout could prove consequential if the vote is
close again. Recent polls show the contest is close, with Barak
pulling ahead in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big influence in a very close, very tight race,'' said
Udi Behr, 38, a jewelry designer from Manhattan, who organized the
Kesher effort.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the interest stirred in New York by the prospect of
going home for the Israeli elections could be found in a recent
visit to the bustling offices of Chai L'Yisrael. The group is
working out of donated second-floor space overlooking 13th Avenue
in Borough Park, Brooklyn, in what is normally the political club
of state Assemblyman Dov Hikind, a Democrat and one of Netanyahu's
most prominent American supporters. Volunteers, many of them
speaking in Hebrew, worked nearly a dozen telephones to inform
people of their flight departure times.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides say they have not employed direct or indirect
measures to filter out potential customers who might not share
their political views, Chai L'Yisrael and Kesher are clearly
employing subtle means to steer their seats to sympathetic voters.
Chai L'Yisrael, for example, has advertised in The Jewish Press, a
conservative newspaper; distributed leaflets in New York
neighborhoods known as enclaves for the religious Jews who are more
likely to support Netanyahu, and set up its headquarters in the
heart of one of the city's most religious and conservative
neighborhoods, Borough Park. And the language of the leaflets
echoes almost exactly the campaign rhetoric that Netanyahu used in
1996: ``Help keep Israel Jewish and secure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I want to see Bibi Netanyahu elected,'' Hikind said. ``I
am 100 percent for him. But that is not a question that is asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Kesher has been advertising on the Internet, and has made a
particular effort to recruit Israeli students, who as a rule tend
to be liberal. And while Chai L'Yisrael is chartering jets for the
May 17 election, Kesher is holding off for the expected June 2
runoff between Barak and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   An influx of support for Barak might prove valuable then because
some of the voters who back Barak on May 17 _ in particular, Arabs
who are drawn to the first round because it will include choosing a
Knesset _ may find little reason to show up for a runoff for prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two groups here, Chai L'Yisrael is the more heavily
subsidized, as shown by its low ticket prices _ $180 _ and its
hopes to charter as many as 20 747s. By contrast, Kesher is buying
seats in bulk on El Al and then subsidizing the discounted tickets
so they cost just over $449, plus tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
