<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-REYNOLDS-SURVEY-A     05-07 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-REYNOLDS-SURVEY-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLOBAL VOTE FOR U.S. STYLE OF CORPORATE OPENNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 9)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK J. LYONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the people who wield the big money have anything to say about
it, country-to-country differences in corporate governance
practices will give way to a homogenous global approach based
largely on the American and British model.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments come through clearly in the latest survey of
institutional investors commissioned by Russell Reynolds
Associates, an executive search firm. The study, scheduled to be
released Monday, found that investors in Germany and Japan want
companies in those countries to be as open and forthcoming about
the way boards operate and directors are chosen as American and
British companies are. They favor establishment of international
standards for corporate governance practices, and they believe
companies everywhere should follow the British-American model of
placing shareholder value above the interests of other
``stakeholders'' like employees and suppliers, or considerations,
like the health of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments are not just an idle wish list; they help drive
investment decisions. About half the investors surveyed in Japan
and the United States and significant minorities in Britain and
Germany said corporate governance issues were very important or
extremely important factors in investment decisions; even larger
numbers cited adequacy of disclosure as a very important or
extremely important factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good corporate governance practices are becoming a key way for
companies to distinguish themselves when they are trying to attract
capital,'' said John Hawkins, managing director of Russell
Reynolds' board. ``It's analogous to the steps some companies have
taken to bring their accounting standards into line with Western
methods.''
</P>
<P>
   By wide majorities, the investors said good corporate governance
is essential whether or not a company is performing well and that
strong returns do not excuse opaque policies and practices.
</P>
<P>
   German and Japanese investors were included in the survey for
the first time this year, in part because companies in their
countries have structures very different from the British-American
model. For example, under German law, corporations generally have
two boards, a management board that directly runs the company and a
supervisory board on which employees are heavily represented. In
Japan, most corporations stock their boards with dozens of company
insiders, and independent outside directors are rare. For their
part, institutional investors in the two countries have much more
in common with their American and British counterparts in their
views on governance, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   One issue on which they differ is the role of credit rating
agencies: Japanese and German investors were much more likely than
Americans or Britons to want credit agencies to include corporate
governance practices in their rating reports. Hawkins speculated
that the finding could be attributed to the tendency of companies
in Germany and Japan to depend more heavily on capital raised
through borrowing and less on equity.
</P>
<P>
   British investors gave the most scrutiny to company leadership,
citing the quality of chief executives and board members as
important factors in investment decisions much more often than
their peers in the United States, Japan or Germany. A series of
high-profile commissions on corporate governance has kept the issue
in the news there in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said that it is difficult to isolate any direct link
between governance practices and corporate performance _ ``there
are too many other, stronger variables'' _ but that most
institutional investors believe that good boardroom practices make
a difference at the margin and will loom large if markets turn
sour. ``Clearly, in a down cycle a shareholder-oriented board will
be an important protection for investors, especially minority
investors,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIPPER-DEPRESSION-NYT     05-07 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIPPER-DEPRESSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPPER GORE DISCLOSES TREATMENT FOR DEPRESSION IN 1989  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tipper Gore, the wife of the vice president,
disclosed in a newspaper article published Friday that she was
treated for depression after their 6-year-old son was severely
injured in an automobile accident in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, published by USA Today in a question-and-answer
format, Mrs. Gore said she had taken medication and received
counseling for the depression and was not now under treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Her office confirmed the details of the published account but
said she would not be available to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore has long been an advocate of efforts to combat mental
illness. She said in the interview that she hoped her story would
encourage others to seek treatment and that her husband's campaign
for president was ``not really'' a factor in the timing of her
public account. But it is nonetheless clear that her making her
illness known now pre-empted the possibility of a potentially
damaging disclosure about it later, in the heat of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a clinical depression and one that I was
going to have to have help to overcome,'' Mrs. Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling her counseling from a social worker, she added, ``You
just can't will your way out of that or pray your way out of that
or pull yourself up by the bootstraps out of that _ you really have
to go and get help, and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, whose son, Albert Gore III, recovered from the
accident, did not disclose many details about her depression. She
did not say how long it had lasted, and she declined to say which
medication she had taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when someone singles out a particular
medication,'' she said, ``then someone's reading about it saying,
`I'm going to try that' or `Other things don't work as well.' It's
not a one-size-fits-all kind of answer.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly the first time that the spouse of a political
candidate has been led to disclose a personal problem, and on her
own terms. One memorable instance occurred in July 1987, several
months after Michael S. Dukakis began running for president, when
his wife, Kitty, said she had been dependent on amphetamines for 26
years and had been treated for addiction in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mrs. Gore, she said that in her travels she had
encountered many young people suffering from depression and thought
her disclosure might be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``extremely frightening,'' she said, to realize that she
needed professional help, but ``I do consider that I have
recovered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
