<SLUG> BC-CABIN-HELP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE COMES SOME HELP FOR AGING, ROTTING LOB CABIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONDS, Wash. _ A historic log cabin in downtown Edmonds is
deteriorating and needs repairs fast.
</P>
<P>
   Children are dropping coins into ``Save Our Cabin'' donation
boxes. The historical society has prepared a cabin slide show. The
city government is sending in log cabin experts.
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this have to do with ``Here Come the Brides,''
a minor cult-classic TV show from decades past?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, but enough that the show's fans from around the
country want to save the cabin too.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely connection is Edmonds native Bridget Hanley, an
actress who starred in the 1960s adventure-comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley's grandparents once lived in the tiny cabin, and her
family has been active in restoration efforts. Now ``Brides'' fans
nationwide have rallied behind the cause since learning of the
connection through fan club Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just knocked out'' by the support, Hanley said by
telephone from her Los Angeles home this week. ```Here Come The
Brides,' God bless it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC show began in 1968 and was set in Seattle's pioneer
days. It served as a career springboard for many of its stars,
including teen heartthrob Bobby Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Fans have set up an online ``Save Our Cabin'' store, unfazed by
the fact that the cabin itself had nothing to do with the show.
</P>
<P>
   In the brief weeks since the online store opened for business,
it's done a brisk trade in fan-donated memorabilia like a Bobby
Sherman stuffed pillow, an old issue of TV Guide featuring the show
and 8x10 glossy photographs of `Brides' stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the fan club have felt a need to
participate and support Bridget and her family in this,'' said
Olympia supporter Wendy McAbee, who bought items off the Web site,
donated others for sale, and is helping the Edmonds committee.
</P>
<P>
   The fan efforts, while appreciated by cabin supporters, are just
a small part of the widespread local drive to save the building,
which is now owned by the city and serves as its visitors bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just charming. It's one of those places you go into and
you feel warm,'' said historical society and cabin restoration
committee member Mary Van Meter. ``It's an important part of the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   The cabin isn't particularly old as log cabins go. It was built
in the 1930s from Douglas firs cleared from the Edmonds woods and
modeled after lodges at Yellowstone National Park. It was used as a
guest house by a Edmonds business leader, then as a home by
Hanley's grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The family later donated the cabin to the city, and it was moved
next to the historical museum for the nation's bicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   Grade-schoolers visit it for history lessons each year, running
hands along the shiny sapling banister, learning about the chinking
system that sealed the logs, and seeing how the interior is
unchanged from the black-and-white family photos on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cabin's problems came about because the bicentennial
movers placed it directly on the ground, with no foundation to
protect the logs from moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Rotting logs now need to be replaced, sound ones need to be
preserved, and a new foundation is essential, city officials said.
Early repair estimates range from $28,000 to more than $100,000,
and getting a solid figure is the next step.
</P>
<P>
   Van Meter and others are working to place the cabin on a state
historic register, which would exempt the cabin from the
modernizing features that would otherwise be required by the
building code if the building were renovated.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has raised about $7,000 for restorations to date,
with the largest contributions coming from the historical society
and the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brides'' fans plan to continue their fund-raising work, and
Hanley herself plans to come to the area for fund-raising
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley said she's always loved visiting the cabin when she
returned to her hometown, and felt it was an important part of the
city's history as well as her family.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers Edmonds as a child's paradise of dirt roads and
forest and wild blackberry vines, with the cabin ``a gingerbread
house'' where she and her sisters sat and licked icicles in the
wintertime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like being in a fairyland...'' she said. ``It was
just a charming, wonderful, warm and very gentle way to grow up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
