<SLUG> BC-LITTON-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED DEALS WOULD MAKE LITTON LEADING MILITARY SHIPBUILDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., La., Va.)  (rk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Litton Industries, one of the nation's largest
shipbuilders, has seldom made waves. As the defense industry
consolidated around it in a series of megamergers, Litton contented
itself with a string of small acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   But with its unusual proposal Thursday to simultaneously acquire
two of its competitors, Newport News Shipbuilding and Avondale
Industries, Litton is trying to seize the moment to turn itself
from a midsized defense contractor into the leading supplier of
naval ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an aggressive move for a company that historically has
not been aggressive,'' said Jon B. Kutler, president of Quarterdeck
Investment Partners, an investment banking firm specializing in
aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubel, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., agreed. ``I
give Litton a lot of credit for finding the right moment to
strike,'' he said. ``It's a cougarlike move.''
</P>
<P>
   The aggressiveness appears to reflect to some degree the
handiwork of Michael R. Brown, who became Litton's chief executive
a year ago but did not fully take over until his predecessor, John
Leonis, retired from his post as chairman in March.Brown, who
briefly played professional football for the San Diego Chargers,
recently hired a new chief financial officer, D. Michael Steuert.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors were not completely enamored of the proposed
transaction or of the new management team, sending Litton shares
down $1.625, to $63.125. The shares of a company attempting an
acquisition often fall, but investors were also apparently
disappointed that Litton executives, in a conference call with
analysts, had been vague about the cost savings they expected from
the double acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Litton, based in Woodland Hills, Calif., proposed to acquire
Newport News and Avondale in deals that were valued at a combined
$1.8 billion when announced after the close of trading on Thursday.
Litton would also assume $600 million of Newport News debt.
</P>
<P>
   The double purchase would make Litton the nation's fifth-largest
defense contractor _ it is now eighth _ and the largest
shipbuilder, surpassing the General Dynamics Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can compete on any class of ship the government wants, head
to head with General Dynamics,'' Brown said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics had tried to buy Newport News, but was blocked
by the Pentagon on antitrust grounds. Analysts do not expect the
Litton acquisitions to raise the same issues because they would not
leave the building of all nuclear ships in one company.
</P>
<P>
   Both Newport News and Avondale, which had agreed to merge
themselves, have said they are reviewing Litton's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard for them to resist this deal,'' said
Loren Thompson, a defense expert at the Lexington Institute in
Arlington, Va., referring to Newport News. He said the company was
under pressure from workers, who are striking; from the Pentagon,
to which it has promised cost cuts; and from shareholders
disappointed that the deal with General Dynamics did not go
through.
</P>
<P>
   Still, since Litton is offering to pay 0.55 share for each share
of Newport News, the drop in Litton's stock price Friday lowered
the value of its offer to $34.72 a share from $35.61 Thursday.
That, plus the fact that the offer is less than the $38.50 General
Dynamics was willing to pay, could give Newport News a reason to
reject Litton's offer or at least bargain up the price. Newport
News shares soared $5.75, to $32.75.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed acquisition of Avondale, which is worth $38 a share
in cash, seems more straightforward. Shares of Avondale, which
makes amphibious assault vehicles and auxiliary naval vessels, rose
$4.3125, to $36.0625.
</P>
<P>
   If Avondale, which is based near New Orleans, does agree to be
acquired by Litton, this could put more pressure on Newport News to
accept the deal as well, since Newport News would lose its own
opportunity to grow by acquiring Avondale. Litton has said either
acquisition could go ahead without the other.
</P>
<P>
   Litton was once a sprawling conglomerate involved in businesses
ranging from microwave ovens to oil-field services. Since divesting
its oil-field services business, Western Atlas, in 1994, it has
concentrated on shipbuilding, defense electronics and electronic
components. It has taken its cash flow from shipbuilding and used
it to build up a fourth leg of its business by buying companies
that provide computer services to government agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
