<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8874 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS     05-07 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRIAL METALS: THE TEA LEAF COMMODITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of copper has jumped 15.4 percent since its low this
year, to 70.78 cents a pound. The price of tin is up 12 percent
from its 1999 low; nickel, 41.3 percent; lead, 11.8 percent, and
aluminum, 17.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So what?
</P>
<P>
   The price of spot copper is still 17.3 percent below its 1998
high. Aluminum is down 13 percent; tin, 10.4 percent; lead, 10.2
percent, and nickel, 6 percent. The prices of these metals, all
traded on the London Metal Exchange, are even further below their
highs of the last big commodity rally, which reached its peaks in
1995 and 1996. (And at the same time, agricultural commodities,
except for hogs, are still declining.)
</P>
<P>
   For for all kinds of investors, there are reasons to be
concerned. But there is one issue _ inflation _ that is not worth
worrying about yet.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rise in industrial commodity prices is important
because it could help lead to rising wages and, therefore, more
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   One of the recent surprises for economists has been the slowdown
in the rate of wage increases, despite a drop in unemployment. The
April employment data released on Friday showed that the increase
in average hourly earnings had slowed to 3.4 percent in the last
year, below the 3.8 percent for the 12 months ended in December.
</P>
<P>
   One theory to explain it is that the sharp decline in the
inflation rate in 1998 tempered wage demands. The Consumer Price
Index rose just 1.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Shepherdson, chief United States economist at High Frequency
Economics in Valhalla, N.Y., thinks the CPI will end the year up
about 2 percent. That is not a major increase. But he thinks that
the jump in oil and gasoline prices will temporarily push the
annual rate of increase in the CPI to 2.5 percent. And that
headline, he said, ``will not play well in Peoria, and it could
well affect pay negotiations later this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The price increases in metals could also signal that the global
economy is turning around, a fact that would make a slowdown here
less likely and a rate increase by the Federal Reserve, to put a
drag on growth, more likely.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening globally is one of the most important
questions for investors over the next several months. The selloff
last week in the bond market, which pushed the yield on the 30-year
bond up to 5.81 percent, the highest in almost a year, was prompted
in part by the fear that a rebound in Asia and Europe would make a
slowdown here almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, compounded that
concern by saying on Thursday that the global financial crisis
appears to have passed. He said the threat was now that low
employment would drive wages _ and inflation _ higher.
</P>
<P>
   If commodity prices are accelerating, Shepherdson said, ``it is
more likely that the world economy is turning around.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherdson and other economists caution that, as of now, this
is the likely, but not the certain, outcome. There are not enough
data yet to prove that the global economy has turned around.
</P>
<P>
   While South Korea and some other Asian countries are showing
signs of revival, Japan is still a big question mark. And Europe is
sluggish despite the surprising interest-rate cut last month by the
European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Neill, director of futures research at Merrill Lynch,
said: ``It is premature to say that commodities are telling us that
we are heading to a new global economic boom. But the worst may be
over.''
</P>
<P>
   What is not to worry about is that inflation is going to shoot
dangerously higher. ``We're not set for a big commodity or
inflation boom,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   A main reason is that commodities constitute such a small part
of American products, making up less than 10 percent of the total
cost, according to Shepherdson. And companies can offset the higher
costs. So outside of oil and gasoline, it is very difficult to
predict what portion of commodity price increases will reach the
consumer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
