<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-POISON-PILL-AR     05-07 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-POISON-PILL-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING THE DEATH OF THE POISON PILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y., Del., Okla.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)  
 (af)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Chubb Corp., an insurance company known for the
gilt-edged coverage favored by some of the wealthiest Americans,
held its annual meeting last month at its headquarters in Warren,
N.J., there was a prickly item on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders, led by a union that owns $1.63 million of Chubb
stock, a small fraction of the total, wanted to do away with the
company's poison-pill provision, intended to foil hostile
takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   The company strongly opposed the move. Yet nearly 70 percent of
the ballot-casting shareholders voted to get rid of the poison
pill, backing the contention that a sale of the company _ whether
through a hostile takeover or otherwise _ might well increase the
value of the shares.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the poison pill, a device created in the early 1980s
by a New York lawyer to combat the advances of a horde of corporate
raiders, is perhaps the hottest issue in corporate governance in
this season of annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions vary, but they tend to make hostile takeovers
impractical. One technique is to issue large numbers of shares to
existing shareholders, thus diluting the value of a hostile
bidder's stake.
</P>
<P>
   Many poison pills that were instituted a decade ago are up for
renewal, and shareholders at a half-dozen companies have taken
steps to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   For years, shareholders have voted to recommend that companies
get rid of poison pills, but management has found it easy to ignore
these moves. Now, shareholders are upping the ante, trying to force
change through bylaw amendments. The law on whether companies will
have to comply is still evolving.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the Chubb vote, 52 percent of the voting
shareholders of Union Carbide supported such an amendment to
eliminate their company's poison pill. This week, there will be
votes at Quaker Oats and at US West, with a vote at J.C. Penney set
for next week.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the debate over poison pills is whether they
help or hurt the price of a company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   The most vocal shareholders, mainly public and union pension
funds, say poison pills scare away potential bidders and keep
prices down. Yet the 2,000 or so companies with poison pills say
the very nature of the provisions is to prevent a potential buyer
from taking control simply by amassing shares and, instead, to
force negotiations with management for a higher sale price.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have studies to back up their arguments. And John
Coffee, a securities law professor at Columbia University, says
that to some extent, both sides are right.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line with a poison pill, he said, is this: ``You
reduce the probability of a takeover bid being made, which
shareholders don't like. But, on the other hand, you increase the
premium for shareholders if a bid is made.''
</P>
<P>
   The poison-pill confrontations are another chapter in a
long-running campaign by institutional shareholders to gain a
greater voice in corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we don't like about poison pills is that the
board gets to make all the decisions in the event of a takeover
bid,'' said Michael Zucker, the director of corporate and financial
affairs for the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile
Employees, which led the vote against Chubb's poison pill. That
situation, he said, often has a negative financial impact.
</P>
<P>
   John Wilcox, the chairman of Georgeson &AMP; Co., a proxy
solicitation firm that is working for Chubb, says shareholders
delegate authority to their board for many things, including poison
pills. ``You can't say you're going to invest millions in this
company, but that you don't trust these people at all when it comes
to takeover bids,'' Wilcox said. ``The role of shareholders is to
elect directors, not to micro-manage how companies run.''
</P>
<P>
   Another shareholder objection to poison pills is that they
provide job protection to managers whose poor performance has
propelled a decline of share values to the point where raiders are
attracted. That, however, is not the issue at Chubb. Though its
stock is down nearly 21 percent from its 52-week high last July,
its chief executive, Dean O'Hare, and his staff are highly regarded
by shareholders and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox acknowledged that shareholders and boards often have
conflicting goals. ``Managers want to preserve the enterprise,'' he
said, ``and shareholders want to get their money and get out of
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two companies whose poison pills were challenged this year _ St.
Paul Cos., an insurer, and International Flavors and Fragrances _
agreed to eliminate the devices without a vote being taken. But
Chubb has taken a defiant stand.
</P>
<P>
   While discussions were under way with the Needletrades Union
pension fund on preparations for the shareholder vote at Chubb, the
company's board simply revoked the existing poison pill and created
a new one designed to run for 10 years. In its proxy, Chubb said
its lawyers had concluded that under New Jersey law, the board has
exclusive authority over poison pills.
</P>
<P>
   When a majority of shareholders voted against a poison pill,
Chubb refused to recognize the results. ``We don't intend to do
anything,'' said Gail Devlin, a senior vice president who handles
investor relations at Chubb.
</P>
<P>
   The union is considering suing. Earlier this year, a federal and
a state court in Oklahoma upheld the right of shareholders to
eliminate a poison pill through a bylaw amendment, as they did at
Chubb. But New Jersey's courts are free to come to their own
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware, where many of the biggest American companies are
incorporated, has yet to deal with whether shareholders can abolish
poison pills. But its courts have tended not to curtail the
authority of corporate boards, and some experts believe that New
Jersey, which has little case law on corporate matters, could be
influenced by Delaware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
