<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-REVIVAL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reverend answers long-distance calling
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At 7 p.m. on a Monday evening in Miamisburg,
outside the whitewashed two-story building behind Sara Jane's
Restaurant on South Main Street, you can hear the Rev. Bernard Dada
shouting at God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it, Jesus. Do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We Africans shout at God,'' he explains, exuberant with a
wide, shiny smile.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, God spoke to Dada in the bedroom of his home in Agbor
in midwestern Nigeria. ``He said, `Go to Dayton, Ohio, and pray for
revival there,''' Dada says, his accent thick. ``I said, `Where is
it?' Dayton, Ohio? I couldn't even pronounce it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dada, a 43-year-old British seminary graduate, hastened to a
map and saw it was near Cincinnati, a city he had once visited.
Then he hastened to the visa office to explain his calling. A visa
was granted, more expeditiously than usual, Dada claims. He
promised to return to his wife and four children.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's evangelical community has welcomed Dada without
skepticism, believing his coming from afar is surely a sign that
Dayton is God's chosen site for revival that will spread throughout
the country, says the Rev. Don McMurry of the Greater Dayton
Baptist Association in Huber Heights. If the faithful will only
pray.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Bill Hoerr of Centerville met Dada during a visit to
Africa several years ago. He welcomed him and helped him to find
shelter here.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four months, he has made the rounds to dozens of
area churches, crossing denominations. He preached at Courthouse
Square on Thursday in observance of the National Day of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   And on Mondays, Thursdays and Saturdays, Dada's revival prayer
meetings have drawn as many as 170 people of various denominations,
races and classes to the low-ceilinged makeshift sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
