A8879 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOMS-SPI &LR;      05-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOTHER'S LOVE CAN'T BE BOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Material Mom. She wants silks and sapphires, truffles
and trifles, the two-piece outfit with the three-digit price tag in
the full-page advertisement for ``that special day.''
</P>
<P>
   Material Mom wants it all.
</P>
<P>
   But where is this woman?
</P>
<P>
   Not, apparently, on the streets of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things _ they come and go,'' says Kay Fox, who has four grown
children. ``What mothers really want is their children's love.
Could you ask for anything more?''
</P>
<P>
   Cruising downtown this week in what should be the heat of
Mother's Day gift-buying, we asked moms what they wanted for The
Big Day.
</P>
<P>
   Their answers had nothing to do with money, and everything to do
with love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want presents _ I just want the kids around,'' said
Nita Glass, 76, strolling Pike Place Market with her daughter,
Gail. ``A lot of jewelry and stuff, it doesn't mean much, and it
costs a fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Advises Glass: ``Save the money and use it for a telephone call,
or to buy gas to go see your mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Nelson, fresh from a visit to Seattle Aquarium with son
Christopher, 2{, said she wants only health and happiness for her
family. Christopher was born after four attempts at in-vitro
fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a miracle to us, so Mother's Day is very special,'' said
the 42-year-old mother.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of the children we stopped were in heavy-thinking
mode. ``If I could get my Mom anything, I'd get her surgery for her
throat. She has these nodes on it,'' said 13-year-old Stephanie
Ashmore, at The Market with her family.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Seattle Aquarium, Lizeth Cervantes, 10, told why she
wanted to buy her mother a trip to Mexico. ``She needs tickets to
go see her mother and to stay there for five months, because she
hasn't seen her in eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Time was the only thing most moms wanted spent on Mother's Day _
time with the family and, for a few hours, time alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want is so easy,'' said Liz Snyder, shopping downtown
with her 2{-year-old daughter. ``I want her father to take her for
the whole day so I can sleep and hang out and do my toenails if I
want to.''
</P>
<P>
   At Westlake Center, surrounded by shops full of 14-karat gold
jewelry and slinky lingerie, mothers described the gifts that
mattered most to them _ the bouquets of weeds, the clay vases made
with tissue-paper flowers, the coupon book with promises to wash
the dishes and sweep the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like to get is the pictures she makes for me _ pictures
of girls in dresses and flowers and rainbows,'' said Nancy Millard,
visiting the mall with her daughter Julia, 5{.
</P>
<P>
   Millard described going through her grandmother's keepsakes and
finding a Mother's Day card she had given Grandma as a child. ``I
had drawn a horse on it. I was 8 or 9,'' said Millard. ``Those are
the things mothers remember. No one remembers The Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing in the Food Court at Westlake Center, Claire Bangasser
touched her heart as she talked. ``Mothers don't want the blenders
and the coffee machines. All we want is a hug from our children.
And the older you get, the more hugs you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Bangasser, mother of two grown daughters, was visiting from
France, where Mother's Day is celebrated the fourth Sunday of the
month. In America, it's always the second Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations of motherhood trace back to ancient Greece, where
spring celebrants gave thanks to Rhea, the mother of the gods. The
American holiday was the suggestion of Julia Ward Howe in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who wrote the words to ``The Battle Hymn of the
Republic,'' wanted Mother's Day dedicated to peace. And, despite
the American marketing blitz, that theme survives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like is to have a peaceful world for my
grandchildren to grow up in,'' said Gina Brewington, who has seven
grandchildren. ``I would like them to grow up to be people who care
about others, respect others and are responsible, happy citizens
who love America.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tall order, and impossible to wrap.
</P>
<P>
   But _ like a mother's love _ the price is right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
