<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVEST DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Offerings Online? Better Get in Line
</P>
<P>
   Investors who signed up with online brokerages to get access to
potentially lucrative initial public offerings of stocks are
instead getting a lesson in the laws of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Andrew D. Klein, founder of the fast-growing Wit
Capital, an on-line brokerage firm in New York, sent a message to
the company's 41,000 customers, pointedly asking them to stop
calling to inquire about the status of newly offered shares they
might be seeking to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate that many of you are frustrated by the fact that
you have not received allocations in our IPOs,'' the message said.
``As we have told you in the past, the demand in the market has
outstripped the supply.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Wit declined to comment, because the company has
entered the quiet period after the registration of its own initial
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, The Wall Street Journal reported, 500 customers
of Datek Online of Iselin, N.J., had their accounts credited with
shares from Goldman Sachs Group's much sought-after initial
offering on Tuesday, only to be told later that the shares did not
exist. The mistake was a result of a ``communications breakdown''
with Goldman, said Robert O. Bethge, chief marketing officer for
Datek.
</P>
<P>
   Bethge was philosophical. Now, he said, ``we know some of the
pitfalls.''
</P>
<P>
   401(k)s: MORE STOCKS, MORE OPTIONS, MORE ASSETS
</P>
<P>
   Investors in 401(k) and similar savings plans have been
contributing more to stocks and less to safer investments,
according to a new study by Spectrem Group of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Spectrem found that the retirement savers increased their
contribution allocations to equities to 75.7 percent by the end of
1998, from 64.4 percent in 1994. Allocations to bond funds
decreased slightly, to 7.2 percent from 8.5 percent, while those to
super-safe stable-value funds, which often offer low but consistent
returns, plummeted to 9.3 percent from 17.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The firm surveyed 2,000 households in July and August of last
year. It also found a growing number of investment options in
401(k) plans _ an average of 8.4 last year, versus 4.6 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by the surging stock market, the mean account balance
grew to $40,740 in 1998 from $31,700 in 1994. Just 34.4 percent of
those surveyed had balances of less than $10,000 in 1998, compared
with 38.9 percent in 1994. And 18.4 percent had accounts of
$100,000 or more, more than twice the 7.1 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW FUND MANAGER? DON'T WORRY, BE HAPPY
</P>
<P>
   Investors who bite their nails when a portfolio manager departs
a favorite mutual fund may well be fretting needlessly. A new study
by Value Line, the research firm, has found that funds with new
managers tend to go through a relatively brief, one-year period of
lagging performance vis-a-vis their peers, but then go on to beat
them over the three-year period after the change.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at two groups of new managers and compared
their returns with those of other managers with longer tenures.
</P>
<P>
   The managers in the first group started running their funds in
February 1998. They returned 1.65 percent, on average, for the 12
months through February 1999, versus 2.69 percent for the tenured
managers.
</P>
<P>
   The second group of new managers started two years earlier, in
February 1996. They returned 12.07 percent for the three years
through February 1999, compared with 9.52 percent for a peer group
of tenured managers, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups of new managers, as well as their peer groups of
old-timers, included equity and fixed-income fund managers. There
was a minimum of 60 fund managers in each group.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggested three factors in the initial
underperformance:
</P>
<P>
   _ New managers often take over sagging funds, and it may take a
while to sell underperforming securities.
</P>
<P>
   _ The time spent deciding how to turn around a fund may take
time away from the process of selecting securities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Returns may suffer as a new manager incurs the expenses of
selling off holdings.
</P>
<P>
   As for the better three-year performance of new managers, Omer
Mohammed, issue chief of the Value Line Mutual Fund Survey, which
published the study, attributed it to the skill of fund company
executives in hiring replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the aggregate, the fund families do a good job at replacing
these managers with ones that will outperform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
