<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY RELEASES DETAILS OF AMERICAN SOLDIERS' CAPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO closed its posts along the Macedonian border
after three American soldiers on routine patrols there were
ambushed and captured by Yugoslavs six weeks ago, the Army
commander of the soldiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. David Grange said Friday that NATO had kept the
observation posts open throughout March despite the attacks on the
U.S. Embassy in the Macedonian capital, Skopje, and the rising
tensions along the border. It only decided to close the posts after
the American soldiers were captured.
</P>
<P>
   During a briefing on the nearly completed military investigation
of the soldiers' monthlong captivity, Grange insisted that the
three soldiers were more than one mile inside Macedonia when they
were captured by Yugoslav troops on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs seemed surprised to run into the American team
that was patrolling an emergency extraction route, the general
said, but once they spied the Americans, at least 15 Yugoslav
soldiers, some hidden in haystacks, quickly surrounded the
soldiers' armored Humvee. Firing an array of weapons, including an
anti-tank rocket launcher, they disabled the Humvee's engine and
forced the three American soldiers to surrender without firing a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers, Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, Staff Sgt.
Andrew A. Ramirez and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, were then knocked to
the ground and beaten even though they had raised their hands in
surrender, Grange said in the fullest official account of the
soldiers' captivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were kicked repeatedly in the face, the head and other
parts of their body. They were tied up and hoods were placed over
their heads,'' Grange said. ``Several times they were threatened
with rifles pointed at their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   One soldier told investigators that his initial captors had said
they would cut off his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the U.S. Army's Europe headquarters in Heidelberg,
Germany, Grange told reporters that the three men then embarked on
a disjointed odyssey, moving from prison to prison until they
reached their final destination in or near Belgrade. They suffered
the worst treatment during their first week of captivity, including
four painful interrogations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were beaten, sometimes with batons,'' the general said.
``They were almost always hooded, forced to sleep in uncomfortable
positions on the floor, feet shackled, or in a chair. When they
moved from those positions, they were hit on their hands and feet.
Their hands were kept secured behind their backs, their arms
constantly going numb, except when allowed to eat, when their hands
were tied to the front.''
</P>
<P>
   While the men were beaten at every prison and were always kept
in isolation, the treatment improved as the days wore on.
</P>
<P>
   Once installed in a civilian prison in the Belgrade area, they
were supplied with clean Yugoslav uniforms and put in solitary
cells with water and a toilet, but there were still two shifts of
guards for the daily beatings, the general said. Nonetheless, Stone
``in a moment of happiness'' did write a letter that was read over
Serb television praising the few guards who showed him some
kindness, the general said.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers were released on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Since their initial capture, the Pentagon has denied Yugoslav
claims that the Americans were inside Serbia when the Yugoslav
soldiers captured them on March 3l.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, the leader of the three-man patrol, had radioed half of
the necessary coordinates confirming his group's whereabouts at the
moment of their capture, said Grange, who said he was unsure
whether Stone had used his satellite positioning device, or GPS, as
well as his maps to come up with his coordinates.
</P>
<P>
   But citing Stone's eight years of experience as a scout and his
familiarity with the rocky border terrain, the general said that
``if you took Stone's GPS and map away, he would have known where
he was. And I'm convinced of that because I've been out there with
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
