<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-BEHAR-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH BERNICE S. BEHAR: JOHN HANCOCK EMERGING GROWTH
FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of John Hancock Emerging Growth is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)  
 (Eds: The word (star) in the 2nd graf should be replaced with the
symbol)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Portfolio managers who limit themselves to small-capitalization
stocks face a recurring quandary: Their best performers grow into
mid- and large-cap stocks, forcing them to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice S. Behar, lead manager of the $650 million John Hancock
Emerging Growth fund, understands the problem _ and welcomes it.
``Our goal is to buy companies that graduate out of the fund, like
Starbucks and E(STAR)Trade,'' she said, referring to two previous
stock picks. (Actually, the fund still holds a small amount of
Starbucks shares.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behar succeeds by finding stocks that benefit from economic,
demographic or industry trends like outsourcing and Internet
growth. ``The linchpin for us is finding companies that are
exploiting a change,'' she said from her Boston office, overlooking
the Charles River. &UR;  &LR;  In a period when many small-company stock
funds have struggled, Emerging Growth has turned in a solid
performance. It returned 12.8 percent, annualized, for the three
years ended April 30, versus 5.6 percent for the average small
growth fund, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher. And for the 12 months ended April 30, the fund returned
5.9 percent, versus a loss of 4.9 percent for the peer group.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behar, 38, came to money management via Tokyo, where she
studied at the International Christian University. Her fluency in
Japanese helped lead to a job at Sanyo Securities America in New
York, as an analyst focusing on Japanese stocks. She moved to
Boston in 1990 to work as an analyst on John Hancock's Pacific
Basin fund, and soon began focusing on small-cap U.S. stocks in a
variety of positions.
</P>
<P>
   She looks for companies with revenue and earnings growth of at
least 20 percent a year. But she said she shuns using computer
screens to find them: ``We take a bottom-up, analytic approach,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behar personally covers retail, consumer-product and
business-services stocks. One other manager focuses on technology,
another on health care, and a third on media, entertainment and
education. Their industry expertise helps pinpoint companies that
offer both outstanding growth potential and top-flight executives. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Management takes on a heightened importance in small
companies,'' she said, ``because they need not only a vision of
where their market is but how the company will grow to serve the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behar considers unloading stocks that lag behind the Russell
2000 Growth index or their industry groups for a year from the time
they are bought.
</P>
<P>
   Small-cap growth stocks, of course, are an especially risky lot.
``These stocks can be quite volatile because of the lack of
liquidity,'' she said, ``and the companies themselves are volatile
because they're in their early stages of development.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversification helps to lower the fund's risks. The fund owns
180 companies, each accounting for just 0.4 percent to 1.4 percent
of assets.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Behar doesn't buy the tiniest companies _ or stocks with
little liquidity. She looks for those with market capitalizations
of at least $100 million and a 10-day average trading volume of at
least 100,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   In February, she bought shares of Pacific Sunwear of California,
a retailer with 350 stores nationwide, for $27.54 a share. The
company sells casual clothing for teen-age boys, a fast-growing
group, Ms. Behar said. She said the company's management is adept
in a fickle business, shifting rapidly as fashion trends change.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Anaheim, Calif., is introducing a line of
clothes geared toward older customers _ in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   She expects Pacific Sunwear to earn $1.50 a share this year, and
she sees annualized earnings growth of 30 percent over the next
three years. The stock closed on Friday at $34.125.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Getty Images of Seattle, which provides
images to advertising companies, magazines and newspapers and which
last week agreed to buy Art.com, a Chicago-based seller of art
images, for up to $202 million in cash and stock. Getty has a
library of 30 million images; customers use them in lieu of hiring
photographers. Getty recently signed an agreement with Amazon.com
to supply photographs for that company's on-line greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behar first bought Getty Images shares in March 1998 at
$19.29 each. She expects the company, which lost $36.4 million last
year, to post a 28 percent increase in after-tax cash flow in 1999
and to become profitable in 2001. The stock closed on Friday at
$27.875.
</P>
<P>
   A third holding is Exodus Communications of Santa Clara, Calif.,
a company that develops and maintains Web sites. Clients include
Yahoo, Ebay and Lycos. One positive for the stock, of course, is
the growth of the Internet, she said, ``but it's also an
outsourcing play because it costs companies six times as much to
develop and run their Web site themselves than to have Exodus do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund first bought Exodus stock in March 1998, at $15. The
company lost $66.4 million in 1998, but she figures that its gross
revenues will grow 70 percent a year, on average, over the next two
years, and that it will be profitable by the fourth quarter of
2000. The stock closed on Friday at $80.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
