<SLUG> BC-VICTORIA-SEWAGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIA OFFICIALS DEFEND DUMPING RAW SEWAGE INTO STRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, B.C. _ Despite protests from the United States and a
lawsuit filed by a labor union and environmental group,
Victoria-area officials continue to dump of millions of gallons of
untreated sewage into the Strait of Juan de Fuca, saying the
environmental impact is ``minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report released this week, the Capital Regional District,
an umbrella organization of local governments, said: ``Water
quality at beaches in the vicinity of the outfalls is not adversely
affected by the two outfalls.''
</P>
<P>
   Sewage discharges average more than 20 million gallons a day
from the two release points.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued on the eve of a meeting of U.S. and Canadian
mayors, failed to quell calls for the British Columbia capital to
treat its effluent before discharging it into the international
waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to do something,'' Seattle Mayor Paul
Schell, a co-convenor of the Cascadia Mayors Association, said at
the meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham Mayor Mark Asmundson, whose city just south of the
Canadian border spent $45 million to build a secondary sewage
treatment plant, added: ``Tourism is the big deal here. Tourism is
the economic engine. I would think their attention to this
particular environmental issue would be higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost estimates for treating Victoria's sewage have ranged from
$90 million to $600 million (Canadian), and neither the provincial
nor Canadian federal governments have shown any eagerness to pay
much of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   David Anderson, Canada's minister of fisheries and Victoria's
member of parliament, argued in a recent interview that cold,
fast-moving waters of the Strait of Juan de Fuca effectively
disperse and oxygenate the sewage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sewage is treated naturally,'' Anderson said. ``Within
meters of the discharge outfalls, you have sailboarders. Within 400
meters, the sewage is barely detectable. It is one of the few
places in the world where this occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1983, however, the fisheries ministry has closed
down shellfish harvesting in waters near the discharge outfalls in
Victoria and nearby Esquimalt. The closure area now totalsmore
than 30 square miles of the Strait of Juan de Fuca.
</P>
<P>
   ``They discharge enough effluent to fill 50 Olympic-sized
swimming pools a day. ... How can they say there are no impacts?''
said John Werring, an attorney with the Sierra Legal Defense Fund.
Along with the United Fishermen and Allied Workers Union, the
environmental group has filed a lawsuit to halt the sewage dumping.
It is due to be heard in Victoria provincial court next month.
</P>
<P>
   The sewage dumping has prompted protests in the United States,
even a 1994 effort by some Seattle-area yacht owners to boycott the
annual Swiftsure race over the Memorial Day weekend. Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., and Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., asked the U.S. State
Department to take up the issue with Canada's federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Capital Regional District committed to acquiring a
site for a sewage treatment plant within three to five years. It
made a similar commitment in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But no land has been purchased. The provincial government has
ordered the regional district to find a treatment plant site, but
B.C. Environment Minister Cathy McGregor recently granted a
seven-month extension on plans. The Capital Regional District now
has until Dec. 31 to find a site.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the mayors' meeting, Victoria Mayor Bob Cross touted
his city's environment as its primary attraction. ``The
satisfaction with the environment and quality of life is perhaps
the most notable feature of Victoria,'' Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, asked about the sewage dumping, Cross took a
conciliatory approach. ``We can't stand still in today's world. We
have to move forward,'' he acknowledged. Cross predicted a site
will be found by year's end, and that sewage treatment in some form
will come within 5-10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Cross added that getting provincial or federal money ``is an
uphill battle ... the big question.''
</P>
<P>
   Former British Columbia Premier Mike Harcourt joked that
Victoria used to be derided as a staid town of ``the newly wed and
the nearly dead.'' But it is now one of Canada's fastest growing
metropolitan areas. British Columbia's capital city and its
surrounding suburbs have a population of more than 350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Noted Werring: ``We are talking about waste from a significant
number of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondary sewage treatment, a process adopted by U.S. cities
across the water from Victoria, involves construction of a
treatment plant. The plant holds ponds in which solids are settled.
The remaining liquid sewage is treated with micro-organisms which
remove objectional materials.
</P>
<P>
   With federal help, Vancouver-area governments are spending about
$196 million (Canadian) for a secondary treatment plant at Lulu
Island, on the Fraser River south of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria is looking at several other options, including simple
screening, in which sewage is chopped up. Another is sand filtering
of sewage, and another is treatment with chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Schell said he would do some quiet lobbying of Victoria-area
mayors to get moving on treatment. ``It is something that so
negatively impacts us,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cross seemed to acknowledge that years of delay are coming to an
end, but was not ready to predict what will be done and when. ``We
can't just do nothing,'' said Victoria's mayor. ``We have to start
planning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
