s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-THINK-JOURNAL-     05-07 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-THINK-JOURNAL-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE SALON'S OFFERING, SOME NEGATIVE REVIEWS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is one thing for investors to bet their money on an initial
public offering of an Internet company with a speculative but
potentially lucrative business model.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say next month's planned offering of Salon Internet
seems to go several steps further: asking investors to put money
into a flawed business model that happens to operate online.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Salon has operated as a Internet opinion magazine.
(Think The Village Voice without the classifieds.) Contributors
include Garrison Keillor and Camille Paglia. Yet analysts say that
the business falls short on a number of fronts _ and that they are
just plain confused about some numbers in the prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Salon said it had about 1.2 million Internet
visitors in March of this year, a healthy increase from 790,000 in
March 1998. The numbers sound impressive.
</P>
<P>
   But Media Metrix, a company that measures Web traffic, isn't
sure what the numbers refer to. It counted 521,000 Salon visitors
in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   According to Doug McFarland, senior vice president of Media
Metrix, Salon's larger traffic numbers may take international users
into account. But it is also likely, he said, that Salon, like many
other Internet companies, is counting the total number of server
hits that its sites receive, rather than individual users.
</P>
<P>
   Salon, based in San Francisco, declined to comment because the
company has entered the quiet period after the registration of its
offering. But on April 28, Kaitlin Quistgaard, an associate editor
at Salon, wrote an article on the site that took issue with Media
Metrix's methodology for measuring traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Another worry is Salon's short roster of paying users in its
Salon Member program, which furnishes members with e-mail and
discounts on Salon merchandise. It costs as little as $20 a year,
yet had only about 1,050 members as of March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salon doesn't present a compelling traffic story,'' said
Patrick Keane, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, a consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Salon is trying to attract more paying members. In March, it
bought the Well, a virtual community that at the time had 7,000
paying members, for an undisclosed amount. In early April, Salon
announced that it planned to add more news to its own site.
</P>
<P>
   But Neil Barsky, co-founder of the Midtown Research Group, which
tracks initial offerings, said Salon's ``huge'' amount of content,
and its move to provide more news, makes for a high-cost business
model.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of advertising raises a flag, too. During the nine
months ended Dec. 31, so-called barter transactions, in which it
swaps free ads with other companies, accounted for $307,000, or 15
percent, of Salon's $2.1 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The offering is expected to be priced at $10.50 to $13.50 a
share. With 10.73 million shares outstanding, that would give Salon
a market value of $113 million to $145 million. The company, which
will officially change its name to Salon.com, plans to sell 2.5
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Internet companies, Salon loses money. But analysts
are concerned that its expenses are so much greater than revenue.
For the nine months ended Dec. 31, Salon lost $4.3 million on
revenue of $2.1 million, versus a loss of $2.9 million on revenue
of $689,000 for the comparable 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many investors want quick profits on new Internet
stocks, selling them shortly after the offerings. But Salon is
going public via an online process introduced recently by W.R.
Hambrecht &AMP; Co., a San Francisco brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht conducts so-called Dutch auctions, in which the price
is set at the highest possible level that allows all shares to be
sold. So Salon's stock probably won't get the initial pop in price
that many other Internet stocks have enjoyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
