<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COUPLE AMONG MISSING AFTER OKLAHOMA TORNADO 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ A missing British couple touring America in a
rented motor home are believed to have been swept up in the immense
tornado that tore through central Oklahoma this week, officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   John and Barbara Potton and 23-year-old Tram Bui of Seminole,
Okla., are the last three people known missing since the killer
tornado roared across Interstate 35 Monday evening during a rampage
that killed at least 41 other people, said Ray Blakeney, spokesman
for the state medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   The Pottons, whose hometown in England was withheld by the
medical examiner's office, called relatives there around 3 p.m.
Monday from somewhere in southern Oklahoma City, Blakeney said. The
couple, said to be in their 60s, have not been heard from since,
even though Tuesday was the birthday of John Potton's mother,
Blakeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Bui, her husband and two children sought shelter from the huge
tornado under an I-35 overpass in southern Oklahoma City, Blakeney
said.
</P>
<P>
   The husband led the children up under the roadway and the mother
trailed, struggling against driving rain and wind, witnesses told
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father laid down on top of his two children and I think
another gentleman was trying to hold on to her, from what was
reported,'' Blakeney said. ``When the storm was over she was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakeney refused to release Bui's husband's name or details
about her two children.
</P>
<P>
   Although the list of those reported missing was cut to three
from more than 100 on Wednesday, specially trained dogs brought in
by federal officials from Nebraska, New Mexico, Missouri and
Washington state continued Friday to search areas of Moore, one of
the suburbs in which hundreds of homes were blasted apart.
</P>
<P>
   While local police used dogs to search all damaged areas earlier
in the week, the dogs brought in by Federal Emergency Management
Agency officials Thursday are capable of searching wreckage off
their leashes, following hand and arm signals from their handlers
standing many yards away.
</P>
<P>
   The dog searches were expected to end Saturday and cleanup and
recovery efforts were to begin in earnest over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA should have three service centers opened in Oklahoma City,
Midwest City and Del City by early next week, said Jeff Chalmers,
of the Oklahoma Department of Civil Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   A mobile service center in which people can seek federal aid
also will be working in stricken areas, Chalmers said.
</P>
<P>
   In Midwest City, dozens of volunteers turned out to help begin
cleanup Friday, Fire Chief Mike Bower said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually starting to get back to normal a little bit,''
Bower said. ``The streets are open.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 Midwest City homes were destroyed and more than
600 were damaged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five hotels and several apartment complexes also fell victim to
the tornado in Midwest City, Bower said.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Chief Medical Examiner Dr. Fred Jordan said all but one
of the 41 bodies of tornado victims had been turned over to
families by late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Teams from the medical examiner's office and police using dogs
have searched intensively in the area where Bui disappeared and
found no trace of her body, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have searched for signs of the Pottons' motor home by
air and on the ground, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeney said helicopter searches for the Pottons and Bui would
be suspended for security reasons during President Clinton's visit
to the disaster area Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeney said every damaged vehicle that has been found has been
searched.
</P>
<P>
   Police began to open more of the damaged areas in Moore, Midwest
City, Del City and other areas to residents and property owners on
Friday
</P>
<P>
   ``Bit by bit, we're shrinking the restricted areas but we're
limiting access only to those people who live there and people who
are working for them,'' said Oklahoma City police Capt. Charles
Allen. ``But many areas are still without power, many are still
dangerous because we have a lot of rubble and unsafe conditions.
</P>
<P>
   County health officials have conducted health inspections at Red
Cross, church and other shelters serving meals to storm victims.
All water systems in the county have been approved for drinking
water as well, health officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
