<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER ISSUES DENIAL FOR LOS ALAMOS SCIENTIST ACCUSED OF SPYING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.M.)  (rk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The lawyer for Wen Ho Lee, a scientist fired from
his job at Los Alamos National Laboratory for violations of
security rules, has issued his first detailed denial of allegations
that his client spied for China.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, issued on Thursday by Los Angeles lawyer Mark
Holscher, says that Lee has never handed over secret information to
China, and that Lee and his wife have helped the FBI in other
counterintelligence matters.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a Taiwan-born scientist who worked at Los Alamos for more
than 20 years, has been the focus of the FBI's investigation into
China's suspected theft of American nuclear secrets from Los Alamos
for nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee was fired on March 8, he has not been charged with
any crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Wen Ho Lee is a loyal American, and has always fully
cooperated with the government's investigation,'' the statement
said. ``He has submitted to four interviews with government
representatives regarding his activities during this period and
continues to cooperate with the U.S. attorney's office for the
district of New Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-page statement provides new details about the
relationship between the FBI and the Lees.
</P>
<P>
   Lee first came to the FBI's attention in 1982, after he
telephoned a scientist who had been fired from Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory in California and who was under suspicion of
giving China neutron bomb secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The phone call was intercepted by the FBI, prompting an
investigation and a polygraph of Lee. Lee proved deceptive on the
first polygraph, conducted in 1984, but was given a chance by the
FBI to retake the test and passed the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Holscher's statement said Lee then agreed to an FBI request to
fly to Lawrence Livermore to meet with the scientist as part of
that investigation, code-named ``Tiger Trap'' by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Lee received instructions from the FBI before the meeting,
met with the scientist and then briefed the FBI after this
meeting,'' Holscher's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Lee, Lee's wife and formerly a secretary at Los Alamos,
also provided information to the FBI. She told the FBI about
Chinese scientists visiting Los Alamos, and traveled to China with
her husband in 1986 at the FBI's request, obtaining background
information on Chinese scientists for the bureau, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In helping the FBI, Mrs. Lee put herself and her husband at
risk, with no possible benefit to herself or her husband,''
Holscher wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He also stated that ``it simply defies logic for critics to now
allege that Dr. Lee was engaged in improper activities in mainland
China while he and his wife were there.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 1988 trip to China with her husband, Mrs. Lee wrote a
report for the FBI, and allowed an FBI agent to monitor her
communications with Chinese scientists in her role as Los Alamos'
liaison with Chinese visitors, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Holscher also disputed reports concerning assertions that Lee
improperly transferred huge amounts of secret nuclear weapons data
from a classified computer into an unclassified system. Officials
have said that those files were then accessed by someone from the
unclassified system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Press reports incorrectly state that Dr. Lee mishandled his
Los Alamos Laboratory computer files,'' Holscher wrote. ``Dr. Lee
has never given classified computer files to any unauthorized
person. In fact, Dr. Lee took substantial steps to protect his
computer files, and we are confident that federal investigators
will also conclude that no third party could have or did access his
protected files.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee and his wife plan to continue to live in New Mexico near the
lab where they once worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Lee will not be a scapegoat for alleged security problems
at our country's nuclear laboratories,'' the statement said. ``Nor
should he be used to further the political agendas of those who are
illegally leaking confidential information concerning the details
of the government's investigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
