<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: TALKS ON FALKLANDS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina and Britain will hold talks this month to discuss the
possibility of reintroducing commercial flights between Argentina
and the Falkland Islands for the first time since the 1982 Falkland
War. The islands have been cut off from the rest of South America
since March, when Chile halted flights between Punta Arenas and the
Falklands in protest at the arrest in London of Gen. Augusto
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Clifford Krauss
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS FREE 7 FROM PLANE
</P>
<P>
   The leftist guerrilla group that hijacked a domestic flight
April 12 released seven passengers, leaving 25, including an
American, still being held in a jungle encampment. The National
Liberation Army said it was freeing the hostages in an effort to
advance propects for peace in Colombia. They acted after President
Andres Pastrana refused to create a demilitarized zone and cede
control of it to the rebels in return for the release of all the
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rother'
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: CITIZENSHIP LAW PASSES
</P>
<P>
   The Bundestag approved a law making it easier for Germany's 7
million foreigners to acquire citizenship. Children of non-German
parents will have the right to citizenship, but must decide before
they reach 23 if they want to be German or take their parents'
nationality. Foreigners will be eligible for citizenship after
eight years. The law will now go to the upper house, where approval
is expected May 21.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Roger Cohen
</P>
</TEXT>
