<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLY-MURDER08-COX     05-07 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLY-MURDER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen faces life in prison for bus-stop beating
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A high school sophomore from Cherokee County was
convicted of felony murder and other charges Friday evening in the
bus-stop beating of a 13-year-old neighbor seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Miller, 15, sat stone-faced when the jury foreman stood
up and announced the convictions. He showed no emotion until one of
his lawyers clasped his shoulder, looked him in the eye and said
something to try to comfort him. He began to cry just before a
sheriff's deputy led him away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, Jon!'' a relative said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, too!'' he said through tears.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction brings an automatic life sentence in prison. He
would be eligible for parole 14 years into the life sentence under
current guidelines, but Superior Court Judge C. Michael Roach also
must impose a sentence for Miller's convictions on charges of
aggravated battery and aggravated assault, felonies that each carry
a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison. A formal sentencing date
has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was convicted in the Nov. 2 beating of Josh Belluardo, an
eighth-grader who was hit in the back of the head after he stepped
off his school bus at the end of a six-house cul-de-sac where he
and Miller lived. The blow caused a microscopic tear in an artery
at the base of Josh's skull, but the cut was big enough to let
blood seep onto his brain. He fell to the ground and was brain-dead
within 60 seconds, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Josh lingered in a coma for two days before his family made the
agonizing decision to take him off life support. A medical examiner
testified that it is ``exceedingly unusual'' for a single blow to
the back of the head to kill someone.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses described Miller as a bully, and the killing led state
lawmakers to pass an anti-bullying law that was signed by Gov. Roy
Barnes about two weeks ago. Friends of Miller's family said he was
a typical 15-year-old who was trying to become an Eagle Scout.
</P>
<P>
   After six hours of deliberations, jurors filed into the
courtroom at 6:35 p.m. to announce their verdict. Miller's mother,
Robin Miller, began to cry. She rested her head on the shoulder of
her other teen-age son as Roach asked each of the seven men and
five women of the jury to stand up and verify their verdict.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end of the same wooden bench, Josh's mother,
Vickie Belluardo, leaned into her husband, John, and cried quietly.
Moments later, they passed a bank of television cameras and
reporters outside the courtroom. They declined to talk with
reporters, but their pastor, the Rev. Scott Miller, said they were
relieved that the trial had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day,'' he said. ``We're glad this day is over and
just hope everybody keeps us in our prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also declined to comment following the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Harvey, one of three attorneys who represented Miller,
said he plans to appeal to the Georgia Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a very sad state of affairs when a 15-year-old
boy is charged'' after what otherwise would have been a relatively
minor confrontation between teen-agers, Harvey said. He admitted
during the three-day trial that Miller hit Josh from behind but
said his actions do not justify a sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will come out a lot worse than he came in,'' Harvey said.
``Society will have made him into something else.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the killing of 15 people at a high school in suburban
Denver last month and the rash of copycat threats of violence
across the United States created a climate that deprived Miller of
a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Miller has been unusual from the start, and it
took another twist Friday afternoon when word of an approaching
tornado sent jurors to the ground level of the Cherokee County
Courthouse. They continued deliberations as warning sirens wailed
outside.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments Friday morning, prosecutor Rachelle
Carnesale urged the jury to pay attention to evidence. She said the
evidence proved that Miller taunted Josh on the bus and then rushed
him front behind and ``smashed'' Josh in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to send a message with your verdict in this
case,'' she said. ``You need to think about what you're telling the
children of this community with this verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carnesale described the attack that left Josh gasping for
air, face-down in the grass of a neighbor's yard, Josh's mother put
her arm around her daughter. Robin Miller dabbed her eye with a
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ambush. It is an attack,'' the prosecutor said.
``It was planned out loud and executed in front of a bus load of
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   She told jurors to dismiss any sympathy they might have for
Miller because he is 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He meant to hurt Josh, to beat the hell out of him,''
Carnesale said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she turned toward Miller and glared at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Mr. Miller, I guess you did beat the hell out of him,
didn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   David Wolfe, another of Miller's attorneys, argued that the
attack justified a misdemeanor charge of assault, battery or
reckless conduct. State law says someone who commits a misdemeanor
that leads to a death is guilty of involuntary manslaughter,
punishable by one to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was convicted under the state's felony-murder law, which
says that someone who commits a felony that causes a death can be
found guilty of murder. It does not matter whether that person
intended to kill anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe told jurors that prosecutors failed to prove that Miller
acted with the intent to commit ``serious bodily injury.'' They
must do that to support an aggravated battery charge. He also said
the state did not prove that Miller used his fists as ``a deadly
weapon,'' which they had to do to support the aggravated assault
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is Jonathan Miller is not guilty of felony murder''
because ``he's not guilty of aggravated battery and he's not guilty
of aggravated assault,'' Wolfe said. ``He's guilty of involuntary
manslaughter because, unfortunately, Josh died.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnesale clashed several times with Wolfe and Harvey during the
trial, which began Wednesday morning after more than six days of
jury selection. Defense attorneys raised nine objections during
Carnesale's 50-minute closing argument Friday. Carnesale asked
Superior Court Judge C. Michael Roach to ``rebuke'' Harvey and
order him to ``keep his mouth closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys said they objected because Carnesale made
improper arguments and tried to play on jurors' sympathy for Josh.
</P>
<P>
   Carnesale also tried to equate the tactics of the defense team
with that of their client. She told jurors that Miller's three
attorneys and two jury consultants had tried to ``sucker punch''
the jury by trying to get them to focus on Miller's youth and
otherwise trying to divert attention from the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that you reap what you sow,'' she said. ``It's time
for Mr. Miller to reap the whirlwind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
