<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8900 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-3     05-07 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MOVING MEXICO'S COLA TO SHAKING ITS POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
Vicente Fox as the leading presidential candidate is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)  
 (af)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vicente Fox Quesada, the cowboy-boot manufacturer
and former Coca-Cola executive who has become the first
businessman-turned-politician to have a serious shot at the Mexican
presidency, smiles as reporters fire questions at him, some of them
not too friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he obstructing an alliance among opposition parties? Has
he stopped quarreling with a rival politician? Fox fields the
questions patiently, unruffled.
</P>
<P>
   But minutes later, when he sits for an interview in a nearby
cafe, the first query sets him on edge: ``Can you name some
business people who support you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I could give you a list,'' Fox responds, pensively.
``But probably they won't talk to you. In Mexico, anybody who
announces support for the opposition suffers government
reprisals.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is right about his supporters' desire for privacy. Now the
governor of the state of Guanajuato in central Mexico, he has been
campaigning nationwide for a year for the presidential nomination
of his National Action Party, or PAN, saying that if elected, he
will work closely with entrepreneurs to modernize Mexico's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say he is attracting more private-sector
support than any other opposition presidential candidate in this
century. Yet few of his business backers are willing to be
identified publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not alone in being skittish about announcing a
presidential choice; so are most of the wealthy entrepreneurs who
are long-time backers of the party in power, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   That is a dramatic shift in Mexican politics.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has won every presidential election since it was formed
in 1929. And before every vote during those 70 years, Mexico's
wealthiest entrepreneurs have spoken out in overwhelming numbers in
support of the PRI candidate. But so far this time, neutrality has
become fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months before the presidential balloting, all but a
handful of business executives refuse to be identified publicly
with any party; Mexican politics have become too unpredictable.
Despite Mexico's creeping transition toward more effective
democratic institutions, business success here often continues to
hinge on political considerations, like whom you know in government
and which candidate you supported in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, experts say, many wealthy Mexican businessmen
are hedging their bets, donating money both to Fox and to
politicians who may become the PRI's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the big money is supporting Fox,'' said Alfonso
Zarate Flores, who edits Carta Politica, a political newsletter
here. ``This time, there's no guarantee of a PRI victory, and
nobody wants to bet exclusively on a party that may not win. On the
other hand, money is pragmatic, and those with money are not going
to take unneeded risk with it. Supporting anybody other than the
PRI is still pretty much done in secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's nationwide campaign has helped him forge an early
advantage in opinion polls. He leads Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano,
the mayor of Mexico City, who is the likely candidate of the
leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   He also leads all potential PRI candidates, including the
interior minister, Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who is said to be
President Ernesto Zedillo's preferred choice.
</P>
<P>
   One wild card is the governor of Veracruz, Miguel Aleman
Velasco, whose ties to the PRI elite as the son of a former
president, helped him during a lengthy career as a broadcasting
executive. Were he to become the PRI's candidate, which is far from
certain, he could be expected to attract overwhelming
private-sector support, experts said, because some businessmen
believe he could be even more effective than Fox in controlling
powerful PRI hard-liners who oppose economic initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 elections are likely to provide stark choices for
Mexico's economic and business-related policies. The modernization
program pursued by Zedillo and his predecessor, Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, has stalled, with several privatization initiatives
floundering amid nationalistic opposition, and it is not clear how
vigorously the eventual PRI candidate will champion further change.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cardenas, who is also the son of a former
president, advocates increased state intervention in the economy;
he vowed recently to renegotiate the North American Free Trade
Agreement. Fox, in contrast, offers policies that are frankly
pro-business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Fox because he's a businessman who became a politician,
which is unusual here,'' said Carlos Rojas, president of AMROP
International, an executive search firm with offices in Mexico City
and Monterrey and one of a handful of Fox's business backers who
have acknowledged their support openly. ``My business doesn't
depend on the government. If it did, I wouldn't talk about
politics.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For decades, many successful businesses in Mexico depended on
executives' cozy, if not downright corrupt, relations with the
state. Successive PRI governments protected Mexican industries with
high tariffs, which from the 1940s through the early 1970s produced
spectacular growth, averaging about 7 percent annually, although
the country's famously low wages remained stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   Construction, broadcasting, real estate and transportation
businesses and other companies with PRI connections amassed
extraordinary fortunes, even under governments that often preached
an anti-capitalist gospel. But executives were expected to leave
politics to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business people accepted their apolitical role and tolerated
the government's revolutionary and anti-business rhetoric in
exchange for the guarantee of a profitable economic environment,''
wrote Kristin Johnson Ceva in a recently completed Stanford
University doctoral dissertation on Mexico's private sector. ``This
was not an alliance based on ideological principles, but a
pragmatic `Alliance for Profits.'''
</P>
<P>
   After 1970, however, relations between government and business
soured. President Luis Echeverria Alvarez adopted an openly
anti-business posture in the early '70s, and his successor, Jose
Lopez Portillo, nationalized the country's banks in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some entrepreneurs reacted by turning for the first time to
political activism, forming new organizations to protect their
interests, including the Business Coordinating Council, now
Mexico's main private-sector umbrella group.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs-turned-candidates like Manuel J. Clouthier, a
vegetable exporter who ran for president in 1988, and Ernesto
Ruffo, a fishing-company executive in Baja California who became
Mexico's first opposition governor in 1989, pioneered new political
roles for businessmen. Both ran as members of the PAN.
</P>
<P>
   Partly in reaction to the new business pressure, Presidents
Miguel de la Madrid and Salinas began adopting free-market
policies. Mexico entered the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
in 1986, reversing decades of protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   And after his 1988 inauguration, Salinas sold off state-owned
companies, reduced Mexico's regulatory burden and campaigned for
NAFTA. Since it took effect in 1994, NAFTA has spurred billions of
dollars of U.S. investment in Mexico, especially in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA, along with the peso devaluation and banking crisis that
opened Zedillo's administration in December 1994, also created a
sharp divide in Mexican business.
</P>
<P>
   The largest and wealthiest industrial groups, many of which
focus on exports and have access to foreign capital markets, have
benefited greatly from the treaty and the currency adjustment. Even
so, many of the wealthiest executives are dissatisfied with the
virtual collapse of Mexico's drive toward privatization and other
economic initiatives during the Zedillo administration.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of thousands of small and medium-sized businesses,
meanwhile, NAFTA has meant the painful end to protection from
foreign competition. The peso devaluation multiplied their debts,
and subsequent high interest rates cut off entrepreneurs and
consumers from financing, choking the expansion of the fledgling
middle class on which the domestic market had depended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the multimillionaires with government connections have
prospered,'' said Alejandro Gurza Obregon, who owns the Ford
dealership in Torreon, Coahuila, in northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Gurza, who says his dealership has been audited repeatedly over
the years because of his opposition views, said he would vote for
Fox ``because he's a brave man, brave enough to try to change
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurza's own dealership is still in the black, but he said some
300 of Mexico's 1,100 auto dealerships had gone bankrupt since
1994.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Mexico's presidential campaign gets under way,
entrepreneurs divide into two broad groups: the heads of large,
prosperous firms, who are impatient in their desire for further
change, and smaller business people, who are impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   Fox wants to galvanize the support of both groups. His own
career has given him roots in the two sides of Mexican capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating with a business degree from Mexico City's
Universidad Iberoamericana in 1964, he went to work for Coca-Cola
de Mexico. Over 15 years, he rose from route supervisor to chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the university, they taught me to reflect and to analyze,''
Fox said in the interview in the Mexico City cafe. ``But working at
Coca-Cola was my second university education. I learned that the
heart of a business is out in the field, not in the office. I
learned strategy, marketing, financial management, optimization of
resources. I learned not to accept anything but winning. I learned
an iron discipline for getting results.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Fox left Coke and moved his family from Mexico City to
the grimy industrial city of Leon in Guanajuato to help his
brothers manage his family's two footwear factories and 1,100-acre
vegetable ranch. During the next eight years, he experienced the
rigors of running a small business in an authoritarian state with a
chaotic economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, the Fox brothers used their own lands and
other assets as collateral, taking dollar-denominated loans from
Mexican banks to finance new wells for irrigation and, in 1984, the
construction of a plant to package their frozen broccoli,
cauliflower and other vegetables, Fox's brother Cristobal recalled
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad time to be in debt, especially in dollars. During
the presidency of de la Madrid, from 1982 to 1988, the Mexican peso
was devalued repeatedly, from 150 to the dollar to 2,900 to the
dollar. The Fox brothers managed to keep their businesses afloat,
partly because they began earning dollars by exporting their
vegetables. But they watched a dozen other Mexican packers go
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every micro, small and medium-sized entrepreneur in this
country is a hero for surviving, growing and exporting under these
circumstances,'' Fox said. ``I'm not embarrassed to say the
businesses of the Grupo Fox are still highly leveraged, because
that's the situation of all Mexican businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Fox and dozens of other beleaguered Mexican
entrepreneurs from regions north of Mexico City ran for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Fox announced his candidacy, government health
inspectors temporarily shut down the family packing plant because
employees lacked photo identification cards. Later, Social Security
officials audited the plant's books.
</P>
<P>
   Peasants _ stirred up by the PRI, Fox says _ invaded Fox family
lands, seizing property. (They were eventually evicted after an
agreement with authorities.) ``It was pure political harassment,''
Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the distractions, Fox was elected to Congress. He served
one term and then ran for governor of Guanajuato in 1991, losing an
election that was marred by fraud. He ran for governor again in
1995 and won a sweeping victory.
</P>
<P>
   Two years into his governorship, he started his bid for the
PAN's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He campaigns as a plain-talking, no-nonsense populist; some in
the PRI see him as a kind of Mexican Ross Perot, though he lacks
the Texas businessman's eccentricities. He promises political
change after 70 years of PRI rule, but his pro-business ideas are
central to his vision of a Fox administration: ``The private sector
will be completely integrated into the task of governing,'' he
said. ``There's going to be an intense, very intense relationship
with the country's entire productive sector, an absolute commitment
to serve and support entrepreneurs, shoulder to shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox doodled on a napkin as he outlined his economic ideas, which
closely resemble the broad programs drawn up by Mexico's main
business organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He promises a disciplined, orthodox economic program aimed at
eliminating fiscal deficits within three years, maintaining a
healthy trade balance and lowering Mexico's annual inflation rate,
which was 18.7 percent last year, to the level of the United States
economy, now less than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He also pledges to maintain a stable currency, saying he is
``studying'' proposals to link the peso to the dollar through a
currency board system like Argentina's, under which every peso in
circulation is backed by an American dollar in reserve. He is
opposed to abandoning the peso as the national currency.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Fox promises to share federal resources equitably with
states, to prompt regional development and to increase greatly
government spending on education.
</P>
<P>
   In a special effort to attract the support of small-business
people who have been cut off from credit by Mexican banks, Fox
promises ``reconstruction of the national financial system,'' so
that it can offer credit at reasonable interest rates to ``100
percent of Mexicans.''
</P>
<P>
   But he offers special treatment for Mexico's wealthiest
executives, too. There will be no vendetta, he says, against the
robber barons who have grown wealthy through corrupt ties to PRI
governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be strict in enforcing the law, and we won't
permit a single new dishonest act,'' he said. ``But every
democratic transition requires that a country look to the future.
The transition in Chile allowed Pinochet to stay. In Spain, those
who were with Franco's dictatorship were allowed to stay. We're not
going to waste time and energy pursuing vengeance for the
corruption of the past in some endless witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a year, about 40 of Mexico's richest entrepreneurs, members
of an invitation-only business group, the Mexican Council of
Businessmen, meet for a televised breakfast with the president at
the Mexican White House. Usually they ballyhoo their investment
plans and applaud politely as the president delivers an economic
pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's event was different. When it was his turn to
speak, Eugenio Clariond Reyes Retana, the president of Grupo IMSA,
an auto battery conglomerate and the council's current president,
delivered a blunt lecture to Zedillo about the virtues of linking
the peso to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Clariond's speech would have seemed routine. But in
Mexico, presidents have always enjoyed kinglike powers. They are
given applause, not advice, at least in public. Zedillo sat
stone-faced through Clariond's address, then rose to deliver a
defensive explanation of his administration's free-floating
exchange-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the president's face and it seemed to say, `That
wasn't to be today's theme,''' Clariond told reporters after the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts speculated later that Clariond's
extraordinary breach of protocol was a signal that he had joined
the PAN. He denied that in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a priista,'' Clariond said, using a familiar
term for members of the PRI. ``Despite all its errors, the PRI
still backs many concepts that will do the most to bring Mexico's
long-term development.''
</P>
<P>
   But the incident exemplified the increasingly independent path
taken by the men who have been the PRI's most generous backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest businessmen are losing their patience with the
slow pace of reform,'' said Rogelio Ramirez de la O, who runs a
Mexico City consulting firm called Economic Analysis for Company
Planning. ``The economy needs more deregulation, more
privatization, more reform than Zedillo has been able to deliver.
These men are saying, `What's wrong, why are we being stalled?' And
that's why they're hedging their bets with Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   No member of Clariond's council has publicly expressed support
for Fox, but political affiliations are nonetheless in flux. The
clearest sign has come in several statements of neutrality from men
long identified with the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Carlos Slim, the billionaire who presided over the
privatization of Telmex, the Mexican telephone company, and is
chairman of Grupo Carso, demonstrated his loyalty to the PRI before
the last presidential election by participating in a now-legendary
fund-raising banquet in which 30 magnates committed themselves to
donating $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Slim was asked if he supported any presidential
candidate. ``No, no, not me; I don't get involved in politics,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entrepreneur has to function in the nation, with the
nation, and for the nation, not with the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dramatic shift occurred recently in the family that
controls Televisa, the broadcasting conglomerate. During his three
decades of control, Emilio Azcarraga Milmo, the founder, offered
unconditional support to PRI candidates and policies on Televisa's
nightly newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same 1993 PRI fund-raiser attended by Slim, Azcarraga
offered a $50 million contribution. But when his son, Emilio
Azcarraga Jean, who took control at his father's death in 1997, was
asked by a Mexican reporter in March if Televisa ``would continue
being a soldier of the PRI,'' he replied, ``Televisa only supports
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Because political financing laws here are riddled with
loopholes, it is impossible to track how much money Mexico's
richest businessmen may be donating to Fox or other politicians
waging expensive national campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has voluntarily disclosed records showing that thousands of
small donors give him a few pesos each month. But 73 percent of the
$163,000 his main campaign committee reported receiving in March
came from unnamed donors in sums ranging from $2,100 to $53,000,
the records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting important support from entrepreneurs, people who
want a different Mexico,'' Fox said. But he added: ``Many of these
same businessmen are also probably supporting the PRI.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
