<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-07 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' SPREWELL AND CAMBY GET READY TO TAKE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The last two New York Knicks in the gymnasium
Friday were Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, both lingering in
the comfort and safety of home like naive freshmen before a week of
hazing.
</P>
<P>
   That was before they would be bumped, banged and baited for 48
minutes. Before they would be prodded and poked at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   There stood the fresh-faced Camby, whose view of the playoffs
had always been via satellite in Toronto. And the enigmatic
Sprewell, whose National Basketball Association playoff experience
had been limited to his Golden State Warriors team being swept in
three games five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Charles Oakley and John Starks _ who have a combined
18 years of playoff experience _ Camby and Sprewell will venture
into the hostile territory of a Knicks-Heat playoff series
beginning with Game 1 of the first-round matchup Saturday afternoon
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, it is impossible to understand the history
of hostility between the two teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll find out real quick,'' Chris Childs said Friday of his
two teammates at the Knicks' practice facility at SUNY-Purchase
just before the team departed for Miami. ``I think they've both had
a full season here in New York, and they know what to expect.
They're both mature men and I think they look forward to the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   It has already been a challenge for Sprewell and Camby to just
fit into the Knicks' way. More was expected out of the two players
when they were acquired before the season. They were supposed to
push the Knicks ahead of Indiana and Miami in the East and bring a
dash of color to the Knicks' bland style.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks wound up scraping for the eighth and final
playoff seeding, while Miami finished No. 1 in the East. But this
is no ordinary first-round pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a ride,'' Childs said. ``I'm going to enjoy
it. People have said it's going to be a boxing match, a rumble in
the jungle. It's hard to play body to body and not get into a
skirmish. But a cool head has to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Some even think the Knicks can prevail in this series. Although
the Knicks adamantly deny it, many of them privately wanted destiny
to make this matchup. The core players _ including Patrick Ewing,
Larry Johnson and Allan Houston _ have a history of digging up some
of their best efforts against a Heat team they know as well as
their own ATM codes. There are no secrets here.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks know their success begins with shadowing Tim
Hardaway, closing on the Heat's perimeter shooters, walking away
from conflict and luring Alonzo Mourning into foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Knicks knew they could count on Oakley clearing
a path for Ewing and would have faith that Starks could stop a Heat
run with a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Now what? Sprewell and Camby are the unknown quantities in this
series. Sprewell could be electric and inspiring, or he could shoot
2 for 17. Camby could rise up for heroic blocks in a pinch, or he
could become grounded on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   By now, both are used to being looked at with skeptical eyes.
Sprewell unexpectedly found himself as the sixth man and Camby was
left to work through his frustrations with his limited playing time
until he gained the trust of coach Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the question was being asked: Why did the Knicks trade
for them again?
</P>
<P>
   After hearing what ill fits they were for the Knicks all season,
Camby and Sprewell will have a chance to show they can adapt their
up-tempo habits to the grind-it-out half-court style the playoffs
usually reveal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just focused on what I have to do, not why I was brought
here,'' Sprewell said. ``I know there is a lot of animosity between
the two teams. You have to be aggressive but show poise, too. You
have to know when to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not like Sprewell to back off on the floor. That is not
his background. He is more comfortable running up and down in a
reckless race to the hoop. But in the playoffs, every possession is
critical, every careless mistake on defense is pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has been prone to launch quick 3-pointers in transition
and leave his man open on the perimeter for a 3-pointer. But as the
season has progressed, he has become a hair more disciplined in
both areas. Against the Heat, Sprewell will be asked to be more
patient and defend with more courage against a bulkier Jamal
Mashburn in the post.
</P>
<P>
   And if given the chance, a lot will be expected of Camby as
well. Not only will he have to be wary of Hardaway's penetrating
drives to the basket, he will have to shadow P.J. Brown and provide
help on Mourning. Offensively, Camby will try to sneak free and cut
to the basket for the kind of easy dunks he had in Miami two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping Jeff has enough confidence in me to go with me
during the playoffs,'' said Camby, who went from playing zero
minutes against the Heat in the 15th game of the season to 28
minutes with 15 points in the Knicks' wild 20-point comeback April
26. ``If not, I'll be fine. It doesn't matter if I play 5 or 35
minutes; I just want to get in there and have fun and play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens. From everything I've seen on TV, it's
been an intense and brutal rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Television is not reality. Saturday in Miami, that begins the
real test for Camby and Sprewell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
