 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas, Fla., Md.)  (af) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sip With a Straw and an Agenda &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drink my clean water, and help protect yours: Robert F. Kennedy
Jr., long an environmentalist, recently introduced Keeper Springs
mountain spring water. Influenced by Paul Newman's charitable
example, Kennedy pledges the profits to local water conservation
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people think of the environment, they think of global
issues like the ozone layer or the destruction of the rain
forest,'' he said. ``They don't think about their own backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   The water is already available in the New York area and will be
sold nationally next year. The suggested price is 89 cents for a
half-liter and $1.39 for 1.5 liters.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds will be used to protect water supplies where the
water is bought. Revenues from the Northeastern debut will go to
organizations like Riverkeeper, a conservation group in
Garrison-on-Hudson, N.Y., where Kennedy is a lawyer; the Long
Island Sound Keeper, and the New York Watershed.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy guarantees that Keeper Springs will be bottled in
Saratoga Springs, N.Y., in such a way that fish, especially
spawning fish, are not disturbed. _ DANA CANEDY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Road Not Taken &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leslie H. Wexner, chairman and chief executive of The Limited
Inc., knows a good deal when he sees one _ and, presumably, a bad
one, too. Last week, his board let him escape from one of the
latter, a deal that could have forced him to sell nearly one-third
of his Limited shares back at $25, half the current market price.
</P>
<P>
   Several Limited shareholders squawked, saying the company was
effectively transferring more than $400 million from their pockets
to Wexner's. Those pockets are already quite stuffed: Wexner's
holding of Limited stock alone is worth more than $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy flared when The Limited said last week that it
would buy 15 million shares from the public at $50 to $55 each,
replacing the plan that would have forced Wexner in 2006 to sell
almost a third of his 57 million shares for $25 each.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the company pay $50 now for the public's shares rather
than $25 later for his? Company executives said last week that
there is ``greater immediate tangible benefit'' for all
shareholders in the earlier purchase. Besides, they said, the
company has oodles of excess cash. Apparently that's a problem that
few shareholders _ other than Wexner, perhaps _ understand.
</P>
<P>
   _ EDWARD WYATT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What John D. Doesn't Tell John Q. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Orlando, Fla., divorce battle threatens to penetrate the
secrecy surrounding the history, size and substance of the fabled
fortune created by John D. Rockefeller. The case involves George
O'Neill Jr., John D.'s 48-year old great-great-grandson, and Amy
O'Neill, his wife of 10 years, who is 31.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. O'Neill's lawyer wants to make public documents involving
four trusts that O'Neill's great-grandfather (John D. Rockefeller
Jr.), grandmother and mother set up between 1934 and 1976.
O'Neill's lawyers are fiercely campaigning to keep the files
closed.
</P>
<P>
   The last time even sketchy information about the trusts became
public was when Nelson A. Rockefeller became vice president in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles Prather's deadline for a disclosure agreement came
and went on Thursday, but as of late Friday he was considered
almost certain to grant the lawyers' request for a one-week
extension. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do Those Coughs Sound Familiar? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So that's why the new Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance
Hall in Fort Worth looks so much like New York's Carnegie Hall,
horseshoe-shaped tiers and all. There, in a first-tier Carnegie
Hall box on a recent Sunday afternoon, sat Sid R. Bass, Perry's
oldest son, and his wife, Mercedes, for one of the Metropolitan
Opera Orchestra's sold-out concerts under James Levine.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Sid and Mercedes Bass, living in Fort Worth and
New York, are among Carnegie Hall's largest donors, with Mrs. Bass
serving on the board. Mercedes, in particular, was a
behind-the-scenes adviser on the design of the Fort Worth hall,
carried out by the architect David M. Schwarz and overseen by
Edward P. Bass, another Bass brother.
</P>
<P>
   Sid Bass, who can be impatient for people to get to the point,
listened to a Mozart symphony and then scooted out of his box
before the Mahler that followed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It Wasn't All About Winning &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The recent passing, at age 80, of Jerold C. Hoffberger, a
Baltimore businessman who once owned the Orioles, recalls a time
when some sports-team owners had loftier goals than building the
most luxurious sky boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Melvin Tuggle, president of Clergy United for the
Renewal of East Baltimore, said in an interview that Hoffberger
brought Frank Robinson to the team in 1966 in part to break down
the city's racial barriers. ``He believed sports could do that,''
Tuggle said.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson led the Orioles later that year to their first
World Series win, Mayor Theodore McKeldin ask for the repeal of the
local Jim Crow laws. He called it a ``distasteful irony'' that the
man who brought home the pennant couldn't enter a bar in downtown
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffberger sold the team in 1979 but tried to buy it back in
1988 with a syndicate with investors who would have been the
league's first black majority owners. The bid was rejected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ROY FURCHGOTT
</P>
</TEXT>
