<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, May 9,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CONTRACTS (Undated) _ A slew of recent events _ from the
panic at major labels over the distribution of music on the
Internet to the blood-letting following large music company mergers
_ has made it clear to musicians that the structure of major record
companies is not conducive to either their financial or, more
important, their artistic goals. Talking to everyone from
up-and-coming bands to those who have been signed for more than a
decade, from artists with low sales to superstars, from lawyers to
former executives, there is a growing dissatisfaction with a system
that has been building its fortress for more than 100 years _ since
a company called Columbia sprung up to challenge Thomas Edison's
exclusive distribution of prerecorded cylinders to be played on the
phonograph he invented. By Neil Strauss. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THREE-SEASONS-FILM (Undated) _ The Vietnamese film by Tony Bui,
``Three Seasons,'' opened in New York on April 30 and will open
nationwide on Friday. It is the first American feature film to
attempt a portrait of contemporary postwar Vietnam, poised on the
brink of modernity. ``Three Seasons,'' which landed a major
American star, (Harvey Keitel who has been known to be partial to
small, independent films), is an interweaving of three stories and
operates on several narrative levels: past and present, personal
and national, realistic and poetic. By Laura Winters. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH-FRANZ-THEATER (New York) _ Some people say there has
never been a Linda like that of Elizabeth Franz as Willy Loman's
wife in ``Death of a Salesman.'' The play's author is one of them.
Speaking of the actress's portrayal in the 50th-anniversary
production now on Broadway, Arthur Miller said, ``She has
discovered in the role the basic underlying powerful
protectiveness, which comes out as fury, and that in the past, in
every performance I know of, was simply washed out.'' By Dinitia
Smith. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ANNIE-REVIVAL-THEATER (subslug) (Undated) _ The story creaks,
the characters are stereotypes from another time, the theatrical
style doesn't work on modern audiences, but oh, that music. It is
as fresh as on the day it was born. Surely we're talking about ``La
Sonnambula'' or one of its bel canto opera pals, but what about
``Annie Get Your Gun,'' a musical pulled forcibly from the past and
now running strong at the Marquis Theater on Broadway? Vincenzo
Bellini and Irving Berlin have more things in common than you
think: not least, an infallible gift for melody. By Bernard
Holland. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTE-CARLO-BALLET (Undated) _ With its Mediterranean vistas and
posh casinos, the little principality of Monaco has reigned for
generations as a playground for the rich and famous. It's not all
fun and games, though, for Les Ballets de Monte Carlo, a local
troupe that spent 48 weeks rehearsing and performing last year. Led
by Jean-Christophe Maillot, an amiable young Frenchman with big
ambitions, this 14-year-old company is striving to reconcile its
loyalty to tradition with a passion for something new. It seems
fitting that the company will take up this theme when it opens a
weeklong season at City Center in Manhattan on Wednesday. By
Christopher Reardon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BEBE-MILLER-DANCE (New York) _ The choreographer Bebe Miller,
wearing baggy black pants and a simple black shirt, took a position
in front of the wall-length mirror. A compact woman with
dreadlocks, she faced front, then side, then back, and front again,
allowing herself to be scrutinized. Over a tape recording came her
mellow voice. ``Who is looking for gay men in the group?'' The
questions are aimed at her audiences. ``Who is counting the white
people?'' ``How important is it that these dancers work for a black
choreographer?'' The dancers remained lost in their own worlds
until a gentle rap by the Fugees started up. They then fell into
loose, silky movements. ``This section represents a party,'' Ms.
Miller reminded them. ``Don't be so serious.'' But this 60-minute
piece, ``Going to the Wall,'' which premiered at Dartmouth College
last year, is very serious. It will have its New York premiere on
Tuesday at the Joyce Theater, beginning a weeklong engagement, its
first in three years. By Valerie Gladstone. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCDUFFIE-MUSIC (Undated) _ A lot of musicians these days are
already starting international careers before they have completed
the early stages of professional development, so that they find
themselves putting their clothes on in public. Into such a world
suddenly comes Robert McDuffie, 40, a violinist fully and
impeccably dressed, ready to make his New York Philharmonic debut
on Thursday evening at Avery Fisher Hall after nearly two decades
of giving coconcerts. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   KOUSSEVITZKY-MUSIC (Undated) _ At a time when the New York
Philharmonic celebrates George Gershwin one season and Aaron
Copland the next, it is easy to forget that the groundbreaking
music of American composers once went unheard in concert halls.
Indeed, such scores were ultimately absorbed into the canon largely
through the efforts of one man, Serge Koussevitzky, the first major
maestro to make ``modern'' American music a priority. A double-bass
virtuoso born in Russia, Koussevitzky led the Boston Symphony
Orchestra from 1924 to 1949 and blazed a trail for innovative
American music by not only performing new scores but also
commissioning more. By David Mermelstein. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GILBERTO-GIL-MUSIC (Undated) _ Gilberto Gil, like Caetano
Veloso, Os Mutantes and Carlinhos Brown, comes from the Brazilian
state of Bahia. If the Brazilian-music fetishism of the moment
centers too heavily on that northern region (and especially on the
late 60s Tropicalia movement), it doesn't change the fact that
``Ensaio Geral,'' a 12-CD set of early work by Gil, is an
extraordinary document _ a tracking of a distinctly Bahian but also
fairly universal pop artist's growth and achievement. By Ben
Ratliff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ST-JOHN-CATHEDRAL-ART (New York) _ The history of the quarries
of Vinalhaven Island, Maine, and specifically, the erection of
eight monumental columns in the St. John the Divine Cathedral's
sanctuary, are the subject of an exhibition lining the cathedral's
photography wall. ``The Eight Columns of Worship: A Tribute to
Human Ingenuity and Faith,'' tells the story behind the buildings
that stand as a testament to the majesty and endurance of
Vinalhaven granite. By Kathryn Shattuck. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GLASGOW-ARCHITECTURE (Glasgow, Scotland) _ Glasgow, which was
named the United Kingdom's City of Architecure and Design for 1999,
is looking to the future as much as reveling in the past. Through
the end of the year, it is devoting itself to architecture and
design through a program called Glasgow 1999, a dizzying array of
more than 300 exhibits, building projects, competitions,
conferences, educational programs and special events. The $62.7
million program, though wide ranging, is placing particular
emphasis on the way architecture and design affect and shape
everyday life. The By Sarah Lyall. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARY-PHOTOGRAPHERS (Undated) _ At the turn of the century,
Hungary was the most photo-obsessed country in the world. Princes
and princesses of the Austro-Hungarian Empire frequented photo
exhibitions and proudly displayed their own prints. From a nation
the size of Indiana emerged many of the leading names of modern
photography, including Andre Kertesz, Brassai, Laszlo Moholy-Nagy
and Robert Capa. But four decades of Communist rule isolated
Hungarian photography from this artistic heritage, from the outside
world and from many of its subjects. Now, at the turn of a new
century, Hungarian photographers are struggling to rebuild that
tradition. A series of exhibitions of Hungarian photography is now
on view at the Hungarian Consulate in New York City. By Lyler
Rexer. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NAKASHIMA-FURNITURE-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ Like most collectors of
George Nakashima's furniture, Ms. Victoria Fiore, a former opera
singer who worked 15 years as a recepitionist for the furniture
designer, did not just buy a handful of pieces to use as design
accents; she filled her home with his work. Installing Nakashima
tables, chairs, cabinets, bedroom sets and more, she created a
total environment out of his elegant wood furniture, notable for
their angular bases topped with primitive slabs of wood displaying
grain patterns and naturally craggy edges. Last Sunday, the entire
collection _ save for the first stool Ms. Fiore bought _ was sold
for more than $170,000, roughly three times the presale estimate,
at David Rago Modern Auctions in Lambertville, N.J., one of the
primary auctioneers of Nakashima furniture. By Elizabeth Hayt.
(Moved).
</P>
