<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-INSURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG THOSE TORNADO SURVIVORS ARE THANKING: THE INSURANCE COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Snapping photos of her tornado-ravaged home on
Friday, Moore resident Kay Harrell tried to recall all the generous
folks who had come to her aid since she emerged from a neighbor's
cellar squinting at the devastation of Monday's tornado.
</P>
<P>
   There were the neighborhood church workers who staged prayer
services at her curb; there were her husband's co-workers, who gave
them shelter; there was the friend who gave her the only clothes
she has _ the jeans she's worn four consecutive days. ``I can't
even remember who gave them to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And her insurance company, State Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response of those people has just been wonderful. They've
cut us checks already. They had a generous check the very next
day.''
</P>
<P>
   For Harrell and hundreds of residents in the Oklahoma City area,
the catastrophe action squads sent by insurance companies were
among the first people at the scene comforting them. Instead of
bringing emotionally draining paperwork, they came with soothing
words and filled out checks on the spot. Many said the insurance
people were their first symbols of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the day after the twisters struck, more than 1,000
insurance agents began pouring into neighborhoods on foot and in
cars. Most skirted the usual red tape to offer advances on claim
payments and advice in starting the repair process.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency checks ranged from $1,000 to $30,000 to help with
food, fix-ups and temporary shelter. Some people had lost
everything, including identification papers, but still were cut
checks if they could simply provide their name and address for
database checks.
</P>
<P>
   Many agents spent hours simply comforting their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being extremely sensitive. Some of these people have
lost their mother's china or a wedding dress. I've said to our
adjusters, If you have to sit there and listen to them all day,
just do it,'' said Joyce Washington, market claims manager for
Allstate Insurance's national catastrophe team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our intent to have people deal with the real claims
process until they're ready. It's important to deal with them
emotionally first.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance firms are dealing with whopping numbers: State Farm,
Oklahoma's largest property insurer, expects 26,000 homeowners with
more than $100 million in claim losses. Allstate officials say they
hesitate to make any cost predictions right now but expect a huge
claim toll.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and other insurance managers said that because of the
widespread devastation, it will take two to three weeks in many
cases to get adjustors to the homes to begin the formal claim
processing.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm sent 10 mobile claims units to the disaster zone,
including one stationed at the central command center in Moore. The
catastrophe teams zoomed in from locations across the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, John Whitaker, a 30-year-old State Farm claims
worker, steered his green Plymouth into dozens of shambled Moore
neighborhoods just west of Interstate 35 and through National Guard
checkpoints, flashing his credentials and scanning porches for
policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you State Farm? What about you?'' Whitaker shouted from
his car window at Eastlake Estate residents, many of whom were
using lawn tools to rake blown-off pieces of their homes into
curbside garbage piles.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Whitaker has had more than five years experience
working disasters, he couldn't shake the television images of the
tornado bearing down on Oklahoma City. After it rumbled through, he
raced to get out and help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to get to our people; that's the most important
thing right now,'' he said. ``One of the problems we've got is that
there are so many people offering homes to the victims, we're
having trouble finding them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get to the people who have nothing. And even if
they're not with State Farm, we want to hook them up with their own
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastlake residents Harold and Laura Case, who hid in a stairwell
closet with their dog and children during the storm's fury, were
among the Eastlake residents whose homes escaped severe damage.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker was waving his checkbook, but the Cases resisted,
saying they wanted the people in more harrowing situations to have
the first crack at the money pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a lot more people who need this money,''
Laura Case said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Whitaker said he kept running into people who were
refusing the checks so others could be helped first.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are incredible, just incredible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In one house, Whitaker joked with a family whose home sustained
only minor damage. He was escorted around by an 8-year-old and when
he emerged from her room, he shouted: ``Great news! The Beanie
Babies weren't damaged at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore resident Mario Jaramillo, who works at Tinker Air Force
Base, lost his 8-month-old home. On Thursday, he was lugging what
personal possessions he could salvage from the ruins, namely
pictures of his son and furniture, then loading them into the back
of his truck.
</P>
<P>
   He commended Farmers Insurance for responding quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky,'' Jaramillo said. ``No one was hurt, and I had a
lot of help. My spirit is not broken. If I break my spirit, I might
as well get another life.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at Harrell's home, another State Farm representative, Sean
Mounger, tried to soothe her, gently patting her on the shoulder as
she snapped her photos to submit with her insurance claim.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell guessed that her property loss could easily reach
$200,000. The tornado leveled her home and threw her 1994 van 50
yards, where it lies upside down in the middle of a neighbor's
collapsed home.
</P>
<P>
   But she and her husband and stepchildren did escape with their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to rebuild despite all of this, right here,'' she
said. ``We'll never lose our memories. We'll build new memories. We
won't let this evil defeat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Allstate's Washington has managed team responses to several
hurricanes, floods and other disasters, but is continually amazed.
So far, her company has processed 2,500 claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always humbled by the damage,'' she said. ``I'm always
still challenged by the experience and what nature really does.
It's just so very humbling.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
