<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY THREE STILL MISSING AFTER TORNADO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The number of missing tornado victims dwindled
to three Friday: a frightened young woman who hid under a bridge
and a British couple who were ``touring America'' in a motor home.
</P>
<P>
   They are the last on a missing persons list that at one point
contained the names of 100 people feared hurt or killed when
tornadoes slammed into residential communities in and around
Oklahoma City on Monday, causing massive destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The others on the list have been found alive, many in emergency
shelters or hospitals or with friends and relatives, Medical
Examiner Fred Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said there is strong hope the last three will be found
safe. But, he said, ``we are quite concerned that those are
legitimately missing people.''
</P>
<P>
   The death toll Friday remained at 41, including three children:
two infant boys, ages 3 weeks and 4 months, and a 6-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to visit Oklahoma Saturday to
tour the hardest-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon news briefing Friday, the Oklahoma Medical
Examiner's Office identified the missing British couple as John and
Barbara Potton, believed to be in their 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said the Pottons ``were touring America in a motor
home.'' They were on Interstate 35 south of Oklahoma City, near the
town of Moore, when a monster tornado struck about 7 p.m. Monday,
tossing about vehicles, flattening homes and killing people.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 p.m. Monday, the Pottons had called relatives in Britain
to say they were in Oklahoma City. They have not been heard from
since, breaking a routine in which they had called home each day
they were on the road, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gentleman's mother's birthday was Tuesday, and they
(family members) still have not heard from them, which is very
unusual,'' the state medical examiner said.
</P>
<P>
   The third missing person was identified as Tram Bui, 23, of
Seminole, Okla. She and her family were traveling on I-35, also
south of Oklahoma City, when the tornado approached, said Ray
Blakeney, director of operations for the medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got out of their car and got underneath an underpass at
the time of the storm. After the storm passed, she could not be
found. She has not been seen since,'' Blakeney said.
</P>
<P>
   He said search efforts were beginning to slow as the number of
missing people drops. But, he said, ``we will certainly not quit
looking until we have zero on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents who lost everything in the tornadoes say they will
bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that I've talked to, they figure on rebuilding,''
said Clarence Frey, a retired farmer who lost his house in Mulhall,
a town of 200 about 45 miles north of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Frey said he and his neighbors do not care that officials
consider their community virtually a total loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who live here really like the little town,'' he said,
standing near the shambles of buildings. ``I love it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Janie Jeffrey said she feels lucky to be alive, and her home is
one of the few still upright in Mulhall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank's ruined. The churches have taken on big damage. The
grocery store is gone. So is the school,'' Jeffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a lot, but we're going to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 76 tornadoes touched down in 11 counties, cutting a
path of destruction that could come to more than $1 billion in
losses, officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   The storms destroyed more than 3,700 structures, many of them
homes, and severely damaged 500, according to the Oklahoma
Department of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   To help maintain order and assist victims, 969 guardsmen from
the Oklahoma National Guard and 127 troopers from the state highway
patrol were dispatched to the devastated areas, the emergency
management agency said. &QL; 
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
