<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BRITAIN'S QUIET REVOLUTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, May 8:
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere of civility and general good cheer, voters in
Scotland and Wales this week ratified a historic shift in the way
Britain is governed. The Scots voted for their first Parliament
since 1707, the Welsh for their first assembly ever. This decorous
revolution could have important consequences. Beyond its stated aim
of decentralizing authority throughout the United Kingdom, it could
invigorate Britain's politics and even its culture. Beyond that, it
could well provide a useful model for other European governments
that are seeking ways to give restive parts of their own countries
a measure of self-rule short of full independence.
</P>
<P>
   For Prime Minister Tony Blair, who had made self-governance a
major issue in his election campaign, the outcome was largely if
not entirely satisfactory. His Labor Party finished first in both
Scotland and Wales but failed to win outright control in either,
which means it will have to share power in a coalition arrangement.
Labor also suffered unexpected losses to the Conservatives in
municipal elections throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Scottish Nationalist Party, which favors
total independence, finished well short of the expectations it had
when campaigning began in earnest last summer. This outcome
appeared to vindicate Blair's gamble that he could neutralize
Scotland's radical separatists by offering a significant measure of
home rule. Independence was not a significant issue in Wales.
</P>
<P>
   The new Welsh assembly will have important administrative powers
but no authority to make laws. The Scottish Parliament, however,
will be able to write laws governing criminal and civil justice,
housing, health, education, transportation, the environment and
culture. The British Parliament will continue to control defense
and foreign policy, social security and fiscal and monetary policy,
although the Scots will be able to adjust tax rates at the margins.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had more in mind than merely keeping the separatists at
bay. He regards decentralization not only as a useful
administrative device but as a means to encourage different
regional identities. The Scots are fiercely attached to their own
civil institutions, which include a distinctive legal system and
schools and universities with their own curriculums. Scotland is a
proud place. Blair clearly hopes that by providing its citizens
with even greater control over their day-to-day affairs, he can
make it a happier and more productive place.
</P>
<P>
   Some British commentators have suggested that Scottish
devolution could help England as well. An editorial in The
Economist's current issue argues that England has long suffered
from the decline of its provincial cities and the ``unhealthy
concentration of political, cultural and economic power around
London and the South-East.''
</P>
<P>
   It notes approvingly the revival of confidence in cities like
Edinburgh and Cardiff _ a revival it links to the promise of
greater home rule _ and suggests that this could ``provide a model
for the revival of England's once-powerful provincial cities.''
That would suit Blair just fine. His long-range program for
decentralization envisages what will amount to regional governments
in the middle and north of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in France, Germany, Belgium, Italy and Spain have
also expressed keen interest in this week's British elections. All
are testing their own formulas to accommodate politically or
culturally diverse peoples within their own borders. Perhaps the
British example will provide inspiration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
