A8920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-07 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Up-for-grabs title enhances playoffs
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   So here are a few of the things we won't have:
</P>
<P>
   Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   So does that make the NBA playoffs better or worse?
</P>
<P>
   Neither, it says here. Just more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe less pretty. Maybe less ethereal. But definitely more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than reading like the script of Titanic, where everybody
knows the ending, the next seven weeks will have us turning the
pages as if reading a potboiler mystery to see how it all comes
out.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it. For all of his wonderful talent, penchant for
flamboyant acts and last-second heroics, as long as Michael Jordan
stayed around, the playoffs always were going to be a Gilligan's
Island marathon, where the rest of the league was a bunch of
castaways stuck in the middle of the ocean without a raft or a
paddle or hope.
</P>
<P>
   Line them up, and he knocked them down like milk bottles at a
carnival booth. Jazz, Sonics, Blazers, Suns and a leftover bunch of
Lakers that was the equivalent of the Pips without Gladys Knight.
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the trouble with the Jordan Dynasty. In all
those years since they started winning championships in 1991, the
Bulls never had a fierce, compelling rival who could test them,
stretch them, push them to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Questions abound
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls never were forced to a Game 7 in the NBA Finals and
only once _ last season by the Pacers _ in the Eastern Conference
finals. They never had to go through the Bird-Parish-McHale
Celtics, the Magic-Kareem-Worthy Lakers or the Dr.
J-Moses-Toney-Cheeks Sixers.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years when Hakeem Olajuwon was the stuff of which
Dreams are made and the Rockets might have been that
honest-to-goodness challenger, Jordan was off whiffing at
curveballs in baseball's minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Our bad luck. Maybe his good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Jordan is gone, and when the doors to the throne
room are thrown open today, the race will be a crowded
bumper-to-bumper affair straight out of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be NCAA-style, single-elimination March Madness. But it
likely will provide enough May Mayhem to keep us turning on our TV
sets for a reason other than to see what color overpriced sneakers
Air Jordan is modeling each day.
</P>
<P>
   Can Karl Malone and John Stockton finally drag the Jazz over the
last hurdle to a championship? And if they do, will club owner
Larry Miller get fined for cussing and trash-talking commissioner
David Stern during the trophy presentation?
</P>
<P>
   Can Tim Duncan carry off the Most Valuable Player trophy and a
title in just his second year in the league for the Spurs? And if
he does, will he have to stop along the road to the Finals to
administer the Heimlich maneuver to David Robinson and Sean
Elliott?
</P>
<P>
   Can the Trail Blazers use a deeper-than-Stephen Hawking 12-man
rotation to roll all the way to the top? And if they do, will
mainstream America know any of their names?
</P>
<P>
   Can Shaquille O'Neal at long last live up to the hype and
produce like the most physically dominating center of his time to
carry on the Lakers' tradition of titles? And if he does, will it
be because he stepped on teammate Kobe Bryant like a bug?
</P>
<P>
   Can Scottie Pippen win his seventh championship, Olajuwon his
third and Charles Barkley his first in carrying the Rockets? And if
they do, will they need wheelchairs and portable oxygen bottles to
ride in the victory parade?
</P>
<P>
   East has intrigue, too
</P>
<P>
   Can Reggie Miller sling in enough 3-point bombs from somewhere
outside Terre Haute to lift long-ignored Indiana to a crown? And if
he does, will driven, demanding, unsatisfied coach Larry Bird
promptly rip off his suit jacket at the final buzzer and beat him
at a game of H-O-R-S-E?
</P>
<P>
   Can Alonzo Mourning spit and hiss and snarl a path of glory for
the Heat to follow? And if he does, will Machiavellian coach Pat
Riley claim his persecuted team had to overcome a conspiracy among
the FBI, CIA and Miami Vice?
</P>
<P>
   These will be the all-comers playoffs, where the Sixers and
Bucks make their return after an eight-year absence, where Allen
Iverson will try to take every shot for Philly and George Karl will
take no prisoners in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons are back in, and that means Grant Hill gets another
chance to be the next-great-thing. The Kings are back, and that
means Chris Webber is finally happy, and White Chocolate (Jason
Williams) is everyone's favorite candy. The Knicks are back, and
that means a riot in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   We still like Utah and Indiana in the small-market matchup of
NBC's worst nightmare. But in truth, it's a horse race, a mad
sprint, as easy to figure out as picking numbers in the lottery. No
Bulls. No sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing we won't have: Slobbering Ahmad Rashad interviews
with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
