<HEADER>
A8924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CARE-NYT &LR;      05-07 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PAY THE LEGISLATORS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, May 8:
</P>
<P>
   Few New Yorkers are shedding tears for the state Legislature,
whose members have not been paid in more than a month. The
lawmakers have only themselves to blame. In order to get a pay
raise from $57,500 to $79,500 last December, they agreed to have
their paychecks withheld in each new fiscal year until they finally
passed a budget.
</P>
<P>
   The pay freeze, demanded by Gov. George Pataki as the price for
not vetoing the pay raise, has failed to work any magic. The
budget, which is supposed to be passed April 1, is late for the
15th year in a row. But the idea of withholding pay was bad in
principle and should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   No one would defend the sorry succession of budget impasses and
delays that have played havoc with state finances and the finances
of local governments dependent on state aid. But withholding the
pay of lawmakers, and not of the governor or any other statewide
elected officials, distorts the balance between the legislative and
executive branches.
</P>
<P>
   In any budgetary standoff the legislators will be under economic
pressure to cave, whereas the governor will not. Even though 14
Assembly Democrats who have challenged the pay freeze in a lawsuit
insist they would never vote for an unpalatable budget in order to
get paid, the whole purpose of the law was to coerce a budget
agreement. It is not acceptable for such pressure to fall unevenly
on the legislators, some of whom may face tight economic
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Democratic-controlled Assembly and
Republican-controlled Senate have passed their own versions of the
budget this year. Democrats favor more spending for education and
health programs than either Pataki or the Republicans in the
Legislature. The impasse is as deep as anyone in Albany can
remember, with some legislators fearing openly that the state might
limp along without a budget for a whole year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the stalemate has as much to do with political advantage
as principle, it is not easy to think of incentives to force a
meeting of the minds. The poisonous atmosphere in Albany in recent
years has aggravated these confrontations, and everyone has been
understandably searching for something, anything, that might force
a compromise. But freezing the lawmakers' pay is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Legislature could change the law to require that no
state operations can go forward without an overall budget. They
could tie passage of the budget to the issuing of new debt
obligations, a step that might force legislators to act. They could
take some of the acrimony out of the process by opening it up,
mandating committee hearings and conference committee meetings, or
setting up a nonpartisan panel to make spending and revenue
estimates. These steps would go a long way toward instilling a
sense of responsibility in Albany. Docking legislators' pay is the
wrong way to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
