<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-LONG08-COX     05-07 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-LONG08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran Long extends to bridge Hawks' gaps
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was the 1988-89 season, Miami's first as an NBA
franchise. The rookie Grant Long was in love with the town and with
being an NBA player. He was a guy from Romulus, Mich., who courted
and won over a woman named Nikki by plying her with burgers and
fries from the local Jack in the Box.
</P>
<P>
   He thought for a time he was going to be there forever. ``I fit
in that town,'' he said. But forever lasted six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Long, 33, won't get fooled again. Now with the Hawks, his
fourth NBA stop, the 11-year veteran knows his role, knows the
business of pro basketball and knows where he is wanted.
</P>
<P>
   He surely is wanted by the Hawks, who are counting on Long
throughout the playoffs beginning tonight at the Georgia Dome with
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we would have been without Grant this
season,'' Lenny Wilkens said. Maybe he simply doesn't want to think
about it.
</P>
<P>
   This is Long's second term with the Hawks, who shipped him to
the Pistons and brought him back after discovering he had the
qualities they were looking for all the time. The 6-foot-9 forward
isn't even a starter, unless the Hawks are short-handed. In this
abbreviated season, he was the last player added to the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he has become the essential man, the indispensable Hawk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say that. No one's indispensable,'' Long says. ``The
business doesn't allow that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, he is right. The Hawks could have played this season
without him. But they would not have won 31 games, maybe not even
25.
</P>
<P>
   The trail that brought Long back to the Hawks included a series
of events that altered the lives and careers of good players. The
team signed Alan Henderson to a $45 million contract because he
beat Christian Laettner out of a job. The irony is that the Hawks
had gotten rid of Long because they had acquired Laettner and
needed Dikembe Mutombo to play alongside him. Now, it was Long's
turn, and it paid off when Henderson missed a dozen games this
season and Long played in all 50, starting 13, averaging 9.8
points.
</P>
<P>
   By conservative count, Long had a major hand in a dozen Hawks
wins, either making the play that turned it around, or hitting the
actual shot or making the defensive stop that clinched it.
</P>
<P>
   Against Charlotte, it was a corner jumper; against Indiana, it
was a steal in one game, two free throws in another. Against
Houston, he started at power forward and produced 20 points and12
rebounds, blocking Scottie Pippen's three-point try late in a close
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have learned they can't afford to be without Long
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's important, very important to us,'' general manager Pete
Babcock says. ``Grant's a vital part of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   From last May, when he walked out of the final year of his
contract in Detroit, until the Hawks signed him Feb. 1, a week
after the lockout ended, Long was in limbo. A five-year Atlanta
resident, he knew he would play somewhere, that two years pining on
the bench in a Pistons uniform had neither robbed him of his skills
nor destroyed his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   To mark time, he watched his wife boldly buy her own business, a
company in Heath Springs, S.C., that manufactures children's
furniture and sells to upscale kids stores. She calls it Blessings.
The deal went through the day before the lockout started.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the idle time, Long allowed his wife to operate the
business. ``I wouldn't dream of interfering, because she knows what
she's doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Long is a stylish woman, a mother of four, a decorator
originally for her own amusement who later turned her talent into a
profit. And the Longs are a good fashion fit, she in diaphanous
whites, he in the occasional derby hat, tipping it with a cane.
Somehow he carries it off in the locker room. When he comes out
onto the court, his chiseled torso wrapped in Hawks red and white,
there is the sense of a Roman officer going into the field.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Steve Smith, who begged the Hawks to bring back his
teammate of six years _ four in Miami, two in Atlanta, said about
Long's sartorial bent: ``Grant carries it off. But it wouldn't
matter how he dressed, because, when the game starts, you know he's
bringing everything he's got. That's why I said we had to have him.
I was right, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was right, but not because Long is a great scorer or a
spectacular rebounder. Rather, Long is so mature in his thinking,
so dedicated, that he was voted captain of the Heat all six years
he played there.
</P>
<P>
   Long is proud of that. ``I was on a team with Rony Seikaly, Glen
Rice, and I was the guy they asked, `What do we do next?' I hit the
ground running and got that.''
</P>
<P>
   It came from his senior season at Eastern Michigan, when he
averaged 23 points and 12 rebounds and led his school to its first
NCAA Tournament appearance. It happened because Long understood
that he needed to help make his teammates better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lesson that year,'' he said. ``You can't win
anything without your teammates. And I've learned playing in this
league that, if you don't win a championship, you haven't done
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In his two otherwise-wasted years in Detroit, when he was nailed
to the bench by coach Doug Collins, he studied under guard Joe
Dumars, who will retire after these playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not comparing abilities when I tell you that Joe did for
me what a guy like Magic (Johnson) did for the Lakers,'' Long said.
``It goes on and on. It's not the numbers the superstars have in
those games but what they give everybody else, what Magic did for
the Lakers or what Larry Bird did for the Celtics. (Dumars) showed
me how to win, what you have to do, the discipline in the offseason
that you must bring to the next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Long is back to leading by example, even if he is not on
the court as long as some other Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I understand the sacrifices you have to make _ playing
when you're hurt, playing with intensity _ because if you don't
bring it to the next game and then the next game,'' he said, ``how
are you ever going to reach the championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game, every play, every rebound is important. Someone
wrote that Grant Long plays every game like it's the seventh game
of the championship. And for me, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
