<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PLAYOFF-PREVIEW08     05-07 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYOFF-PREVIEW08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's call to new order
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When last there was a championship not earmarked for
Michael Jordan, the Houston Rockets of the Western Conference
seized it and basked in the glow. The notion that their titles of
1994 and '95 were tainted because Jordan did not play full seasons
was poppycock to them. A ring is a ring is a ring.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in this first year of Jordan's retirement and of the
Chicago Bulls' descent _ and after a post-lockout season shortened
to 50 games per team _ the prize is there for the taking again. And
the sentiment remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put an asterisk on this title if you want,'' New York
Knicks center Patrick Ewing said. ``It's still a championship.
That's all I want. I wanted to beat Michael. But he ain't here now,
so you get it how you get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West, the opportunity is especially appetizing, for the
only champion from out there in the last decade, Houston, came when
Jordan was either absent or rusty. Like most years, the teams to
the left of the Mississippi River have the more flashy and
aesthetically pleasing styles, along with the big names.
</P>
<P>
   There are Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant on the talent-rich
Los Angeles Lakers. Karl Malone and John Stockon on seasoned Utah.
Tim Duncan and David Robinson of sizzling San Antonio. Hakeem
Olajuwon, Scottie Pippen and Charles Barkley on the grizzled
Rockets. And there is Portland, with a slew of quality parts.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the season's best three records belong to West
squads. But does any of that translate into a title?
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the thinking is the same as always: The slow-down,
defensive-oriented teams that flourish in a half-court game get
their hands raised at the end. That's what bolsters the hopes of
physical Miami and experienced Indiana and the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   On either side, the list of contenders is hardly exclusive.
``It's as wide open as it could be,'' Orlando Magic coach Chuck
Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, only six games separate the top-seeded Heat (33
wins) from the eighth-seeded Knicks (27). ``It's very equal, a lot
of parity from teams 1 through 8,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said. ``I
think anybody can beat anybody if you're not on top of your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird said: ``You take five or six teams,
they're so evenly matched, it's scary. It's whoever's playing best
that day is going to win.'' Riley sees one team out West that can
take control, but maybe not this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changing of the guard is maybe a year away. Maybe next
year, San Antonio could be the team for a long period of time, as
long as Robinson and Duncan stay together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one's been better than the Spurs, who won 31 of their last 36
games to wrest the league's best record from Portland and Utah.
Duncan's growth into an MVP candidate has been pivotal, but the
influence of free-agent swingman Mario Elie might be the biggest
factor.
</P>
<P>
   Elie brought championship experience from his days with the
Rockets and a toughness that the allegedly soft Spurs needed. ``We
had too much talent to play so passively as we did early in the
season,'' Elie said. And he told the other players just that,
challenging them _ particularly Robinson _ to be more physical and
more tough mentally. They responded.
</P>
<P>
   Another element adding to the unpredictability is that players
on low-seeded teams such as Allen Iverson of Philadelphia and Jason
Kidd of Phoenix have the skills to dominate a short series. And
upstarts Sacramento and Orlando have the talent to be trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Lakers, who have had the most eventful season
of all. They fired coach Del Harris, signed and shunned Dennis
Rodman, traded Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to Charlotte for Glen
Rice and dealt with discord between stars O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put it behind us,'' veteran guard Derek Harper said.
``We have the talent to be a dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Barkley of first-round opponent Houston said: ``It
depends which Lakers team shows up. If they have their heads on
straight, we'll have the toughest series of anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can speak more to the craziness of this NBA season than
Barkley's teammate, Pippen. The former Bull no longer has Jordan at
his side, and his new team, just like all the others, has no clear
path to the championship. So many of them are lacking in one area
or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly feels different this year,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the season sans Jordan, that's not enough to be
discounted.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
