</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER OVERCAME '84 GAFFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It reads like a chapter from ``Strange But
True Basketball Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange, what happened to Derek Harper in those five seconds.
Strange, how Derek Harper has been able to make us forget his
blunder in the 15 years since.
</P>
<P>
   It happened May 6, 1984, as the Lakers played the Dallas
Mavericks at Reunion Arena in Game 4 of the Western Conference
semifinal series. Harper was a 22-year-old Mavericks rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had blown an 11-point, fourth-quarter lead and were
tied at 108 after Mavericks center Pat Cummings drove for a layup
and drew a foul by Magic Johnson with 31 seconds left. Cummings
missed the free throw. Now you know more than Harper did at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Abdul-Jabbar missed a jump shot with :12 on the clock.
The Mavericks' Rolando Blackman rebounded. He threw the ball
upcourt to Dale Ellis. Ellis passed to Harper on the right side at
:05.
</P>
<P>
   Harper dribbled. And dribbled. And dribbled. Around in circles.
Trotting up and back. Smiling all the while.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking the Mavericks were ahead by a point, thinking that all
he had to do was dribble out the clock, thinking that Cummings had
MADE the free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Five seconds was a long time if you were one of 17,007 Dallas
fans, pleading, ``Shoot!'' Or if you were Blackman, screaming,
``Shoot!'' but drowned out by the crowd. Or if you were Mavericks
coach Dick Motta, wishing you could ``go out there and tackle
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The buzzer sounded and Blackman not so gently broke the news to
Harper. He'd dribbled away the upstart Mavericks' chance to tie the
series 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, Harper made the first jumper and followed up by
stealing a Michael Cooper pass, but the Lakers scored 10 points in
a row and won 122-115. They wrapped up the series two nights later
at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had lost his mind,'' Abdul-Jabbar said after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   One writer nominated Harper for the Bonehead Hall of Fame.
Another called it ``the biggest single mistake of the NBA season.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were kinder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake made (in) innocence and enthusiasm,'' Motta
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't have been in the game if it hadn't been for
him,'' Lakers coach Pat Riley said, referring to Harper's 14 points
in Game 4 and his clutch jumpers late in the Mavericks' Game 3
victory.
</P>
<P>
   At the rookie's locker, one Southern California writer grew so
morose in his effort to console Harper, ``eventually Harper was
consoling the writer,'' recalled Mitch Chortkoff, a Lakers beat
writer then.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Rambis played in that 1984 game, and when I asked him about
it Friday, the Lakers coach replied testily, ``Why are you bringing
that up now?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm bringing this up now, as Harper prepares for his first
postseason as a Laker, not because the incident has come to define
his career but precisely because it hasn't. The scatter-brained
rookie has turned into one of the wise old men of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great ballplayer, he's had a great career and he's been
a great leader for us,'' Rambis said. ``You make mistakes. If you
don't learn from them, then it's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Harper who called the players-only meeting in Vancouver
after the Lakers' third straight loss on Feb. 24. His ``look at
yourself in the mirror'' speech, the coaching change from Del
Harris to Rambis and the activation of Dennis Rodman preceded a
10-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   It was Harper who called the meeting that stretched to 2{ hours
after the Lakers' third straight loss on April 26. That airing of
the team's conflicts preceded the four-game winning streak the
Lakers will take into Sunday's playoff opener against the Houston
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contribution he's made is one of stability,'' said Derek
Fisher, the starter at point guard while Harper comes off the
bench. ``Being a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd love to believe the rookie mistake 15 years ago taught
Harper something that made him the man he is today. That would be
stretching the truth for the sake of a good story. Harper doesn't
stretch the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think so,'' he said, though he does say vaguely
that the experience ``helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think about it,'' Harper said good-naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that even if he'd taken the shot, there's no
guarantee he'd have made it. Anyway, the Mavericks had a chance to
win in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to rewind,'' Harper said. ``I think the worst
thing you can do in life is go back. You've got to move forward. I
don't think I'd be around now if I'd carried it with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is the most telling thing: Harper said people really
don't mention the incident to him all that often. He has made them
forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the clock is running down on Harper again. He's with his
fourth NBA franchise. He's 37. He's never played for a champion,
although he was part of the 1993-94 New York Knicks team that lost
Game 7 of the NBA Finals to the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   He signed with the Lakers during the lockout believing they'd
contend. It hasn't worked out as he expected, but they might be
peaking at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly feel we have a chance to win a championship,'' Harper
said in his voice-of-reason baritone.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an omen: The Rockets come to the Forum with an all-rookie
backcourt. Their names are Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley.
Otherwise known as innocence and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Check the clock. Maybe it's time for Derek Harper to get one
back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
