<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, MAY 8
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SCI-YOUNG-KILLERS-NYT (moved on Monday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 3,
about the hidden psychological problems of violent youths misstated
the affiliation of two experts who studied normal adolescents. The
researchers, Dr. Daniel Offer and Dr. Kenneth Howard, work at
Northwestern University, not the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-LYMPH-NODES-NYT (moved on Monday, Apr. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Apr. 19,
about a procedure to detect the spread of breast cancer misstated
the role of a dye and a radioactive isotope injected near the
tumor. They are used to identify the lymph nodes that should be
analyzed for cancer through a biopsy; the materials do not
themselves indicate whether the nodes are cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incorrectly to a major earlier advance
cited by Dr. Patrick Borgen as comparable in importance. It was
development of the lumpectomy, not breast reconstruction, as a
replacement for mastectomy.
</P>
</TEXT>
