<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8935 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-PLAYOFFS-TEX     05-07 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BULLS SPLINTERED, THERE'S AN OPEN ROAD TO THE NBA TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Further proof that one man's garbage is another man's gemstone,
this weekend 16 teams begin a seven-week playoff scramble to pick
up what Jerry Krause threw out _ the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we were all playing for the silver medal because
of Michael \RJordan\S and the Bulls,'' Atlanta Hawks guard Steve
Smith said. ``With them gone, I think a lot of teams can smell a
championship, and it's making us all hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause, the Bulls' vice president of operations, broke up the
team and voluntarily surrendered Chicago's NBA title stranglehold.
Because of that, plus the absence of the game's greatest player and
the lockout-induced irregular season that saw plodding play and
record-low scoring, critics say this season's champion will be
asterisked, if not altogether tainted. The participants, however,
promise one of the most fiercely competitive, exciting and
unpredictable postseasons in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there is an asterisk on the trophy,'' Utah Jazz owner
Larry Miller said, ``I promise it won't bother me if we finally win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the top-seeded San Antonio Spurs ride the Twin Tower power
of Tim Duncan and David Robinson in the West and the favored Miami
Heat count on Alonzo Mourning's inside presence and Tim Hardaway's
timely shooting in the East, every playoff team needs something
``One-derful'' _ the spectacular Jordan-like performance of one
player carrying his team to win a game, a series, or even a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where stars are born,'' Indiana Pacers guard Reggie
Miller said. ``Think of Michael's greatest moments, and most of
them were in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   All 16 teams have a go-to guy, from Kevin Garnett's versatility
in Minnesota, to Steve Smith's streaky scoring in Atlanta to Jason
Kidd's triple-doubles in Phoenix. The New York Knicks' Latrell
Sprewell, Milwaukee's Glenn Robinson, Orlando's Anfernee Hardaway
and Portland's Isaiah Rider have the potential to win a game with a
35-point outburst, but likely couldn't sustain the production
throughout a series. Los Angeles Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal
can't make clutch free throws, Houston's Hakeem Olajuwon is too
eager to pass out of passive double-teams, Detroit's Grant Hill is
often too unselfish and Sacramento's Chris Webber often too
disinterested to keep the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of players seem to have the talent and
temperament to single-handedly take their teams to the title.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the group is Philadelphia 76ers guard Allen Iverson, the
league's scoring champion and the most baffling player to stop
one-on-one. At only 6-foot, he combines an eye-blink crossover
dribble, unlimited shooting range, the courage to drive into the
lane and the creativity to get off a variety of shots against
taller defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a one-on-one tournament, my money would be on
him,'' teammate Matt Geiger said. ``I face him every day in
practice and I think I've blocked his shot maybe three times. He
can get off any shot he wants from almost anywhere on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ability to pour in 40 points every night _ and a
conscience to shoot enough to score that much _ but an
average-at-best supporting cast, it's unlikely Iverson can lead the
76ers to the title. The same can't be said for Duncan, who has
pushed Robinson aside, himself into MVP consideration and his team
into the favorite's role with a dizzying array of low-post moves,
soft hands and a demeanor that belies his 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're seeing a changing of the guard,'' Pacers coach
Larry Bird said of Duncan. ``In a couple of years, he'll be by far
the dominant player in this league. We'd all better beat him while
we still can.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Duncan has emerged on the scene, Miami's Alonzo
Mourning, Indiana's Miller and Utah's Karl Malone have always been
there. In the Jazz's intricate half-court sets, Malone uses his
muscle to forge ideal position, then a variety of power layups,
step-back jumpers, left-hand baby hooks and numerous free-throw
attempts to top 30 points consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, meanwhile, is still the league's most feared clutch
shooter and a deadly free-throw shooter in crunch time. If the
Pacers are ahead or behind by three points or less in the final
minute, it's guaranteed Miller will have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you just cross your fingers and hope he
misses,'' Magic coach Chuck Daly said. ``Because you know he's
going to find a way to get off a good shot. He's just got the knack
for drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning's game is more about termination than theatrics. His
relentless effort on defense has made him an legitimate MVP
candidate, while his ability to make intimidating dunks is second
only to O'Neal. His 10 rebounds and five blocks a night are a
given; his 20 points almost icing on Miami's cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no-nonsense,'' teammate Tim Hardaway said. ``When we need
a big bucket there's no question we look to 'Zo.''  &LR; tagtop:Richie
Whitt, (817) 390-7760  &LR; tagbottom:richie &LR; star-telegram.com
Douglas C. Pizac An array of jump shots and power moves to the
basket make the Jazz's Karl Malone one of the league's top scorers.
Michael Conroy When a game is on the line, Reggie Miller, right, of
the Pacers is considered the league's Mr. Clutch.
Mark J. Terrill The sheer power and dunking ability of Shaquille
O'Neal and a strong supporting cast make the Lakers one of the
playoff favorites.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
