<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CARE-NYT &LR;      05-07 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE NEED FOR CARE AS WELL AS PROFIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, May 8:
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the 1990s will be remembered as the decade
when developers and older, affluent, anxious Americans discovered
each other with enthusiasm, with results both encouraging and
worrisome. The concept that both they and Wall Street have embraced
is called assisted living. There is no common definition of it.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 50 states regulates it differently, and the federal
government not at all. But to older retirees who can pay to live in
the new and reconditioned spaces sprouting across the country, the
assisted living communities offer something irresistible. It is the
promise of Pleasantville, where they can live out their lives
gracefully, with hotel services, assistance when they need it, and
the chance to hold off or avoid what many of the aged most fear _
the nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   For developers, some with no experience in caring for the aged,
the attraction is clear. The number of old people of financial
means is growing. Some 6.5 million now need some help with the
chores of daily living. That figure is expected to double by 2020.
Ten years ago there was not even an industry trade group. Today the
Assisted Living Federation of America estimates there is a
kaleidoscopic collection of about 30,000 such facilities in the
United States, with a million old people living in them, almost all
of whom pay their own way.
</P>
<P>
   Some facilities fall into state licensing categories, and some
do not. Their average national monthly rate per person is $1,500,
but elegant two-bedroom units on Long Island may rent for $5,000 or
more. The National Investment Conference, a group that specializes
in the senior housing market, found in a survey of 73 assisted
living developments released this year that the median profit
margin was 29 percent. For a quarter of the properties, it was more
than 35 percent. Those numbers warm Wall Street, but do not
guarantee that the communities deliver high-quality services.
</P>
<P>
   Because the phenomenon has grown up around existing rules, many
kinds of places can advertise ``assisted living.'' A government
Accounting Office survey, performed at the request of the U.S.
Senate Special Committee on Aging, found that about half the
residents sign up without being sure what services the facilities
provide, how much they cost or what medical care the residents can
count on. A quarter of the places surveyed were cited for five or
more problems involving quality of care or resident protection
within two years.
</P>
<P>
   When Albert Fleischmann, 85, a St. Petersburg Yacht Club member
and retired owner of a hardware chain, moved into an assisted
living facility in Pinellas County, Florida, in 1997, his daughter
was reassured. Patricia Fleischmann Johnson heads a charity that
serves as guardian for 134 people in such places. But when
Fleischmann suffered a heart attack at his table in the dining room
this year, he was ignored. He called his daughter. She took him to
the hospital. She then called back to ask the facility how he was,
and was told _ as if he were there _ that he was ``fine.'' Because
Fleischmann likes the place, he is still there. But his daughter,
who testified before the Senate committee, is more concerned now,
and she is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   There are no pending bills in Congress, but 32 states are
expected to consider legislation this year to increase regulation
of the assisted living industry. They should do so. With so many
frail lives and so much money involved, this issue is not going
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTA-PROBE08-C     05-07 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-PROBE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House begins inquiry into Atlanta's bid
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A U.S. House subcommittee began an inquiry Thursday
into Atlanta's Olympic bid effort and is sending federal
investigators to review all records related to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee wants to know if the same kind of improprieties
that tarnished the Salt Lake City bid effort occurred during
Atlanta's campaign for the 1996 Olympics, according to a letter to
bid chairman Billy Payne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing would make me feel better than to know Atlanta has a
clean bill of health,'' Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.) said Thursday.
Upton is co-chairman of the House Committee on Commerce's
subcommittee on oversight and investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to use all means necessary to get to the bottom of
this one way or another,'' Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   Upton and Rep. Tom Bliley Jr. (R-Va.) said in the letter to
Payne that they are seeking information about gifts and payments to
members of the International Olympic Committee during the bid
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to begin to ascertain whether the regrettable events
surrounding the IOC's selection of Salt Lake City were an
aberration, or part of a broader practice associated with other
Olympic site selection bids,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee is trying to determine if the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act should extend to the IOC, which is undergoing massive
reforms because of the corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, chaired by Payne, said
Thursday it welcomed the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this represents an opportunity to have an objective
and legitimate review of how Atlanta won the Games without the
pressure of lawyers and the press,'' foundation spokesman Lee
Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said they are sending investigators to review all
1,400 boxes of documents related to the bid and staging of the
Games. The records are stored at the Atlanta History Center and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   They requested that the foundation ``take every available
precaution to ensure that all records'' _ including those already
purged from the files _ related to the activities of GAAF, the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games and the IOC are preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic organizers,'' Echols said, ``have always said from
the beginning we would welcome and fully cooperate with any federal
inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the foundation said it is willing to cooperate with
federal investigators, and has offered to make its records
available to the state attorney general, it filed a lawsuit in
Fulton County Superior Court on Wednesday seeking a judge's
declaration that the historical record of the Atlanta Olympic bid
campaign is private and not subject to the Georgia Open Records
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker said earlier Thursday
that he intends to be ``heavily involved'' in the open-records
litigation
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded opinion issued Wednesday, Baker said he
believes that the records are public and should be made available
as quickly as possible. Reading GAAF's lawsuit Thursday ``doesn't
change my opinion that the records need to be released,'' Baker
said.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, the foundation claims that the dispute is not about
whether GAAF acted improperly during the bid process but about
``whether private volunteers who give their time and money to
support an important project in their community are to have their
privacy, their confidences and their financial information subject
to public invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation argues that it was formed by a ``collection of
volunteers'' who exercised no governmental power and pursued the
Games only on the condition that the city would not be financially
liable.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the files should be made public because of the
``overwhelmingly public nature of the 1996 Olympics (and) the
inextricable link between private interests and government entities
in the pursuit'' of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's complaint included a letter from former Mayor
Andrew Young to Baker, asserting that he believed the bid effort
was a ``privately funded initiative conducted by private
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Young wrote that, although he was a member of the foundation's
board of directors and he supported the bid group's effort, the
board appointment was ``not as an ex officio position due to my
role as Atlanta Mayor.'' If that were the case, Young said,
subsequent mayors would have assumed the board position.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he did not know what role his office would play but
added, ``It is fair to say we are going to be heavily involved in
this matter, for obvious reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Echols said, ``We have offered all of the records to Attorney
General Baker for his review, but he declined our invitiation. We
really are delighted that the House committee wants to, in a way,
to accept our invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he would not review the records unless attorneys for
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, which has sought to open the
records, are allowed the same opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of fairness,'' Baker said. ``We need to make
sure both sides have an opportunity to know what you are fussing
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2146EDT &QL; 
