<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-ART-1STLD-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST STEP TO FINANCIAL INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)  
 (Eds: Please use this version of story)  
 (af)  
 Barbara Stanny is the author of ``Prince Charming Isn't Coming: How
Women Get Smart About Money''(Penguin Books, 1997).  
 By BARBARA STANNY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up, the only advice my father ever gave me about money
was ``Don't worry.'' Beneath those words, of course, was an
unspoken assumption: There will always be a man to take care of
you.
</P>
<P>
   One would expect something more substantial from Richard Bloch,
the ``R'' of H&AMP;R Block. But my father was well-meaning. He truly
didn't want his daughter to worry about money, and he sincerely
believed that managing it was a man's job.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't going to argue. Money was too complicated. And my
husband, a former lawyer who became a stockbroker and financial
planner, was perfect for the job. Or so I thought, until I found
out that my Prince Charming was a lousy money manager.
</P>
<P>
   But even knowing that, I continued to let him handle the
finances. That's how intimidated I was by money. I just signed
whatever he told me to sign. During our 15-year marriage, he lost a
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   That would have kept up indefinitely had it not been for an
incident at the ATM. I wanted to withdraw something like $60, but
the machine wouldn't give me the money. ``Insufficient funds,'' the
screen told me. I panicked, raced home and angrily confronted my
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' he said calmly. ``I'll take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words felt so soothing, like a warm bath on a chilly
morning. I desperately wanted to stay submerged in my illusion of
safety. But the ATM had just thrown a bucket of ice water in my
face. I could no longer not worry. I knew I had to do something.
</P>
<P>
   After the divorce, I made some feeble attempts to learn about
money, but my brain would fog up and my eyes glaze over. I quickly
gave up and returned to my blissful state of financial ignorance.
Life, however, had other plans.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, I received a total of over $1 million in bills
for back taxes my ex-husband never paid and penalties for a
disallowed tax shelter he put us in. He had left the country; my
signature was on the documents, so I was left holding the bag.
Unable to pay, I asked my father for a loan. He refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supposed to worry about this stuff, remember,'' I
screamed as I slammed down the phone. I was furious, but also
terrified. I had three daughters, one just a baby. At that moment,
I knew that staying stupid was no longer an option.
</P>
<P>
   Then fate intervened. Working as a journalist, I joined a
research project on women and money. I interviewed more than 100
financially savvy women. Those interviews were life-changing.
</P>
<P>
   As I listened to how they went from being ignorant to smart
about money, I saw that it wasn't so much what they did, but how
they thought that made the difference. Each woman had come to a
series of seven realizations. I recognized immediately that those
realizations, when combined, were a process I could follow.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly what was inconceivable looked possible. In a short
time, I not only became smart about money, but I also wrote a book
to urge women to do the same. Now my publisher bills me as a
financial expert.
</P>
<P>
   How did I do it in such a short period after a lifetime of
financial lethargy? The key lies in the first realization _ the
quintessential step.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every woman I interviewed spoke of it as a turning
point, the defining moment in her financial life. They all started
with essentially the same realization: No one will do this for me.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Prince Charming isn't coming _ and please note
that the prince need not be a man. Our prince could be an insurance
settlement, the lottery or anything we fantasize will rescue us
financially.
</P>
<P>
   To become genuinely savvy, we must be able to say with total
conviction that we can do it ourselves. It doesn't matter if we are
male or female, single, married or living with a partner.
</P>
<P>
   As long as even a tiny part of us is waiting for, hoping,
expecting someone or something to assume responsibility for us, we
will never fully take charge of our finances _ and our future
security.
</P>
<P>
   For that lesson, I owe my father a debt of gratitude. He had the
guts to say no when I asked for a loan. I know now that it wasn't
easy for him. In hindsight, I see his refusal as both an admission
of wrong thinking on his part and a vote of confidence in me. It
was his way of saying: ``You can do it, I know you can, and it's
time you did.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess we both had to learn the hard way that Prince Charming
isn't coming.
</P>
<P>
   Submit your account of struggling or succeeding in financial
life to My Money, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036, or e-mail to
mymoney(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
