A8951 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAILING-LIST-SCHEME-B     05-07 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAILING-LIST-SCHEME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV STATION'S SUBSCRIBER DEAL WITH DNC EXPOSED BY CURIOUS MOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A 4-year-old boy's loyal attachment to public TV's
Barney ended up making him the surprised recipient this spring of a
fund-raising pitch and ``agenda survey'' from the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Little Sam Black got this mail because his mother, Jody Black,
included his name with hers last fall when she sent in a $40
donation to WGBH, the public TV station in Boston, never suspecting
the station would then swap names with the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   An embarrassed station official Friday admitted that, in
violation of station rules, WGBH had ``exchanged'' portions of its
225,000-member mailing list with the Democratic National Committee.
Tax experts questioned whether the deal was legal under the
station's nonprofit tax status.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the station, not the DNC, that initiated the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Lifsey, director of media and community relations at WGBH
in Boston, acknowledged the list-swap after the Globe inquired at
the request of Black, who was sure that her name and her son's were
being peddled by WGBH.
</P>
<P>
   Lifsey said that, of the entire membership list, ``a few
thousand'' of the names were given to the Democratic National
Committee in exchange for an equal number given to them.
</P>
<P>
   She said some new employees who made the deal with the DNC had
not been aware of the station's policy against sharing lists with
political or religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little embarrassed about it, and sorry it happened,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As a public relations matter, a cozy relationship with the
Democrats is not what any public television station needs. Several
years ago, some Republicans in Congress sought reduced federal
funding of public broadcasting, saying the stations were too
left-leaning.
</P>
<P>
   And as a legal matter, public television stations cannot play
political favorites. WGBH is a tax-exempt group, referred to in
legal circles as a 501(c)(3). It faces serious IRS sanctions if it
does anything that appears to be lobbying or supporting a political
party, according to Doug Fleming of Fleming &AMP; O'Neill, head of the
Massachusetts Bar Association's tax section.
</P>
<P>
   Lifsey said she is not aware of any other occasion when the
station violated its mailing list policy. When asked if the
Republicans were approached about exchanging lists, she said they
were not.
</P>
<P>
   All of this may not have come to light had it not been for
Black, a former corporate lawyer who is now at home full time to
raise her two young children. Sometime last fall, she donated $40
to WBGH, partly in gratitude for all the children's programs on the
channel. She made out the membership donation in her name and the
name of her oldest child, Sam.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was the only time their two names appeared together
on a mailing list. When her WGBH membership card and other mailings
came to Sam and Jody Black, she was amused thinking that WGBH
probably thought Sam was her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the past month, she received in the mail a
questionnaire and donation request from the Democratic National
Committee. While the envelope was addressed to ``Sam Black and Jody
Black,'' the survey and money pitch inside was addressed only to
Sam.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old mother instantly made the connection. She said
she was appalled that WGBH shared her name with a political party,
not to mention that it was the source of unwanted junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   She said the station should have told her about its marketing of
mailing lists. ``At the very least,'' she said, ``I should have
been given the opportunity to restrict usage of the information I
furnished to them.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH officials say when someone signs up, they receive a
membership packet that contains an ``opt-out'' card. If filled out,
the member's name and information will not be shared with any other
group. Black does not recall such a card.
</P>
<P>
   Lifsey said she is aware of consumers' hatred of junk mail, but
she said ``it's a standard industry practice'' for nonprofits like
WGBH to swap or ``rent'' lists to other nonprofits or other groups
in an effort to expand membership.
</P>
<P>
   She emphasized they do not ``sell'' lists. She said ``renting''
names means the other group can use WGBH names for one mailing
only.
</P>
<P>
   Lifsey said on average, WGBH has some kind of mailing list
exchange or rental about four times a month.
</P>
<P>
   In Wellesley home, Jody Black said she'd like the chance to fill
out the form that prohibits WGBH from sharing her or her son's name
with others. Will she fill out the Democratic survey? It's
doubtful, she's a registered Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
