<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8952 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD     05-07 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE EMBASSY HIT IN NATO BOMBING OF BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs lede and 6th graph to show conflicting accounts of
fatalities; inserts new 2nd and 7th graphs; adds ambassador's
comment to 11th graph; inserts new 12th graph to add statement from
Annan; 2nd take is all new) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
a chronology of NATO mistakes is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO forces pounding the center of Belgrade
apparently struck China's embassy Friday night, only hours after
knocking out electrical power across much of the country. Yugoslav
authorities immediately reported numerous injuries, both inside and
outside the embassy, which they said held 26 people at the time,
and offered conflicting accounts about fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are greatly shocked by the reports of NATO's bombing of the
Chinese Embassy,'' China's ambassador to the United Nations, Qin
Huasun said, ``NATO's barbarian act is a violation of the U.N.
Charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Only moments before reports of the strike on the embassy, which
was hit just before midnight in Belgrade, NATO officials
acknowledged that cluster bombs dropped from an F-16 fighter jet
had caused extensive damage to a hospital complex and marketplace
in Nis, Yugoslavia's third largest city. Belgrade said 15 people
died in that attack.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials, who escorted journalists to the scene,
reported that an additional 60 were wounded. Dismembered bodies lay
on a street nearby around yellow casings from the cluster bombs,
which upon detonating cover a target with smaller bomblets.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy, in the new section of the capital west of the Sava
River, is near the headquarters of a television station owned by a
close associate of Milosevic. Smoke and flames poured from
blown-out windows of the two-story embassy building, which was
fully evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav official said 26 people were in the building when it
was hit, and some were taken to hospitals but none with serious
injuries. But a Foreign Ministry spokesman, Nebojsa Vujovic, said,
``there are deaths and injuries,'' without providing details.
</P>
<P>
   China's Xinhua news agency said four were injured and four were
missing. There was no immediate reaction from the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to the embassy is certain to add still more tumult to
already strained relationship with NATO and the United States for
China, which has been sharply critical of NATO's air war. On
Thursday, China's foreign ministry called on NATO to halt the
bombing, saying it had caused ``great civilian casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   As a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, China has
veto power over any settlement of the conflict that would have the
international body's imprimatur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing we can say at this point,'' the Pentagon's
spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately reached out to China's embassy here
in Washington to inform its diplomats of the strike, an
administration official said. Later, America's ambassador to China,
James Sasser, spoke with Chinese government officials in Beijing,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. secretary general, Kofi Annan, was ``shocked and
distressed'' at the report, his spokemsan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese delegate to the United Nations, Qin, said, ``We call
on NATO to stop immediately its military actions so as to avoid
further humanitarian disasters.'' He added that it was possible his
country would call a special meeting of the Security Council to
address the incident and that ``NATO should be responsible for all
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials were scrambling for information that
could explain whether one of its missiles or bombs was involved.
The strike occurred during a powerful series of explosions from
NATO bombs that rocked the capital through the evening.
</P>
<P>
   After nightfall, allied warplanes attacked four electrical
transformers in and around Belgrade, once again darkening the
capital and much of the rest of the country. The raids reportedly
struck several government and military buildings in Belgrade's
center, as well as the city's main power plant.
</P>
<P>
   The barrage in Belgrade followed a three-day lull in strikes
against the capital that coincided with diplomatic efforts to end
NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia, even though NATO officials
insisted there was no correlation.
</P>
<P>
   Even as diplomats from Washington to Moscow shuttled from
capital to capital carrying the outlines of a settlement, the
United States and NATO vowed to keep intensifying the attacks,
which continued for a 45th day.
</P>
<P>
   A consequence of NATO's intensified assault has been growing
numbers of misfires and civilian deaths, which the alliance has
repeatedly said it hoped to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth time, a stray missile landed in Bulgaria. No one
was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials reported a large attack by allied
warplanes against the airfield in Nis, as well as a radio tower,
but at least one bomb fell short of its targets, for reasons that
were still not clear, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it is highly probable that a weapon went astray
and hit civilian buildings,'' a statement released late Friday at
NATO's headquarters in Brussels said. ``There was no intent to harm
civilians during this strike.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, NATO has emphasized that civilian deaths were
always a possibility in warfare, despite the technological
precision of its laser- and satellite-guided weapons. But NATO has
found itself on the defensive after several incidents resulted in
dozens of deaths _ from the bombing of a train crossing the Juzna
Morava River in mid-April to the destruction of a neighborhood in
Surdulica last week.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's government has used the deaths to portray NATO's
attacks as indiscriminate acts of barbarity.
</P>
<P>
   To counter what many officials here consider disproportionate
attention to NATO's mistakes, the Pentagon Friday provided a
compilation of reports of atrocities attributed to Milosevic's
campaign of ethnic cleansing in Kosovo. The Pentagon's compilation
detailed more than 20 towns or cities inside of Kosovo where more
than 100 people were reported killed or more than 1,000 people had
been displaced.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, the Pentagon's spokesman, said that the compilation,
based on American intelligence reports and reports by refugees,
showed that 100,000 military-age men from Kosovo have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may have been used to dig graves,'' he said. ``Some may
have been forced to support the Serb military in various ways. We
have reports that some have been used as human shields. Some may
have died in the hills or working. We just don't know, and that's
one of the mysteries that won't be resolved until this conflict is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, foreign ministers from NATO's six major members and
Russia, joined by Japan, reached an agreement for the first time
about the need for an international force to protect Kosovo and
ensure the return of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians
driven from their homes by Yugoslavia's military and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   Although significant details remain unresolved, the agreement
and Russia's growing role as an intermediary appeared to signal a
turn after six and a half weeks of daily bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite expressing a willingness to seek a settlement, U.S. and
NATO officials vowed again Friday to keep intensifying the attacks
until Milosevic agreed to withdraw his forces from the province,
accept a NATO-led peacekeeping force and allow the refugees to
return.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting American troops and political leaders in Macedonia,
Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
the diplomatic efforts would have no effect on the air war. ``The
campaign will continue until such time as Milosevic has agreed to
the terms established by NATO,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite poor weather, airstrikes continued to pound Yugoslavia's
cities and its armed forces in Kosovo. Overnight on Thursday,
American and NATO forces attacked 16 pre-planned targets, including
a bridge over the Danube River on Yugoslavia's border with Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a senior officer on the Pentagon's joint
staff, said allied warplanes also attacked nine other targets that
were encountered during the raids.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell in Belgrade, officials said they expected a heavy
night of bombing in the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
