<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-STORMS08-COX     05-07 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-STORMS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storms threaten northwest Georgia
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith and Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tornadoes and severe thunderstorms formed a
threatening crescent to the west and north of Atlanta on Friday,
but they stayed away from the heart of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The storms maintained a steady traveling speed of 35 miles per
hour throughout the afternoon and evening, shooting a twister down
in Bremen and prompting warning sirens to sound in Cherokee, Cobb,
Carroll, Paulding and Haralson counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no reports of fatalities or even serious injuries,''
said Pamela Swanson, spokeswoman for the Georgia Emergency
Management Agency. In Paulding County, there were reports of damage
to trees and barns. In Carroll County _ where the first
``touchdown'' occurred at 4:27 p.m. _ some structural damage was
reported, but no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The storm moved across the line into Haralson County where it
spawned a tornado in Bremen around 4:30, causing damage to property
along Highway 78 and Pacific Road.
</P>
<P>
   The twister turned the Wade Brothers' mobile home sales lot into
a sea of debris. Owner Truman Wade estimated 35 mobile homes were
damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Employee Kendall Bell watched as a mobile home from the back of
the lot went airborne and crashed into the roof of the dealership.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,000 people were without electricity in Haralson County _
5,000 of them in Bremen, a Georgia Power spokesman said. The
utility said it expected to restore electricity by noon today.
</P>
<P>
   Northward, in Cobb County, a funnel cloud was reported over
Kennesaw, but it did not touch down, Swanson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funnel was sighted in Cherokee County at Bell's Ferry and
Sixes Road, but it also stayed aloft, and no damage was reported,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   After dark, severe thunderstorm warnings continued in Cobb,
North Fulton, Troup, Meriwether and Dawson counties.
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport, flights were
delayed and canceled throughout the day and evening.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellations were owed to a band of bad weather extending
from Georgia to Boston, spokeswoman LaniiThomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Alabama and parts of the Carolinas were under nearly
continuous tornado watches Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In Cherokee, storm sirens interrupted jury deliberations in the
Jonathan Miller murder trial for 45 minutes. The jurors were sent
to the ground floor of the Canton courthouse when a tornado warning
was issued.
</P>
<P>
   A ferocious storm cell straddled Interstate 20 and headed for
Douglas County, dumping rain on evening commuters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Paulding County town of Dallas, golfball-sized hail was
reported around 5:17 p.m. Elsewhere in the county, a tornado
reportedly scooped up a chicken coop and scattered the contents
over the neighboring area.
</P>
<P>
   Paulding County Sheriff Bruce Harris said the damage happened at
Ga. Highway 101 about six miles east of the Haralson County line.
</P>
<P>
   The coops ``got tore up and the sky was raining debris,'' said
Jimmy McCarthy, who lives in southwest Paulding.
</P>
<P>
   Rain from the storm was welcomed in some quarters. Georgia
Agriculture Commissioner Tommy Irvin called the front that moved
through Thursday and Friday ``a lifesaver'' for the parched farm
belt.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Gary Hendricks and Clint Williams, and The
Associated Press, contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
