<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8956 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-07 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN LEADERSHIP FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the end of this terrible century, why was another
murderous tyrant in Europe able to carry out mass killings and
expulsions?
</P>
<P>
   Weakness of leadership is the reason. Political leaders in the
West, most significantly in the United States, repeatedly turned
away from the responsibility of stopping a menacing psychopath.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic did not begin his campaign of terror two
months or two years ago. He began in September 1991, when Serb
artillery shelled _ and in due course leveled _ the Croatian city
of Vukovar.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush was president, and he did nothing. He did nothing
the next year, when the Serbs began their cruel war of rape, ethnic
cleansing and murder in Bosnia. The recent book by Bush and his
national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, ``A World
Transformed,'' does not mention Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Eagleburger, deputy secretary of state at the time,
wrote last month on The New York Times Op-Ed page that NATO's
credibility must be preserved ``or all the would-be Milosevics
around the world will believe that they, too, can kill and maim
with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was from Larry Eagleburger and the rest of the Bush
administration that Milosevic learned he could kill with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton came to office in 1993 promising a tough line
against the Serb aggressors in Bosnia. But he fiddled while Serb
shells rained on Sarajevo. He finally acted, calling the Dayton
conference, only when shamed by the Serb massacre at Srebrenica.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders were no better. A Conservative government in
Britain led the way in appeasement of the Serbs. A British general
in charge of peacekeeping forces in Bosnia, Michael Rose, blocked
responses to Serb outrages. (Today, retired, Rose writes newspaper
articles urging NATO to give up the conflict with Milosevic.)
</P>
<P>
   After Dayton, Richard Holbrooke and others expected the
international force that moved into Bosnia to arrest the two
Bosnian Serb leaders indicted for war crimes, Radovan Karadzic and
Ratko Mladic. Karadzic, it was thought, might give evidence on
Milosevic's role in the slaughter. But they were not arrested, then
or since. Milosevic read that as a sign that we did not really care
about his savagery.
</P>
<P>
   Given that dismal history, what confidence can we have that the
United States and its allies at last understand the menace of
Slobodan Milosevic? Confidence that they will stick to their
fundamental demands in the conflict over Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   There is, understandably, much skepticism. It animated some of
the reaction to the agreement made Thursday by the Group of Seven
with Russia on steps for a political settlement of the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement fudged two of the crucial NATO demands: that Serb
forces be withdrawn from Kosovo (NATO has not said ``all'' forces
but means virtually all), and that an international force with NATO
at its core take over security. A Wall Street Journal editorial on
the agreement concluded: ``Once again the NATO allies are proposing
to let Slobodan Milosevic off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   But as one who has been a hawk on Milosevic for eight years, I
think there are some reasons for confidence now.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other NATO leaders are determined to get the
expelled ethnic Albanians back into Kosovo. And they know that the
Kosovars will not go back unless all significant Serb forces have
pulled out and an international armed force with NATO at its core
has taken over in Kosovo. That means, as one American put it to me,
a force headed by the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, and
responsible politically to the NATO council.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the attitude of the European members of NATO.
They have plainly learned how dangerous it is to tolerate
Milosevic, and they are surprisingly united behind the bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomat put it to me that NATO members have a ``steely
resolve to make their demands irreducible.'' Skepticism is still
needed. If there is resolve, it will have to hold through much more
of a brutal conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who cares nothing about other lives, has a talent for
his own survival. But maybe the West has learned that it must say
no to him, and mean it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
