<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8959 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JONES-VERDICT-SUB-     05-07 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JONES-VERDICT-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES VERDICT SEEN A WARNING FOR TALK SHOWS, JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits thruout; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Michigan jury found ``The Jenny Jones Show'' negligent in the
murder of a guest on the program, in a ruling decried by First
Amendment advocates and seen as an ominous warning about public
anger not only at trash television, but at the increasingly murky
mix of entertainment and journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The $25 million verdict stemmed from a ``Jenny Jones'' episode
in which one guest, Scott Amedure, revealed himself as the secret
admirer of another guest, Jonathan Schmitz. Three days after the
March 1995 taping, an apparently humiliated Schmitz shot and killed
Amedure. He is currently awaiting retrial after a 1996 murder
conviction was thrown out on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's secret admirer show seemed ``unusual and extreme, even
by talk television standards,'' TV historian Alex McNeil said.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find anyone with a kind word for the sort of
video voyeurism that the jury penalized with its verdict Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers believe that the decision is more than simply
a repudiation of junk programming. They interpret it as part of a
public backlash against a range of media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a jury found ABC liable for $5.5 million in damages
after it used undercover reporters to unearth allegedly unsanitary
conditions at the Food Lion supermarket chain. Last year, The
Cincinnati Enquirer's use of purloined voice mail messages in an
expose of Chiquita Brands International Inc. spawned a major
criminal investigation of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction is first that it's another sign that the public is
angry at the `media at large,' '' said Tom Rosenstiel, director of
the Project for Excellence in Journalism. ``And it's a warning
signal to journalists that that the public in some manner . . .
wants to hold us accountable for consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether Jenny Jones is a journalist or not . . . any
journalist should recognize that there's a message here for them,''
he added. ``Increasingly, there is a blending of the media. What's
the difference between Oprah's book review and The New York Times
Book Review?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Paratore, president of Telepictures Productions, which
produces ``Jenny Jones,'' announced his intention to appeal. ``The
public and every single media outlet should fear the chilling
effect this verdict, if upheld, will have on the basic interview
process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Harvey Silverglate says he harbors few illusions about
the value of the Jones show. ``The history of incursions into the
First Amendment is they pick on the medium that doesn't have
respectable public support,'' Silverglate said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he compared the verdict to ``the other cases that
have arisen where courts have attacked the techniques by which news
has been gathered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a continuum that goes from what we would agree is
hard news to entertainment,'' Silverglate said. ``We're talking
about one phenomenon. You cannot, as a legal matter, distinguish
between Jenny Jones and The Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Court TV anchor Rikki Klieman pointed to the performance of
plaintiffs' attorney Geoffrey Fieger _ who gained fame as Jack
Kevorkian's lawyer _ in convincing the jurors. But Klieman also
contended that the tricky First Amendment issue and the ``proximate
cause'' theory _ which contended that the show was responsible for
the subsequent murder _ ought to keep the matter in the courts for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think they have viable issues on appeal,'' she
said. ``Warner Brothers would be foolish indeed not to take this
all the way to the US Supreme Court. There's never been a case like
this.'' Warner Brothers is the show's distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think the hard-core talk TV wave may have crested.
Pioneered by Morton Downey Jr. and Geraldo Rivera, TV talk has
developed into shows like Jerry Springer's, that rely on
confrontation between guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Springer took it to its illogical extreme,'' said
cultural critic Steven Stark, who points to the success of kinder,
gentler talk show hosts, such as Oprah Winfrey and Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones verdict ``probably will be seen as a turning point,''
McNeil said.``We're probably on the downside of that glut.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jones case was one of Court TV's highest-rated
trials, Klieman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have sex, you have murder, you have possible
homosexuality. Then you've got Fieger. This would have made a
great-made-for-TV movie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0390 </DOCNO>
