York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 7, 1999 -- ISRAEL-FLYING-VOTERS, 5-07 --
Udi Behr, a 38-year-old jewelry designer from Manhattan who
organized the Kesher effort, describes Israel's upcoming election
for prime minister as the most important in history. Two
organizations, Behr's Kesher and Chai L'Yisrael, are arranging to
fly thousands of Israelis living in the United States back to their
homeland for the elections. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 7, 1999 -- INDEPENDENT-SCHOLARS-2, 5-07
-- James Trilling, an independent scholar of Byzantine art studies
and the history of ornament, does some research while working out.
In a country in which the academy has been accused of vaccuuming up
all of intellectual life and processing it into something less
deserving of the name, some scholars have traded the satisfactions
and frustrations of colleges and universities for the mixed
blessings of independence. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 7, 1999 -- INDEPENDENT-SCHOLARS, 5-07 --
Anne Hollander, an art historian whose subject is dress, at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. In a country in which the academy has
been accused of vaccuuming up all of intellectual life and
processing it into something less deserving of the name, some
scholars, like Hollander, one of the better-known independent
scholars, have traded the satisfactions and frustrations of
colleges and universities for the mixed blessings of independence.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
BROOKS-BROTHERS, 05-07 -- ``This is Brooks Brothers for the
millennium,'' said Joseph Gromek, the store's chief executive at
the celebration of the opening of a new, hip branch of the retailer
on Fifth Avenue. The actor Alan Cumming was just one of the stars
who attended the celebration last week. (Miles Ladin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
GEISHA-FASHION, 05-07 -- The glamour that resides in the geisha's
mystery and illusion has infiltrated the fashion world. A classical
Japanese sensibility informs designs by Akira Isogawa of Australia,
who collects vintage kimonos, right, on regular trips to his native
Japan. At left, the cover of Arthur Golden's book ``Memoirs of a
Geisha.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) FORT DIX, N.J. -- May 7, 1999 -- NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2,
5-07 -- Young ethnic Albanian refugees get a push from a U.S.
soldier on Friday. More than 450 Kosovar refugees arrived from
refugee camps in Macedonia on Wednesday. The military facility of
Fort Dix has been furnished with swings, toys, televisions and play
rooms to help the refugees adjust and recover from their
experiences. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) FORT DIX, N.J. -- May 7, 1999 -- NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1,
5-07 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees get their lunch in a cafeteria on
the military base, Friday. More than 450 Kosovar refugees arrived
from refugee camps in Macedonia on Wednesday. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) OMAHA, Neb. -- May 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
BERKSHIRE-HATHAWAY-3, 05-07 -- Bill Adams, a Berkshire Hathaway
shareholder, holds a picture of himself with Warren Buffet from his
wallet from last year's conference. At this annual three-day
gathering Buffet spends time with his shareholders posing for
photos and signing old photographs, annual reports, ticket stubs,
baseball caps and dollar bills. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OMAHA, Neb. -- May 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
BERKSHIRE-HATHAWAY-2, 05-07 -- The Omaha Golden Spikes baseball
farm team held a Berkshire Hathaway night at Rosenblatt Stadium
where Warren ``the Whip'' Buffet warmed-up his arm for the first
pitch. Buffet's first pitch is a staple and a favorite of
shareholders attending the three-day gathering of investors in
Berkshire Hathaway. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OMAHA, Neb. -- May 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
BERKSHIRE-HATHAWAY-1, 05-07 -- Giant screens projecting the images
of Warren Buffett, left, and Charlie Munger are available for those
Berkshire Hathaway shareholders, who weren't able to get seats in
the auditorium. The question and answer session is just part of the
annual, three-day gathering of investors in Berkshire Hathaway.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- May 7, 1999 -- FBN-OBIT-HESS-2,
05-07 --The New York Jets owner, Leon Hess, looks relaxed at the
press conference announcing the appointment of Bill Parcells as
head coach on Feb. 11, 1997. Hess, one of the original owners of
Jets and the retired chairman of Amerada Hess Corp., died Friday at
Lenox Hill Hospital of a blood disease. He was 85. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- May 7, 1999 -- FBN-OBIT-HESS-1,
05-07 --The New York Jets owner, Leon Hess, at a practice in
December 1995. Hess, who was part of a group that bought the Jets
of the American Football League in 1963, died at Lenox Hill
Hospital of a blood disease Friday. He was 85. (Steve Berman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
