<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-TAILWIND-SUIT-NYT     05-07 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-TAILWIND-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC OF FLAWED CNN REPORT IS NAMED AS SOURCE FOR IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A retired military officer who has been a leading critic of
CNN's repudiated broadcast on the use of nerve gas against
defectors in the Vietnam War was named Friday as one of the
confidential sources for the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Maj. Gen. John Singlaub, who in the late 1960s
commanded a special forces unit in Vietnam, was identified as
someone who had confirmed the charges contained in the broadcast in
a lawsuit filed against him Friday by April Oliver, the lead
producer of the discredited report on a Vietnam mission known as
Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver, who was dismissed by CNN, is suing Singlaub for
breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub is already suing Ms. Oliver, CNN, and Peter Arnett, the
lead correspondent on the broadcast, for defamation.
</P>
<P>
   The general, who last summer said he had repeatedly warned Ms.
Oliver that she was following a false trail, Friday denied Ms.
Oliver's claim that he had corroborated the use of nerve gas in
Operation Tailwind, or that he had ever said the mission was
directed against American defectors. Both he and Ms. Oliver agree
that he was no longer in command of his special forces unit, the
Studies and Operations Group, at the time of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's filing was the second time in recent months that a
journalist whose reporting was under attack has revealed the
identity of a confidential source, but the two cases vary greatly.
In the first case, Mike Gallagher, a reporter for The Cincinnati
Enquirer, disclosed that a lawyer for Chiquita Brands International
had helped him gain access to the company's voice-mail system. He
had promised the lawyer that he would go to jail rather than
identify him, according to evidence produced in litigation stemming
from The Enquirer's articles.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, after the CNN report was broadcast, Singlaub
appeared at a Pentagon news conference and said he had spoken with
Ms. Oliver and tried to convince her that the claims about the
nerve gas were inaccurate. He had then vociferously denounced the
report she and her co-producer, Jack Smith, had prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists often gather information from sources who refuse to
be named in the material that is eventually published or broadcast,
and it is extremely rare for the journalists to break that pledge
of confidentiality. For it to happen twice and in high-profile
cases has surprised specialists, who are divided on when, if ever,
such a disclosure is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN case, ``is possibly one of the most uncommon scenarios I
have ever heard of,'' said Sandra Barron, the executive director of
the Libel Defense Resource Center. ``It's a very unusual situation
where a confidential source sues a reporter for the story for which
he was a confidential source. One can argue that it puts the
reporter in the same position as the attorney whose client sues him
for malpractice _ it frees him from the pledge of
confidentiality.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver's lawsuit includes several lengthy verbatim passages
from notes she took in her six interviews with Singlaub. In these
conversations, she frequently referred to nerve gas by its military
shorthand designation _ either CBU-15 or GB. Another designation,
CS, was used for tear gas, which Pentagon officials say was used in
various operations in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver's notes reflect this closing exchange in her last
interview with Singlaub, a month before the broadcast:
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver: ``Just one last time, your own personal
understanding of Tailwind is that it was a mission in which CBU-15,
GB, was used at least twice on the village base camp and on
extraction, and that the target was a group of American
defectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub: ``You are not going to use my name on this, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver: ``No sir, you are on background as a senior military
official.''
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub: ``Yeah, that's my view.''
</P>
<P>
   On hearing this exchange in a telephone interview, Singlaub
said: ``I deny that I said that. I never once thought this thing
had taken place, so I can't imagine how she would write things that
would put those thoughts down.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter read a portion of the notes, which also shows
him agreeing to a question posed about the use of ``CBU-15,'' he
said. ``Gosh. You know, I may have been mixed up on what CBU-15
was. It was my understanding that we were talking about CS, and
that's the only thing I ever agreed was used.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I just don't believe that the total conversation she
could have assumed I supported that wild story when in fact it
never entered my mind that it was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver's counterclaim against Singlaub accuses him of breach
of contract. In an interview, she denied the general's claim that
he repeatedly warned her off the story.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday, Ms. Oliver said: ``Singlaub shattered our
confidentiality contract. First, he told the public he wasn't a
source. Then, at a Pentagon press conference in July, he told the
world he was a source, but had always denied the story. Then he
filed suit against me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a companion legal action, Ms. Oliver on Friday sued CNN for
wrongful dismissal, breach of contract, and defamation. In an
interview, she said she was having difficulty pursuing a career in
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a pretty good career,'' she said. ``I loved what I did.
I'm looking into law school now. It's going to be hard enough to
carry this burden in journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   A CNN spokesman said Friday that the network would have no
comment on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
