<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8970 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON &LR;      05-07 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Schwab Chief Responds to SEC Criticism
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The top executive of Charles Schwab Corp., the nation's largest
online broker, said he agrees with most of the criticisms recently
leveled at the electronic brokerage industry by the head of the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In an impromptu interview earlier this week at a Schwab
conference in San Francisco, Schwab co-chief executive David
Pottruck said though that the SEC should not have singled out
Internet brokers. ``The one issue we have is that many of the
issues facing online firms are issues facing all brokers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt in a Washington, D.C., speech earlier
this week warned online brokers that they must do a better job
protecting investors from stock-market risks.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt criticized firms whose ads suggest online stock trading
is a recipe for getting rich quick. Without mentioning the
advertiser by name, he condemned a Discover Brokerage commercial
that features a tow-truck driver who buys an island with his stock
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck said other firms, not Schwab, were responsible for
encouraging false hopes. ``There is no question that some of our
competitors advertise that getting on the Net and achieving a
fortune is something any investor can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's own ads stress how the Internet gives investors more
control over their finances.
</P>
<P>
   A Discover spokesman said the firm supports Levitt's call for
informing investors about market risks but declined to discuss the
content of the firm's commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said in his speech that brokers must make sure they have
the capacity to handle the rapid growth of online trading, that
they execute customer orders at the best possible price and that
they clearly disclose Internet investing risks.
</P>
<P>
   Critics suggest that Internet trading makes trading stocks so
easy that some investors end up putting money into the market
without thinking through their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck didn't address that issue but he agreed that online
trading lowers barriers to investing. ``There's less friction in
the system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's chief said the stock market as a whole isn't overvalued
but many individual issues are trading at prices that make little
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still plenty (of reasonably priced stocks) out
there,'' he said. ``But there are an awful lot of stocks that
reflect no underlying economic model.''
</P>
<P>
   Like its electronic brokerage rivals, Schwab has been all but
swamped by the surge in online trading volume. Trading rocketed 49
percent in the quarter ended March 31, according to Piper Jaffray,
a Minneapolis brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab customers have complained in recent months about
recurring problems getting through to the broker's Internet site,
reaching the firm by telephone or getting timely responses to
e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has been feverishly adding employees and computer
capacity to keep up with demand, but company officials admit they
have had trouble staying ahead of the curve.
</P>
<P>
   In his conference speech before the interview, Pottruck said the
firm has learned that building capacity is much more complicated
than simply plugging in more computers. ``You start finding out
about stress points and bottlenecks that you never new existed,''
he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck was speaking Thursday at an event aimed at recruiting
computer and Internet professionals for Schwab's online brokerage
business.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has 60 openings locally in jobs such as software
development and technical support, part of an estimated 2,000 new
slots the firm expects to fill in the next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
