A8971 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBACOL-COLUMN-LAD     05-07 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBACOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP TO BOTTOM, THERE'S INTRIGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take Pat Riley's ego, Larry Johnson's temper, the New York
tabloids, the San Antonio Spurs' flaccid playoff history and Kevin
Garnett's impending meeting with mega-stardom, and what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   Two better-than-average matchups between No. 1 and No. 8 seeds
as the NBA playoffs open today.
</P>
<P>
   These sure don't look like the usual three-and-outs that happen
when the NBA pits its elite against postseason bottom feeders, and
an upset is not considered preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why these series should be more interesting than, say,
Atlanta-Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat might be superior, but even Riley sees the
ramifications, as round 3 is about to begin between these teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is beyond everybody's control,'' Riley said.
``This is preordained. This is something the gods wanted. It's the
rubber match and here we go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have already lobbed the first grenade, expressing
their glee over facing the Heat during Wednesday's victory over
Miami. They were high-fiving on the bench and could not hide their
happiness over the outcome. Johnson echoed the fans at Madison
Square Garden who started chanting, ``We want the Heat, we want the
Heat,'' when the Knicks clinched a playoff spot Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better than them Davis Boys (the Pacers' Dale and
Antonio) and the Dutchman (center Rik Smits),'' Johnson said. ``We
match up well against Miami because of our similar styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Be careful, L.J., because you are getting what you wish for.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they wanted us, they think they can beat us,'' Heat
guard Tim Hardaway said. ``Here's their chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild-card element is the fist-factor. Johnson and Alonzo
Mourning got into it last year, which resulted in Mourning's
suspension and Miami's demise. Too many players were suspended in
1997 to list here, but suspensions have determined the winner the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Without the same melodrama, Minnesota also has a chance to
inflict some damage to the Spurs. The Wolves are 6-2 with two or
more days rest and have three days off before Sunday's opener at
the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the surprise factor. The first three times the
Spurs and Wolves played, Stephon Marbury played for Minnesota and
Chris Carr started twice. Neither is still with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in the fourth meeting, Wolves point guard Terrell
Brandon was out with a thigh bruise, Garnett was recovering from
the flu and Anthony Peeler had yet to return from a calf injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't played us . . . the combination that's out on the
floor now,'' Garnett said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Spurs' lofty status, which flies in the face of
their 25-34 postseason record in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the top gun, you're supposed to be there, you're
supposed to win,'' Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. ``Does your
team ever get in a situation where it's playing not to lose rather
than to win?''
</P>
<P>
   Just think how good this series might have been if Wolves GM
Kevin McHale had added Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell before the
season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Easy, Rider: Portland's Isaiah Rider created some
bulletin-board material because of his strong words on the eve of
the Blazers' series with the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix can't guard us, but they can put the ball in the
basket,'' Rider said.
</P>
<P>
   Suns center Joe Kleine replied: ``That's kind of funny that
Isaiah Rider is talking about defense. Instead of worrying about
our defense, he should worry about what time their shoot-around
is.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Goggle-gate: Speaking of the Suns, keep an eye on Rex Chapman
to see if he's wearing his $300 goggles that are protecting a
fractured right eye socket.
</P>
<P>
   After the Suns' final practice before departing for Portland on
Thursday, Chapman showed disgust for the goggles. When assistant
coach Frank Johnson handed Chapman the goggles afterward, Chapman
dropped them to the floor, stomped on them, kicked them across the
court and continued his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The goggles remained on the floor, in two pieces, long after
Chapman was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Goggle-gate began at the beginning of the second half in the
Suns' game with Minnesota. When Chapman took the floor, he left the
goggles on the press table. Suns coach Danny Ainge picked them up
and gave them to Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wear them, please,'' Ainge said. But Chapman refused and Ainge
immediately pulled Chapman from the lineup. &QL; 
TOP 10 AND NO. 29 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Utah: All three games with Sacramento were decided in
overtime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. San Antonio: Tim Duncan _ not David Robinson _ can lead Spurs
to finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Miami: Odds of fight-free postseason for Heat: 1,000-1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Indiana: The Davis duo (and their elbows) is what teams dread
in playoffs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Lakers: Glen Rice can stay as long as he scores 40 a game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. Portland: Congrats on regular season, now go get eliminated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. Orlando: Chuck Daly was hoping to play Milwaukee instead of
Philly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. Houston: Rockets not so cocky about facing Lakers after all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9. Atlanta: Hawks led NBA in defense, but Steve Smith needs to
stay healthy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10. Detroit: Loy Vaught, Bison Dele didn't fuel this playoff
run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. 29 Clippers: At least Vancouver plays in its own arena.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sign of the times: Heat forward Mark Strickland became the
third victim to suffer a broken nose this season from Hawks center
Dikembe Mutombo. The other casualties were New Jersey's Jayson
Williams and Boston's Vitaly Potapenko.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland, who received an elbow from Mutombo, was actually
called for a foul on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo also elbowed Knicks guard Chris Childs in the mouth,
knocking out a tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way he plays, he plays with his arms above,'' Heat
coach Pat Riley said. ``It was just a freak thing.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rumor of the Week: The Seattle SuperSonics are getting ready
for a major purge of their roster. Hersey Hawkins and Don MacLean
will be traded, and 36-year-old small forward Detlef Schrempf will
not return. Also being dumped are Olden Polynice, Aaron Williams,
Drew Barry and John Crotty.
</P>
</TEXT>
