<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Web Ad Firms' IPOs Are a Hit
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Two companies that make their money in the growing field of Web
advertising cashed in on the public's appetite for Internet stocks
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices soared for AdForce Inc., a Cupertino provider of
Internet advertising management services, and for Media Metrix
Inc., a New York firm that measures Web site traffic, on their
first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   AdForce nearly doubled its asking price of $15, closing the day
at $29.94 as it sold 4.5 million shares on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which was handled by Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, equaled a 23
percent stake in the company and raised $67.5 million for AdForce.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix shares soared 168 percent from $17 to $45.56. The
company sold 3 million shares on the Nasdaq market, or an 18
percent stake, raising $51 million. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
Securities Corp. handled the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The successful public offerings showed there's still life in the
market for Internet stocks, even after Comps.com, a San Diego
online real estate firm, fizzled in its stock market debut.
Comps.com, which went public on Wednesday at $15 per share, closed
yesterday at $13.75.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, another Internet advertising firm, San
Francisco's Flycast Communications, kept boosting its opening
price, but hasn't seen its stock jump much since then. It opened
Wednesday at $25 and closed yesterday at $26.25.
</P>
<P>
   These stocks hit the market the same week a report came out
showing that Web advertising has eclipsed billboards and taxi tops.
U.S. spending on Web banner ads, site sponsorships and e-mail
marketing more than doubled in 1998 to $1.92 billion _ trumping the
$1.5 billion spent on outdoor advertising, according to a study by
the Internet Advertising Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Internet ad spending could grow to $7.7 billion by 2002,
according to estimates in AdForce's filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Internet advertising has skeptics who note that very
few people actually click on banner ads _ less than half of 1
percent of Web users, according to NetRatings _ the new and dynamic
nature of the medium has many people excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape is shifting very quickly with this whole new
medium that provides interactive capabilities on an impressive
scale,'' said Greg Vogel, an Internet analyst with NationsBanc
Montgomery Securities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies on the Internet can personally interact with you and
do targeted marketing,'' Vogel said. ``That's hugely powerful.
That's not a capability that was possible in the past. You have a
host of technologies and companies that are leveraging this new
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Both AdForce and Media Metrix find themselves in competitive
markets.
</P>
<P>
   AdForce competes with DoubleClick, Engage and NetGravity. Those
firms provide the technology that lets advertisers track Web
surfers' behavior online.
</P>
<P>
   A site such as Yahoo, for instance, could use ad management
technology to see that a Web user had just visited ESPN's Web site
_ and then post an ad for sporting goods just for that user.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of the Net,'' said Michael Tchong, editor of
Iconocast, an Internet marketing newsletter in San Francisco. ``You
can target much more richly than traditional media.''
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix is the leading provider of crucial data showing
who's visiting what Web sites, Tchong said, but it too faces stiff
competition. The biggest challenge will come from Nielsen Media,
the leading provider of television-audience measurement services,
which formed a strategic relationship in October with San Jose's
NetRatings Inc. to provide Internet audience measurement services.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tchong said, PC Data of Reston, Va., has also
started a similar service called AtPCData.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Net firms, neither AdForce nor Media Metrix are
profitable. AdForce lost $5 million on revenue of $3.2 million in
the first quarter of this year, compared with a loss of $2.6
million on revenue of $414,000 in the first quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix lost $7.5 million on revenue of $6.3 million last
year, compared with a loss of $4.9 million on revenue of $3.2
million in 1997. It merged with its chief competitor, Atlanta's
Relevant Knowledge, in November. On a pro forma basis, as if the
companies had been merged for the full year, the company lost $16.2
million on revenue of $8.1 million in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
