<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MOSCOW RETURNS TO THE HEAD TABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ While NATO leaders congratulated themselves on Thursday
for nudging Russia over to their side in the search for a
diplomatic settlement in Kosovo, Russian diplomats took another
view, claiming a small but significant victory in their monthlong
attempt to mediate a peace.
</P>
<P>
   Seen from Moscow, the document signed in Bonn, Germany, on
Thursday by the foreign ministers of Russia and the Group of Seven
industrial countries had the ring of a compromise, a classic
example of diplomatic give and take.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of some Russian analysts, the give came mostly from
the six NATO partners who for the first time opened the door to a
settlement brokered by the U.N. Security Council, where Russia
holds the power to veto. In Moscow's view, the council should play
the leading role in solving the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can speak about quite a substantial success for Russian
diplomacy,'' said Sergei Rogov, director of Moscow's USA and Canada
Institute. ``We were alone against seven Western countries.''
</P>
<P>
   No one here was touting the Bonn agreement as a breakthrough.
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov called it ``a step in the right
direction.'' Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special Balkans envoy,
who sets off Saturday on his third mission to Belgrade, Yugoslavia,
and other capitals, talked only of ``progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Russia, the significance of the agreement lay in the
fact that for the first time since NATO began its bombing of
Yugoslavia, Moscow's place at the head table of the world's leading
powers has been reaffirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at this whole story as an effort by NATO to
establish itself as the dominant player, deciding questions of war
and peace, and deciding them without Russia, we can already
conclude that this effort has failed,'' Rogov said.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO launched its first attack against Yugoslavia on March
24, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, then en route to Washington,
turned his plane around over the Atlantic in a move that signaled
the depth of Russian fury at being ignored and shut out.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by a domestic public opinion that is united against the
air raids on a traditional Russian ally, and by a Communist-led
opposition that blames the West for Russia's weakness, President
Boris Yeltsin has had little room for diplomatic maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   But even against a backdrop of saber-rattling by its top
military leaders, Russia began revving up its diplomatic efforts in
early April, first at a meeting in Oslo, Norway, between Ivanov and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, and then with Chernomyrdin's
shuttle diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the leader of the Communist Party, Gennadi Zyuganov,
criticized the government's diplomatic overtures in the Balkans. He
accused Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin of ``silently betraying and
selling Yugoslavia the way they sold and betrayed the united
country, the Russian economy, friends, history, culture and
traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   By putting his signature on the Bonn document, Ivanov _ once one
of the loudest voices in the Moscow chorus condemning NATO as a
criminal aggressor _ signaled Russia's determination to be part of
the solution to a crisis that had thrown its relations with the
West into a freeze almost reminiscent of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement signed on Thursday will dash any hopes that
Belgrade may have had of drawing Russia into its war with NATO,
commentators here agreed. But some argued that by drawing the
United Nations into any future peace settlement, Moscow has helped
give President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia a way out of the
conflict, if he chooses to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis, this is not our war,'' noted Maksim
Yusin, a Balkans expert at the newspaper Izvestia, ``and the peace
will be decided between NATO and the Serbs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With its broadly stated goals, and flimsily worded proposals,
the Bonn document raises more problems than it solves. Its success
will lie in details that have yet to be hammered out, probably in a
Security Council resolution that promises to be the focus of the
next round of intense international diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's chief concession _ first touted by President Clinton _
lay in its agreement to join in an international peacekeeping
presence in Kosovo. But as several analysts noted, Russia had
already dropped broad hints of its willingness to allow and to take
part in such a force under U.N. auspices with Yugoslavia's consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``An international presence in Kosovo is out of the question
without the consent of Yugoslav leaders,'' Chernomyrdin said flatly
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Russian view, the West's concessions came in the
agreement's acceptance of a U.N. framework for both the
peacekeeping force and for an ``interim administration'' for
Kosovo. ``The four-letter word NATO is not even mentioned,'' Rogov
said.
</P>
<P>
   That NATO will insist on playing a key role in keeping the peace
is accepted here as one of many issues still to be negotiated. One
option that some here think might be accepted by Belgrade would
involve troops from NATO countries that have not taken part in the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have already signaled their intention to step up
the pace of negotiations, seeking out new partners in the search
for a settlement, including perhaps Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovar
Albanian leader now in Rome. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott, who came from Washington last month for talks on Kosovo,
is to return here next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
