<HEADLINE>
CONFLICTING REPORTS OF CASUALTIES AT CHINESE EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Smoke was streaming from the Chinese
Embassy here early Saturday morning, and a gaping hole could be
seen in one side half an hour after bombs struck the modern
six-story building, setting it ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 firetrucks surrounded the embassy, their headlights
and red-and-blue emergency lights illumining its walls _ and a red
Chinese flag still flying in its forecourt. Firefighters in
fluorescent uniforms clambered in and out of smashed windows.
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports of casualties. Talking to
reporters outside the damaged building, a Yugoslav government
official, Goran Matic, said that 26 Chinese were inside when the
bomb fell, and that all had been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   He said that although some had been taken to hospitals, no one
was seriously injured. But later Nebojsa Vujovic, the Foreign
Ministry spokesman, told reporters that there had been deaths and
injuries. Later Saturday morning, a Yugoslav news agency, Beta,
reported one death.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials attributed the bombing to NATO, which had no
immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're crazy, those NATO pilots,'' Matic said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the night, NATO bombers again cut electricity
throughout the city, plunging it into darkness on a cloudless and
moonless night. Several bombs struck in the vicinity of the
Interior and Defense Ministries, both of which have been hit
before. Large fires could be seen from the direction of the
ministries.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese Embassy, in a residential area called Novi Belgrad,
was hit around midnight. Beta, said four explosions were heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a criminal act, they can see this is a completely
residential area,'' a Chinese diplomat told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   The military commentator of the Studio B radio station termed
the attack unprecedented. He said the embassy had been attacked
intentionally because of China's support in the U.N. Security
Council for Belgrade's position.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions also blew out the windows in an apartment
building across the street from the embassy. The pavement was
strewn with shattered glass, and people could be seen in their
homes clearing the rubble to the light of candles.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour after the bombing of the embassy, two blasts were
heard toward the center of Belgrade, followed by an orange flash.
The fire engines raced off, leaving the smoking embassy in the
dark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
