u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT &LR;      05-07 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG ALLIES, DOUBTS AND DISAGREEMENT ON OIL EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The bark of NATO's planned naval blockade of
oil deliveries to Yugoslavia may be worse than its bite, allied
diplomats said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the legal charge against the blockade that was wanted by
NATO's U.S. commander, France has apparently persuaded most allies
that there is no basis in international law for allied warships to
challenge ships of countries that have not declared war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the French argue, there is no U.N. embargo against
Yugoslavia barring fuel shipments. They have rejected U.S.
arguments that a ban on importing war materials provides
justification enough.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, allied political authorities sent instructions
Friday to their military colleagues at NATO headquarters to devise
a different kind of ``visit and search'' system, one that would use
psychology rather than force to dissuade merchant ships from trying
to run oil, gasoline, and other fuels into Bar, the main Yugoslav
port in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, which with Serbia is a constituent part of
Yugoslavia, has opposed President Slobodan Milosevic's operations
against Albanian civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This week, officials in Bar said Milosevic had ordered the navy
to block shipping into the port.
</P>
<P>
   But allied commanders say ships flying flags of opportunity
occasionally do make runs into Bar, so the NATO commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark, wanted a full-fledged blockade. Instead, the French
suggest, NATO ships should be empowered to board ships of allied
and European countries that have declared a ban on fuel shipments
into Yugoslavia, just to check that any vessels heading into Bar
are carrying no fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans argued that this was ridiculous, because we'd
only be checking on shipping that had already agreed not to bring
in fuel,'' one European diplomat reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the French contend that a voluntary or cooperative blockade
is better than none at all and that getting an allied naval
inspection system up and running could scare or shame would-be
violators out of trying to run the blockade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Friday that the 15-nation
European Union had proposed that ships flying its flags could agree
to be boarded by naval inspectors from fellow European countries.
Other countries that had decided to stop oil shipments would be
invited to do so as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to have an effective, comprehensive visit and
search regime,'' he said. ``We're off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Greece was insisting, one allied diplomat in Brussels said
Friday that none of its merchant ships could be boarded by Turkish
naval inspectors. Greece and Turkey are united both by membership
in NATO and by a cordial dislike of one another.
</P>
<P>
   Allied diplomats said Friday they expected that the new system,
if approved, could go into effect as early as next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JETS-FUTURE-NYT &LR;      05-07 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETS-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEON HESS WANTED JETS SOLD AFTER HIS DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also OBIT-HESS)  
(DW) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leon Hess, who died Friday at the age of 85, told other National
Football League owners and officials that he wanted the Jets to be
sold upon his death, and that he planned to specify that wish in
his will.
</P>
<P>
   Three team owners, three league officials and a Hess business
associate, none willing to be identified by name in print, gave
similar descriptions Friday of conversations they had had with Hess
concerning the future of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning about two years ago and as recently as seven months
ago, they said, Hess systematically approached some of his
contemporaries and confided that for a variety of reasons he was
reluctant to leave the responsibility of running the team to his
heirs, which would include his son, John, and his daughters,
Marlene Hess and Connie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, the owners and league officials said, also did not want to
burden his heirs with a decision over whether to sell or retain the
team, something that a mandate to sell the team would avoid.
</P>
<P>
   If the Hess family sells, the Jets are expected to fetch at
least $500 million, sports finance experts said. The price reflects
the value of an NFL franchise in the New York market that will
receive an average of $70 million annually from the league's
network television contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ultimate ego play for a wealthy New York
investor,'' said Marc Ganis, the president of Sportscorp Ltd., a
Chicago consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Among the potential bidders are Cablevision's Dolan family,
which was recently spurned in negotiations to purchase a
controlling interest in the Yankees; Donald Trump, who owned the
New Jersey Generals of the U.S. Football League in the 1980s; the
New York Mets co-owner Nelson Doubleday, and the New Jersey Devils
owner John McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   John Hess, who took control of the family's oil business in
1995, has not had an active role in the operations of the team and
holds no official title in the organization. One NFL owner who
spoke with Leon Hess on the subject said the longtime Jets owner
wanted someone with a passion for football to be running the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   A friend and associate said Hess also wanted to spare his family
the angst and disappointment he experienced during the many
turbulent, controversial and losing Jets seasons he owned the team.
</P>
<P>
   A league official said Friday he believed that Hess' resolve to
have the team sold after his death might have been strengthened
after he witnessed the rancorous dispute that enveloped the
Washington Redskins in the aftermath of the owner Jack Kent Cooke's
death.
</P>
<P>
   One NFL owner said Friday that Hess indicated he was planning to
make the sale of the Jets a priority in his will _ the first asset
to be handled by the executor of his estate.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gutman, the Jets' president, said the team would have no
comment on its future. ``We're focusing on Leon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A change of Jets ownership could disturb the reign of Bill
Parcells, who acts as the team's football czar as both head coach
and general manager. Hess was known for letting his coaches and
executives plot the team's football course without interference
from ownership.
</P>
<P>
   A new Jets owner, especially if he has a hands-on management
approach or enjoys the spotlight, might not sit as well with the
opinionated Parcells, who left the New England Patriots two years
ago in part because he disdained the splashy, assertive style of
the team owner Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Forbes magazine valued the Jets at $259 million, but
they are now worth at least $300 million. A potential buyer would
pay a premium over the basic value of the team. ``With Bill
Parcells there, the Jets are a premier team in a major market,''
said Dean Bonham, a Denver-based sports consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The price would be higher if not for the Jets' lease at Giants
Stadium, which ends after the 2007 season and places them in the
``lower third of NFL teams in stadium revenues,'' said Michael
Ozanian of Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Teams with sweetheart leases in new stadiums, like the Cleveland
Browns, or those that own their stadiums, like the Redskins, garner
large sums from luxury suites, club seats, parking and concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Those revenues were reflected in the $530 million paid for the
Browns last year and the $800 million expected to be paid for the
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Milstein, the New York real estate magnate, withdrew his
$800 million bid for the Redskins last month because owners were
concerned about the high level of debt he was using. His bid
created enough controversy to raise doubt about whether he would
bid for the Jets. A spokesman for Milstein had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dolan, the chairman of Cablevision, which owns the New
York Knicks and New York Rangers, tried to buy the New York Yankees
and has shown interest in acquiring the Mets. On his own, Dolan
also tried to buy the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hess was one of the great gentlemen of sports and industry,''
Dolan said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The newly merged YankeeNets company could also be a candidate,
but the deal that brought them together has not been closed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever price the Jets sell for, the Hess family will have to
pay 55 percent of the sum in federal estate tax. If the family
keeps the team, it could argue that the basic value of the Jets is
less than a sale price and pay less in taxes, although the tax rate
would remain the same, said Cheryl Hader, a partner at the
Manhattan law firm Paul Weiss Rifkind Wharton &AMP; Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   Hess' original investment in the team was $250,000 in 1963, when
he and four other partners salvaged the failed franchise then known
as the Titans. In 1984 Hess bought out his last remaining partner.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jets are now a popular, division-winning team and
Super Bowl contender, there were many seasons when they lost far
more games than they won. A league official revealed Friday that
Hess routinely bought thousands of tickets to Jets home games at
Giants Stadium so that they would not be blacked out on local
television, as league laws dictate for games not sold out. Hess
would donate the tickets to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is not as decent, it is not as fair, it is not as good
as it was yesterday because of the passing of Leon,'' said Art
Modell, the Baltimore Ravens' owner, who along with the Giants
co-owner Wellington Mara is one of the league's most veteran
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jets offices in Hempstead, N.Y., Gutman said he was
overwhelmed by the expressions of sorrow in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you fell into Leon's life, you were very lucky,'' Gutman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells issued a statement that read: ``I'm saddened by the
loss of this great man who had such a quiet dignity. His word was
always good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets players remembered Hess' annual Thanksgiving Day addresses
to the team, and that Hess was there to greet the team as it
returned from its American Football Conference championship game
defeat in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure nobody will forget him standing there when we came
off the plane,'' wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson said. ``He was
thanking us. That meant a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Giants general manager George Young, who is now a
league executive, recalled how Hess refused to raise ticket prices
because his team was not winning. Until recently, the Jets usually
had the lowest average ticket price in the NFL. Last season, the
$35.50 average ticket price ranked 24th, according to Team
Marketing Report, a Chicago publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anyone in the league who didn't like him,'' Young
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
