<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB08-COX     05-07 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Explosives likely for sale, not use, officials believe
 &HT;    By A. Scharnhorst and Brian D. Crecente
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Federal investigators Friday were
looking for the origin of four bars of military C-4 explosives
found in a truck near Lantana on Thursday, but they said they may
never know where they came from.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Gregory Jeffreys and Andre Ruben Morse, both of Fort
Walton Beach, were arrested Thursday afternoon on federal
explosives charges after an anonymous caller told police the men
were carrying the material. The C-4 bars were wrapped in black
mylar and were not set to explode, said Dale Armstrong with the
West Palm Beach office of the Federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms. The men probably did not intend to use the material
themselves, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears it's going to turn out just like other cases, where
people are in it for sale or trade for drugs,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   This particular explosive is manufactured only for military use
and was probably stolen from a military installation, he said. The
wrapped bars still contained a lot number that might lead
authorities to the installation where they were stolen, but not
necessarily to the thieves, he said. The explosives could have been
traded on the black market for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can zero in on where it came from,'' Armstrong said.
``It's going to be difficult, but not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffreys and Morse were in U.S. District Court in Fort Pierce on
Friday morning to be formally charged, although details of the
charges were not made public. U.S. Magistrate Frank Lynch sealed
the complaints against the two men at the request of Assistant
United States Attorney Diana Acosta.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who face up to 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine,
were ordered held without bond.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
