<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk)  
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW SOARS TO RECORD AS INFLATION FEARS RECEDE
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed to yet another record
high after the closely watched employment report for April soothed
Wall Street's fears about inflation. The Dow closed up 84.77
points, or eight-tenths of 1 percent, to 11,031.59. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 12.95 points, or 1 percent, to 1,345,
and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index jumped 31.34
points, or 1.27 percent, to 2,503.62.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported that the number of workers on the
nation's payrolls outside the farm sector increased by 234,000 in
April and the unemployment rate hovered close to a 30-year low at
4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices declined as traders fretted that next
week's quarterly government debt sales will overwhelm demand. The
yield on the 30-year bond rose to 5.81 percent, from 5.78 percent
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   LITTON CHIEF SEIZES AN OPPORTUNITY
</P>
<P>
   Litton Industries is trying to turn itself into the leading
supplier of naval ships with its proposal to buy Newport News
Shipbuilding and Avondale Industries for $1.8 billion in cash and
assume $600 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   UNEMPLOYMENT RISES IN GERMANY
</P>
<P>
   Germany reported an unexpected rise in unemployment, with the
seasonally adjusted jobless rate edging up to 10.7 percent in April
from 10.6 percent in March. Although the change was small, it
surprised economists who had been expecting either no change or a
continuation of recent declines. It also pointed to renewed
pressure on Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who has come under
widespread criticism from industrialists for what they call his
listless economic program.
</P>
<P>
   CNN PRODUCER NAMES SOURCE IN SUIT
</P>
<P>
   A retired military officer, Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub, one of
the chief critics of CNN's repudiated Operation Tailwind broadcast
about the use of nerve gas against defectors during the Vietnam
War, was named in a lawsuit filed by the show's producer, April
Oliver, as one of the confidential sources who had confirmed the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC-GTE HURDLE CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department cleared the merger of Bell Atlantic and
GTE after the companies agreed to sell one of their two interests
in overlapping wireless mobile telephone systems in nine states.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA ENERGY SEEKS BID REPLY
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to force Consolidated Natural Gas to respond to its $6.7
billion hostile bid, the Columbia Energy Group said that it would
send Consolidated's board a merger proposal Saturday. Consolidated
has agreed to a $6.3 billion deal with Dominion Resources.
</P>
<P>
   LEAR IS SELLING ELECTRIC-MOTOR UNIT
</P>
<P>
   The auto-interior maker Lear agreed to sell an electric-motor
business to Johnson Electric Holdings, the maker of small motors,
for $310 million.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA CLAMPS DOWN ON FOREIGN TV
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has begun to clamp down on the illegal
reception of foreign television channels. On Thursday, state TV
showed the police confiscating satellite dishes, receivers and
decoders from a Chinese satellite television company in Fujian
province.
</P>
<P>
   INSTINET FORMS A STRATEGIC ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Instinet has organized a consortium to buy a 54.4 percent stake
in Tradepoint Financial Networks, a British electronic stock market
that recently won SEC permission to accept orders from American
money managers.
</P>
<P>
   A THAI SURGE OF ANTI-AMERICANISM
</P>
<P>
   Washington's opposition to the candidacy of Supachai
Panitchpakdi of Thailand to lead the World Trade Organization has
led to a surge of anti-Americanism in Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990507.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLSPEECH08-COX     05-07 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLSPEECH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton stumps for money in Texas
 &HT;    EDS: Will update with quotes when Friday night speech ends.
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ President Clinton, raising money in a state that
has moved solidly into the other party's side of the political
ledger, rallied Democratic troops Friday night at a fund-raising
event at the home of a longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   The event at the home of Roy Spence, owner of an advertising
firm in Austin, was expected to raise between $250,000 and $350,000
for the Democratic National Committee. The money is earmarked for
the 2000 campaigns. The gathering followed a $450,000 fund-raising
luncheon for about four dozen people held earlier in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Current polls show Texas Gov. George W. Bush could be atop the
GOP national ticket, possibly squaring off against Al Gore,
Clinton's vice president and frontrunner for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always been able to draw crowds and money in Texas,
a state he failed to carry in his 1992 and 1996 elections. In 1992,
running against Houstonian George Bush, then the incumbent
president, Clinton made little effort to carry Texas. Again in
1996, when it became clear that the Democrats' chances of carrying
statewide races had dwindled to near zero, Clinton made little
effort in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's friendship with Clinton dates back to their 1972
efforts on behalf of George McGovern, another Democratic
presidential candidate who had little chance of winning Texas'
electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Money raised in Texas on Friday will go the Democratic Party's
national coffers for an election cycle that will be crucial to
Texas Democrats. As a result of a 1998 sweep led by Bush, the GOP
now holds all statewide offices in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, when Bush may try for president, the only major
statewide race on the Texas ballot will be Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison's likely re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A strong showing by Bush and Hutchison could carry the ballot
and give the Republicans their best-ever chance of wresting control
of the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving in Austin, the Democratic stronghold in an
otherwise Republican state, President Clinton urged Texas
legislators to approve a bill that would stiffen the penalties for
crimes motivated by bias against a person's race, religion,
national origin or sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, as the bill became stalled in legislative
process, Bush has declined to take a position, opting to say
nothing more than he'd look at it if it hits his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there's no reason for anyone to be unclear about
the right thing to do. He signaled his support for the bill shortly
after climbing off Air Force One and hugging the daughter of James
Byrd Jr., the Jasper man who was dragged to his death behind a
pickup truck occupied by three alleged white supremacists.
</P>
<P>
   On the airport podium, Clinton invoked the name of past Texans
who worked for civil rights causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I'm here today I cannot help noting that the work of
Lyndon Johnson and Barbara Jordan is being carried on today here in
Austin by state legislators who are trying to pass hate crime
legislation in the name of James Byrd,'' said Clinton, drawing
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Senfronia Thompson (D-Houston) filed the hate crimes
legislation in memory of Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the bill last week, but it is still pending
in the Senate. Bush has said he is undecided on whether to support
the hate crimes measure but that he opposes special rights based on
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, speaking on the House floor moments after Clinton made
his remarks, said she was ``honored'' by his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very honored and very happy that he sees the importance
of this significant piece of legislation,'' Thompson said. ``I just
regret that our governor has not shown that kind of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to spend the night at an Austin hotel before
heading to Oklahoma on Saturday to look at tornado damage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
