u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-N     05-07 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORRIED AID OFFICIALS KEEP WATCH OVER A SILENT BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ After nearly 25,000 Kosovo refugees flooded
into Macedonia earlier this week, the border fell eerily silent
Friday and refugee officials said they feared that Yugoslav forces
were expelling ethnic Albanians from their homes but barring them
from fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian border guards accused of closing the border on
Thursday appeared to no longer be blocking crossings, officials
from the office of the U.N. high commissioner for refugees said.
But the thousands of refugees believed to be heading toward
Macedonia earlier this week, as well as 1,000 refugees reportedly
forced back into Kosovo by Macedonian police on Wednesday, have
simply vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the refugee agency, said in a
telephone interview from Macedonia that the silence along the
border was particularly unnerving. The refugees arriving earlier
this week from northern Kosovo, including some children, were
suffering from wounds, malnutrition and exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely alarmed,'' she said. ``Thousands of people
from across Kosovo were trying to get out and now they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the exodus from Kosovo, the flow of refugees arriving
in neighboring countries has shifted from as many as 40,000 in a
single day to none at all. At times, Yugoslav officials have closed
the border and forced thousands of refugees back into Kosovo with
no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats have said that the Yugoslavs may want to keep
some ethnic Albanians in Kosovo as protection against NATO bombing.
They also may need to clear roads at times to quickly move military
convoys.
</P>
<P>
   The current lull is particularly alarming, Ms. Ghedini said,
because reports by some of the people who flooded over the border
between Monday and Wednesday indicated that Yugoslav forces had
recently intensified their efforts to expel ethnic Albanians in
three towns in Kosovo. Some of the refugees who came across the
border were particularly weak, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving from Podujevo in northern Kosovo said they had
spent weeks hiding in the woods before food shortages and
indiscriminate Yugoslav shelling forced them to return to the town,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting lots of children with bullet and shrapnel
wounds,'' Ms. Ghedini said. ``They're in an extremely weakened
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees also told aid workers that in Glogovac in Central
Kosovo, Yugoslav forces went from house to house on Sunday and
ordered all ethnic Albanians out. Ethnic Albanians were then
marched to buses that took them to Pristina, the provincial
capital. There, the refugees were loaded onto a special night train
that hauled them to the Macedonian border, the aid workers said.
Refugees recently arriving from Objilic, located just west of
Pristina in central Kosovo, said the Yugoslavs had stepped up
expulsions there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people turned back at the Macedonian border were
among 600 people who arrived in Albania Friday from Kosovo,
officials from the refugee agency said. A group of 360 people from
villages around Pristina and Mitrovica crossed into Albania on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees told aid officials that they were originally sent
by train to Macedonia, but Yugoslav border guards told them the
border was closed. Yugoslav officials then ordered the group to
return to Pristina where they were forced to board buses and pay
$65 each for a ride into exile, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees arriving in Albania reported that Yugoslav forces
are continuing to pursue Kosovar Albanian intellectuals. A group of
men arriving from the town of Prizren in southern Kosovo Friday
told aid workers that they had been abruptly picked up at their
offices and expelled directly into Albania, refugee agency
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who tended to be educated professionals, said they were
forced out of the town with only the clothes they were wearing and
without being allowed to speak with their families. The officials
said similar attacks have been reported over the last week and
Yugoslav forces appear to be stripping the town of its educated
elite.
</P>
</TEXT>
