<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CROATIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP GENERAL REQUESTS ARMS AT BORDER WITH CROATIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to widen the attack on Yugoslavia, NATO's
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, has asked the Pentagon to position
additional long-range rocket batteries along Yugoslavia's borders,
including some in the territory of its arch-enemy Croatia, U.S. and
NATO officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has not yet approved Clark's request, though one
senior official said it was not expected to be a problem. But some
officials within the Pentagon and the Clinton administration fear
basing the rockets in Croatia could inflame Serb-Croat tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets are another of NATO's efforts to broaden the scope
of the air raids against Yugoslavia, which continued for a 45th day
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen on Thursday ordered 176
additional aircraft to join the campaign, including 96 attack
fighters, and the Pentagon said still more would be on their way
soon. France announced Friday that it would send 22 more aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Once the latest squadrons arrive, NATO will have more than 1,100
aircraft committed in the Balkans, more than 800 of them American.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be in an even better position with these extra assets
to operate seven days a week, 24 hours a day,'' said NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea. ``It has never been so true that NATO never sleeps.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark requested the additional rocket batteries _ known as the
Army Tactical Missile System _ several weeks ago as part of his
strategy to cut down Yugoslavia's air defenses. The batteries fire
rockets with a range of about 100 miles and are designed to
immobilize anti-aircraft weapons or radar systems with fragmentary
shells.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has already sent a battalion of the long-range
rockets to the region. The batteries accompany the two dozen Apache
helicopters now in Albania readying themselves to join the attack.
The rockets often work in tandem with the Apaches, knocking out air
defenses moments before the helicopter gunships enter enemy
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Clark requested an additional battalion, the officials said. A
battalion includes three batteries that are able to fire nine
rockets each, as well as 300 soldiers to operate them.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Clark's request did not specify an exact
location, but one area under consideration was the Dalmatian coast
of Croatia, south of Dubrovnik.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the rockets could cover much of Montenegro, the
junior republic in Yugoslavia and a pathway for NATO's air raids.
The Pentagon has also considered placing the batteries in Hungary
and Bosnia, where the United States and NATO have about 30,000
troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
