<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-STEELE-1STLD-WR     05-07 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-STEELE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DECLARES MISTRIAL IN STARR'S CASE AGAINST STEELE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: ADDS Willey's first name in first reference in 4th graf) 
(ATTN: Ark.)   (rk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ After jury members twice described themselves
as ``hopelessly deadlocked,'' a federal judge declared a mistrial
Friday in the obstruction of justice trial of Julie Hiatt Steele,
the Richmond, Va., woman who played a peripheral role in Kenneth
Starr's investigation of President Clinton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mistrial represents the second setback in a month to Starr's
office. In April, a jury in Little Rock, Ark., acquitted Susan
McDougal of one count of obstructing justice when she refused to
testify before a grand jury about the Clintons' Arkansas financial
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. McDougal, Ms. Steele had attacked the motives and
tactics of Starr's prosecutors. The mistrial appeared to startle
members of the prosecution team, who seemed confident after the
defense abruptly rested its case on Thursday without calling Ms.
Steele, or any witnesses, to testify. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than eight hours of deliberations over two days,
the jury failed to reach a unanimous verdict on any of the four
charges of obstruction of justice and making false statements to
federal investigators stemming from what Kathleen Willey described
as Clinton's unwelcome advances in a White House encounter in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a note to the judge late Friday afternoon, the jury foreman
wrote that they were ``hopelessly deadlocked'' and ``any further
deliberations will not change the outcome.'' U.S. District Judge
Claude M. Hilton announced that the foreman had underlined the
word, ``not,'' to emphasize the point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I will then declare a mistrial in this case,'' Hilton
told the jurors, ``and we'll excuse you all.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither the foreman, nor any members of the seven-woman,
five-man jury, would talk about their deliberations as they left
the courthouse. Afterward, Ms. Steele, 52, beamed, telling
reporters, ``It's time to start my life again.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that she hoped it would be the last time that she
would have to have her photograph taken on the steps of a court
house. ``It's been a long, long road,'' Ms. Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors declined to say whether they would seek a
retrial of Ms. Steele. And although they also refused to express
their feelings about the outcome, their expressions made it clear
that the mistrial was a deep disappointment. ``I'm proud of my
legal team and the job they did,'' said prosecutor David Barger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Ms. Steele marked the first and only
criminal prosecution arising from Starr's lengthy investigation of
the president and his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The she-said, she-said case rested on the jurors' evaluation of
the truthfulness of Ms. Willey and Ms. Steele, whose differing
accounts of the 1993 episode discouraged Starr from sending the
Willey matter to the House of Representatives as part of his
impeachment referral.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors advanced the argument that Ms. Steele had been told
by Ms. Willey about her encounter with the president on Nov. 29,
1993, several hours after it allegedly occured. They said Ms.
Steele had lied when she refused to corroborate it to the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers say that Ms. Steele did not hear about the
incident until March 1997, when Ms. Willey asked her friend to lie
about it to Michael Isikoff, a reporter at Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   During an initial interview with Isikoff, Ms. Steele did confirm
hearing about the encounter, but later she recanted, telling the
reporter that Ms. Willey had asked her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Barger said that Ms. Steele changed her story because she was
motivated by money. Ms. Steele sold a photograph of Ms. Willey and
the president to The National Enquirer for $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was willing to make money off her friend,'' prosecutor
Stephen Binhak said during his closing argument. ``Selling the
story is what defendant Steele wanted all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele's conviction was clearly a top priority for Starr,
who had six members of his office sitting behind two prosecution
tables in the courtroom all week. By contrast, Ms. Steele had three
defense lawyers seated with her. Starr, who was traveling Friday in
Florida, was informed of the mistrial by deputy independent counsel
Jay Apperson, who declined to say whether a retrial would be
sought. But he added, ``It would be nice to get a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Had she been convicted, Ms. Steele faced a maximum of 35 years
in prison and $1 million in fines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Ms. Steele and Ms. Willey were close friends, but
they have been pitted against each other in an escalating battle
since the summer of 1997. Their deep animosity for each other was
on display this week, as Ms. Willey shot angry glances toward Ms.
Steele, who sat several feet from the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Although it appeared the case could possibly be a forum for one
final performance from the scandal's major figures, such as Ms.
Lewinsky and Linda Tripp, most of the witnesses were friends and
acquaintances of Ms. Steele and Ms. Willey. The trial was less a
reprisal of last year's voices and instead it became a forum for
the bitter dissolution of their once close friendship.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Steele's lawyers, Eric Dubelier, asked Ms. Willey to
describe a confrontation with Ms. Steele at a Richmond supermarket
over Easter weekend. Ms. Willey acknowledged that she had called
Ms. Steele an obscenity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which of the women to believe became impossible for the jurors
to decide after Ms. Steele's lawyers took the calculated risk of
resting their case without calling her to testify. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the jury seemed to want to hear from Ms. Steele when
they asked the judge during their deliberations for a tape-recorder
to listen to audiotapes of phone messages she had left for a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Luque, the lead attorney for Ms. Steele, said that her
client had been eager to testify but had decided her testimony was
unnecessary because Starr's prosecutors had failed to prove their
case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Willey acknowledged that she had lied to investigators about
a relationship she had had in 1995 with a younger man. She said she
did so because she was embarrassed about the affair. Dubelier made
the point that prosecutors could have chosen to revoke Ms. Willey's
immunity agreement, but instead they simply forgave her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the independent counsel, Starr, who betrayed the rule
of law,'' Ms. Luque said in her closing argument. ``This is
America. They can indict anybody, but only you can convict. Only
you can stop this. I think you will.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although she said in her final arguments that Ms. Steele was hit
by Starr's ``runaway train,'' Ms. Luque admonished Ms. Steele
outside the courthouse not to say anything about the prosecutors.
Ms. Steele left the courthouse in a blue van, accompanied by her
two grown children and Richard Gooding, a tabloid reporter whom she
called a friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
