<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT-NY     05-07 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK MAY WIDEN CHINA OPPOSITION TO NATO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The bombing of its embassy in Belgrade is certain to
inflame China's already passionate opposition to the NATO air
attacks in Yugoslavia, but it is not clear what direct measures
China can take in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has already been under increasing pressure to
take stronger action against the NATO bombing,'' said a military
officer who spoke on the condition of anonymity, and did not know
about the embassy incident until he was told.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said that even before the attack, there was a
consensus among senior military officers that China should more
strongly counter the NATO raids, which China views as an illegal
intervention in a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   On hearing of a Yugoslav news agency report that the embassy was
hit by more than one bomb, the officer said this would indicate
that the attack on China's mission may have been deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   The government was weighing how strongly to respond to the
reports that the embassy had been hit by bombs that caused damage
and casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The 8 a.m. television news reported extensive NATO bombing in
Belgrade over the night but did not mention the embassy bombing.
The New China News Agency reported that the embassy had been hit
and that four people were wounded and four others missing, but
their report was available only to news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, the Chinese delegate, Qin Huasun, said,
``NATO's barbarian act is a violation of the U.N. Charter,'' and
called for an immediate end to the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, China has virulently opposed the American-led
bombing of Yugoslavia. The state-run media attacked the NATO
operations as savagery, part of a plot to extend NATO control over
Eastern Europe. The press here has been consistently one-sided in
its coverage of the conflict, virtually ignoring evidence of
Serbian brutality in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
