<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAY PRESSURE BUSH ON HATE-CRIMES BILL IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) President Clinton all but dared Texas Gov. George W.
Bush Friday to support passage of a new hate-crimes bill, meeting
with relatives of James Byrd Jr. between high-dollar fund-raisers
in Houston and Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work of Lyndon Johnson and Barbara Jordan is being carried
on today here in Austin by the state legislators who are trying to
pass hate crimes legislation in the name of James Byrd,'' Clinton
told a crowd of about 3,000 people at Austin's Bergstrom
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd is the black man from Jasper, Texas, kidnapped and dragged
behind a pickup truck to his death last year by racists.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's daughter, Francis Renee Mullins, 28, and his nephew,
Darrell Verrett, 27, met with Bush on Thursday to urge him to pass
the bill that would strengthen and expand Texas' current
hate-crimes law in Byrd's name and came away disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has promised only to ``seriously'' look at any hate-crimes
legislation that reaches his desk. He has expressed his opposition
to hate-crimes laws in general _ saying it is difficult to punish a
person for his thoughts _ and his opposition to including gays and
lesbians in such laws in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The White House went out of its way to arrange a brief meeting
between Clinton and Byrd's relatives. Clinton met the pair warmly,
on embracing Mullins and keeping his arm around her while they
talked. The two relatives of Byrd wept openly as the president
offered his condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, according to Mullins, said he would call Bush if he
thought it would do any good. She said Clinton told her he might
contact Bush through an unnamed ``mutual friend.``
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the airport crowd that the racist killing of Byrd
was ``anathema'' to most Texans and Americans. But he said
Americans have to take moral stands against such killings to have
the moral authority to halt ethnic genocide in places like Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in America, if we want to do good abroad, we have to be
good at home,'' Clinton said. ``If we want to be a force against
ethnic cleansing and genocide around the world, we have to be a
force for harmony here at home.``
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, just back from a two-day trip to Europe that focused on
NATO military operations in Yugoslavia, stopped in Texas for two
events that netted the Democratic Party $700,000. He will travel
Saturday to Oklahoma to tour the tornado damage and to offer some
support to the communities ripped apart by the powerful storms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be bringing federal commitments worth millions to
help the devastated areas in Oklahoma, Kansas and Texas rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raising lunch in Houston and at a dinner at the home
of Austin ad executive Roy Spence, Clinton sought to tie the
storms, Byrd's death and the school violence in Colorado into a
lesson about good triumphing over evil if Americans can resist the
temptation to assign blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand there are forces at work in our society
that call on us to make an extra effort to protect our children
from violence,'' Clinton said. ``But instead of saying, `Whose
fault is it?' we should all say, `What can I do to take
responsibility.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act passed the
Democratic-controlled state House last week but has met strong
opposition in the mostly Republican Senate, where a vote is
expected on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, as a white Southerner, the thought that a man could be
murdered because of his race in 1999 is heartbreaking. I hope that
law will pass,'' Clinton told about 50 people who paid $10,000 a
couple for lunch in Houston on Friday. ``I hope that Texas will
say, `We don't want people to be hurt because of their race,
because they're gay or because whatever.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The state passed a hate crime bill in 1993 under Democratic Gov.
Ann Richards. Bush signed an amended version of the law in 1997.
But proponents of the new bill say the current law is vague and
virtually unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said Bush would talk to the
president if he calls. But McClellan said Clinton does not
understand the full situation in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the president does not realize Texas already has a
hate crimes law that was strengthened by the legislation signed by
Governor Bush in 1997,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
