<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-U.S.-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING MAY COMPLICATE U.N. SUPPORT FOR PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-MILITARY) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The apparent bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, is expected to complicate, and could even
undermine, efforts by the United States and other NATO members to
win U.N. endorsement of an international peacekeeping force for
Kosovo, administration officials acknowledged Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   China, which has a veto in the U.N. Security Council, has
steadfastly opposed the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia and has
made clear its suspicion about the motives of the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, administration officials said they believe that if NATO
is able to come up with a Russian-endorsed peace plan that ends the
bombing, it is difficult to imagine that China would veto a
Security Council resolution sanctioning a peacekeeping force,
despite the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Operating on little beyond television news accounts of the
bombing, White House and State Department officials said they
immediately telephoned senior diplomats at the Chinese Embassy in
Washington Friday evening to express their concern.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, the American ambassador, James Sasser, was alerted
by the White House by phone to the developments in Belgrade and
asked to meet with senior Chinese officials to offer condolences.
</P>
<P>
   News of the bombing was immediately relayed to President Clinton
and to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright shortly after she met
with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said in a statement issued after the meeting that he was
``shocked and distressed to learn that NATO airstrikes'' apparently
hit the embassy and a civilian hospital in the city of Nis. ``He
reiterates his conviction that an urgent political solution must be
found to the present crisis in the region,'' said a spokesman, Fred
Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
   While consultations with the Chinese have seemed almost a second
thought to the Clinton administration during the air war, China has
the power through its Security Council veto to defeat any U.N.
resolution endorsing an international peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Under a peace plan approved this week by the Group of Seven most
industrialized nations and Russia, any peacekeeping force in Kosovo
must be ``endorsed and adopted by the United Nations,'' wording
apparently intended to satisfy Russia and to make it possible for
Moscow to take part in a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, American and European leaders had begun to court
China more aggressively for its support for _ or, more likely, its
lack of opposition to _ a Security Council resolution. Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder of Germany had been expected to travel to Beijing
next month for talks with the Chinese leaders and to press them to
reconsider any possible plans to exercise their U.N. veto on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   China has opposed the air campaign against Yugoslavia from the
start, consistent with its fiercely held position that a group of
countries cannot interfere in the internal affairs of others. The
Chinese may well see a parallel between Kosovo and Tibet or Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Chinese vetoed a separate Security Council
resolution to extend the mandate for a U.N. peacekeeping operation
in Macedonia, across the border from Yugoslavia, apparently a
demonstration of China's fury over Macedonia's diplomatic
recognition of Taiwan earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insisted Friday night that they had no
confirmation that NATO was responsible for the bombing at the
Chinese Embassy. ``One of the things we've learned during the last
45 days is to be careful of what what we say before we know
anything,'' said a senior official.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another senior official said he believed that whether or not
NATO proves to be responsible for the attack, the Chinese are not
likely to veto an international peacekeeping force in Kosovo that
would end the bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did indeed hit the Chinese Embassy by accident, we would
express our regret to them,'' the official said. ``There would be
discussions and regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``But China has made very clear that it is opposed to the use of
force. And if every other member of the Security Council believed
that a peaceful solution was possible, China does not have a
history of standing in the way. It would be hard to envision them
justifying that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, China had close relations with Yugoslavia,
largely because the government in Belgrade, while Communist, held
to a policy of fierce nonalignment, and was seen as a foil in
Europe to the power of the Soviet Union. The relationship has
remained friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, visited China after
the 1995 peace agreement in Bosnia and received all the trappings
of a formal state visit. His wife, Mira Markovic, has been to China
on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ms. Markovic unveiled plans to build a Chinatown
in Belgrade, but a shortage of funds apparently killed the project.
Her only complaint about the Beijing government is that it has
adopted an economy that is too capitalistic. China was delivering
oil to Yugoslavia until several days ago, but stopped deliveries
for reasons that appeared to be entirely capitalistic: Beijing was
not being paid for the fuel.
</P>
</TEXT>
