<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DOWNPLAYING GAME 1'S SLASHFEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe this transition to toughness has gone too far for the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bad Boys of Hockey'' made another trip to the principal's
office yesterday and lost another player. Pat Verbeek will leave
for a one-game suspension the same day Derian Hatcher is scheduled
to return from his seven-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   So much for anyone calling the Stars soft.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek and St. Louis forward Jamal Mayers were suspended
yesterday for today's Game 2 of the best-of-seven Western
Conference semifinals series. Each player was disciplined by NHL
director of operations Colin Campbell for related slashing
incidents in Game 1, won by the Stars, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents put a new twist on the Stars-Blues series as both
sides declared beforehand ``ultimate respect'' for the other. Now,
there seems to be a little debris, as Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
likes to call it. The Blues called for a longer suspension for
Verbeek, who slashed center Pierre Turgeon on the back of the knee,
causing nerve damage that might force Turgeon to miss tonight's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek said he willingly accepts the one-game suspension, but
he disagrees vehemently with those who say he was trying to injure
Turgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were trying to make it out like it was a malicious,
intentional attempt to injure, and it wasn't at all,'' Verbeek
said. ``I saw him trying to take liberties with \Rgoalie\S Eddie
\RBelfour\S after the whistle had blown, and I wanted to send a
message. The play happened in a split second. I wasn't aiming for
any area; I just wanted him to know to stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars tried to downplay the incident, but the Blues said the
issue has not been settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that got us excited, knowing that the bad blood is
exposed,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville said. ``That could carry
and energize our team and may be bring out the passion that was
needed \RThursday\S and for the rest of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams will try to ferret through the emotional litter, a
couple of potential lineup changes and some key conditioning issues
to play a game that likely will be critical to the series outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 2 is the most important game for the home team,''
Hitchcock said. ``It sets up the race or the gap, one way or the
other. You either go into the other team's rink with them knowing
they can have home-ice advantage or you set up the gap. It always
has more emphasis for the home team, just like Game 3 does for the
team going back to their home.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Hitchcock was trying to take the emotion out
of Game 2. After a physically and emotionally draining series with
Edmonton in the opening round, Hitchcock was an advocate for a
calculated approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just part and parcel of the game,'' he said. ``It's so
tame compared to the Edmonton series that I don't even worry about
it. I don't think there will be focus in \Rrevenge\S once the puck
drops. We both might use it as motivation, but that stuff leaves
after the first couple of shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Hitchcock said he'll have enough trouble trying to rein
in Hatcher, the team captain who was suspended seven games for
breaking Phoenix center Jeremy Roenick's jaw. The Stars have gone
5-0 in the playoffs without Hatcher. What's more, they've posted a
league-best 1.17 goals-against average while missing their top
defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to put a leash on him,'' Hitchcock said. ``He'll be
pretty revved up to play. and we'll have to have it somewhat under
control... somewhat.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the control was hopefully provided by Campbell, who
moved quickly to announce equal suspensions. Verbeek started the
incident by making what Blues coach Joel Quenneville called a
``vicious'' slash on Turgeon with about two minutes remaining in
Game 1. Then Mayers tried to send a retaliatory message in the
final 28 seconds by rushing in to slash Stars defenseman Darryl
Sydor. Sydor is listed as ready to play after getting a bruise on
his upper left arm. Turgeon is listed as questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think \RCampbell\S decided that he wanted to avoid the
situation turning into a matter of retribution,'' Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said. ``From his point of view, using whatever
criteria he wants to use, I think he was saying he doesn't want to
see any more of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, bad boys that they are, have learned that detention
could await.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
