<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-SUSPENSION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLASHES SIGNAL BAD BLOOD BETWEEN STARS, BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Forget needing Phoenix and broken-jawed Jeremy Roenick
to provide second-round drama.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stars players find themselves contending with an
injured Pierre Turgeon and an agitated bunch of St. Louis Blues in
Game 2 of the Western Conference semifinals at 6:30 tonight at
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that got us excited, knowing that the bad blood is
exposed,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville said. ``That could carry
and energize our team and maybe bring out the passion that was
needed \RThursday\S and for the rest of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after Turgeon was injured by a two-handed slash by Stars
winger Pat Verbeek with 2:18 remaining in Game 1, Blues officials,
coaches and players were lobbying for a lengthy suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Turgeon, after all, is questionable for Game 2 because of
soreness in his left knee resulting from Verbeek's slash.
</P>
<P>
   Justice proved to be a bit lighter, though. Verbeek was
suspended for one game _ identical to a suspension given to Blues
forward Jamal Mayers for a retaliatory slash on Stars defenseman
Darryl Sydor with 28 seconds remaining in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in these types of situations you always feel the same
way,'' Blues GM Larry Pleau said. ``I think you're always saying to
yourself: `It should be more.' But all we can do is present our
case and let the NHL make its decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleau pleaded St. Louis' case to NHL director of operations
Colin Campbell after Game 1 as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek's slash of Turgeon was intentional, a callous attempt to
injure St. Louis' best forward after play had been whistled dead.
</P>
<P>
   Turgeon missed practice and may miss Game 2. Quenneville said he
has nerve damage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek has a history of cheap shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it certainly was intentional because you don't hit a guy
behind the leg, right where you don't have any padding, right in
the knee where he is defenseless,'' Quenneville said. ``\RTurgeon\S
had his back turned, too, so \RVerbeek\S knew what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleau and Quenneville said that equating Mayers' slash of Sydor
to Verbeek's slash of Turgeon isn't fair. Both said Mayers' slash
lacked an intent to injure.
</P>
<P>
   Mayers said he had simply been trying to disrupt Sydor's shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it a lot of times,'' Mayers said. ``The guy is following
through with his shot, and if you stop his follow-through, the puck
won't go as far. I just happened to catch him in an awkward spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Quenneville: ``I think he was respecting his teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said Sydor's fine and will play in
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor may be back to normal, but this series doesn't seem likely
to return to its placid beginnings, with the juiciest plot being
Stars winger Brett Hull returning to play his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the star player (Turgeon) already has been slashed. The
villain (Verbeek, a k a Little Ball of Hate to his teammates)
already has been suspended. The suspension (one game) already has
been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The fun begins here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope the league deals with it, but if they don't, we have
25 guys who saw it,'' Blues goalie Grant Fuhr said. ``What goes
around, comes around. If that's the way it's going to be, you get
an eye-for-an-eye deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
