<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK MAY WIDEN CHINA OPPOSITION TO NATO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS first 5 grafs to writethru with updates on reaction to
bombing; to move up comment from U.N. delegate and to update New
China News Agency info with 1 DEAD, 3 MISSING, and 4 wounded; subs
last two grafs with writethru to add quote from professor of
international studies.)  By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As China weighed its formal response to the NATO
bombing of its embassy in Belgrade, foreign policy experts and
officials here said the attack would create intense pressures on
the government to oppose forcefully the U.S.-led air attacks in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday morning, news of the embassy bombing had not yet
been reported on television, the public remained unaware of the
attack, and government offices in Beijing had not made any formal
comment. At the United Nations in New York, the Chinese delegate,
Qin Huasun, said, ``NATO's barbarian act is a violation of the U.N.
charter,'' and he repeated Chinese calls for an immediate end to
the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the bombing and casualties becomes known here, it is
certain to inflame the already passionate sense that NATO's bombing
raids in Yugoslavia constitute illegal aggression _ a view deeply
held by much of the public as well as by officials.
</P>
<P>
   The New China News Agency said Saturday morning, in a report
seen only by news organizations, that one embassy staff member was
killed, four others were wounded and three were still missing after
three missiles hit the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   But if current diplomatic initiatives fail to stop the campaign,
it is not clear what direct measures China could take to counter
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has already been under increasing pressure to
take stronger action against the NATO bombing,'' said a military
officer who spoke on the condition of anonymity, and did not know
about the embassy incident until he was told.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said that even before the attack, there was a
consensus among senior military officers that China should more
strongly counter the NATO raids, which China views as an illegal
intervention in a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   Jia Qingguo, a professor of international studies at Beijing
University, said, ``This strengthens the hand of those who have
argued for closer Chinese-Russian cooperation in aiding Serbia
against NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, China opposed the bombing but Yugoslavia was far
away,'' Jia said. ``Now the war is brought closer to home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
