<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH HURT BUT RELIEVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Knoblauch was stretched out on the trainer's
table with his left leg elevated for more than two hours Friday. He
rubbed his eyes, scratched his head and spoke to several Yankees as
they trickled by him. Knoblauch did not start against the Seattle
Mariners Friday night and will probably miss at least a few games,
but the Yankees are still very relieved.
</P>
<P>
   After Knoblauch was body rolled by Minnesota's Corey Koskie at
second base on Thursday, his leg buckled and he crumbled to the
artificial turf. The Yankees had initially feared that Knoblauch
would miss an extensive amount of time, but medical tests revealed
no broken bones or ligament damage. Knoblauch has a severely
bruised lower left leg and the Yankees still have a mostly healthy
second baseman who will probably not have to be put on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very fortunate,'' Knoblauch said. ``It's amazing. It
definitely could be a lot worse. I could be lying somewhere else
right now if I was hit one fraction of an inch one way or the
other. To be unscathed after that, I'm lucky to be standing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch looked weary as he stood near his locker. He barely
slept on Thursday night because of the throbbing pain in his leg,
yet he claimed that he would like to try to play Saturday. But Don
Zimmer, the interim manager, said the Yankees would probably rest
Knoblauch for the weekend and see if he is ready to start on
Tuesday against the Angels. Like Knoblauch, Zimmer is relieved that
Knoblauch's injury seems minor and that he did not even need to
have additional tests Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he could have been hurt very, very bad,'' Zimmer
said. ``When he said he was lucky, I know what he meant. He's lucky
he didn't tear up a knee or break a leg.''
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied, 3-3, in the bottom of the eighth inning
Thursday, the Twins had the bases loaded with one out when Ron
Coomer hit a chopper to Derek Jeter. It would have been difficult
to turn a double play, but Knoblauch hung in at second to try for
it and Koskie barreled into his leg with a half-slide,
half-takedown.
</P>
<P>
   With Knoblauch on the ground writhing in pain, the Yankees were
concerned that their second baseman might be out for a while.
Umpire Jim Joyce ruled that Koskie, who is 6 feet 3 inches and
weighs 217 pounds, had interfered with Knoblauch's attempt to turn
two and called him out, squelching the rally. But general manager
Brian Cashman was so worried about Knoblauch's status that he
immediately called Mark Newman, the vice president for player
development and scouting, and told him to alert the minor leagues
that the Yankees might be recalling an infielder.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that Knoblauch was seriously hurt, Cashman did not
even wait until Knoblauch returned from getting X-rays at the
hospital before contacting Newman. ``You go into worry mode and you
think the worst,'' Cashman said. ``It's easy to think about Joe
Theismann. That's the first thing I thought about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman called the collision a ``career-threatening situation''
and reiterated that the Yankees did not think Knoblauch would be
disabled. Even though Knoblauch stressed that he would like to play
Saturday or Sunday, the Yankees have Luis Sojo to take his place
and they will surely be conservative in allowing Knoblauch to come
back. Knoblauch, who must wait until the swelling dissipates and he
gains more flexibility in the leg, conceded that he felt like a
tackling dummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To actually get blindsided like that,'' he said, ``I've never
been hit like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even after cringing as he watched replays of the collision,
Knoblauch did not feel that Koskie was guilty of a dirty slide and
merely called the slide reckless. What looked horrible on Thursday
looked much better Friday. Knoblauch's leg was heavily taped and he
was limping, but he still felt lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The replay looked bad,'' Knoblauch said. ``I feel fortunate
that nothing happened. To see it on the replay, I really appreciate
it more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
