<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BREATHLESS IN MIAMI ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: REMOVES reference to pink panties in third graf; ADDS detail
to last graf)  (af)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The average plant manager or chief operating
officer sticks his or her head into a bucket of ice water and is
immediately suspected of having spent too much time in the sun. Pat
Riley dunks himself and _ glug, glug _ he is lauded once again for
masterfully motivating his Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can envision that happening,'' Jeff Van Gundy said Friday,
before leaving for Miami, where his Knicks begin another tractor
pull of a playoff series Saturday against the top-seeded Macho Men
of Riley. ``I've been inside that locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant inside Riley's notorious chamber of pre-game challenges
to his players' manhood, where this season Riley reportedly went
face down into the bucket, emerging to declare: ``You've got to
want to win as much as you want to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   We may shake our heads at the preposterousness of this, but, as
we live and breathe, Riley's next collection of inspirational
urgings, just like the last one, will probably wind up on the
best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches do what works for them, what their personality is,''
Van Gundy said. ``That's not in mine, but when Pat was coaching
here, I saw him walk into the locker room in a pair of cleats, as
if to say, `We're coming in with our spikes up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Van Gundy's favorite you-had-to-be-there
reminiscence of Riley's New York years, a pre-game locker room in a
playoff series against Chicago. Riley told the story of the frog
that agreed to carry the scorpion across the water as long as the
scorpion promised not to sting. After the inevitable, as they were
both sinking, the frog wanted to know what the point of the sting
had been.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I'm a scorpion, and that's what scorpions do,''' Riley said.
And to his team: ``We are Knicks, and what Knicks do is sting
Bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley then turned to Dick Harter, another assistant, and asked
if he had something to add. Harter suggested that the first time
B.J. Armstrong pushed his mouth guard out of his mouth with his
tongue, as he often did during stoppages of play, someone seize the
opportunity to shove it down his throat.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley stood up to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm talking about!'' Oakley yelled as he led the
frothing Knicks out the door.
</P>
<P>
   While Van Gundy and the Knicks were massing at the Miami border
Friday, the predictably stupid war metaphors were being applied to
the third installment of the Knicks-Heat playoff trilogy. Both
coaches, conversely, expressed confidence that the principal
players finally understood the dire consequences of crossing what
we may call the Thorn Line, named for the man who dispenses fines
and suspensions for the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   One would think so, at least hope so. No one should hold his
breath, though, unless he plans to watch these games with his face
submerged in a glass water bucket. Riley and Van Gundy can talk all
they want about self-control, but their players have also been
getting an earful this week about fighting to the last gasp, spikes
up. That's what the Heat and Knicks do, even if it means they both
drown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go down there with force,'' Van Gundy said,
borrowing again from his mentor's short list glossary of playoff
hardball.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to dispute Riley's 1990s regular-season success in
New York and Miami, beginning with a Knicks team Van Gundy fondly
remembered as nasty. Riley didn't invent physical playoff
basketball, but he surely heightened its bad intentions, and so it
is not unfair to point out that he is 0-for-the-decade in terms of
achieving his ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   Most people believe he won't win his first title sans Magic
Johnson this year either, despite bleeding every last victory out
of a team handicapped by injury and offensive inefficiency. With
Michael Jordan gone, the smart money is on the slick-passing and
skills-endowed teams from Indiana, San Antonio, Portland and Utah.
Riley won four titles in Los Angeles with Showtime, but when he
came east, the man behind the makeup turned out to be the street
tough from Schenectady, with his pack of cigarettes tucked under
his T-shirt sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   No team wins the championship holding its breath. This is, above
all, a game of movement, of accuracy, of flow. If the Knicks can
muster enough offense out of Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell, if
Patrick Ewing can let the game come to him, then they have a chance
to again knock Riley out of the first round. They can dunk and
debunk his motivational mystique for good. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
