<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRIAL TO GO ON FOR AIDE TO SHEIK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Brooklyn refused Friday to drop an
indictment against an Egyptian man whose lawyer claimed he was
being unfairly targeted for prosecution because of his political
and religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, by U.S. District Court Judge Carol Bagley Amon,
clears the way for a trial of the man, Nasser Ahmed, a follower of
Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman, the cleric convicted in 1995 in the
conspiracy to blow up landmarks in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, who worked as a paralegal for Rahman during his trial,
has been involved in a bitter, three-year battle with the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service over its attempts to deport
him based on classified information that the agency refuses to make
public. In that case, which is still pending, Ahmed has been
detained without bond for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government indicted Ahmed in December on
charges of making false statements in a decade-old immigration
matter; because of Friday's ruling, he will now be tried in June on
those charges. The case involved an application from Ahmed for
residency status under a special program for farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed's lawyer in the false statements case, Roger Stavis, said
his client had been the victim of selective prosecution because of
his links to Rahman.
</P>
<P>
   Stavis said the government had acknowledged in the past that the
farm worker program had been so rife with fraud that the government
had essentially decided against prosecuting any of the hundreds of
thousands of individuals suspected of submitting false applications
_ until the authorities decided to indict Ahmed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors disagreed, telling Judge Amon that several
other such cases had been brought in Manhattan, and that there was
a basis for prosecuting Ahmed, although the reasons had to remain
secret. In much the same way that the authorities have moved
against Ahmed with secret evidence in the immigration matter, the
government filed a secret document with Judge Amon laying out the
evidence in the criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   The information was ``highly confidential,'' the government told
the judge in a public document, and its disclosure ``could create
significant safety risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have said in the deportation case that Ahmed is
a member of the Islamic Group, an extremist organization, based in
Egypt, that has claimed responsibility for several acts of
terrorism. Ahmed, who has not been charged with terrorism, has
denied being a member of the group or having any role in terrorist
acts.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors told Judge Amon that another reason they indicted
Ahmed was that he had lied in the deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   A former federal prosecutor, Gerard Lynch, who is now a
professor of law at Columbia University School of Law, said that
motions to dismiss cases on grounds of selective prosecution are
rarely won, and that prosecutors have broad discretion in their
charging decisions as long as they do not discriminate on racial or
other grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In court Friday, Ahmed stood quietly by his lawyer, rocking
occasionally on his feet. Afterward, his lawyer, Stavis, expressed
disappointment in the ruling, and said that his client would
contest the charge at trial in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that he's being prosecuted not because of what he
did,'' Stavis said, ``but because of who he was associated with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
