<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NJ-HARBOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS 2 STATES FEUD, 2 MAJOR SHIPPING LINES AGREE TO STAY IN N.Y.
HARBOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y., N.J.)  (bl) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two of the largest shipping lines in the world
announced Friday that they had accepted a lease proposal from New
Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman and the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey that would allow them to remain in the New York harbor
and expand their operations instead of moving to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The shipping lines, Sea-Land Services and Maersk Inc., said they
had decided to develop a deep-water port here even though New York
Gov. George Pataki, who controls the Port Authority with Whitman,
has not approved a new lease for the two shippers at the Elizabeth
Marine Terminal in New Jersey. The two moderate Republican
governors have engaged in a bitter public feud in recent months
that has paralyzed billions of dollars in projects and threatened
to tear the Port Authority apart.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki could still scuttle the agreement as the Port Authority
works out the details of the 29-year lease over the next couple of
months. But with Friday's announcement, the shippers signaled their
intention to stay anyway, lured by New Jersey's proposal of an
additional $120 million in state funds, much of which will go
toward paying for dredging the shipping channels in the harbor. The
states had originally sought to pass the cost of this work on to
the shippers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the two shippers have dropped their threat to move
1,000 jobs and a $100 million payroll to Baltimore, shipping
executives and politicians on both sides of the Hudson River are
hoping that the tension between the two governors will subside and
that they will be able to resolve their dispute. Sea-Land and
Maersk together handle about a quarter of the 1.5 million cargo
containers moving through the port.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns down the heat under the pot,'' said Joan Verplanck,
president of the New Jersey State Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Several important Port Authority projects that had been stalled
by the dispute are now expected to move forward, including a new $1
billion terminal for American Airlines at Kennedy International
Airport and a $700 million renovation of the Continental terminals
at Newark Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow us to continue to be the No. 1 port on the
East Coast, bringing new jobs and commerce to the region,'' said
Port Authority Chairman Lewis Eisenberg, who was appointed by
Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the simmering rancor between the two states was evident
in their responses to the announcement by the two shippers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Torpey, Whitman's chief of staff, said he was pleased
with the shippers' decision. New Jersey had feared that the loss of
Sea-Land and Maersk could cause defections by other shippers and a
decline in a $20 billion industry that accounts for 166,500 jobs,
evenly split between New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that whatever issues that need to be resolved
will be resolved,'' Torpey said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gargano, vice chairman of the Port Authority and
Pataki's chief negotiator, was less enthusiastic. He said he was
confident that Maersk and Sea-Land were merely seeking concessions
on their lease, and would not have moved to Baltimore. After New
York refused to budge on the lease negotiations in April, New
Jersey sweetened an old Port Authority lease offer that had been
rejected by the shippers by adding $120 million in state funds.
Sea-Land and Maersk have now embraced that proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano said that New York and New Jersey still have to resolve
larger issues over the division of Port Authority revenue between
the two states. In recent weeks, Pataki has demanded a radical
restructuring of the Port Authority that would give New York 75
percent of the revenue because, he said, New York projects generate
most of the agency's profits. Whitman has agreed to restructure the
Port Authority, but has refused to agree to Pataki's revenue
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a number of significant issues that remain to
be resolved with New Jersey, particularly as they relate to
insuring that New York is treated fairly by the Port Authority,''
Gargano said.
</P>
<P>
   The lease negotiations with Sea-Land and Maersk have been marked
by intense bargaining by the shippers, as well as the two states.
After rejecting an initial lease offer from the Port Authority last
year, Sea-Land and Maersk publicly invited other ports on the East
Coast to bid for the their business.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore saw an opportunity to double or even triple its
shipping volume and offered to build the two companies a 330-acre
complex. The longshoremen's union and New Jersey accused New York
of failing to grasp the importance of the shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, New York saw the lease negotiations as an
opportunity to wrest financial control of the Port Authority from
New Jersey. Even after Sea-Land's lease expired Feb. 28, New York
refused to change its position, forcing Whitman to provide $120
million in state funds or risk losing the shippers.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Land and Maersk, in turn, could no longer postpone their
final decision on where to build a hub port. Maersk president Tommy
Thomsen said Friday that New York's proposal proved superior.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Moss, director of the Urban Research Center at New York
University, said Pataki had called the shippers' bluff and forced
New Jersey to pay a greater share of the cost of retaining the two
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Pataki turned out to be a far better poker player than
Christine Whitman or the shippers,'' Moss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
